<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, May 4.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pec, Yugoslavia) _ A reporter's impressions of hell: A
drive here from Belgrade reveals an eerie, other-worldly place,
full of blood and blood oaths, of houses licked by flame and others
painted with Serbian slogans and symbols to protect them from the
fiery fate of Albanian properties. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ Talking to people in Belgrade and Novi
Sad about what the stepped-up air campaign means in their daily
lives. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-MOSCOSO (Panama City, Panama) _ A Woman-in-the-News
profile of Panama's president-elect, Mireya Moscoso. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBAN-CLOUT (Washington) _ Fifty years ago fewer than a
quarter of Americans lived in the suburbs. By early next century
more than half of Americans will live there. Every 10 years,
another 10 congressional districts become suburban. As the battles
for the presidency and control of Congress get under way, these
growth patterns are already having a profound effect on the
language and policy proposals of the two parties. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-PRESSURE (Undated) _ After nearly a decade of piling on the
responsibilities, a smattering of American companies are beginning
to worry about the consequences. Concerns ranging from a lack of
creativity to ``burnoal treasure trove has been converted
into a gold mine for profiteers who have been gathering every
turtle in sight fo sale as food and medicinals in the turtle
markets of neighboring China. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAKING-BMBS (Undated) _ The carnage at Littleton reportedly
caused in part by the explosion of homemade bombs highlighted the
ease of making such devices from common, easily obtainable
materials. Many lethal recipes from ``The Anarchist's Cookbook''
originally published in the 1960s, and from other public sources,
have been broadcast electronically for years, available to anyone
with a computer and access to the Internet. An essay by Malcolm W.
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RIVER-RESCUE (Undated) _ The San Pedro River is in danger of
drying up because groundwater pumping for urban development and
farms is drawing water from the river on both sides of the
U.S.-Mexico border. Saving this ``extraordinary biological treasure
chest,'' as an international panel of experts recently called the
river habitat, has become a test case for a cooperative effort
under the NAFTA to save an ecosystem shared by the two countries.
By Jon Christenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEERE-LYME (Boston) _ A Scientist-at-Work profile: Dr.
Allen Steere has been studying Lyme disease for 24 years, longer
than anyone else. He was the first to identify the ailment among a
baffling cluster of kids with swollen knees in Lyme, Conn. Over the
protests of civic leaders he gave the disease the town's name. He
led research efforts on the vaccine, then came under fire for his
theory that some people with Lyme disease suffer a post-disease
syndrome, which has prompted some insurance companies to cease
coverage. By David France.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: By the
time most compulsive gamblers seek help, they are hugely in debt,
owing anywhere from $38,000 to $120,000 and sometimes more, and
their families are a shambles. About 80 percent of problem gamblers
seriously consider suicide and 13 percent to 20 percent attempt
suicide or succeed. More than 5 million Americans are pathological
or problem gamblers, and another 15 million are at risk of falling
into the same morass, according to a study reported last month by
the National Gambling Impact Study Commission. By Jane E. Brody.
(1240 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MACULAR-DEGENERATION (Undated) _ Work in Progress: A drug
activated by shining light into the eye could offer hope for people
suffering from age-related macular degeneration, the leading cause
of severe vision loss in the elderly. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-BUSINESS (Undated) _ More and more physicians find
they are unable to deal with the complexities of today's medical
business and are returning to school to complete MBA's or enrolling
in dual business programs during medical school. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-CYCLO-CROSS (Undated) _ Cyclo-cross, a combination
of mountain biking and steeplechasing, is catching on among fitness
advocates. Participants ride laps over a narrow loop that is filled
with technical challenges like logs, sand pits, mud puddles, and
man-made obstacles. The courses travel over soggy meadows, stream
beds, and dirt trails; no more than half the distance may traverse
paved road. Riders often hop off their bikes, sling them over their
shoulders, and sprint over unbikable terrain on foot. By Liz
Neporent.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLOOD-PRESSURE (Undated) _ People with high blood pressure
often fail to respond to medication, leading their doctors to
prescribe more and more pills for them. Instead, doctors should
help them remember to take the pills they already have, an
international expert in blood pressure control said last week. By
Abigail Zuger, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
