<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OSLO AND THE ISRAELI ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   Five and a half years after the historic handshake at the White
House by Yitzhak Rabin and Yasser Arafat, negotiations to reach a
final peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians are
dormant. Tuesday, May 4, marks the date that both sides had
targeted for completion of an accord, yet the most difficult issues
remain to be addressed, including the shape and status of a
Palestinian state and the future of Jerusalem. Whatever government
Israelis select in the coming election must revive the Oslo peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Oslo timetable has been frozen since December, when Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu abruptly suspended implementation of
the phased withdrawal of Israeli forces from the West Bank that was
set at the Wye Plantation summit meeting in October. Netanyahu said
he could not go ahead with more pullbacks because the Palestinians
had not cracked down on terrorism. But he also acted after
concluding that his fractious Likud coalition was not prepared to
follow through on the Wye agreement. He then struck a deal with the
opposition to dissolve Israel's parliament and hold an election a
year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu showed courage in signing the Wye accord, which would
have put 40 percent of the West Bank territory previously
controlled by Israel under at least partial Palestinian control. It
was unfortunate that he decided to suspend the process after the
first of three phased steps. The Palestinians have not done all
that some had hoped, and Arafat has made too many inflammatory
threats to return to violence. But the Palestinians changed their
charter and worked to arrest suspected terrorists. Under American
pressure, they also withdrew their threat to declare the
establishment of a Palestinian state on May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the first round of Israeli voting, candidates
for prime minister have said little about the Wye agreement and
Oslo peace efforts. That could be a positive sign, indicating a
consensus in Israel over trading land for peace with the
Palestinians. A new government embracing that view is not
guaranteed, however. Netanyahu charges that his opponents would
give too much away to the Palestinians. Yitzhak Mordechai, leader
of the new Center Party, insists that Netanyahu cannot be trusted.
Ehud Barak of the Labor Party says the economy and the peace
negotiations are ``stuck,'' though he is unclear on what he would
do.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have been watching the campaign with some
restraint. Clinton recently said he supported Palestinian
aspirations ``to determine their own future on their own land,''
his strongest endorsement yet of a possible Palestinian state.
Whoever wins will quickly have to complete the withdrawal of forces
contemplated by the Wye agreement. Last week, Clinton rightly
pledged to restart the process after the elections, aiming for a
summit meeting within six months. Negotiations, not threats or
unilateral actions, are the best way to achieve self-government for
Palestinians and security for Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
