<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: INTERNET ADVERTISING HAS BEEN SLOW TO CATCH ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the 4th graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
(lh) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To address the nagging issue of how to make
Internet advertising more effective and profitable, a group of
advertisers and Web publishers formed an organization called FAST,
or the Future of Advertising Stakeholders, last August.
</P>
<P>
   But during a trade show on Internet advertising being held here
this week, FAST's chairman, Richard A. LeFurgy, joked that maybe
the group should change its name.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about `not-so FAST,''' LeFurgy said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting during the (AT)d:tech conference on Internet advertising
and marketing, FAST members said Monday that while they had made
progress in the last nine months, much work remained to convince
companies to spend their advertising dollars online. The mixed
sentiment is reflected in two studies released to coincide with the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for advocates of online advertising comes from the
Internet Advertising Bureau, an online advertising association also
led by LeFurgy. The bureau reported that Internet advertising
revenues hit $1.92 billion in 1998, more than double the $907
million spent in 1997, surpassing the $1.58 billion spent on
outdoor advertising in 1998. LeFurgy called that a significant
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the types of products and services
advertised online were becoming more diverse. During the fourth
quarter, noncomputer retail advertising represented 29 percent of
Internet advertising, compared with 20 percent for computer-related
advertising. LeFurgy said that demonstrated that Internet
advertising was no longer merely the realm of the technology set.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a study to be released Tuesday morning by the Association of
National Advertisers has found evidence that mainstream advertisers
continue to feel uncertain about the medium. The association's
study, which mostly focused on the advertising patterns of the 500
largest industrial companies, concluded that the percentage of
companies it surveyed that advertised online had decreased to 61
percent during 1998 from 68 percent the year before. Those that do
advertise on the Internet are spending less than they did a year
ago, the study found _ $649,000 in 1998 versus $714,000 the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   The figures were based on reports from 121 member companies,
although a handful of the companies surveyed in 1998 differed from
those that participated in 1997, thus making the year-to-year
comparisons inexact, said Robin Webster, the association's senior
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Webster said, the study clearly showed that major
corporations remained skeptical of how to put a value on online
advertising. ``They're still not comfortable with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, 68 percent of companies surveyed said that a ``key
barrier'' to advertising online was that they did not yet know how
to measure their return on investment _ in other words, whether the
ad dollars they spend bring in new consumers or revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want proof that the ads they pay for wind up on
consumer monitors, not downloaded halfway, or never seen at all,
Ms. Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In print you have a tear sheet, on TV you get a report that
the commercial ran,'' she said. ``This medium has not been able to
do that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she said the association's study found major
corporations were increasingly comfortable with the Internet in
general. She said that in 1998, not one company reported it had
limited Internet advertising because senior management did not
``appreciate the value of the Internet.'' In 1997, 33 percent of
companies surveyed gave that response.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webster was quick to praise FAST, of which she is one of 750
members, for being the ``best vehicle'' for helping create
standards for Internet advertising and measuring the effectiveness
of online ads.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has recently published guidelines for Internet
advertisers and publishers on three topics: how to protect consumer
privacy, how to create standard sizes and placement for
advertisements and how to measure how many people view an ad. The
hope is that the guidelines will become de facto standards, much
the way print and television have accepted standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made tremendous progress in the last eight months,''
LeFurgy said. ``We've taken on issues of breadth and depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivienne Bechtold, director of interactive marketing for Procter
&AMP; Gamble, which helped form FAST and is one of the nation's largest
advertisers, said the prognosis was improvingfor Internet
advertising. She said P&AMP;G now advertised 30 brands online _
including Crest, Tide and Cover Girl _ three times more than it did
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed some of the increased comfort to the work of
FAST. ``Considering it's a totally volunteer organization with no
resources, it's made some really great progress,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
