<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CELTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS EARN PLAYOFF BERTH BY BEATING CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There had been a clamor for change, a call for a new
twist on an old team during the summer. And so the New York Knicks
looked around every corner, peered down every dark alley and found
the kind of talent to ultimately phase out Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not a night to celebrate a sleek remake of the
Knicks. This was a night when the Knicks found comfort and calm
amid the flurry of a big game by leaning on what was familiar. They
turned to Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   And he turned in one of his most dominant games of the Knicks'
tumultuous season to help the Knicks clinch a playoff berth with a
95-88 victory against the Boston Celtics on Monday night at Madison
Square Garden. By winning their next-to-last game of the regular
season, the Knicks advanced to the post-season for the 12th
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing ignored the pain in his Achilles' tendon, shrugged off the
boos from a crowd that grew impatient with his plodding style in a
tight fourth quarter, scored 27 points, grabbed a season-high 19
rebounds and put the Knicks in a spot they have grown accustomed
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Heat,'' the crowd chanted in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   And for the third straight year, the Knicks (26-23) could see
their old rivals from Miami in the playoffs. If the standing
remains as it was on Monday night, the Knicks will lick their lips
and set their sights on the team they love to loathe, the Heat, in
a matchup of first- and eighth-seeded teams. And Ewing helped make
this tantalizing matchup possible despite playing his first
back-to-back games in a month, and in spite of anyone who believed
he should shut himself down for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been writing me off for a long time,'' Ewing said.
``I always believe in myself, and when I stop believing in myself,
and believe that I can't play this game at a high level, that's the
day I'm going to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not care what people think. I'm just playing ball. I
think when my body is healthy, I can perform at a high level. If
the shot clock is running down, I'm going to take the shot unless
I'm doubled, then I'll pass it. Everyone can moan, and y'all can
write what you want, I don't care. I'm me and I'm going to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was typical Ewing to the end. After the Celtics tied the game
at 81-81 with 5 minutes 17 left, Ewing was part of a 7-0 run to
pull away after he hit a 5-foot runner and gobbled up two key
rebounds. Even though he had missed two previous shots, and the
crowd was beginning to squirm, Ewing stubbornly kept fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disppointing to me that every time he shot, the crowd
murmured,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He was the dominant
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing put the Knicks into a position to face the Heat. Miami may
be the one elite team the Knicks have the best chance to beat. But
there are an array of playoff possibilities for the Knicks. At the
least, they have secured the eighth and final playoff spot. At
best, they could finish in sixth place, albeit that is a remote
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Knicks beat Miami in the last regular-season game on
Wednesday and both the Bucks and 76ers lose their final two games,
New York would win the three-way tie. On the tie breaker, the
Knicks would have the best combined record against the other two
teams. A two-way tie with Milwaukee would go to the Bucks because
they won the season series with the Knicks. To finish seventh, the
Knicks would need to beat Miami and have the 76ers lose their last
two games to force a tie; the Knicks, by virtue of their season
series edge with Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   If the 76ers win just one or their last two games, the Knicks
would be in eighth regardless of whether they beat the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy just had to cross his fingers on how his team would
approach such an important game. Although the Knicks are a veteran
group, this was not the grizzled group with a history of big games
behind it. The Knicks traded John Starks and Charles Oakley for two
players from losing franchises in Latrell Sprewell and Marcus
Camby.
</P>
<P>
   So it was hard to predict the start. But the beginning was not
the problem. Quickly, Ewing, working around the paint without a
limp, hit his first three shots as the Knicks built an eye-popping
16-0 lead with seven minutes left in the first quarter. By that
point, every Knick starter had scored for an offense that was
working efficiently and unselfishly.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, the Celtics (19-30) turned up the ball
pressure, cranked up their chaos-causing defense and squeezed the
Knicks into a four turnovers. The Knicks mistakes gave them life
for a 22-9 run to finish off the quarter trailing by just 25-22.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Ewing was off and missed five shots in a row during
Boston's spurt. And no one was picking up the slack, not Houston or
Sprewell. Unless there was a dunk, as there was when Charlie Ward
broke the press and found Sprewell darting free to the hoop, the
Knicks' offense was at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks stopped moving the ball, were trying to take every
Celtic one-on-one and fell behind, 30-29, early in the second
quarter. Once they discovered each other again via the assist, and
picked up their defense, the Knicks inched ahead and closed out the
first half on a 7-2 run and held a 46-38 lead at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
