<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEGIN INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Los Angeles Dodgers didn't wait for official word
from the commissioner's office regarding allegations made by two
minor-league players that team officials helped with their
defections from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The club began its own investigation during the weekend. Among
those interviewed were the involved players _ outfielder Josue
Perez, 21, of Single-A Vero Beach and first baseman Juan Carlos
Diaz, 23, of Double-A San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The players said the Dodgers staged secret tryouts in Cuba,
assisted them in leaving the country and signed them at their
offices in the Dominican Republic. The players, through agent Gus
Dominguez, have asked the commissioner's office to declare them
free agents because they are upset about their signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Monday, Dodgers officials said they hadn't heard or
received anything, from the commissioner's office. But Steve
Schneider, a partner of Dominguez's at Total Sports International
in Beverly Hills, said he expects Major League Baseball to contact
the Dodgers within 24 to 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers issued a statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned Friday that Mr. Gus Dominguez has written a letter
to Major League Baseball requesting an inquiry into the
circumstances under which the two players were signed in 1996
(Diaz) and 1998 (Perez). We have not received a copy of the letter
and therefore cannot comment on its contents. However we have
commenced our review of the allegations . . . and are prepared to
cooperate with the commissioner's office in addressing this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The players contend that Pablo Peguero, general manager of the
Dodgers' baseball complex Campo Las Palmas in the Dominican
Republic, scouted the two players and held tryouts in Cuba,
eventually arranging their defections. But Peguero said he hasn't
been to Cuba in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Diaz said via telephone from San Antonio.
``He saw me one time. He talked to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz also said he worked out for Peguero in Cuba, which Peguero
denied. The players also said Campo Las Palmas vice president Ralph
Avila helped in the manner.
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach manager Alvaro Espinoza declined an interview request
for Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no personal knowledge whether that's true,'' Schneider
said of the players' claims.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz was given a $65,00 bonus and Perez's bonus was $40,000.
Neither are considered top prospects in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said he read the documents sent to the commissioner's
office but didn't feel it was appropriate for him to comment on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a pending investigation from the commissioner's
office. A correspondence was made with them,'' Schneider said.
``The documents speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers face fines, suspensions and the possible loss of
selections in the amateur draft if they are found in have broken
rules. But most of the front-office staff for the Dodgers are new
to the organization, which could factor into a ruling if the
accusations are true.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Fox Group purchased the Dodgers there was a feeling
of autonomy throughout the organization. That's changed in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   While Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone wouldn't comment on
the Cuba allegations, he did reaffirm his belief in the way he runs
a minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chain of command,'' Malone said. ``We have a system
in place where there are supervisors, department heads and
directors. We're trying to implement a system.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Osuna returns: The Dodgers strengthened their bullpen by
activating right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna prior to Monday's
game and optioned lefty Jeff Kubenka (0-1, 20.25 ERA) to Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson will have to use Osuna
cautiously. He's been on the disabled list for all but three days
of the season and is pitching with a bone spur in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs time off in between (appearances), a day off, which I
like to do anyway,'' Johnson said. ``(The bullpen) is an intricate
part of the club and I need all the parts there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Raul Mondesi was in the cleanup spot
for the second straight game; Todd Hundley (3 for 5, 3 RBI) was
inserted into the fifth spot and Eric Karros dropped to sixth. It
was the 19th different lineup Johnson used this season. . . . A
strange rule was enforced in the fifth inning when second base
umpire Terry Tata ruled Chan Ho Park took more than the allotted 12
seconds between pitches, awarding ball four to batter Dustin
Hermanson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
