<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BOW TO ROYALS, 9-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tony Muser, the manager of the Kansas City
Royals, has heaped praise upon the New York Yankees in the last two
years for their intense play. During Sunday's loss to the Yankees,
he stopped his young infielder Carlos Beltran in the dugout and
noted Bernie Williams's hustle to first base on an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   That desire, that's what it takes to win, Muser told Beltran, in
so many words.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night, Muser could have pulled Beltran aside and
used some of the Yankees as examples of how you should not play the
game, how a lack of concentration can bury a team. Mental mistakes
killed any chance for a Yankees' comeback in a 9-3 loss to the
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are cruising in the American League East standing,
winning two-thirds of their games. They are hardly a juggernaut,
however _ their middle relief is something of a mess, their defense
has been erratic, they have had little run production from the
bottom third of their lineup. And they are regularly committing the
kind of mistakes that almost never occurred last year, when they
won 125 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trailed, 3-1, in the sixth inning on Monday night,
but in every inning they were pressing the Royals, who already had
used three pitchers. It was just a matter of time, it seemed,
before the relentless Yankees would get someone on base and someone
else would drive a ball in the gap to tie the score or take the
lead, allowing Muser to rave about their desire.
</P>
<P>
   But desire and concentration abandoned the Yankees in the bottom
of the sixth. Orlando Hernandez, who had allowed three runs in the
first two innings and kept the Yankees close in spite of very
lackluster stuff on this night, allowed a one-out single to the
slow-footed Chad Kreuter, the ball flaring to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, the left fielder, moved deliberately to the ball,
without any sort of anxiety about Kreuter, who rounded first and
charged toward second while Ledee fumbled the ball. Ledee was
charged with an error, but he could have had two: one physical, for
bobbling the ball, and a mental mistake, for not scampering after
it. The Yankees have 20 errors in their last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals loaded the bases, bringing Beltran to the plate, and
he slapped a bouncer to the right side; Tino Martinez, the Yankees'
first baseman, came in a couple of steps to catch the ball and
throw home for the second out. Catcher Jorge Posada was set to fire
to first base for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Except nobody was at first base. Martinez was too far from the
bag to make the play because he had fielded the ground ball, but
Hernandez had not moved from the mound _ at least the third time
since the final days of spring training that a Yankees pitcher had
failed to cover first base.
</P>
<P>
   The inning continued, with devastating results. Hernandez walked
home a run and was replaced by Mike Stanton, who, in his first
outing in four days, walked home another run on four pitches. Dan
Naulty relieved Stanton and made a wild pitch that allowed the
Royals to score their third run of the inning. He then gave up a
three-run homer to Mike Sweeney. It was a finishing blow.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had no hits in the first three innings against Jose
Rosado, the Kansas City left-hander who broke three bats with a
fastball that ran in on the hands of right-handed batters. But the
Yankees knocked Rosado out of the game, quite literally. After Chad
Curtis rapped a one-out single in the fourth, Williams smashed a
one-hopper that caromed off Rosado's left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado folded over near the mound, grabbing his shoulder. Muser
and the assistant trainer Lee Kuntz rushed out, and so began a
lengthy debate as to whether Rosado would remain in the game.
Rosado spoke to Kuntz and Muser, who talked to the home plate
umpire, Tim McClelland, and then Rosado threw warm-up pitches,
appearing as if he was fine. He talked some more to Muser, who
spoke to his trainer and then McClelland. The moon rose. The sun
set, somewhere west of here.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado threw two more warm-up pitches and stepped off the mound.
More talking. And more. Finally, Rosado handed the ball to Muser
and departed, and when another few minutes passed before a reliever
emerged from the Kansas City bullpen, Don Zimmer, the Yankees'
interim manager, jumped to the top step of the dugout and glared.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Service replaced Rosado and maintained a lead for Kansas
City. Chili Davis hit Service's first pitch on the ground and to
second base, for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez doubled to open the fifth inning and eventually scored
on a sacrifice fly by Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   But the Royals still held a 3-1 edge when Service relayed the
lead to the left-hander Alvin Morman in the sixth inning, with two
outs and two on. Morman struck out Martinez on three pitches to
close out that rally. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
