<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY PRE PARES FOR WNBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Budke remembers the day four years ago when Cheryl Miller
came to Athens, Texas, to call on Shalonda Enis. He even has photos
of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, Cheryl Miller was the greatest ever to play the
game,'' said Budke, coach at Trinity Valley Community College.
``People who are saying Chamique (Holdsclaw) didn't see Cheryl
Miller play. It was an honor to have her come in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then coach at the University of Southern California, Miller was
in Athens to recruit Enis, the 1994-95 junior college Player of the
Year. But Los Angeles is a long way from Celeste, Texas, where
Enis' son Chase, then 4, would be living with his grandmother while
Shalonda went off to a Division 1 school.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC was too far away for Shae,'' Budke said. ``At Alabama, she
could drive home on weekends. But she loved Cheryl, I do remember
that. I know they're both very competitive people, and they'd get
along very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance could come today if Miller's Mercury makes the
25-year-old Enis the 10th pick of the first round in the WNBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Although Phoenix needs a perimeter shooter and the 6-foot-1 Enis
(pronounced INN-is) was a power forward with the Seattle Reign of
the American Basketball League, she has small-forward shooting
skills.
</P>
<P>
   And with 6-1 Michelle Griffiths, who started 31 games for the
WNBA runner-up, out due to pregnancy, the Mercury can find a place
for a talented front-court addition, either as a starter or
reserve, depending on how successful it is in switching 6-3
Jennifer Gillom to power forward and starting 6-8 Maria Stepanova
at center.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive season, Stepanova and 6-5 backup
center Marlies Askamp will be late to training camp because of the
European Championships, May 28-June 6, a qualifier for the 2000
Olympics. The 32-game WNBA season begins for Phoenix on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Enis fits in every category, particularly if she can play on the
perimeter like she did in the 1998 ABL All-Star Game: 15 points, 5
rebounds, Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mercury were to grab Enis, she would be a taller and
potentially more productive option at small forward than two-year
starter Umeki Webb, a 5-10 defensive specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The ABL Rookie of the Year in 1997-98, Enis averaged 18 points
and 7.6 rebounds. Her second-season numbers were 13.7 and 8.0 when
the league folded in December. She averaged 20.1 points and scored
a school record 766 in her first season (1995-96) at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Enis is one of a group of talented swing forwards from the ABL
that the Mercury would welcome. Others include 6-1 DeLisha Milton,
6-foot Adrienne Goodson and 6-3 Tari Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so effective because they can step out, guard on the
perimeter, they can post up, flash and slash,'' said Linda
Hargrove, who coached the ABL Colorado Xplosion last fall and is a
consultant for this draft for the expansion Orlando Miracle.
``They're going to be very valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who will direct the Mercury draft, said she is not
adverse to taking a `quality big player of the Milton/Phillips
variety, but lights up at the thought of a scoring small forward
with Webb's defensive tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's Enis or Goodson or a guard-forward swing player
like Edna Campbell or Crystal Robinson will be known early today.
The four-round, 50-player draft (expansion Minnesota and Orlando
each pick five players, the other teams four) begins at 8 a.m.
Arizona time.
</P>
<P>
   League officials still were racing to sign players Monday, since
only those under contract are eligible for the draft and the
signing process was delayed until ratification of a four-year
collective bargaining agreement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The long rumored allocation of ABL guards Shannon Johnson to
Orlando and Katie Smith to the Minnesota Lynx became reality
Monday, leaving centers Yolanda Griffith (to Sacramento) and
Natalie Williams (Utah) as the likely second and third overall
picks after Washington selects Holdsclaw, the four-time All-America
forward from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Then the draft could get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   If 34-year-old point guard Teresa Edwards does not sign by this
morning, and the Los Angeles Sparks go for the best available
player, say Milton over sore-kneed point guard Dawn Staley, that
could leave Staley and Jennifer Azzi available for Charlotte (No.
9) and Houston (12th), both of whom need point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Coach Brian Agler is expected to choose guard Tonya
Edwards at No. 7 to pair with Smith, reuniting two-thirds of his
perimeter trio from the two-time ABL champion Columbus Quest.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Detroit (No. 5), New York (No. 6) and Orlando (No.
8) with picks that could influence the Mercury selection. One
logical scenario is: 6-5 center Clarisse Machanguana to Detroit;
Goodson to New York; and Phillips, who played high school and
college ball in Orlando, to the Miracle.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow Enis, who has also been in frequent contact
with both expansion teams, to fall to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheryl's a great coach, a players' coach,'' Enis said. ``She
gets into her players and brings out the best in them. The energy
she brings to her team is something I'd love to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel blessed to go anywhere. I just want a job, period.
Wherever I go, I'll give it all I've got.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
