<HEADLINE>
FISHER IS POINT MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Derek Fisher, who began the season by
playing his way out of a starting job, has played himself back into
it in time for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis said Fisher will finish out the season as the
Los Angeles Lakers' starting point guard and continue into the
playoffs, which begin this weekend. Derek Harper, who started 29
games between Fisher's stints, will remain as the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the way it's kind of evolved with this team right
now,'' Rambis said. ``I just like the way that he starts, and Harp
gives us a big lift coming off the bench, and Ty (Lue) is kind of a
spot-minute guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has been steady if not spectacular, but then this team
has no shortage of spectacular with Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant. It was Fisher that Rambis went out of his way to praise
after Sunday's win at Seattle, when Fisher posted six points and
six assists and set the tone on both offense and defense with his
gutty play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Derek plays his butt off every night. It's unfortunate
our point-guard situation gets criticism,'' Rambis said. ``The
high-profile players get all the notice and stuff, but there's a
lot of players who do a lot of unselfish, unheralded things on this
team that never get recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is averaging 4.8 points, 4.4 assists and 1.9 turnovers in
19 starts this season, including a shaky nine games to start the
season which prompted Harper's insertion as the starter. But when
Rambis decided to rest Harper for the postseason, Fisher got
another chance and has earned the right to stay in the lineup.
Heading into Monday's game, he'd started eight straight games,
averaging 5.2 points, 4.2 assists and 1.4 turnovers in that span.
</P>
<P>
   Now he'll start in the playoffs for a second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's news to me,'' Fisher said, ``but at this point whatever
has to be done to keep us playing the way we've been playing,
that's what I'm for. If it was coming off the bench, starting,
whatever, I like the way things are going now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Prep time: If the Lakers hold onto the fourth seed and start
the playoffs at home, Rambis is considering a quick jaunt to Palm
Desert for a two-day minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being kicked around,'' he said. ``We're looking at
College of the Desert right now, but we're not 100 percent that
we're doing that yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
