<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-REDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS WIN DRAMA PRIZE, GAME, TIP D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Darren Holmes shrugged off the twisted ankle Monday
night, and, after one warm-up pitch, declared himself fine.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't. Not with his location.
</P>
<P>
   His sinker was sinking too much. His slider was breaking out of
the strike zone. Before he knew it, the Cincinnati Reds had the
bases loaded in the bottom of the ninth, a situation all so
familiar with the Diamondbacks' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cameron, on an 0-13 slide at the plate, one-hopped a pitch
off the right-field wall for a 4-3 victory that had the
Diamondbacks slowly walking off Cinergy Field, dejected by another
last-inning loss.
</P>
<P>
   They saw too many in the first week, and they're starting to see
them again.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the fell to Milwaukee, 6-5, after blowing two leads and
failing to score with the bases loaded and nobody out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, like anything, is cyclical, and the bullpen, it seems,
is hitting the bad cycle again.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not Brian Anderson and Gregg Olson, squandering leads,
one day. It's Holmes unable to get through one inning, the next.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Cameron's hit was the best pitch Holmes delivered _
a low-and-away fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he'd try to pull the ball and I wanted him to hit it on
the ground,'' Holmes said. ``It was a good at-bat. He's a good
hitter. He's going to be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   The blame can't all go to the bullpen. Greg Swindell gave the
Diamondbacks a chance with two shutout innings, before Holmes
started the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Andy Benes was willing to take some of the fall. He
walked two batters and gave up two hits in the first to put Arizona
(14-13) in a 3-0 hole. After that, however, his velocity improved,
his fastball was hitting the spots he wanted, and he looked closer
to the guy who shut the Reds down last year in a no-near no-hitter
than the one who came in with an 8.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad first inning,'' Benes said. ``I just wasn't
sharp. I fought back and we had a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bats fell silent in the last five innings when the only
hit was by left fielder Luis Gonzalez, who extended his
league-leading hitting streak to 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Credit starter Steve Parris, called up from Triple-A
Indianapolis for this game, and relievers Dennys (cq) Reyes, Scott
Sullivan and Scott Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long trip,'' Gonzalez said. ``Fourteen days feels
like a month already.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially coming of two three-plus hour games. Sunday's 3-hour,
37-minute game was Arizona's longest ever for nine innings.
Monday's game last 3:02.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have two more games with the Reds, before they
can come home.
</P>
<P>
   Two more games to try to right themselves in the pen and at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking a certain finality in the seventh, eighth,
and ninth innings,'' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``A lot of things
can happen. We have nine inning to score more runs. I try to put
that in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Things just didn't fall for the Diamondbacks. A potential big
inning was squashed in the second when Matt Williams, running on a
3-2 count, was nailed on his trail leg by a sharply hit grounder by
Damian Miller. The ball would have gone through, Williams would
have scored to make it a 3-1 game and runners would have beeen on
first and second with one out. Instead, Williams was out on the
play, and Parris got Tony Batista to ground out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored a run in the third on Jay Bell's fly in
the right-center gap that was hauled in by center fielder Cameron.
Bell had two other balls hit hard in the gaps that were caught by
the speedy outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff happens,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller tied the score at 3 in the fourth with his two-run homer
after Steve Finley triped with one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things happen when you close your eyes and swing,'' said
Miller, who didn't know he was going to start for ailing Kelly
Stinnett, until after he lifted weights in pre-game.
</P>
<P>
   If figured, it wouldnt be easy for the Diamondbacks in the ninth
when Holmes came up hobbling while fielding Aaron Boone's leadoff
bunt single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt when it happened, but I didn't feel it after that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Pokey Reese advanced Boone on a sacrifice, pinch hitter
Mark Sweeney was intentionally walke. Holmes walked pinch hitter
Hal Morris on four pitches and fell behind Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes never could get ahead in the count on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw some good 0-2 pitches (in my mind), just not against
them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
