r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-A     05-04 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN WOULD BOOST DRIVE FOR ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Welcome to Game 7, the best moment in sports, the
ultimate clash of pressure and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   And welcome to ground zero, the first of two hurdles that will
serve as radical turning points in the future of the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   When the puck drops this evening, you will see an entire
organ-I-zation ride a mad teeter-totter of emotion. When it's over,
people will be exhaling with victory. Or bracing for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And if you listen closely, you can almost hear the ground
moving.
</P>
<P>
   A win on May 4 doesn't _ to borrow a phrase from Coach Jim
Schoenfeld _ guarantee victory on May 18. But the two are certainly
related. More than ever, and much more than the owner wants to
admit.
</P>
<P>
   Simple as a ripple: As long as the Coyotes are playing, they
carry a buzz, make headlines, remain relevant. Advertising without
cost, escorting you to the doorstep of the Los Arcos referendum.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes prevail, the tail wind will be strong. They will
be hailed as conquerors, the team that finally went in and killed
the beast. You will look at them differently. And so will the
owner, Richard Burke.
</P>
<P>
   If they win, they accomplish everything.
</P>
<P>
   Before the playoffs, Burke was very comfortable, almost cocky
about his set of polling numbers. But the story has gotten a bit
complicated. Jeremy Roenick ended up in a hospital bed. A city
council member in favor of Los Arcos received a death threat. The
project's funding mechanisms came under new scrutiny. And at the
worst time, a hockey team took the dreaded detour. North. Toward
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes lose now, after a 3-1 lead in the series, the
dissection will not be pretty. For a few days, it will matter that
the Coyotes fought valiantly with what remained in the room. But
inevitably, they will be thrown into the blender of their past.
Because they fit the profile. Caretakers of the Evil Twinnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   As if the stifling pressure of a Game 7 weren't enough of a
load, this undeniable debris is swirling over the Coyotes. They
feel it, and, oh, how they bristle at this Winnipeg thing. They are
right in claiming distance, that most had nothing to do with a
tailgate legacy. What they don't understand is that history matters
in sports. That, to you and me, legacy is always part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Win, and it all goes away. Win, and maybe the owner wins, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a murky stage of finance redesign, the Los Arcos project
sorely needs a lift, a sales force, and none is better than the
hockey team. If the Coyotes win, the vote might pass. And if
victory brings victory, the owner will have his building, his
revenue streams, his chance to spend ``and'' feel good about
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes win one of these two battles _ a playoff series
or the referendum _ there is a good chance that the team will
remain largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   But if loss breeds loss, cover your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Arcos dies in the wake of a celebration that never
happened, there could be sweeping changes. You know about
Schoenfeld, but it would go deeper than the anointed scapegoat.
Burke is a passionate owner prone to mood swings. He is tired of
losing money trying to win. And if he must return to America West
Arena in defeat, no doubt, he will begin by cutting his losses.
</P>
<P>
   First, the crunching of numbers. Then, the big question: If the
gutting becomes too severe, does Bobby Smith jump off the train?
Leaving behind a couple of empty offices, a pair of titles and a
job tailor-made for the real phantom menace, Mike Keenan?
</P>
<P>
   So welcome to Game 7, an event dizzy enough on its own merits,
full of stress and finality, full of ends and beginnings. But this
time, the stakes are raised to an absurd level.
</P>
<P>
   Put your ear to the ground and you can hear the rumblings. A
sense of dread. And a party waiting to burst.
</P>
<P>
   No, not much going on tonight at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Just a night that may build a stadium. Or tear down the existing
walls. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
