<HEADER>
A3209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-04 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TWO weeks earlier in San Antonio, Mario Elie pounded the point home
in fitting and dramatic style.
</P>
<P>
   He nailed the game-winning 3-pointer against the Rockets in what
was then a huge game for both teams. He screamed. He stared at the
Rockets' bench with eyes that said, ``Take that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he pounded his fist on his chest, like a sort of kiss of
death. It was as if he was showing the Rockets that contrary to the
flat-line impression made in 1998, Elie's heart still was beating
like a champion's.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Sunday. In another huge game against the Utah Jazz,
Elie showed that heart again in a game that could lead the San
Antonio Spurs to the best record in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   There was Tim Duncan, who could win the Most Valuable Player
award. There was David Robinson, the former MVP whose role has
changed drastically. And there was still another player, Sean
Elliott, suddenly showing the kind of nerve that matched his skill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rockets were facing the Los Angeles Clippers,
trying to find their way into top playoff form, desperately trying
to fight their way to the No. 4 seed and a home-court playoff edge
against the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Could one player _ one mere complementary player such as Elie _
make such a difference? The Spurs say yes. The Rockets are left
only to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   As the playoffs now fast approach, it has become clear the
Rockets underestimated Elie at his best. They underestimated the
Elie who has a raging fire, a champion's heart and an undying will.
</P>
<P>
   They underestimated the Elie who is not afraid to tell a player
of Robinson's caliber that he needs to draw more out of his
basketball soul. They underestimated the Elie who can tell Elliott
he is indeed soft and then challenge him to fight like a champion.
They underestimated the Elie who can demand that Duncan show more
emotion on the floor and not be afraid to become the best player in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the Elie who was in a Rockets uniform a year ago.
And that's why the Rockets can only wonder if Elie would have made
these 1999 Rockets better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Elie the Rockets knew a year ago often was surly, less
productive than expected and a mere shell of the emotional force
that helped bring a pair of NBA championships to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He moped about not getting a two- or three-year contract
extension. He felt hurt and unappreciated when his name was
mentioned in trade rumors. Eventually he left, and the Rockets felt
better off because of it. But were they?
</P>
<P>
   Elie was a huge presence in San Antonio's win over the Jazz, as
he has been in so many games this year. He scored 15 points, and
his influence on Duncan, Robinson and Elliott never was more clear.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was the second choice in the Spurs' attack all day, as
he has been throughout their resurgent 1999. But he seemed to revel
in it all, with huge rebounds, tip-ins and blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott hit big free throws down the stretch and was unshakable
in situations that once had him quaking in his Nikes. He drove and
dunked on Jazz star Karl Malone for a big bucket in the fourth
quarter. Later, when Malone tried to rattle Elliott before he took
a pair of crucial free throws, Malone flexed in front of Elliott
and said, ``Give me two, Sean.'' Elliott stared Malone in the face
and said, ``Yeah, I'll give you two.'' He sank both to secure the
win.
</P>
<P>
   Of Elliott's transformation, Elie said, ``I think Sean's gotten
tired of me riding him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Elie, Duncan said, ``He's been huge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the season, San Antonio was a team in transition,
perhaps not to the point the Rockets were in transition, but
looking for its way nonetheless. The Spurs were soft.
Underachieving in the playoffs. Robinson's role needed to change.
Duncan needed to assert himself as the focal point. Clearly, the
Spurs needed Elie and are better because of him.
</P>
<P>
   Would a new contract and the influx of new faces have been
enough to reignite Elie's fire in Houston had he stayed? Or would
the Rockets' transition season with Scottie Pippen have been
complicated even more, with rookies Michael Dickerson, Cuttino
Mobley and Bryce Drew getting some of Elie's minutes and so many
postgame locker-room scenes finding Elie surly and mumbling again?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only a team such as San Antonio could have brought out
Elie's best. Perhaps only a team desperate to find a championship
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Lakers, whose search for direction went so far as
the signing of a caricature _ Dennis Rodman _ could have used him.
Rest assured, Elie would not have been afraid to look Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant in the face and tell them what it was all
about.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Sonics, who are out of the playoffs despite talents
such as Gary Payton, Vin Baker and Detlef Schrempf, could have
found heart with Elie rattling cages and bluntly quashing egos.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are still searching for their championship-caliber
game. They can only wonder. But the Spurs wonder no more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
