<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-GAME-7-AZ     05-04 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-GAME-7-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR TALK IS OVER  
 THERE'S PLENTY ON THE LINE AS ROUND 1 REACHES END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it all boils down tonight for Coach Jim Schoenfeld
and the Coyotes. Nothing more, nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   If they beat the St. Louis Blues tonight at America West Arena
in Game 7 of their nail-biting, first-round playoff series, as
Schoenfeld boldly has guaranteed, the Coyotes move on.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose, Schoenfeld is under the impression that ``he''
likely will be on the move _ looking elsewhere for work. The
second-year coach gave more credence to mounting speculation that
he could be relieved of his duties if the Coyotes don't make it out
of the first round for the first time since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise has managed to accomplish that task only twice _
both times as the Winnipeg Jets _ in its 20-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``History this, history that,'' snorted Coyotes forward Dallas
Drake, who leads the club in postseason scoring with four goals and
seven points. ``You guys have to write about that, but 99 percent
of the guys on this team weren't around for the Winnipeg days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can write about the Winnipeg stuff all you want, but it's
up to the 20 guys in here to just forget about it and go play.''
</P>
<P>
   Put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Faceoff is at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As if this Western Conference quarterfinal series didn't have
enough twists and turns and one-goal-game drama, Schoenfeld made
sure it became the most talked-about match-up so far in the
postseason with his surprising post-game prediction on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After the Blues scored twice in the third period of Game 6 to
snap a 3-3 tie and hang on for their second straight win after
losing three in a row, Schoenfeld uncorked this beauty:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win Game 7. . . . I would tell you I would
stake my job on it, but that's already been done, so I'll just say
we're going to win Game 7. Thanks, fellas.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the fiery former NHL defenseman who's grabbed
headlines during the postseason before as a coach with things to
say, abruptly cut short his question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   He'll probably want to make it even shorter if the Coyotes are
eliminated and allow St. Louis to become just the 15th team since
the best-of-seven format was introduced to the Stanley Cup playoffs
in 1939 to rally from a 3-1 deficit to win the series.
</P>
<P>
   It would be so Winnipeg-like, too, if it happens. You can
already hear the one-liners coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do the Coyo-Jets keep getting kicked out of bars?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they can't handle the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix players will tell you it's unfair to link their
first three seasons in the Valley to any past first-round failures
by the Lose-ipeg Jets. They shouldn't be held accountable for the
sins of their forechecking fathers, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody from the past is still here so we can't
go around carrying their baggage,'' center Mike Stapleton said.
``The Coyotes are a new organization, so I don't think we bring any
of that with us.''
</P>
<P>
   They probably shouldn't, either. But there's only one way to
make it permanent. Put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the team that can do it,'' center Bob Corkum
said. ``Everybody will step up and we'll get the job done and get
this Winnipeg jinx or whatever the media is calling it off our
backs. And then, I never want to hear it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hear this: The Blues hail from the ``Show Me'' state of
Missouri, and they aren't as impressed with talk as they are
action. They haven't been impressed with the Coyotes'
penalty-killing units, either. St. Louis has rattled off an NHL
playoff-high nine power-play goals in the series so far and are on
pace to break the 1990-91 Minnesota North Stars' record of 35 if
they make it to the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schoenfeld, of course, the Blues are toast tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' St. Louis forward Scott Young said.
``It's just a way for him to try and pump up his team. We've got
the momentum and he's just trying to get his troops going.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many sports personalities have been able to make gutsy
guarantees like that and get away with it. Joe Namath did and the
New York Jets won a Super Bowl. Mark Messier did and the New York
Rangers won the Stanley Cup in 1994. So did former Suns Coach Paul
Westphal, whose team got past the pesky Los Angeles Lakers in 1993
and advanced to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just trying to let everyone know he's behind us,'' Drake
said of Schoenfeld. ``Unfortunately, he's trying to take the
responsibility right now and he shouldn't. It's the 20 guys in that
room. The coaches have come up with a good game plan for us. It's
up to us 20 guys to go out and do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner advances to the conference semifinals to meet the
Dallas Stars or, if San Jose can knock off Colorado, the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're going into this game thinking we're going to win,
too,'' Coyotes forward Stephen Leach said. ``We're going out with
the mind-set it's going to be fun. A lot of guys in this room have
played in Game 7s before and that's what hockey's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   A win, and the season, the coach, and maybe even hopes for a new
arena are saved. A loss, and you probably can expect changes from
top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure's on to win, that's the bottom line,'' Coyotes
captain Keith Tkachuk said. ``The pressure's on them to win, too.
Nothing else matters. What happened in the first six games, you can
just throw out the window. . . . We'll see if home ice pays off in
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'll also see if Tkachuk and the Coyotes' other top dogs
can break out offensively in the biggest game of this franchise's
life. Tkachuk has one goal. Robert Reichel has one goal. Rick
Tocchet has none.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to produce, no question,'' said Tkachuk, who led
Phoenix in goals (36) during the regular season for the fourth
straight year. ``It comes down to one game and who wants it more
and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, put up or shut up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
