<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GOES HOME TO HEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals rookie  &UR; David Boston was supposed to go
to Boca Raton, Fla., in the next two weeks to train with All-Pro
wide receiver  &UR; Cris
 &UR; Carter of the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   The workout will have to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, the Ohio State wide receiver picked eighth overall,
instead has returned to his hometown of Houston to recover from a
fractured bone in his left shoulder suffered at Sunday's minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   His sister,  &UR; Alicia, who also is one of his agents, said Boston
still is hurting but is not upset about the injury, which is
expected to keep him out about a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday, he was in shock,'' she said. ``He couldn't believe it
had happened. He didn't talk to anybody because he was in pain. He
still doesn't feel very good. But otherwise he's doing OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia, a Dallas attorney, said her brother is relieved that he
doesn't have to have surgery and that the bone will heal on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   She said team orthopedist  &UR; Russell Chick and offensive
coordinator  &UR; Marc
 &UR; Trestman called Monday to see how the rookie was feeling.
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother and second-year cornerback  &UR; Corey Chavous,
whose collision with Boston caused the injury, have spoken and that
there is no problem between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at the tape and they both know it was an
accident,'' she said of the play that happened during a no-pads
workout. ``Corey apologized and told David he even tried to stop
himself (from colliding). Everything is fine between them.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury isn't expected to have an effect on Boston's contract
negotiations, which haven't begun. Doctors have told Boston he will
be fully recovered by the July 30 start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Fast start &QL; 
Second-year wide receiver  &UR; Andy McCullough continues to tear up the
NFL Europe League.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough's five catches for 109 yards and one touchdown give
him 17 receptions for 298 yards and three scores this season.
McCullough, who plays for the Frankfurt Galaxy, is second in the
league in receptions and scores.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end  &UR; Jomo Cousins, who plays for Berlin, is third in
the league in sacks with three. &QL; 
Full of confidence &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle  &UR; Anthony Clement, who has predicted he will win
the starting left tackle job, said doctors have told him they
aren't certain his back will be 100 percent healed when training
camp opens.
</P>
<P>
   Clement, who missed all but one game last season because of a
herniated disc in his back, is optimistic he'll be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in my heart I'll be ready,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Lee Shappell contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
