<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NJ-VERNIERO-NYT &LR;      05-04 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NJ-VERNIERO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LOYALTY AS A COURT CREDENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey has described State Attorney
General Peter Verniero, whom she has nominated to the New Jersey
Supreme Court, as ``110 percent loyal.'' She has rewarded that
loyalty by appointing him to ever-higher positions, making him her
chief counsel, chief of staff and then attorney general in 1996.
But personal loyalty to Whitman is not a good enough reason to
promote Verniero to a seat on the state's highest court, a position
that he may hold for 30 years. The Republican-controlled State
Senate should reject Verniero's nomination for his lack of legal
experience and his long failure to stop the use of racial profiling
by the New Jersey State Police, which his office oversees.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court has a history of intellectual rigor
and nonpartisanship. Verniero, who barely meets the State
Constitution's requirement of 10 years of legal practice, has spent
years as a political appointee. Prior to 1993, when he joined the
Whitman administration, he had worked less than six years in
private law practice. His lack of experience has made his
nomination controversial in the legal community.
</P>
<P>
   His performance in office also argues against his elevation to
the Supreme Court. For nearly his entire tenure as attorney
general, Verniero denied that the state police discriminated
against minority drivers. Despite a court ruling in 1996
substantiating racial bias in traffic stops, Verniero continued to
defend the state troopers. Last week, in appearing before a State
Senate committee, he refused to accept blame for doing nothing for
years about a problem he now acknowledges exists.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero is not the first attorney general to ignore complaints
of racial harassment by the state police. But his failure to take
timely action shows he lacks the legal judgment needed on the high
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
