<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NO MORE COMEBACKS FOR ELWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 4:
</P>
<P>
   John Elway, who retired Sunday after 16 seasons as quarterback
for the Denver Broncos, is the third exceptional athlete to leave
the American sporting scene this year. Michael Jordan said farewell
to basketball in January and Wayne Gretzky ended his hockey career
in April. Elway does not rise to quite the same level as Jordan or
Gretzky, each of whom may have been the best player in the history
of his sport. It would be hard to make a case that Elway was the
``best'' of a breed that includes Sammy Baugh, Johnny Unitas, Joe
Namath and Joe Montana. But he was certainly something special, and
football will be poorer without him.
</P>
<P>
   There are two words that Elway brings to mind _ toughness and
confidence. Elway was the master of the comeback, scrambling and
improvising as the final seconds ticked away, then rifling the ball
to an open receiver in the end zone. In this category, he is
indisputably the best of all time _ engineering 47 game-winning or
game-tying drives in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For years, it appeared that football's greatest prize, a Super
Bowl victory, would elude him. Denver lost in its first three
appearances, but in 1998, Elway got his first championship,
direct-ing a fourth-quarter drive to defeat the favored Green Bay
Packers. He won his second title last January.
</P>
<P>
   Elway says he will now spend more time with his family and on
the golf course, which should be a lot easier on his 38-year-old
body. Despite limited playing time, he regularly shoots par, and
has driven a ball 380 yards in Denver's rarefied air. Television
viewers may not have seen the last of his toothy grin and
competitive fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
