<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-GAME-7-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES SURVIVE HULL EXIT  
 OTHER PLAYERS CREATE IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He was the spirit of St. Louis, the life principle of
a sporting community longing for greatness from its hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blues lost career scoring leader Brett Hull to free
agency last summer, fans led the cry of ``Now what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what'' can be seen tonight at America West Arena, as the
Blues and Coyotes face off for Game 7 of their Western Conference
playoff series. Suggesting the team is better off without Hull, who
signed with Dallas, is absurd, but the Blues are successful in a
different way and are on the verge of eliminating the Coyotes from
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season, any time we had a two-game slump or a shutout, it
was `Brett Hull, Brett Hull' with the media,'' defenseman Jamie
Rivers said. ``Hopefully, after the season's done, we'll never hear
about Brett Hull again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean that in a bad way. He was a good guy and a great
hockey player, but he's not a St. Louis Blue anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull not only was a great scorer, but because he attracted
attention, he opened room for his linemates, particularly on the
power play. Yet an area that was expected to suffer this season
finished third in the NHL after tying for ninth last season.
</P>
<P>
   The key has been the point play. Al MacInnis' slap shot from the
right is downright intimidating, and Chris Pronger, who stepped in
at left point when Steve Duchesne left, is creative and dangerous.
Down low, Pierre Durgeon is the biggest factor behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Chris and Al make good decisions with the puck,'' St.
Louis Coach Joel Quenneville said, ``whether it's a shooting power
play or a more controlled power play. I think these guys recognize
the type of pressure they're facing. They improvise very well,
which is probably the best kind of power play.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of a legitimate star, 24-year-old Pavol Demitra,
the Blues' go-to guy and top scoring threat, also surfaced after
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   The forward led the team in goals, assists, points and power
play goals this season and was second in the NHL in game-winning
goals (10).
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great year, and maybe if Brett was over there, he
wouldn't have been able to use his shot and skills as much,'' left
wing Geoff Courtnall said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the players were eager to see Hull leave. Yes, he was
opinionated and honest, but he was also well-liked and he wasn't
nearly as divisive in the locker room as many believe.
</P>
<P>
   His contractual differences with management did make life
interesting last season. The issue was less about money than about
the Blues' unwillingness to put a no-trade clause in his new deal.
The Stars were willing and signed the standout to a three-year, $17
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, a Blues victory tonight could set up a
second-round meeting with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hull's contract talks were so public, his teammates
weren't stunned when he wasn't re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Courtnall said. ``We went through so much of it
last year when Brett was upset and he voiced his opinions in the
paper. They were really in a battle all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who took it hardest were the fans, who couldn't understand
how the organization could let a legitimate superstar go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame the fans in St. Louis,'' said Larry Pleau,
Blues senior vice president and general manager. ``He played on the
team for 10 years, and he was one of the best goal scorers ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things always can be bumpy, but I felt the way Brett
handled it, so professional, kept it from being really rocky. He
had his reasons, we had ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall said: ``I think it shows what a great group this is
and what a great job the coaching staff has done this year. When
you lose a guy like him that puts up 80 points a year, yet your
power play is one of the best in the league and you still have a
lot of success, it says a lot about this organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
