<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAKE'S PLAY EARNS PRAISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  AND TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He's played right wing, left wing, been moved from the
first line to the second and back again, but it seems no matter
where the Coyotes play him, they know they're going to get an
honest effort from veteran  &UR; Dallas Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Drake has scored at least a point in five of six playoff games
and leads the club in postseason scoring with seven points on four
goals and three assists. He had just three goals in 21 previous
playoff games before this series against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's played great so far,'' goalie  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin
said. ``He's been our top scorer and he's really stepped up his
game more than anybody else. I've known Dally for a pretty long
time and I know he can play good, so this isn't a big surprise, but
it's a good one.'' &QL; 
Time bandits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting developments in the series is the
staggering amount of ice time being logged by Blues defensemen
 &UR; Chris Pronger and  &UR; Al
 &UR; MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger has played 34 minutes, 52 seconds, 40:14, 33:38, 30:19,
37:39. In Sunday's Game 6 he logged 33:39. MacInnis has logged ice
chunks of 31:59, 37:16, 34:26, 34:42, 36.09 and 36:10,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I'd do if I ever got that much ice time,''
Coyotes forward  &UR; Louie DeBrusk said, ``I'd probably have to go
right to the hospital and have to be put on life-support systems
because I'd probably die. I have no idea how they do that, but
those two guys are phenomenal athletes. It's unbelievable. I take
my hat off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger averaged a league-high 30.6 minutes during the regular
season. MacInnis ranked fourth overall at 29.1. The Coyotes'
ice-time leader was defenseman  &UR; Teppo Numminen at 24.4. &QL; 
Cup crazy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Injured center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick, contemplating returning for the
playoffs _ perhaps tonight? _ despite a broken jaw and a fractured
thumb, was asked what his wife,  &UR; Tracey, thinks of his decision:
</P>
<P>
   ``She already knows I'm nuts.'' &QL; 
No home cooking &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes worked hard for 82 regular-season games to gain no
worse than a No. 4 seed so they could have home-ice advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Their first-round series will go the distance of seven games,
but MacInnis, the Blues' playoff scorer leader with nine points,
pretty much thumbs his nose at the Coyotes' home-ice edge. He
points out that each team has won two games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think home ice is a big advantage in Game 7,''
MacInnis said. ``In fact, it doesn't seem to be much of an
advantage at all in this series. We're ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been facing elimination now for two games. They're the
team that kind of had the pressure off them.'' &QL; 
Grant is correct &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grant Fuhr said after Game 1 that he likes playing before the
whiteout crowds in America West Arena for the playoffs, largely
because it enables him to see the puck better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably does help,'' said the Coyotes' Khabibulin. ``White
is white and black is black. The puck stands out more.''
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested that perhaps the team should provide end zone
fans black flash cards _ such as those used in football card
sections _ which they could hold up on each Coyotes shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do, move the fans every period when we
exchange ends?'' he asked. &QL; 
The big hurt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a slap shot from  &UR; Chris McAlpine, not
MacInnis, that caught Coyotes left wing  &UR; Mike Sullivan in the left
leg during Friday night's 2-1 loss in Game 5. But the shot was
still painful enough to force Sullivan to skip Game 6 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His availability tonight is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also are without  &UR; Juha Ylonen (fractured foot) and
 &UR; Greg Adams, who missed his second straight game because of a
pulled groin and is questionable for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let it wear on you,'' Sullivan said. ``Every team
goes through injuries and we've had our fair share, but I think
guys have stepped up when other guys have been out of the lineup
and the team has found ways to win.'' &QL; 
By the numbers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr passed  &UR; Billy Smith on the all-time playoff victory list,
moving to No. 2 behind Colorado's  &UR; Patrick Roy with his 89th career
postseason win. Roy entered Monday's game with 102 victories.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis has 100 career playoff assists, moving him ahead of
 &UR; Guy Lafleur into 23rd place in all-time playoff scoring with 135
points.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
