<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS PLAYER OF MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Diamondbacks third baseman  &UR; Matt Williams was
honored on Monday as the National League Player of the Month for
April, but he considered it more a team honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't ultimately be there if  &UR; Jay Bell wasn't having a
great season and  &UR; (Tony) Womack wasn't getting on base and  &UR; Luis
Gonzalez wasn't hitting as well as he is,'' said Williams, who had
a league-best 25 RBIs for April and hit .357 with eight home runs
and had a .694 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a Diamondback was honored as player of the
month. Bell and Williams were named NL player of the week,
back-to-back, in April.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Williams was honored for a month was May '95, when
he hit .404 with 12 homers and 31 RBIs for San Francisco. Williams
had forgotten about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just goes to show how much it means,'' he said. ``I can't
even remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it's nice, but you play the game to get to the
playoffs and win the World Series, not for individual awards.'' &QL; 
Cursed tattoo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just above reliever  &UR; Greg Swindell's right ankle is a tattoo of
a T crossed through a horseshoe.
</P>
<P>
   He said the T came about a year after the horseshoe, which he
got while pitching for the Houston Astros in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's supposed to be for good luck, right?'' Swindell said.
``After I got it, I had the worst (expletive) year of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was slowed by a groin injury and, with a 7.83 ERA and 0-3
record, the Astros released him.
</P>
<P>
   The following spring, in Fort Myers, Fla., Swindell was back in
the tattoo parlor. Not to get rid of the horseshoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have cost $1,000 to get rid of it,'' he said. ``I
just had them put a T through it.'' &QL; 
Weighing in &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do the Diamondbacks do in the clubhouse in their spare
time? Monday, at Cinergy Field, they were weighing heads. Pitcher
 &UR; Brian Anderson's head weighed 13 pounds. Assistant athletic
trainer  &UR; Dave Edwards led those who weighed in at 19{.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got too many brains,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Edwards, ``It's dead matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The readings were made by laying on the ground and putting their
heads on the scale.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre suggested a better way of achieving a
more accurate reading of everyone's heads: ``Chop them off.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher  &UR; Kelly Stinnett was a late scratch from Monday's lineup,
because of flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said he may give Bell a day off at
second base during this three-game series. That means Womack would
return from the outfield to play his natural position. Asked
whether he thought Womack would mind, Showalter's answer was an
emphatic no.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching three straight days, closer  &UR; Gregg Olson was not
an option Monday, Showalter said. Olson gave up a three-run homer
to
 &UR; Marquis Grissom in the eighth inning of Sunday's 6-5 loss to
Milwaukee. Olson said the difference between that blown save and
the three he blew the opening week is, ``I won't carry this one
with me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
