<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS PUT CELTICS IN A CLINCH
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-CELTICS-KNICKS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By PETER MAY 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just for the record, Patrick Ewing would like you to
know a few things. He's not done. He doesn't care if you think he's
done. He doesn't care if we think he's done. And when he is done,
he'll know it.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Monday night's performance, there's still some fuel in
the tank.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing willed his Knicks to victory, a 95-88 decision over the
Celtics at Madison Square Garden that clinched a playoff spot. In
38 minutes, he had 27 points, 19 rebounds (a season high), and 2
blocked shots as New York earned a playoff spot for the 12th
straight year, the top active streak among Eastern Conference
teams. All this came on a sore left Achilles' tendon that had
knocked Ewing out of three of the previous four games. Not to
mention sore knees and who knows what else.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know with Pat who's going to show up,'' said Tony
Battie, who had 14 points, 10 rebounds, and 3 blocks. ``Everybody
knows he's a great player, but sometimes he doesn't have real good
games. He might have a good game. (Monday night) was his night. He
had a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, of course, is the lightning rod for much of what has gone
awry with the Knicks this season. Critics say he won't yield his
all-consuming role in the offense and that at age 36, he doesn't
realize he's not the player he once was. He has missed 11 games
with the heel problem; the Knicks are 6-5 without him.
</P>
<P>
   But they needed him Monday night. Allan Houston had a good night
(21) and triggered the game-breaking 9-0 run down the stretch that
snapped an 81-81 tie, the third of the night. But Ewing was clearly
the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick carried us,'' Latrell Sprewell said.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of his vintage performance, St. Patrick was
happy to remind skeptics, critics, and anti-Ewings of that very
fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been writing me off for a long time,'' he said. ``I
don't listen to anything you all write (sic). I believe in myself.
I don't care what they think. I don't care what any of you think. I
believe in myself. The day I don't believe in myself, that's the
day I retire. When my body is healthy, I can still perform at a
high level.''
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't healthy. That's not a trade secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows it,'' said Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy.
``That's what makes me marvel at what he can do, mindwise. His will
to be great superseded his health.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks brought in some cast members from the musical
``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' to perform before the game and at halftime. It
was a most appropriate choice. Each team had its Jekyll moments _
the Knicks led, 16-0, out of the box _ and each team had its Hyde
moments _ the Knicks blew leads of 16 points in the first quarter
and 10 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, meanwhile, got Jekyll/Hyde captain Antoine Walker
back in the lineup, but it would be a stretch to say he was back in
the game. Walker, who missed eight games with a sprained left
ankle, was predictably shaky and finished with 11 points (4 of 15),
7 rebounds, and 3 turnovers. Then again, we've seen those numbers
when he's been healthy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to get back to competition,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks trailed only once, in the second quarter by 1 point
on three occasions. They had leads of 16 in the first quarter, 12
in the third, and 10 in the fourth. The Celtics, who got 18 each
from Ron Mercer and Paul Pierce, stayed feisty to the bitter end,
rallying for 10 straight points to create the 81-81 deadlock with
5:18 to play.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine how the New York fans would have handled a
Knicks collapse with the playoffs on the line and hated Miami due
in Wednesday night for the season finale.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Houston wormed his way in for a scoop and was
fouled by Battie for a 3-point play. Mercer then threw it away and
Ewing followed with his final hoop, a jumper from the lane. Two
more Boston bricks, both by Pierce, begat Knicks hoops by Sprewell
and Houston, and the game was over. Start spreading the news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
