<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-COLISEUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL CALLING PLAY ON OWNERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK OROV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With negotiations entering a critical phase, the
National Football League has pressed its demand that it be able to
choose whatever ownership it wants for a new football franchise at
the Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Friday and obtained on Monday, NFL attorney
Frank Rothman asked Coliseum Commission President Sheldon Sloan for
more detailed information on the ability of the commission to
negotiate a deal with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Football League must have total flexibility,'' in
its ability to select an ownership group, Rothman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to earlier correspondence from Sloan in which the
Coliseum president asserted the panel was free to negotiate with
others despite a memorandum of understanding with the New Coliseum
Partnership of Ed Roski and Eli Broad allowing two years to bring a
professional team to the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman said that Roski and Broad have told him they believe
they have exclusive rights to negotiation for an expansion
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disagreement between your interpretation and the
interpretation of Mr. Broad and Mr. Roski is of concern to the
NFL,'' Rothman said. ``It would be our view that this matter should
be straightened out by you and the New Coliseum Venture group.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has insisted for more than a month that it wanted to
see the Roski agreement voided, feeling it was being forced to
select the developer as an owner. Roski has said he would not be a
roadblock to the selection of an ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   However, the memorandum states he must be reimbursed up to $5
million in costs by any new team if he is not part of the
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said he was preparing a response to Rothman insisting the
Coliseum had the freedom to accept different owners and planned to
also send the agreement to the NFL for review.
</P>
<P>
   The letter comes at a tense point as the Roski-Broad group and
one headed by Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz and food magnate Ron
Burkle are completing the business plans the NFL wants to review
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both sides indicated they plan to have their
work wrapped up late this week or early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has said it will place an expansion team in the
Coliseum, but wants to reserve the right on selecting the ownership
group.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a new debate has developed over the impact of
professional football returning to the Coliseum on the University
of Southern California and the museums within Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   Also, questions are being asked over the level of public
involvement that will be required since the NFL has made clear it
expects a significant public investment as part of the award of any
expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue has indicated a willingness to
accept what local officials have offered.
</P>
<P>
   That amounts to some $348 million, including $85 million in land
value, $110 million in earthquake retrofit work on the Coliseum,
$113 million in work done on the Harbor Freeway and $20 million
from the Community Redevelopment Agency as well as $20 million in
revenue from a ticket surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Additional public funds could be needed for a parking facility.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said whoever gets the franchise would need to have
near-total control of the Coliseum for all types of events to turn
much profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at only a 1 to 2 percent return at best,'' said
one official close to the discussions. ``You have $300 million in
work to remodel the Coliseum and another $600 million to $700
million for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a $1 billion investment that you're not going to get
back with just eight football games a year. You need to have the
right to put on soccer matches, concerts and other things to turn a
profit.''
</P>
<P>
   John Semcken, executive vice president of New Coliseum Partners,
said the group has been working with the different museums and
cultural facilities in Exposition Park as well as USC on its plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about making sure we accommodate their
ability to operate during games,'' Semcken said. ``We think the
return of football to Exposition Park will help everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said the commission would insist that the needs of the
other tenants be assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are there and they added a huge amount of credibility to
the bid of the Coliseum,'' Sloan said. ``We benefited from those
institutions and, by the same token, a renewed Coliseum will bring
millions of new people to the park, many of whom have never been
there before. I think we will see an increase in attendance if
football returns.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
