<HEADLINE>
NO DEFECTS IN CUBA'S GAME
</HEADLINE>
 BB-CUBA-ORIOLES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By STEVE FAINARU 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ In a game cloaked in political symbolism, Cuba's
powerhouse national team whipped the Orioles Monday night at Camden
Yards, 12-6, in a strange exhibition that seemed to settle, at
least temporarily, the longstanding debate over whether the Cubans
can compete with major league teams.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, Cuba lost the first game of the home-and-home
series with Baltimore, 3-2, in 11 innings at Havana. Monday night,
in their first appearance in the US since the 1959 revolution, the
Cubans hammered the worst team in the American League for 18 hits,
held Baltimore to six, and seemed to be in almost constant motion
after a 56-minute rain delay in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation had centered on how many Cubans might use the
opportunity to defect. The team's hotel crawled Monday afternoon
with Baltimore police officers, Cuban security officials, major
league scouts, and covetous agents in what seemed to be an odd
waiting game to see who might make a run for the front door.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, no one did. The Cubans clearly had come to play, not
leave their country. Omar Linares, the team's legendary third
baseman, described the game as ``a dream come true.'' By contrast,
the Orioles treated the game like a chore. Right fielder Albert
Belle told fans on his website: ``Most of us probably still would
have preferred to have the day off.''
</P>
<P>
   But he allowed that the stakes were high: ``We want to win no
matter who we're up against,'' he wrote. ``But there's also the
underlying theme that this game is about democracy vs. Communism,
so that adds a little something more to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If that was so, the death of communism has been greatly
exaggerated. Rumors circulated that Fidel Castro exhorted the
Cubans before takeoff Sunday. Unlike the Havana game, which several
players missed for the Cuban league playoffs, the core of the
amateur team that has dominated international play for years was
here: Linares, first baseman Orestes Kindelan, and second baseman
Antonio Pacheco, who have combined for 1,060 career homers. But the
barrage was led by the No. 9 hitter, Danel Castro, who went 4 for 5
with two triples.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Orioles removed their five starting pitchers
from the roster. They started a pitcher who is on the disabled
list, Scott Kamieniecki. Still, the starting lineup included Brady
Anderson, B.J. Surhoff, Belle, Harold Baines, and Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans started righthander Jose Conteras, who dominated the
Orioles in Havana. Conteras faltered after 2 1/3 innings, but Norge
Vera, a 28-year-old sidearming righthander, didn't give up a hit
for the next two hours. He lasted until the ninth, when he tired
and gave up a three-run homer to Delino DeShields. He struck out
Belle, who seemed utterly uninterested, twice.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the event seemed evident most of the day. At a
morning news conference, Humberto Rodriguez Gonzalez, the Cuban
sports minister, refused to answer a question from a reporter for
Radio Marti, the anti-Castro radio station. The press conference
became heated when Rodriguez was asked about German Mesa, who was
left off the trip, even though many still believe he is the finest
shortstop in the history of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, along with pitcher Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez and
catcher Alberto Hernandez, had been banned in 1997 for allegedly
plotting to defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, discipline is a key fact of sports, and discipline
doesn't have a name,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom does,'' said the questioner, a Miami television
reporter, before the debate was cut off by Orioles spokesman John
Maroon.
</P>
<P>
   But the political moment of the evening came in the top of the
fifth, when a man ran on the field and waved a sign that read,
``Freedom! Strike Out Castro.'' Cesar Valdez, the Cuban second base
umpire, intercepted the man in short center field, picked him up,
and body-slammed him to the ground before an army of police
officers and plainclothes Cuban security agents wrestled him to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of protesters _ both anti-Castro and anti-embargo _
gathered outside before the game but did nothing to stop a capacity
crowd from pouring into Camden Yards. Even Joe Cubas, the
Miami-based agent who vowed last week to bag another defector, was
nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if one of them wanted to leave, they'd have to be
Superman,'' said Mike Brito, a Cuban-born scout, standing outside
the Sheraton. ``They'd have to crash through that window right
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
