<HEADER>
A3234 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS &LR;      05-04 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The way Chris Holt feels, he's not digging early holes
for himself. They're more like craters.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holt spotted the New York Mets a four-run advantage after the
first inning Monday night, and the Astros again ran out of time to
crawl out in a 5-3 loss at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss, only the Astros' third in their last 11 games, snapped
their season-high four-game winning streak. And New York continued
to be one of the hottest teams in baseball, extending its winning
streak to six.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first inning is killing me,'' said Holt, who allowed four
hits, a walk and a hit batsman in the first. ``I've been putting us
out of the game. You can't put your team in a hole 4-0 and expect
it's going to be easy to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on a night when the Astros struggled to generate any
offense. They finished with their second-lowest hit total (six) of
the season, and the top four men in the lineup went a collective
2-for-14 with five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   New York righthander Rick Reed, making his first start since
being placed on the disabled list with a slightly torn calf muscle
April 12, allowed three runs and five hits while striking out six.
At one point, Reed (2-0) retired 11 straight batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised we didn't find a way to score some more runs,''
said Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose team entered the game with
a National League-leading .295 batting average. ``You can't explain
everything. I can explain why they hit Chris, because he got behind
in the count and threw the ball down the middle. I can't explain
why we didn't do a little bit better against Reed.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Holt (0-4) is still searching for his first victory
since Aug. 21, 1997. He missed all of last season after undergoing
rotator-cuff surgery on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The source of his latest problems was a familiar one. Holt left
pitches high and over the plate during a 40-pitch first inning. He
has allowed nine runs in the first inning this season.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeo led off the New York first with a single, John
Olerud walked two batters later, and Mike Piazza delivered an RBI
single through the hole at shortstop to put the Mets ahead 1-0.
Robin Ventura loaded the bases with a single, and Holt pushed
across a run when he hit Mike Kinkade.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae added a two-run single to put the Mets in front 4-0.
The Mets sent nine batters to the plate in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to control my adrenalin,'' said Holt, who in five
starts has allowed 21 runs in 28 innings. ``I'm leaving pitches up
and making bad pitches. You give up runs when you do that. I can't
live up there. It's easy to stay downstairs (in the strike zone)
and then come up if you have to. But when you're staying up, it's
harder to come down, and that's one thing I have to get mentally in
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed five runs, eight hits and four walks in six
innings. After the first, he settled down to allow only one run and
four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big hurdle with him is we have to get him a win,'' Dierker
said. ``He's throwing the ball really well, but he hasn't had a win
in over a year. It's been a long time since he's had that winning
feeling. If we can get him back in the winner's circle, I think we
are going to have ourselves a pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got one run back in the second inning when Ken
Caminiti led off with a walk, advanced to second on a single by
Paul Bako and scored on a two-out single by Holt.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was nearly untouchable over the next three innings,
allowing just a single to Derek Bell in the third before Richard
Hidalgo's two-run homer in the sixth pulled the Astros within 4-3.
The 402-foot shot to left-center field was Hidalgo's sixth homer
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said the long layoff factored into his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time I've been on the DL,'' Reed said. ``It
seemed like forever. It was tough waiting. I just wanted to go out
there and pitch at least six innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pushed their lead back to two runs in the sixth when
Cedeo led off with a double, stole third and scored on Edgardo
Alfonzo's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Think Reed was tough for the Astros? Try facing the Mets'
bullpen, which pitched three scoreless innings to lower its NL-best
ERA to 2.50. Turk Wendell pitched two scoreless innings, and John
Franco pitched a 1-2-3 ninth for his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   With Craig Biggio at first, the Astros had the tying run at the
plate in the seventh against Wendell. But Bell struck out for the
third time in the game and seventh in his last nine at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be able to score Holt some runs,'' Biggio said.
``But tonight we just didn't give him enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
