<HEADLINE>
CUBAN NATIONAL TEAM CRUSHES ORIOLES, 12-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Baltimore Orioles on Monday night took one small
step for international diplomacy and one huge step for their own
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The team that already had the second-worst record and the
second-highest payroll in the major leagues pitched poorly, hit
ineptly and fielded sloppily as the Cuban national team won a
historic exhibition game, 12-6, in the second game of the
home-and-home series between the teams. The Cubans outhit the
professionals, 18-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, who barely won the first game in 11 innings in
Havana on March 28, should be grateful that no third game is
scheduled. Their manager, Ray Miller, should be grateful if he does
not lose his job over Monday night's debacle. Already teetering on
the brink of dismissal, Miller could find out quickly that this
game was the one that prompted Peter Angelos, the Orioles' owner,
to take the step that he has been reluctant to take.
</P>
<P>
   A Camden Yards crowd of 47,940, including a small knot of
exuberant Cubans seated behind their team's third-base dugout,
watched the Orioles disintegrate before their very eyes as the
Cubans outplayed them in every aspect of the game. ``I thought we
were geared up for the game,'' Miller said. ``Then the rain delay,
and they threw six runs up on the board. Obviously their desire was
much better than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Contreras, the pitcher who in relief allowed two hits and
struck out 10 in eight innings in Havana, faltered as the starter
this time, giving up three runs in one and one-third innings that
included a 56-minute rain delay. But just as he bailed out Jose
Ibar, the first-game starter, he himself was rescued on Monday
night by Norge Vera, a 27-year-old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 Vera even outdid the Contreras relief performance,
permitting the Orioles no hits in his first seven innings. He
finally weakened in the ninth as the Orioles rapped three
consecutive hits, the last a home run by Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry, however, made no dent in the outcome. Vera entered
the game in the second inning with two runners on, one out and the
Cubans ahead, 4-3, and shut down the Orioles while his hitting
teammates increased their lead. ''He was throwing breaking balls,
offspeed pitches, keeping his pitches down, throwing strikes on the
first pitch,'' Miller said, explaining Vera's success.
</P>
<P>
   Danel Castro, whose presence at shortstop in place of the almost
legendary German Mesa prompted some question and suspicion before
the game, justified his selection by collecting four hits,
including a pair of triples, scoring four runs and driving in two.
He singled in one time at bat in Havana, giving him five hits in
six tries against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the $13 million-a-year Albert Belle failed to get a
hit in three at-bats, striking out twice. In two games, he struck
out four times and got no hits in eight at-bats, failing to get the
ball out of the infield even once.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans applied the coup de grace in the ninth inning with a
finishing barrage of four extra-base hits and five runs against
Gabe Molina, the fifth and last Baltimore pitcher. The first hit
was Castro's second triple, the last a three-run home run over the
right-center field fence by Andy Morales, the Cubans' designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, in absolute shock and ecstasy, ran around the bases in
a manner not seen in major league games. He held his arms
outstretched most of the way, clapped, appeared to be flying,
motioned to the Cuban delegation sitting behind the Cubans' third
base dugout and as he neared home plate with arms outstretched,
looked skyward. His teammates, who had burst out of the dugout,
mobbed him.
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, the Cuban players gathered in the infield
and held two Cuban flags. The Orioles then emerged from their
dugout, to some boos, and the teams shook hands with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, other people went onto the field, though none was in
uniform. Five fans in all went onto the field, the first carrying a
small Cuban flag. Police calmly walked after the four interlopers
in the fourth inning, grabbed them and took them off the field.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the Cubans' fifth inning, another fan carrying a
small sign jumped onto the field and ran past second base. Cesar
Valdez, one of three Cuban umpires in the game, tackled the fan and
slammed him to the ground. They began tussling, and policemen
quickly rushed to the scene and pulled them apart.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff, the Orioles' left fielder, also ran to the spot
and appeared to keep one of the other Cuban umpires from becoming
involved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the game, Alfonso Urquoila was asked about the selection
of the 25-man roster, specifically why Mesa was not on the team.
``He was in the training sessions,'' Urquoila said. ``We have a lot
of good players. We took players who were in better condition right
now. I believe both shortstops we brought are in better condition
right now. They are the youngest players on the whole team. Both
are 22 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro was listed as 22 on the roster, but Michel Enrique, the
other shortstop, was listed as having been born in 1969, making him
30.
</P>
<P>
   Urquiola also said that Cuban officials were not leary of
possible defections, which have wracked the Cuban national team in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would feel if a Cuban player went into the
Baltimore dugout for a foul pop and did not come back, he said,
``We have no fear; we are not concerned about it. We let them play
freely on the field and we have no concern about it. We have no
fear. Otherwise we wouldn't be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
