<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CUBA GAME COULD OPEN SOME DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 5th graf for updating, rewriting) (lh) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The orange and black banners were hanging, giving a
festive feel to a soggy day.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Welcomes Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   This was not New York or Cleveland coming in for a big game.
This was the national team of Cuba. Salsa music danced out of the
Camden Yards loudspeakers, turning the arcade and the old brick
factory behind right field into a Latin plaza.
</P>
<P>
   When they hang out the bunting for the World Series, they don't
mention the opponent. It's just generic decoration. This was
different. This was one of the grand old baseball cities _ Wee
Willie, the Babe, Earl, Frank and Brooks _ playing host to a
baseball nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing they don't have automatic relegation in
baseball, the way they do in world soccer leagues, because the
inept Orioles would be good candidates for demotion after Monday
night's embarrassment, a 12-6 Cuba victory that more than made up
for the taut 3-2 Orioles victory on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we all will win,'' said Omar Linares, the superb
Cuban third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   But who really wins from this strange little sequence? You could
almost hear the baseball scouts salivating over the talent that
Cuba saw fit to load onto the plane. They would love to pick off a
few, to slip a few business cards into a few willing palms, but
what does that prove? Is there some bigger picture here?
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Welcomes Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans with memories of their homeland may fear that a
baseball relationship would only strengthen Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to say that a mere game or two cannot balance out
four decades of political repression in Cuba, economic sanctions
that the United States has imposed on Cuba, mutual bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were, big-timers with more than a bit of swagger,
in their glittering blue jackets, white pants and bright red ball
caps, playing in Camden Yards, a trifle more solemn than visitors
for a World Series, but ballplayers nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it sounded just like any other big sporting event,
with American sportswriters asking Alfonso Urquiola, the roly-poly
Cuban manager, why he had omitted this player or that player from
the road squad.
</P>
<P>
   Just the words ``Los Hermanos Hernandez _ the Hernandez
Brothers'' conjure up the specter of defection, but Urquiola
sounded like every other touchy manager when he said, ``I thought I
already explained that.'' Still, it was more than a game, it was a
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Welcomes Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   There is something to be said for gestures _ the nod, the smile,
the word, the phrase that just might lead to something better.
There is something to be said for gestures like Preacher Jackson
going into Serbia and bringing back three captured American
soldiers, making sure they are safe at home, and then letting the
politicians argue about who is using whom.
</P>
<P>
   What is the endgame for this little home-and-home gesture? Why
would Fidel Castro even permit the American professionals to play
his state-supported amateurs? What could be worth the intense
security, the fears of defection, even the possibility of
ignominious defeat? What's in it for Fidel?
</P>
<P>
   Here they were, the cream of the international baseball circuit,
big-timers who play teams from Russia, Japan, Mexico, the Dominican
Republic, Australia. This summer they will go to Winnipeg for the
Pan American Games. These guys get around.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Welcomes Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   If they were flabbergasted by the amenities of a chain hotel
alongside the glitzy renovated harbor, they were not about to let
on. Did they glance at the varieties and the prices of a
room-service menu? On the other hand, did they catch a glimpse of
America's poverty outside their bus window? They were not saying,
but they did not shy away from the impulses of their baseball
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are changes taking place,'' said Luis Ulacia, an
outfielder with a firm jaw and an appraising glance. ``We do not
rule out that Cuban players will play professionally some day. It
all depends on change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish not to be forced to defect,'' Ulacia said, talking
about joining the majors some day. ``It would be a beautiful
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would play for free, just to prove himself, Ulacia
brought up the U.S. sanctions. ``Because of the blockade, I believe
it would be difficult. If they gave us the opportunity to play, I
believe the Treasury Department would not let us get paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ulacia was making propaganda. There is plenty of that between
the countries. What is needed is the next step _ a series in
November, maybe, or a few Cuban players allowed to earn salaries in
the majors. There is something to be said for gestures.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Welcomes Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
