<HEADLINE>
SALMON INJURED IN LOSS TO CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels' road trip that will bring
Mo Vaughn back to Boston will begin without Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels learned after Monday afternoon's 8-1 loss to the
Chicago White Sox that Salmon probably will miss three games in
Detroit with a sprained left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, the club leader in batting average (.347), home runs (7)
and RBI (25), was injured in the fourth inning diving for Paul
Konerko's soft liner to right.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon remained in the game, but left in the fifth and was taken
to UC Irvine Medical Center. X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a day out or two or maybe three, I can live with
that,'' Salmon said. ``It's a little swollen and the doctor said it
probably would be really stiff tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon dove for Konerko's ball on his left side and nearly
jammed his knee in the turf. But he rolled his wrist trying to
break the fall. The ball rolled to the wall for a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw the play, I thought he hurt his leg,'' said
manager Terry Collins, who raced to right field with trainer Ned
Bergert. ``When I heard the X-rays were negative naturally I was
relieved. We would go on without him because we have to, but, jeez,
I don't even want to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon missed 26 games last season with a strained left arch.
With Mo Vaughn expected to return to first base during the trip,
the Angels could move Garrett Anderson from center field to right
and Darrin Erstad from first base to center. Vaughn, who has been
the Angels DH since returning from the disabled list (sprained left
ankle) April 22, still is hobbled by the injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick Hits:Left-hander Scott Schoeneweis replaced Tim Belcher
with one out in the fourth and allowed just one run in 32/3
innings. It was the longest outing of his three-week major league
career. . . . White Sox' left-fielder Jeff Abbott started Belcher's
undoing by opening the fifth with a home run that just cleared the
fence in left field. ``I didn't think it went out but it was so
high, it took forever before I knew,'' he said. About Belcher,
Abbott said, ``He got hurt by a couple of infield hits, but he also
threw some pitches right down the middle.'' Belcher is signed
through the next year at $5 million per season. . . . With a double
in the first inning, Chicago first baseman Frank Thomas broke Hall
of Famer Luke Appling's club record of 587 extra-base hits. Appling
did it in 2,422 games. It took Thomas 1,258. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
