<SLUG> BC-PLAINS-TORNADOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30 DEATHS REPORTED IN PLAINS TORNADOES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page)  (sw) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A band of vicious tornadoes streaked through Oklahoma and into
Kansas on Monday, killing at least 30 people and injuring hundreds.
The storms destroyed more than 600 homes, flattened entire towns
and scattered cars on highways like pins in a bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   At least 24 people were dead in Oklahoma and 6 in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of anything like this,'' Gov. Frank Keating
of Oklahoma told CNN on Monday night. ``The extent of the
devastation is unprecedented. Perhaps Alabama in the near past
would be close, but these are some of the biggest tornadoes that
have ever been reported here.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating called in the National Guard and estimated property
damage in the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Of those dead in Oklahoma, eight were killed in Chickasha, eight
in Oklahoma City, four in Midwest City, three in Moore, and one in
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said there were probably 10 to 20
separate tornadoes, the offspring of at least half a dozen tornadic
thunderstorms. The storms first struck about 80 miles southwest of
Oklahoma City around 5 p.m., the weather service said, and moved
northeast, through Chickasha, Norman, Oklahoma City and its
suburbs, and then fanned out northeast and northwest of Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service classified the Oklahoma tornado as at least
F-4, the second-strongest tornado classification.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Woodall, the warning coordination meteorologist for the
National Weather Service in Forth Worth, Texas, said that some of
the tornadoes were a half-mile wide. Spring is tornado season on
the Plains, Woodall said, but the storms seldom hit this hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're having tornadoes in May is not that
significant,'' he said. ``The significance is the number and the
amount of damage we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodall said that as the strom system continue to move north
through the night, more tornadoes were likely.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a suburb just south of Oklahoma City, was one of towns
hit hardest.
</P>
<P>
   The tornadoes caused widespread blackouts and ruptured natural
gas lines, raising the specter of deadly fires and hampering rescue
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Johnson, an emergency medical technician who lives in
Oklahoma City, said that when he went to Moore to help the victims
there, ``They made us leave because of the gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Austin, a Moore resident, huddled in a neighbor's storm
shelter as the tornado passed overhead. ``Basically it was a very
large black wall that just moved here,'' he told CNN. .
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear the snapping and metal buildings rolling
around,'' Austin said.
</P>
<P>
   When he ventured outside afterward, he said, he saw a landscape
that was ``totally flat, with no walls standing. Just rubble, with
cards thrown on them. People bleeding with head injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras showed footage of parents in Oklahoma City
searching frantically for children amid leveled homes and mangled
cars.
</P>
<P>
   In Sedgwick County, Kan., which includes Wichita, 6 people were
confirmed dead as of 11:45 p.m. and at least 50 were injured, said
Fred Ervin of the Sedgwick County Emergency Preparedness Office.
</P>
<P>
   Several mobile homes in south Wichita were blown into a lake and
several other homes were damaged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, with the strong winds and heavy rains we had power
lines down, trees down in the roadway, that's all part of tornadic
activity,'' Ervin said. ``We had funnels that touched down in
several locations.''
</P>
<P>
   The county declared a state of disaster emergency, essentially
an appeal to the state to open the National Guard Armory in the
southern part of Wichita for use as as emergency shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Oklahoma are two of the four states in what is known
as Tornado Alley, an area where tornadoes often hit in the spring.
The other states are Texas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Penn, a spokesman for the Federal Emergency Management
Agency regional office in Denton, Texas, said the government was
mobilizing helicopters to help in search and rescue, and agency
officials were rushing to Oklahoma early Tuesday to aid local and
state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any preliminary damage estimates because the
situation is so dynamic,'' Penn said. ``We'll have a better idea
when the morning sun comes up and we can take a look around.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Galuszka, a spokeswoman for the American Red Cross in
Wichita, said that Haysville, a suburb 15 minutes south of Wichita,
was hit especially hard, with reports that all electricity was out
and roads were blocked. She said that the Red Cross had set up two
shelters in Haysville and one in Wichita but that it was advising
residents to bring their own flashlights and sleeping gear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
