<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CUBA-SCENE-NYT &LR;      05-04 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY IS TIGHT FOR CUBA-ORIOLES GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ As different as the atmosphere felt on Monday night
inside Camden Yards, where the Baltimore Orioles completed their
home-and-home series with the Cuban national team, so it was on the
streets beyond the gates.
</P>
<P>
   For one unmistakable change, the downtown stadium was awash in
police protection, with more than three times the usual number of
patrol officers assigned to an Orioles home game. ``The normal
complement is 44,'' said Col. Bert Shirey of the Baltimore Police
Department, who served as commander of the stadium contingent.
``Today we have 140.''
</P>
<P>
   If it seemed, at times, like 1,040, it was only because of the
explosive nature of Cuban-American politics and the local
authorities' expectations that more than 2,000 protesters planned
to attend, at least to make their cases outside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said usual procedures were in place in case
anyone from the Cuban delegation defected, as some athletes have
done in the past after appearances in the United States and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans brought a 300-member delegation made up of team
members, sports officials, government officials, youths, athletes
from other sports and security personnel. They arrived in Baltimore
Sunday night and checked into a hotel on the inner harbor; a Cuban
official said the players stayed at the hotel all day until coming
to the ball park. A Cuban youth team played a local Little League
team on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Shirey said the police were helping to protect the Cuban
contingent until its expected departure on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By game time, the hundreds of those outside the ball park
opposing the game as a propaganda coup for the Cuban president,
Fidel Castro, far outnumbered those favoring the end of the 40-year
trade embargo by about 4-1. There were many speeches, signs, chants
and songs by the larger group, but the protests were relatively
tame.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were arrested after running onto the field during
the game, the first of them carrying a small Cuban flag and
several, according to the police, wearing ``Freedom for Cuba''
T-shirts. A fifth was detained, then released. All were chased down
by police officers and escorted off the field in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The four people, all from Miami, were ``criminally cited and
released'' and must return here for trial. In addition, 19 people
were ejected for various disorderly conduct behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has grown used to large-scale international political
events. Three years ago, a Sunday afternoon visit by Pope John Paul
II required the same kind of coordinated effort that the Cuban team
necessitated, Shirey said. And during a 1991 visit to the United
States, Queen Elizabeth took in an Orioles game.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the Baltimore police worked with state and federal
law enforcement agencies, including the FBI, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the baseball commissioner, said, ``This is in a class
by itself,'' assessing the security. But he added that the State
Department did not necessarily expect defections.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore authorities also arranged with the Federal Aviation
Administration to restrict the airspace over Camden Yards from 1
p.m. to midnight to keep away what they feared would be a traffic
jam of small planes with trailing, and opposing, political
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Angelos is very particular about maintaining order in the
stadium at any game,'' Shirey said, referring to the Orioles'
owner, Peter Angelos. ``He likes to maintain a family atmosphere.
No nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   For hours before the game, the plazas ringing the ball park were
filled not only with the usual mob of Orioles fans, even in this
season of constant losses, but also with hundreds of Cuban-born
residents of New York, New Jersey and Florida. They made up a major
part of the protesting groups. The larger group of protesters was
loud and united in its vilification of Castro as a ``traitor,
assassinator and dictator,'' as one chant went. Signs compared him
with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav leader, and Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a flatbed truck parked near Babe Ruth Plaza at the
front gates, Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., one of Castro's harshest
critics in Congress, criticized the Orioles and Major League
Baseball for allowing the game to proceed. ``The game played inside
presents a vision to the world that everything inside Cuba is fine,
is normal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then referring to the Orioles' visit to Havana on March 28,
Menendez added, ``We're here to remind the nation and the world
that at the same time Castro was sitting with officials of the
Orioles and Major League Baseball, at that very time in Havana, it
was Castro sentencing leading human rights activists to long prison
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those attending the game who favored a renewal of
relations with Cuba wore red baseball hats that said, ``End the
Embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in a negotiated peace with all people we have
differences with,'' said Joyce Wheeler, an elementary school
teacher from Baltimore who equated the United States' Cuban policy
with the war in the Balkans. ``The embargo hurts women and
children. The bombing of Yugoslavia hurts women and children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
