<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTSPY-AZR &LR;      05-04 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTSPY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS WALK LINE BETWEEN OPENNESS, PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Note: Merie is cq in 17th graf 
 
 By HANK HUGHES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your teen, the one living in the Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch T-shirt or
painting his fingernails black, seems to forever be behind the
closed door of his room. Should you be worried?
</P>
<P>
   Depends, according to several youth counselors, parents and
teenagers in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   How are his grades?
</P>
<P>
   Who are her friends?
</P>
<P>
   What are their interests?
</P>
<P>
   If you can answer those questions to your satisfaction, your
kid's probably OK. If you can't, you have a problem _ a
relationship problem.
</P>
<P>
   You need to become more engaged in your child's life, parents
and counselors agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``1999 is not a good time to not know what your kid's doing,''
said David Shuff, head counselor at Shepherd Junior High School in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing can drive a parent to distraction, especially in
light of the Littleton, Colo., tragedy. No doubt many are thinking
along the same lines as President Clinton, who said, ``This should
be a wake-up call for all parents.''
</P>
<P>
   No parent suspects her child of making pipe bombs in the
bedroom, but, still, what is going on in there?
</P>
<P>
   One way to find out is dubbed ``parental espionage.'' That
generally means snooping, but can go so far as to include telephone
taps, hidden video cameras, Internet-use monitors, barging into a
teen's room unannounced or sneaking a peek at her diary.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions vary on these tactics. ``Never,'' everyone agrees,
before adding, ``unless they're warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids deserve the same degree of privacy as adults,'' said
Chris Yager, who counsels youth at Adobe Mountain and Black Canyon
detention centers. ``But if there's some suspicion. . . . It's the
same as with our homes and the police. They can't come in unless
they have probable cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Froemming, a 17-year-old junior at the Heritage Academy
charter school in Mesa, says privacy is not a problem at his house,
even though his parents routinely go into his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``My room is open to them because I'm living in their house,''
he said. ``But if I wanted to stay in my room and not be bothered
by anyone, that's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Jennifer Froemming, doesn't hesitate to enter
Brandon's room. ``I think it's the parents' responsibility to know
what your children are doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying you go in and read their diaries. But if I see
a change in their demeanor over a period of time, then I might. I
tell them that it's not that I don't trust you, it's the society
we're living in today.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale therapist Francis Mills-Yerger said, ``You need to
respect your child's privacy, but you need to know there's a
difference between privacy and secrecy. When they hide something
and keep it secret, it's because it's bad or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The doors are almost never closed in Linda Candelario's West
Valley home. That doesn't bother her 16-year-old daughter, Merie.
She has privacy when she wants it. The key to her relationship with
her parents, the Dysart High School junior said, ``is that we have
an open relationship. I can talk to (them) about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting to that point would solve most parent-teen problems, the
counselors said. ``Finding out what they're doing, who they're
doing it with, what their interests are, that's No. 1,'' Yager
said.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have that kind of relationship with your teen, how
do you get it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a lot of overreacting,'' Shuff said. ``It's hard,
especially with adolescents, to drastically change anything. I see
that in divorce situations. A dad's never had a relationship with
the kids, and now, boom, he wants to be a part. The kids go,
`What's going on?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yager said it starts with simple conversations, finding out
teens' interests, their thoughts and not being judgmental when they
say something bizarre or immature. The conversations may be
one-sided at the beginning, but the teen will appreciate you taking
an interest.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Holt, 19, no longer lives at home. When she did, she said
she fell in with the wrong crowd and got into trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, she said, weren't as involved in her life as much
as she wished they had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stepdad never tried,'' she said during a recent visit to
Arizona Center in Phoenix. ``And when my mom did, he'd be jealous.
So she stopped trying.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposite, parents trying too hard, can also backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``One complaint the kids have is when the parent tries to be one
of them or be cool around their friends,'' Yager said. ``They want
you involved, but at a distance. It's like, `Come to my game, but
don't talk to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you know what they're doing and who they're with, it's OK
to back off and give them some space.''
</P>
<P>
   Being cool around your child can also be symptomatic of wanting
to be a friend rather than a parent. ``The hard part (of
parenting),'' said Jennifer Froemming, ``is setting rules and
following through. Parents today want to be kids' friends. It's
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Froemming, who has six children between the ages of 4 and 17,
works outside her home about six hours a day. She'd been a
stay-at-home mom until about 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   She said working makes it ``harder to keep the home up, but not
harder to keep tabs on the children. You have to prioritize.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Dalton of Glendale said she and her husband, Chris, both
work but are able to keep close watch on their two adolescent
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to my kids, we are very, very strict, and they can't
do a lot of things their friends can do,'' Kelley Dalton said.
``But we see a lot of parents doing as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the counselors said parents should seek help with a
social worker at school if they have a particularly troubled
relationship with their child or if the child is very angry or
habitually lies, is cruel to animals or enjoys burning things.
</P>
<P>
   The counselor is trained in confronting teens and can check on
truancy, monitor the child in school and order a full psychological
profile, or personality testing, if warranted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
