<HEADER>
A3291 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-F-16-CRASHES-AZR &LR;      05-04 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F-16-CRASHES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
F-16 REPAIR SCHEDULE BLAMED IN STRING OF CRASHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(Resending with dateline) 
 
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Air Force officials say at least half the recent
fighter jet crashes in Arizona could have been prevented had they
acted sooner to correct engine problems, some detected as early as
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, a half-dozen $20 million F-16 fighter jets from
Luke Air Force Base have been destroyed in crashes. Four of the
crashes were blamed on engine problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably three of four (accidents) could have been prevented
if we had taken the most aggressive action we could have a couple
years ago,'' said Robert May, who is responsible for managing Air
Force engines. ``But it is a balance of readiness, maintenance
workload and risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with shrinking budgets, the Air Force increased
inspections but delayed replacement and major repairs of parts
unless they were deemed immediate safety risks. May, the Air
Force's propulsion product group manager, said it could take as
long as four or five years to identify an engine problem, order a
new part, manufacture and test it, and install it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spate of accidents _ a dozen across the Air Force
since fall _ has prompted top officials, and some legislators, to
ask for more funding and a faster schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Those requests have an added urgency after NATO officials
announced Monday that engine problems likely caused the crash of an
F-16 in Serbia on Saturday during an attack mission. The pilot was
rescued but the plane was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Air Force Whitten Peters has asked Congress for
another $127 million to speed up replacement of parts in F-16
engines used throughout the Air Force. Two of those parts have been
blamed for recent Arizona accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Even if new parts are available, May said the military does not
have the manpower or funding to install all the parts at once and
would have to ground much of the F-16 fleet to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford to do that, particularly today when we're
fighting a war,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The jet lost over the weekend in Serbia was the first F-16 to
crash in the Kosovo conflict. The Air Force is investigating the
crash and does not plan to ground nearly two dozen remaining F-16s
involved in Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   In March, it grounded 400 F-16s across the country _ half of
them at Luke _ when a fifth Luke plane crashed. Though no one has
been killed or seriously injured in the crashes, officials were
concerned enough about engine problems in Luke's F-16 fleet that a
month earlier they convened an engine summit at the Glendale base
to study the string of crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we completed the review we decided it would probably be
prudent to accelerate fixes to some known problems,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt &AMP; Whitney spokesman Tim Burris defended his company's
engine, which is used in all the Luke planes, and said the company
sent inspectors to the engine summit.
</P>
<P>
   Before a Luke fighter jet crashed in December, he said it had
been nearly two years since the 220 model was blamed for an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Pratt &AMP; Whitney engine model has more than 5,000 parts and
is still considered the safest fighter engine in the Air Force, May
said. But he noted ``there are phenomena in the engines we don't
always understand.''
</P>
<P>
   At first it appeared none of the engine problems in the Luke
crashes were related. Now, officials say at least three parts of
the F-16 engines should be replaced _ the augmentor ducts,
low-pressure turbines and fan disks.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Luke lost an F-16 when some of the turbine blades
broke free. The February and March accidents have both been blamed
on cracked augmentor ducts. May said there had been at least seven
incidents across the Air Force caused by the same problems over the
past few years. In those cases, the pilots safely landed the jets.
</P>
<P>
   In the crashes involving the augmentor ducts, Luke pilots
ejected safely but the planes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got our attention,'' May said. ``We said, `Holy cow,
there's more safety risk than we thought.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance crews at Luke have increased inspections of the
ducts to the most thorough conducted ``outside of a laboratory.''
By Monday, they had reported cracks in 19 engine ducts. Those
engines were removed. Maintenance inspectors have not detected any
problems with the landing gear, which was blamed for a Luke crash
last week.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 jets, the equivalent of an entire squadron, have been
grounded at Luke until the augmentor ducts and turbine parts can be
replaced. May said 60 augmentor ducts should be ready by late
summer, but it may take four years to manufacture and replace the
ducts across the Air Force fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Luke officials hope to be first in line. In the meantime, the
base has resumed about 160 sorties a day _ just below its average
training schedule _ but the groundings have delayed training by a
week.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
