<SLUG> BC-BKC-NULAKER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CAST OFF DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 _ WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Entertaining as it is, the Los Angeles
Lakers' two-man vaudeville act of Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant
is a show with limited drawing potential. For the long haul,
they'll need an ensemble cast, so they trotted out every supporting
actor and bit player they had Monday night in a performance they
hope earns many encores.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reviews were encouraging. Every Laker who stepped on
the court scored, five in double figures, and the feel-good plot
included 31 assists in a 115-102 victory over the Dallas Mavericks
at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The critics loved it. The starring cast was pretty pleased with
itself, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always gonna be a plus for us when we can get everyone
involved,'' said Glen Rice, who snapped out of a recent funk to
score 22 points. ``I think when you just rely on two people to take
you to that finish line every time, sometimes you're gonna come up
short, but when we get everyone involved, it's been proven that
we're a much better basketball team.... Anytime you can go out
there and have as many assists as we had today, things are gonna
pretty much fall in your favor.''
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have been better timed, giving the Lakers their
first three-game winning streak since late March and pushing them a
half-game ahead of the Houston Rockets for the home-court advantage
in their first-round playoff matchup.
</P>
<P>
   If the streak can make it to four, against Portland in the
season finale Wednesday, the Lakers will start the playoffs at home
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If the offense remains a 10-man game, good results will follow.
The Lakers' previous win, at Seattle, was all Shaq and Kobe. O'Neal
got his 26 points and 11 rebounds Monday, and Bryant scored 17
points to go with a career-high 10 assists, but this time they had
help: from Rice, from Derek Fisher's 10 points and eight assists,
Rick Fox's 11 points off the bench, J.R. Reid's nine points, and an
eight-point fourth quarter from Derek Harper.
</P>
<P>
   And when things got boring at the end, crowd-pleaser Tyronn Lue
turned on the Forum faithful with a few quick bursts of speed and
four points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know that people are finding their grooves
offensively,'' said Robert Horry. ``That's a sign that guys are
gearing up and getting ready to really buckle down and play. Here
lately everyone's scoring points, two here, four there, so it's
nice that everyone knows we're geared up for the playoffs. And nice
to know that everyone's playing as a team, passing the ball. I
think that's the most important thing. Before, we would hold it,
try and do our own thing first, then kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, riding a four-game winning streak coming into the game,
had been derailing playoff teams left and right in a late-season
surge, knocking off San Antonio, Phoenix, Minnesota and Houston
(twice). The Mavericks led the Lakers by two at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But then teamball took over. The Lakers outscored the Mavericks
30-15 in the third quarter and at one point built a 20-point
cushion. And, conveniently, they've never looked closer to being
ready for the playoffs than they look now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a much better team,'' coach Kurt Rambis said. ``But I
know we can play better. I've been telling you guys for a long
time, this team has a huge upside potential. We've seen some of it
but not all of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
