<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Crime of the Century
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two boys, 18 and 19, were smart, dreadfully smart. They came
from an affluent neighborhood in a big city. Their friendship was
intense and poisonous. One of the boys, the 18-year-old, seemed to
be the leader. Together, without adult supervision, they cooked up
a Nietzschean superman fantasy: their brilliance and superiority
entitled them to murder anyone they considered inferior.
</P>
<P>
   And murder they did. They picked up a 14-year-old neighbor and
killed him with a chisel. Their act was once called the Crime of
the Century, a title since appropriated for each subsequent crime
of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1924. The city was Chicago. The Crime of the
Century was the Leopold-Loeb case. The defense lawyer was Clarence
Darrow, who got his clients, Nathan Leopold and Richard Loeb, off
on a plea of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   There are two points to be made here about Littleton, Colo. 1)
There is nothing much new about young people drawing fatally wrong
conclusions from complicated ideas adrift in the culture. 2) What
larger deeds might Leopold and Loeb have accomplished if they had
been armed with guns instead of a chisel?
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
