<P>
   &UR; CLONING THE WOOLLY MAMMOTH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By RICHARD STONE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If you thought reproducing sheep and mice was a leap ahead, you
won't believe what the Japanese have in mind: cloning a woolly
mammoth that last walked the earth during it's heyday in the
Pleistocene Epoch. This bizarre quest may sound unbelievable, but
there is no science to deny the viability of the idea. The only
catch: finding a small bit of well-preserved mammoth tissue
containing normal DNA. To what lengths will the Japanese team go to
realize their cloning dream?
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-CLONING-A-PREHISTORIC-CREATURE-NYTSF. Sent to
category codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINE MAKING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TWO COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT KUNZIG &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Blended wines, such as those cheerfully thrown together by
Californians, may turn out to be top-notch, but to a Frenchman they
will lack something special _ terrior. Terrior, a vineyard's
particular combination of dirt, rock and exposure to sunlight may
