<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos and graphics are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   A broad range of individuals have gained refuge in the United
States despite evidence of their involvement in human rights abuses
elsewhere in the world. They include alleged participants of
``ethnic cleansing'' in the former Yugoslavia, former henchmen of
the murderous regime of Somali strongman Mohammed Siad Barre, and
Haitian military officers and Salvadoran generals accused of
covering up the massacre of four American churchwomen. The Boston
Globe, in a three-part series, explores the development.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMINALS-I (Port St. Lucie, Fla.) _ Carl Dorelien was once
a small-time dictator, and a proud one at that. He was part of a
clique of military officers who held Haiti at gunpoint until 1994,
when the junta's abuses became so grave that the Clinton
administration dispatched 20,000 troops to the tiny Caribbean
nation to restore order. By Steve Fainaru. PHOTO. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMINALS-II (PRIJEDOR, Bosnia and Herzegovina) _ Zijad
Music arrived in Burlington, Vt., directly from the war that ripped
apart his home in Prijedor in Bosnia. But Music is hardly a typical
refugee of the war in the former Yugoslavia. By Steve Fainauru.
PHOTO. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   WAR-CRIMINALS-III (Undated) _ The United States, with no
coherent strategy, lacks resources to track suspected human rights
offenders, or investigate their crimes once they are discovered. By
Steve Fainaru. (2 takes)
</P>
