<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3462 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLONING-A-PREHISTORIC     05-04 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONING-A-PREHISTORIC-CREATURE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLONING THE WOOLLY MAMMOTH  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD STONE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Look, over here! Hair!'' shouts one of the sperm hunters,
pointing to a frayed brown tangle protruding from a cliff along the
Kolyma River in Siberia. When ecologist Sergei Zimov, a big-boned
Russian with a thick blond beard, gets close enough to touch the
hair, he rips a few strands free and rolls them across his fingers,
pondering.
</P>
<P>
   Could this, finally, be the hair of a woolly mammoth, its frozen
body locked inside the crumbling black cliff? Could this be the
first step in a bizarre quest led by Japanese biologists to
inseminate an Asian elephant with woolly mammoth sperm and
selectively breed a fabled prehistoric creature that became extinct
thousands of years ago? ``I know it sounds unbelievable,'' says
Kazufumi Goto, the leader of the project, ``but no science can deny
our idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimov turns the hair in his hands, rubs it between his fingers
and thumb, then poisons the air with his words: ``Steppe bison.''
</P>
<P>
   The heyday of the woolly mammoth was the Pleistocene Epoch,
stretching from 1.8 million years ago to the end of the last ice
age 11,000 years ago. Mammoths thrived particularly well in
Siberia, where dry grasslands once supported a vibrant ecosystem of
mammoths, bison and other jumbo herbivores. Famished after the end
of the Ice Age by a diet of low-nutrient mosses, and increasingly
harried by human hunters, the big grazers dwindled to extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Although most mammoths left behind only their bones, in a few
cases the Siberian permafrost preserved mammoth skin and muscle.
Most of the cells in this tissue had degraded, but in the past
decade scientists managed to rescue a few proteins and fragmented
genes to compare with those in living elephants. And until Goto
began to think otherwise, that was about as close as anyone thought
we'd get to mammoths again.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when Goto began his career at Kagoshima
University in Japan, he applied his nascent understanding of
reproductive biology to his country's pursuit of the ultimate
steak. Goto's task was to use artificial insemination methods to
develop beef with more marbling. Getting sperm from well-marbled
bulls was easy, however, collecting cow eggs wasn't so simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started going to the slaughterhouse,'' Goto says. There he
could take ovaries from cows with good marbling.
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1986, while peering through a microscope at sperm
swarming an egg, Goto had an epiphany. ``Once a sperm attaches to
the egg's membrane, it stops moving,'' he says. After the two
membranes fuse, the sperm is engulfed by the egg and the tail
breaks off. It dawned on him that the sperm is already dead by the
time it is carried into the egg and delivers its genes.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Goto enlisted a student to perform a series of
experiments using dead sperm. ``We could freeze and thaw 20 times,
and the sperm DNA would never break.'' But when they tried
injecting the dead sperm into mouse eggs, it failed thousands of
times. Goto decided mouse eggs were too fragile and instructed his
student to use bull semen and cow eggs. Success: an egg divided
into an embryo. They subsequently implanted the cluster in a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got pregnant on the first try,'' Goto says.
</P>
<P>
   At a 1992 reproductive biology meeting in Fort Collins, Colo.,
Goto was peppered with questions from a reporter about the
implications of the discovery. Could viable sperm be recovered from
the Ice Man, the 5,000-year-old mummy that had just been discovered
in the Alps? Could dead sperm save endangered species? Or extinct
ones, such as a mammoth?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the beginning,'' Goto says. He wrote to several
Russian scientists over the next few years, asking about frozen
mammoths. No one wrote back. Then, in 1996, Goto met Kazutoshi
Kobayashi, an entrepreneur adept at doing business in Russia.
Meanwhile, Goto found a scientific partner, Akira Iritani, chairman
of the department of genetic engineering at the prestigious Kinki
University in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Goto told Iritani his vision: Find mammoth sperm with genes
still intact and use it to fertilize a living elephant egg. But
Iritani decided to attempt an even more improbable feat: Clone a
mammoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If even a small bit of mammoth tissue is found with normal
DNA, it would take only a one-time procedure to clone a pure woolly
mammoth,'' Iritani says.
</P>
<P>
   Goto and Iritani decided to travel to Siberia. But in Seoul,
between planes on the way to Yakutsk, a bag packed with $60,000 to
sponsor the dig, disappeared. Arriving empty-handed, Kobayashi
scraped together a few thousand dollars from associates and sent a
team on a trek to Chokurdakh. When the mayor of the tiny settlement
demanded a tax of $70,000, Kobayashi balked, negotiations failed
and they had to look for other places to dig.
</P>
<P>
   They settled on Duvannyi Yar, a renowned mammoth site, but
troubles plagued the researchers as soon as they arrived in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customs officers wanted us to pay arbitrary fines,''
Iritani says. Money changed hands, but their equipment remained
impounded.
</P>
<P>
   When they finally got to Cherskil, the scientists set to work
scouring the cliffs for any sign of mammoth flesh. Using picks to
probe the sediments at the cliff face, the researchers homed in on
spots with mammoth bones or swatches of hair.
</P>
<P>
   By the third day, all the expedition had to show for its efforts
was the discovery of an ancient horse skeleton. The weather started
to turn foul, and the Russians pressed to return to Cherskii.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating not to come back with tissue,'' Kobayashi
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese haven't given up. This summer they plan to go to
one of several sites where there have been reports of frozen
mammoths. Iritani says his university has spread the word that it
will pay 1 million yen ($9,000) for mammoth tissue preserved well
enough for experiments, a bounty he hopes will entice Russians who
illegally collect mammoth tusks for ivory.
</P>
<P>
   If Goto and his colleagues do find the mammoth of their dreams
this summer, they are prepared to spare no expense. Goto would be
happy with even a single mammoth, for it would fulfill a pledge he
made to children in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, he made a drastic career change, giving up his
position at Kagoshima University to head the Ezu Kindergarten,
which his family owns, in Kumamoto. Goto says he has always wanted
to help shape the minds of children long before they get to a
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say, `The mammoth is dead under the ice. Why don't
you leave it in peace?''' Goto says. ``But I promised the kids I
would create a mammoth. I want to do my best to accomplish the
children's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Stone is a deputy news editor at Science magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
