<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     05-04 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN INDIANS WIN SMALL VICTORY AT DEVILS TOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune  
American Indians won another court battle over their right to
worship without interference at Devils Tower National Monument in
the northeast corner of Wyoming. Unfortunately, the victory at the
10th Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver wasn't along constitutional
lines, which would have provided greater leverage for tribal
worship at other sacred sites located on public lands.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 20 Plains Indian tribes consider the 600-foot butte,
Devils Tower, a sacred site. Archaeological evidence shows that the
ancestors of the Lakota Tribes lived in the area a thousand years
ago. The site has also been a significant part of the religious and
cultural beliefs of the Sioux and other Northern Plains Indians.
Tribes travel to the tower to perform the Sun Dance and vision
quests during the month of June, around the time of the summer
solstice.
</P>
<P>
   The monument is also a premiere crack climbing site.
Approximately 6,000 climbers attempt to scale the tower each year
using the 220 routes to the top. Chas Cartwright, who has been the
superintendent of the national monument since March 1997, says that
prior to 1994, approximately 1,200 to 1,400 climbers visited during
the month of June.
</P>
<P>
   Climbers sometimes must replace metal bolts and metal pitons in
the rock face of the tower for their own safety. And the climbing
requires them to yell advice to their climbing partners. Obviously,
such activities interfere with the solitude and solemnity required
for tribal religious ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   That's the clash: climbing vs. praying. The National Park
Service brought diverse groups together, including climbers and
American Indians, to work out a plan that might satisfy the needs
of both groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Climbing Management Plan for Devils Tower National
Monument requests that climbers voluntarily refrain from climbing
during the month of June. Cartwright says that since the plan was
implemented in 1994, the number of climbers in June has dropped to
approximately 200.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been clear sailing. A few disgruntled commercial
climbers, Andy Petefish, Kenneth Anderson, Gregory Hauber and Wes
Bush, challenged the management plan. They were joined in the
lawsuit by the Bear Lodge Multiple Use Association. The Mountain
States Legal Foundation in Denver represents them. It should be
noted that the commercial climbers who brought the lawsuit continue
to climb the tower during the month of June.
</P>
<P>
   The climbers and the association lost at the federal district
level. The district court found that since the climbing plan was
modified to make the June climbing ban voluntary, the plan is
constitutional and within the Department of Interior's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   William Perry Pendley, president and chief legal advisor of the
legal foundation, in oral argument before the circuit court of
appeals, took the position that the climbing management plan
unconstitutionally promotes religion _ in this case, various
American Indian religious beliefs. Pendley argued that the plan
violates the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment by
pressuring climbers to stop climbing in June in order that tribal
people may worship peacefully at the tower.
</P>
<P>
   Pendley neglected to point out, as the appellate court did, that
a number of laws ``allow ... temporary closure of specific tribal
sacred sites located on federal lands.'' The appellate court's
decision lists two such sites in a footnote: El Malpais Monument
and the Cibola Historical Park, both in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Law Resource Center in Washington, D.C., as an
intervenor representing the Cheyenne River Sioux Tribe and four
prominent Indian spiritual leaders, also pointed out to the court
that the National Park Service owns Christian churches and
religious properties and has a long tradition of allowing groups
``to conduct religious services on these properties, and it
prohibits recreational or other activities that would conflict with
the religious services.''
</P>
<P>
   But the appellate court did not decide the question as to
whether accommodating American Indian religious ceremonies at
Devils Tower violates the Constitution. The court never reached
that question. It decided the case on much simpler grounds: Did
those who brought the lawsuit have standing to do so? No, said the
unanimous court.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has outlined three conditions necessary
to establish standing in a court of law: 1) The plaintiff must have
suffered a concrete and specific injury because of an intrusion on
legally protected interests; 2) there must be a causal connection
between the injury and the conduct that brought the complaint; and
3) it must be likely that the injury will be redressed by a
decision favorable to the plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in this case failed to prove they suffered any
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial climbers continue to climb in June, the members
of the Bear Lodge Multiple Use Association who do not climb in June
could if they wished. The court singled out Andy Petefish and
stated in its decision that he ``did not substantiate his claim of
economic injury as a result of the voluntary closure, and he has
provided no additional substantiation here.'' The court pointed out
that ``standing is not measured by the intensity of the litigant's
interest or the fervor of his advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pendley said in an interview Friday that he intends to file a
request for a hearing before the entire 10th Circuit Court of
Appeals. He noted that such en banc hearings are rarely approved,
but he feels that the court did not apply the law correctly in
regard to Establishment Clause precedence. Pendley contends that
the so-called voluntary ban creates injury to the parties because
it violates their constitutional right not to be coerced to
accommodate a religion by a government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Gunn, of Volunteer Lawyers in Boston who represented the
Indian Law Resource Center, said that he would be surprised if the
circuit court accepted Pendley's request. The court's ruling on
standing was straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright said that his staff would do an internal review of
the climbing management plan in late summer or fall, after they see
how the voluntary climbing ban works this June. He said the plan
had ``achieved a good level of success'' and that he ``plans to
stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court gave tribes a narrow win on this issue, but
a win, nevertheless. The court felt that once it ruled on the
plaintiffs' standing, it didn't need to address the constitutional
question. That's standard jurisprudence. If a case can be decided
on other issues, courts refrain from addressing constitutional
questions.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a greater victory for all American Indians
had the court decided that the management plan did not violate the
Establishment Clause. Had the court done so, the positive
ramifications for tribal religious ceremonies would have reached
across the nation. Thus, this victory is bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Last week, this column addressed the harassment of freelance
journalist Peter Sussman. The California attorney general's office
had subpoenaed 10 years of writings, records and documents that
Sussman had created while reporting on the California prison system
and the restrictions it has put on news media access to inmates. He
was subpoenaed as a result of being listed as a possible witness in
an inmate's case against the warden of a California prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sussman had been ordered to appear in court on April 29 for a
hearing on releasing his records. The hearing never occurred. New
Attorney General Bill Lockyer, an advocate of the First Amendment,
ordered negotiations to reach a reasonable settlement and quashed
the subpoena. Sussman agreed to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-03-99 1155EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3504 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-CRIMINALS-II-2ND &LR;      05-04 1708
