</P>
<P>
   Atko Blazevic, the former member of El Manijakos, said that
drinking altered Music's behavior. ``Whatever stupid things Zijo
did, he always did them when he was drunk,'' he said, refusing to
be specific. ``He wasn't a stable character even before he was with
us,'' said Blazevic. ``He'd drink, then he'd shoot off his mouth
and get violent.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gloginja said Music has been criticized simply because
he was a Muslim who fought with the Serbs: ``They say, `Look, he's
fighting against his own people.' That's why people are against
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Music may have believed he could protect his family. Former
Prijedor residents said Music's wife was allowed to keep her job as
a nurse long after the Serbs had fired most Muslims and Croats in
town. Sakib Music said his nephew came around once ``to ask me if I
had any problems, if any of the Serbs had touched me. I said, `I
don't need anything from you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Music's family was in fact protected, that ended in 1995. He
apparently was already in trouble with the Serbs. According to
Gloginja, Serb military police arrested Music in 1995 and briefly
jailed him for pouring gasoline into the oil tank of a military
vehicle. Serb military officals apparently suspected him of
sabotage, but Gloginja said Music was drunk and did it by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Major Milodrag Glusac, of the 43d Motorized Brigade, confirmed
the incident but said he was unsure of Music's motives.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear if Music's arrest was related in some way to the
Serbs' attack on his family. Bosnian refugees familiar with Music
said they believed the Serbs were trying to take over the apartment
of Music's mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Gloginja said he went to see Music shortly after the Serbs had
shot his family. ``Believe me, he didn't say, `Thank you, Serbs,'
'' said Gloginja. ``He said, `Goddamn you. I've been fighting with
you for four years and this is what you do for me?' '' After the
shootings, Gloginja said, Music knew ``he had to go to another
side, a third side. He didn't know who had done it, so he was
afraid they would come to his door and do the same to him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   False papers used
</P>
<P>
   to escape Prijedor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Music made his way to the United States shortly after he was
released from jail. He said he was forced to use false papers _ he
said he used Gloginja's name _ to escape Prijedor. ``I can't
explain how terrifying it was,'' he said. ``You're terrified that
you're going to see somebody who knows you, and they'll call you by
your name and turn you over to the police.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bosnian refugees pointed out that Music traveled to
Belgrade, the Serbian capital, instead of Croatia, where most
Muslims seeking asylum fled. They said it was an indication that
Music left with the consent of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Remmel, of the International Organization for Migration,
which assisted the INS in screening Music, said the fact that Music
is Muslim yet came through Belgrade ``is alarming, but more in
hindsight.'' He said privacy restrictions forbid him from talking
about Music's case. However, he said responsibility for determining
the merits of Music's persecution claim resided with the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not really something we focus on,'' he said. ``It's
something for the INS to delve into.''
</P>
<P>
   Music said he received affidavits of support from relatives in
Burlington to help him with his case. ``Nothing good has happened
to me the last five or six years,'' he said. ``The only good thing
was when I first got here. You should have seen it. I got out of
the airplane and kissed the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he has settled into a relatively normal life. He
said his wife continues to be haunted by memories of Prijedor and
cries into the night, but he pushes the memories out of his mind.
``There are horrible things that you think about,'' he said. ``You
try to push them down inside of you but they keep coming back to
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Music said he has heard rumors that other refugees might pursue
him. Asked if he had been threatened, he said, ``Threat is a big
word, but there was a lot of talk. I didn't pay too much attention
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Bosnian refugees in Vermont clearly live in fear of Music.
One man, after guiding a reporter to the used-furniture store where
Music works, refused to go within several blocks of the building.
The man, who like most refugees asked that his name not be used,
said refugees don't know where to turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do, go to the Burlington police station
and tell them this guy is a war criminal?'' he said. ``Good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   An elderly woman from Prijedor, who said she saw Music
``countless'' times with other members of El Manijakos, said she
would be terrified to run into him in Burlington. ``I used to go
down to the market to sell things, and when you heard El Manijakos
was in the market you'd just get your stuff and run,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiko Zjakic, who now works as a brewer, said he happened to be
at the Burlington airport picking up a friend the same day Music
arrived. Before coming to the United States, Zjakic was held by the
Serbs at the Omarska prison camp, where thousands of men were
starved, tortured, and killed in perhaps the worst crimes against
humanity in Europe since the Nazi concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   When Zjakic saw Music, he said, he couldn't believe his eyes. He
said the last time he had seen him, Music was carrying a gun on the
streets of Prijedor as a member of El Manijakos.
</P>
<P>
   As Music approached, Zjakic looked away. ``Those were the same
people who put me in the camp,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Freelance journalist Karmen Jelincic contributed to this  &QL; 
article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
