<SLUG> BC-BBO-OHIO-DRAGONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio city has one year to prepare for minor league team
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They have league permission, they have a name,
now they need to build a home.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Monday that the new Class A minor league
baseball team coming to Dayton next year will be dubbed the Dragons
leaves the team a little less than a year to build a stadium, sell
tickets and make inroads into the region's entertainment-buying
subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   A marketing campaign is under way to introduce the team to the
Dayton metropolitan region. The team's lead owners, Mandalay Sports
Entertainment, are going to target Springfield to Xenia to
Middletown and all points in between to create a base of fans for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great opportunity for baseball here and for us as a
company,'' said Paul Schaeffer, a California entertainment
executive and one of Mandalay's investors.
</P>
<P>
   The team already has a little more than 1,800 down payments for
season tickets for the 7,500-seat stadium under construction near
Patterson Boulevard and Monument Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The layout of the seats will be determined by this summer, team
officials said. Then, depositors will be contacted in the order
they put their money in and given the opportunity to pick seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God we have another year to plan for this,'' said Hank
Stickney, Mandalay Sports Entertainment's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Seat prices have not been set but are expected to range between
$4 and $8 a game.
</P>
<P>
   The team is already unloading a host of Dragon-emblazoned
T-shirts, caps, sweatshirts and memorabilia to spread the name.
</P>
<P>
   Merchandise will be available initially through the team offices
at 500 East First St., across the street from the stadium
construction site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important both from a revenue standpoint but it is more
important from a team identification standpoint,'' said Dragons
President Robert Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, construction crews are due to begin pouring concrete
on the northwest corner of the stadium site near Monument Avenue
and River Corridor Drive.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium site is now a deep muddy pit but the construction
schedule calls for the playing field to be in place by fall.
Construction on the stands and concourse will begin this summer.
The stadium is scheduled to open in April, 2000 as the new home for
the Class A affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the stadium is still up for bid. Stickney said they
are negotiating with three local firms to sell the naming rights to
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
