<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3506 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAJORETTES05-COX     05-04 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAJORETTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where have the Majorettes gone?
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the toss, flip and look-fabulous
world of competitive baton-twirling, hair can matter as much as
hand-eye coordination.
</P>
<P>
   That's why 17-year-old Katie Noland sports a modified Dorothy
Hamill 'do. She wants to distinguish herself from hundreds of
long-tressed, limber-limbed, stick-lobbing competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Katie's spin needs doctoring. In a 14-year twirling
career, she's won more than 300 trophies. In July, the reigning
Advanced Teenage Miss Majorette of the Southeast will head to the
national Miss Majorette contest at Notre Dame University, where she
pulled down a sixth-place finish last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Palm Beach resident's latest coup: a free, two-week
trip to Peru this September to spread the twirling gospel. When she
arrives, Katie will be greeted by two bodyguards who'll escort her
on a tour that will include parades, performances and meetings with
South American royalty.
</P>
<P>
   To nab a spot in that 12-girl lineup, the brunette faced a
challenge more daunting than flying knives (which Katie has been
known to twirl): Peruvians prefer blondes. The trip organizer
``said it didn't matter if I wasn't blond,'' Katie says. ``She said
I had a lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   You throw, girl!
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the mighty majorette, in her sassy sequins
and pompommed boots, was envied by campus coeds everywhere. Over
the past two decades, though, she has pretty much pranced off the
football field and into gymnasiums where competitions are held.
</P>
<P>
   Twirlers still suit up at the University of Florida, although
there's not much competition to wear the Gatorette uniform.
Gatorette instructor June Stoeber said 24 young women auditioned
for next year's squad of 16.
</P>
<P>
   And a few local high school bands still field twirlers. Atlantic
High School in Delray Beach had five last fall, while regional
champs Wellington High boasted 14. (A baton instructor starts
training girls in elementary school, Wellington's band director
says.) And there's Katie, the sole twirler at Suncoast High School.
</P>
<P>
   A disappearing breed
</P>
<P>
   But most area schools don't have even a single majorette to
march with their bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a twirler in 20 years, at least,'' says Willie
Pyfrom at Glades Central Community High in Belle Glade. Jupiter
High School has been majorette-free for almost a decade, and it's
been even longer at Martin County High School in Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, the drum-and-bugle-corps movement swept the
nation, says Rob Roadman, band director of the Martin County Tiger
Regiment. Quick-step marches up and down the field were out,
classical selections and show tunes were in.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers and members of the flag corps elbowed twirlers out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the repertoire changed, the drill design changed,''
Roadman says. ``The football field is now a stage more than a
gridiron.''
</P>
<P>
   John I. Leonard High School abandoned its twirling troupe two
years ago for artistic reasons: A fast-moving baton doesn't show up
that well on the 50-yard line. ``Batons are kind of small and thin,
but a 10-foot flag is colorful and more visible,'' says David
Skinner, Leonard's assistant band director.
</P>
<P>
   (Flip through the 1975 Leonard high yearbook, however, and
you'll find four pages devoted to the school's twirlers. The
Leonard Majorettes numbered 20 that year, and the junior varsity
Twirlettes consisted of 16 girls.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond aesthetics, there's the passage of Title IX in 1972,
which requires schools to provide girls with equal sports
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many more opportunities now,'' says Paula Welch,
professor of exercise and sports sciences at the University of
Florida. ``There are just so many other things that girls can
participate in,'' often with the possibility of weighty
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Twirling's development also has been hampered by a lack of role
models, promotion and fans, Welch says. People just don't show up
to watch twirling competitions in the same number as football games
or soccer matches, she says.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the image problem.
</P>
<P>
   Pop culture avatars Jane and Michael Stern included baton
twirling in their Encyclopedia of Bad Taste, between Barbie dolls
and beer. ``Despite the extraordinary coordination it requires,''
the Sterns wrote in 1990, ``baton twirling is one of those exotic
athletic skills, like bowling-pin juggling or musical spoons, that
grow increasingly kitschy as its routines become more elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   The flying baton is even something of a rarity at Miss America
pageants. Only Miss Illinois twirled in the 1998 contest; Miss
Oklahoma alone upheld the twirling tradition the year before.
(Local trivia: Twirler Kylene Barker Brandon, a West Palm Beacher
competing as Miss Virginia, was crowned Miss America 1979.)
</P>
<P>
   But Katie says the Sterns and other detractors are just out of
step with the times. ``Obviously they haven't seen twirlers of the
new age. There's a new trick made up every five minutes that you'll
probably only see once in your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody should take those people to a contest so they could
see what it's like now. It's nothing like it was 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   She's got many abilities
</P>
<P>
   Katie first picked up a baton at the age of 3. But before
pigeonholing her as little more than a figure-eighting anachronism,
consider these numbers:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Suncoast senior scored a 1580 on her SATs. That's a 780 on
the verbal portion, a perfect 800 in math.
</P>
<P>
   _ She plans to major in math at either the University of Miami
or the University of Central Florida, which she'll enter as a
junior thanks to a hefty load of advanced-placement credits.
</P>
<P>
   _ For two years in a row she's won first place in the area
Martin Luther King Jr. art contest.
</P>
<P>
   _ She's school vice president and has earned the nickname ``Fire
Marshal Katie'' for her flame-throwing routines with Suncoast's
Chargersonic Sound marching band. ``I don't have to wear hair spray
so that's not a problem, but I have burned the hair off my arms,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Katie sees nothing unusual about possessing a mathematician's
mind, an artist's eye and an athlete's quick hands on her 5-foot-3
frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twirling is my sport, art is my hobby, and math is my study,''
she says, taking a break from practice at Royal Palm Beach's rec
center.
</P>
<P>
   Hold on a minute. Twirling's a sport?
</P>
<P>
   ``World Book Encyclopedia, 1989,'' Katie recites. ``The first
sentence says, `Twirling is a sport.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I sweat just as much as these guys,'' she says, motioning to
the basketball players behind her at Royal Palm Beach's rec center,
where she practices five days a week. ``I probably practice twice
as hard. I have the same feelings they do about competition, and I
go through the same letdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   And, chances are, she follows the advice of more coaches. She's
under the tutelage of four private coaches, one in New York, two in
Fort Lauderdale and a local ballet teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Twirling's relative rarity is what appeals to Katie, who plans
to continue twirling in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being different,'' she says. ``Like with the hair
thing, it makes me stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
