A3507 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN05-COX     05-04 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ways to rebel more noticeable now
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Three teens dressed in black coats and
wearing combat boots were handcuffed and taken into custody at the
site of the Columbine massacre. They were questioned and
subsequently released. One of the boys explained they were just
``three punks with a lot of curiosity.'' He said they were probably
singled out because of what they were wearing and their overall
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no duh! He's probably right. It's tough to blend with a
crowd of average joes when you're wearing a ring through your
tongue and sporting a pony tail atop a shaved head. Purple hair
doesn't help either.
</P>
<P>
   Now don't go giving me the old tolerance lecture. Heck, I
practically invented it, but lately an odd thing has been
happening. I think I'm turning into my mother. I swore that could
never be _ but here it is _ geezer gap-osis.
</P>
<P>
   Take the weirdness in stride, I tell myself. Stop gawking at
striped hair and half-bared butts. They're not indicators of the
person inside. I'm listening, but I don't think I'm getting it. I'm
still judging the book by its cover.
</P>
<P>
   What I wear may not reflect the real me (whatever that might be
since my generation was never encouraged to get out and ``find
ourselves''), but I can bet you dollars to doughnuts that if I
checked into the classroom one morning wearing combat boots and
black lipstick, my principal would send me to counseling so they
could figure out just how far off level my bubble had bounced.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a typical teen-ager (and I was), youthful rebellion
wasn't quite as noticeable as it is today, mainly because nobody
was worried about kids' rights. Hell, we didn't even know we had
any. Our parents never let on.
</P>
<P>
   Long before I knew the word ``rebel,'' I guess I was one. When I
was six, I lost interest in school and from time-to-time wandered
off to the ice cream store or sometimes, the library. It wasn't
long before the ice cream man and the librarian wised up to my
peregrinations and squealed on me. Eventually, by means of coercion
and an outright violation of my juvenile rights, the big people got
their point across. I stayed in school.
</P>
<P>
   When I was eight, I discovered lamb chops didn't grow in
somebody's garden and in a fit of revolt, refused to eat meat. That
lasted a week.
</P>
<P>
   In junior high I decided to test the school's dress code by
showing up one morning in jeans and one of my father's dress
shirts. The principal bounced me out on my (r)ear and my mother
explained that if I insisted on (SET ITAL)wearing(END ITAL) said
shirts, I'd have to learn to (SET ITAL)iron(END ITAL) them. The
insurrection was called off due to laziness.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, I spent all of my lunch money on cherry pie and
iced tea, and when my mother asked what I'd had for lunch, which
she did daily, I'd lie. ``Meat loaf and green beans,'' I'd say. A
small fabrication that kept us both happy.
</P>
<P>
   My best friend Jeanne had some pretty cool ideas about
rebelling. Her favorite was refusing to iron her clothes. Today,
nobody would notice, but back in the days of dotted swiss and
crinolines, a person's character, home life, and birth sign could
be read in a wrinkle. One time she painted her toenails with green
porch paint and for a month was too embarrassed to wear sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Lately I've found myself wondering if our parents were as
offended with our jalopies and rolled up jeans as we are now with
kids who show up for school looking like Count Dracula complete
with white makeup and faux blood droplets on their chins. Maybe
they were. And maybe I (SET ITAL)am(END ITAL) turning into my
mother, but an odd notion keeps running through my old fogey brain:
As long as the geezers are still running the world, maybe the
weirdos ought to be careful how loudly they demand we stop it and
let them off. Some days it's mighty tempting.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH, 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
