<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-CRIMINALS-III-2TA     05-04 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMINALS-III-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS VIOLATORS EXPLOIT US IMMIGRATION SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the years following World War II, US immigration officials
made a shocking discovery. Among the waves of refugees fleeing the
Holocaust were hundreds, perhaps thousands, of former Nazis who
managed to slip into the United States by posing as victims of
their own crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon became something of a national scandal, and in
1979 the Justice Department set up an Office of Special
Investigations. Armed with attorneys and multilingual historians
who pored over the Nazis' voluminous archives, the unit has
stripped 61 former perpetrators of their citizenship, deported 48,
and compiled a ``watch list'' of some 60,000 suspected war
criminals for possible exclusion from the United States
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now the world's longest-serving prosecutor of World War
II cases,'' said Eli M. Rosenbaum, who directs the $3.7 million
program.
</P>
<P>
   The success of OSI, now often viewed as the world's most
effective Nazi-fighting organization, has been held up by human
rights activists as an example of what the US government can do to
address the growing problem of modern war criminals who also have
quietly sought refuge in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to keep out people who commit human rights crimes _
then track them down once they slip through _ remain inadequate,
critics said. Lacking a coherent strategy, the government is
hamstrung by archaic laws that can bar members of the Communist
Party from entering the country but also prevent the deportation of
people accused of atrocities. Immigration officials lack resources
to track suspected offenders, or investigate their crimes once they
are discovered. The Immigration and Naturalization Service
acknowledges that it has no idea how many human rights offenders
might be in the United States, nor has it bothered to keep track of
how many such people it has deported.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the same process that allowed the Nazis to enter
the country following World War II is being repeated, critics said.
Although the magnitude of the problem is unclear, human rights
criminals from other global hot spots are exploiting weaknesses in
the government's refugee program, which admits tens of thousands of
persecuted people each year. In addition, government agencies
sometimes seem to act out of competing political interests, such as
when US officials granted visas to Haitian military leaders in
1994, even after US troops had removed them from power.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is a vastly complicated one for the United States,
which for decades has offered a safe haven to millions of
persecuted people around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American government is trying to open their arms, but at
the same time close their eyes to what is happening,'' said Ahmed
Samater, who has helped immigration officials document former
members of Somali strongman Mohammed Siad Barre's murderous regime
who have settled in the United States and Canada. ``Nobody wants to
have a neighbor who's a torturer or a killer.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Yusuf Abdi Ali, a former Somali colonel accused of
overseeing the slaughter of thousands of his countrymen in the
1980s, appears to demonstrate the weaknesses in the system. Ali,
who is known as ``Tuke,'' or The Crow, was deported from Canada in
1992 after a television program exposed him as a war criminal. He
then lived comfortably in the United States until 1996, when CBS
exposed him again and he returned to Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long. Immigration officials said Tuke reentered the
country under an assumed name, then became a permanent resident of
the United States by marrying an American citizen. After being
tipped off by outraged Somali immigrants, the INS finally arrested
him in Virginia last year and moved to have him deported, accusing
him of concealing his involvement in ``genocidal acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Under immigration law, the INS needed the State Department to
issue a finding that genocide, not just atrocities, had occurred
under Tuke's command. The State Department refused to go that far,
so the INS attempted to deport him on grounds he had lied on an
application he had submitted for political asylum. An immigration
judge dismissed the case because Tuke had withdrawn the application
after becoming a permanent resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say he's a nice guy; we all know what he is,''
said an INS official. ``But that's not enough for us. We have to
act under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Despots take advantage
</P>
<P>
   of gaps in refugee program
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Samater said the case illustrates not only the porousness of the
US refugee program but also the inability of the immigration system
to handle such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody even addressing the central theme: that he
committed crimes against humanity,'' Samater said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration specialists said the refugee program has become
especially vulnerable to despots seeking asylum. The program is a
lifeline for tens of thousands of people who each year are
legitimately escaping persecution. The most recent example is the
exodus of hundreds of thousands of people driven from Kosovo by the
Serbian army. The United States plans to take in 20,000 refugees
from the crisis, US immigration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But the screening of refugee applicants has become almost
perfunctory, according to people who administer the massive
program. The screening often takes place amid the chaos of armed
conflict, in ``places that have descended into hell,'' said Dan
Cadman, who heads the National Security Unit for the INS. Those
conditions make it difficult to verify persecution claims or to
identify specific perpetrators of human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government relies on ``joint voluntary
agencies'' to perform most screening tasks. Contracted by the State
Department, the relief agencies are responsible for compiling
information to evaluate persecution claims before passing along the
files to INS officers. But the agencies are essentially refugee
advocates, lacking resources to investigate and seldom making
recommendations to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of in a delicate position; we have to be lenient,''
said Gary Remmel, head of processing in Belgrade for the
International Organization for Migration, which screened two
Bosnian refugees who were admitted into the United States, even
though the Globe later identified them as participants in ethnic
cleansing. ``We don't have the authority to be too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Remmel said many applications passed on to the INS are difficult
to support. People who advocate for refugees ``sometimes don't
realize the amount of weak claims you see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Remmel said he was unfamiliar with the two cases investigated by
the Globe. However, with few safeguards and a crush of
applications, he said: ``It's no surprise that people get in who
shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   INS officers are responsible for investigating the background of
applicants, but people involved in the process said the refugee
program has become so large it is difficult to do more than a basic
40-minute interview, particularly during a crisis. During the war
in Bosnia, each INS officer conducted roughly a dozen such
interviews a day, according to Karen McCoy, an INS officer who was
part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
