<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3509 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAMPOOS05-COX     05-04 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAMPOOS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming clean about over-the-counter shampoos
 &HT;    (EDS: Story has tips at end of take and art; for info, contact
Rod Aydelotte at 254-757-5726.)
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ WARNING! Your shampoo may be hazardous to your
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Many women and men have trouble with their hair. And the
problems can be due to their shampoo and conditioner, said Brenda
Fields, director of admissions at Vogue College of Cosmetology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be overshampooing, undershampooing or
overconditioning, which really weighs the hair down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instructors in the cosmetology field agree that using
professional products is always best. But when that's not an
option, how do women sift through the sea of non-salon shampoos and
conditioners (not to mention styling products) to find the best
products for their hair?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is going to be trial and error,'' said Laura Hays,
a cosmetology instructor at McLennan Community College.
</P>
<P>
   If she had to pick the best store-bought shampoos (or
over-the-counter shampoos as stylists call them), she said she
would go with those that at one point were professional shampoos,
like Clairol products or Vidal Sassoon. Hays would shy away from
products that have big names backing them but have never been
professional products _ products like Neutrogena and Pantene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some you're paying for the name and some of them are full of
wax,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She advises women to keep in mind that ``you get what you pay
for'' when it comes to cheaper shampoos like Flex and Suave.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Gordon, director of education at Vogue, said shampoo and
hair products have come a long way in the 35 years she's been in
the hair business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazingly they've come out with a lot of great products, not
just in the professional business but in the over-the-counter
products,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of her favorite over-the-counter lines is the Aussie brand,
which originated in Australia. She also likes Pantene. Fields has
used and likes L'Oreal's Color-Vive products. Both women say the
Infusium line is one of the best store-bought shampoos for your
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infusium has every kind of ingredient your hair needs,''
Gordon said. ``The leave-in treatment is good, especially in the
summertime for those out in the sun a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to narrow down the choices of shampoos is to look for
shampoos specifically for your hair type. For instance, for oily
hair use shampoos formulated for oily hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does make a difference,'' Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   Many women don't know it, but one of the most important things
about shampoo is whether it's pH balanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be as close to the hairs' pH as possible,'' Hays
said.
</P>
<P>
   A good pH for a shampoo is in the 4.5 to 5.5 range, Hays said,
while Fields and Gordon said anything from 5.5 to 7.5 is normal and
that anything higher would be extremely alkaline.
</P>
<P>
   Most shampoos don't list their pH number, but you can test it
yourself with litmus paper strips, which can be purchased at beauty
supply stores or pharmacies. When dipped in shampoo, the strips
indicate what the pH is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a shampoo is real high in alkalinity, it will leave your
hair dry and brittle,'' Fields said. ``Baby shampoos used to be the
highest in alkaline. I think they've changed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Prell and Pert are very high in alkaline, Gordon reported.
</P>
<P>
   The shampoos that are high in alkaline often make the hair look
and feel great for a couple of weeks before fizzling out, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, Fields and Hays agree that shampoos like Pert and Prell
that tout ``thicker, fuller'' hair actually open up the hair's
cuticle to plump the hair. But after months of use, hair usually
has dull buildup and becomes unmanageable.
</P>
<P>
   Hays says people should be leery of promotional advertisements
for hair products and unscientific surveys.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was astounded to see a survey on a TV investigative
report that put about 20 shampoos to the test. Women shampooed with
the products for about three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women picked Pert, saying it left their hair really full
and bouncy, but where the problems lie is after about about three
to six months of use,'' Hays said. ``The show left the public
thinking Pert was the best shampoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a woman finds a couple of good shampoos and conditioners,
it's a good idea to alternate them about every two weeks to give
your hair a break, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never stick with the same shampoo,'' she said. ``You've got to
rotate.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to strip off the buildup on the hair at
least once a week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for your hair, especially if you use a lot
of mousses and things,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   To test for buildup, stretch out a lock of hair and scrape the
open edge of a sharp pair of scissors back and forth on the hair.
The white flakes that pop up are what has built-up on the hair.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon doesn't trust many of the ``clarifying shampoos'' to do
the job of taking off the buildup. Some may not only take off the
buildup, but color and perms, too. Baking soda will do the job
better, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take plain baking soda from the kitchen and mix it in your
hand with some shampoo and just work that with the shampoo,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   TIPS ON GETTING HAIR BACK INTO SHAPE
</P>
<P>
   _ For dry, brittle hair: Try cutting back on the amount of
shampoo you use if you wash your hair every day. Use a conditioning
shampoo. Try a leave-in treatment like Infusium 23, concentrating
on the ends.
</P>
<P>
   Be weary of overconditioning the hair and using waxy ingredients
like oils and cholesterol, which weigh the hair down. Use
alcohol-free styling products.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating all or some of the heat you style your hair with is
key to getting dry hair back on track. Of course, that's not always
possible, so experiment with a couple of the above tips to see
wha-- , if anything, works. n For thick, course hair: Naturally
curly hair tends to dry out faster than any other type of hair,
says Pat Gordon of Vogue College of Cosmetology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be using a leave-in conditioner all summer,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Use products specifically formulated f-- r dry, damaged hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ For colored or permed hair: Using a good shampoo and
conditioner on permed and colored hair is a key to keeping a perm
from falling out and color from fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shampoos will shorten the life of a perm and you need to watch
that,'' said Vogue's Brenda Fields. ``A lot of (salons) will not
guarantee their perms because if you go home and use something like
Suave or Prell or Head and Shoulders, it will strip that perm out.
Like that shampoo Perma Soft that was so popular several years ago.
I had more customers whose perms didn't hold and they'd come back
and blame me. They were using Perma Soft. It was making the hair so
soft, it -- as overconditioned.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For fine, fly-away hair: The center of the hair, called the
medulla, usually isn't formed completely in fine hair _ the same
reason a lot of children's hair won't hold a perm, Gordon said.
Always use products for fine hair, but shy away from shampoos that
tout things like ``fuller, thicker, bouncy'' hair, like Pert, she
advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Healthy hair, without a lot of chemicals, probably could stand
it for a while, but overall, it's going to damage it,'' Gordon
said. ``It roughens it up and that's what makes it feel thicker and
more volumnized.'' It also could stri-- color-treated hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ For flakes and dandruff: Some shampoos will dry out hair and
activate dandruff. Ask your hairdresser or doctor about suggested
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   _ For oily hair: It's important to use a shampoo formulated for
oily hair. Concentrate the shampoo more on the roots than on the
ends of the hair. Use a light conditioner that contains no wax or
coating ingredients that willweigh the hair down.
</P>
<P>
   _ For men's hair: Men can use the same shampoo women do because
they have the same scalp and the same hair. Men should try to cut
back on the amount of shampoo they use because it could be drying
their hair and scalp. Try mixing a few drops of shampoo with a few
drops of water in your hand before shampooing. Men need to
condition their hair, especially if spending a lot of time in the
sun or if they use a blow-dryer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men need to condition, but maybe not quite as often as women,
but they need the whole treatment,'' Fields said.
</P>
<P>
   And men, stop grabbing that bar of soap to wash your hair!
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
