<HEADER>
A3510 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX     05-04 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    While NRA show carried on, father lead gripping procession
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ To hear Charlton Heston say it, you'd think the
National Rifle Association was just in Denver on Saturday to pay
its respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same right to be here, to shoulder the grief, to
share our sorrow,'' he said, an eagle over his shoulder with rifles
in its talons. Good grief.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters outside the hotel while Heston spoke preferred that
he send regards from afar. But surely the Denverites understand.
The NRA has membership drives to run, souvenirs to sell, campaign
caches to amass, political enemies to target.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's presence did one good thing. It brought out a peaceful
army that gathered at the state Capitol and walked in procession to
the hotel five blocks away, gaining people all the way. It circled
the hotel before heading back. One marcher at the front was stunned
at the numbers. When the front end of the line returned to the
Capitol, ``we met up with the other end of the line.'' That's
12,000 people _ a half-mile of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   At the front was Tom Mauser, holding a sign with a fresh young
face on it and the words: ``My son Daniel died at Columbine. He'd
expect me to be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauser since has been on morning news programs, pointing out
what a poor job we do keeping guns out of the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know about the loopholes in the Brady Law? This is not a
rhetorical question. It's one that Daniel Mauser asked his father
one day after school. Tom Mauser didn't know. His son filled him
in.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest loophole: Though federally licensed gun merchants
must perform background checks for sales, those who aren't licensed
_ about half of all gun-show vendors _ don't. That makes gun shows
attractive for felons and people trying to stay one step ahead of
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Gun shows were a favorite haunt of David Koresh and followers as
they amassed the arsenal that led to the tragic standoff near Waco,
Texas in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe three of the guns used in the massacre
were purchased by a girlfriend of one of the Columbine shooters at
the Tanner Gun Show. The other gun, a semiautomatic TEC-DC9,
appears also to have had gun-show lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not these sales were legal, it appears the show takes
few provisions to guarantee that its sales are.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, to demonstrate the ease of purchasing an assault
weapon, staffers of Congresswoman Diana DeGette, D-Denver, went to
the Tanner Gun Show and purchased an SKS rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't ask for ID. They didn't ask for anything,''
DeGette told the Denver Post. ``They sold it for $200 cash, no
questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the type of profligate end run on gun laws that
President Clinton wants to end with background checks for all sales
at gun shows, not just from licensed dealers. Legislation of that
sort has run aground in the Texas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, quickly becoming a master of evasion, said
he supports closing the loopholes as proposed, but won't push
reviving the bill in Austin _ too late in the session, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady Law is nothing more than a provision to better enforce
gun laws already on the books. The NRA continuously says that the
federal government doesn't do a good enough job enforcing the laws
it already has. Daniel Mauser could have shown the NRA how.
</P>
<P>
   I agree with those who say that simply looking at firearms is an
act of delusion. The ingredients of the Columbine tragedy are
layered and all-encompassing _ every social nightmare rolled into
one. But among those layers is America's gun culture, a cult of
convenience even for lawbreakers, a cult of commerce that puts the
customer first.
</P>
<P>
   Heston blamed the media and people with political motives for
stirring up crowds such as the one outside his hotel. What an
insult to Mr. Mauser. He has no political agenda. Neither did his
son _ no souvenirs to sell, no lawmakers to buy.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
