r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK05-COX     05-04 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Index fund approach gains momentum
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someday soon, the gigantic, hallowed Fidelity Magellan fund may
not be the biggest mutual fund in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The amounts involved are staggering: Magellan, $90.77 billion;
Vanguard Index 500, $82.52 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There are other surprises:
</P>
<P>
   _ The challenger is, of all things, an index fund. You know, one
of those stodgy outfits that aim to be average, or as close as they
can get.
</P>
<P>
   _ Magellan has something of a handicap, since it closed to new
investors 17 months ago. But the fund has grown by more than $20
billion since then. How could that be? Retirement accounts continue
to pour in money every month, and the rising stock market has
driven the total value up nearly every month.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Bogle Sr., who sired the Index 500 fund and spent most of
his career pitching it to individual investors, no longer puts his
own new investments into the fund. He holds on to Index 500 shares
he already owns, but his choice for new money is a Vanguard fund
based on the much broader Wilshire 5,000-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, these two indexes should perform quite
similarly,'' Bogle said. ``I just think that owning the entire
market should be the basic approach in indexing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Index 500 fund does move into first place, it will be a
triumph of Bogle's passive approach over Peter Lynch's aggressive,
stock-picking techniques. Lynch was extraordinarily successful in
the years he made the Magellan fund famous.
</P>
<P>
   An index fund is a sloth by comparison, attempting to mimic the
performance of a given stock market index by buying and holding all
the stocks in the selected index. The theory is that stocks, and
the underlying indexes, generally go up over long periods. Thus,
long-term investors can go along for a worry-free ride by buying an
index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Active investors sneer at that rationale. They ask, ``Why try to
be no better than average?''
</P>
<P>
   One answer is that index funds are low-cost investments,
compared with other mutual funds. That means a relatively small
percentage of investors' money gets siphoned off to pay operating
and trading expenses. Another cost factor: Index funds don't buy
and sell very often, so they don't generate lots of tax
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Index funds also remove one element of investment risk. They
still have market risk, meaning they will go down if the stock
market does. But they don't expose investors to the risk that the
manager will pick the wrong stocks. That happens frequently with
hotshot fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the factor that explains why many institutional
investors, such as the big pension funds, started indexing years
ago with at least a portion of their portfolios: They never have to
explain why they picked crummy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason many individuals have picked index funds in
recent years is that the returns have been outstanding. The S&AMP;P 500
index has risen dramatically, and so have index funds that track
them.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Index 500 fund has given investors a 26.6
percent return, on average, over the last five years. That beats
the returns of 95 percent of similar stock mutual funds, according
to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago-based mutual fund researcher.
</P>
<P>
   This will not go on forever. Many people believe Vanguard Index
500 will lose investors the next time the market falls back. ``Much
of that money is not there because these are true converts to
indexing,'' said Sheldon Jacobs, publisher of the No-Load Fund
Investor newsletter. ``It's because the fund is doing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Jacobs has been increasing the percentage of
index funds in the sample portfolios he recommends in the
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The index funds are really for long-term investors,'' he
explained. ``If you get a year or two of underperformance, it's not
the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to look into indexing, there are a number of
choices. Among the fund groups that offer an S&AMP;P 500 mutual fund
are Fidelity (800-544-8888), Schwab (800-435-4000), T. Rowe Price
(800-638-5660), USAA (800-382-8722) and Vanguard (800-662-7447).
</P>
<P>
   For a Wilshire 5000 fund, check out Vanguard or Wilshire
(888-200-6796).
</P>
<P>
   Is indexing the right method for everybody, all the time? No.
But it's worth considering, especially for those who plan to leave
the money alone for many years. You can get arguments both for and
against. Remember what Mark Twain said: ``It's a difference of
opinion that makes horse races.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
