<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3512 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAVER05-COX     05-04 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAVER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaver goes Electric
 &HT;    By Carl Hoover
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Billy Joe Shaver has a ready quip for those
wondering about the title of his new album Electric Shaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my boy was born in Waco, I tried to name him that, but
wouldn't nobody go for it,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The joke within his joke is that between Shaver and his son
Eddie, Electric Shaver really could be named after Eddie, whose
blistering guitar work powers the album, energizing the rough-hewn
beauty in the senior Shaver's lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The two Shavers and their backing band perform as Shaver,
generally a foursome when they're on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Shaver split his childhood between Corsicana and Waco and
considers the latter his home. He spends his downtime in a home
outside Waco, although he prefers to keep its location close to his
vest to maintain a modicum of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   While he and Eddie performed for a ``Texas Music Cafe'' taping
late last month, it's unusual that Shaver plays publicly in the
Waco area. The reason? The money's not there for a musician to pay
the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pay hasn't been that good,'' he explained. ``It's a
strange market. It's my hometown, too, but we don't play around
here much.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he, Eddie and their band will support their new CD with
shows in Chicago, New York, Los Angeles, Houston, Dallas, San
Antonio, Austin and the like.
</P>
<P>
   A follow-up to Victory, his gospel-themed release on New West
Records, Electric Shaver brings Shaver and his son back to the
sound of Tramp On My Street, the 1993 album that put the
singer-songwriter back on the map, although not the map of
mainstream country.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Kennedy, who produced several albums for country
roots-rocker Steve Earle, shepherded Electric Shaver, and Shaver
says he's proud of the result.
</P>
<P>
   From the wailing initial note of Eddie's electric guitar to the
bluegrass flavor of ``She Can Dance,'' Electric Shaver offers odes
to the ordinary (the cheap booze of ``Thunderbird''); love songs to
Brenda, the love of his life who's fought cancer for more than a
year (``She Can Dance,'' ``I'll Be Here''); practical advice (``Try
and Try Again,'' with Shaver improvising as a shouting gospel
preacher); and humor (``People and Their Problems'').
</P>
<P>
   The latter shows Shaver's knack for summing up people and
situations in everyday language that's dead on target:
</P>
<P>
   My sister's kid is tatooed from his head down to his toes.
</P>
<P>
   He claims trouble follows him everywhere he goes.
</P>
<P>
   He's such a lazy, loafing, good for nothing drunken slob.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still thinks I oughter give his sorry a-- a job.
</P>
<P>
   People and their problems are giving me a pain.
</P>
<P>
   People and their problems are messing with my brain.
</P>
<P>
   I try to help them solve them, but they always stay the same.
</P>
<P>
   People and their problems are driving me insane.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that one doesn't hear much of Shaver's work on
country radio, although he's found a friend in the Americana music
format. Americana's affinity for roots music with an edge and grit
reminds Shaver of another musical movement two decades earlier, a
counter-Nashville one led by Willie Nelson, Kris Kristofferson,
Jerry Jeff Walker, their colleagues and a young man from Central
Texas who penned songs like ``Honky Tonk Heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just turns over, just like leaves,'' he says today.
</P>
<P>
   Shaver's songs married with son Eddie's crowd-pleasing guitar
style has found a home in the Americana niche where roots-rockers,
alternative country and neo-folk music find audiences and exposure.
Rolling Stone, CD Review and The Village Voice all put Shaver's
Tramp On My Street on their year's best albums lists, while
customers for the Internet book and music store Amazon.com tabbed
Victory the best country CD of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Early response to songs from Electric Shaver has confirmed
Shaver's pride in the new album. ``I like the balance of this one .
. . Young people enjoy it a lot and the older people seem to
tolerate it, so I guess it's OK,'' he deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Joe and Eddie will spend much of the immediate future
touring in support of their album, and Billy Joe notes he's working
on songs for its successor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he acknowledges that his son's musical talent
has drawn the attention of some notable rock musicians interested
in signing him to their touring bands.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens if Eddie decides to pack up and join another
band? Shaver paused. ``Punt, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaver knows enough about fame's roller coaster ride and the mix
of good and bad his own career has seen to place his pride in
quality of work, not the week-to-week travels a song may take on
the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy doing what I do and I sleep well,'' he summed up.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hoover writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
