<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There are, suddenly, a couple of freshets of
progressive impulse from political barrens ordinarily known instead
for their aridity: A referendum for liberal drug laws in Arizona
and popular support for protecting gays from hate crime in Texas.
(Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg is on vacation. His column
will resume May 24 for publication May 26.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Take the weirdness in
stride, I tell myself. Stop gawking at striped hair and half-bared
butts. They're not indicators of the person inside. I'm listening,
but I don't think I'm getting it. I'm still judging the book by its
cover. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ To hear Charlton Heston say it,
you'd think the National Rifle Association was just in Denver on
Saturday to pay its respects. ``We have the same right to be here,
to shoulder the grief, to share our sorrow,'' he said, an eagle
over his shoulder with rifles in its talons. Good grief. (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ The two boys, 18 and 19, were smart,
dreadfully smart. They came from an affluent neighborhood in a big
city. Their friendship was intense and poisonous. Together, without
adult supervision, they cooked up a Nietzschean superman fantasy:
their brilliance and superiority entitled them to murder anyone
they considered inferior. The year was 1924. The city was Chicago.
The Crime of the Century was the Leopold-Loeb case. (Rosenfeld, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
