for Disease Control and Prevention recommends targeting the vaccine
to people with the disease's distinct risk factors: multiple sex
partners, injection-drug use, frequent occupational exposure to
blood and transmission at birth from an infected mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's mandatory hepatitis B vaccine was tacked onto a hazardous
waste bill last year without debate. The AAPS said no Ohio school
has reported hepatitis B transmission.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A new laparoscopic procedure could help many of
the 41,000 Americans waiting for kidney transplants by making it
more practical for living relatives to donate a kidney, say doctors
who performed the operations at The University Hospital in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional operation is safe and reimbursed by insurance,
but would require an incision which nearly cuts the patient's body
in half. A 12- to-18-inch incision goes from the belly button
toward the spine, where a rib often must be removed to take out the
kidney. The recipient's operation, with the new kidney placed in
the abdomen, is much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Laparoscopy requires just a 3-inch incision just above the belly
button for removing the kidney, plus four holes of less than half
an inch along the ribcage for inserting miniature surgical tools
and a tiny camera to guide the surgeon. The donor watches a video
monitor to detach the kidney, and then it is pulled out through the
abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Laparoscopy evolved during the 1980s from arthroscopic joint
surgery, the first use of camera-guided miniature surgical tools.
Gynecologists used the scopes for examinations and by the late
'80s, surgeons used them for the relatively simple chore of
removing gall bladders. ``Sort of like picking a cherry off a
tree,'' Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland and Johns Hopkins Medical School in
Baltimore pioneered laparoscopic kidney removal. Only the Maryland
hospitals and Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York have done more
than 100, with another 12 to 20 starting in the past several
months.
</P>
<P>
   A calculating threesome spends time assessing the pesky airborne
grains that cause so much misery
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Every morning by 5:10, Atlanta's pollen patrol peers
through a microscope at hundreds of pink circular blobs. Then they
sort and count: one pine, two pine, three pine; one oak, two oak;
one ash; one sweet gum.
</P>
<P>
   How those numbers add up will make or break the day for hundreds
of thousands of allergy sufferers in the Atlanta area. The numbers
represent how thick with tree, grass and weed pollen our local air
is.
</P>
<P>
   LaWanda Day, Marie McFalls and Pam Griggs are the pollen
counters for the Atlanta Asthma &AMP; Allergy Clinic, which posts the
information daily on its pollen hotline. While this is the only
official pollen collection site in metro Atlanta, the readings
represent pollen concentrations from Cartersville to Covington.
</P>
<P>
   The more blobs on the slender glass rod under the microscope,
the higher the pollen count. Each pink spot represents a particular
pollen from a tree, grass or weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one that resembles Mickey Mouse ears is pine,'' Day
explained, peering into the 40-power microscope. ``We have to come
up with descriptions we can easily remember. Cedar is like a circle
with a star in the middle of it. Elm we think of as having a circle
within a circle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know pollen travels hundreds of miles, from sailors being
affected while out on ships,'' said Dr. Bob Berkowitz, research
director for the Atlanta Asthma &AMP; Allergy Clinic. ``Even if we
blacktopped all of Georgia, we would still get Alabama pollen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Marietta clinic, pollen is collected in a wooden box on a
second-story roof. Inside the box is a slender, inch-long glass
spindle nestled inside a narrow metal holder.
</P>
<P>
   One side of the tube is covered with silicone grease, to which
pollen particles stick. After the sample is collected every
morning, another tube is inserted and the box is put back into
place on the roof. To get an accurate reading, the collector must
spin for 30 seconds every 10 minutes, or 72 minutes out of every 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spinning time can be critical during peak season,''
McFalls said. ``It must be carefully timed for accurate sampling.''
</P>
<P>
   After a day and night of exposure to the air, the spindle is
covered with a dusty fuzz. To identify the pollen under a
microscope, the glassware is streaked with a pink stain that picks
up the proteins of each distinct pollen grain. The count begins
from one end of the spindle and ends at the other. After one-third
of the surface is counted, a mathematical formula tabulates the
total count.
</P>
<P>
   Wind-blown pollen is how trees spread their male seed but the
pollen counters say they don't think about their livelihood in
terms of nature, science or propagation.
</P>
<P>
   Tree Pollen Counts on April 12, 1999
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: 6,013
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh: 35
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C.: 96
</P>
<P>
   Miami: 10
</P>
<P>
   Fort Smith, AR. : 1,867
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, Okla.: 6,299
</P>
<P>
   Corpus Christi, Texas: 1
</P>
<P>
   Denver: 210
</P>
<P>
   Los Angles: 24
</P>
<P>
   Tucson: 30
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa holds highest pollen count ever recorded in nation: 14,000
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Highest pollen count ever recorded in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rain washes pollen out of air. Reading below 1 is rounded up.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Academy of Allergy, Asthma &AMP; Immunology
</P>
<P>
   WEED POLLEN
</P>
<P>
   (x 4000): Weeds, such as ragweed (Ambrosia), cause lots of
allergy misery. Just one ragweed plant can produce 1 billion pollen
grains. Ragweed is prevalent from mid-July through the first deep
frost.
</P>
<P>
   TREE POLLEN
</P>
<P>
   (x 3600): Many tree pollens, such as oak (Quercus), tend to
pollinate from February through May, causing allergy problems for
people in the Northeast, Southeast, South-
</P>
<P>
   west and along the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   GRASS POLLEN (Poaceae, x 1600): Grasses make up about 20 percent
of the earth's vegeta-
</P>
<P>
   tional cover. There are more than 1,200 species native to North
America; they are the primary cause of allergies from May through
October.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
