<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3520 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-EMOTIONS05-COX     05-04 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-EMOTIONS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Understanding the pulse of emotions
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Rollin McCraty says the heart has its own
brain, he's not suggesting the left ventricle can calculate long
division, conjugate verbs or identify colors.
</P>
<P>
   Those conscious decisions are made in the gray matter within the
skull. It's the unconscious emotions that are processed in the more
than 40,000 neurons of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   So when a car cuts us off on the highway, it is the brain that
quickly converts the sight into instructions to hit the brakes or
change lanes. And just as quickly, the heart converts the same
sight into the tense and testy feelings we associate with fear and
anger.
</P>
<P>
   Once we understand the heart's physical relationship to
emotions, we can use that relationship ``to help manage emotions,''
says McCraty, research director and institute co-founder of the
Institute of HeartMath near San Jose, Calif. With his co-founders,
he has developed techniques for changing the messages the heart
sends through its own nervous system to the rest of the body,
creating the highs of love and compassion or the unpleasant
physical and mental effects of fear, anger and other stressful
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   The approach takes advantage of growing evidence that emotions
can affect thoughts instead of only the other way around, as has
been traditionally believed. HeartMath researchers, lacking medical
backgrounds and challenging mainstream philosophies, have raised
some eyebrows and voices among critics, but also have been
published in The American Journal of Cardiology and have assembled
an international advisory board of doctors in various specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Their techniques are the cornerstone of The HeartMath Solution
(HarperCollins, $24), which McCraty will present from 7 to 8 p.m.
Wednesday at Borders Books, Music &AMP; Cafe, 2040
Miamisburg-Centerville Road., Miami Twp. It was written by
co-founders Doc Childre and Howard Martin with Donna Beech.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between emotional states and heart physiology
traces its roots to Yellow Springs, where John and Beatrice Lacey
studied it through the 1960s at the Fels Research Institute, now
part of the Wright State University School of Medicine, with a
focus on changes in body shapes.
</P>
<P>
   They called the heart's communication pathways to the brain
``the key to the understanding'' of what is now called the
mind-body connection, and advocated the cardiovascular system as an
important area of psychiatric study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Laceys are legends now,'' McCraty says, and their research
is still valuable more than 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's relatively new,'' he says, ``is how complex the nervous
system in the heart is, and that it can and does function
independently of the central nervous system. It can beat on its own
without any connection to the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Heart rates are always changing in a healthy heart, McCraty
says. When we experience pleasant emotions such as appreciation,
those changes are consistently rhythmic enough to dance to,
yielding a graph of smooth peaks and valleys. But during
frustration or insecurity, the graph is erratic and jagged, a
pattern that interferes with the heart's messages to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't think as clearly,'' McCraty says. ``Which is one
reason when we get angry, we tend to say things we later regret.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a fine response to prehistoric stresses that were
pretty much limited to large, hungry animals, devastating weather
or other humans with spears. That reaction of the brain to
emotional stressors is the fight-or-flight response, named for the
only prehistoric options to danger. It accelerates the heart,
breath and hormonal rates that are needed for strength and speed,
and it shuts down everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting and fleeing don't apply very well to the modern
stressors of rude retailers, unreasonable bosses, crying children
and empty checkbooks. That is why we have stress-management
programs, although McCraty says they still aren't prevalent in
corporate cultures that generate the most stress.
</P>
<P>
   The programs available for managing stress typically feature
either meditation or exercise, he says. Both approaches are aimed
at the brain's fight-or-flight response, raising the threshold
before it becomes disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're helpful, but they really don't get at the source of
the stress,'' McCraty says. That source begins with ``how we're
perceiving the events in our life,'' and proceeds to which emotions
the perceptions trigger and which heart patterns the emotions
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ultimately shift our perceptions,'' he says. ``The
same events are going to happen. We're not going to stop the
traffic jams. But we can modify how we're perceiving them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the HeartMath techniques, called Freeze-Frame, can be
used ``in the middle of a staff meeting or while you're talking to
someone on the phone,'' McCraty says. While meditation works at
preventing emotions from going out of control under stress, the
HeartMath team wanted to develop easy techniques that could be used
in the moment of stress _ more of a drive-through solution for a
drive-through world.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze-Frame begins with recognizing the stress and shifting the
focus away from the problem, toward the heart for at least 10
seconds. Then recall a happy moment _ of friendship, recognition or
enjoyable activity, for example _ and try to experience it again.
The idea is to learn how to create feelings of love or appreciation
that override the jagged heart rhythms of instinctive frustration
or anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart has a type of intelligence that's not cognitive,''
McCraty says, ``but more on the feeling level, more intuitive. It's
part of why we feel our emotions in the heart. That's been
recognized in folklore for centuries, but not in science until the
modern recognition that the heart is one of the key points in our
emotional system.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
