<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-CRIMINALS-II-2TAK     05-04 2207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-CRIMINALS-II-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN `CLEANSING' BY SERBS LIVING IN VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (a and i coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo/graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIJEDOR, Bosnia and Herzegovina _ Three years ago, Zijad Music
arrived in Burlington, Vt., directly from the war that ripped apart
this city. He has been working like a dog ever since. He moves
furniture by day and works in a bakery at night, getting home just
in time to see his two daughters head off to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here,'' he said during a recent interview at a bar
in a Burlington mall. ``I'm really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Music is hardly a typical refugee of the war in the former
Yugoslavia. Although he entered the United States by portraying
himself as a victim of ethnic cleansing, Music appears to have been
a participant in one of the most brutal episodes of the war: the
deadly purge of some 60,000 non-Serbian civilians from Prijedor and
its surrounding villages in northwestern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Former Serb combatants, Bosnian refugees, and even Music's own
relatives identified Music as a former member of a ruthless
paramilitary unit that terrorized local Muslims and Croats during
the Serb army's campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   The events here between 1992-95 were a grim preview of the
slaughter now taking place in Kosovo. A United Nations commission
concluded that the systematic application of murder, torture, rape,
and mass deportation in Prijedor constituted ``crimes against
humanity'' and probably genocide, resulting in the deaths of
thousands of innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Music (pronounced Moo-shich), 39, denied he was ever part of the
much-feared paramilitary group, which called itself El Manijakos,
or The Maniacs.
</P>
<P>
   But Jean Ouellette, deputy district director of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service's regional office in Portland, Maine,
called the information gathered by the Globe about Music ``very,
very disturbing.'' Had the INS known of it beforehand, Ouellette
said, ``certainly the process wouldn't have resulted in the
granting of refugee status'' without an investigation of the
charges. He said the agency has begun a review of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Music's presence in Vermont has sparked fear and outrage within
Burlington's 4,000-member Bosnian community, and has raised
questions about the number of Serb collaborators who may have
slipped into the United States through the government's vast
refugee program, which provides a safe haven to tens of thousands
of people each year who are deemed to have been persecuted abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 83,247 Bosnian refugees who entered the United States
between 1993-98, most were Muslim and Croat civilians fleeing the
bloodiest war in Europe since World War II. However, in addition to
Music, there have been several recent reports of refugees with
possible links to ethnic cleansing who have surfaced in other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the INS opened an investigation into another Bosnian
refugee, Jezdimir Topic, after witnesses told the Globe that he had
served as a guard at the notorious Trnopolje prison camp outside
Prijedor before settling with his family in the Boston suburb of
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has identified another member of Music's paramilitary
group, Dragan Borcic, living in Bismarck, N.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are definitely part of a larger problem,'' said Shawn
Roberts, legal counsel for the Center for Justice and
Accountability, a San Francisco-based human rights organization
funded by Amnesty International. The group brought a civil suit
last year against Nikola Vuckovic, a Bosnian Serb refugee in
Atlanta who allegedly beat Muslim and Croat detainees with pipes,
bats, and other objects. The suit charges Vuckovic with genocide
and other crimes against humanity. He has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Music has not been charged with any crimes, and no suits have
been filed against him. He said people mistakenly have accused him
of being a member of El Manijakos because the Serbs forced him to
work as an accountant for the 43d Motorized Brigade, to which El
Manijakos reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are bitter and they're blaming me,'' he said, speaking
through a translator in his native Bosnian. ``I worked for the army
and so they automatically blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Music hinted that as a Bosnian Muslim who worked for
the Serbs, he may have taken actions he regrets to protect himself
and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're supposed to save your own life, in a certain
situation, what are you supposed to do?'' he asked. ``I mean, you
have your family to protect and you're forced to do all kinds of
things. There were threats, and more threats, and then it all
played out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumping into one's persecutor after fleeing horrors experienced
thousands of miles away can be a refugee's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   One former Muslim resident of Prijedor who lives in Vermont and
requested anonymity, said of Music: ``I can't understand how the
aid agency and the American government could let him come in.
Everyone knows what he did. And they put him in Burlington, where
there are a lot of people from Prijedor.''
</P>
<P>
   US immigration officials did not interview Music before he
entered the country, said an INS official familiar with the case,
who added there is no indication he was even asked to fill out a
refugee application form, on which he would have been asked about
his military history. Music's persecution claim, the official said,
appeared to rest entirely on statements made by his wife, Asra, a
former nurse who was kidnapped and shot by Serb assailants along
with her mother and brother. Music's wife was the only one of the
three to survive the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, what a great country we have,'' said the official, who
asked not to be named. ``A lot of the time in these refugee cases
it seems like they just throw open the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Music contended that the shooting proved that he and his family
had been persecuted by the Serbs like most Muslims in Prijedor.
However, several pieces of evidence suggest that the shootings _
which were confirmed by Serb military sources _ occurred despite
the fact that Music had been a member of one of the most dangerous
Serb ``hit squads.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence includes a homemade video, obtained by the Globe,
that shows Music wearing a distinctive El Manijakos patch on his
Serb uniform while serving as a pallbearer at the funeral of the
unit's commander, Dragan Janjetovic. The video also shows Music
drinking with about 30 members of El Manijakos, singing Serb
nationalist songs, and posing with a powerful M-34 machine gun
known to soldiers as the ``Sower of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Nusret Sivac, a former Bosnian Muslim resident of Prijedor,
identified Music as a member of El Manijakos in a book he wrote
about the Serb assault on the town. The unit, he said in an
interview, was ``responsible for doing the dirtiest deeds'' of
ethnic cleansing. ``They would do whatever they wanted: killing,
slaughtering, robbing, raping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former member of El Manijakos, Atko Blazevic, said in an
interview that he, Music, and five other members of the unit were
arrested and detained by Serb military police following a botched
1993 robbery attempt in which a woman was allegedly tortured.
Blazevic said the group had intended to force an elderly Muslim
couple from their home and give the house to a Serb family, a
common tactic used by the Serbs during ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Blazevic claimed that the crime wasn't his idea and that he
stayed outside the house while Music and the others went inside.
``You should ask Zijo about that; he was inside the house,'' said
Blazevic, using Music's nickname. ``He was with that old couple.
They picked him out when the military police came and asked who did
what.''
</P>
<P>
   Music said he was aware of accusations that he participated in
the crime but denied he committed it. Instead, he alleged that
Blazevic and three other members of El Manijakos were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about everything that happened there, but I wasn't
there,'' Music said.
</P>
<P>
   Semsa Suhonic, 67, said in an interview that while robbing her
home the attackers stuffed a rag in her mouth, kicked and beat her,
burned her breasts with cigarettes, dropped a heavy sack of corn on
her head, tried to hang her with a belt, slashed her clothes, and
drew a knife across her throat, cutting her, until she finally
begged them to kill her. The attack put her in the Prijedor
hospital for 12 days, according to a hospital certificate that
confirmed her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started burning my hair with matches and cigarettes,''
she said. ``Then one of them said, `Don't burn her hair, it smells.
Just light her on fire completely.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She said one of the men head-butted her several times, then, as
she slumped against a wood-paneled wall, stabbed a knife around her
head, and threatened to thrust it into her forehead if she refused
to give him money. She said the man then forced her to recite a
prayer from the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police came they saw me all bloody and they asked,
`What did the guy who hit you the most look like?' '' said Suhonic,
who later gave her testimony to a Bosnian government commission
investigating war crimes. ``I said it was a balding guy, with a
black mustache, in a black coat. They said, `That's the Muslim,
grandma, that's our captain Ziko.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ziko is one of Music's nicknames. He has a receding hairline and
a mustache. Other refugees from Prijedor said he was often seen
wearing a black hat and coat.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bosnian refugees have cited Suhonic's account as evidence
that Music was one of the assailants. However, Suhonic was unable
to positively identify Music from a recent photo or pick him out of
the video of El Manijakos. She noted that six years had passed
since the incident. In addition, former members of the unit said
Music was not a captain but merely a soldier. Blazevic said the
group, including Music, was held for nearly a week by the Serbs,
then released.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military officials in Prijedor referred questions about
Music and El Manijakos to Major Milodrag Glusac of the 43d
Motorized Brigade. Glusac said he could not confirm the incident,
but that it sounded consistent with activities El Manijakos engaged
in, particularly when they drank.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Manijakos had problems with everybody when they got
drunk,'' Glusac said. He recalled Music as a good soldier who,
while a Muslim, was ``more of a Serb than half of the people in
Manijakos. . . . He performed his assignments very well. Of course
he did some small bad things, but everybody did a few bad things.''
</P>
<P>
   Music's apparent involvement with El Manijakos has left him
estranged from much of his family. His uncle, Sakib Music, said:
``He was worse than the Serbian Chetniks,'' the ultranationalists
charged with widespread abuses during the war. ``I'm his father's
younger brother, and I can tell you that he killed his father _ not
directly, but his father died of agony and suffering'' knowing what
Music had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd kill him if I could get my hands on him,'' Sakib Music
said.
</P>
<P>
   Music's aunt, Zekija Music, also said Music's father, Eniz, was
overcome with grief over his son's involvement with El Manijakos.
``He got sick and he died, yes, that's right,'' she said. But she
feels more pity than anger for her nephew. ``I feel bad for people
like Zijo, do you believe me?'' she said. ``The world has accused
them, condemned them. I feel bad because his own people hate him.
There's no more room for him with the Serbs or the Muslims. And
that's the real truth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little hint
</P>
<P>
   of horrors to come
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Music's relatives said he lived a rather ordinary life before
the war. A kung fu champion in his youth, he dressed well, worked
hard, and landed a job as an accountant at a state-run construction
company called Bosnamontaza. Eniz Music, his father, was one of the
most popular men in Prijedor, the helpful and affable manager of an
appliance store in the center of town.
</P>
<P>
   Music courted his wife walking the promenades of Prijedor. Their
two daughters, said Sakib Music, ``are like golden apples.'' Zijad
Music's only affiliation with the military before the war was
mandatory duty as a reservist in the former Yugoslav army. Although
he is Muslim, he said his life wasn't much different than everyone
else's in Prijedor: he thought little of his ethnicity and counted
Serbs, Muslims, and Croats among his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine what kind of life we had,'' he said. ``We
had such a good life. For all of us to become enemies, when we all
speak the same language, when we all lived together so beautifully,
it was just like mass confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Music said he was still an army reservist when Yugoslavia began
to come apart in 1991. When the Serbs took over the military, he
said, they forced him to continue working ``on computers and
accounting. It was very difficult. Any mistake you made you could
be held accountable for; in a second you could be killed.'' He said
he left the military for good in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
