   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ A compilation of health briefs from the past
week. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-EMOTIONS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When Rollin McCraty says the
heart has its own brain, he's not suggesting the left ventricle can
calculate long division, conjugate verbs or identify colors. Those
conscious decisions are made in the gray matter within the skull.
It's the unconscious emotions that are processed in the more than
40,000 neurons of the heart. So when a car cuts us off on the
highway, it is the brain that quickly converts the sight into
instructions to hit the brakes or change lanes. And just as
quickly, the heart converts the same sight into the tense and testy
feelings we associate with fear and anger. Once we understand the
heart's physical relationship to emotions, we can use that
relationship ``to help manage emotions,'' says McCraty, research
director and institute co-founder of the Institute of HeartMath
near San Jose, Calif. With his co-founders, he has developed
techniques for changing the messages the heart sends through its
own nervous system to the rest of the body, creating the highs of
love and compassion or the unpleasant physical and mental effects
of fear, anger and other stressful emotions. (Lamb, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SHAMPOOS _ WACO, Texas _ WARNING! Your shampoo may be hazardous
to your hair. How do men and women sift through the sea of
non-salon shampoos and conditioners to find the best products for
their hair? We take a look at the drugstore-brand shampoos. (Mays,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HESAID04 and SHESAID04 _ Bo Emerson and Maureen Downey share
thoughts on letting children take risks. (Bo's more willing to let
them do so; Maureen errs on the side of protectiveness.) (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MAJORETTES _ What has happened to the twirler? There was a time
when the mighty majorette, in her sassy sequins and pompommed
boots, was envied by campus coeds everywhere. Over the past two
decades, though, she has pretty much pranced off the football field
and into gymnasiums where competitions are held. (Sturrock, Palm
Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
