<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-GM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM TO BUILD FUTURISTIC ASSEMBLY PLANT IN SOUTHERN BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The General Motors Corp. has reached an
agreement on terms for completion of a futuristic factory in a
southern Brazilian state, which last week lost a similar project
planned by the Ford Motor Co. because of disagreements on how it
would be financed.
</P>
<P>
   In an accord reached on Saturday, GM agreed to earlier
repayments on a loan of about $150 million extended by the state of
Rio Grande do Sul so the car maker could move forward with the
plant, an innovative assembly operation known as Blue Macaw
expected to produce 120,000 subcompact automobiles a year.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to repay the loan more quickly, GM will ease some of
the budget anxieties that had led Rio Grande do Sul into conflict
with GM and Ford. GM had stopped construction and said that it
might have to delay opening the plant by as long as six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``By next week, work on the plant should be started again,''
said Luiz Moan, institutional affairs director for GM's Brazilian
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Rio Grande do Sul had said they could not afford to
spend money subsidizing the construction at the expense of
education and public welfare projects that have already been hurt
because of the country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Their position seemed to soften after Ford decided to leave,
taking the promise of hundreds of jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The $600 million GM factory, considered a prototype for future
GM plants in North America, is designed so that suppliers are
adjacent to the assembly of the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   GM chose the site because of a combination of incentives granted
by Rio Grande do Sul's previous government and the proximity to
Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay, Brazil's partners in the Mercosur
trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has yet to choose another site for its factory, a project
to produce a competing small automobile. Parana and Santa Catarina,
two other states in southern Brazil, have shown an interest in
luring Ford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
