<P>
   BABBITT-EXECUTION (San Quentin, Calif.) _ Manuel Pina Babbitt, a
decorated ex-Marine who claimed he was having a Vietnam combat
flashback when he murdered a 70-year-old woman nearly two decades
ago, was executed at San Quentin Prison early Tuesday. His final
words were, ``I forgive all of you.'' By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-WITNESS (San Quentin, Calif.) _ Although an execution
in California has become somewhat uneventful, routine even, it is
still hard to watch. As Manuel Babbitt started convulsing early
Tuesday morning, his head and chest lifting several times and his
restraints barely able to keep him on the table, even Laura
Thompson, the granddaughter of the murder victim, could not watch.
By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   MALLORY-EVEREST (Undated) _ It is perhaps the 20th century's
greatest unsolved exploration mystery: Did Englishman George Leigh
Mallory, clad in a tweed jacket and felt hat, reach the summit of
Mount Everest 29 years before Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing
Norgay? A big step toward answering that question was taken
Saturday with the discovery of Mallory's body high on Everest's
windswept north face. By JOHN FLINN.
