r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     05-04 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-RUNNING-FOR-PRESIDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADIES AND GENTLEMEN, THE NEXT NON-PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 For release: Tues., May 4 or thereafter  
 By GERALDINE A. FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    On January 20, 2001, it's an even chance that I'll be part of
the crowd outside the United States Capitol, bundled in a warm coat
and scarf but still freezing as I watch the next president of the
United States promise to support and defend the Constitution.
 &HT;    And it's almost certain that the hand on the Bible won't be
Lamar Alexander's.
 &HT;    Now, I'm not picking on the former Tennessee governor. It's also
pretty good odds that the person taking that oath won't be Gary
Bauer, Steve Forbes, John Kasich, Alan Keyes, Dan Quayle, Bob Smith
or even my former ``Crossfire'' partner, Pat Buchanan.
 &HT;    In the good old days, when candidates were chosen by political
bosses huddling in smoke-filled rooms, any of these men might have
had a chance. But today the voters do the picking, and getting to
those voters requires a political network and money _ lots and lots
of it.
 &HT;    Once upon a time, a dark-horse candidate could lie back and hope
the front-runner stumbled. Six back-of-the-packers took that
approach in 1992 against Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas, and were
rewarded when the front-runner's campaign crashed and burned.
Allegations of financial irregularities, draft-dodging and
marijuana use climaxed in a juicy sex scandal only days before the
all-important New Hampshire primary.
 &HT;    And still Clinton won.
 &HT;    So odds are that, come 2001, it will be Vice President Al Gore
or Gov. George W. Bush of Texas that we'll be calling ``Mr.
President.''
 &HT;    No, they're not the only prospects. Former Sen. Bill Bradley is
proving to be a formidable fundraiser and a credible alternative to
Gore, while Elizabeth Dole is new and exciting as the first female
to ever seriously contend for president. And with their experience
in government, no one questions for a minute that either would be
able to do the job as president.
 &HT;    But at 20 percent or more behind the front-runner, they face
formidable odds.
 &HT;    The rest of the candidates have virtually no chance, a fact that
seems apparent to everyone except themselves. Which raises the
obvious question: What makes these guys run?
 &HT;    I know a bit about losing campaigns. In 1984 I ran for vice
president on a ticket that started the campaign 18 points behind a
very popular incumbent president.
 &HT;    What did I think I was doing? Well, pundits told us it was
hopeless, but when the crowds were 10,000 and 20,000 deep on the
campaign trail I really believed we could win. I was also
convinced, having observed George Bush for four years, that I could
do the job.
 &HT;    But I had another incentive to give it my all. No matter what
happened on Election Day, the campaign was tearing down gender
barriers and opening doors of opportunity.
 &HT;    That might be the case with Pat Buchanan. Pat conceivably may be
deluding himself that he can win but, even if he doesn't, he will
fire up the extreme right merely by running, and make sure that the
issues he cares about are part of the debate.
 &HT;    Steve Forbes may simply believe he can buy the nomination. He's
a man who will bend in the political wind to shape his message into
whatever Republican voters want it to be, and he has the unlimited
financial resources to get that message heard.
 &HT;    The trouble is, he's not as rich as Ross Perot, and even Perot's
billions couldn't buy him a lease on the White House.
 &HT;    John McCain may simply not care what the odds are. The Arizona
senator, who happens to be my favorite of the group, is smart. He's
a war hero who's not an ideologue, and he tells the truth. The
latter two attributes, however, are probably his biggest obstacles
to raising the money he needs to be a plausible candidate.
 &HT;    Dan Quayle fills his own niche. He's a favorite of the
conservative money machine, and he's a former vice president. I
imagine he's noticed that, if Gore gets nominated, seven of the
last 10 vice presidents will have subsequently won nomination by
their party, and hopes he can make it an even eight.
 &HT;    Of course, none of them were running against their former boss'
namesake _ one Bush heir vs. another. But, that aside, his biggest
problem is getting people to stop giggling when he starts talking.
 &HT;    John Kasich may be running with the idea of raising his profile
for a future leadership role in the House, while Alan Keyes may be
in because he likes to debate and it means more and better paydays
on the lecture circuit in days to come.
 &HT;    But I can't conjure up even similarly weak reasons for Gary
Bauer, Lamar Alexander and Bob Smith to be in this race.
 &HT;    We politicians are often accused of being on ego trips, and in
some measure that's true: If you didn't believe you were better
than your opponents, you wouldn't be running.
 &HT;    But, unless you had some higher goal, I don't see how you could
subject yourself to the torment of fund raising, demanding voters,
unrelenting press criticism and grueling schedules if you didn't
believe you could win.
 &HT;    I'd bet that a lot of guys in positions of power in corporate
America, in professional organizations or in politics wake up
occasionally and say, ``I'm presidential material!''
 &HT;    Fortunately, they hit the snooze button and go back to sleep.
 &HT;    Too bad for the Republicans that half of their presidential
candidates didn't.
 &HT;    (Geraldine A. Ferraro, a former congresswoman and the Democratic
nominee for vice president in 1984, is a Manhattan-based
attorney.) 
 c.1999 Geraldine A. Ferraro 
