<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 5. If you have any questions, please call The Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO FOLO (developing; more slugs possible):
</P>
<P>
   BLOCK _ In Oklahoma City after Monday's tornadoes, where houses
once stood, there was nothing but garbage. Trees were stripped bare
or ripped from the ground. Devastation stretched as far as the eye
could see. Rick Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS _ Wichita was struck hard by the storms. The town of
Haysville was also hit by the Andover storm that killed 13.
Checking report that mobile homes were blown into a lake. Jim
Sullinger and Tom Perrin.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLAIN _ Tornado explainer. Mike Mansur.
</P>
<P>
   SAM _ U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican, holds a
hearing on the culture of violence. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   LOTT0: We meet the person who won $27 million in the Powerball.
The ticket was bought in Grandview, Mo. Photo. Erica Wood. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: Missouri legislators have crafted the partial birth
abortion bill to skirt the legal problems similar laws have
encountered in other states. Missouri's tactic was to declare
partial-birth abortions infanticide. The bill has been beset by
lots of partisan bickering, particularly over whether to comply
with Carnahan's request that the bill include a health exception
for mothers. Without it, he has promised to veto the bill. Sentell.
18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   LOGAN: It's not fair that one of Kansas City's most memorable
doctors might be best remembered for taking an ax to construction
equipment and then going to jail with a flower in his lapel. But a
1939 jailhouse photo is part of a new exhibit on Logan Clendening
at the University of Kansas Medical Center. He was a renaissance
man: Writer, doctor, friend of Hemingway and Mencken, collector of
rare medical books that make up the Clendening Library at KU
Medical Center. But he wasn't altogether well-adjusted. Brian
Burnes.
</P>
<P>
   KCPL _ KCP&AMP;L has its annual meeting. The status of the merger is
expected to be the main topic. Steve Everly
</P>
