<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALLORY-EVEREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY OF MALLORY'S BODY STIRS DEBATE THAT HE CLIMBED EVEREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is perhaps the 20th century's greatest unsolved exploration
mystery: Did Englishman George Leigh Mallory, clad in a tweed
jacket and felt hat, reach the summit of Mount Everest 29 years
before Sir Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay?
</P>
<P>
   A Northern California mountaineer-detective took a big step
toward answering that question Saturday when he discovered
Mallory's eerily well-preserved body high on Everest's windswept
north face.
</P>
<P>
   The remains, found on a ledge at about 27,000 feet where Mallory
apparently landed after a fatal fall, contain some tantalizing
clues that may help mountaineering historians unlock the
75-year-old riddle.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Anker of Big Oak Flat, Calif., who found the body, is
part of an expedition searching the upper flanks of the world's
highest mountain for clues to the fate of Mallory and his partner,
Andrew Irvine, who were spotted about 800 feet below the summit and
``going strong for the top'' before they disappeared into the
clouds June 8, 1924.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who believe Mallory may have reached the summit
before perishing is his grandson, Rick Millikan, a real estate
developer in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the odds are better than 50-50 that he did get up (to
the summit),'' said Millikan, 57, who added that the discovery of
his grandfather's frozen remains made him feel ``excited but a
little creepy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallory was the best-known mountaineer of his day, the dashingly
handsome, Cambridge-educated darling of British society. Asked why
he wanted to climb Everest, Mallory uttered the most famous phrase
in mountaineering history: ``Because it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallory and Irvine, a strong Oxford rower but inexperienced
mountaineer, were last seen alive high on Everest's Northeast Ridge
by Noel Odell, the expedition's geologist. The time was 12:50 p.m.,
and Odell wrote in his diary that the two appeared to be ``nearing
(the) base of (the) final pyramid.'' Minutes later, the clouds
closed in and they vanished into the mist.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they made the summit has been a mystery and controversy
debated from the venerable halls of the Alpine Club in London to
campfire circles in the Sierra Nevada for the last 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   One clue to the mystery emerged in 1975 when a Chinese climber,
Wang Hong Bao, told his teammates he had spotted the body of an
English climber in old-fashioned clothing on a ledge below the
Northeast Ridge. Before he could give more details, though, Wang
was swept to his death in an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory's body was discovered at least 1,000 feet below where
Odell last saw him, and considerably farther back down the ridge
toward the climbers' highest camp. According to Erin Copland, the
Anker expedition's U.S.-based spokeswoman, it appears Mallory must
have been on his way down when the fatal accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The search, conducted in temperatures well below zero, was grim
work. Anker, reporting on the expedition's Web site
(www.mountainzone.com), said he had passed the remains of two more
recent Everest victims that morning before finding Mallory.
</P>
<P>
   The body was face down on a rock ledge. Copland said some of
Mallory's clothing had been torn away _ possibly during the fall _
but that his body ``was remarkably well preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to be at peace,'' Anker reported.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with the wishes of Mallory's family in England,
the climbers performed a brief ceremony and buried the body where
they found it.
</P>
<P>
   Before doing so, though, they uncovered important evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory's mountain goggles were in a pocket inside his tweed
jacket, suggesting that he may have been descending after
nightfall, Copland said. And his body was still tied securely into
his climbing rope, which would seem to disprove a popular theory
that he had left Irving behind and continued alone toward the top.
</P>
<P>
   Anker and his teammates have descended to advanced base camp to
rest, and will return to the upper mountain to search for the body
of Irvine and the most important evidence of all: the Kodak
Vest-Pocket cameras Mallory and his partner were carrying.
</P>
<P>
   If either or both the climbers reached the summit, indisputable
proof probably lies within those metal boxes. Kodak engineers
believe that after 75 years in Everest's deep freeze, the film can
still yield usable images.
</P>
<P>
   Galen Rowell, a San Francisco area mountaineer and photographer,
has climbed high on Everest's north side twice and written about
the mystery of Mallory. It was apparently his reporting that helped
steer his friend Anker to the body. Rowell thinks the odds are that
Mallory probably didn't reach the top, but adds that ``nothing we
know right now rules out that he made it.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who's generally uncertain is Hillary. When he and
Tenzing made the first confirmed ascent of Everest in 1953, one of
the things he did during his short stay on the summit was search
for evidence that Mallory had preceded him. He didn't find any, but
he has always maintained there is a possibility he wasn't the first
on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tenzing and I would be downgraded a bit to be (only) the first
to reach the summit and survive, but I don't think we would
complain,'' he said in 1986. ``I personally believe that if anyone
has the right to be the first to be on top of Everest, it would be
George Leigh Mallory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
