<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERSATION GOES BEYOND WORDS IN DEALING WITH TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ My son is 16.5 years old. That unremarkable
fact gained relevance as I followed the news of the Littleton
school massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Young people of my son's age and circumstances _ teen-age high
school students _ stopped living, suddenly and without warning, in
murders perpetrated by two well-armed schoolmates. Their demise is
beyond sad.
</P>
<P>
   Like countless others, I tried to figure out why this happened,
and like everyone else, have gotten no deeper than the usual
cliches, platitudes and banalities: We live in a violent society,
the mass media glorify violence; guns and bomb-making ingredients
are too easy to get.
</P>
<P>
   And what about parental responsibility? The public knows little
of the relationship between the two killers and their parents other
than superficial details, such as the fact that both young men had
middle-class parents who lived at home together.
</P>
<P>
   How could they not have known their sons were planning for a
year their deadly assault on the high school? After all, the
sheriff said, a sawed-off shotgun barrel and bomb parts were found
in one boy's room.
</P>
<P>
   I believe parents bear a great deal of responsibility for the
behavior of their offspring. Our behavior around the home has
enormous influence on our children. How we guide, nurture and
direct our children also has significant consequences as they
develop from totally dependent beings to fully independent ones.
But being the father of a teen-age boy is teaching me not to judge
too quickly how other parents shepherd their children. It's an age
when our freedoms are virtually unlimited, and the best of
technological and industrial output is at our fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   I consider myself close to my son. I am around the house all the
time. It is hard for us to avoid contact. But there are things I do
not know about him, and that is how he wants it right now. This is
an all-too-familiar pattern of adolescent behavior in our
post-modern, post-industrial age. It is called growing up.
</P>
<P>
   At 16, he is still largely dependent on us in a material sense _
for shelter, food, clothing. From the start, his mother and I did
what we could to instill a value system, ill-defined and
intangible, that we believe falls within the norm of a civilized
society. We have always told him we love him, and continue to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   His mind, his feelings, his emotional life, however, are areas
where we are less certain of his dependency on us, and that too is
as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   He has learned from us, and presumably will continue to learn
from us. He has had and will continue to have other mentors and
influences _ peers, teachers, relatives, and, yes, the dreaded mass
media.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the Littleton massacre unfolded, he and his
mother had an emotional conversation about his right of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted his private space and time. He doesn't want his mother
or me to know too much about his friendships.
</P>
<P>
   He is fortunate to have close relationships with others his age
at a North Oakland after-school program called Destiny Arts Center,
which teaches martial arts, dance and performance as vehicles to
prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   It is a safe setting for him and other young people to share
deep feelings that are part of being a teen-ager today, whether
from middle-class or working-class backgrounds, regardless of
racial and ethnic heritages.
</P>
<P>
   My son and I have talked about the Littleton murders. He wrote a
powerful monologue about it for a performance Destiny Arts Center
is staging on May 21 and 22 at Holy Names College in Oakland _ and
I am pleased he, his mom, and I continue to talk, even if sometimes
he doesn't want to say too much to us.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
