<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI WALKS TIGHTROPE ON ISSUES DEAR TO GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As New York Gov. George Pataki takes his first,
faltering steps toward a spot on the Republican national ticket
next year, he's struggling to define himself to a nationwide
audience as a fiscal conservative and a social moderate. Each
position creates problems.
</P>
<P>
   As a fiscal conservative, the governor can't get a budget
through in his own state. And that's not merely because Democrats
in the Legislature want to spend more than he does. Pataki's fellow
Republicans want to spend more, too. They're fretting over what
they fear will be a tough election next year, especially in the
GOP-controlled state Senate. They want more state money to spread
around their districts before next year's races.
</P>
<P>
   As one Republican operative told me, New York remains a 5-3
Democratic state. A high turnout by an electorate still angry over
Bill Clinton's impeachment trial is a major concern for state
Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a lot of people,'' the operative told me, ``a Republican
senator is a Republican senator. They don't really distinguish
between Republican senators in Washington and Republican senators
in Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion movement is intensely powerful in the
Republican presidential primary process. If Pataki goes all out,
he'll have to sell his generally pro-choice view in states where
sentiment against abortion runs high in his party. In Heartland
states, a pro-choice position is difficult for GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of actually electing a Republican president
next year, however, Pataki is right. The most recent public polls
show that few Americans are comfortable with abortion, especially
late-term abortions. But nearly nine in 10 of us believe that a
woman should be able to obtain one if her health is seriously
endangered by the pregnancy, and three in five of us figure that
abortion is not the government's business.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than half of Americans agree with the 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision in which the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that
a woman could have an abortion at any point during the first three
months of pregnancy. But, in general, the polls indicate that
Americans view abortion as more acceptable early in pregnancy and
less acceptable later on.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two in three Americans view abortion rights as
reasonable, two in five view abortion opponents as extremists and
three in four oppose a constitutional amendment to ban abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Even among GOP voters, anti-abortion activists constitute a
distinct minority nationally. Nearly one in three Republicans
opposes abortion, but only one in four Republicans figures the
party should take a firm position against it. A larger percentage
of Republicans, one in three, believes that the GOP should leave
the issue alone.
</P>
<P>
   The reality, then, despite the 30 million abortions that have
taken place during the past quarter century, is that Roe. vs. Wade
seems to be settled law for most Americans. As a political issue,
abortion is really debated now at the margins _ parental
notification, later-term abortions, Medicaid funding for abortions
for poor women.
</P>
<P>
   What all that seems to mean for a pro-choice Republican seeking
a spot on next year's national ticket _ George Pataki, for example
_ is that the best way to argue his position to his party's
vigorous anti-abortion minority is simply to stress that most
voters don't share their views and that the party should avoid a
hard position on an issue on which so many Americans are so
ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tough sell to Republican voters in some parts of this
country. Ideally, a candidate pushing that view could change the
topic to how tight he is with taxpayer dollars. To do that, though,
a governor needs an austere state budget.
</P>
<P>
   So far, George Pataki doesn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
