<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLLY NED! MIDWESTERN IDIOM REDUX 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I don't know how they did it, but I am convinced
that long ago my parents implanted in me some sort of time-delay
computer chip. It is now going off.
</P>
<P>
   I decided this the other day after a disturbing incident in
which I tried to order a prosciutto-and-Gorgonzola sandwich at a
nearby coffee bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the weekly special,'' I told the nice young counter
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one of the specials?'' he said. ``The prosciutto or the
feta-and-tapenade?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you have two specials?'' I said, suddenly perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Then these words tumbled from my mouth: ``Golly, Ned!''
</P>
<P>
   The clerk blinked and said, ``Golly, Ned? I've never heard
anybody say `Golly, Ned!'''
</P>
<P>
   I mumbled that it was Midwestern idiom. I did not tell him that
I hadn't uttered it in at least 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   My mom says ``Golly, Ned'' a lot and has for as long as I can
remember. But I, the San Francisco sophisticate, do not say
``Golly, Ned.'' At least I didn't used to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the computer chip has been activated, who knows? The
Golly Ned shocker got me to paying attention to the rest of my
speech. It's riddled with Momisms _ and Dadisms.
</P>
<P>
   Upon seeing the slightly scuffed face of a friend, just off a
grueling, many-stops flight from New York, I shook my head and
said, ``What happened to you? You look like you've been sorting
wildcats.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother and father make the sorting-wildcats comment often.
</P>
<P>
   But in all my nearly 50 years, I think I never said it until I
saw my friend's face.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that, a colleague was trying to describe the
circuitous route she took to complete several errands. Groping for
the right words, she said, ``By the time I was finished it was like
I'd, uh, uh ...''
</P>
<P>
   Reflexively, I completed her sentence: ``You ended up having to
go around Joe Dilly's barn.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked at me and said, ``Who the hell is Joe Dilly?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, my parents deny implanting a chip in me. But they
have no other explanation for why I'm all of a sudden using their
homey Midwestern phrases.
</P>
<P>
   I have to stay on the alert.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a friend from Back East told me she'd heard we
were having unseasonably chilly weather again in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It took Herculean strength to keep from saying, ``Yep, it's
colder out here than a well digger's wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-04 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A WORRY IN THE WORLD WITH ANXIETY HOT LINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wednesday is National Anxiety Screening Day, and
I'm ready.
</P>
<P>
   I'm good and worried. Are you?
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever experience a sudden, unexplained attack of intense
fear, anxiety or panic for no apparent reason? Do you find it
difficult to control your worrying? Have you ever been afraid of
not being able to escape in certain situations?
</P>
<P>
   Those are three of the questions posed by a Massachusetts outfit
called the National Mental Illness Screening Project. It's a tough
time to be doing differential diagnosis on worrying.
</P>
<P>
   How do you tell from a few questions if you're one of the
estimated 19 million Americans with panic disorders, phobias,
obsessive-compulsive disorders or generalized anxiety disorders?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of us have sudden attacks of fear that the new millennium
could bring a stock market crash or a prolonged Balkans war. Is
that a natural human worry, or is it a panic disorder, which can be
treated with therapy?
</P>
<P>
   After the mass killings at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., a lot of us can't control our worrying about our kids. Is
that so nuts?
</P>
<P>
   Is it better if it's all in your head or not?
</P>
<P>
   If you're seriously anxious about something (or especially
nothing), call a hot line at 888-442-2022, and the National Mental
Illness Screening Project will give you some local numbers to call.
</P>
<P>
   I can't vouch for the shrinks you'll see, but the automated hot
line was very professional, although I don't know if it was nodding
reassuringly.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this is the group that started an automated
depression hot line for city workers in Boston. It's a good thing
they didn't start it in San Francisco, because Mayor Willie Brown
would be on the line all the time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm worried that San Francisco has a civic-compulsive disorder.
People here keep doing the same things over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   A group of advocates of anonymous sex is trying to put a
initiative on the ballot to reopen the gay bathhouses that were
closed in 1984 because of the AIDS epidemic. Never mind that the
epidemic hasn't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a ballot initiative, naturally it has a marvelous
name, the Sexually Transmitted Disease Reduction Initiative. I
guess the idea is that getting groups of men together for anonymous
sex reduces transmission of disease because they'll be reading
pamphlets together.
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, so there are people with even wilder and
safer ideas about sex.
</P>
<P>
   The people at Good Vibrations, San Francisco's leading sex toy
store, remind us that the safest sex of all is with someone you
really love _ yourself.
</P>
<P>
   May is the fourth annual National Masturbation Month, and Good
Vibrations is celebrating it with the first national
Masturbate-a-Thon. It's a fund-raiser for HIV-prevention charities
that works like bike-a-thons.
</P>
<P>
   You get people to pledge a certain sum for each minute you spend
enjoying the form of sex that former Surgeon General Jocelyn Elders
recommended as healthy, and the Catholic Church of yore did not.
Please, do not bring proof of time spent Jocelyning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-CHILD-LABOR-NYT     05-04 2229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CHILD-LABOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN INDIA, CHILDHOOD is FOR SALE  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By SOMA WADHWA  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Sonia is 12 and blind; not surprisingly, she has never played
with footballs, but from age six she was forced to stitch them,
eight hours a day, seven days a week. Her dainty, deft fingers
would often pierce her tiny hands with the needle as she pieced
together tough bits of leather.
 &HT;    But the child taught herself never to yelp in pain for fear of
losing employment, which would have threatened her family's
survival. Yet at the end of each day, she had not earned enough to
buy even a loaf of bread.
 &HT;    Still, Sonia was one of the lucky ones. Kailash Satyarthi, who
has been fighting child labor for the last two decades, raided the
factory _ media in tow _ where she and many other children worked.
After a tough fight through headlines that embarrassed the football
manufacturer, Mayor and Co., Sonia was given back her childhood.
She now lives in the state Vocational Rehabilitation Center for the
Blind in Ludhiana, Punjab.
 &HT;    Kailash, who is 44, has seen many such misery-ridden Sonias
through to happy endings, yet he is no invincible hero. In fact,
the crusade he has launched against child servitude in South Asia
has seen him coping with as many disheartening defeats as
victories.
 &HT;    ``How can I gloat over little triumphs when I see so many
children being wasted as overworked and underpaid help at squalid
factories, dingy shops and affluent urban homes every single day of
my life? When I know that parents still give children away at brick
kilns to work as bonded laborers as repayment of debt?''
 Millions of Workers, Millions of Slaves  
 &HT;    Sikander was 17 when he joined the Delhi shelter after six years
of inhuman working conditions in a carpet factory in the Mirzapur
district in Uttar Pradesh. Forced from age 10 to support a widowed,
ailing mother and two younger siblings, Sikander toiled 12 hours a
day to keep starvation at bay.
 &HT;    ``I worked in tin sheds, which get terribly hot during summers.
Also'' _ and he winced as he recalled those times _ ``we were often
beaten if we made any mistakes.'' Then he was rescued by Kailash's
network, and he is now training to become a welder.
 &HT;    Of the estimated 140 million working children in India, nearly
half are, in effect, slaves. Poverty-stricken parents who need
paltry sums of money _ sometimes just for basic sustenance _ borrow
from moneylenders and literally sign away their livelihoods
forever.
 &HT;    ``There is just too much of this around for us to feel content
about our work,'' Kailash said. ``A problem of such a large scale,
I have come to believe, has to be fought strategically: Raids,
rescue and rehabilitation have to go hand in hand with engineering
national and international aversion and support against child
labor.''
 &HT;    This is the philosophy that Kailash practices, that has spurred
him and his organization, the South Asian Coalition Against Child
Servitude, to identify and liberate more than 34,000 children
working in industries across India, where grimy little hands
working to fight hunger are an accepted reality. Even the upwardly
mobile middle-class thinks little of employing young children to
prepare their morning cuppa because such domestic help is plentiful
and cheap.
 &HT;    And parents in the poverty-ridden rural pockets are often forced
to barter their children to repay debts that keep death away.
 The Economics of Bonded Labor  
 &HT;    Many companies fight to keep child laborers at work because to
the manufacturers, it makes good economic sense. Factories making
carpets, sporting goods, firecrackers, bangles and brassware prefer
smaller hands to do the intricate work especially because children
do not demand better working conditions or more pay.
 &HT;    There are also criminal elements who conspire to control the
network of children in servitude and thwart the laws that ban
employment of youngsters. As a result, no employer has ever been
punished for violating a 1986 act that prohibits employing children
in the carpet industry, a sector defined as hazardous. Frequently,
employers of child labor shield their enterprises by posing as
family concerns.
 &HT;    Kailash has attacked this evil despite the many powerful
interests that resist any change that could damage profit margins.
 &HT;    He also recognized that the rescued children need
rehabilitation, and in 1991, he established the Mukti Ashram
(Shelter for the Liberated) in Delhi, which is run by volunteers.
He has also established 14 informal education centers, which are
funded by such international agencies as Bread for the World,
Christian Aid, Terre des Hommes and Miserior.
 &HT;    The first shelter found Kailash knocking on doors _ literally _
with requests for donations. ``I guess because the initiation of
the shelter saw ordinary people personally involving themselves in
the cause by giving it their hard-earned money,'' he said, ``the
project has always been run at a personal level: Each child is
special to us. Before we train them in a vocation, we make sure
there is a need for such skills in their village. If the locality
has no tailors or is short on a radio repairer, then that's the
skill we prepare the child for. Along with education, of course.''
 Escape Through Education
 &HT;    At Mukti Ashram, the children get basic training in literacy,
health and social issues. Those over 14 get vocational training in
such trades as carpentry, tailoring and making cane and bamboo
products. There are group discussions on the legal system and
children's rights, as well as current political issues. The
youngsters also help manage the ashram, thus acquiring leadership
skills.
 &HT;    Once the children return to their villages, the ashram keeps
track of how they fare. Many become economically independent,
setting up small enterprises. Most importantly, these rehabilitated
youngsters are helping to teach their communities to fight for
their rights in order to prevent further bondage.
 &HT;    Some of the youngsters return to help Kailash in the
raid-and-rescue operations. Thirteen-year-old Mohan, from Bihar
state, was rescued from a carpet factory in Uttar Pradesh, where he
had worked from age seven to 10. After a year in the Mukti Ashram
in New Delhi, it became clear that he was a bright youngster, and
Kailash enrolled him in one of the marches against child labor.
After this Mohan returned to his village and gave talks in local
schools about the cruel realities of child labor.
 &HT;    Fourteen-year-old Govind is doing the same. An underpaid
telephone booth attendant during the day and a cook at night for a
shopkeeper in the Nepal-Sikkim border town Jhaba, the boy was
rescued by Kailash's activists about three years ago. Once at the
shelter, Govind impressed everyone by his quick mind and grasp of
academic subjects, so he was encouraged to be part of all the
coalition's rallies and marches.
 &HT;    He returned from a three-week visit to his village near Jhaba
and informed Kailash about the local networks that he has set up
there. He went to each family in his village and informed them of
the poor conditions their children work in once they are sent away
to the bigger cities.
 &HT;    ``He is so fired up by what he has learnt here,'' Kailash said,
``that he now plans to go to different villages in India and talk
of his experiences as a child who had to work 16 hours a day. My
children are all so bright. They are going to change society.'' He
calls them ``young multipliers of the message.''
 &HT;    Through the Coalition, which was founded in 1989, Kailash has
supplemented these individual rescue operations with a vigorous
campaign to garner public opinion against child labor. Today The
South Asian Coalition Against Child Servitude comprises 400 partner
organizations, including human rights groups and trade unions in
Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, Bhutan and Sri Lanka.
 &HT;    ``The need for comrades in the combat was obvious,'' he said.
``I realized that children in the region were all facing the same
pernicious fate, and that the fight had to be for all of them.
Banning child labor in India would only shift businesses that
thrive on such inexpensive labor to the neighboring countries.
These children are ours, you cannot shun their problems because
they don't share your nationality.''
 &HT;    Every wall in Kailash's small, functional office in South Delhi
seems to reflect this belief. Huge black and white photographs of
children from South Asian countries who are working away their
childhood crowd the office, reminders that millions will have to
join hands to save the millions suffering.
 &HT;    He points at them and says, ``Children are world citizens and
the world must come together to save them.''
 &HT;    It was this global outlook that brought Kailash to push through
a carpet-consumers' awareness campaign that culminated in the
creation of Rugmark, a label that certifies carpets made without
child labor. To be Rugmark-certified, carpet manufacturers agree to
independent monitoring and inspections. A presentation by Kailash
in 1991 before a U.N. human rights subcommission in Geneva resulted
in U.N. endorsement of the label.
 The Power of a Positive Label 
 &HT;    He is unwilling to hazard a guess on the percentage of carpet
manufacturers who comply with the Rugmark requirements, but he
points out that Germany, the Netherlands, Denmark, Britain and the
United States import only Rugmark carpets from the Subcontinent.
The certification is not foolproof, of course.
 &HT;    James Tufenkian, an American who is on the board of Rugmark and
whose company employs about 6,000 weavers in Nepal, was quoted in
The New York Times last October as saying, ``While Rugmark's heart
is 100 percent in the right place, how can we know what's really
going on in the weavers' homes?''
 &HT;    Added to these advocacy efforts, Kailash has organized many
marches in India and Nepal as part of an ongoing protest against
child labor. His latest effort saw him co-ordinating a Global March
Against Child labor this year. Commencing in January 1998, the
march saw activists, supporters and many a child laborer march in
Asia, Africa, America, Australia and Europe and many of them
traveled to Geneva in June for the drafting of a new convention on
child labor by the International labor Organization.
 &HT;    ``Marches have been so much a part of the Indian tradition of
protest,'' Kailash says. ``Mahatma Gandhi used marches effectively
to protest British laws.'' Kailash also wrote 800 letters to
organize different groups for the March to Geneva.
 &HT;    Gauri Pradhan, of NGO Child Workers in Nepal, credits Kailash
with having made the cause a regional rather than a
country-specific issue; Ishtiaque Ahmed, who works against child
labor in Dhaka, Bangladesh, credits Kailash with perseverance and
vision.
 &HT;    Not that Kailash is hungering for appreciation; he is quite
prepared to meet any criticism that might come his way and advances
some himself: ``People might say we have no business touring the
world when the problem of child labor is nowhere near eradication
back home. But that's a very narrow approach. In today's globalized
world you can't sort out anything by remaining home.''
 An Early Start  
 &HT;    Kailash's first brush with child labor was close to home in a
small town in Madhya Pradesh. Perplexed to see the cobbler's son
not attending school like him, 7-year-old Kailash innocently asked
why, only to be told that children born to the ``untouchable''
castes in India have no option but to work.
 &HT;    The sentence stuck with him. So did the desire to change the
terrible truth of the statement.
 &HT;    Years later, while studying electrical engineering at the
Regional Engineering School in Vidisha, Madhya Pradesh state, where
he was born, he organized a book bank to help those students who
could not afford new textbooks.
 &HT;    After teaching engineering for a few years Kailash decided to
work more directly for social change. ``The world had to know the
shocking truth. And I chose not to remain with a mainstream
profession but to change things. I walked out of home.'' Now,
others walk with him, in his marches against the sale of childhood.
 &HT;     c.1999 Changemakers.net Journal  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Soma Wadhwa is a Delhi-based correspondent for the weekly
magazine Outlook in India. She has also written on development and
gender issues for Living Media, The Pioneer, The Times of India and
other publications.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Changemakers.net Journal is the on-line publication of the
Arlington, Va.-headquartered Ashoka: Innovators for the Public, a
nonprofit group that focuses on social problems around the world.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
