<SLUG> BC-SPREWELL-KNICKS-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREE-ALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKE WISE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    As he stepped from a black stretch limousine in front of a
modest Milwaukee house in January, Dave Checketts, the president of
Madison Square Garden, knew a lot was riding on the interview he
was about to conduct.
 &HT;    Just how much, it would later turn out, he couldn't fully
understand.
 &HT;    Joined by Ernie Grunfeld, then the Knicks' president, their
coach, Jeff Van Gundy, and another team executive, Checketts was
there to gauge the character of Latrell Sprewell.
 &HT;    A three-time All-Star guard, Sprewell had been on furlough ever
since attacking his coach with the Golden State Warriors, P.J.
Carlesimo, the year before, choking him, threatening to kill him
and, 20 minutes later, returning to the gym to punch him.
 &HT;    Both Grunfeld and Van Gundy wanted Sprewell badly, but if
Checketts was going to gamble on the National Basketball
Association's most prominent pariah, he needed to know more, and
not just about Sprewell's celebrated assault but also about a
strange 1994 incident in which one of Sprewell's pit bulls bit off
the ear of his 4-year-old daughter.
 &HT;    Sprewell had refused to put the dog to sleep until the 10th and
final day of its quarantine and, when questioned by reporters, had
airily dismissed the episode, saying, ``Stuff happens.''
 &HT;    Checketts questioned Sprewell closely about the incident. ``I
have six kids, and I know how I feel about them,'' Checketts said
that day. ``And I don't expect everyone to feel for their kids the
way I feel for mine. But I have to get something off my chest and
ask, 'Why would you say that?'''
 &HT;    Sprewell answered the question in two parts, first picking up a
framed picture of his daughter and handing it to Checketts.
 &HT;    ``I love my daughter dearly,'' he said. ``I took care of her
plastic surgery, it didn't affect her hearing and I've never had
anything hurt me more in my life.''
 &HT;    He also had an explanation for the ``stuff happens'' remark. ``I
was tired of the press crawling all over me. I didn't want them to
go to the hospital.''
 &HT;    ``He was not indignant,'' Checketts said. ``He was not
defensive. I believed what he was telling me.''
 &HT;    Four months after that Jan. 17 visit, Checketts scans his memory
for something else that stood out, something else that persuaded
him to give Sprewell an opportunity to resume his career after a
13-month layoff, how a meeting barely lasting 90 minutes could
alter his perception.
 &HT;    ``I'd have to say, 'Footprints in the Sand,''' Checketts says,
recalling a familiar poem etched in a mirror inside the doorway of
Sprewell's home. It's about a deceased man looking back on his life
and remembering that there were always two sets of footprints in
the sand.
 &HT;    ``The man confronts the Lord about only remembering one set of
footprints in his deepest, darkest moments,'' Checketts says. ``'My
son,' the Lord replies, 'it was during those times I carried you.'
It was deeply personal for me at different points in my life.''
 &HT;    Staying behind for a few minutes as the rest of the Knick brain
trust shuffled back to the limousine, Checketts asked Sprewell,
``That's an appropriate verse for you, don't you think?''
 &HT;    Sprewell nodded.
 &HT;    ``Do you ever think about it?''
 &HT;    ``Oh, many, many times.''
 &HT;    ``Does it mean anything to you?''
 &HT;    ``Yeah,'' Sprewell replied. ``I know I've been carried.''
 &HT;    Returning to his home in New Canaan, Conn., that night,
Checketts asked his family for advice. ``You know what kind of
stuff I would take at school if we got him, Dad?'' asked one of his
sons. ``Are we really going after him?''
 &HT;    Checketts also questioned his own values, wondering what
credibility he would have if he acquired Sprewell. (Checketts, a
Mormon who came to New York via Bountiful, Utah, had once said he
would never have Dennis Rodman on his team.)
 &HT;    His two youngest sons thought Sprewell deserved a second chance,
which got the other one thinking again. ``You think he could help
us win?'' His father nodded.
 &HT;    ``Look, I did not lead the family in prayer to ask God whether
we should take Latrell Sprewell,'' Checketts says. ``And it wasn't
like a light turned on in my head. But I felt I understood the man
a lot better. The visit we had with him convinced me it would
work.''
 -0- 
 &HT;    In basketball, before a big game, it is not uncommon to
experience ``butterflies.'' Your stomach churns and you hope your
surging adrenaline carries you those first few minutes until you
calm down and find symmetry and purpose in the way you play.
 &HT;    But as Knicks' fans, players and management have come to
understand, there is neither purpose nor symmetry in Sprewell's
game. It's more of an avant-garde jazz riff, played at high speed
and with little discernible logic. And for the Knicks' management
and coaches, the anxiety never goes away.
 &HT;    They tried to tap into Sprewell's psyche that January day but
forgot to ask whether he could cope with coming off the bench,
rather than playing with the starting team. They went in search of
personal character and walked right past team chemistry. Their goal
was a noble one _ to transform a good player on a bad team into a
great player on a championship team. They never imagined that that
player could take a good team and play a major role in turning it
into a very bad one.
 &HT;    But somewhere over the last few months, Sprewell managed that
feat, pulling the Knicks into his world _ an enigmatic one, in
which he gets his points, his team loses and everyone wonders why a
once-proud franchise is on the brink of missing the playoffs for
the first time in 12 years.
 &HT;    He stands in the middle of the chaos and uncertainty,
irredeemable after all _ but not for the reasons that Checketts and
the Knicks feared.
 &HT;    Sprewell, the player who has never seen a shot he didn't like,
who glowers at teammates when they don't pass him the ball, who
forgets defensive assignments at crucial moments, is actually more
harmful to a team than Sprewell the supposed human hand grenade in
high-tops.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, it hasn't worked out like everybody had hoped,'' he
says, sitting inside his locker cubicle after a recent loss to the
Toronto Raptors. ``Maybe I'll be here next season, but you never
know. Things change quickly in this league.''
 &HT;    Indeed. On April 21, the day Sprewell's agent complained
publicly that a rift between Grunfeld and Van Gundy was hurting the
team, Checketts dismissed Grunfeld and took over the team himself.
(One of his first acts was to fine Sprewell $25,000 for allowing
his agent to speak out.) And those are just the casualties off the
floor.
 &HT;    On the court, it is surreal to watch him go one-on-nine, using
his teammates and opponents as pylons. Surreal and sad. For
whatever redemptive qualities Sprewell has, they have yet to emerge
on the floor.
 &HT;    His talent can be mesmerizing. At Golden State, where Sprewell
established himself in some people's eyes as the second best
shooting guard in the league, behind Michael Jordan, his
explosiveness and production masked his liabilities.
 &HT;    He played defense with passion and fire. On offense, at a sinewy
6 feet 5 inches, he could dart through defenses, either getting to
the basket for a layup or stopping abruptly to nail a long jumper.
 &HT;    In a league enamored of great one-on-one players, he looked like
the real deal, the guy who could break down a defense
single-handedly. For the Knicks, who have a long history of looking
for (and never finding) that one great player to put alongside
Patrick Ewing and produce a championship, Sprewell seemed like the
answer.
 &HT;    Yet, had they looked closer, Knick officials might have noticed
disturbing signs. After one playoff season, in 1994, the Warriors
began to implode. Trades and losses mounted, and so did Sprewell's
frustration. He feuded and fought with teammates. A self-described
loner, he lost his senses on Dec. 1, 1997, an incident that
catapulted him into the role of America's Thug.
 &HT;    ``He fits the perpetrator to a 'T,''' says Spike Lee, sitting in
his courtside seat at the Garden, his No. 8 Sprewell jersey peaking
out from beneath his jacket. ``The corn rows. The scowl.
Everything. People would think he's another thug the NYPD has to
protect us from. What's interesting, though, is he's very
articulate.''
 &HT;    When you speak to Sprewell, you see no rage, no contempt for
authority. He is intelligent and engaging. But his comments and
actions, on the court and off, tend to confirm your worst thoughts
about him.
 &HT;    The laughing after losses. The failure to pass the ball to an
open man. And, particularly, those out-of-touch remarks.
 &HT;    In late March, for example, Van Gundy began to wonder seriously
whether Sprewell cared about winning.
 &HT;    On March 27, during a practice, the coach coolly called Sprewell
aside to talk about something he had said in a column I wrote the
night before. Van Gundy specifically mentioned a passage in which I
had asked Sprewell whether it bothered him that the Warriors and
Knicks were a combined 7-22 with him in the lineup over the last
two seasons.
 &HT;    Sprewell's response was: ``That's just one of those stats. That
doesn't bother me.''
 &HT;    Van Gundy questioned Sprewell on a vacant, dark stairwell as the
Knicks shot baskets and reporters anxiously hovered about 20 yards
away. If the concerned coach wanted a better answer, the nonchalant
player wanted to know why Van Gundy had made a power play in front
of the press.
 &HT;    ``I think if he had do it over again, I think he'd give a
different answer,'' Van Gundy said soon after. ``It's not a valid
stat? Every player has to be concerned first and foremost with
winning. That is going to be their legacy in this league. He would
probably like to have a do over on that.''
 &HT;    A few days later, I asked Sprewell if he would like to clarify
or add to that statement.
 &HT;    ``No, I said what I said and I meant it,'' he said. ``I didn't
think what I said was that big a deal. I don't know why Jeff had to
say anything to me about it. Basketball is supposed to be fun,
right?''
 &HT;    You get the sense that sometimes he just does not get it, that
the reason Sprewell is such a polarizing force has nothing to do
with a nasty disposition or a conscious desire for confrontation _
and everything to do with Spree-ality.
 &HT;    Conventional reality: You sacrifice to win.
 &HT;    Spree-ality: You balk at coming off the bench, rather than
starting, and make sure your agent informs the news media about the
grave injustice taking place.
 &HT;    Conventional reality: You put the choking incident behind you.
 &HT;    Spree-ality: Since, down deep, you feel you committed no crime,
you pursue a racially based lawsuit against the team and the league
_ a suit that a federal judge has twice rejected.
 &HT;    Conventional reality: You complete an anger-management course,
if for no other reason than to send the right message.
 &HT;    Spree-ality: You blow off the sessions, calling it all a joke
and insisting you don't have a problem.
 &HT;    One odd quirk about Sprewell is his penchant for gravitating to
the youngest players on the team. At Golden State, Sprewell, now
29, hung out with an impressionable rookie, Joe Smith, and the
young equipment manager, Shane Salazar. In New York, Marcus Camby,
25, and Rick Brunson, 26, became his frequent dinner companions.
 &HT;    From the beginning, Sprewell had trouble adjusting on the floor.
Yet never did he seem more out of place than the night of April 7
in Charlotte, N.C. Speaking before the game, he said: ``People have
written stuff, but I'm not bringing anybody down. I'm not making
other people play poorly. I don't know what I'm doing that's so
bad.
 &HT;    ``I mean, you know, at this point, they're not accustomed to
having seasons like this. Everybody has to come up with a reason
why we're playing badly. So, obviously, it's Latrell's fault.''
 &HT;    Hours later, after a 24-point drubbing by the moribund Charlotte
Hornets _ the Knicks' fifth loss in seven nights _ Ewing said he
could not recall a more depressing night in his 15-year Knick
career. Rumors of Van Gundy's demise crackled through the press
room.
 &HT;    Sprewell? He looked around and wondered why all the sad faces.
``Being in sixth place with 15 games left, that's a lot of time,''
he said, unaware that the Knicks were actually in 10th place. ``We
don't have a lot of time, but we have enough time to make a run
here. So I'm not throwing in the towel yet. I know we're down, but
we got to get over it. You can't stay down. That's the attitude I
have.''
 &HT;    When someone intoned, ``You seem kind of unfazed by all that's
taken place,'' Sprewell shrugged his shoulders.
 &HT;    ``I've played on losing teams before,'' he said. ``I know what
it takes. A lot of these guys haven't experienced times like this,
and I have. We can't think championship right now. I think we have
to take it game by game and think: 'Hey, let's get in. And let's
build on that.' I've said it before. I don't see the elite teams in
the East being that much better than us, especially when we're
playing well.''
 &HT;    Whatever his intention _ and no one seriously doubts his concern
for the team's fortunes _ Sprewell sounded like some wise old sage,
saying something to the effect of: ``I can lead you. We're on my
turf. We're losing. The unpromised land is near. Let me take you
there.''
 -0 
 &HT;    During a recent visit to Oakland, a player on last season's team
will show you where the incident took place, five floors above the
Oakland Convention Center, on the Warriors' practice floor. How
they traded words and, in a moment of fury, Sprewell grabbed
Carlesimo around the throat, changing his career forever.
 &HT;    And yet, after all the discussion about the altercation, you
forget it began with someone telling Sprewell what to do on a
basketball court. Unlike his previous coaches, who let Sprewell
freelance without conscience, Carlesimo wanted more team play.
Specifically, he wanted Sprewell to make better passes during a
drill.
 &HT;    He doesn't like living up to obligations imposed on him by
others. He has thrived whenever people let him do what he wanted to
do. It's as if, approaching 30, he is still in his Terrible Twos.
Sprewell lives and plays in his own universe, undermining structure
and reason.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
