<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LEXUS-BOS &LR;      05-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LEXUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRODDING TO CHECK RAPID GLOBALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE 
Understanding Globalization 
By Thomas L. Friedman 
Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 394 pp., $27.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a stock car enthusiast at Daytona, Thomas L. Friedman has
watched globalization move faster than anyone imagined just a few
years ago. The Iron Curtain has come down, the Internet has gone
up, world financial markets have exploded in both volume and
velocity. Even Africans far up remote rivers have cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lexus and the Olive Tree'' describes these developments
with the enthusiasm of a sportswriter, most of it positive.
Globalization can help improve the standard of living, and
human-rights standards as well, for many millions of people
worldwide. In Friedman's view, it even promotes peace because the
world marketplace is raising the cost of making war.
</P>
<P>
   But there are dangers, too. Friedman carries a handful of yellow
caution flags: unfettered markets could despoil the environment
worldwide; fast-paced economies widen the income gap between rich
and poor; galloping globalization threatens to homogenize ancient
cultures. Yet Friedman only waves these flags occasionally,
suggesting that careful application of ``filters'' can limit the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   But Friedman largely ignores the giant red flag bulging in his
pocket. Worrisome factors are noted, including the facts that bad
investments can pull down good ones globally, and that the speed of
markets now can stampede rational response. Friedman asserts that
the dominoes now are financial rather than political, yet he gives
meager attention to the possibility of collapse. Perhaps he feels
that the Asian and Russian debacles _ devastating to millions in
those countries but felt only modestly here _ represent the worst
that can be expected. But the biggest difference between Friedman's
view and stock car racing is that globalization is continuing to
accelerate with no end in sight. It doesn't even slow down at the
corners.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Friedman just received another demonstration of this
himself. Books about fast-moving current events are intrinsically
risky. Friedman and his publisher did the best they could with an
accelerated production schedule; the book quotes material published
as recently as this January. Still, ``Lexus'' was dated by the time
finished copies were arriving in the bookstores. A pivotal section
describes the qualities that define a country's economic power and
potential. The assessment is based on the opinions of the top
executives from the firm named by Forbes magazine last year as the
best-managed company in America: Compaq Computer. Faster than you
can press the Cancel Execute key, these heavily quoted executives
are gone from Compaq, sacked by directors last month after
disappointing earnings. Still, the coup at Compaq illustrates more
than it undercuts a recurrent theme of Friedman's: Global
competition weeds out laggards with no remorse, and with
breathtaking speed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Friedman's story describes the tension between the
Lexus, representing speed, technology and world markets, and the
olive tree, representing stationary, age-old values. Friedman's
inclination is clear: ``Tip O'Neill was wrong,'' he says. ``All
politics isn't local _ not anymore. All politics is now global.''
Friedman is persuasive in describing the inevitability of
globalization; more attention could be focused on preventing it
from trampling important values.
</P>
<P>
   Other books on globalization have been and will be produced by
persons better schooled in macroeconomics or world diplomacy. But
Friedman may be the best possible writer to provide this overview
at this time. A veteran New York Times reporter who won two
Pulitzer Prizes for work in the Middle East, he is now
foreign-affairs columnist for the Times. Like ``From Beirut to
Jerusalem,'' which won him the National Book Award in 1988, this
book is a lively mix of anecdote and analysis, with dozens of
interviews full of solid reporting from all over. Perhaps it is
true, as Friedman suggests, that he has eaten at a McDonald's in
more countries than any other person alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding Globalization,'' the book's subtitle, is
partilly apt. As a guide to the questions raised by globalization,
Friedman is eager, provocative, often entertaining, occasionally
insightful. Anyone seeking answers, however, must keep looking.
Friedman offers a first-rate description of the starting grid, and
the first few squealing movements, of a race that will be long,
fast and uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
