<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      05-04 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR BRINGS BOOM IN ALBANIAN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Like most Albanian men, Dokliat has two guns _
an assault weapon and a pistol _ and he has the critical family and
communist-era secret police connections to back them up. His four
gold rings match his two gleaming bracelets, setting off his
expensive-looking sleek black suit.
</P>
<P>
   A full 24 hours with Dokliat, a professional bodyguard, will
cost you $300, which in edge-of-the-war Albania is a coldly
calculated investment: Travelers to the mafia-controlled north of
the country are almost certain to be robbed by one of the feuding
gangs of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Dokliat brings along hand grenades and other weaponry for the
ride north _ munitions he boasts he's never had to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find a lot of bodyguards in Albania, because everybody
has a gun, so they can say, `I'm a bodyguard,' '' Dokliat said,
waving off the pretend-protectors. But it's Dokliat's school ties
that set him apart; many of the official and unofficial armed men
who stop cars on Albania's poorly constructed roads are his former
classmates at secret police training. ``Everybody knows me,'' he
boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling with its own poverty and lack of development, Albania
has found a boom industry with the arrival of NATO troops and the
threat of a war spilling over its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Students whose parents live on less than $100 a month are making
that in a day, translating for journalists and international
organizations. Families subsisting on two-digit monthly salaries
are camping out in relatives' homes, renting their own apartments
for $100 to $300 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers now charge $200 to $300 to take people north, while a
private helicopter company will take five passengers for $1,200,
saving the passengers six hours in travel time each way. Bodyguards
charge $100 to $300 daily, not including a car.
</P>
<P>
   Not that getting a car is a problem. Albania is Europe's poorest
nation, with virtually no functioning legitimate economy and a
third-world infrastructure. But buying a late-model Mercedes-Benz,
BMW, or Jeep Grand Cherokee is a breeze at the makeshift vehicle
sales lot on Albania's western coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are thief cars,'' said a man in the lot who described
himself as a professional driver. Asked the fee for a Volkswagen
Golf, the man said, ``You want one? I go to Germany tomorrow. No
problem. I bring it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of vehicles on the lot indeed look suspicious, with
their Italian, German, and Swiss license plates still screwed on.
Cars ``with documents'' cost more, one salesman said, and the
others ``can't go out of Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   The stretch of road where the car lot is located defines
Albania, a throwback nation in the heart of modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   There is the suspect car lot full of luxury vehicles, on a road
so beat up the cars won't last long if driven on them. The white
stucco houses on the hill across the street are barely standing,
and are too small for the shoeless children and weathered-looking
adults who inhabit them.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately next door to the car lot is the headquarters for
Albania Force, a humanitarian branch of the NATO operation against
Yugoslavia. The base, too, sits on the Adriatic sea, a beach that
could be a world-class resort if the Albanian government had the
means to clean up the sewage.
</P>
<P>
   The whole country has a feeling of being occupied. The roads are
taken up by aid trucks and huge vehicles carting heavy weaponry.
NATO soldiers cruise around the streets in green military vehicles,
and have virtually taken over the Rinas airport area.
</P>
<P>
   Long isolated, poor, and malfunctioning, Albania may find its
most promising role yet as that of the potential staging ground for
a NATO assault on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albanians, even though they feel really bad about what's
happening, still feel the beginning of a new era for Albania,''
said Dashi Peza, a businessman whose translation, logistics, and
hotel services are currently overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think the presence of NATO will be very productive. For
some Albanians, this period of war has been very beneficial,'' Peza
said.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits, however, have largely gone through the black
economy, or what Arben Malaj, a member of Parliament and former
finance minister, calls ``the informal economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cash-strapped Albanian government, already saddled with the
most severe economic and developmental troubles in the region,
still is not being reimbursed adequately for its housing of Kosovar
refugees, Malaj said.
</P>
<P>
   Malaj estimated that the refugees will cost the Albanian
government $200 million if the crisis lasts the year; just $100
million in direct aid has been promised. The impact of the refugees
on the education, health, water, and energy systems is also heavy,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of NATO, and the potential improvement of the
infrastructure that may come with a long-term stay by the troops,
``will be, I guess, exploited for good,'' Malaj said.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors, always skittish about putting money into
unstable Albania, were scared off completely after the disastrous
pyramid schemes of 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every Albanian family sank all their money into the
phony get-rich-quick schemes, and most lost everything. The crisis
led to mass riots and the looting of Albania's military arsenals
for weaponry _ munitions that have made for a well-armed populace.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Albania is still ``a mess,'' Peza said.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is an accepted condition here. Locals say a job
working as a customs officer goes for as much as $18,000. That's
not the salary, they say; that's the price an Albanian has to pay
as a bribe to get the job, on the presumption that the employee
will make that much and more by demanding fees from people bringing
things into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of money changing hands in Albania, but few people
seem to be actually working. Illegal money-changers flap their wads
of local lek at passersby on Skanderbeg Square, right under the
eyes of local police.
</P>
<P>
   Fake visas to Greece, where an estimated 300,000 Albanians go to
find under-the-table work _ go for $300 to $800, locals say,
leaving little incentive for the buyer or seller to earn money
legitimately in Albania, where the average monthly income is $106.
</P>
<P>
   Armed banditry in the north is common; an AP television crew,
robbed of $250,000 in cash, equipment, and vehicles, was offered it
back _ for $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny Western Union office downtown has a guard outside
controlling the crush of people who go there every business day to
collect money. Nearly every Albanian family has at least one family
member working abroad and wiring money home, said economist Fatmir
Mema _ one explanation of how Albanians are able to eat, when
unemployment is 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's presence may bring cash, international attention, and
some sense of order to Albania, some here say, improvements that
could help make the tiny nation more like its European neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But the initial benefit may well be worse in the long term for
Albania, which needs to shed its dependency economy and develop on
its own, Mema said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, NATO's presence is positive. In other ways, it
is a disaster,'' Mema said. ``Albania needs work and investments _
not aid. The destiny of Albania is not now in the hands of
Albanians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
