<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNANSWERED QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So Robert Kraft says he's going to keep the Patriots in the
Boston area. Hartford is livid at having been seduced and
abandoned. Stony with anger is John Rowland, the 41-year-old
Connecticut governor who put his career on the line for Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting questions are unanswered. They have to do with
whether the National Football League enforced its interest by
threatening to put another team in the Boston area if the Patriots
moved out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows the official story. As Kraft wrote last week to
the governor, ``Unfortunately, we have not seen sufficient evidence
to give us adequate assurance that the planned Hartford stadium can
be ready for the beginning of the 2002 season on the terms we
contemplated in our agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people know too, that NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue took
an interest in the decision, to the extent of asking lawyer Paul
Kirk (a former aide to Senator Edward M. Kennedy who served for a
time as chairman of the Democratic National Committee) to take a
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Those who read Globe columnist Will McDonough know also that
Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney played a key role. As
president of the Ireland Fund, Rooney is well-acquainted with the
Boston businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A panel led by the Rev. Donald J. Monan, chancellor Boston
College, was duly formed, to forge consensus among legislative
leaders, including House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, Senate
president Thomas F. Birmingham, Governor Paul Cellucci, and Boston
Mayor Thomas M. Menino.
</P>
<P>
   The state's offer of an infrastructure package was marked up to
around $70 million (from its original $57 million) and set against
Connecticut's offer of a $375 million stadium and a dizzying series
of guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Kraft turned down the richest deal ever
negotiated by an owner for a publicly financed stadium _ worth more
than $1 billion over 30 years _ and accepted instead what columnist
McDonough described as ``just about the worst any owner has had to
accept to stay put in the National Football League.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Kraft says he had a change of heart. What isn't
known is the extent to which he figured he could lose it all by
leaving. Did the league threaten to put an expansion team in Boston
if the Patriots left?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reasonable speculation,'' says Andrew Zimbalist, a
Smith College economist who is an expert in the economics of
sports. ``It could have happened two ways. There could be an
explicit threat, as in, `We don't like to expand, we don't want to,
but if someone brings an antitrust action, we might be forced to.'
'' Even without some explicit threat, he says, ``the existence of
the problem was unavoidable.'' In other words, the shadow of
Cleveland hung over the deal.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1996 that Art Modell moved his Cleveland Browns to
Baltimore and changed their name to Ravens in exchange for a
tax-built stadium, after Cleveland repeatedly refused to foot the
bill. An outraged Cleveland fan base quickly elicited an NFL
promise of an expansion team. The new Cleveland Browns will kick
off this summer. Billionaire Alfred Lerner paid $530 million for
the franchise. The sum was split evenly among the other 28 owners,
minus Modell.
</P>
<P>
   Could a Hartford-based Kraft have antagonized sufficiently the
coalition of 23 owners that would be required to authorize an
expansion team for Boston? It's possible.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the enormous profits that he contemplated from
the move would have been mainly his alone, ticket revenues
guaranteed by Connecticut taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams pool most of their advertising revenues. Boston is the
nation's sixth-largest market; Hartford is 27th. Thus Kraft's gain
would have been every other owner's loss. Also, a Patriots team in
Harford inevitabley would cut into the business from the two New
York-area teams, the Giants and Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Modell, of course, moved his team far enough from Cleveland that
it didn't matter what the NFL did back home. But the value of
Kraft's franchise in Hartford would have been killed by a new
Boston team _ although the legislature had guaranteed his profits
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Did the panel assembled by Monan serve to remind Kraft of the
seven enthusiastic bidders who showed up afer the Cleveland
franchise was authorized? Surely the answer is yes. Kraft may have
ceased to be a whining millionaire. But he is certainly is no
public hero.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
