<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS NEEDS A BIG SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Soccer is off to either a distressing or
encouraging start in its fourth season, depending on one's
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is down in strongholds Los Angeles and New England,
and unimpressive in East Rutherford, N.J., Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
and Kansas City, according to statistics. Or, crowds are just
warming up, attendance is about equal to last year, and will exceed
'98 totals, according to MLS commissioner Doug Logan.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the best time to make definitive evaluations, but
professional sporting operations are judged largely on perception,
and the MLS needs to make a stronger impression. Attendance should
improve with warmer weather, the opening of the Columbus Crew
Stadium, the Women's World Cup, and doubleheaders involving
national teams. Television ratings are ``dead even with hockey,''
according to Logan, and have increased by 20 percent. Season-ticket
sales are up more than 42,000, a 9 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But many questions are being raised about the direction of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making so many mistakes that it makes me very
nervous,'' said Steve Gans, a Newton resident and former
administrator with the Baltimore Blast indoor team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the league dies, and there would be nothing to replace it
for 10 or 15 years, it would not be soccer's fault. I don't want to
have to go places and have people ask me, `Why can't soccer make it
in this country?' The fact is, it can. Since the '80s, soccer has
established itself, but too often it has been run into the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Gans, like many others, is concerned that MLS officials have
seldom learned from mistakes or benefited from the successes of
past leagues, such as the North American Soccer League.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so desperate to jettison everything from the past
because it is associated with failure,'' Gans said. ``But those who
forget the past are condemned to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certain teams were successful is unbelievable in the
midst of this holistic failure. What did they do right?''
</P>
<P>
   The most successful US pro teams of the pre-MLS days were either
committed to community activities, signed interesting players, or
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about inculcating soccer in the sports culture,''
Gans said. ``The opportunity is there, by stressing community
relations and doing the things that are essential for setting down
roots, getting a critical mass who will support the team when
things go bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing some things right in the MLS, especially the
Revolution. But for every Revolution and (general manager) Brian
O'Donovan, there is a buffoon. The Revolution have had people
coming to their games without ever having a winning season, and in
some sense that's groundbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long the MLS sticks to a low-budget blueprint, though,
its growth will be limited. Big-name foreign players are not even
being courted, and young domestic players are not capturing
imaginations, either because of lack of ability or promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be a league that is flooded with new
foreign players every year,'' Logan said. ``We're out of that
business. Maybe it's a fair criticism that young players like Jay
Heaps (Miami) or Jason Moore (D.C. United) haven't been given that
degree of buildup. But it takes a while for them to find a roster
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   This is indeed a conundrum. The top young players in MLS are
being taken from the collegiate system, which simply does not
prepare them for the professional level. Most of those who succeed
from the college ranks do so despite that experience, not because
of it. In any case, none of those players have captured the
attention of fans on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   US players should be important to MLS, but they should not be
patronized. I happen to believe there are enough American players
to stock an MLS, but those players are not all in the collegiate
system. In fact, if the league depends too heavily on the
collegians for development of coaches, players, and referees, it
will fail.
</P>
<P>
   The NASL expanded too ambitiously, played on artificial
surfaces, etc. But the league also promoted incessantly and its
administrators constantly searched for players who might capture
the imagination. There was excitement and a feeling of adventure
because of that. Once a league has that spirit, publicity is easily
generated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to grow, basically from within, and have some
patience,'' Logan said. ``The teams are mostly playing better than
last year. We have four pretty good teams, and then everyone else,
and we have to make sure the caliber of all the teams improves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to be an instant success. We are a work in
progress. But there are positive signs that we are catching on and
starting to grow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
