<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GERTNER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERTNER ADAPTS RADICALISM TO THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- During the 25 years she was a defense lawyer, Nancy
Gertner was known for her radical causes, red clothing, and loudly
voiced opinions, in the media and the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   In five years as a federal judge, the TV sound bites have given
way to written opinions, the preferred way for judges to voice
their views. The leftish sympathies and scarlet garb seem toned
down too, if only to liberal and maroon. Even the Wall Street
Journal writes approvingly that she has ``largely issued mainstream
rulings, peppered with only occasional flashes of liberalism.''
</P>
<P>
   But recent cases indicate that reports of Gertner's
transformation may be greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   She has found in favor of a woman suffering gender
discrimination at the hands of male-dominated financial
institutions, a black man she believes was repeatedly stopped by
police simply because he's black, and a Latino pursued by federal
agents for possessing ``suspicious'' cash.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, she will decide whether she has the authority to reopen
the case of a man serving a life sentence for the 1988 slaying of
12-year-old Darlene Tiffany Moore during one of Boston's most
notorious gang gunfights. If she does, the move would run counter
to the federal trend against reopening criminal cases tried in
state court.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there's been no great public outcry from prosecutors
over any of Gertner's ruling, few of which have been overturned on
appeal. But she is attracting growing attention in public and legal
circles, a result, defense lawyers and prosecutors say, of Gertner
finding her voice as a judge, becoming accustomed to being behind
the bench rather than in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is careful about when she steps out,'' said Ellen Zucker,
a close friend and former law clerk. ``She doesn't swing from the
branches and say `I'm going to do whatever I want.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She is definitely more attuned to the rights of the accused
than some of the federal judges who used to be prosecutors,''
Zucker said. ``That's no surprise. But she puts everyone through
the paces.''
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney Donald K. Stern, the chief federal prosecutor in
Massachusetts, praised Gertner's courtesy to all who come before
her but faulted her for decisions like the so-called
driving-while-black case, in which she reduced a defendant's
sentence because she believed the man's criminal record was
inflated by traffic violations that he probably would not have
incurred had he been white.
</P>
<P>
   ``She identified a problem in law enforcement, and it's a good
thing she surfaced the issue,'' Stern said. ``But to address it in
that way, she was way off base.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern considered appealing the decision, decided not to, and
won't discuss his reason. But a prosecutor familiar with the case
said even if an appeals court had overturned Gertner on the issue
of alleged racial discrimination, the other reasons she cited for
reducing the sentence would have been upheld, along with the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   This points up a key aspect of Gertner's judicial approach:
using exhaustive legal research to buttress a novel theory, which
in turn is packaged with more traditional, well-established
precedents.
</P>
<P>
   One of the toughest adjustments for Gertner has been living with
the constraints on her freedom to speak out, a change that has not
come easily. In the summer of 1996, two years after becoming a
judge, Gertner summoned reporters to her chambers to complain about
their coverage of the defense's case in a high-profile Charlestown
murder trial _ a move that stunned some of her colleagues on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she has come to accept the differences between
lawyering and judging.
</P>
<P>
   During her first bail hearing as a judge, ``I realized the
enormous difference between arguing for someone's freedom and
freeing them,'' Gertner said in a recent interview in her
courthouse chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be irresponsible as a lawyer. Your only job is to
represent your client,'' she said. ``You keep your eye on that
ball. As a judge, there are so many more balls.''
</P>
<P>
   By design, she has created other outlets for the passionate,
dissident convictions she once would have aired publicly. She
teaches at Yale Law School, speaks regularly at Northeastern
University Law School, writes articles for law journals, and is
working on a memoir, ``Lawyer With A Red Dress On.''
</P>
<P>
   She also sprinkles her decisions with what she calls ``the Oy
footnote.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Gertner's way of noting her disagreement with rules by
which she is bound. It's a way of saying, ``Oy! I am required to
rule X, but boy do I believe Y,'' Gertner said. ``It is important
that the public understand that just because something is
constitutional does not mean it is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Her law journal writings can cause discomfort, among friends as
well as other judges, because they can be sustained, strongly
worded critiques, including, in one case, criticism of a ruling by
the appellate court that oversees her.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-author on that critical article, Northeastern law
professor Deborah A. Ramirez, tried to persuade Gertner to withdraw
from their collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned because she cares a lot about this and her
voice is strong,'' Ramirez said. ``I thought that in the culture of
the community in which she lives in the courthouse, they might not
accept this. She is a relatively new judge, and I thought she might
want to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   But the case went to the core of a fundamental issue for
Gertner: the exclusion of blacks from a jury considering rape
charges against a black man. The prosecution used its challenges to
eliminate most of the blacks from the jury pool, resulting in an
all-white jury. But the appeals court found no discrimination had
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The law review article was stinging, asserting that the decision
was ``out of step with the First Circuit's own cases, those from
other jurisdictions, as well as the scholarly commentary,'' and
could slow the elimination of racial imbalance on juries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I disagree with something (other judges) do, I will say
it,'' said Gertner. ``I will not be silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important for any judge, though, are the cases she decides
herself. And it is there, when Gertner reveals her frustrations,
that she defines herself as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: a request that from the US Customs Service, which
wanted permission to seize some allegedly pornographic books.
</P>
<P>
   Gertner said she looked at one of the books and ``didn't think
it was obscene. It was pictures of children, art photos. But when I
looked at the statute, it said that pictures of children with erect
penises are obscene. I was heartsick, but the statute was clear. So
I signed the papers and the books were seized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seizing books! Oy!'' Gertner moaned. ``But there was no
alternative. If the law is against it, the law is against it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the perspective Gertner brings to her consideration of
whether to reopen the Tiffany Moore murder case, in which
investigators reportedly have evidence that the man now serving a
life term did not commit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will work hard and look to find what I think is a just
outcome,'' she said. ``But I also understand that when you hit a
wall in case law that is 180 degrees against you,'' the case law
must be obeyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
