<HEADER>
A3690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      05-04 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ The scene in Kosovo's capital: Not
a lot of people or damage, but among those remaining, much fear. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Gen. Klaus Nauman, the No. 2 general in
NATO, who is retiring this week, says that bombing alone can't stop
Milosevic, that refugees will have to go back in with ground force
_ but that NATO has no plans for a ground force. Also, both the
Norwegian foreign minister, who is head of OSCE, and refugee
agencies are talking about having to winterize the refugee camps.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GORE (Washington) _ The vice president met with Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy, for four hours on Monday night. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO forces shoot down another
Yugoslav MiG-29; other military developments.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate sets aside a motion by
Sen. John McCain to authorize the use of all necessary force in the
Kosovo campaign. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GERMANY (Berlin) _ Europeans see President Clinton's
visit to the G-8 meeting in Bonn on Thursday as the opportunity for
an important show of allied unity. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NUKE (United Nations) _ The International Atomic Energy
Agency decides to go back to Serbia to inspect some worrisome
nuclear material there after getting invitation from Yugoslavia. By
Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica) _ Of the 70,000 Kosovar Albanians
who have sought refuge in the Yugoslav province of Montenegro, many
are leaving for Albania because they do no feel safe. Refugee
agencies are hampered in what they can do because these people are
technically still in their own country. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IRAQ (Washington) _ Even with the Pentagon's gaze focused
on Yugoslavia, the U.S. pursues a quiet air war with Iraq, with
daily skirmishes that result in the destruction of Iraqi
air-defense sites and reported deaths of dozens of Iraqi civilians;
the administration fears Saddam Hussein, who has issued predictions
this week of major ``confrontation'' with the U.S., will take
advantage of Kosovo crisis. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
