<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DOLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE TALKS LIKE A MODERATE AT N.H. SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEMBROKE, N.H. _ In her fitted blue suit and clicking black
heels, Elizabeth Dole walks through the halls of the Pembroke
Academy, attracting squeals and shrieks as well as puzzlement from
the public high school students here.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's like Bob Dole's wife or something,'' one student told
another. Another student was slightly more astute: ``She's running
for president.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after Dole took on the gun lobby in the heart of
gun-friendly New Hampshire, she continued to position herself as a
political moderate in the 11-person Republican field. She
reiterated her opposition to assault weapons and armor-piercing
bullets; she continued to insist that talk of a constitutional
amendment to ban abortions ``is a dead end'' for the GOP; and
unlike many Republican politicians and voters, she insisted that
the United States must stick with Kosovo and win the war.
</P>
<P>
   In Roy Annis's history class Monday, the former executive
director of the Red Cross came to talk about education and public
service with his 20 students. In fact, Dole had hoped to listen to
the students, and said so repeatedly. But the session was as
painful as a root canal. Students were reticent about speaking up,
and some were visibly rolling their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Annis tried to help Dole out, asking his students whether any of
them ever felt in danger when they come to school. The answer was
no. So Annis asked what they would do to improve their school.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Tetrault, 17, who had been looking on with disdain,
decided to pipe up. ``I would get a lot more caring teachers who
actually cared about what they're teaching,'' she said. ``We have
some of them in the school, but not all of them care.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Karr-Walter, 17, concurred with that assessment. ``A lot
of them are just here because they need a job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole quickly praised teachers as the true heroes in society, but
she acknowledged that Tetrault and Karr-Walter have a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think there are some teachers who are not well prepared
and not qualified to be in the classroom and we've got to change
that, don't we,'' she said. Dole said there needs to be more
rigorous teacher training programs and a more rigorous
certification process in order to provide students with better
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   When Annis told Dole that his students had held a car wash and
raised $1,000 for the refugees from Kosovo, Jodi Cowger, 17, raised
her hand. She asked Dole why the United States would involve itself
in the Balkans, but not in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you thinking of Rwanda?'' Dole asked, as Cowger nodded her
head.
</P>
<P>
   Dole recounted her visit to the Congo to see the Rwandan
refugees when she ran the Red Cross. ``I was literally stepping
over dead bodies,'' she said, noting that the children were
traumatized from watching their parents hacked to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we probably should have intervened,'' Dole said of the
civil war in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Besides gun control and abortion, Dole has also tried to stake
out a position on Kosovo that would help her stand out from the
field. Like Senator John McCain, a Vietnam veteran and another
candidate for president, Dole said, ``We've got to win the war and
win it absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole said the United States has a national interest in
stabilizing the region, as well as a stake in asserting national
values.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly shifting gears, Dole asked the class ``what about
drugs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me how it starts and what you feel can be done to stop
it,'' she said. ``Obviously, a lot of young lives are being
ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   She called drugs ``a cancer on our society,'' and said she wants
to have a drug-free nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it can absolutely ruin your life,'' Dole said. ``I
feel we need to speak out that drugs aren't cool, they kill, they
ruin your mind. How are we going to stop this? How do you feel
about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's soliloquy, however, was greeted by stony silence and a
few smirks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad, can you get drugs at Pembroke Academy,'' Annis asked,
trying to help out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' the student said, noting that cigarette smoke in the
school bathrooms is prevalent as well.
</P>
<P>
   As Dole left the class, she stopped to shake hands with each of
the students. Tetrault told a reporter she thought the session was
stupid. ``It's not real, it's not realistic at all,'' she said,
just as Dole stopped to shake her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Cowger, however, was breathless at the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's awesome. She seems sincere and smart,'' Cowger
said. ``I think she's genuine. I was impressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
