<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SHAHEEN'S SAVVY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; -- It's time for the rest of the country to take a
peek at New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the presidential primary nine months away; that stuff
has yet to acquire the relevance even of spring training. The
reason New Hampshire beckons is for the lesson in consensus
politics it can teach right now, all the more important because the
issue involved is education. Moreover, the lesson will tell serious
politics watchers a great deal about the atmosphere in which the
presidential season will ultimately unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Not many weeks ago, local analysts were doing tap dances on
Governor Jeanne Shaheen's head, celebrating the presumed demise of
her efforts to reform the state's method of paying for the public
schools under Supreme Court order.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly from within her Democratic Party, both locally and
nationally, many were also gloating at the presumed political
demise of Shaheen because she failed to see their wisdom in arguing
that New Hampshire's school crisis was the perfect opportunity to
impose an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many saw the same old shouting match between left and
right as a conversation that ordinary citizens were having, which
was presumed to have framed the debate and the choices for the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this noise and inaccurate analysis and prediction, one
of the country's best governors quietly, and at critical times,
stubbornly, plugged for a consensus solution to one of the toughest
dilemmas a state can face. And now, give or take a few final
details, she has prevailed in a fashion _ conceptually and
legislatively _ that only enhances her special reputation.
</P>
<P>
   For those who insist on strictly political metaphors, here's
one: The leadership Governor Shaheen has shown and the huge results
her gentle relentlessness has produced constitute exactly what
Texas Governor George Bush was unable to pull off when faced with a
similar challenge. For those local and national geniuses who crowed
that Jeanne Shaheen, after this mess, would never be considered for
national office by Al Gore or Bill Bradley, let's drag out those
two words one last time _ wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   In the almost two years that have passed since the New Hampshire
Supreme Court decided an open-and-shut case and ruled that local
property taxes alone are an unconstitutional method of paying for
public schools because they are unevenly levied among wealthy and
not-so-wealthy communities, both the left and right have screamed
more than they have thought. New Hampshire is a place justly
infamous for its polarizing politics.
</P>
<P>
   The right pushed for amending the New Hampshire Constitution to
undo the ruling, in effect ending the state's responsibility for
educating kids. The left tried to seize the opportunity to impose,
at long last, an income tax, even though Shaheen had pledged not to
allow one.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially alone, Shaheen argued that the inequity found by the
court could be fixed through consensus rather than revolution, and
the state gradually realized that here was a veteran pol who
actually meant what she said and said what she believed.
</P>
<P>
   And what Shaheen believed was that the court requirement that a
fair method of financing the cost of an adequate education could be
devised without a tax revolution.
</P>
<P>
   She was right. The core of an effort to come up with $825
million ($4,220 per pupil) to make the system whole is a statewide
property tax that will actually reduce levies for people and
business in 80 percent of the state's localities, contains some
compensating business taxes, raises cigarette taxes by 25 cents,
and uses a chunk of New Hampshire's share from the settlement of
national tobacco lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   That and a few other items still leaves the Legislature's
package $40-plus million short, and further litigation could mess
the case up again. But the journey Shaheen started is almost ended
_ and on the same, fair terms with which she began it.
</P>
<P>
   The shame for the state is that she had to do it alone, in the
face of hate, ridicule, and condescension. As usual, the people out
of touch were the ideological elites, not ordinary folks and their
tough governor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
