<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE, SWEET HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under-30 Americans may never have heard of the issue, but a good
many older readers were taught that a house is not a home, and
several have written recently to complain about the house-wreckers
among us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even that most wretched of poets, Edgar Guest, knew the
difference between a house and a home,'' writes Robert Stange of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shouldn't we say `house for sale' instead of `home for
sale'?'' asks Lily Chen of Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And a plea for help comes from Pat Bailey of Tucson, who teaches
English as a second language. ``I was asked for a general rule
regarding when to use house and when to use home,'' writes Bailey.
``The more I thought about it, the more difficult it became. . . .
How can I explain this simply to my students?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, even in English it's not simple. Homes as a synonym for
houses _ as in ``stately homes of England'' _ is relatively recent.
And in the 20th century, as social barriers became more permeable,
house and home became a usage marker separating the better classes
from the strivers.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Post's Etiquette, published in 1927, devotes an entire
chapter to language. There's a Do Not Say list (say wash, not
perform ablutions), and a Very Bad Taste list (``Drapes . . . an
inexcusable vulgarism''). Worse yet, though, is saying home for
house; even in the 1945 revision, the issue rates its own section.
You may say ``Our home was an old Georgian house,'' but never ``We
had a Georgian home.'' The war continues in Nancy Mitford's 1956
collection of commentaries on class and usage, ``Noblesse Oblige.''
``They've a lovely home'' is labeled non-U, or non-upper-class,
usage; home for house is apparently an unseemly intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   But even for the purists, the line isn't always clear: House and
home are not two entirely different words, like flaunt and flout.
It's precisely the overlap in meaning that puts the humor in ``A
House is Not a Home,'' Polly Adler's title for her book about
brothel life. It's the overlap that makes the sentimental point in
Guest's, ``It takes a heap o' livin' in a house to make a home.''
(Another source quotes it as, ``It takes a heap o' livin' and some
love to make a home,'' which is not an improvement.)
</P>
<P>
   For Pat Bailey's ESL students, perhaps the safest course would
be to choose house when a noun is needed; it will rarely be wrong.
My house is your house is less welcoming than my home is your home,
but no less correct. The home has a leaky roof, on the other hand,
is clearly not idiomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate ads aside, the rest of us can relax. Few people
nowadays go around saying our home in an effort to sound superior.
As language fights go, house vs. home was a minor domestic dispute;
it's time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write or e-mail Jan Freeman at The Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and
phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-AMIRAULT-BOS &LR;      05-04 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-AMIRAULT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TAKES UP RULING THAT SUPPORTED AMIRAULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When bizarre, horrific stories emerged in 1984 about
toddlers being sexually abused at the Fells Acres Day Care Center
in Malden _ molested with butcher knives, tied naked to trees _ the
arrest and prosecution of the center's elderly owner and her two
adult children came to symbolize a criminal justice system righting
a terrible, tragic wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 15 years later, as the latest in a string of legal appeals
makes its way to the state's highest court this week, the
prosecution of the now-dead Violet Amirault and her children,
Cheryl Amirault LeFave and Gerald, has, for many, come to symbolize
something quite different: a criminal justice system gone horribly
wrong in its zeal to protect and punish.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, as popular opinion and courtroom
verdicts have tilted away from the once-unchallenged belief that
children always tell the truth _ even when coaxed by investigators,
even when what they're saying is truly fantastic -- the Fells Acres
case has become a rallying point for those who think investigators
pushed too hard and accepted too much that was told them by small
children.
</P>
<P>
   What brings the case before the state Supreme Judicial Court, in
fact, is a judge's finding last June that the alleged child victims
were manipulated by ``overzealous'' investigators who succumbed to
``a climate of panic, if not hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   In throwing out the child abuse conviction of LeFave, Superior
Court Judge Isaac Borenstein also barred the alleged victims from
testifying in the future, in effect blocking a retrial of the case.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave and her mother had actually been granted a new trial in
1995 by a different judge, who ruled that the special courtroom
seating arrangement for the child witnesses violated their
constitutional right to confront their accusers. But a new trial
was never held. Her mother, who was released from prison pending a
new trial, died of cancer in September 1997. Gerald Amirault, who
was tried separately, remains in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein's ruling came in a stinging, 140-page decision which
faulted interviewers _ including a nurse and police officers _ for
using overly-suggestive techniques and refusing to take ``no'' for
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Borenstein wrote, investigators were out to get
the Amiraults, ignoring the children's ``incredible'' claims of
talking robots, the torture of animals in public and children being
tied naked to a tree in front of the school.
</P>
<P>
   As time has passed, cases like Fells Acres have spawned a
massive national dialogue on the handling of similar allegations of
widescale child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the good things that has come out of cases like Fells
Acres is a better practice of looking at how interviews are
conducted of children, especially younger kids,'' said Brian
Holmgren, senior attorney for the National Center for the
Prosecution of Child Abuse in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, those cases also generate the kind of publicity
and public response that tend to influence a lot of prosecutions
and create judicial precedent,'' he said, ``and that is not
necessarily for the good.''
</P>
<P>
   With time, scrutiny of Fells Acres and other cases like it gave
way to techniques that are less leading and less aggressive. Just a
month ago, the Middlesex District Attorney's office, which
prosecuted the Amiraults, unveiled its new, less-suggestive
techniques for interviewing alleged child abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some children's advocates and law enforcement officials
worry the pendulum is now swinging in the opposite direction. The
flood of criticism aimed at the Fells Acres investigation, they
fear, has had a damaging effect on the public's will to investigate
and prosecute sex crimes against children.
</P>
<P>
   Some worry that continuing research on children's
``suggestibility,'' or vulnerability to outside influence, may
cause children's claims of abuse to be viewed with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, we see an undermining of the child
witness...and a general perception of victims of child abuse that
is completely changing,'' said Eileen King, executive director of
One Voice, an alliance of survivors of sexual abuse, attorneys and
mental health professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children and parents are being told to come forward and tell,
but when they do they are either not believed, or the case gets
stymied or never prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, King said, ``It becomes more and more difficult for
children to come forward, be believed, receive proper
representation, and have prosecutors confident of being able to
take these cases forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you create a body of research that says children cannot
be reliable witnesses, you not only have an effect on the Amirault
case, for bettter or worse,'' King said, ``but that research is
then used by defense attorneys all over the country to create legal
arguments against child abuse witnesses everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a result of retooling investigative techniques used in
child sex abuse cases, prosecutors have ``come up with guidelines
to how we should question children in these kinds of events,'' said
attorney James L. Sultan, who represents LeFave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand now that it has to be done very carefully,
without leading questions, without threats, without promises, and
without pressure,'' Sultan said. ``And it has to be done in a very
careful, deliberate way if there's any chance of actually getting
to the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
