<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH IN HIS OWN BACKYARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it takes a move or a remodeling job to discover your
own backyard. Although I'm a native Bostonian, it took my native
New York wife to lead me to discover there is indeed life beyond
Interstate 495.
</P>
<P>
   For five years we explored and lived in Franklin County, some 80
miles west of Boston, discovering the scenic beauty, especially
during foliage season; taking boat rides along the Connecticut
River from the Northfield Mountain Recreation Center; wandering
along Historic Deerfield's mile-long street (said to be one of the
most beautiful in America) lined with 18th- and 19th- century
homes; then heading down routes 5 and 10 to Yankee Candle (a sight
to behold, it's said to be the world's largest candle shop and one
of the state's top attractions); shopping in Greenfield with its
classic and lively downtown; driving west on Route 2 past rocks
with dinosaur tracks imbedded in them to Shelburne Falls for the
beautiful Bridge of Flowers and million-year-old glacial potholes;
then continuing along the Mohawk Trail (America's first scenic auto
route) to Williamstown to visit the magnificent Sterling and
Francine Clark Art Institute (413-458-9545) filled with more than
30 works of Renoir, Impressionists, Old Masters, and paintings by
Homer, Sargent, Cassatt, and Remington.
</P>
<P>
   We'd cap off the trip with a stay at The Orchards in
Williamstown (413-458-9611), an inn that is both stately and
welcoming. The rooms are large and accommodatingly comfortable.
Many rooms overlook a delightful garden courtyard. English antiques
are everywhere. The service and dining is superb. Many on the staff
are from Scotland and Germany, and innkeeper Sayed Saleh, an
impeccable Egyptian, has just added an unbelievable wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   The inn scene in Massachusetts is one of the commonwealth's
delights we've come to appreciate only recently. With our getaway
Cape home being remodeled, we've been forced to find other places
to stay to avoid the mess at our place. This has led us to discover
some of Cape Cod's best inns, all of which we highly recommend..
</P>
<P>
   The Whalewalk Inn in Eastham (508-255-0617) has 12 wonderful
rooms, some with fireplaces. Innkeepers Carolyn and Dick Smith are
friendly and welcoming. The outdoor brick garden patio is a nice
setting for breakfast in summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Captain's House Inn in Chatham (800-315-0782) is a stately
Greek Revial house set behind an equally stately hedgerow. The main
house is filed with antiques and four-poster beds. We stayed in the
carriage house in a room with both a Jacuzzi and fireplace.
Innkeepers are Jan and Dave McMaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Wedgewood Inn in Yarmouthport (508-362-5157), along scenic
Route 6A, is the quintessential New England inn. Built in 1812, it
is a Greek Revival home with Federal accents. We dined in the main
house, but stayed in the carriage house where the old and the new
blend beautifully. Innkeepers are Gerrie and Milt Graham.
</P>
<P>
   The Dan'l Webster Inn in the heart of Sandwich, the Cape's
oldest town, is a full-service inn with many awards for its dining,
accommodations (Mobil four-star), and wines. The 47-room inn is
adding eight super deluxe rooms with fireplaces, oversized
whirlpool baths, two-person showers, and ``Romeo and Juliet''
balconies. These rooms will be available in late June. In season
there is an outdoor pool and gardens. The inn is just minutes from
Heritage Plantation, a wonderful museum filled with Americana (even
a classic carousel), antique cars, and gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Plantation opens next Sunday, Mother's Day, and all
mothers will be admitted free.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to discover your backyard is by reading the
1999 Massachusetts Getaway Guide. For a free copy, call
800-447-MASS, ext. 300.
</P>
<P>
   Now we've moved to Rhode Island and the backyard-discoveries fun
begins again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
River search
</P>
<P>
   Whether your fantasy is plunging through class IV rapids on
Fiji's Navua, traversing the immense gorges of China's Yangtze, or
shooting down a turbid stretch of the Penobscot in Maine, the top
whitewater river outfitters are only a mouse-click away.
Riversearch.com offers a central site to 35 of the best whitewater
outfitters from 10 countries. Members of Riversearch must maintain
a high safety and service standard. Riversearch.com is organized by
geographic region. Interested Web surfers merely point to the
region of interest and click on to find outfitters, prices, and
services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whitewater thrills
</P>
<P>
   Maine's whitewater rafting season began Thursday, and this year
there's more space on the Kennebec River. Up to 1,000 rafters a day
are allowed, up from the previous 800. On the Penobscot the rafting
capacity remains the same at 560 passengers. This year there are
also seven high-water releases on the Dead River on May 8, 15, and
30 and June 5 and 12, Sept. 5, and Oct. 2. The Dead River offers
the longest continuous stretch of white water in the East. For
information, call Raft Maine, an association of 13 outfitters, at
800-723-8633 or visit www.raftmaine.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne Museum in Vermont will hold its annual Lilac Festival
May 22 and 23 from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Shelburne has more than 400
lilac bushes.
</P>
<P>
   The American Textile History Museum in Lowell opens ``And So To
Sleep'' this week. The show brings to life the material culture of
the 19th century with its exhibit of jacquard-woven coverlets.
Coverlets commemorate dates of celebration, events, and people and
depict an exuberant period of hand weaving in mid-19th-century
America.
</P>
<P>
   The 37th annual Windjammer Days Festival will be held June 22
and 23 in Boothbay Harbor, Maine. The highlight is the arrival
under full sail of the Windjammer fleet on June 23 between 2 and 4
p.m. The festival includes food, music, fireworks, a parade, and an
antique boat parade. For information, call 207-633-2353.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dining Inn
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem, N.H. has an unusual way to showcase its inns. A
Dining Inn will be held May 14-15 and will include two nights'
lodging, breakfasts, a lantern tour, and a five-course progressive
dinner at the four participating inns. The weekend package begins
at $129 a person, including tax and gratuity. For reservations,
call The Little Guest House (603-869-5725), the Mulburn Inn
(603-869-3389), the Balmoral (603-869-3169), or Angel of the
Mountains (603-869-6473).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cape Cod train
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, June 20, the Mystic Valley Railroad Society will
operate the Day Cape Codder from Boston's South Station along the
new Old Colony Railroad, and across the vertical-lift railroad
bridge at Buzzards Bay across the Cape Cod Canal and onto the Cape.
Boarding is also at Braintree, Brockton, and Middleborough. A
luncheon and harbor cruise are also available. Tickets are $65
adult, $40 children under 12. For information, call 617-361-4445.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dialysis center
</P>
<P>
   The Half Moon Golf, Tennis &AMP; Beach Club has added a dialysis
center to its medical diagnostic facility. The resort is in Montego
Bay, Jamaica. The facility offers patients needing dialysis the
opportunity of a Caribbean vacation while maintaining treatments.
Treatments are $300 each. For information, call 800-408-6031.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coffee milk?
</P>
<P>
   Coffee syrup, the key ingredient in coffee milk, Rhode Island's
official state drink, is now available in nostalgic souvenir-size
bottles. The Blackstone Valley Tourism Council is offering
four-ounce bottles of the syrup as a way to raise funds for the
British canal boat being built in England for the Blackstone
Valley. The canal boat will be used for tours of the Blackstone
River. ``Coffee milk is important to every Rhode Islander,'' said
Robert Billington, president of the tourism council. ``This is a
wonderful way for those not familiar with coffee syrup to sample
its many uses. It's best enjoyed mixed with milk, or as an ice
cream topping.'' The syrup is made by Autocrat Coffee, based in the
Blackstone Valley of Rhode Island. Bottles are $2 and can be
obtained by calling 401-724-2200 or stopping by the Visitor Center
at 171 Main St., Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tiffany exhibit
</P>
<P>
   ``Brilliant Ideas: The Designs of Louis Comfort Tiffany'' will
be on display at the Mark Twain House National Historic Landmark in
Hartford through June 1, 2000. The exhibit features Tiffany pieces
from exquisite lamps and vases to stained glass. The Twain house,
where Samuel Clemens (better known as Mark Twain) lived, was
redecorated in 1881 by Tiffany's firm and is the only
Tiffany-designed interior open to the public. The Tiffany exhibit
in the museum's Visitor Center is free. Admission to the house is
$9 for adults, $8 for seniors, and $5 for children ages 6 through
12. For information, call 860-247-0998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean music
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rico JazzFest, featuring talents such as the
Manhattan Transfer, the Rippingtons, and the Jazz Messengers, along
with performers Poncho Sanchez and Elaine Elias, will be held June
10-13. For information on Puerto Rico, call 800-866-7827.
</P>
<P>
   Grenada's second annual Spice Jazz Festival will be held May
20-23. Grenada's sister island, Carriacou, will salute the event
with a special program May 24. For island information, call
800-927-9554.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Ocho Rios Jazz Festival in Jamaica is set for June
12-20. Top performers have been booked, including the legendary
jazz pianist Monty Alexander. For more information, call the Jazz
Center at 876-927-3544 or the Jamaica Tourist Board at 800-JAMAICA.
</P>
