<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALUTING THE GREATEST GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a different time it was. Overseas, it was a time of war. At
home, it was a time of sacrifice _ making do with broken-down cars,
using ration stamps, growing victory gardens, and displaying blue
or gold stars in the window. But it was also a time when Americans
sang the ``Beer Barrel Polka'' along with ``God Bless America,''
bought War Bonds, admired Bogart and Bergman in ``Casablanca,'' and
danced the jitterbug.
</P>
<P>
   The American Home Front, with all its joy and sadness, is the
theme of our Museum of the Month, the Wright Museum in Wolfeboro,
N.H. Exhibits re-create the nation during the World War II years of
1939 through 1945, with memorabilia, vehicles, films, artifacts,
and stories about the men and women whom newsman Tom Brokaw has
justifiably called the Greatest Generation.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are first introduced to the Home Front through an
eight-minute movie that highlights the unique events of each year
(in 1943, for instance, girls were swooning over a skinny singer
named Sinatra). Then it's on to the displays _ gas pumps, autos,
red cents for rationed goods, a soda fountain, a living room
dominated by a console radio that brought the war news, models of
soldiers and war brides, and the faces and voices of local people
who lived through those years, telling their stories on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   A second building is replete with the paraphernalia of war _
jeeps, tanks, command cars, half-tracks, and motorcycles. Exhibits
and videos highlight such topics as the role of women fliers, the
sinking of American ships and submarines, and a salute to a local
hero, Rene Gagnon, who helped raise the flag at Iwo Jima.
</P>
<P>
   Those who participated in the struggles and triumphs of Home
Front America should find the Wright Museum fascinating. But so
should those who never knew.
</P>
<P>
   (The Wright Museum is at 77 Center St., Wolfeboro, NH 03894;
phone 603-569-1212 or visit www.wrightmuseum.org. There is a
nominal charge. The museum is on a six-acre site, and a 200-yard
footpath connects it with the town's delightful shopping-and-dining
area and marina.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; And speaking of those days: Meanwhile, in Middlesex, Vt., there's
the Camp Meade Victory Museum. For a nominal fee visitors are
transported to the 1930s and '40s at this former Civilian
Conservation Corps camp. (The CCC was one of President Franklin
Roosevelt's New Deal programs in the '30s, giving unemployed young
people an opportunity to do useful conservation and reforestation
work in exchange for room, board, and a small stipend.) As guests
learn about the camp's history, the sounds of Harry James's trumpet
and the Glenn Miller band fill the air. More than 25 indoor and
outdoor exhibits present artifacts, photos, videos, recordings, and
lifelike displays. You can dine at the USO Canteen, and for $42
even stay overnight in a comfy cabin. The camp is open from mid-May
through mid-October. For more information, call 802-223-5537.
</P>
<P>
   Travel trivia: What creature is found on the Maine state seal?
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``It was not price or money that could have purchased
Rhode Island. Rhode Island was purchased by love.'' _ Roger
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: The name of the Maine community of Ogunquit comes
from an Algonquin Indian name meaning ``Beautiful Place by the
Sea.'' And so it is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: The first European potato in the United States
was planted in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should call it New Ireland: There are more people of
Irish descent (4 million) in New England than in Ireland (about 3.5
million).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drip, drip: A posting in hotel rooms at the
environmentally-conscious Boston Park Plaza explains why guests
should be sure faucets are completely shut: ``It takes more than 2
million gallons of clean water to bathe and feed one adult for a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of cats and castles: It's a good thing stage actor William
Gillette built a castle in Connecticut: You need a lot of room when
you keep up to 17 cats at once. Gillette's castle in East Haddam is
one of about a dozen described in Yankee magazine's annual Travel
Guide to New England. Also featured: 30 perfect vacation days, 75
unique New England souvenirs, and 500 new picks for food, lodging,
shops, and places you shouldn't miss. The magazine, available at
newsstands and supermarkets, costs $4.99.
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? The moose, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
