<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IT'S LIKE TO STAY IN A YURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKWOOD, Maine _ After a day of cross-country skiing, I arrived
back just in time to watch a soft sunset turn the sky pink from
atop the hill our yurt was perched on. Only woods and snow were in
sight, and our off-white canvas-covered home for the night blended
in to the scenery. If you're used to sleeping indoors and eating
out, then staying in a yurt at the Birches on Moosehead Lake might
seem like roughing it, but if you're a camper, like I am, bedding
down in one of their three yurts is a five-star experience.
</P>
<P>
   Yurts, circular tents more than tall enough to stand in, were
first used by Mongolian nomads. They are becoming popular in
back-country ski areas, both as warming huts and places to stay,
and are used in the summer by hikers and mountain bikers. The wall
framework is composed of lattice-work, similar looking to that used
for baby gates. Atop this framework are a number of roof rafters
that come together at the peak of the roof, eliminating the need
for a center pole.
</P>
<P>
   The yurts at the Birches come equipped with two bunk beds topped
with foam mattresses, a cooking stove, water, a Coleman lantern,
and kitchen equipment, and they all have outhouses a few yards
away. For winter use, the highlight is the wood-burning stove _
complete with a supply of wood and an ax. Talk about luxury. Summer
features are a skylight for star gazing and windows all around. Our
yurt was furnished with a picnic table, two chairs, and even a
couch, giving it a kind of frat-house effect. The best part of all:
Birches staff will deliver you and your gear, either by snowmobile
in the winter or by all-terrain vehicle, to the yurt.
</P>
<P>
   In February my camping buddy, Bill, and I stayed in the Overlook
yurt, about a mile and a half from the lodge of the Birches, a
wilderness resort area on Moosehead Lake and across from Mount
Kineo, about a five-hour drive from Boston. A sporting camp built
in the 1930s, the Birches has a full-service restaurant and rustic,
charming housekeeping cabins just a few feet from the water. But if
you stay in those you have next-door neighbors, whereas the yurts
are surrounded only by woods. The Three Sisters yurt is about 2
miles from the lodge, and the most recent addition, the Poplar Hill
yurt, is 7 miles away and overlooks Brassua Lake. I liked being
able to walk to the lodge in less than 30 minutes, but my next stay
will be at Poplar Hill, because I like the idea of solitude even
more.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think (and hope) that the 11,000-acre wilderness preserve
the Birches sits on would mean peace and quiet, but that's not
always the case. As Bill observed, it's a place where two worlds
collide, where the tree-huggers (that's us) and the machine-lovers
share turf. Opening up its land to both factions is the only way
the Willard family can stay in business (the Birches rents both
nordic ski equipment and snowmobiles), and for the most part, it
works. But be warned that in the winter there is an oft-heard buzz
of snowmobiles out on the many trails throughout the woods. And in
the summer, Jet-Skis cruise the 3,000 feet of shoreline on Maine's
largest lake.
</P>
<P>
   The nordic ski area has 24 miles of mostly groomed trails _
which snowmobiles are not allowed on, a rule that Birches president
John Willard enforces. (If you're interested in downhill,
Greenville's Big Squaw Mountain is nearby.) Most trails are rated
intermediate and novice. Many go over abandoned woods while others
wind through beautiful woods of tall spruce and hemlock, such as
the Baker Trail loop, one of the prettiest places to ski I've seen.
Conditions were icy when we visited, and for this novice skier it
was tough going, but unlike touring centers near Boston, the trails
were nearly empty, allowing me time to go as slowly as I needed to
go. Bill, on the other hand, a pro at back-country skiing, went on
almost all the trails, stopping for lunch and a rest at the scenic
Poplar Hill yurt. He decided that that remote yurt would make the
perfect weekend vacation spot for his wife and three children. Not
only do the yurts come stocked with a roll-away bed along with the
bunks and couch, you can pitch a tent nearby if you need more
space.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, we got the stove going until we were as toasty as
we could stand being, then heated up chili I'd brought from home.
We later went down to Moosehead Lake in the light of the moon, me
on foot and Bill on skis. We walked out on the frozen lake, dotted
with a few ice-fishing shacks. The snowmobilers had turned in for
the evening, and we could hear heaving ice and the water moving
underneath the lake, making whale-like sounds. It was eerie and
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight the temperature dipped to the single digits. The
inside of the yurt was only barely warmer when we awoke, as we had
let the fire die. We had winter sleeping bags, and knew we'd be
fine, but it was not easy getting out of them. Once the stove got
going again (thank you, Bill), we were happy.
</P>
<P>
   After warming up with a big bowl of oatmeal, I went to the lodge
to meet ski instructor Karen Francoeur, who promised to help me
feel more comfortable on cross-country skis. She's a patient,
knowledgeable teacher for all levels, even remedial types like me,
and my skiing indeed improved.
</P>
<P>
   Just before sunset, Billy and I showed up at for a prearranged
dog-sled trip with musher Ed Mathieu, who also guides moose safaris
and ice fishing trips. The dogs were fired up, and it was fun
(although chilly) sitting in the toboggan as we jostled and bumped
along ski trails.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, the Birches maintains a nice lakefront beach just
behind the lodge, along with kayak and motorboat rentals. There
also are daily pontoon boat moose cruises and guided kayak trips,
where usually at least one moose is sighted on the shoreline or
wading across shallow parts of the lake, munching on vegetation. In
warm-weather months, the ski trails are used for hiking and
mountain biking (rentals are available). I'm looking forward to
cycling out to my summer yurt, but I think I'll still let the
Birches carry my gear; after all, it is a vacation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
