<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKET GOES TO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My dear friend _ and modern stock market fanatic _ Joe King,
always has a provocative word or two. So, when he offered, I jumped
at the chance to publish his personal diary covering the first
month of the war in the Balkans. I've taken it upon myself to edit
Joe a little, in order to tone down his intemperate glee and coarse
gloating. &QL; 
 &QL; 
March 25. Forget bull or bear _ I'm a hawk. After so much
dilly-dallying, we're finally on our way to war. On TV, I see
missiles demolishing their targets _ kapow! I hear that Milosevic
is herding up people for no other reason than the quirk of their
birth, kicking them out of their country, or worse, slaughtering
them. And I can only drum my fingers on my desk, thinking _
tallying up my winnings. Dow up 169 points. Not bad for the first
day of battle. But still quite a few bullets shy of 10,000. God, I
love this war. I love this market. May they march in lock step to
the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   March 26. NATO declares: they're in it for the long haul.
Yeehaw! Optimism everywhere in the market. The news now filled with
reports of executions by the Serbs, burning of villages, refugees
streaming to the borders. I see the dazed children torn from their
parents, all alone now, and maybe forever _ who knows if mom and
dad are face down in a muddy mass grave in their own yard? In the
fumes of death and destruction I smell 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   March 29. A new week. New atrocities. And a glorious new world
on Wall Street. Bodies of ethnic Albanians litter the streets of
Kosovo. WalMart jumps 3 1/4. United States accuses Milosevic of
crimes against humanity. Dow spurts ahead 184 points, and finally _
the big one for the record books _ finishes above 10,000!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   March 30. Horrors! Oh horrors! Milosevic offers to withdraw some
of his forces from Kosovo if the bombing stops _ what is the man
thinking?! Compromise, reconciliation, peace _ none of it is good
for this market. Dow sinks 66 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 1. A big sigh of relief. We're back on track. Three
captured US soldiers shown on Serb TV, looking battered and angry.
Refugees pouring into Albania. The infirm carted for days in
wheelbarrows. A swaddled baby reaches the camps, born the night
before at the side of the road somewhere. Dow dusts itself off,
flexes those toned muscles. Up 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 5. The worse things get, the fatter my portfolio grows. US
orders up Apache attack helicopters. Horror stories of the refugees
are mindboggling. Reinforcements called in to help with the flood
of fleeing Kosovars. Troops on TV look like so many teenage boys in
military helmets and green fatigues. All I see is the green, green,
green. Dow rockets up 174 points. There seems no end to the misery
in Kosovo and the merriment on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 12 to April 16. Another dismal week for the war.
Completely delightful. NATO bombs a refugee convoy. The United
States sending summons out to 30,000 military reservists. Clinton
warns the war could spread across the Balkans, across all of
southeast Europe. Pentagon says air war may drag into the summer.
Hot dog! The Dow climbs every day of the week, deeper and deeper
into record territory. Now 10,000 is just a quaint memory _ 11,0000
just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 22. NATO celebrates its 50th anniversary _ huge summit in
Washington. NATO missiles find Milosevic's villa, and leave it a
smoking, burned-out shell. What a lovely little war we've had this
month. Since the bombs first fell, the Dow is up 1,055 points, or
11 percent. All this in one tiny hot spot. Man alive! Imagine the
market sizzle we'd get from a nuclear holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollars--nonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
