<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE REASON TO BE JEALOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We admit it right upfront: We're jealous.
</P>
<P>
   How else should we react to the news that a 29-year-old
entrepreneur has just sold his seven-month-old company for $200
million?
</P>
<P>
   Last week Stig Leschly joined the ranks of multimillionaires
when he sold his Cambridge, Mass. start-up to Amazon.com. Leschly's
company, Exchange.com, electronically links up buyers and sellers
of out-of-print books and records. The company has 31 employees.
</P>
<P>
   If Leschly's story were one of a kind, we might be inclined to
shrug it off. Maria Grasso, the Chilean au pair, won a $197 million
lottery prize last month. Freak things do happen. But in the
super-charged world of technology, the amazing is becoming
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   In just the last few months, a series of young and small
Massachusetts companies have been sold for hundreds of millions of
dollars each. It goes without saying that most of the companies
weren't making a profit. But in many cases they didn't have any
sales either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to buy companies on earnings,'' says Howard Anderson,
head of the Yankee Group, a local consulting firm. ``Now we buy on
growth potential.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly was the case with Omnia Communications. The
Marlborough, Mass. company was sold in March for $429 million to
Ciena Corp. of Maryland. Omnia's product, a technology that allows
voice and Internet transmissions to travel over fiber-optic lines,
is in the final stages of development. The company is two years old
and has 75 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone Communications of Westford, Mass. was a similar story.
Redstone is getting ready to ship a high-speed switch for
aggregrating Internet traffic. The firm is just 18 months old. In
March Redstone was purchased for $500 million by Siemens, the
German telecom company. The deal reportedly made millionaires of
more than a dozen Redstone employees.
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of deal-making seems to have thrown out all of the
rules traditionally associated with company building. Once upon a
time, a young entrepreneur started a business with the expectation
it would grow into the next IBM or Microsoft. Today that same
entrepreneur is happy to sell out before the company gets its name
listed in the telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   If the current trend continues, big companies may soon be
shelling out hundreds of millions of dollars for clever ideas
sketched out on the back of cocktail napkins.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   According to experts, a blend of technology, heightened
competition, and soaring stock prices has changed the way business
is done. The tremendous growth in Internet use has fueled the
demand for companies that can sell something over the Internet and
for companies that can boost the speed and carrying capacity of the
network itself, the highway portion of the information
superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   The highway business has attracted a slew of players, everyone
from Lucent Technologies and Siemens on the telecom side to Cisco
Systems and 3Com Corp. on the computer networking side. All of
these companies are locked in a fierce global struggle for market
share and each is looking to get the technological edge on its
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all want to be sure they are not left behind,'' says Paul
Ferri of Matrix Partners, a Waltham, Mass. venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny Massachusetts companies make products that could
deliver that technological edge. They make switches, software, or
chips that the giants want. And thanks to the incredible runup in
stock prices, the giants have plenty to spend. Half a billion
dollars in the form of stock may sound like real money to you, but
for a Cisco or a Lucent, whose market values exceed $150 billion,
those sums don't amount to much. The purchases have been paid for
with a combination of stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The giants are buying early-stage companies because in the
Internet era, getting there first is critical. As Fidelity
Investments says in its latest ad campaign for electronic
brokerage, ``On-line trading is like the Old West. The slow die
first.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fast can make a pile of money. Exchange.com founder
Leschly said he knew he had to move quickly to establish a foothold
in his little corner of the electronic commerce department store.
He has already signed up 3,000 music and book dealers who list
their inventory on his Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   At 29, barely a year out of Harvard Business School, Leschly
already has made a fortune. Still, his life isn't perfect. He told
the Globe that he and his employees have to relocate to Seattle,
where Amazon.com is based. He also suggested his girlfriend wasn't
too thrilled with the prospect of the move.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the story? That even the young and megarich have
problems. That doesn't make us feel a lot less jealous. But it's a
start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston was honored last week for its charitable work by the
National Society of Fund Raising Executives.
</P>
<P>
   The bank responded appropriately: It is giving away more money.
BankBoston will give $2,500 to each qualified nonprofit
organization that is able to raise at least $5,000 of new corporate
support between now and May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in finding out how the program works should
call 617-426-6400.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
