<HEADER>
A3716 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-B     05-04 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON MAKING A POWERFUL STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- At ice level, the action took place slowly,
methodically. It was an exercise in patience on the power play. The
Bruins' point men, Raymond Bourque and Darren Van Impe, passed the
puck along the blue line. They waited for an open lane, an
opportunity to slide the black disk down low.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 25 seconds into the first-period man-advantage, the action
gathered speed. Bourque and Van Impe traded places. The veteran
captain fed the puck to Jason Allison. The Bruin forward circled
behind the net. He threaded the puck to Dmitri Khristich. The right
wing spied Joe Thornton in his peripheral vision, just beyond the
left post.
</P>
<P>
   For Thornton, the action slowed during one decisive
split-second. The center calmly picked Khristich's pass out of his
skates and turned toward the open net. He threw the puck toward the
goal and past Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe. The last of five Bruins
to touch the puck on the power play, Thornton raised his hands in
celebration after scoring the first goal in Game 6 of this Eastern
Conference quarterfinal _ a goal that stood up as decisive in
Boston's 2-0 series-clinching win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dmitri could see me in the corner of his eye,'' said Thornton.
``I had an open net so it was an easy goal for me. I had a lot of
time, so it was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thornton's young, fast-track world, time has always been
relative.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from No. 1 draft pick to NHL force seemed neither
quick nor easy. The progression from mature second-line forward to
major playoff contributor seemed to happen in a matter of weeks.
But Thornton's performance in this series _ making hard plays look
easy _ was the result of two years of NHL experience.
</P>
<P>
   A first-round series win was the logical next step in the
education of the younger Bruins, with Thornton youngest among them.
They needed to know what it felt like to advance in the playoffs.
They needed the confidence that comes with shaking hands at the end
of a series and telling a defeated opponent, ``Have a nice
summer.'' They needed to meet a raised level of expectations and
succeed at a more intense level of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a way to get the job done, and a lot of guys played
big roles on this club and all these guys were young guys,'' said
the 38-year-old Bourque, who is 19 years Thornton's senior. ``It's
real important for us to move on and get that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton and Anson Carter, 24, ``stepped up their game,''
Bourque added, ``and their future is really unlimited as far as how
good they could be in a lot of ways. They're going to be key guys
for this team for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stepped it up at the important times. That's huge, when a
young guy knows the situation, wants to be a big part of the
success of the club. These two guys really wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton was the first player a visibly emotional Bourque
embraced after Game 6 ended.
</P>
<P>
   Although the second-year center asserted himself in the regular
season with 16 goals and 25 assists, the playoffs offered another
opportunity to make up for a forgettable rookie campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Thornton has more than met the postseason challenges.
Against Carolina, he picked up one goal, four assists, and
increasing confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's first assist came in Boston's losing Game 3 effort,
when he found Sergei Samsonov for a tying goal. In Game 4, Thornton
was responsible for the chip pass that caught Irbe off guard and
allowed Landon Wilson to score the game's decisive goal, on a power
play. Thornton notched a second assist less than 10 minutes later
on Steve Heinze's insurance goal.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Sunday night's winner, Thornton's feed to Carter in
the second overtime of Game 5 was the center's most important
playoff contribution. The flip pass set up Carter's winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never experienced going past the first round,'' said
Thornton. ``I think experience-wise that's going to be very
important. A lot of us in here are so young. After we taste some of
this, I think we'll want more.''
</P>
<P>
   After being the No. 1 overall pick in the 1997 entry draft,
Thornton struggled through a rookie year of limited ice time and
little production (3 goals, 4 assists). The Bruins organization
preached patience, but it was clear the grace period would be only
a year. Thornton spent the summer working on strength and
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a season when I didn't get too many points and I didn't
play too much, I wanted to make this year better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, his presence and contributions in the Carolina series
made the concerned and critical voices of the past seem very
distant.
</P>
<P>
   And he certainly was in sync with the power-play unit. Unlike
other times in the series when the FleetCenter fans would
frantically yell, ``Shoot! shoot!'' each time a Bruin got the puck
on a power play, an air of anticipation hung quietly over the
crowd. They were mesmerized by the crisp passes, the thwack of
rubber meeting wood. They remained confident the Bruins would
score.
</P>
<P>
   With Thornton's goal, the patience paid off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
