<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY ANTLEY RIDES HIGH AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Racing can be like a roller coaster. You win,
you lose. You're up, you're down. But perhaps no one in the history
of the sport went from the bottom to the top faster than jockey
Chris Antley, who was out of racing until two months ago but came
back to win last Saturday's Kentucky Derby aboard Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Antley, 33, was a sensational apprentice on the Maryland
circuit, then moved to Monmouth Park in New Jersey, where he won
riding titles from 1984-86. In '85, he led the nation with 469
victories, 39 of them coming in stakes. He moved to New York in
'87, and in '89 established a record by riding at least one winner
on every card for 64 consecutive racing days. He captured his first
Kentucky Derby aboard Strike the Gold in '91.
</P>
<P>
   However, Antley, who is from Monrovia, Calif., had problems with
substance abuse, including a positive drug test in '88. He moved
his tack to California in 1994, and slowly began to fade from the
picture. He wound up at Woodbine in Toronto, did not enjoy racing
in Canada, and called it quits early in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While on the sidelines, Antley's biggest problem became his
weight. His normal riding weight is 114 pounds, but Antley went up
to 147. When he decided to make a comeback, he embarked on a
vigorous diet and exercise program, which included long runs, and
he made his return to the races in early March at California.
</P>
<P>
   Racing can be about redemption, too. And trainer D. Wayne Lukas
specifically picked Antley off the scrap heap, asking a jockey who
had overcome a weight problem, to handle Charismatic, whom Lukas
described as ``a big, fat horse that wants to run every two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the Demolition Derby, rougher than usual, and Antley
rode a smart race, keeping Charismatic, who broke from post No. 16,
wide and out of trouble. When he put the chestnut son of Summer
Squall _ who had been plodding along in seventh place _ into gear,
Charismatic came running, exploding past the 16th-pole to take a
clear lead.
</P>
<P>
   With about 20 yards to go, Antley raised his left index finger
toward the sky, riding only with his right hand, and upsetting the
purists. But he had the wire measured, and Charismatic held off the
late-charging Menifee by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pointing to God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Antley, who came a long way to regain the spotlight, ranked this
Derby win higher than his score in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has a lot more sentimental value, probably more than
anything I've done in my career, by far,'' he said. ``I've had
things handed to me, and always been able to come back quick, or
get through hard times. This was a little bit of a role reversal,
in the sense that I couldn't just come back nonchalant. I had to
find the depths of myself to be able to get back. So this was
something special. There was a lot of work done to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert tips cap
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert missed his chance to become the first man to train
three consecutive Derby winners, as his charges finished fourth
(Prime Timber), fifth (the filly Excellent Meeting), and 11th
(General Challenge). However, Baffert was gracious after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne Lukas is the trainer of the '90s,'' he said. ``He should
have been in the Hall of Fame a long time ago (Lukas was elected
last Tuesday). The guy is tough. He's a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   All three of Baffert's horses got beaten up in the melee that
was the 125th Run for the Roses, giving him something of an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for me to get into the Derby this year because of
the 20 horses,'' said Baffert. ``It becomes a crapshoot. You still
need a good horse, but you need so much luck. I've been really
lucky all these years because I got the trip. Saturday, I couldn't
get the trip with any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Challenge's eyes were full of dirt and stuff. The poor
guy. He probably took the worst of it of all of them. He's all
right, but he looked like he was dragging his hind leg a little
bit. He probably strained himself. Excellent Meeting ran
unbelievable. She was, like, dead last and she came 10-wide. She
was so wide coming for home, and she still only got beat about 3
lengths. Prime Timber was pretty tired after the race. He had a
little bit of a rough trip, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Derby turned into a war, Baffert was glad he didn't
run his other top filly, the smallish Silverbulletday, who won the
Oaks on Friday in a bravura performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the plan Mike (Pegram, the owner) and I were using:
Don't run her in a 20-horse field,'' said Baffert. ``She could have
been in there getting knocked around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dosage diminished
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest loser in the Derby was the Dosage Index.
Dosage is a calculation purported to measure a thoroughbred's
ability to run 1 1/4 miles on the first Saturday in May. If a horse
is above 4.00 on the Dosage Index, he/she is supposed to be a
throw-out in the Derby. This year, Dosage took a double dip, as the
Derby produced a nonqualifier perfecta; Charismatic had a Dosage of
5.22, and Menifee a Dosage of 5.50. The Dosage theory suffered a
crack in '91, when Strike the Gold became the first to win the
Derby without being a qualifier, which was a big deal at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
