<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE SALUTES KRAFT'S SETTLING OF STADIUM ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When it comes to the future of the New
England Patriots, Drew Bledsoe knows better than to take anything
but his bulging paycheck to the bank. But he may finally breathe
easier now that the team appears destined to stay in Foxborough,
where a $250 million state-of-the-art facility may be ready by
2002, when the quarterback will turn 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I took the `for sale' sign down,'' kidded Bledsoe about
the multimillion-dollar house he recently moved into in Medfield.
``I'm looking to be in the area for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief for a couple of reasons. I really wanted to stay
here, No. 1. We've built a strong fan base here. We have a good
following. Most of those people would have followed us to
Connecticut. But this makes it easier. And No. 2, we've started to
establish roots here as a family _ built a house _ and it would be
tough to pick up and move.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe spoke to Patriots owner Robert Kraft at times during the
abortive Hartford courtship, but said, ``He wasn't at liberty to
say much. I congratulated him when the Connecticut offer came in
and I spoke to him now and then only because we like to know what's
going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great offer. The credit goes to Mr. Kraft to walk
away from the financial windfall and do what he thought was the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I know about Mr. Kraft is he wants to win football
games first and foremost, that's the reason we need the new
facility, to be competitive financially in order for him to give
out signing bonuses and be creative with the contracts. We've got
to have luxury box revenue. And all along he wanted to have
something here in his home state. When that was no longer an
option, then he looked at the next-best option, which was to go to
Connecticut and keep it in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe thinks few people would have taken the road Kraft did.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it: If somebody offers you five times what
you're making to go someplace else but you decide to stay because
you think it's the right thing to do? That's commendable,'' he
said. ``There aren't many people who would make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe thought back to 1993, when he first saw the Foxboro
Stadium facility as the Patriots' No. 1 draft pick out of
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' he recalled. ``In college, our facilities
were about the worst in the Pac-10, and we had far better
facilities then what we had here, which was really surprising for a
professional football team. To have one grass practice field and a
50-yard bubble . . . it's really ridiculous when you think about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the reaction a lot of guys have when they visit here.
When you think about it, in order to attract free agents, you're
going to have to pay them more or find another way to attract them
here. You almost want to bring them to Boston and not show them the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Jim Harbaugh came in my rookie year. They talked
about bringing him in as my mentor. And he was just dumbfounded
that we had to put on our pads and drive to practice at the mental
institution (Wrentham State School). You come back and we had a pop
machine in the locker room at that time and you actually had to put
money into it to get a Coke. So many things are ridiculous about
this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and other players have certainly put the bug in Kraft's
ear about the facilities in other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to places to play and visiting areas are nicer than
what we have, I'll go to Mr. Kraft and say, `This is pretty nice,'
'' said Bledsoe. ``Being a competitive guy, I would think he would
want to have something just as nice if not better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe never saw the stadium issue as a distraction to the
team. He also knows that, because of the way things are in the NFL
now, there may be only 10-12 current Patriots who will be around to
play in the new facility.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe and his wife, Maura, who are expecting their second
child any day, had talked about a game plan if the team moved to
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I wasn't going to commute,'' said Bledsoe. ``It was
too much to ask to have her up here by herself. We were trying to
decide, do we buy a new place or just rent a place until I decided
to retire in a few years?
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side of it is when we were talking about Hartford,
they were talking 2002, which I took to mean 2004 and 2005. With
the way things tend to go with big construction projects everywhere
_ my own house is a year and half late _ I took the attitude that
when the moving vans moved up and packed things up, we were moving
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he harbor any fear that the Massachusetts plan won't come
off?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take the same attitude,'' he said. ``I'd love to
play in a new facility in Foxborough. I'll believe it when it
happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
