<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS MAKING BELIEVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Remember what I was tellin' you? Remember how I told
you the Bruins were gonna be all right, and how they had a
goaltender who could kick 'em out with anybody (any American and
Canadian, anyway) and how the kids were gonna fool everybody and
Joe Thornton was gonna be a huge hero before too long and how it
would be wise to remember that Ray Bourque is 38 going on 28 and
would be there when you needed him, like, say, in his 54th minute
of a double OT game and how one place the Bruins were absolutely in
as good shape as anybody in the league was the coaching department?
Remember all that?
</P>
<P>
   Now, exactly when was I tellin' you all this? Thanksgiving?
Christmas? The day the pitchers and catchers reported? Marathon
Day? OK, not quite. It was last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   I'm 'fessing up. I have come a little late to this party. But
I'm here to tell you that the puckhead experts among us weren't so
sure of anything about a week ago, when the Bruins were down to the
Carolina Hurricanes, two games to one. Don't let any of them
attempt to slip some jive by you. They looked at the Hurricanes and
all they could see was Keith Primeau flying around and Gary Roberts
nailing people and Ray Sheppard continually in the right place at
the right time, with a little Arturs Irbe thrown in. They thought
the Bruins might just be too small and too professionally immature
to beat a veteran team like Carolina in a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   That was before a stirring victory in Game 4 and an exhausting
and thoroughly satisfying road triumph in the epic Game 5 and the
solidly commanding performance in Game 6. The Bruins have won a
playoff series for the first time in five years. They also have the
Big Mo going for them after what they did in Games 4, 5, and 6.
</P>
<P>
   It is now official. Thanks to this Bruins team, we now know it
most certainly is possible for a Boston winter professional sports
team to derive the benefit of a home court/ice appearance. The
Celtics are only dimly aware of this fact, but the Bruins now know
it to be true. You could not ask for much more support than the
FleetCenter crowd has given the newly beloved Bruins these past
three games.
</P>
<P>
   It is absolutely chilling how fast things can change in sport.
Before the Carolina series, the Bruins had not played before a
capacity crowd for a playoff game in the FleetCenter. You kind of
thought they had warranted the maximum level of support following
the kind of season _ and especially the kind of finish _ they had,
but with prices in all sports the way they are these days, no one
ever can fault people for opting to take in the game on radio or
TV.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting we're back in the early '70s, but we are back
where the Bruins used to be in the Garden. The diehards never left,
of course, but the fence-sitters are back, and with good reason.
The Bruins are putting on a great show.
</P>
<P>
   How far can they go? The best answer is ``as far as anybody else
in the East.'' There are no absolutes in this side of the draw.
There are no absolutes, and no great teams, either. Spectacular
individuals? Oh, sure. Perhaps you've heard of chaps named Jagr and
Hasek. They don't come any better. The former might be the best
player in the game, period, and the latter is now the standard by
which all goalkeepers are being judged. If the Fates so decree, the
Bruins might be facing Mr. Hasek in the next series and, if they
were so fortunate as to win, Mr. Jagr in the series after that. But
neither plays for a great team.
</P>
<P>
   This team already has accomplished something by winning a
playoff series. It was the primary goal for the 1998-99 Boston
Bruins, a team populated by young players who never had known the
taste of Stanley Cup victory in any form. Now they have it, and it
has to taste even better than they imagined because these guys
truly earned it by winning three games in a row when the doubts
were starting to creep in.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have a chance to be something even better. They can
stop being a pesky team and become a downright dangerous one. There
is a berth in the Stanley Cup finals open to anyone and everyone
left in the tournament. New Jersey is the team with the most
credentials, but the Devils don't scare anybody, as evidenced by
the fact that they have to play Pittsburgh in a Game 7. No matter
who the Bruins wind up playing, they will do so with justifiable
confidence. You will be reading and hearing that the Bruins can
beat anyone they play in the East, and can do so in any building,
and it all will be true. They really can.
</P>
<P>
   They really are likable, even lovable the way they're playing
now. It's easy to root for the kids, the budding stars such as
Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Joe Thornton, to name three. It's
also easy to root for a guy like Steve Heinze, who kept his mouth
shut when his playing time was cut and who responded when called
upon in the Carolina series with timely goals and clever assists.
It is very easy to root for goaltender Byron Dafoe, who continually
has given his team an edge in this most demanding of all sports
positions. It shouldn't be too dfficult to pull for a quiet,
dependable veteran like Don Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is The Captain. If there ever was someone who led
by example . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics soon will be done. The Red Sox, in case you haven't
figured it out, will not be a factor. The Patriots won't be showing
up for 2 1/2 months. The spotlight is now trained on the Bruins. I
told ya so. No, really. I was spouting off pretty good right after
Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
