<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE CROWN BIDS WILL BE A HORSE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charismatic's improbable victory in last Saturday's Kentucky
Derby whetted the appetites of networks vying to buy the television
rights to the Triple Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, CBS, and Fox will be at the table this fall when
negotiations are supposed to begin for the rights now held by ABC.
The Disney-owned network is paying about $9 million per year for
all three races, including about $5 million for the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good price for all three. Thirty-second ad spots during
the races range from $125,000 for the Derby to to $85,000 for the
Preakness to $65,000 for the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   And the ratings are solid. Saturday's race earned a 6.6 national
rating, not bad for a Saturday afternoon. Last year's number was a
6.7. But the problem is that, for the first time in the '90s, the
Derby did not have competition from the NBA playoffs. So the rating
is not a good sign. It means the Derby has a solid core of fans but
has been unable to capture the eyes of casual observers.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources suggest that NBC is eager to add the Triple
Crown to its package of horse races, which includes most notably
the Breeders' Cup. Another reason is that NBC could promote the
races during the NBA playoffs. Fox has the money and a strong horse
racing lineup, but not even Rupert Murdoch wants to throw money
away.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has the rights for another year, and doesn't plan on giving
them up without a fight. Despite recent cost-cutting moves at
Disney, ABC spokesman Mark Mandel said retaining the Triple Crown
is a ``major priority.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Icy stares
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins pulled in good numbers for their first playoff series
victory since 1994. Their 2-0 clincher over the Hurricanes Sunday
night on Channel 38 earned an 11 rating and 16 share, peaking
during the last 15 minutes at a 15.6 rating and 23 share. Friday
night's double-overtime game, also on Channel 38, pulled an 8.4
rating and 15 share, but the overall numbers don't do justice to
the game. From 10:45-11:30 p.m., it earned a 12 rating and 27
share, peaking at 11:15 p.m. with a 12.6 rating and 24 share. The
ratings show again that Boston fans turn on the tube when the home
team is winning. It doesn't hurt to play on the East Coast, either.
The Red Sox-A's game in Oakland late Friday night mustered only a 3
rating and 8 share on Channel 56. The game peaked at 12:15 a.m.
with a 4 rating and 12 share, but viewership dropped significantly
thereafter . . . Boston viewers aren't showing a lot of love to the
NBA. Sunday afternoon's doubleheader attracted barely 44,000
household viewers. The first game, Knicks-Pacers, earned a 1.9
rating and 7 share. The second game, Jazz-Spurs, pulled a 1.4
rating and 4 share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late word
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday late-night shows produced the usual numbers. ``Sports
Final'' on Channel 4 earned a 4.7 and beat Channel 7's ``Sports
Xtra,'' which had a 3.1. The untold story is that Channel 5 earned
about a 6 rating for its ``ER'' rerun between 11:30 p.m. and
midnight. The hourlong show pulled a 5.7 overall rating, leading
into George Michael's sports show, which earned a 3.9 rating.
Channel 7 executives must be wondering how to keep viewers tuned in
Sunday nights. Their news at 11 p.m. beats out the competiton, but
the sports show can't hold the audience . . . CNN/SI's ``Sports
Tonight,'' hosted by Fred Hickman and Vince Cellini, has gotten a
little bump in its 11-11:30 p.m. ratings. It pulled a .5 for the
month of April, or an average of 359,000 households. Last April,
the number was .3, or 224,000 households. The increase comes at a
time when Fox Sports has poured millions into Keith Olbermann
promotions and ESPN continues its dominance . . . Speaking of the
cable sports giant, Mickey Mantle is the ``SportsCentury''
37th-greatest athlete.
</P>
</TEXT>
