<P>
   CALIF-EXECUTE (San Francisco) _ A Vietnam veteran who received a
Purple Heart on death row was executed by injection early Tuesday
for beating a 78-year-old woman to death. Manuel Babbitt was
sentenced to death for killing Leah Schendel in 1980. By Evelyn
Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ASTHMA-HOMELESS-KIDS (New York) _ A new study finds that 30
percent of homeless children have asthma, a percentage far higher
than the general population. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DISASTER-INDUSTRY (Undated) _ When a disaster like the Kosovo
crisis strikes, humanitarian agencies race to provide aid.
Supplying many of these groups is a growing disaster industry, a
loose network of brokers, wholesalers and companies who, for a
profit, can supply anything from drugs to cooking kits to armored
personnel carriers to concertina wire. It is a curious industry in
which salesmen drumming up business may stalk aid workers in
refugee camps and a good year in terms of disasters can mean
hundreds of millions of dollars. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Treasury prices fall sharply in heavy
selling. At 11 a.m., the long bond was down about a point, yielding
5.72%, up from 5.65% on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:55 p.m. the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 67 points. European markets were slightly lower.
Tokyo was closed. Hong Kong rose 1.67 percent. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ A bill to overhaul financial
services legislation goes to the Senate floor for debate. President
Clinton announces proposals to better protect privacy of personal
financial data and to strengthen consumer protections against
banking promotions. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ GM reports April sales; also looking at
GM's plan to move ahead in building a plant, its first new one in a
decade, in Lansing, Mich. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-IPO (New York) _ Shares of Goldman Sachs start trading
at $76, up 43 percent from the initial offering price. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ With the summer driving season
approaching, the price of gasoline across the country has climbed
from historically low levels. The supply of crude oil remains the
most crucial factor affecting gasoline prices but many experts warn
that a shortage of another kind may drive up prices at the pump in
the months ahead: tight supplies of refined gasoline in the United
States. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MARKET (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Eight European stock
markets _ Paris, London, Frankfurt, Milan, Madrid, Amsterdam,
Zurich and Brussels _ sign an agreement to create one single
electronic trading platform, with common rules and regulations, for
blue-chip stocks. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Internet mania comes to Hong
Kong, as shares of Tricom Holding rise more than 1,000 percent. The
company had labored in obscurity until Richard Li, son of the
legendary Hong Kong tycoon, Li Ka-shing, announced a plan to take
it over and turn it into a vehicle for his Internet ventures. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-SUIT (Los Angeles) _ Michael Eisner takes the stand in
trial of Jeffrey Katzenberg's breach-of-contract suit against Walt
Disney. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
