A3740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS05-COX     05-04 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE DUCKS CONTROVERSY ON BALKAN WAR
 &HT;    390&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate, dodging a near-certain rebuff of
President Clinton's handling of the Balkan war, Tuesday shelved a
resolution authorizing the use of ``all necessary force'' against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 78-22 for a motion by Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., to table the measure, killing it without a vote on
the merits.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of the White House, Republican and Democratic
leaders locked arms to block the resolution sponsored by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., who has been pressing Clinton for more forceful
steps to assure victory in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a presidential hopeful for 2000, bitterly attacked the
White House for opposing his resolution even though it would have
broadened Clinton's powers and permitted him to deploy ground
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is prepared to lose a war
rather than do the hard work, the politically risky work, of
fighting it as the leader of the greatest nation on Earth should
fight when our interests and values are imperiled,'' he charged.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's supporters, including senators from both parties, had
conceded that the measure did not have a majority. The White House
and its backers feared a potential embarrassment if the Senate had
voted against expanding Clinton's authority in conducting the war.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, a critic of the U.S. policy in the Balkans, said he wanted
to avoid a divisive vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the resolution was ``out of sync with current events''
because the Clinton administration has not sought authority to
expand the conflict beyond the current bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's resolution provoked the most extended debate in the
Senate over the air war since it began six weeks ago and revealed
deep divisions about the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is left to us, as our war on the cheap fails to achieve
the objectives for which we went to war?'' McCain said. He
ridiculed the idea of a bombing pause, which Clinton said Monday he
would consider. Recalling his five years as a prisoner of war in
Vietnam, McCain said more bombing, not bombing pauses, had secured
his eventual release.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, called for a
five-day moratorium in the bombing campaign. ``I think it's worth a
try,'' she said, calling on Clinton to take a ``bold step'' in
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some senators, including Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., invoked images
of World War II to argue for U.S. military involvement on behalf of
the victims of Serbian ethnic cleansing. ``The objectives are
extremely reasonable and just,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others, including Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., heard echoes of
the Vietnam war. There is ``no strategy to win, no exit strategy,''
and ``most of the planes and troops are American,'' said Cleland,
an Army veteran who was severely injured in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House sent contradictory messages by failing to
muster a majority to support the ongoing bombing campaign in the
Balkans but refusing to vote to withdraw the forces.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, the House is expected to approve an emergency
spending bill of $12.9 billion, double the amount sought by the
White House for the Balkan effort. Senate action on the funding is
expected next week.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
