<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABBITT-EXECUTION-HNS     05-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA EXECUTES DECORATED VETERAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN QUENTIN, Calif. _ A decorated ex-Marine who said he was
having a Vietnam combat flashback when he murdered a Sacramento
woman nearly two decades ago was executed at San Quentin Prison
Tuesday after last-minute legal efforts to save his life failed.
</P>
<P>
   The final words of Manuel Pina Babbitt, delivered to San Quentin
Warden Jeanne Woodford, were, ``I forgive all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled 12:01 a.m. execution was delayed for nearly 30
minutes as the U.S. Supreme Court considered his final appeal,
which the court rejected without comment.
</P>
<P>
   The death warrant for Babbitt, who turned 50 on Monday, was read
at 12:29 a.m., followed immediately by the lethal injection. He was
declared dead at 12:37 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt became the seventh killer executed in California since
the state resumed capital punishment seven years ago after a hiatus
of more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first African-American executed by the state in that
period; his supporters argued to the end that he was represented at
trial by a racist and drunken lawyer and that the victim,
prosecutor, public defender and jury were all white.
</P>
<P>
   But John Rizzotti, a great-grandson of Babbitt's victim, Leah
Schendel, called the execution a justifiable death that was ``the
only way to end my family's 18-year nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schendel family, in a statement read by Laura Thompson, Leah
Schendel's granddaughter, said, ``We know that nothing will bring
Leah Schendel back to us but we feel that we have done everything
in our power to see that justice was done in her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel as always that the only proper response to capital
crime is to demand the highest penalty for the taking of innocent
lives,'' she said. ``From the beginning all we have ever asked for
is justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine members of the Schendel family, mostly grandchildren and
great-grandchildren of the victim, witnessed the execution. William
Babbitt, who turned his brother into the police 18 years ago, also
was a witness.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's denial capped a parade of appeals that has
become part of the execution night ritual.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Manuel Babbitt's appeals were turned down by the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and by the California Supreme Court.
Gov. Gray Davis, a fellow veteran of the Vietnam war, denied
Babbitt's clemency appeal on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt spent his last hours meditating in a death watch cell
only steps away from the chamber where an unidentified doctor
administered a lethal cocktail of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He had fasted for two days and skipped the traditional last
meal, prison officials said. He asked that his last meal go to a
homeless veteran, but prison officials rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would like to die with dignity,'' one of his defense
attorneys, Charles Patterson, said. ``He said to me at one time
that God has different ways of calling us home and this is the way
he's chosen for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The drugs injected intravenously were sodium pentothal to put
Babbitt to sleep, pancuronium bromide to arrest his breathing and
potassium chloride to stop his heart. It took the drugs a little
more than seven minutes to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   The doomed man showed no emotion when the curtain to the small
death chamber was drawn to allow witnesses to see. Several minutes
after the injections, his chest sharply convulsed, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 700 anti-capital punishment demonstrators gathered in the
windy cold outside San Quentin until the death was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The vigil was peaceful and unlike previous executions, there
appeared to be no pro-death penalty demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the demonstrators were other Vietnam veterans, including
Larry Yepez, who carried his Marine uniform from his home in
Lathrop, Calif. ``I know what he went through,'' Yepez said. ``I
woke up today and I knew I had to go out of respect. No matter what
he did, we're brother Marines and brother post-traumatic stress
syndrome victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt was convicted of robbing, attempting to rape and
murdering Schendel, who was 78, during a burglary in her Sacramento
apartment in December 1980. Schendel died of a heart attack during
the assault, which included a beating so savage it cleaved her
forehead to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   In death-row interviews, Babbitt said he did not doubt that he
killed the woman but had no memory of it.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers argued that he may have been suffering from
post-traumatic stress, or shell shock, from his experiences in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters said he had suffered from mental illness since he
was a child and the pressure of made him crack even more.
</P>
<P>
   While on death row, Babbitt was awarded a Purple Heart for his
wounds suffered during the 77-day siege of Khe Sanh. The outcry
from the Schendel family and the public ended such prison
ceremonies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
