<HEADER>
A3743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXECUTION-WITNESS-HNS     05-04 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-WITNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WITNESSES TO AN EXECUTION, SOMBER END TO LONG ORDEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN QUENTIN, Calif. _ Although an execution in California has
become somewhat uneventful, even routine, it is an event that is
still hard to watch.
</P>
<P>
   As Manuel Pina Babbitt, 50, started convulsing early Tuesday,
his head and chest lifting several times and his restraints barely
able to keep him on the table, Laura Thompson, the granddaughter of
Babbitt's murder victim, could not watch.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes were cast downward as Babbitt, straps across his arms,
chest and legs and handcuffs around his wrists, heaved
dramatically, minutes after a lethal injection began coursing
through his veins.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt was the seventh person executed at San Quentin in the
last seven years. Prison authorities ran the proceedings without a
hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The only delay was caused by a last-minute appeal to the Supreme
Court, which denied Babbitt's motion for a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   A guard read the death warrant at 12:29 a.m. About 15 witnesses
were seated in a semi-circle around the hexagonal-shaped death
chamber. More witnesses stood on risers in the back of the small
room.
</P>
<P>
   When the guard declared, ``The execution shall now proceed,''
two other guards pulled back the dainty white curtains to reveal
the small chamber, painted an inappropriately cheerful sea green.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt lay calmly, his head moving a few times. Two catheters
were in his arms, the tubes extending to the room behind the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The handcuffs had not been used in previous executions.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman Vernell Crittendon would say only that they
were necessary for security but said Babbitt had not been
uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has stated unequivocally that Babbitt deserved
execution for murdering her grandmother, Leah Schendel. At a
clemency hearing last week, she said Babbitt's death would not be
nearly as agonizing as her grandmother's.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt was convicted of robbing, attempting to rape and
murdering Schendel, who was 78, during a burglary in her Sacramento
apartment in December 1980. Schendel died of a heart attack during
the assault, which included a beating so savage it cleaved her
forehead to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   At the execution Thompson was surrounded by eight other family
members, mostly Schendel's grandchildren and great-grandchildren.
Many of them held hands as Babbitt lay dying in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the convulsions stopped, Babbitt stopped breathing.
The room was quiet for several minutes as the witnesses watched the
motionless body.
</P>
<P>
   The only noise was the dull thumping of old pipes in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   John Rizzotti, Schendel's oldest great-grandson, turned to the
young woman next to him and mouthed, ``You OK?'' She nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Although Babbitt wanted none of his relatives to watch him die,
he finally relented, allowing his older brother William, who turned
Babbitt into the police 18 years ago, to witness the execution.
William Babbitt had indicated he wanted to be with his brother up
until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a sweat shirt with the hood pulled over his head and his
hands in his pockets, he stood off to the side during the eight
minutes it took his brother to die. Some witnesses said he appeared
to be smiling slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The only other witness Babbitt allowed was Charles Patterson, a
Los Angeles lawyer worked without compensation on the case for more
than three years. Patterson, a fellow Marine and, like Babbitt, a
survivor of the bloody siege at Khe Sanh, said his law firm had put
more than $1 million into defending Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   The last time San Quentin had an event for Babbitt was last
year. He was awarded a Purple Heart for his service in Vietnam,
where he fought countless Viet Cong and saw fellow Americans die.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
