<SLUG> BC-FASHION-CAMPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY CAMPERS FIND A QUIRKY SHOE THAT FITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They're clompy and quirky and too, too cute.
Above all, they're comfortable, not to mention pricey. They're
Campers, heretofore available only in Europe. And they're invading.
</P>
<P>
   So what are Campers? Athletic shoe? Sandal? Platform? Mismatched
ballerina flat? They're all these in one totally fun piece of
footwear, totally out of the ordinary. Campers, in other words,
look like they've been made by committee.
</P>
<P>
   Plus: They have this very neat-o Web site (www.camper.es) where
you learn about the history of the company, see the styles, ads
(which are as radical as Benetton's) and archives, and even send
the company e-mail missives.
</P>
<P>
   The Camper shoe has its roots in 19th-century Spain on the
island of Mallorca. Artisan-cobbler Antonio Fluxa combined his
artistic sensibilities with English technology _ on a trip to
Britain, he got his first Goodyear sewing machine _ and built an
extended family of shoemakers working in independent workshops all
over the island. Antonio's son, Lorenzo, continued the tradition
and Lorenzo's son, also Lorenzo, created the Camper shoe brand in
1975.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the loosey-goosey post-hippie sensibilities of island
living (a kind of waste-not, want-not philosophy of using recycled
materials like truck tires, canvas and hemp thread) with the needs
of his customers (those who eschewed automobiles and preferred to
walk around Mallorca; those who loved soccer; those who needed
shoes to wear to the beach). Campers are a quirky combination of
art and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quirky? You bet,'' said Rita Hurault, a preschool teacher in
Oakland, Calif. ``Mine are unmatched.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Hardy's first pair of Campers are 2 years old already and
they're so durable, they hardly look worn. They are bright yellow
futbol shoes called ``pelotas,'' which Hardy bought in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend came back from shopping one day with shoes that were
clunky and had little felt patches with Japanese writing on them,''
Hardy said. ``They were cute. I got my first pair last year when my
husband and I were were in Paris _ the mustard yellow ones. I
bought my second pair in Paris this winter. They're black and heavy
and the shoe is so wide that I bump into things.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo Fluxa opened his first Campers store in 1982 in
Barcelona, the perfect spot for an idiosyncratic designer
(Barcelona is the city of Gaudi and his eccentric cathedral).
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Paris have bought them in the Campers store in the
Marais district. And now, Campers have come to America, if in
limited supply.
</P>
<P>
   Like olives and anchovies, Campers are definitely an acquired
taste. Those who adore the delicacy (and put up with the
discomfort) of such high-styled shoes as Manolo Blahniks or
Christian Louboutins probably would enjoy the humor of some of the
Camper sandals (one pair is printed with tortellinis on the right
foot and stripes on the left) but might blanch at wearing the
combination Mary Jane/athletic shoe in funereal black that looks
like the creator couldn't decide just what it was he was trying to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clodhopper look was big before Campers,'' said Marjorie
Ingall, a free-lance writer who said she doesn't wear them because
``The heel gapes on me; besides, I am a tightwad and they're
expensive'' ($90 to $160).
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why people love them?'' said Kay Hardy, an attorney
and legal writer. ``They fit wide American feet and when you've
been tromping around Paris for two weeks and go in to try them on
with your swollen feet, they fit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
