A3791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-BATHHOUSES-HNS &LR;      05-04 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-BATHHOUSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY GROUPS SEEK VOTER APPROVAL TO REOPEN BATHHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A coalition of gay organizations has launched a
ballot campaign to reopen San Francisco's gay bathhouses, which
were ordered closed in October 1984 during the height of the AIDS
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to increase the number of venues where gay people can
practice safe, sensual sodomy,'' said Michael Petrelis of the
organization Queer Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some two dozen gay bathhouses were closed in 1984 when then
Mayor Dianne Feinstein declared a public health emergency as HIV
infections increased exponentially in the city's homosexual
population. The rationale was that unsafe sex behind locked doors
in the bathhouses was spreading the fatal virus.
</P>
<P>
   Bathhouses have remained closed since, but health officials do
allow sex clubs, where men typically gather in large, common rooms
where employees can check for condom use. Sex clubs are prohibited
from allowing private rooms with locked doors.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Katz, the director of the Department of Public Health,
said it was important to maintain such rules to prevent new HIV
infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that these rules are important to ensure safe
sex,'' Katz said. ``We believe that businesses also have a
responsibility to monitor behaviors in the establishments to ensure
that safe sex is practiced. It's important for us to prevent as
many HIV infections as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates of reopening bathhouses say San Francisco is
erring too much on the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other major metropolitan areas ... and San Jose and Berkeley
all have bathhouses,'' said David Pasquarelli of ACT UP San
Francisco. ``It's time for San Francisco to get with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Pasquarelli, there is no evidence that sex behind
closed doors in bathhouses is inherently less safe than it is in
the more open sex clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the Sexually Transmitted Disease Reduction
Initiative have until July 5 to gather 10,200 signatures to put the
measure on the Nov. 7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether a ballot initiative, if approved by
voters, would overturn current policy, or merely serve as an
advisory measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This policy was started in the 1980s when we had a health
emergency in San Francisco, and we still have a health emergency in
San Francisco,'' said Lee Ann Monfredini, president of the city
Health Commission. She noted that the Board of Supervisors declares
AIDS a health emergency every two weeks, a legality required to
distribute clean needles to drug addicts who might otherwise become
infected with the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has had 25,976 reported cases of AIDS, resulting
in 17,814 deaths, as of March 31 this year, according to the Health
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The groups arguing to reopen the bathhouses have asked health
commissioners several times in recent months to consider their
request. Monfredini said a meeting had been set for June 5 with the
HIV Prevention Council to discuss the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that we (the Health Commission) will have a hearing
on this,'' Monfredini said. ``We just don't know yet until we see
the data and hear the prevention council's recommendation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
