<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the devastating storms and tornadoes in Oklahoma and
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-STORMS (Oklahoma City) _ Ledeall: Devastating tornadoes too
numerous to count roared across Oklahoma and Kansas, killing at
least 45 people and destroying entire neighborhoods in cities and
small towns alike. About 150 miles north, a tornado spawned by the
same storm system tossed mobile homes like tin cans, damaged houses
and killed at least five people in Wichita, Kan., and its suburb of
Haysville. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-SCENE (Oklahoma City) _ The scene of devastation and how
the city is coping. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-INTENSITY (Undated) _ These were the biggest tornadoes to
hit Oklahoma in years and the deadliest since 1985. By William K.
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-AID (Washington) _ Federal response to the Oklahoma storm
damage is swift. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
