<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GOVERNMENT05-COX     05-04 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOVERNMENT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV HEAPS SCORN ON PUBLIC OFFICIALS, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    350&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the TV version of America, Newman of
``Seinfeld'' mostly doesn't deliver the mail. Marge Simpson's
chain-smoking sisters, Selma and Patty Bouvier, are uncaring clerks
at the Department of Motor Vehicles in Springfield. New York Mayor
Randall Winston bungles through every episode of ``Spin City.'' And
a social worker on ``The X-Files'' turns out to be the devil in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1990s, public officials have the worst image of any
major occupational group on television, and civil servants aren't
far ahead of them,'' concluded a report released Tuesday by the
Center for Media and Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   After examining network prime-time TV series aired from 1955 to
1998, the nonpartisan research organization found that depictions
of elected officials and government workers have grown increasingly
negative over the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   In general, teachers and police officers have generally been
portrayed more favorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``From its earliest days, television has split its vote on
government employees,'' the report said. ``Prime time has usually
given thumbs up to law enforcement officials and public school
teachers, thumbs down to public officials and office seekers, and a
dismissive wave of the hand to civil servants.''
</P>
<P>
   The images have turned darker as public trust in government has
steadily eroded.
</P>
<P>
   Most TV viewers _ 55 percent _ believe that government officials
and public servants are accurately portrayed on prime-time
entertainment programs, according to a poll by Yankelovich
Partners. Among younger viewers between the ages of 18 and 34, the
proportion rises to two out of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, the viewing public is buying into these negative
stereotypes,'' said Patricia McGinnis, president of the Council for
Excellence in Government, a non-profit, non-partisan organization
of private sector leaders who have served in government. The
council, which seeks to improve both the performance and image of
government, sponsored both the TV study and the public opinion
poll.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   To find out how entertainment TV portrays government,
researchers examined 1,234 series episodes and 9,588 characters
appearing on the air from 1955 through 1998. On these shows, 2.664
characters _ 28 percent _ were civilian public sector employees.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Our Miss Brooks'' to ``Welcome Back Kotter'' to the
short-lived ``Dangerous Minds,'' programs have usually portrayed
teachers favorably, the study found. Not so principals. From the
blustery Osgood Conklin of ``Our Miss Brooks'' to the hapless
Seymour Skinner of ``The Simpsons'' to the scheming Principal
Snyder of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' the heads of schools have
been buffoons or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and elected officials have never fared particularly
well in TV imagery, but the portrayals have grown harsher over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   In past decades there have been a few competent and honest
public officials _ Fess Parker as a homespun senator in the TV
version of ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,'' state legislator James
Slattery in ``Slattery's People'' and the problem-solving butler
who evolved into a problem-solving lieutenant governor in
``Benson.''
</P>
<P>
   But from Boss Hogg on the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' to Senator Strobe
Smithers on ``Hearts Afire'' to Mayor Winston of ``Spin City,''
elected officials have more often been shown as scatterbrained or
greedy, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most government officials are portrayed as
``politicians and bureaucrats who serve their own interests or
special interests rather than the public interest,'' the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990s programming, elected officials committed crimes more
than twice as often as characters in other occupations, the study
found. Seven out of 10 episodes that dealt with government services
gave a negative portrayal of the government performance. Among
episodes that dealt with probity of political or legal
institutions, three out of four portrayed the system as corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime-time entertainment today gives public service little
notice and less respect,'' said Robert Lichter, president of the
Center for Media and Public Affairs. ``The core institutions of
government _ the political system and those who work within it _
are treated badly.''
</P>
<P>
   The negative portrayals could have serious ramifications on who
votes and who will run for public office, McGinnis said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   But she conceded that there is no proven ``cause and effect''
between negative TV portrayals and declining public trust in public
officials and workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television takes off on reality,'' said Lichter. ``It takes
out all shades of gray'' and ``magnifies'' actuality.
</P>
<P>
   TV's comedic mail carriers _ ``Seinfeld's'' Newman and Cliff
Craven of ``Cheers'' _ exaggerated and amplified traits that many
viewers already attributed to postal employees, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The negative stereotypes generally have not extended to TV cops,
however. From Sgt. Joe Friday of ``Dragnet'' to Sheriff Andy Taylor
of ``The Andy Griffith Show'' to ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' law
enforcers have been shown to be caring, competent and honest. Andy
Sipowicz of ``NYPD Blue'' is a considerably more flawed cop,
however. And a malevolent government usually provides the villains
as well as the FBI good guys on ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Even law enforcers are more often portrayed negatively in the
'90s than previous decades _ a 2-to-1 ratio of positive portrayals
now, compared to 5 to 1 in the past, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankelovich Partners poll was conducted from March 11-14,
1999. The researchers interviewed 1,002 American television
viewers, aged 18 or older, and the survey had a margin of error of
plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
