r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMANPOUR-CNN-OPED-NYT     05-04 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMANPOUR-CNN-OPED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS WAR CORRESPONDENTS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By CHRISTIANE AMANPOUR  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For reasons that often have little to do with journalism, it can
be surprisingly difficult to maintain a commitment to honest and
courageous reporting while trying to cover certain wars.
 &HT;    The sacred principle of our business is objectivity, and in the
nine years I've been covering war, I've come to learn exactly what
objectivity means _ whether in wars between nations like the
Persian Gulf War or dirty civil wars like Somalia or the kinds of
genocidal campaigns against civilians that have plagued the end of
our century from Yugoslavia to Rwanda.
 &HT;    The only way I can discuss the difficulties of covering the
crisis in Kosovo is by relating my personal experiences. In my
view, this war is still mainly between Yugoslav forces _ special
police units and paramilitaries _ against a civilian population in
the name of rousting terrorists.
 &HT;    A fundamental problem of covering the war concerns objectivity.
First and most important, I have learned that ``objective'' does
not mean ``neutral.'' The sometimes obsessive desire to find equal
weight between two sides is often simply wrong. There is no moral
equivalence between the aggressor and the victim, a civilian who
has been raped and the thug who did it.
 &HT;    Let's be clear: Objectivity means trying to give all sides a
hearing. It does not, in my view, mean treating all sides as equal.
That, I believe, would be a fundamentally incorrect and immoral
application of objectivity.
 &HT;    This is what the French writer and philosopher Albert Camus
warned: Not choosing is also a choice. I have chosen to apply, to
the best of my ability, contextual objectivity to all my reporting,
especially during war and especially when confronted with the most
serious crimes against humanity as determined by the international
conventions. I insist on putting my reports in context, and I am
often strongly impassioned. I won't apply moral equivalents where
none exist.
 &HT;    At the Kosovo-Albanian border, watching what was happening,
seeing babies and old people and sick people and handicapped people
being forced to march out of their country and listening to their
stories, I reported the tragedy and it was one of the most
difficult things I've had to do in a long time. It was essentially
all of the experience of Bosnia telescoped into a very short period
of time.
 &HT;    We are human beings; I make no excuse for that. Yet our humanity
needs to come across without overwhelming what we do. I have
learned to direct the incredible emotional burden and the physical
and mental pain of what we see into telling the story. Our task is
comparable to that of emergency-room doctors who cannot help but be
affected by what they see yet cannot allow it to overwhelm their
professional obligations.
 &HT;    And that brings us to a second difficulty when covering war,
especially in places such as Serbia which by any definition is a
dictatorship and which has iron-tight state-controlled media that
gives out propaganda and hate and which, importantly, is the only
source of information for most Serbians. This difficulty is
censorship.
 &HT;    I am, without wanting to be self-serving, CNN's longest-serving
Balkan hand. And yet I am no longer in Belgrade because the Serb
authorities hate my reporting.
 &HT;    On March 24, the night the air war started, I was in Belgrade
describing the action from a hotel rooftop when mayhem broke out:
Plainclothes police were carting other journalists off and
deporting many of them. In my case, the notorious paramilitary
known as ``Arkan'' _ his name is really Zeljko Raznjatovic _ had
his thugs looking for me. They burst into a colleague's office, put
everyone against the wall, brandished automatic weapons and began
yelling for me. This is because I had done an investigative report
about Arkan's work _ what he had done during the Bosnian war.
 &HT;    Before the NATO bombing began, Serb television went on a fierce
anti-Western journalist campaign, blaming foreign correspondents
for bringing in NATO, specifically calling CNN ``a factory of
lies.'' It became impossible for me to report, and because of the
direct threats I left Belgrade.
 &HT;    Even after other reporters were returning, a high-level Yugoslav
minister told CNN that I could not go back because they could not
guarantee my security. That is a threat. Then they allowed CNN to
put another, more presumably to-their-liking correspondent in
Belgrade. In my view that is censorship. It is at least control.
 &HT;    And throughout we have endured a form of censorship there, as
have all the other news organizations. Our crews are escorted by
special government or police minders. They are not free to go where
they want, when they want, and they have to rely mostly on Serbian
television pictures. This isn't to say that CNN or others shouldn't
be there, but simply that our viewers should know all the
restrictions we operate under.
 &HT;    The ultimate form of censorship, of course, is expelling all
journalists from Kosovo and keeping them under tight control in
Belgrade. For myself, I ended up on the border where we had much
better access to information. The testimony of those people being
deported en masse, their shocking and consistent accounts, built a
chilling and brutal picture of ethnic cleansing and executions,
separation of men and women, rape _ and all of this against
civilians.
 &HT;    In my years of covering Bosnia, Croatia and Kosovo, the most
terrible things were often first reported by journalists from
eyewitness accounts. And then they were proven true: the death
camps in Bosnia, the mass graves, for instance.
 &HT;    Of course, none of the Albanian refugees on Serbian television
are portrayed as fleeing the terror campaign; Serb officials insist
they are only fleeing NATO bombing. And most Serbs believe that.
They don't have a choice. There is no alternative to them other
than state-controlled media.
 &HT;    Some ask, but doesn't NATO also restrict its information _
impose censorship? The answer is, of course, yes. We don't get the
full story in real time from NATO. But again, in my view, there is
no moral nor practical equivalent between a dictatorship carrying
out what many are now calling crimes against humanity and a
military organization of the free democratic world which is subject
to scrutiny of a free and vigorous press.
 &HT;    And lest anyone doubt Belgrade, one of the few prominent
independent Serbian journalists was recently shot dead near his
home. This has a chilling effect.
 &HT;    Consider the way some Western news organizations covered Arkan,
whose secret indictment by the war-crimes tribunal at The Hague was
made public on March 31. He was either sought out or offered
himself up for interviews; he is a legitimate news story. But if
one is going to give a man like that air time, in my view, one is
obliged to challenge him.
 &HT;    This is one of the most brutal psychopathic killers to patrol
the Balkans. Yet several global news organizations allowed him to
