<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      05-04 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING A PARASITE IN WINE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992, the scene across the Napa Valley was desolate. In what
had been some of the most beautiful vineyards in the world, piles
of dead vines pulled from the soil were being burned. The pall of
black smoke mirrored the mood of winemakers, who watched grimly as
their lives' work went up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Phylloxera, the dreaded parasite that had devastated the vines
of Europe and California a century before, had returned, and
despite a hundred years of research, it seemed there was little
anyone could do to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   In Napa County and the other wine regions of northern
California, the insect destroyed some 50,000 acres, about half of
the total vines.
</P>
<P>
   The phylloxera epidemic has run its course. The insect surfaces
occasionally, and old vines must still be burned, but fresh
plantings are everywhere. What's more, the new grapes are better
than ever, and most California winemakers are convinced that the
wines will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the first chardonnays and sauvignon blancs made from these
new vines are released in the next year or so, will wine drinkers
be able to taste the difference? Probably not. Most wines are
blends of different vintages, and it would take a very discerning
tongue to tell which of the new ones contain a bit of the
pre-phylloxera grapes.
</P>
<P>
   But for winemakers, good has come from bad: the disaster opened
the door to new and better ways to make wine. ``We were forced to
rethink everything,'' said Tom Selfridge, the president and chief
executive of the Chalone Group of wineries. ``If there had been no
phylloxera, we would have replanted gradually and made changes as
we went along. But this was war; we were forced to make a lot of
major decisions quickly, and we knew we had better make the right
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Grape vines normally are replaced every 30 to 35 years, as they
become less resistant to disease. Most Napa Valley and Sonoma
County vines were planted in the 1970s and were not due for
replacement until 2000 or 2010. But because of the inexperience of
some of the winemakers and some misadvice over the years, many of
the 1970s plantings turned out to have been the wrong vines in the
wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, phylloxera in California ``presented an
otherwise unavailable opportunity to redress the legacy of the
1970s,'' said the Australian winemaker James Halliday.
</P>
<P>
   Phylloxera is a microscopic insect native to the eastern United
States, but indigenous American vines are resistant to it. It was
accidentally introduced into Europe around 1860 on vine cuttings
from the United States, and within two decades it had destroyed
virtually all of the vineyards of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It reached California, where European vines had been planted, in
the 1880s and by 1892 had destroyed 15,000 acres in the Napa Valley
alone.
</P>
<P>
   The only effective way to fight the bug is to graft European
vines, from which the best wines are made, onto native American
roots. In the 1960s, before phylloxera was a problem here,
agricultural experts at the University of California recommended a
rootstock called AxR1, which was thought to be phylloxera resistant
and produced plenty of grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Most California growers, who had been using a less productive
native American rootstock called St. George, quickly switched to
AxR1. Most of the new wineries that opened in California in the
1970s used it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Within years, however, Napa Valley vines on AxR1 roots had begun
to sicken. In 1983, it was discovered that phylloxera was the
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decade, the Northern California wine industry
would spend more than a half billion dollars replanting vineyards.
The Robert Mondavi Winery, which began its own experiments with
various new rootstocks in 1983, estimates that it has spent $50
million in redeveloping its phylloxera-stricken vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every case, however, the wineries ultimately benefited
from the disaster by rectifying errors they had made and by taking
advantage of the latest research on new grape clones, planting
density and the compatibility between rootstocks and the vines
grafted to them.
</P>
<P>
   They learned about new kinds of vine trellises and how to orient
the vines to get the best combinations of sun and irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   With the new plantings there are now hundreds, sometimes
thousands of additional vines per acre compared to what was there
20 years ago. The idea is to make the plants compete for nutrients,
water and sun, creating grapes with greater intensity and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers have warned of potential problems stemming from
doing too much too fast; indeed, some of the new rootstocks have
shown signs of previously undetected viruses. But most growers and
winemakers who could afford the changeover are happy with the
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot we don't know,'' said Daniel Roberts, a
soil expert with Kendall-Jackson Vineyards, ``but we are going to
be able to produce high-end, reserve-quality wines in three years,
where it once took 20 years'' for vines to fully mature.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roberts' tutelage, Kendall-Jackson is replanting in
smaller blocks so that the development of different techniques can
be studied over the years. But what of the post-phylloxera wines?
Are they better or just different?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are better,'' said Warren Winiarski, the owner of Stag's
Leap Wine Cellars. ``They are more concentrated; they have a more
mature taste when they are still young.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mondavi is one of the few wineries that has released a
wine made entirely from post-phylloxera grapes _ a 1997 cabernet
sauvignon. Most winemakers, including Winiarski, are making wines
using post-phylloxera grapes along with grapes from vineyards that
were never affected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   I have had the opportunity to try two Beringer Vineyards'
Knights Valley cabernets made in part from post-phylloxera vines, a
1994 and a 1995. Both were first-rate, but the 1995, which had more
of the new grapes, was stylistically different from the 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It showed what the Beringer winemaker, Ed Sbragia, called a
sparkle or brightness that the earlier wines did not. I preferred
the 1994, but I suspect that the new grapes had very little to do
with making it outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   What vineyard managers and winemakers hope to obtain from the
new vineyards is intensity and consistency. If they achieve it,
perhaps it will push American winemaking to a new level _ and also
help drive away the bad memories of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even in periods of great change, some people remain
happily uninvolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my vineyards were in St. George when the big move to AxR1
was made,'' said Rodney Strong, the founder of Rodney Strong
Vineyards in Sonoma County. ``I was too poor to switch over. I was
disappointed then. I'm not now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
