<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     05-04 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU ARE MY LYRICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What are the words to ``You Are My Sunshine?'' My 2-year-old
grandson goes to sleep almost instantly when I sing it, but I only
know one verse.
</P>
<P>
   _ K., Everman, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The lullaby effects are probably confined to the chorus:
``You are my sunshine, my only sunshine,/You make me happy when
skies are gray./You'll never know, dear, how much I love
you;/Please don't take my sunshine away.''
</P>
<P>
   The verses aren't so calming: ``The other night dear, when I was
sleeping,/I dreamt I held you in my arms./When I awoke, dear, I was
mistaken;/So I hung my head and I cried ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always love you and make you happy,/If you will only say
the same,/But if you leave me to love another,/You'll regret it all
someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You told me once, dear, you really loved me/And no one else
could come between/But now you've left me and love another/You have
shattered all my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The song by Jimmie Davis and Charles Mitchell sold a million
copies when Davis recorded it in 1940. Davis followed the success
with two terms as Louisiana's governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't write it about anybody special, although I might have
been courtin' two or three at the time,'' Davis told the Wisconsin
State Journal last year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you tell us the college in Ohio where John Glenn
teaches?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.B., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Glenn is an adjunct professor and honors fellow at Ohio State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The school recently launched the John Glenn Institute for Public
Service and Public Policy to encourage citizen participation in
public service.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, which has an initial fund-raising goal of $20
million, also will house the papers and memorabilia of the former
senator and astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   You can write to Glenn in care of the institute at 100 Bricker
Hall, 190 N. Oval Mall, Columbus, OH 43210-1357.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for my favorite fragrance, Tuberrose from Mary
Chess. Where can I find it today?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.H., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: A Washington company specializing in hard-to-find and
discontinued perfumes lists Mary Chess as one of the brands it
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   To see if it can find Tuberrose or other fragrances, call (800)
257-4513 or write to the Fragrance Factory, Box 1536, Walla Walla,
WA 99362.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
