<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANTS-CELL-PHON     05-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-CELL-PHONES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANTS' MESSAGE: NO CELL PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Conn., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walter Weiss remembers the good old days, which in
restaurants now means B.C. _ Before Cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, the maitre d'hotel at the ``21'' Club, has been in its
employ since 1946 and lived through the era of ``The Sweet Smell of
Success,'' which eternalized Burt Lancaster as a gossip columnist
working the phones brought to his table at ``21.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant will still bring a phone to the table, should a
customer need one, Weiss said last week. Because in a sweet twist
of fate, cell phones don't work at ``21.'' ``There are too many
steel beams,'' he said. ``You get no reception at all. Some of them
work in our lounge, but most people have to go on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should stay there. Cell phone abuse is sweeping
dining rooms throughout New York, from the priciest, like ``21,''
to the more humble, like the Old Town Bar, at 45 East 18th Street.
Prominently displayed there is a picture of a cell phone surrounded
by a red circle with a line through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cellular-free zone _ people have to go outside,'' said
Gerard Meagher, the manager. ``We were built in 1892, and we try to
maintain the spirit of a tavern, a place of good feeling and
fellowship. Talking on a cell phone is self-indulgent.''
</P>
<P>
   And Danny Meyer, the owner of Union Square Cafe, Gramercy
Tavern, Eleven Madison Park and Tabla, has also decided cell phones
make him mad as hell and he won't take it anymore. Last week new
signs were posted at all four front desks, reading: ``Out of
respect to our guests, we ask you to please refrain from using your
cell phone in the dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is so exercised, in fact, that he included a special
message in the Union Square Cafe spring newsletter that began by
saying, ``If clouds of cigarette smoke and pungent fragrances like
Giorgio and Poison were the dining room scourges of the 80s, then
the rampant, inconsiderate use of cell phones in restaurants has
become their baneful heir as we approach the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Them's fighting words from Meyer, a mild-mannered St. Louis
native whose emphasis on hospitality keeps his restaurants at the
top of the Zagat Survey's popularity polls.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent phone interview (from his office, not a cell phone),
he said: ``The thing about cell phones is that they've taken the
city by storm before anyone had a chance to be brought up the right
way about them by their parents. Their use lacks etiquette, form
and propriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Tabla one night, we had three people at the same table on
separate phones at the same time. I understand that restaurants are
also places to do business, but what is particularly annoying is
two things: One is that the people doing it are creating a scene
around themselves, needing to show how important they are. Two is
that restaurants are also places people go to enjoy being restored.
It's hard to be restored while someone is doing something that's
all about being elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the rudeness of inflicting a private conversation on
others, whether of the ``buy/sell'' or ``Mommy will be home soon''
variety, is hardly confined to the dining room. Complaints abound
from all kinds of public spaces, especially theaters and trains,
where callers have all-too-captive audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't cell phone offenders recognize themselves, their
victims ask. They seem to have bountiful excuses, usually
business-related. But no matter what they claim, cell phone victims
say all roads lead to one indisputable element: ME. Look at ME.
Listen to ME. Stop everything you are doing at your own table, and
pay attention to ME.
</P>
<P>
   The offenders seem blind to the sorry reality that these
high-volume, one-sided, arrhythmic monologues are becoming the
technological equivalent of halitosis. Some diners see a cell phone
at the next table and flag the maitre d': it is most definitely
time to move.
</P>
<P>
   While Meyer is at the forefront of the anti-cell-phone movement
in New York, he has been beaten by Gordon Ramsay, the acclaimed
British chef who owns the restaurant bearing his name in London.
``We have printed on the menu, `Please refrain from using mobile
telephones in the dining room,' and it works,'' Ramsay said.
``There are 42 seats in my dining room, and in terms of invading
our privacy and intimacy, it is the height of bad manners. We have
them leave the telephones at the front desk, and if it's necessary,
we will answer them, take the call and let them know. What did
these people do 10 years ago? As a chef, I work 16-hour days, and
nothing infuriates me more than delivering an appetizer to the
table and seeing someone on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But for those who insist that work is all, Judith Re still says
that's not good enough. The founder of the Judith Re Academie in
Fairfield, Conn., she is an expert on etiquette who advises
corporate executives, most of whom are so concerned about
identifying a fish fork that they are oblivious to the disgust of
their fellow diners or, more crucially, Ms. Re says, their business
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you break bread with a client, you create a boardroom
feeling,'' she said, ``but by introducing a cell phone, it
minimizes your lunch. You've turned the boardroom back into an
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also tell executives that if a client stays on the phone
more than three minutes, you've lost them. They are not interested
in what you are saying. If this happens, discontinue eating and try
to end the lunch earlier than you had expected. I really don't know
why people feel an important need to be reached during a meal. If
you were in your own office having an important conversation, you
wouldn't take calls. Why is it different if you go to a
restaurant?''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Wolf, a restaurant consultant based in Manhattan agrees.
``I would much rather be in a room full of smokers than cell
jockeys,'' he said. ``If people have to use cell phones in a
restaurant, they should buy the kind that vibrate, so only they
enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is outraged by cell phone use, however. Gary
Greengrass, the owner of Barney Greengrass, takes it in stride.
``When a phone rings, you see 50 guys move toward their pockets,''
he said, amused. ``It doesn't bother me at all.'' He does concede,
however, that ``in a fine dining environment, it would be a little
more annoying.''
</P>
<P>
   And Julian Niccolini, an owner of the Four Seasons, claims to
have no problem with cell phone use. ``Most of our customers seem
to be very knowledgeable about the fact that it is bad manners to
use them at the table, especially to receive calls there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Niccolini's patrons notwithstanding, others in the restaurant
business are taking a practical approach. Steve Monkewicz, the
marketing director for the Santo Family Group, which is to open the
new Domus by the Sign of the Dove in April 2000, said the owners
are ``giving strong consideration to not allowing cell phones
during dining hours.''
</P>
<P>
   While Meyer may eventually do the same, he is giving his
customers a chance to do the right thing on their own. ``We ask
them to take their cell near the pay phone area or to go outside,''
he said. ``At Eleven Madison Park, a week or so ago, we had a scene
right out of a Steve Martin movie. A cell phone rang, and 50 heads
turned in unison and scowled at the table. I think a lot of people
are completely unaware of how they sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have two rules in my restaurants. I tolerate nothing
that is offensive to the staff and nothing that is offensive to the
guests. We're in business for everybody, not just the one guy on
his phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat, a publisher of the Zagat Surveys, said most people
surveyed do not approve of cell phones in the dining room: ``I
personally find them offensive in fine dining, at some place like
Lespinasse. But some place like Maloney &AMP; Porcelli, it almost comes
with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   A manager at Maloney &AMP; Porcelli, a raucous steakhouse known for
its oversize portions of meat, oversize space and oversize ratio of
male diners, would not identify herself when speaking about the
cell phone issue, though she did introduce another consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large majority of our customers do have them,'' she said.
``But when most people want to use their phones here, they can't.
It's so loud they have to go outside to hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
