<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVING BRAINS, COURAGE _ AND SMILES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had completed a delightful repast at the British pub-styled
Moon Under Water restaurant in St. Petersburg, Fla., and was
scanning the bill:
</P>
<P>
   One crab cake appetizer, $4.95. Correct. One sauteed shrimp
entree, $7.95. Right again. And both scrumptious.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a double-take.
</P>
<P>
   Brains, $3.97. Courage, $3.97.
</P>
<P>
   What, no $3.97 heart for the Tin Man, Toto?
</P>
<P>
   I kept staring at the slip of paper. Was someone playing a joke?
Finally, I realized that my companion had ordered a pint of John
Courage beer while I chose a Brains Traditional Welsh Ale.
</P>
<P>
   Brains and Courage. Valued equally. Can you imagine trying to
justify those purchases on an expense report?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WISE INVESTMENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If only I could get in contact with French chef Marc Meneau who,
upon learning last month that Michelin had demoted his Burgundy
restaurant L'Esperance from three to two stars, sighed, ``That's
it, I am no longer one of France's top 20 chefs. You ask yourself,
`Why me and not another?' There is no answer, so I will try to
rebuild my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding no doubt would be so much easier if Meneau knew to
invest in a few of those $3.97 pints of courage.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, life on the road does bring surprises. And laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone headed to the Caribbean island of St. Lucia? I receive
word of hundreds of hotel promotions every month _ the vast
majority not worth passing along _ but the Jalousie Hilton's newest
service is a first:
</P>
<P>
   ``Guests can now make appointments to see St. Lucia's Bush
Doctor, local resident Daniel Cherubin aka `Menziel,' who dispenses
hands-on healing and natural herbal medicine from his garden and/or
from the island's natural rain forest,'' the promotion advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicinal remedies which Daniel concocts include boiling
japanah with pea leaves to cure the common cold; making a tea of
tichimai and salt to lessen the severity of headaches; boiling
glory cedar with Epsom salts to induce a relaxed state; boiling
dried sour sop leaves with water to alleviate sleeplessness; and
combining braden and logwood leaves to encourage bloodclotting.''
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-445-8667 to make an appointment ... er, reservation,
and to inquire whether the wizardly bush doctor conjures up doses
of courage for less than $3.97.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOMETHING TO BARK ABOUT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Alexis Hotel in Seattle got my attention, too, by recently
introducing a new ``Doggie Room-Service'' menu for
``health-conscious dogs traveling with their owners.'' (Presumably,
pooches traveling alone don't qualify.)
</P>
<P>
   In celebration of National Pet Week, which continues through
Saturday, May 8, the Alexis' permanent menu features low-fat items
such as Poochie Pretzels covered with sesame seeds and soy Spud
Puppies stuffed with brown rice. The hotel already was offering a
$25 ``deluxe doggie upgrade,'' whose amenities include a morning
and afternoon walk by a member of the bell staff and a designer
doggie bed placed in the guest's room.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more: For an additional fee, guests can make
appointments with _ no, not the bush doctor _ a pet psychologist
for individual analysis. Call 800-426-7033 for details or
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Pets also were the focus of one welcomed exception to the
routine humdrum millennium ``party-of-the-century'' announcements I
receive each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pets whose owners leave them out of grand tour plans for the
millennium can party with their own kind at special resorts across
the country,'' reports the Associated Press, which continues,
``Best Friends Pets Resorts are planning a New Year's Eve howl with
party treats, catnip and gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   The party will cost $25 for dogs or cats boarded for less than a
week and is free for those staying a week or longer; for
information on locations of 30 facilities in 17 states, call
888-367-7387.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly for human eyes is a new paperback book, ``No Sleeping
On Pavement: Silly Signs and Offbeat Stuff from America's Two-Lane
Roads,'' authored by Loren Eyrich and available for $13.95 from
publisher Two-Lane Roads by calling 888-896-5263 or accessing
www.two-lane.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I'll leave you with a few signs identified in the book:
</P>
<P>
   _ Along U.S. 301 in North Carolina: ``Jody's Used Tires $6.00
And Up _ Guaranteed One Mile''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Mississippi: ``May Pop Used Tires''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Manning, S.C.: ``D&AMP;H Bar-B-Que Daily Buffet Next to
Hospital''
</P>
<P>
   _ Entering the Pennsylvania Turnpike: ``Last Bar for 1 Mile''
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Assembly of God Church in Florence, Ala.: ``Your Seat
for Eternity Smoking or Nonsmoking''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Minnesota: ``No Driving in Ditch''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Florida: ``Antiques Park in Rear''
</P>
<P>
   _ In upstate New York: ``Slow Traffic Officer Ahead''
</P>
<P>
   _ At Red Cathcart's Dream Camper in Branson, Mo.: ``This
Property Guarded By a Grouchy Old Man With a Shot Gun Three Nights
a Week. You Guess the Nights???''
</P>
<P>
   And my favorite:
</P>
<P>
   _ On the front door of Bob's One Book Bookstore (where the lone
book is authored by Bob) in Frisco, Colo.: ``PUSH. If that doesn't
work, PULL. If that doesn't work, I must be closed. Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep smiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
