<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LYRICAL REVERIE ON A WAY OF LIFE LONG GONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent PBS re-airing of the late Laurie Lee's ``Cider With
Rosie'' on ``Masterpiece Theatre'' has given me a thirst for
reading more of this once-to-a-world writer's work. Most of all, I
wish to read ``Cider With Rosie.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it isn't easy to find in the American marketplace books
by Britons who are not household names here, I had to go to England
_ Wales, rather, in one of the myriad bookstores in Hay-on-Wye _ to
chance upon another book by Laurie Lee. That was ``As I Walked Out
One Midsummer Morning,'' an assembly of autobiographical vignettes
that begins with his departure by foot from Gloucestershire, bound
for far-away London. It ends with Lee in Spain, aiding the doomed
Loyalist cause in that country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   I've searched in vain for ``Cider With Rosie,'' and I promise to
return the copy that any reader may send, or will honor any advice
for seeking and finding it wherever. However, the teledrama is said
to be entirely faithful to the original, so I may comment on Laurie
Lee's most famous book with something approximating authority.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Lee was born in 1914 in the remote Cotswold Valley of
Gloucestershire. He had five older sisters and two brothers _ one
older, one younger _ and all were martialed by an unlettered and
eccentric but endearing mother who was deserted by her priggish
husband during the Great War, when Laurie was only 4.
</P>
<P>
   At age 19 he set off for London, obtaining menial work there
prior to his Spanish adventure, and after World War II he became an
administrative participant in the recovery of Britain's
motion-picture industry. He was already a prolific poet, gaining
praise for several collections of verse issued in the 1940s and
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Lee's poetic orientation is toward nature _ flora and
fauna, not excluding the raffish humanity of his acute familiarity.
He is rather like Robert Frost, but softer, sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Only in his mid-40s did he turn to prose, for a reception that
was immediately rapturous. ``Cider With Rosie'' appeared in 1959
and was both a critical success and a commercial sensation in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Masterpiece Theatre'' offering is exemplary in all its
production values, but the emotionally affecting bonus is the voice
of the aged Laurie Lee in occasional bits of voice-over narration
lifted verbatim from his text.
</P>
<P>
   He tells us that he was ``chance witness to the end of a
thousand years' life,'' when his rustic homeland had ``white roads
rutted with hooves and cartwheels, innocent of oil and petrol.''
``Cider With Rosie'' is a muted, lyrical celebration of a way of
life that has passed forever from civilized society.
</P>
<P>
   So is this nostalgia? Is it sentimentality? It is neither,
although the emotional response is as deep and probably more
genuine. ``Cider With Rosie,'' like all of Laurie Lee's prose and
poetry, is a reverie, a living dream of time long gone by, from a
sympathetic author whose inspired memory is the equal of his
descriptive talent.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emeritus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
