r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-     05-04 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOWNED BARBECUE RESTAURANT'S PITS WILL SOON MOVE TO NEW DIGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHART _ There will be a new altar here soon, a brilliant new
shrine to one of Texas' most revered cultural treasures _ barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are under way for the ceremonial placing of the pits at
the new Kreuz Market. Kreuz (pronounced krites) has long been
considered one of the top barbecue cathedrals in the state. Texas
Monthly magazine has crowned Kreuz as being among the best, and so
have the thousands of diners from Austin, San Marcos and San
Antonio who gladly travel to this Czech-German community on U.S.
183 about 20 miles east of San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   But those accolades were for the cavernous old buildings just
south of the square. Rick Schmidt, owner of Kreuz's, must vacate
those buildings by the end of August, and he has started
construction on his new restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a groundbreaking,'' he said, ``and some people
were a little upset with me because of it. So we're going to have a
pit-placing instead. That's a lot more important to a barbecue
restaurant than the groundbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The new pits, Schmidt promises, will be exactly like the old
ones. He already has official approval from the city fire marshal
and health inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Both are needed because at Kreuz, the meat is grilled over an
open pit while the customers stand in line nearby and absorb the
white-hot heat against their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have the same kind of open-fire pits,'' Schmidt said.
``They will be identical to the ones we are using now. We'll still
put the barbecue on butcher's paper and we'll have the same
condiments.''
</P>
<P>
   That means there will still be no beans, no coleslaw. Only an
onion, tomato or avocado. There is a choice of white bread or soda
crackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business was not broken, so we don't intend to fix it,''
Schmidt said. ``We're just moving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt is losing his lease because he and his sister couldn't
agree on a new arrangement. He owns the business; she owns the
buildings. She has said she will run her own barbecue business in
the building. It will be called Smitty's Market, she said, named
after their father.
</P>
<P>
   But with all the family maneuverings, the question arises: Will
the atmosphere of Kreuz remain intact?
</P>
<P>
   It seems improbable. His place will be new; hers will be
remodeled before reopening.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to explain why the atmosphere at Kreuz is so
important. The long, dark hallway that leads to the pits is an
eerie walk. The old floors creak and the walls reek of smoke. The
pits are scorching hot and the workers have little time for
chitchat.
</P>
<P>
   They pull the meat from the fire, slice it, slap it on butcher
paper, weigh it and price it. Theirs is an assembly line designed
to move quickly and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining area, the hospital-green walls are dirty with
smoke and years of hard use. The paint is peeling in large flakes,
and in many places it is worn through to the chalky drywall.
</P>
<P>
   But a thick slice of beef on a grease-soaked sheet of brown
paper somehow transforms the drab room into a banquet hall. Big
Reds and root beer are sipped like sparkling water, and
conversations spill out among the diners like those at a family
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   It is a setting that will be hard to re-create.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: Artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-04 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-GENEROUS VISITOR NOW A NO-SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I need your help. I'm issuing an all-points bulletin for a
missing person. I've known her for years, and she's very special to
me. She's been to my home many, many times, but, unfortunately, I
don't have a picture of her.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I can't even give you a very good description because
I've never seen her face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I do know about this dear lady. One, she's very,
very fast.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking track-star, world-class-sprinter speed. And I think
she's American, but it's hard to say. My friend is very generous.
She's a bit of a night owl; she sleeps all day. She's quite the
social butterfly, and children adore her. She's petite in stature.
I guess that's why she wears high heels with those long, formal
gowns and the crystal tiara.
</P>
<P>
   She's never been married. It's hard to meet a nice guy when you
work at night. Let's see, she's very strong because she has to lift
stuff and haul it around all the time. And she's loaded. I mean big
bucks! That's all that I can tell you except that she has a most
unusual means of transportation. According to published reports,
she doesn't have a car. Instead, she has wings!
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone seen the tooth fairy?
</P>
<P>
   I need to get in touch with her. The last two times that she was
supposed to come by our house, she was a no-show.
</P>
<P>
   My son is quite upset about it. A few days ago, he came
barreling into my bedroom, clutching a little baby tooth in his
fist. ``Mom,'' he whined, ``the tooth fairy forgot to come again!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, shame on her. My husband glared at me from his pillow and
shook his head disapprovingly. Now, why is this my fault? I don't
even know how to contact this woman. She's been pretty reliable up
until recently. Almost without fail, she shows up in the middle of
the night, exchanges the tooth for money and leaves without a peep.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, I arrange all the doctor's visits, schedule the repair
people and plan the vacations. Why must I be in charge of the fairy
visits, too?
</P>
<P>
   I gave my son a reassuring hug and said, ``Maybe she left the
money in Mommy's wallet again. She does that when she's in a big
rush.''
</P>
<P>
   We checked my purse, but there was only a quarter and two
pennies in there. Dad's wallet was as barren as a desert. I called
911 and learned that the tooth fairy is at home recovering from
some minor surgery. It seems that she takes the baby teeth and
gives them to elderly people who don't have any teeth. I told you
she's nice. Well, while she was trying to deliver the teeth to some
needy grandma, she dropped the heavy bag of teeth and fractured her
big toe. Don't worry, she'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if you see her, please tell her to contact me. I had to
write my son a check! I want my $2 back.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
