<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     05-04 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, May 4, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston Chronicle
sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.    (Adds: KOSOVO-NATO;
ABORTION-TEXAS; BUSH-POLLUTION; TORNADO-DEATHS; TORNADO-SCENE;
TORNADO-WITNESSES; TORNADO-KANSAS; TORNADO-WEATHER; US-POWs; and
BKN-ROCKETS-TIMBERWOLVES.)    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin
meets with Vice President Al Gore and other U.S. officials to hear
President Clinton's offer to suspend the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia
and negotiate a peace force for Kosovo. The Senate, meanwhile,
shelves an attempt to give Clinton the authority to use ``all
necessary force'' against Yugoslavia. By GREG McDONALD and NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ In the wake of the Littleton,
Colo., massacre, key senators from both parties accuse the
entertainment industry of marketing violent films, music and video
games to children. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, says he will introduce
legislation to probe the strategies behind the marketing. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-DEMOCRATS (Washington) _ California Assembly Speaker
Antonio Villaraigosa and Senate President John Burton talk about
prospects for Vice President Al Gore, former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey and Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the key West Coast
electoral battleground. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-COMPETITION (Washington) _ Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y.,
becomes the most recent lawmaker to introduce a bill designed to
spur competition among airlines serving small- and medium-sized
cities. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A key state House committee
prepares to debate the parental notification bill that Texas Gov.
George W. Bush is promoting. Thwarted during the last legislative
session, the bill is expected to have a far greater chance this
year. It would require minor girls to tell their parents before
seeking abortions. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLLUTION (Austin, Texas)_ Texas environmentalists unveil
memos they say show Gov. George W. Bush ``colluded'' with some
companies to halt mandatory compliance with the Clean Air Act in
favor of an industry-developed voluntary program. The
environmentalists made that charge in announcing a lawsuit against
Bush. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DEATHS (Oklahoma City) _ The death toll rises and
hundreds more were injured as Kansas and Oklahoma struggle against
massive storms that hit the region Monday. By ALLAN TURNER and ERIC
BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-SCENE (Oklahoma City) _ In the Oklahoma City suburbs of
Dell City and Bridge Creek, thousands of homes are destroyed and
survivors wander the streets looking for neighbors in the aftermath
of a mammoth tornado. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-WITNESSES (Oklahoma City) _ Survivors at shelters and
hospitals tells their accounts of an evening of terror. By PATTI
MUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-KANSAS (Wichita, Kansas) _ A look at the rescue, cleanup
and damage in Kansas, where up to six people were killed by a
tornado. By PATTI REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-WEATHER (Undated) _ We explain the meteorological
phenomena behind the voracious storms that swept through Tornado
Alley on Monday, triggering winds up to 270 mph. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-POWS (Landstuhl, Germany) _ The families of two of the
released POWs hold news conferences. We also look at the latest
medical information on the three GIs who were held captive for a
month. By LISA TEACHEY and DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
has been making headway in the Democratic presidential contest
primarily because he's the unGore. But Al Gore, the real article,
is pulling ahead again, proving that if you've got two bores, the
one with the vice presidential credentials is your best bet. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS-TIMBERWOLVES (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets play
their final home game of the regular season as they host the
Minnesota Timberwolves. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
</TEXT>
