   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVEN COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   FANTASY FLIGHT: Critics have generally liked ``Pushing Tin,''
the romantic comedy about two fiercely competitive air-traffic
controllers, starring John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton. It's safe
to say most movie critics don't know diddly about guiding planes
from the heavens to terra firma. Viewers who do have a different
spin on the film, and they are not amused. (Includes 3-column color
photo from film ``Pushing Tin'' and 6-pica color photo of jet
landing at airport in heavy fog.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR WARS SOUND: When George Lucas' fourth ``Star Wars''
film debuts May 19, it won't sound at some theaters like any movie
you've ever seen and heard before. (Includes 6-pica color photo of
Yoda from ``Star Wars.'')
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN: A 2-column color graphic,
``Countdown to `Star Wars,''' outlining the number of days
remaining until `The Phantom Menace' opens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE: This spring country music artist Kenny Chesney
tossed off his hat, put on a Hawaiian shirt, headed for the
Caribbean and produced the biggest song not only of his career, but
of country's Class of '99: ``How Forever Feels,'' a danceable,
cotton-candy tune that has ruled the charts for the past month.
(Includes 6-pica color photo of Kenny Chesney.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: Ernst Lubitsch's beloved 1940 film ``The
Shop Around the Corner'' hits the Internet age in ``You've Got
Mail,'' giving director and co-writer Nora Ephron a chance to
reunite Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan in a story ideal for their charms.
Also reviewed: ``Babe: Pig in the City.'' (Includes 18-pica color
photo from ``You've Got Mail.'')
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: After splitting from the British teen-dream
group Take That (``Back for Good''), Robbie Williams set about
changing his image. Also reviewed: Eric Benet (Includes 6-pica
color photo of Robbie Williams)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMMENTARY: Do people randomly maim and murder because
they see violence in films? No, they murder because they are
murderers, predisposed psychopaths. To suggest that Hollywood is to
blame for the tragedy at Littleton, Colo., is ridiculous. (Includes
1-column color photo from film ``Natural Born Killers.'')
</P>
