<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC FIREBIRD TRANS AM: Although only 30 years old, the
Pontiac Firebird Trans Am is absolutely antediluvian. In fact, it's
wonderfully primitive, in other words, intended to appeal to
enthusiasts in their 30s and 40s who have the means to make their
old memories come alive. (Includes 3-column color photograph of
Pontiac Firebird Trans Am's exterior, 2-column color photo of
interior and 1-column detail photo of logo.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 1999 Pontiac Firebird
Trans Am.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: Cars are not playthings, and children
should be taught that at an early age. They should never be allowed
to play in or around a parked vehicle. Nor should they ever be left
alone in one. (Includes 1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   PLACE A BID: Auctioning on the Internet is one of the
fastest-growing forms of electronic commerce, on a pace to reach
$40 billion a year, according to some experts. (Includes one
3-column color illustration of an antique camera.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble are finding
that the Web, while not yet a medium for profit, is a solid place
to sell books. Now, textbook sellers are getting in on the act.
(Includes one 1-column color photo of Yahoo! Internet Life
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: Microsoft may not own the hearts and minds of
the computer world, but it doesn't need to. Its outsized battalions
are sitting there on the battlefield of your computer screen.
(Includes 1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS: Clicking back and forth among various Web sites
covering the Columbine High School shooting wasn't anybody's idea
of fun, but users desperate for information poured onto the Web
nevertheless. (Includes 1-column color photo of teen and parent
hugging in wake of Colorado school shooting.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR MAP ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   HELLO, DOLLYWOOD!: Looking for some homespun fun? Pack up the
ol' minivan and head to Dollywood, where the folks are friendly,
the humor is clean and there are plenty of opportunities to get
wet. (Includes 4-column color photo of Dolly Parton in front of
theme park, 2-column color photo of cars traveling through Pigeon
Forge.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX: How to get to Dollywood. (Includes a
3-column map of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DOLLYWOOD ATTRACTIONS: What to do to make sure you stay
jolly in Dollywood. (Includes 6 pica mug of Dolly Parton).
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Fort Wayne, Ind., is off the usual tourist
track, but history buffs and political junkies may just want to put
it on their itineraries this year. ``Lincoln From Life: As the
Artists Saw Him,'' at the Lincoln Museum brings together 46
paintings, sculptures, photographs and sketches of Honest Abe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES TWO COLOR PHOTOS, THREE B&AMP;W PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   INVENTING TARZAN: The story writer John Taliaferro tells of
Tarzan's creator in ``Tarzan Forever: The Life of Edgar Rice
Burroughs, Creator of Tarzan'' could hardly be filled with more
surprises. Though Burroughs built a career writing about a noble
apeman swinging through the African jungle, the author never set
foot in Africa. (Includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo of Edgar Rice
Burroughs, 6-pica B&AMP;W mug of author John Taliaferro and 6-pica
color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HORTON FOOTE: Intimate astonishments jump out _ like fish
breaking the surface of a still, dark lake _ from Horton Foote's
quiet, warm, dignified narrative in ``Farewell: A Memoir of a Texas
Childhood.'' (Includes 1-column B&AMP;W photo of Horton Foote.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NONFICTION PREVIEW: A preview of forthcoming nonfiction
books for the summer reading season.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Of all sports, stock-car racing is the one
whose popularity is hardest to explain. In Formula One racing, at
least there's an element of artistry, cars quick as cockroaches
darting now left, now right. But a Chevy Monte Carlo roaring 'round
and 'round an oval? Scott Huler offers an amazing look at the
sport's appeal in ``A Little Bit Sideways: One Week Inside a NASCAR
Winston Cup Race Team.'' (Includes color mug shot of columnist)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   SAY GOODBYE TO YOUR OLD FACE: In the last decade, doctors have
come up with dozens of new ways to touch up your looks. They can
zap wrinkles with lasers or peel away mottled skin with chemicals.
They can suck fat out of chins, or deposit it in lips. But when it
comes to seriously overhauling one's visage, the face lift is still
the mainstay. And, if done right, the results are a vast
improvement over the old actress-in-a-wind-tunnel look. (Includes
3-column color illustration of a face, two color photos featuring
before and after shots of a woman with a face lift.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOOK EXCERPT: The ability of children to manage anger and
handle conflict is a topic of conversation in the wake of the
school shootings in Colorado. During the next four weeks, the
SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH page will feature excerpts from a book, ``Tired of
Yelling,'' that addresses the conflict issue. This week, Part 2
deals with reflexive defensiveness _ a conditioned, rapid,
automatic response of resistance children develop that limits
communication and shuts down learning (Includes 6-pica color photo
of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS
</P>
