 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: California angle throughout.  
   
 BAY AREA FOOD PROFESSIONALS BRING HOME BEARD AWARDS  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 NEW YORK _  Bay Area food professionals won several awards Monday
night (May 3) at the Ninth Annual James Beard Foundation Awards in
New York. The awards have become the Oscars of the food world, with
awards going to chefs, restaurants, cookbook authors, wine
professionals and journalists.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Risley of Tante Marie's Cooking School and founder of Food
Runners, a food retrieval system in San Francisco, was named
Humanitarian of the Year for her years of charity work.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the mid-1980s, Food Runners now delivers up to 81/2
tons of food each week to 230 different charitable programs that
feed the hungry throughout San Francisco. More than 360 restaurant,
hotel and other foodservice donors participate.
</P>
<P>
   In the Journalism Awards, Chronicle staff writer Janet Fletcher
won the category Newspaper Writing on Spirits, Wine and Beer for
her story ``Sending Back the Bottle,'' published April 1, 1998 in
The Chronicle's Food section.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco restaurant MC2 won two awards _ for
Outstanding Restaurant Design, a project headed by Mark Cavagnero
Associates of San Francisco; and for Outstanding Restaurant
Graphics, produced by James Propp and Robert Guerin, also of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bertolli, the chef of Chez Panisse for a decade and now the
chef/owner of Oliveto in Oakland was named Best Chef in California,
beating out four other Bay Area chefs _ Nancy Oakes of Boulevard,
Traci Des Jardins of Jardiniere, Cindy Pawlcyn of Mustards and Judy
Rodgers of Zuni Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   In other national awards, Charlie Trotter of Charlie Trotter's
in Chicago was named the year's Outstanding Chef. There were no Bay
Area nominees in that category.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons in New York won the Outstanding Restaurant
award over four other restaurants, including two in San Francisco _
Masa's and Zuni Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Best New Restaurant was Babbo in New York; Bistro Jeanty in
Yountville was also a nominee. Marcus Samuelsson of Aquavit in New
York was named Rising Star Chef of the Year; Dante Boccuzzi of
Silks at the Mandarin Oriental Hotel in San Francisco was
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Prial, wine writer for the New York Times, won the
Outstanding Wine and Spirits Professional, edging out four Bay Area
nominees _ Kermit Lynch of Kermit Lynch Wine Merchants in Berkeley,
Fritz Maytag of Anchor Brewing Co. in San Francisco, Larry Stone of
Rubicon restaurant in San Francisco and Helen Turley of
Turley/Marcassin Winery in Napa.
</P>
<P>
   In the cookbook category, the Cookbook of the Year was
``Smokehouse Ham, Spoon Bread and Scuppernong Wine,'' a look at
food of the Appalachian region, by Joseph E. Dabney. Bay Area
winners include:
</P>
<P>
   Paula Wolfert for ``Mediterranean Grains and Greens'' in the
International category.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Reinhart for ``Crust and Crumb: Master Formulas for
Serious Bread Bakers'' in the Baking and Desserts category.
</P>
<P>
   In the Broadcast Media Awards, ``Jacques Peppin's Kitchen:
Encore with Claudine,'' a production of KQED-TV won in the National
Cooking Show category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1601EDT &QL; 
