<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-PASTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Marion Cunningham, best known for her revisions of 
 the Fannie Farmer cookbooks, now crusades to get more people to 
 cook at home. This column, based on her book ``Learning to Cook 
 With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf, 1999), is expected to be 
 available every two weeks from the San Francisco Chronicle via 
 New York Times News Service. It especially targets novice cooks.  
   
   
 LEARNING TO COOK: Pasta Unites Italian and Mexican Flavors  
   
   
 By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ Even if you are just a beginner, you don't have to
restrict yourself to a single cuisine or expected flavors. It's
great fun to try dishes that combine one or more traditions _ if
the dishes are built on ingredients that can make sense together
and are fairly straightforward to prepare.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago when I was visiting Southern California, I went to
a restaurant that succeeded at combining Italian and Mexican
cuisine. My past experience with fusion food is that it doesn't
always fuse. It can be difficult to get two disparate styles to
blend, but this restaurant really pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs were husband and wife, Mexican and Italian, and if
their marriage is as compatible and pleasing as their food, it must
be a great success.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that experience I've tried different pastas finished
with Mexican ingredients and found that they bring out the best of
both cuisines. So, today I'm sharing a Mexican-flavored pasta that
is simple to prepare. To carry the Mexican theme further you can
serve flour tortillas filled with crisp salad greens. Tortillas
with pasta is far from usual, but I think it's a pleasant surprise
here.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, you can prepare sauteed caramel pears the day
before if you like, but for the best flavor heat them in the syrup
just before serving, then dollop a little cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of &LR; 
 &LR; ``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie &LR; 
 &LR; Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PASTA WITH GREEN CHILES, TOMATOES &AMP; CILANTRO
</P>
<P>
   From ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon + 1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dry spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size yellow onions
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons (1/4 cup) olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 (28-ounce) can crushed Italian tomatoes (get plain tomatoes
without added flavors or ingredients)
</P>
<P>
   1 (7-ounce) can green chiles, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches cilantro (cilantro is in the produce section of the
supermarket with the fresh herbs)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the Pasta:  &LR; Put the water and 1 tablespoon salt in a
heavy-bottomed pot and place on a burner turned on high heat. When
the water boils, add the spaghetti. Using a fork, stir the pasta so
it doesn't stick to the bottom or sides of the pot. If the water
boils over, turn the heat down a little, but keep it boiling. It
usually takes about 12 to 15 minutes to cook spaghetti until it is
tender. Set a timer to start checking on doneness in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To test, fish a strand of spaghetti out of the water, run it
under cold water and take a bite. If it is tender and not firm or
hard, it is done.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the spaghetti in a colander in the sink. Don't worry about
a little leftover water. Put the spaghetti back in the pot and
cover the pot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; While the Pasta is Cooking, Prepare the Sauce:  &LR; Peel and chop
the onions into small pieces. Put the pieces into a bowl. Peel and
finely chop the garlic and put into a small bowl. Put the olive oil
in a skillet and set over medium heat. Add the chopped onion and
cook, stirring often, for about 5 minutes, until the onion is soft.
Spear a little onion with a fork and taste for softness.
</P>
<P>
   Add the garlic, tomatoes (juice and all), the green chiles,
vinegar and 1/4 teaspoon salt. Simmer for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the stems from the bunches of cilantro and discard. Chop
the leaves coarsely. Measure 1 cup of chopped cilantro and stir it
into the sauce. Taste the sauce and add more salt if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Put the drained spaghetti into a bowl, pour on the hot sauce and
mix and toss so the sauce coats all the spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 605 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 102 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 473 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SALAD IN A TORTILLA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 head iceberg or romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   One tortilla per person is usually ample, but use more if you
are serving very hearty appetites.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Use about 1 teaspoon olive oil per tortilla. Smear one side
of each tortilla with olive oil. Put the tortilla oiled-side up on
a large piece of aluminum foil. Continue to oil the remaining
tortillas and place on top of the first one. Wrap the foil over the
tortillas and place in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the remaining olive oil, the vinegar and a little
salt; stir to mix well. Wash, dry and chop enough crisp lettuce to
make 3 cups. Toss with the oil and vinegar dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Finish the salad tortillas just before sitting down to eat. Take
each warm tortilla and put some salad into it. Fold each in half so
it can be picked up and eaten with the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 200 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 20 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 13 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 138 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SAUTEED CARAMEL PEARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe, firm pears (d'Anjou are the best variety, but Bartlett
work nicely, too)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream (whipping cream)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Pears:  &LR; Cut the stem off the pears. Peel the
pears, then slice each in half lengthwise from the stem end. Cut
out the center core and blossom nubbin from each pear half.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the Caramel Sauce:  &LR; Use a skillet or a shallow pan that
is large enough to hold the pear halves in a single layer.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pan on a burner, put the butter in the pan and turn
the heat to medium. When the butter is melted, add the sugar and
stir to mix with the melted butter. Stir until the sugar dissolves.
Keep stirring. Have the water near at hand to add as soon as the
butter and sugar turn golden, which means the syrup is caramelized
and very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Stand back a little and slowly add the water. Stir to blend.
When the syrup is well mixed and smooth, put the pear halves into
the pan in a single layer. Turn the heat down to low, cover the pan
with a lid or foil. Let the pears simmer in the syrup for about 6
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lift off the lid and, using the tip of a paring knife, gently
poke a pear half in the thickest part. If it seems soft, the pears
are done; if the pear feels firm, let the fruit simmer another 2
minutes. When the pears are done, remove from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   These pears are very nice served warm, but you also can serve
them at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Put each serving of 2 pear halves into a small bowl with some of
the sauce and spoon 2 tablespoons heavy cream over each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 515 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 81 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 23 g fat (14 g saturated), 72 mg cholesterol, 109 mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOM-SFCHRON &LR;      05-04 2395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Sidebar on store-bought breakfast foods and 
 recipes follow.  
   
   
 BREAKFAST IN BED  
 Easy but elegant dishes to make Mom feel special 
 &HT;       
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  The more things change, the more they stay the
same: These days, Mom may be a lawyer or a mechanic, and instead of
chatting over the back fence while hanging out the laundry, she may
keep up with her friends via e-mail.
<P>
   But she still expects flowers, a sentimental card and a little
old-fashioned pampering on Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Special recognition of motherhood has existed in different
countries for generations. In the United States, efforts to
designate a special day for honoring mothers go back to the 1870s,
though it wasn't until 1915 that President Woodrow Wilson, having
won approval from both houses of Congress, declared the second
Sunday in May America's official Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring flowers and cards takes little effort these days _
just a trip to the supermarket. But the pampering requires a little
more thought. For this mother, nothing says pampering like
breakfast in bed.
</P>
<P>
   It can be an elaborate treat prepared by the rest of the family
while Mom sleeps in or relaxes with the Sunday paper, or it can be
as simple as a glass of fresh juice, a cup of coffee and a
croissant on a tray with a couple of daisies.
</P>
<P>
   In planning the treat, children and Dad _ or any other adult in
the household _ first need to decide what Mom really likes. No
point in serving her freshly brewed coffee if she is a morning tea
drinker. Then they should realistically assess their cooking
skills. Party plotters shouldn't try to make oeufs en cocotte if
they barely know how to fry an egg.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, Dad or a teen in the family fancies
gourmet cooking, go for it: mac &LR; e &LR; doine of fruit, huevos rancheros,
eggs Benedict, popovers filled with truffled scrambled eggs, pecan
coffee cake, currant scones _ pull out all the stops.
</P>
<P>
   We've assembled a batch of breakfast recipes from Bay Area food
professionals that straddle the line between kitchen illiteracy and
oven panache. They require some cooking, but none demand advanced
skills or lengthy preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Webber, chef/owner of Cafe Kati, contributes simple
buttermilk waffles that his father prepared every Sunday morning,
including, of course, Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   From Bette's Oceanview Diner, one of Berkeley's prime breakfast
venues, there's a mouthwatering strawberry souffle pancake that
anybody who knows how to separate eggs can tackle.
</P>
<P>
   If Mom is the sophisticated type _ and if the budget isn't tight
_ you can do an at-home version of an elegant dish served at the
Black Cat in North Beach: small blinis topped with softly scrambled
eggs and caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you fix, serve it on a pretty tray with a Champagne
flute filled with fresh-squeezed orange juice or a mimosa, along
with something hot to drink in a pretty china cup. Mom will feel
like the most spoiled woman in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and whatever you do, jot down the recipes and remember the
sources of good store-bought foods. After all, Father's Day is
practically around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SIMPLE PLEASURES DELIGHT MOM ON HER DAY &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
If you want to assemble rather than cook a Mother's Day breakfast
to be served in bed, adopt a few simple strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready a tray and a pretty napkin (preferably cloth), good
china and silverware.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever food you choose, buy the best, whether it's fresh
berries or jam, bagels or muffins. A meal as simple as coffee and
toast with marmalade can be wonderful if the toast is made with a
well-textured artisan bread, the marmalade is a thick-cut Scottish
import and the coffee is freshly brewed from just-ground premium
beans.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas for purchases and presentation:
</P>
<P>
   Freshly squeezed bottled juice _ orange, carrot, mixed berries.
Pour into a wine or champagne glass.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh strawberries. Wash; serve whole on a small plate with
brown sugar and sour cream on the side, or slice and sweeten
lightly and spoon into a dessert dish. For indulgence, add cream or
sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Chunks of melon. Presliced is just fine. Serve in a dessert
dish.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of berries, melon and seedless grapes. Add a mint
sprig to the dessert dish for eye appeal and fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Natural yogurt with a drizzle of honey. Place in a pretty glass
dish and decorate with fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh-baked bagel, plain or toasted; cream cheese and lox. A few
blades of chives on the plate are decorative and also add a subtle
onion flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh bakery muffins, Danish or scones. Buy a selection and
after Mom chooses, everyone else can dig in.
</P>
<P>
   Sliced baguette and mild, soft cheese _ brie, Camembert, fromage
blanc or fresh mozzarella. Pair fresh mozzarella with sliced
tomatoes; brie, Camembert or fromage blanc with a cluster of
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Challah or another soft bakery bread, plain or toasted, with
butter and marmalade, preserves or honey _ a selection would make
this extra-special.
</P>
<P>
   The best coffee, tea or hot chocolate you can find. If you own
an inexpensive hand milk foamers, you might even serve Mom a latte.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; STRAWBERRY SOUFFLE PANCAKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is a version of the popular souffle pancakes served at
Bette's Oceanview Diner in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Grand Marnier (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 basket strawberries, washed, hulled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler, placing a rack 4 to 5 inches below the
heating unit.
</P>
<P>
   Separate the eggs and reserve 1 of the yolks for another use.
Beat together the remaining 2 egg yolks and the half-and-half.
Slowly stir in the flour, then the sugar, salt, melted butter and
optional Grand Marnier.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg whites until they hold soft peaks. Fold the egg
whites into the batter, then fold in 1 cup of the sliced
strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease a 10-inch nonstick skillet with an ovenproof
handle, or a cast-iron skillet until almost smoking. Pour the
batter into the pan and reduce heat to medium. Cook until the
bottom is nicely browned and the batter has begun to firm up, about
5 minutes. Arrange a few berry slices over the top in a circular
pattern. Place the pan on the rack in the broiler and broil until
the top of the pancake is brown and the center is just set but
still a little soft, about 3 to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slide the pancake onto a large warmed plate and decorate with
the remaining strawberries. Dust with powdered sugar and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 290 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 24 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (7 g saturated), 339 mg cholesterol, 405 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; JARLSBERG OVEN OMELET &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This dish, adapted from ``Omelettes, Souffles &AMP; Frittatas,'' by
Lou Seibert Pappas (Chronicle Books, 1999), is ideal for youngsters
who are wary of sputtering skillets on the stove _ it cooks
entirely in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon &LR;   &LR; salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dash nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 to 11/2 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups (5 ounces) shredded Jarlsberg, Gruyere or Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 3-cup baking dish, about 6 inches in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the eggs in a large bowl until just blended. Beat in the
milk, salt, pepper, nutmeg, prosciutto and cheese. Pour into the
baking dish; drizzle melted butter over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 20 to 30 minutes, or until set and lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3 or 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 270 calories, &LR;   &LR; 20 g protein, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 20 g fat (10 g saturated), 263 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 477
mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LOBSTER SCRAMBLED EGGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This is a favorite dish at Postrio restaurant in San Francisco,
where it is served with breakfast potatoes. At home, you can use
frozen hash browns.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces cooked lobster meat
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon clarified butter, or 2 teaspoons butter + 1
teaspoon flavorless vegetable oil (see note)
</P>
<P>
   3 medium eggs, beaten lightly
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 ounces mascarpone cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pick over the lobster meat and remove any bits of shell.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the clarified butter, or butter and oil, in a 6-inch
nonstick skillet over medium heat until hot but not smoking. Add
the lobster meat and saute, stirring, until warm, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the eggs and season with salt and pepper. Scramble loosely,
stirring constantly with a wooden spoon; do not overcook.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out onto a warmed plate. Top with a heaping tablespoon of
mascarpone and sprinkle with the chives.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany with hash browns and/or toast.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Melt 1 cup butter in a small pan over very low heat,
letting it simmer slowly until the butterfat and milk solids
separate. Pour off the clear yellow fat, being careful to leave the
cloudy milk solids behind. Clarified butter will keep in a covered
jar in the refrigerator for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 470 calories, &LR;   &LR; 31 g protein, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 38 g fat (17 g saturated), 742 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 481
mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BLINIS WITH EGGS AND CAVIAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This elegant dish, by Scott Warner, is a favorite at the Black
Cat restaurant in San Francisco. Dot the top with creme fraiche and
more caviar, then sprinkle with chopped chives. In a pinch, you can
make blinis from a mix found at some specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Blinis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons white flour
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons buckwheat flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, separated
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Topping &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons caviar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon creme fraiche or sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the blinis:  &LR; Heat the milk in a small pan until bubbles
appear around the edges. Pour into a small bowl and let cool to
warm-room temperature. Add the yeast and stir until dissolved.
Whisk in the two flours, the salt and sugar. Cover with plastic
wrap and let rise in a warm place until foamy, about 11/2 hours, or
overnight in the refrigerator. The batter will be thin.
</P>
<P>
   Just before you are ready to cook the blinis, add the lightly
beaten egg yolk to the batter. Beat the egg white until soft peaks
form; fold into the batter.
</P>
<P>
   May be refrigerated at this point for up to 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a griddle or nonstick pan to medium; grease lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into the pan in 2-tablespoon-size portions. Cook
until golden brown, turning once. Remove to a warm plate and keep
warm while you prepare the topping.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; To prepare the topping:  &LR; Melt the butter in a small nonstick
skillet. Reserve about 1 teaspoon of the melted butter in a small
cup. Add the eggs to the pan and cook, stirring constantly with a
spatula, until just set. Fold in half of the caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle the reserved melted butter on the blinis and pile the
eggs on top. Garnish with creme fraiche or sour cream; top with the
remaining caviar and the chives.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 or 5 three-inch-diameter blinis; serves 1.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 589 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 39 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 37 g fat (16 g saturated), 749 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 521
mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FRENCH TOAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This classic recipe is a perennial favorite at Rick &AMP; Ann's on
Domingo Avenue in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Topping &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mixed berries: blackberries, raspberries, sliced
strawberries, blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Extra sliced strawberries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   &UR; French Toast &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 thick slices challah, cinnamon swirl or sturdy white bread
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Crush the mixed berries in a bowl. Add the sugar and lemon zest;
set aside for at least 5 minutes or up to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; For the French toast:  &LR; Whisk together the eggs, sugar,
cinnamon and salt in a shallow bowl. Add the milk, half-and-half
and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Dip the bread slices into the egg mixture, letting each soak
half a minute or so.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a nonstick skillet or a griddle. Fry the
bread slices, in 2 batches if necessary, until well browned,
turning once. Remove to warm plates.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the berry mixture over the toast, letting it drip down
the sides. Garnish each plate with the sliced strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 490 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 66 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 19 g fat (7 g saturated), 237 mg cholesterol, 249 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 6 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEBBER FAMILY WAFFLES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   These are the waffles chef/owner Kurt Webber of Cafe Kati in San
Francisco ate every Sunday as a boy growing up in Southern
California. His dad was the waffle maker.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk or regular milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   Oil for greasing waffle iron
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Separate the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, baking soda, baking powder, salt and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg yolks with the buttermilk and butter until well
blended.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the dry ingredients into the egg/milk mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg whites until stiff peaks form. Stir a small amount
of beaten egg white into the batter to lighten it, then fold in the
remainder. Do not overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a waffle iron according to manufacturer's instructions.
Grease lightly. Spoon on enough batter to nearly cover surface of
iron _ it will spread to the edges once you close the iron. Cook
until done.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with additional melted butter, whipped butter, warmed real
maple syrup, honey or fruit syrup as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6 waffles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER WAFFLE: &LR;   &LR; 155 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 18 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 6 g fat (3 g saturated), 100 mg cholesterol, 315 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
