<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related 
 businesses more than a half-century old.  
   
   
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Scopazzi's Was Built a Log at a Time  
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 BOULDER CREEK, Calif. _   For the citizens of San Francisco, the
1906 earthquake and fire were unimaginably disastrous. For others,
it created golden opportunities.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the lucky ones were loggers, in high  &LR; il,0l,0,12p,6p6
 &LR; demand for felling the trees to rebuild the city. Their fortune
was the origin of Scopazzi's, a restaurant in the Santa Cruz
Mountains where the pots of spaghetti sauce have bubbled ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the establishment, founded by A.M. Locatelli, was a
boardinghouse for loggers. The two-story building still stands, but
it's been added onto over the years _ the cozy redwood dining room
in the mid-'20s, the brightly lighted bar with large-screen TV and
a casual dining area in the '60s. That was after ownership _ and
the name of the restaurant _ had passed to the Scopazzis, an
Italian immigrant family with many ties to the Bay Area food scene.
</P>
<P>
   The senior John Scopazzi, known in the family as nono(CQ) &LR; ,
owned and operated the Boulder Creek restaurant from 1955 to 1986;
his son John is a former head of the highly regarded Hotel and
Restaurant Program at San Francisco City College.
</P>
<P>
   That John's son _ Johnny to the family _ operates Scopazzi's in
San Rafael. The restaurant used to be known as Guido's when it was
run by Johnny's uncle, Andy Scopazzi.
</P>
<P>
   The senior John's brother, Giuseppe, was a cook at original
Joe's, and his son, Joseph, was a waiter at Taddich Grill for a
quarter-century until his retirement a few years ago _ and the list
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nono'' (grandpa) John still lives in Boulder Creek and still
owns the building of the restaurant that he sold to two former
employees, chef Paul Violante and front-of-the-house man Talal
Janbay.
</P>
<P>
   Violante started working in restaurants as a schoolboy in Santa
Cruz; by the time he was 18, he had his first job as chef. His
Italian background was a perfect fit with Scopazzi's. His partner,
a one-time librarian, started as a Scopazzi's busboy 20 years ago
when he came to this country. ``I went straight from Beirut to
Boulder Creek,'' he says with a grin. He has worked in a few other
places, but ``I always come back to Boulder Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Scopazzi name, Violante and Janbay have retained
the Italian character of the restaurant. In fact, some '50s menus
displayed along with historical photos aren't much different from
today's (except for the prices) _ prosciutto with melon, chicken
cacciatore, saltimbocca, cannelloni a la Romana, scaloppine and, of
course, a full range of pasta dishes.
</P>
<P>
   One popular appetizer, marinated artichoke hearts, has been a
Scopazzi specialty for decades: ``John (Scopazzi senior) and I get
together in the garage each spring and fix them,'' says Violante,
``both for ourselves and the Scopazzi's in Marin.'' The pair puts
up about 60 gallons and 40 quart jars.
</P>
<P>
   Violante says his clientele is a mixture of locals and people
who come from ``over the hill,'' meaning Silicon Valley and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The local population swells during the summer months, which
means more customers. And when there is high fire danger and
campers aren't allowed to light fires, business also booms.
</P>
<P>
   But what about heavy rains and frequent power outages in the
rugged Santa Cruz Mountains during winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' Violante says with a laugh. ``We have a contract
with PG&AMP;E.'' So when the power goes off, not only do locals flock
to the restaurant, but there also may be as many as 50 utility
company workers chowing down on the likes of minestrone, veal
piccata and spumoni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kitchen runs on gas,'' Violante says, ``and for light, we
keep candles on the tables; it's real romantic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
