</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.   
   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Panelists Underwhelmed In a Sea of Tortillas  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Choosing flour tortillas can be a daunting task.
We found 11 different kinds, including nonfat and low-fat
varieties, at local markets.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe the tasting panelists have been spoiled by the fresh
handmade tortillas available in the Mission, because overall they
were underwhelmed by what's available at Bay area supermarkets.
They found many brands too chewy or tough or with little flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The tortillas all were wrapped in foil and heated before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   First place was split between  &UR; Trader Jose's  &LR; (12 count, 24
ounces, 79 cents at Trader Joe's) and  &UR; Whole Foods Fat Free &LR;  (6
count, 10.5 ounces, 99 cents at Whole Foods). All the panelists
commented on the dry texture of Trader Jose's, but one thought it
would probably work well with wet dishes, such as fajitas. Three
panelists liked the flavor. Three would buy it, one might buy it,
and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   None of the panelists suspected the Whole Foods Fat Free brand
was fat free (all the other low-fat and nonfat tortillas scored too
low to rate). Two panelists commented on the classic, traditional
appearance. Another liked the toasty, floury taste. Two would buy
it, one might buy it; two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Trader Jose's Truly Hand Made  &LR; (12 count,
18 ounces, $1.59 at Trader Joe's), which scored only one point
lower than the two first-place winners. Some panelists noted an
overwhelming sweet flavor; others commented on the thickness. One
thought this tortilla would hold up well as a wrap; another liked
it on its own as a snack. But one panelist picked up an off flavor
on the finish. Two would buy it, two might buy it, and one would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to the full-fat variety of  &UR; Whole Foods &LR;  (6
count, 10.5 ounces, 99 cents at Whole Foods). Two panelists liked
the toasty flavor, but two others thought it was too dry. One
panelist thought it looked and tasted more like pita than a
tortilla. One would buy it, one might buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leona's &LR;  (12 count, 32 ounces, $1.99 at Whole Foods) came in
fifth. One panelist thought it was too salty and detected buttery
notes (it is not made with butter). One panelist described it as
``not offensive, but not very good.'' Others liked the flavor. Two
would buy it, one might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions varied on  &UR; Guerrero &LR;  (12 count, 17 ounces, $1.59 at
Safeway). One panelist thought it was the best of all the kinds
tried, and another thought it had a great tender texture. But
others disliked the thinness. One would buy it, two might buy it,
and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Other tortillas that scored too low to rate were Mission,
Mission 98% Fat Free, La Tortilla Factory, La Tortilla Factory 99%
Fat Free, La Tortilla Factory Fat Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
