<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3923 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLINGGAMES-TEX     05-04 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLINGGAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SHOWS AND VIDEO GAMES TEACHING CHILDREN TO KILL, PSYCHOLOGIST
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By his own reckoning, Lt. Col. David Grossman is ``the flavor of
the day.'' ``60 Minutes'' has recently come calling, with NBC's
``Today'' show and ``Court TV'' not long behind. Print and
broadcast journalists otherwise fill up Grossman's day in 15-minute
interview chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman's message explains his new notoriety, one as timely as
it is troubling. He is a former Green Beret, West Point psychology
professor and now a widely quoted expert on how soldiers are taught
to kill. Those same methods, he says, are also being employed on
our children through the debased images of television and video
games. For children, Grossman says, the media amounts to boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``In boot camp, your head is shaved and you're taught to reject
old values and accept that the world is a dark and dangerous
place,'' says Grossman, author of the 1995 bestseller, ``On
Killing: The Psychological Cost of Learning to Kill in War and
Society.'' ``Then you're put on the rifle range and killing is made
a conditioned response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if we're troubled that we do that with 18-year-old
soldiers or a 22-year-old in the police academy, how much more
troubled should we be that we do that to children?'' Grossman says.
``The average preschooler watches 27 hours of television a week,
which is absolutely infected with violence. And they become
convinced, like the Army convinced me in boot camp, that the world
is a dark, dangerous place.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, Grossman and others contend, is an epidemic of youth
violence of which the tragedy of Littleton, Colo., is but the
latest and most horrifying example.
</P>
<P>
   The murderous rampage of teen-age gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, following so quickly after similar incidents in Arkansas,
Oregon and Kentucky, has renewed spasms of national soul-searching
and finger-pointing. Bad parenting has been one common target. But
the world has never been short of parental abuse and neglect, some
commentators say.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is the coarsening effect of television, and a
generation of increasingly realistic and sophisticated video games
often used by the military to simulate warfare. For children, those
games are common entertainment fare, games that dehumanize and
desensitize and place a premium on body counts.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, Grossman says, that witnesses to the Colorado
rampage recount the euphoria of Harris and Klebold as they went
about their grim business. Both were devotees of point-and-shoot
interactive games such as Doom.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike soldiers, Grossman says, ``We're not just teaching kids
to kill. We're teaching them to like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The link between media and youth violence is scarcely new,
Grossman says. Among several studies in the past 20 years, he cites
a 1992 report by the American Medical Association that concluded
that half of all homicides in the United States would not have
occurred but for the influence of television. The link between
media violence and violence in real life, Grossman says, is
stronger than that between cigarette smoking and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence is like the nicotine in cigarettes,'' says Grossman,
whose work was recently quoted by President Clinton. ``The reason
why the media has to pump ever more violence into us is because
we've built up a tolerance. In order to get the same high, we need
ever-higher levels. ... The television industry has gained its
market share through an addictive and toxic ingredient.''
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis psychologist David Walsh, whose 1994 book ``Selling
Out America's Children'' explored similarly deleterious effects of
media violence on children, agreed that while the media is not the
only source of the problem, it might be the most damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silver lining in Littleton, if there can be a silver
lining, is that it will send a message that we just can't insert a
very, very powerful teacher into our kid's lives, one of the most
powerful teachers they will ever have, and think they won't have an
impact,'' says Walsh, founder of the National Institute on Media
and the Family. ``We have to choose our media as carefully as we
choose our baby sitters. And yet we often turn on the television
before finding what's on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't going to throw out their televisions or their
video games,'' Walsh says. ``But they have to realize this is
having an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh says his organization is preparing a list of suggestions
for families seeking to regain control of their children's viewing
and video game habits. An example: Turn off the television during
mealtimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of this whole story is the lack of parental connection
with those kids,'' Walsh says. ``Sixty-six percent of America's
families have the television on during at least one meal a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, whose second book ``Teaching Kids to Kill'' will be
published later this year, envisions more aggressive measures. He
expects to be called as an expert in the $130 million lawsuit filed
this month against several entertainment companies, an action that
contends that violent computer games, Internet pornography and a
violent movie contributed to a 14-year-old's 1997 school-shooting
rampage in Paducah, Ky. Media companies could eventually be under
legal attack as tobacco companies are today, Grossman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feed your children death and horror as entertainment,
don't think you won't reap something terrible from that,'' Grossman
says. ``Anyone who thinks that couldn't happen is in abject denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are totally immersed in a culture of death and
warfare, not for weeks, as in boot camp, but for years. Not every
child will be turned into a mass murderer. Not every person who
smokes will get cancer. But every child will be affected by it, one
way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
