A3953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEARD-AWARDS-NYT &LR;      05-04 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARD-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEFS AND AUTHORS REAP THEIR PLAUDITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second year in a row, New York's restaurants
and chefs have captured the majority of the major national awards
bestowed by the James Beard Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Trotter, the chef and owner of Charlie Trotter's in
Chicago, was an exception, named the country's chef of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons was selected as outstanding restaurant; Babbo
was best new restaurant; Union Square Cafe was cited for the best
wine service, and Le Bernardin won the overall service award.
Marcus Samuelsson of Aquavit was selected rising star chef of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the regional awards, Lidia Bastianich of Felidia (whose
son, Joseph, is a co-owner of Babbo) was named best chef in New
York, and Melissa Kelly of the Old Chatham Sheepherding Company Inn
in Old Chatham, won as best chef in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Other national awards went to Marcel Desaulniers of the Trellis
in Williamsburg, Va., as outstanding pastry chef and to MC2 in San
Francisco for best restaurant design.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were among more than 40 presented Monday night at a
black-tie dinner at the Marriott Marquis given by the foundation,
which is named for the legendary culinarian, who died in 1985. It
was formed in 1986 and has been presenting awards since 1991. To
chef and restaurateurs at least, these are almost the Academy
Awards. About 400 food and wine professionals around the country
chose the winners.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, 28 chefs considered to be rising stars by
the foundation served dozens of dishes to the crowd of nearly
2,000. Those in ascendancy included Milos James of James at the
Mill in Johnson, Ark., preparing corn dogs, and Dante Boccuzzi of
Silks in San Francisco, who made burgundy-braised beef cheeks.
Jacques and Laurent Pourcel, the twins whose restaurant, Le Jardin
des Sens, in Montpellier, France, has three Michelin stars, also
cooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Georges: Cooking at Home With a Four-Star Chef,'' by
Jean-Georges Vongerichten with Mark Bittman (Broadway Books, $35),
was named the best book by chefs or restaurants. Bittman also won
the award for best general cookbook for his own ``How to Cook
Everything'' (Macmillan, $25).
</P>
<P>
   ``Smokehouse Ham, Spoonbread and Scuppernong Wine'' by Joseph E.
Dabney (Cumberland House Publishing, $27.95) was named cookbook of
the year. Trotter's ``Charlie Trotter's Desserts,'' with
photography by Tim Turner and Paul Eldridge (Ten Speed Press, $50),
won for food photography.
</P>
<P>
   Other cookbook winners included ``Saveur Cooks Authentic
American'' by Colman Andrews and Dorothy Kalins (Chronicle Books,
$40) and ``Mediterranean Greens and Grains'' by Paula Wolfert
(Harper Collins, $27.50). A surprise winner, perhaps not to every
cook's taste, was ``Man Eating Bugs: The Art and Science of Eating
Insects'' by Peter Menzel and Faith D'Aluisio (Ten Speed Press,
$19.95). One very specialized wine book was a winner: ``1855: A
History of the Bordeaux Classification'' by Dewey Markham Jr. (John
Wiley &AMP; Sons, $69.95).
</P>
<P>
   The James Beard Foundation was not the only group recognizing
cookbooks this spring. The International Association of Culinary
Professionals also gave Bittman's ``How to Cook Everything'' its
best general book award at its convention in Phoenix two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook of the year was ``Desserts by Pierre Herme'' by Herme
and Dorie Greenspan (Little, Brown, $35). Some other winners were
``Every Grain of Rice: A Taste of Our Chinese Childhood in
America'' by Ellen Blonder and Annabel Low (Clarkson Potter, $25)
and ``Apples'' by Frank Browning (North Point Press, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Complete listings of the winners from both organizations are
available on line at www.starchefs.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
