<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROCKY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PEAK EXPERIENCE AT ROCKY MOUNTAIN NATIONAL PARK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNTAIN NATIONAL PARK, Colo. _ One after another, each
vehicle comes to a screeching halt.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly screeching, given the pace around daunting
Medicine Bow Curve almost 12,000 feet above sea level and near the
summit of the Trail Ridge Road.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sight of three bull elks _ their majestic antlers
rising toward the heavens atop a cliff only a few yards from the
alpine roadway _ does slow traffic to an even slower crawl.
</P>
<P>
   And it represents the highlight of this visit to Rocky Mountain
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight, that is, until a couple of hours later when, upon
descent into Horseshoe Valley, a herd of bighorn sheep plods across
the road almost within breathing distance, making its daily food
pilgrimage to a lush green meadow and seemingly oblivious to dozens
of wide-eyed human onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Until the next morning beside Bear Lake where a lone mule deer
tiptoes onto a walking path, the longing expression in its eyes
saying clearly, ``Any leftover lunch in that backpack?'' It's a
notion shared by a brilliant blue Steller's jay that perches
perhaps six inches away on a rock overlooking the rippling water.
</P>
<P>
   Until evening in downtown Estes Park, just outside the park's
eastern boundary, where cowboys and cowgirls and wanna-be cowhands
gather 'round a campfire to sing and swap stories in the crisp
mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks refer to a vacation in Rocky Mountain National Park _
whose majestic vistas include 113 named peaks higher than 10,000
feet _ as traveling ``to the top of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 3.2 million annual visitors, it represents the
perfect vacation world, especially in summer when the snow-capped
mountains serve as an idyllic backdrop for outdoor adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Situated only 65 miles northwest of Denver, the nation's
10th-oldest national park _ flanked by the down-home friendliness
of Estes Park and of Grand Lake to the west _ also beckons those
whose only passion is to unwind from big-city pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Climb a mountain or spend the day languishing on a cabin porch
beside a babbling brook. Hike from dawn to dusk, from one
glacier-fed lake to another, or spin your fishing reel _ or your
chompers _ at a rainbow trout.
</P>
<P>
   This is, above all, a feast for the senses _ wondrous wildlife,
wildflower bouquets, stark alpine tundra giving way to deep spruce
forests, the lilting sounds of competing songbirds, the captivating
aroma of cinnamon rolls fresh from the oven at an Estes Park
bakery.
</P>
<P>
   But where to begin?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRAIL RIDGE ROAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 75 percent of park visitors traverse the
spectacular 40-mile Trail Ridge Road (U.S. 34), among only 11
scenic byways accorded ``All-American'' status by the Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Dating to 1932, it's the nation's highest continuous paved road,
reaching an altitude of 12,183 feet above sea level. More than 10
miles are at elevations of 11,000 feet or higher, and the road is
never lower than 8,000 feet. Because winter blizzards result in
snowdrifts as deep as 30 feet, upper stretches are usually open
only from about Memorial Day to Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   If you leave your car to explore the landscape more closely _
and chances are you will _ move slowly. The thin air can cause
dizziness. And admire those elk, and other wildlife, from a safe
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to spend much of a day here, too. Always a time-consuming
drive _ in part because the myriad visual pleasures encourage
lingering _ the Trail Ridge Road will demand even more patience
this summer when repairs reduce one short segment near Rock Cut
(elevation 12,110 feet) from two lanes to one.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeding east to west from Estes Park, choose either U.S. 34
or U.S. 36 (Beaver Meadows Road, along which the park headquarters
is located); these highways meet at Deer Ridge Junction where the
Trail Ridge Road commences. A park entrance fee of $10 per vehicle
is required, but it's valid for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Obtain and consult a complimentary map/guide upon entering, and
as you approach Hidden Valley, Rainbow Curve and the Lava Cliffs,
those monikers will take on deeper meaning. At almost every turn,
the eyes are mesmerized by another vista _ perhaps an unusual rock
formation, waterfall or silver stream. Numerous lookout points
encourage stopping.
</P>
<P>
   At an 11,716-foot elevation, signs point to the Forest Canyon
Overlook, a five-minute walk that yields panoramic views of gorges
where ice once stood 1,500 feet thick.
</P>
<P>
   Several twists and turns later, just past the highest point on
the road (near Rock Cut), a favorite stop _ for literature, snacks,
bathrooms or for surveying miles and miles of towering mountains
and verdant valleys _ is the Alpine Visitor Center located atop the
Fall River Pass. Take time to admire a vast natural amphitheater
that collects enormous amounts of snow blown by winds that can
exceed 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing toward the west and south, the 10,758-foot Milner
Pass is on the Continental Divide. The scenic road ends just north
of Grand Lake (at the park entrance for those traveling in the
opposite direction).
</P>
<P>
   All along the route, be on the alert for glimpses of elk, deer,
bighorn sheep, beaver, coyote, chipmunk and marmot. Moose, black
bear, fox, mountain lion and bobcat also live here but in small
numbers and are rarely seen.
</P>
<P>
   In September and October, more than 3,000 elk gather in meadows
for an annual mating ritual in which the bull elk _ with antlers as
wide as 5 feet _ lifts its head, stomps the ground and makes a
bugling sound that can be heard for miles.
</P>
<P>
   Westbound motorists primed for adventure can veer off the Trail
Ridge Road in its initial climb, choosing instead the 10.9-mile
gravel Old Fall River Road from Horseshoe Park to Fall River Pass.
This original park road, completed in 1920, usually opens about
July 4 and is one-way, uphill, with severe switchbacks that make
travel impractical for pulled trailers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
