</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROCKY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK RECREATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
ROCKY MOUNTAIN NATIONAL PARK, Colo.: pulled trailers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who relish a more up-close encounter with the land and
its elements, outdoor recreation opportunities abound.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 350 miles of trails, the park has particular
appeal to hikers regardless of their skill levels, endurance or
time restraints.
</P>
<P>
   A half-day trip to Bear Lake, at the eastern edge of the park,
is recommended especially for those who want to appreciate nature's
wonders without working up a sweat. A half-mile trail, with only a
20-foot elevation gain, circles the lovely lake. Many of the park's
250 bird species live near here, and it's not unusual to see deer.
One caution: The lake's elevation is 9,475 feet, so novice hikers
should drink fluids and pause frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Several longer, more arduous trails also depart from Bear Lake.
From Estes Park, take U.S. 36 west to Bear Lake Road. Continue to
the lake or, to avoid congestion, stop at the Glacier Basin parking
area and take a shuttle bus.
</P>
<P>
   At Sprague Lake, also accessed via Bear Lake Road, a half-mile
trail is completely level and ideal for travelers in wheelchairs.
The Sprague Lake Handicamp here is designed to accommodate visitors
with disabilities; usage is by reservation only with a three-night
limit (call 970-586-1242).
</P>
<P>
   A short distance away, the quarter-mile Moraine Park Nature
Trail provides a good introduction to identifying local plants and
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Also popular: short ``Tundra World'' trails from the Forest
Canyon and Rock Cut overlooks high on the Trail Ridge Road; and a
one-mile trek in the western part of the park to Never Summer
Ranch, an early 20th-century homestead and dude ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Back-country hikers planning an overnight stay must obtain a
permit ($15); call 970-586-1242 or stop at the park headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The park includes 150 lakes and 476 miles of streams, and
fishing is permitted in many areas (but never in Bear Lake). A
valid Colorado fishing license is required, and use of live bait is
prohibited except under specified conditions. Some waters are
restricted to protect recently reintroduced cutthroat trout.
</P>
<P>
   More than 260 miles of trails are open to horseback riders; a
park ranger can provide details. Guided tours on horseback are
available.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycling is popular on the Trail Ridge Road, Bear Lake Road and
Beaver Meadows Road but is not permitted on trails. Bicyclists
entering the park pay a $5 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Five roadside campgrounds fill fast in summer, so it's wise to
plan ahead. Reservations are required for camps at Moraine Park and
Glacier Basin and cost $14; call 800-365-2267.
</P>
<P>
   On summer days, park rangers schedule several nature-oriented
programs, including bird-watching excursions and lectures on birds,
biology and ecology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ESTES PARK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ute and Arapaho Indian families so appreciated a valley situated
just to the west of what is now Rocky Mountain National Park that
they made it their summer home for 10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   That tradition continues in Estes Park, most visitors' favorite
overnight base for park adventures because of the small community's
wide range of accommodations _ riverfront cabins and lodges,
condominiums, bed-and-breakfasts, small motels and the Stanley
Hotel, built in 1909 by F. O. Stanley of Stanley Steamer fame.
</P>
<P>
   The compact downtown area includes dozens of arts and crafts
shops, restaurants and ice cream parlors. Even more appealing are
well-manicured gardens, parks, playgrounds and aspen groves. And
you can never be certain when an elk or deer will meander down a
street.
</P>
<P>
   If much of the town appears new, there is good reason: In 1982,
a man-made dam burst inside the park, sending the Fall River out of
its banks and down Elkhorn Avenue, the main street, causing major
destruction. But townspeople implemented an impressive renewal
project.
</P>
<P>
   Music is an integral part of life in Estes Park. Beginning in
mid-June, campfire sing-alongs are conducted Thursday through
Saturday evenings at 7:30 in Bond Park. Weekend musical festivities
also occur in Barlow Plaza. SummerFest concerts, all free, are
scheduled at the Estes Park Center/YMCA of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Music in the Mountains, a series of chamber music concerts, is
another staple on Sunday afternoons from late June into August at
Rocky Ridge Music Center nine miles south of town. Admission is
$10.
</P>
<P>
   Annual events include the Jazz Fest &AMP; Art Walk (May 22-23),
featuring downtown jazz concerts; the Wool Market (June 19-20), the
largest natural fiber show in the country; and the Scandinavian
Festival (June 27-29), with music, food and folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors here are never far, though, from the haunting beauty
and spirit of Rocky Mountain National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when that elk blocks your path into a souvenir shop.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've proceeded from the Denver International Airport
toward (or around) town, take Interstate 25 north, then U.S. 34
west through Loveland to Estes Park and Rocky Mountain National
Park. Or approach Estes Park from the south on Colorado 7.
Traveling from the opposite direction, enter on U.S. 34 (which
becomes the Trail Ridge Road) just past Grand Lake.
</P>
<P>
   For general park information, call 970-586-1206. For Estes Park
information, call 800-443-7837. For Grand Lake information, call
800-531-1019.
</P>
<P>
   Helpful Internet sites: www.nps.gov (for park information and
maps); www.byways.org (includes the Trail Ridge Road);
www.estes-park.com and www.estesparkresort.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
