<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS GROUPS CARRYING BANNER FOR JUSTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL WEISSENSTEIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Gathered in a circle, sipping Diet Cokes and
nibbling cocktail wieners, they could be any church group or PTA.
But conversation soon turns to life in the wake of heart-rending
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Eight mothers and a father trade tips about how to ease the pain
that comes with birthdays, Christmas and the anniversary of a
child's killing. One has photographs of a daughter in a coffin.
Another can't bear to touch a slain son's homemade Christmas
ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   No one else, they say, can possibly understand.
</P>
<P>
   The twice-monthly meetings of Parents of Murdered Children's
Tarrant County chapter are part of a quiet revolution. Over the
past 20 years, services and support groups have drawn victims into
the criminal justice process, making them informed and influential
participants in prosecutions, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for groups like this, I'd probably go insane,''
said Carolyn Barker, the grandmother of 19-year-old Amy Robinson,
who was kidnapped and killed last year on her way to work at an
Arlington, Texas, grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a growing network of scholars, lawyers and civil
libertarians say that the victims movement has gone too far by
promoting legislation that robs defendants of many constitutional
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is this: (Victims) are often co-opted by either a
police or prosecutory organization,'' said Keith Hampton,
legislative chairman of the Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers
Association. ``They're now saying, `Who do we blame and how badly
can we punish them for that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Tarrant County, at least 17 victims organizations have been
established in the past 20 years. These groups focus on assisting a
wide range of victims, including battered women, children, and
relatives of slain police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Victims can tell their stories at probationers' boot camps and
court-ordered seminars for drunken drivers. They are consulted
during prosecution and reimbursed by the state for losses resulting
from crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like night and day,'' said Jim Sinclair, assistant
director of the Community Supervision and Corrections Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of these local groups stay away from politics,
groups like Justice for All based in Houston, or JFA, have evolved
into an aggressive presence in Austin. The 4,500-member
organization _ founded by Pam Lynchner, a victim of sexual assault,
six years before she died with her two daughters in the 1996 crash
of TWA Flight 800 _ has successfully fought for legislation
focusing on defendants.
</P>
<P>
   This includes laws that restrict capital murder appeals, keep
the capital clemency process closed and allow for the voluntary
surgical castration of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't half-step,'' said volunteer lobbyist Rusty Hubbarth,
a tough-talking ex-Marine who once challenged state Sen. Royce West
to a duel. ``That's what either attracts or repels people to JFA.
(Legislators) are either part of the solution or part of the
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   JFA President Dianne Clements co-founded the group with Lynchner
soon after Clements' son, Zachary, died in an accidental shooting
by a friend playing with a parent's 12-gauge shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice for All believes the lives of innocent citizens should
take precedence over the perceived rights of a guilty individual,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of overwhelming powerlessness and irreversible loss,
Clements and other victim advocates say, activism gives them a
meaningful way to channel their anger.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda O'Quin helped found the Tarrant County chapter of Parents
of Murdered Children after her son, Michael McEachern, was killed
along with teen-ager Katy Nesbit during a robbery in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel so isolated during the (judicial) process. You feel
so powerless,'' she said, adding that activism ``gives back a
little bit of control.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics, the efforts of victims groups like Justice for All
are part of a growing infringement on defendants' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has executed 67 inmates since the 1995 capital appeals
changes, far outpacing other states and drawing international
scrutiny from media and human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 20 years, we've been systematically dismantling
the portion of the Bill of Rights that protects people who have
been accused of crimes,'' said Donald Jackson, a Texas Christian
University political science professor and president of the Fort
Worth chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union. ``One stream
of that is the notion that we're more concerned about protecting
criminals than victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine states, including Texas, have passed constitutional
victims' rights amendments with little opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, victims advocates are pushing for a federal
constitutional amendment that would mandate a victim's right to
attend trials and other judicial proceedings. The proposed
amendment is in a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas and other states, defense attorneys can exclude victims
from the courtroom if they say they intend to call them to the
stand.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment could allow some victims to alter their accounts
before they are called as witnesses, said Robert P. Mosteller, a
Duke Law School professor of criminal procedure and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Because it could result in a flood of false courtroom testimony,
the amendment has raised serious concerns among legal scholars,
Mosteller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very bad idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
