<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MITCHELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS FILM FESTIVAL: ODD WINNERS AND LOSERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas' USA Film Festival emerged from its 29th annual
installment intact, but just barely. The Dallas Observer went after
the festival as if it owed it money. True, the weekly alternative
newspaper could justifiably take the festival to task for making
some odd choices, but then, that's what film festivals are about.
</P>
<P>
   It's also true that many of the festival movies had premiered on
cable, or were about to, like the opening-night premiere ``Dash and
Lilly,'' whose title was similar to the winner of last year's short
film competition _ ``lily and jim.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dash and Lilly'' wasn't a hilarious skewering of
expectations about the dating scene. Instead, it sought to push
down the veil of illusions about America's royal couple of
literature, Dashiell Hammett and Lillian Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Kathy Bates, an SMU graduate, co-star Sam Shepard
had the right hair color, if not exactly the right stuff _ he
looked as if he were loping off the range to pull burrs out of his
saddle. But his co-star's intensity _ Judy Davis only gives bad
performances in Woody Allen movies _ was a one-person exercise of a
poet's definition of purity of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Bates also got some notable actors to show up and take smaller
parts, such as David Paymer, Bebe Newirth _ who gets accolades just
for being a far less irritating Dorothy Parker than the squawking
Jennifer Jason Leigh in ``Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle'' _
and interestingly, Laurence Luckinbill, who has aged into what
looks like a brick building.
</P>
<P>
   An equally odd choice was the film selected to pay tribute to
gifted composer Elmer Bernstein, ``National Lampoon's Animal
House.'' The score for that movie is so serious that it almost
doesn't quite realize if it's in on the joke, or is the butt of
one.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Animal House'' does represent a turning point in
Bernstein's career. Director John Landis pulled Bernstein out of a
self-imposed semi-retirement to write and conduct the musical
accompaniment. And it was great to see the movie, which turned 20
last year, with a nearly full house and be reminded that its humor
still plays. (Even with the bunch that sat behind me, who weren't
old to enough to have seen its original run and had caught the
cleaned-up version ``on TNT, or somethin'.'')
</P>
<P>
   The Great Director Tribute to Arthur Penn didn't include one of
my favorites: ``The Left-Handed Gun,'' with Paul Newman as an
itchy, half-sane Billy the Kid. That film still has power, though
Penn disowned it after the studio, afraid of the adult overtones,
recut the picture. It did include Penn's crowning work, ``Bonnie
and Clyde,'' which had a troubled release in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   It basically flopped, but star and producer Warren Beatty
browbeat the studio over the course of a year into re-releasing the
picture and giving it a better send-off. (The studio, Warner Bros.,
was the same pack of oafs who didn't get ``The Left-Handed Gun.'')
The under-seen 1971 revisionist western ``Little Big Man,'' which
has aged well, was also shown, as was the failed 1975 film noir
``Night Moves,'' which has not aged so well, despite the retro
revival of runway-sized jacket lapels, leather blazers and
checkered pants.
</P>
<P>
   The Short Film Winners program was a weird row of ducks, too.
The Grand Prize winner was the beautifully realized animated
Claymation piece ``More.'' Though ``More'' deserves to win any
place it plays, it was also an Oscar nominee for Best Animated
Short this year, so any other worthy film could've served in its
place.
</P>
<P>
   I'm loath to single out film festival jury selections, since
I've served on so many in the past year that the next time I'm
asked, I think I'll claim I'm doing actual jury duty just to get
out of it. (In the interest of full disclosure, I have to admit it
was my pleasure to be on last year's USA Festival jury.)
</P>
<P>
   But there were a lot of portentous black and white films chosen,
including the winner of the experimental film category, ``My
Turn.'' (Which may have been called experimental because its
credits were so hard to read _ in fact, that must've been the only
reason, since it looked like a narrative film.)
</P>
<P>
   And also partially in black and white was a Fellini-inspired
piece _ if ``inspired'' is the word one would use on this horror _
that included a silent clown. A mime! In a short! And it still won
a prize! Imagine what the losers must've been like.
</P>
<P>
   I was told the judges sat through all the films in their
entirety, which sounded like quite an achievement. Until one of the
jurors was overheard saying they did so only because they couldn't
agree on anything. Immediately, the choice of ``Animal House''
didn't seem so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
