<SLUG> BC-SUZE-ORMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE GURU PRACTICES WHAT SHE PREACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The reigning shaman and high priestess of
personal finance may be a famous author, a television personality
and a millionaire, but she's still one of us. Yes, Suze Orman has
the common touch and a modest lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Orman, 47, drives an old BMW and lives in a small Oakland hills
home she bought when she was a waitress at the Buttercup Bakery in
Berkeley 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She loves down-home diners and cheap fast-food chains. Her
favorite meal: a diet Coke and Taco Bell tacos with hot sauce.
</P>
<P>
   She dresses casually, often wearing a black sweater, dark slacks
and simple jewelry. Her one extravagance: a $14,000 Cartier watch.
</P>
<P>
   No, her friends and colleagues insist, the down-to-earth act
isn't a marketing ploy. It's real Suze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a shtick, and it's not fake,'' said Richard Aulette,
the New York publicist for Orman. ``I've worked with a lot of
celebrities over the years, and she's very real. You won't see her
jumping into limousines.''
</P>
<P>
   Fame apparently hasn't spoiled Orman, writer of three
bestsellers, a frequent guest of Oprah Winfrey and a fund-raiser
par excellence for PBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   The working-class daughter of Russian Jewish immigrants in
Chicago, Orman trucked to California with a bunch of friends in a
Ford Econoline van in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   After toiling as a waitress, she got a job as a stockbroker at
Merrill Lynch in Oakland, where she became a top producer. Then she
jumped to Prudential Bache as a vice president, selling insurance
annuities. Orman soon opened her own office as a financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Orman's first book, ``You've Earned It, Don't
Lose It,'' sold a half-million in hard cover. Her next, ``The 9
Steps to Financial Freedom,'' sold 2 million in hard cover and
topped the New York Times bestseller list for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Orman's new book, ``The Courage to Be Rich: Creating a Life of
Material and Spiritual Abundance,'' is another blockbuster. Since
its debut seven weeks ago, it has already sold nearly 1 million
copies and risen to No. 1 on the New York Times list.
</P>
<P>
   Money gurus come and go. So what's her appeal?
</P>
<P>
   One friend, movie producer Linda Gottlieb, said Orman's success
comes in three parts: She was born with natural charisma and a
dynamic personality. She's sincere and generous _ almost to a fault
_ with her time and money. And she has tapped into the psyche of
the '90s by infusing financial topics with the yearning for
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brings an evangelical fervor to money _ she's genuinely
spiritual and she's genuinely financial,'' Gottlieb said. ``It's
totally in tune with the times. Spiritual gurus are out of touch
with the practical life, and financial gurus don't address people's
emotions and spiritual needs. Suze does both.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb, who produced ``Dirty Dancing'' and helped Orman hone
her television image, said her friend ``puts her money where her
mouth is. She really cares.''
</P>
<P>
   An altruist even when she was poor, Orman said she typically
donates 25 percent of her yearly income _ ``several million
dollars'' _ to charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the wealthy have big-time moral obligations,'' Orman
said. ``It's sad that those who make a lot of money don't give as
much as they can. They're missing out on the incredible joy behind
money, the real gift in making money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have blasted her work. Too touchy-feely, too New
Age-y, they charge. The Wall Street Journal's personal finance
columnist, Jonathan Clements, wrote: ``How awful is Ms. Orman's
(latest) book? I can think of much better ways to spend $24.95.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Forbes magazine attacked Orman for allegedly
inflating her resume and financial credentials. Among other
allegations, Forbes said Orman worked only seven years at Wall
Street firms _ not 18 years, as claimed on her PBS video.
</P>
<P>
   Orman said the PBS publicity material should have read that she
worked 18 years ``with'' financial institutions _ seven years as an
employee and 11 years as an independent financial adviser. She said
a copywriter mistakenly changed the wording.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism slides off Orman's back like water off a dolphin.
What counts is her readers and viewers, she said, and how she can
help them improve their finances and their lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
