<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SPYING05-COX     05-04 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPYING05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPY SCANDAL DARKENING CONGRESS'S VIEW OF CHINA
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration's ``strategic
partnership'' with China is threatening to fray at the seams as
Congress digests reports of the decades-long Chinese effort to
steal U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear scandal is just the main ingredient in a bitter stew
heating up on Capitol Hill. Soon the lawmakers will begin their
annual debate on China's trade status, sure to be filled with harsh
rhetoric on human rights and swelling imports.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming up are a pair of inflammatory anniversaries _ June
4, which marks 10 years since the Chinese government's massacre of
pro-democracy students at Tiananmen Square, and Oct. 1, the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the communist government.
</P>
<P>
   But for Congress members, the burgeoning allegations of spying
at U.S. nuclear weapons labs raise the greatest doubts about the
two nations' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The reports mark ``a low point of Sino-American relations''
since they were restored by President Nixon in the early 1970s,
said Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., chairman of the Pacific
subcommittee of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of a congressional
committee that is investigating the alleged thefts, has said that
China stole ``the crown jewels of our nuclear arsenal'' during the
past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the most recent spying disclosures, some Republican
leaders had come to regard China as potentially the most dangerous
U.S. adversary _ a rival increasingly capable of striking the
United States with ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the GOP leadership in Congress and most of the party's
candidates for president are calling for national security to be a
larger component of the complex U.S.-China relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate focus of the president and Congress must be the
recognition that the United States may now be at significantly
greater risk from a Chinese ballistic missile attack,'' Sen.
Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, recently wrote in The Washington Post. ``This
recognition must inform the continuing debate about the efficacy of
a strategic partnership with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Lugar's conclusions, which are hardly confined to his own
political party, are rooted in the sobering assessment lawmakers
received from government investigators last month: ``China obtained
U.S. nuclear weapons information that probably accelerated its
program to develop future nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has denied that assessment. ``It is not
the policy of China to steal so-called 'military secrets' from the
United States,'' Chinese Premier Zhu Rongui asserted during his
visit to the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
   But a 25-page report to top U.S. officials recently warned that
China ``represents an acute intelligence threat'' to the Department
of Energy, which manages the nation's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The report, disclosed Sunday by The New York Times, said China
conducts ``a full court press'' in its espionage efforts, using
``massive numbers of collectors of all kinds'' to obtain
information.
</P>
<P>
   One such collector, according to the FBI, was Wen Ho Lee, a
Taiwan-born and U.S.-educated computer scientist at the 43-acre Los
Alamos National Laboratory in the New Mexico desert, the secretive
scientific community that developed the world's first atomic bomb
in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 59, was fired after failing an FBI polygraph test in March,
just months away from a planned retirement. The FBI has had
insufficient evidence to arrest him. Through an attorney, Lee has
denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But Energy Secretary Bill Richardson confirmed last week that
reams of top secret nuclear weapons software and data from
classified computers had been found by FBI agents on an
unclassified computer used by Lee. The transfers occurred between
1983 and 1995, but accelerated in 1994 and 1995 when Los Alamos
began installing a new system designed to impede such computer
piracy, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Lee came to the FBI's attention after U.S. intelligence
officials determined in 1995 that seven years earlier, the Chinese
had acquired schematic drawings for light, miniaturized nuclear
warheads known as W-88s. Lee worked on a team developing triggers
for the W-88 warhead, America's most advanced weapon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. counterintelligence agencies took notice of Lee as early as
1982, when the FBI intercepted a telephone call the scientist
placed to a known espionage suspect who had worked at the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory in California. The Livermore
scientist had resigned amid accusations that he had provided China
with neutron bomb secrets, but was never charged.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's critics in Congress have complained that the
administration was too slow in removing a scientist believed to
have stolen U.S. nuclear warhead secrets for China. Current and
former Energy Department officials have given congressional
committees conflicting testimony about whether breaches of security
were ignored or ``minimized'' for political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., in a recent letter asking for
Senate hearings on the Los Alamos spy case, said, ``I believe this
incident is symptomatic of the casual attitude with which the
Clinton administration views issues of national security.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has conceded that the FBI may have been
slow in acting against Lee, in part because his wife, Sylvia, a
former secretary at the lab, was an ``informational asset'' for the
FBI from 1985 to 1991 when her duties involved arranging tours for
visiting Chinese delegations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked for an independent investigation headed by
former Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., to assess the administration's
handling of the Lee inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The president, reflecting the evolving political nature of a spy
case coming on the heels of allegations that his 1996 re-election
campaign received illegal campaign contributions from China, has
also noted that espionage began during the Reagan administration
and continued through the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Lee was actually promoted to a better job at the
lab in 1997 has prompted GOP presidential candidates to accuse the
president, and by extension, Vice President Al Gore, the
front-runner for the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination, of
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   One, Pat Buchanan, even called the Lee case ``the worst breach
of national security'' since the famed espionage case of Julius and
Ethel Rosenberg, who were executed in 1953 for selling nuclear
secrets to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans are trying to cool their party's rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't overreact here, and I say this directly to my
party,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb. ``You can't hold these
issues hostage to partisan games and political leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   In dealing with China, ``I think it's important to understand we
need to emphasize friendship,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla.,
chairman of the House Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The same message may be coming from the business community,
which has begun organizing to lobby Congress to loosen export
restrictions on high technology to China. The country is expected
to be the second-largest computer market in the world next year.
</P>
<P>
   A group of computer companies, including IBM, Intel, Sun
Microsystems and Unisys, have formed the Computer Coalition for
Responsible Exports in response to the congressional criticism of
China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged a balanced view in a speech to the U.S.
Institute of Peace on the eve of Zhu's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we should not look at China through rose-colored
glasses, nor should we look through a glass darkly to see an image
that distorts China's strength and ignores its complexities,'' he
said. ``We need to see China clearly _ its progress and its
problems, its system and its strains, its policies and its
perception of us, of itself, of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
