<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCHOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCHOVIES FROM THE SEA, NOT FROM THE CAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipes at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fresh tuna? Of course. And fresh sardines? They, too,
are showing up in markets and menus. Both fish no longer come just
in cans.
</P>
<P>
   Anchovies are next.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you love anchovies or hate them, that they could be
something other than dark, salty, oily little canned strips of
fish, either flat or rolled around a caper, might come as a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   When freshly scooped from the sea, anchovies are bright-eyed
silver darts that resemble small sardines. Once they have been
deboned and gutted, they can be cooked fresh, but more often, the
fillets are marinated in lemon juice, vinegar and salt and pepper
from six hours to several days. Then, they can be dressed with a
little extra-virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   The marination turns the gray flesh to an opaque white, which is
why they are called white anchovies, and they acquire a taste that
suggests pickled herring.
</P>
<P>
   Though typically a Mediterranean ingredient, white anchovies are
showing up on all sorts of menus, in a salad at the ``21'' Club and
on cold mashed potatoes at the new Red Cat in Chelsea. Michel
Nischan, the chef at Heartbeat in the W Hotel, uses white anchovies
instead of canned ones in his salade nicoise because of their
milder flavor.
</P>
<P>
   A number of chefs, including Francesco Antonucci at Remi,
Stephen Kalt of Spartina and Spazzia, Alessandro Giuntoli of
Osteria del Circo, Mario Batali of Babbo, Joey Fortunato of
Scarabee and Stefano Battistini of Fresco, buy fresh, uncured
anchovies and do their own marinating.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they usually array the silvery ribbons of fish around a
tangle of baby greens or over a mound of potato salad.
Occasionally, they lightly cook them in a pasta dish or use them to
garnish roasted fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main point is to keep the recipe simple,'' said Nicola
Marzovilla, the owner of I Trulli, where the anchovies are served
in a salad with oranges. ``When they're fresh and freshly
marinated, you don't have to do much with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anchovies are caught in the Atlantic, off the coasts of
Portugal, Spain and Morocco, and throughout the Mediterranean.
Unmarinated fresh anchovies are sometimes breaded and fried to
serve at once. At Les Halles, Jose de Meirelles marinates fried
anchovies and turns them into an escabeche. In Turkey, where they
are very popular, they are served baked in a rice pilaf.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh anchovies, seasonal in spring, are currently coming from
Agadir, Morocco, and are available in a number of fish markets.
When buying fresh anchovies to marinate, it's best to select large
ones, no more than 24 to 30 a pound. They will be meatier and
easier to clean.
</P>
<P>
   The anchovies are available at Wild Edibles, 255 Elizabeth St.
(Prince Street) for $3.95 a pound; Tan My My, 249-53 Grand St.
(Chrystie Street), $2 a pound, and Randazzo's Seafood, 2327 Arthur
Ave. (187th Street), the Bronx, $4.99 a pound. They can be ordered
from Sea Breeze, 541 Ninth Ave. (40th Street) and should be
available in a few weeks at Balducci's, 424 Avenue of the Americas
(Ninth Street).
</P>
<P>
   Fancy-food shops and fish markets sell them already marinated,
imported from Italy or from Spain, where they are called boquerones
and are a popular tapas item. At Eli's Manhattan, 1141 Third Ave.
(80th Street), marinated anchovies are $12 a pound, and at Dean &AMP;
DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street), they are $20 a pound. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I TRULLI'S WHITE ANCHOVY AND ORANGE SALAD  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 oranges
</P>
<P>
   48 marinated anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces mesclun
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced flat-leaf parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Use a sharp knife to cut peel from oranges, removing all the
white pith. Cut sections out, slicing close to membrane. On 6 salad
plates, arrange orange sections like spokes of a wheel, alternating
with anchovy fillets, leaving a space in the center of each plate.
</P>
<P>
   2. Beat lemon juice and olive oil together and season. Toss with
mesclun and put in center of each plate. Scatter parsley over
anchovies and oranges. Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SPARTINA'S ROASTED COD WITH NICOISE VINAIGRETTE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 marinated anchovy fillets, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon nicoise olives, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely slivered garlic
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sherry wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 cod fillets, each about 6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees. Mix anchovies, capers, olives,
shallot and garlic with 1/3 cup olive oil and the vinegar. Season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat remaining oil in an oven-proof skillet. Season cod with
salt and pepper, place in skillet and sear on one side until
golden, about 2 minutes. Turn and place in oven until done, about 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place a cod fillet on each of 4 plates. Spoon about 2
tablespoons of anchovy sauce on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
