<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGAR-MAGAZINE-PROFIL     05-04 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGAR-MAGAZINE-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIGARS AND WINE ARE HIS BREAD AND BUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cheap cigars stink but well-made cigars have an
elegant bouquet that people adore,'' said Marvin Shanken, as he
lighted his Havana-made Hoyo de Monterrey Double Corona, a 7
5/8-inch specimen that cost about $15. ``This is rich and spicy,
with notes of cherry and licorice.'' As the smoke billowed through
his office, he caught sight of his visitor's reaction. Abruptly, he
stubbed the thing out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cigar smokers are very sensitive about who might be
offended,'' he said, ``especially when we're smoking in a closed
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The visitor got all choked up.
</P>
<P>
   Shanken, the contrarian editor and publisher of the glossy
magazine Cigar Aficionado, is perhaps the planet's leading promoter
of the cigar and an indignant defender of that hounded,
misunderstood minority, cigar smokers. At the National Magazine
Awards ceremony last week, at which Shanken was a surprise winner
for his magazine's Web site, he remarked, ``In this era of
political correctness, we at Cigar Aficionado are humbled by this
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Humility is not often associated with Shanken, 55, who is happy
to take two fistfuls of credit for the cigar boom of the '90s.
Shanken, owner of Wine Spectator and other good taste journals, is
a canny entrepreneur. He sponsors seminars for food and wine
executives, as well as bonanza sampler events for thousands of
would-be wine and cigar connoisseurs, like the annual Big Smoke in
Manhattan on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   One could assume that this authority on what he dubs ``pieces of
the good life puzzle'' might be as sleekly elegant as the
celebrities who grace the covers of Cigar Aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   But here's Marvin: ragged beard, gimmicky suspenders, a paunch
and a Swatch watch. And a sizable, self-congratulatory grin. ``The
good life is getting better and better,'' said the man who has made
a fortune selling the idea. ``The opportunities for rewarding
yourself have never been better.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanken's background seems to contain few hints that he would
one day become an avatar of tastefulness. By his account, his
upbringing by a New Haven, Conn., jewelry and appliance store owner
and his wife, an occasional painter, was unremarkable, the cuisine
``strictly Bird's-Eye frozen chicken potpies.'' At the University
of Miami, he majored in business and graduated at the bottom of his
class. But Miami was also where he discovered cigars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were Havatampa Jewels, five for a quarter, with wooden
tips,'' he said sheepishly. ``I smoked them in a cute way, not a
serious way.''
</P>
<P>
   With an M.B.A., he started as an investment banker, specializing
in real estate. A deal with a California vineyard cinched it:
already a budding enophile, he would marry profession and passion
and become a wine journalist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he bought Wine Spectator, then a thin newspaper. He
turned it into a fat, sassy must-read that seized on complementary
life-style subjects like food and travel. In 1992, he indulged his
other great passion and published his go-for-broke toy, Cigar
Aficionado.
</P>
<P>
   The debut issue was criticized for its limited appeal, a salute
to a noxious fetish that can cause cancer. (``Well, a cigar isn't
yogurt or grapefruit,'' Shanken said.) Seven years later, Cigar
Aficionado, published every other month, claims an average
circulation of about 320,000. Its June issue on Cuba calls for
normalizing relations with the United States, with thumbs-up,
thumbs-down articles by, respectively, Senators Christopher J. Dodd
and Jesse Helms. Its Web site has had eight million hits since its
founding. Cigar bars are ubiquitous and cigar smokers have taken
their rightful if smelly place in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Among Shanken's good life rewards are a floor-to-ceiling wine
cellar in his office stocked with 200-year-old vintages as well as
a walk-in humidor in his conference room, and the smaller ones on
display, like the 1961 walnut beauty given by Milton Berle to John
F. Kennedy, which Shanken bought for $575,000. (He also bought the
apartment across the hall from his Upper East Side home, where
Hazel, his refined stockbroker wife, permits him to smoke cigars.)
</P>
<P>
   Shanken is admired and even envied by many in the publishing
world. ``His magazines say `yes' in an age of `no,''' said Dorothy
Kalins, the editor in chief of Saveur and Garden Design. Steven
Florio, the president and chief executive officer of Conde Nast
Publications, said, ``His skill, his mind is totally elegant, even
though his suit is rumpled.''
</P>
<P>
   Dining companions say Shanken is a charming raconteur who
unleashes his formidable knowledge only when he deems necessary. At
a dinner several years ago, the host, Gene Pressman of Barney's,
presented the wine, a 1961 Petrus, with an oration about its
provenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin stood up and said, `I agree this is a world-class
wine,''' recalled Carl Portale, the publisher of Elle magazine,
``but I must tell you, this is not the right kind of glass to pour
it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends who have smoked and sipped with him say Shanken
demystifies wine and cigars even as he venerates them. Phil
Guarascio, a vice president of General Motors, remembered ordering
a Fume Blanc at a fine Detroit restaurant. The wine seemed too
rich, too golden to him. ``So I asked Marvin, who has this famous
nose, to taste it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanken took a sip. Then, said Guarascio, laughing, ``Marvin
said: `I dunno. Why don't we ask for the bottle and look at the
label?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
