<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGER-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-04 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YIN AND YANG LITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last two years, there has been a growing genre of books
on food as medicine. Some tell you the health-giving properties of
familiar foods. Others encourage you to make curative tonics,
otherwise known as soups.
</P>
<P>
   They are refreshing in that they encourage readers to look at
eating as nourishing and healthful. But too many of them cross the
line from offering a sensible change of perspective to arguing that
food can transform your health. Orange and fennel salad may contain
phytochemicals and be good for you, but it isn't going to change
your life.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Simonds' latest book, ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' (Knopf,
$30), walks that line with perfect ease. Ms. Simonds, an author of
several books on Chinese cooking, takes holistic philosophies of
eating that she learned as a student in Asia and adapts them to
Western life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian holistic approach does not preach denial or impose a
rigid diet,'' she writes, ``but, rather, stresses a common-sense,
relaxed approach to eating in which balance is key.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simonds bases her claims on a philosophy that has existed
for millenniums. And yet she is careful to point out that the
recipes are ``health giving,'' not ``therapeutic.'' It is an
important distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction defines characteristics of yin and yang body
types and gives descriptions of the foods believed in Chinese
culture to correspond with each season _ cleansing foods like
lentils, barley, shiitake mushrooms and bean sprouts correspond
with the spring, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Chapters are divided fairly typically: soups, seafood,
vegetables and rice, breads and noodles. Essays at the beginning of
each introduce you to practitioners of Chinese medicine and
holistic cooking. The chapters on tong shui, or sweet soups, and
herbal tonics, are the most daring, and in a way the most
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mangoes and silver tree ears in syrup, for instance, is
unusual. Silver tree ears, a dried plant, are believed to improve
complexion; mangoes, to quench thirst and aid digestion. She also
includes tonics like lotus root cooler and a formula for hangovers
made with pueraria flowers.
</P>
<P>
   If you suspect you should begin preparing for a trip to a good
Asian herbal store, this is generally not necessary. There is a
purity about the recipes, many of which are designed to highlight
just one or two ingredients. Flavors are intense and clear.
</P>
<P>
   A chicken soup with ginger was interesting in technique and
taste. Lightly blanched chicken parts are combined with scallions,
ginger, water and rice wine, covered tightly and steamed in a water
bath. With all the aromas trapped in the pot, the soup becomes a
clear, intense broth. As you sip it, the word ``tonic'' does
actually come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   CLEAR-STEAMED CHICKEN SOUP WITH GINGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' by Nina Simonds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ hours
</P>
<P>
   1 3- to 3{-pound chicken
</P>
<P>
   1} cups rice wine, preferably Shaoxing
</P>
<P>
   10 whole scallions, ends trimmed and smashed lightly with the
flat of a knife
</P>
<P>
   10 slices fresh ginger, the size of a quarter, smashed with the
flat of a knife
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, more to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove fat from chicken. Rinse and drain. Cut chicken through
the bones into 10 to 12 pieces. In a large pot, boil 2 quarts water
and blanch chicken pieces for 1 minute. Drain, discarding water.
Rinse chicken in cold water; drain again.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. In a Dutch oven or casserole
with a lid, combine chicken pieces, rice wine, scallions, ginger
and 6 cups boiling water. Cover tightly with heavy duty aluminum
foil; then cover with lid. Place the pot in a roasting pan and fill
with 1{ inches of boiling water. Bake 2 hours, replenishing the
boiling water as needed.
</P>
<P>
   3. Skim the top of the broth to remove any impurities and fat.
Add the salt. Remove the ginger and scallions, ladle the soup and
chicken into serving bowls, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
