<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOICES-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-04 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUMAN VOICES': AUDITIONS FOR HUNGRY MUSES AT THE HOUSE OF TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Adverbs,'' Umberto Eco replied when someone asked him what
``The Name of the Rose'' was really about. More significant than
his story and characters is the drift of voice in which they eddy.
In the same way you might say that Penelope Fitzgerald's novels are
about subordinate clauses. A leading action, a statement, a mood
are yanked from below like a fishing float and dart zigzag away.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in ``Human Voices,'' Vi Simmons, employed in
wartime London, brings a fellow worker to stay in her mother's
house, from which a previous roommate had upsettingly decamped.
``Mrs. Simmons, who was generous enough not to learn from
experience, welcomed a new lodger,'' the author writes.
</P>
<P>
   Between those two subordinating commas a large character has
mushroomed. Ms. Fitzgerald writes characters dramatically, as if
they were actions. Then, beneath character and action, she writes
possibility: the world is such and such a way, but it may be other
ways as well. Mrs. Simmons' dependent clause is one of a number of
apparent asides pervading ``Human Voices'' and giving it both scope
and lilt.
</P>
<P>
   Using the gaiety and unexpected gravity of such asides, Ms.
Fitzgerald, who is past 80, has been writing fiction for only the
last 20 years. Almost by stealth her eight novels have grown
steadily in assurance and dimension, from ``The Bookshop'' and
``Offshore,'' which won the Booker Prize, to four culminating works
_ ``Innocence,'' ``The Beginning of Spring,'' ``Gate of Angels''
and ``The Blue Flower'' _ which deserved it more.
</P>
<P>
   The most European and least insular of contemporary British
novelists, and to my mind the finest, Ms. Fitzgerald works an airy
continuum between what you might figuratively call gastronomy and
eating. ``The Blue Flower,'' a seriocomic evocation of the German
Romantic movement, begins with a great quantity of laundry. Here in
``Human Voices'' notions of truth and mortality meld with a
wonderful passage about piano tuning. Ms. Fitzgerald's writing is
earthy at its most elevated and a trampoline at its most down to
earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voices,'' an early novel published in this country for the
first time, is bumpy in places. It concludes with what feels like a
sketch of an ending; romantic and dramatic but not really worked
out. Several characters assemble some promising contradictions and
paradoxes, but the writer has not figured how to put them together.
Yet in its best moments, and there are quite a few, there is
outrageous pleasure coupled with an occasional disconcerting free
fall: Ms. Fitzgerald's specialty.
</P>
<P>
   The novel takes place at the British Broadcasting Corp. during
World War II. The BBC played a signal role in holding the British
together when there seemed little else in the early years of
blitzkrieg and retreat that could have. Ms. Fitzgerald, too old to
have jettisoned reverence from her peddler's pack of contradictions
_ tenderness, a cold eye, comedy and grief _ interjects what she
believes the place stood for:
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadcasting House was in fact dedicated to the strangest
project of the war, or of any war, that is, telling the truth.
Without prompting, the BBC had decided that truth was more
important than consolation and, in the long run, would be more
effective. And yet there was no guarantee of this. Truth insures
trust, but not victory.''
</P>
<P>
   A stage setting of some dignity, then, for a comedy too pure to
have the slightest use for any. Ms. Fitzgerald's novels are never
far from the stage. (Even when they think or talk to themselves,
her characters perform.) There is a hint of Aristotelian unities in
her use of an office world as the world. If ``Voices'' is theater,
though, it is somewhere between music hall and traditional English
pantomime. What is being performed is a version of St. George and
the Dragon; here the princess rescues the dragon, and George
perishes by accident.
</P>
<P>
   The dragon first: Sam Brooks, the mission-besotted director of
recorded programming. He spends two weeks in the country for
something to be called ``Lest We Forget Our Englishry.'' To his
superiors' horror the records are nothing but squeaks and creaks.
Englishry, Sam had decided, could nowhere be more truly expressed
than by a harvest festival at a rural church. In his aural purism
this was to be registered exclusively by the sound of the Hither
Lickington church door opening and closing as parishioners trundled
in their vegetable offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Sam is the artist as middle-aged child; his fellow workers are
protective as well as dismayed, even when his oddity assumes a more
awkward aspect. An artist needs a muse, Sam figures, and he seeks a
succession of them: young female interns whose hiring he personally
supervises.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to depart as quickly as they arrive, owing to his
habit of summoning them to his office for a late sandwich, a tender
ear for his sorrows and a little hand squeezing. Not much more _
although it is a while before we are sure _ but enough to
constitute what we plainly recognize as harassment and what Ms.
Fitzgerald, interested in inner motions and history's relativities,
frames in a way that is subtler and, oddly, more rigorous.
</P>
<P>
   The novel takes in other territory: the foggily surreal office
politics of an organization that has no idea how to be one, London
in the war, the much-needed reassurance the city gets from an
ebullient American broadcaster, as well as various awkwardly
unfocused subplots and sub-characters. The conversion of Sam is its
heart, though. Human voices wake him from records and avuncular
solipsism. Contrary to the T.S. Eliot line of the title, instead of
drowning, he manages birth.
</P>
<P>
   The voices belong to two other first-rate characters. One is a
cynical and self-indulgent colleague of Sam's who does quite a bit
of good in spite of himself before coming to a near-comic end, a
suddenly ill-fated St. George. The other, Annie, is the last of the
interns.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter of a piano tuner _ the piano tuning is transcendental
and splendidly particular; the laboriousness of real music versus
the surrogate ease of Sam's records _ she withers her boss with her
highly original independence. She also falls in love but conceals
it, harsh on herself as well as him. Harshly, princess frees
dragon; for love, among other things. As storytelling, the ending
is patly contrived. Ms. Fitzgerald would come to them better. As
moral to her witty, earth-attached and buoyant fable, it works
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN VOICES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Penelope Fitzgerald  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   144 pages. Mariner Books, Houghton Mifflin. Paperback. $12. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
