<P>
   COLORADO-KOSOVO-VOTE. U.S. Sens. Ben Nighthorse Campbell and
Wayne Allard joined most of their colleagues Tuesday in rejecting a
resolution that would have given President Clinton broad powers to
intensify the war with Yugoslavia. (400 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-KOSOVO-LAWSUIT. Two GOP congressmen from Colorado have
filed a lawsuit alleging that President Clinton broke the law by
bombing Yugoslavia without Congress's approval. (500 words.) By
Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-YUGOSLAVIA-VOTE. Florida's senators voted against a
motion to kill debate on a measure calling on President Clinton to
use all means necessary to win the conflict in Yugoslavia. (300
words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-TOBACCO-GRAHAM. Sen. Bob Graham on Tuesday called on the
federal government to keep its hands off money won by the states in
settlements with tobacco companies. (Brief.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-OCS. Regional differences among senators emerged at a
hearing Tuesday on a bill to redirect federal oil and gas revenues,
which could mean $200 million a year to Louisiana. (300 words.) By
Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-ICE-STORM. The Housing and Urban Development Department on
Tuesday announced it will give Maine another $17.1 million to
offset the cost of repairing the state's utility grid after last
year's vicious ice storms, an eight-fold increase over the agency's
original grant to the state. But HUD officials said they will only
release the additional funds if Congress abandons a plan to shift
responsibility for the money to a different federal agency. If the
House approves language already passed by a Senate panel that would
give the Federal Emergency Management Agency authority over
disaster relief, Maine might lose some or most of the money HUD has
promised it. (600 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison joined a
group of senators and state officials urging Congress to take
action to protect states' settlements with the tobacco industry
before state legislatures start wrapping up their sessions (400
words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-TOBACCO. Sen. George Voinovich urged the federal government
to stay away from money won by the states in settlements with
tobacco companies.(350 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-STADIUM-BILL. The National Football League or major
league baseball would have to pay for half the construction costs
of any new stadium under a bill introduced yesterday by Sen. Arlen
Specter. (600 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-THOMPSON-TOBACCO. Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson joined
members of Congress at a press conference Tuesday advocating state
control over how states spend the tobacco settlement funds.
Wisconsin stands to get an initial $49.7 million from the
multi-state settlement agreement. Thompson has said he wants to
devote the majority of that money to health care programs, such as
Badger Care. But the American Heart Association said the federal
government needs to restrict the use of the funds so that more
money will be spent directly on smoking cessation and prevention
programs. (500 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
