<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POWS-0505-COX     05-04 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS-0505-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN POWS 'PHYSICALLY' FIT TO MEET THE PRESIDENT, WILL
UNDERGO FURTHER PSYCH EXAMS, DEBRIEFING
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0505.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ The three U.S. servicemen held for more
than a month as POWs in Yugoslavia are physically fit enough to be
released from an American military hospital, doctors said Tuesday,
in time for a scheduled meeting with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Military doctors examining the three soldiers since they were
freed from Yugoslavia on Sunday said they require no further
treatment for injuries, including broken bones, chipped teeth and
skin abrasions, they received during their capture by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The servicemen will remain in the hospital to undergo more
psychological evaluations and for further debriefing about their
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials continued to refuse to discuss the circumstances
of the ambush by Serb forces as the Americans patrolled the border
area of Yugoslavia and Macedonia on March 31 on a peacekeeping
mission. Details will be disclosed when the Army's investigation is
completed, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Monday that the
initial debriefings have reaffirmed U.S. officials' belief that the
soldiers were captured inside Macedonia. Serb authorities have
claimed the three were in Serb territory when captured.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers -- Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles;
Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.; and
Spec. Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas -- have not spoken
to reporters since they arrived at Landstuhl Regional Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the doctors and nurses who have been attending them revealed
details of their imprisonment during a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The soldiers were forced to wear hoods and were constantly
shackled in the first days following their capture, and later each
was held in solitary confinement in a windowless cell. The result
was disorientation; all told the doctors they lost track of night
and day, and how long they had been held.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Their injuries, chipped teeth, bruises and abrasions to all
and a broken nose suffered by Stone and two broken ribs for
Ramirez, were sustained during their capture or in the first week
of their imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  They were fed a sparse diet mainly of soups and bread. All
lost weight, including Stone who dropped 14 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gonzalez received intravenous fluids from the Yugoslavian
authorities during his incarceration. He told doctors he did not
know what was in the IV drip or why it had been given to him,
except that he had been feeling weak at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers and their families will meet with Clinton during
the president's tour Wednesday and Thursday of two U.S. air bases
and a Kosovo refugee center in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the 1st Infantry Division, in which the
soldiers serve, is scheduled to present them with commendations in
a ceremony Thursday for their bravery, and endurance during the
capture and incarceration. The Army trains soldiers to deal with
the potential of capture during wartime.
</P>
<P>
   The course, called ``Survival, Evasion, Resistance and Escape,''
educates troops on techniques to avoid capture, or withstand long
and potentially brutal incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have preferred a better outcome of the 'resistance'
part,'' said Col. Michael Sullivan, spokesman for U.S. Army in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The families of Stone and Ramirez met with reporters Wednesday
for the first time since being reunited with the soldiers in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They said the families and the soldiers were both elated by the
reunion and emotionally exhausted after the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's family said he told them that his survival and safe
release from captivity was a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Chris is a believer in miracles now. I think he
realizes that life is short and there are things you need to
straighten out,'' said Stone's sister Dawn Relliford.
</P>
<P>
   Both families said that little was spoken during their initial
reunion on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't even explain the feelings that you have,'' said
Stone's second sister, Deanna. ``You don't even want to talk. You
want to see them and give them a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Ramirez said she hugged her son so hard that ``I had to
let him go so he could breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
