<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4069 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RANDY-NEWMAN05-COX     05-04 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDY-NEWMAN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newman tackles the bite of real life
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a decade sequestered in a production studio scoring films
_ and racking up an astonishing three Oscar nominations in 1999 for
``Pleasantville,'' ``A Bug's Life'' and ``Babe: Pig in the City'' _
singer/songwriter Randy Newman is back at the piano singing about
the absurdities and ironies of real life.
</P>
<P>
   His new CD, ``Bad Love,'' due June 1, is a quirky collection of
classic Newman vignettes about people and the peculiarities of
living in the '90s. It's the same unmistakable New Orleans piano
sound as classic albums such as ``Sail Away'' or ``Rednecks,'' from
sweet love tunes to biting musical commentaries.
</P>
<P>
   On his first non-film CD since 1988, Newman is a crotchety,
graying baby boomer who sings about watching too much TV, rich
older men married to sweet young thangs and aging rock stars who
won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   The new CD comes on the heels of the release of Newman's boxed
set, ``Guilty: 30 Years of Randy Newman,'' which spans his entire
career, including songs he wrote for others (``Mama Told Me Not to
Come,'' ``You Can Leave Your Hat On'') and his own hits (``Short
People,'' ``I Love L.A.'').
</P>
<P>
   His appearance tonight at Variety Playhouse is one of only 15
dates Newman is doing in the United States this year. We caught up
with him at his home in (where else) Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the new album, you have a song called ``I'm Dead'' which
is a pretty nasty comment on old rock stars. What, or who, inspired
that tune?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I'm Dead'' wasn't really about one person, it's more
generational. There's a mass of us over 50 that are still hacking
away out there. People who said 20 years ago they would never do
this when they got old are refusing to leave the stage. There's
this giant, demographic glob of baby boomers who, until we pass on,
are going to gum up the works for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have a very distinct accent when you sing, kind of a New
Orleans dialect, yet you don't have it when you speak. Is the
singing voice an affectation, or did it come naturally?
</P>
<P>
   A: My mother was from New Orleans, and she never lost her
accent. My brother has none. I didn't really affect it. I've
questioned it in my mind many a time, but I think when I first sang
it sounded better to me, and so that's what I did. I don't know if
somebody like Elton John affects his sound, or if it just sounded
better that way. I loved Ray Charles, Fats Domino, so that may have
had something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You always weave social commentary into your songs. What's
different about these new ones than songs you wrote 20 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think there's the hope now that there was that things
might change, like with racism. I'm sure some places in Atlanta
have changed, but I bet there's probably still a North side and a
South side. There was attention focused in the '60s. It's still an
enormous problem, but not much attention is being paid to it
anymore. Also, I was writing some of these songs from the
standpoint of an idea that appeals enormously to me, which is
someone being a CEO of the company, he has everything in the world,
and things can still rise up and smack you _ your kid's not doing
well in school, you have to listen to some 20-something blather on
about their job. You're never free of something reaching up out of
life and grabbing you by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Newman
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight(Wednesday May 5). $25. Variety Playhouse, 1099 Euclid
Ave. Ticketmaster, 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
