a 2-column color photo of Trans Am's interior and a 1-column detail
photo of a logo.
</P>
<P>
   w/AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 1999 Pontiac Firebird
Trans Am.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ Cars are not playthings, and children should be
taught that at an early age. They should never be allowed to play
in or around a parked vehicle. Nor should they ever be left alone
in one. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column
color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   NET-HEALTHCARE _ ADAM Internet Health has landed several deals
with big-name portals, agreements that the company believes will
propel it to the front of the pack in Net healthcare information.
The deals, including one with NetCenter, compare favorably to
others engineered by WebMD, said ADAM founder and chairman Robert
Cramer. ``I think this is another step toward making Adam.com the
leader in consumer health information on the Internet.'' (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COX-CHECKS _ ATLANTA _ In a first for the cable TV industry, Cox
Communications will use the electronic banking services of
Atlanta-based CheckFree to let its customers receive monthly
statements and pay their bills via computer. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GM _ DAYTON, Ohio _ GM and AM General, a maker of military
vehicles, are close to signing a deal for AM to buy GM's 6.5 liter
diesel engine business. GM will not sell the engine plant in
Moraine, which will force AM to find or build a new plant in this
area and eventually staff it with up to 150 workers. (Wagner,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-WEBSHOPPING _ CNN introduces shopping/commerce component to
its cnn.com Web site. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-ASSISTANT _ BellSouth Mobility will become the first
wireless phone company to offer a ``virtual assistant'' service
that lets the user via phone receive all voice and e-mail messages
and respond to them The service, developed by California-based
General Magic, will be offered in a trial now and then trotted out
to anyone in June. The system responds to the spoken word but does
not require programming to adapt to the user's voice. It lets the
user send faxes and emails, update appointment calendars, and it
can read current stock quotes. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-BANK _ ATLANTA _ A look at online banking, including what
one Georgia bank, Synovus, is doing to compete. Includes
information from a study ranking the top 20 online banks.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-FINE _ Peter Tostos, who ran a number of shaky companies
out of a storefront in Madison, was fined more than $1 million by
the SEC for stock fraud. The fine was never collected and Tostos
has started several firms since. It isn't unusual for such fines to
go uncollected. More than half of such penalties are never
executed. Why? (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOMEBUILDER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Doyle Wilson, one of Austin's
largest homebuilders and one of the only privately owned still in
the top 10, has filed Chapter 11 bankrtupcy protection. (Golz,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   DELL-EXPANSION _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A proposal to give Dell
Computer Corp. local sales tax dollars it would generate if the
company locates in Nashville has been yanked off the table. But the
state is still negotiating with Dell to build a facility in
southeast Davidson County, creating at least 3,000 jobs over five
years. Dell gets a portion of every dollar that the city where it's
headquartered, Round Rock, Texas, receives from the sale of the
company's computers in Texas. The company wanted the same kind of
deal to expand in Tennessee, but state officials said it would be
illegal. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Someday soon, the gigantic, hallowed Fidelity
Magellan fund may not be the biggest mutual fund in the United
States. The amounts involved are staggering: Magellan, $90.77
billion; Vanguard Index 500, $82.52 billion. There are other
surprises. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
