<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-DEMOCRATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIF. ASSEMBLY SPEAKER SAYS GORE HAS TOUGH FIGHT AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic leader of California's lower house
predicted Tuesday that Vice President Al Gore will win heavy
support in the state, but he said competition from former Sen. Bill
Bradley will make him ``work hard'' for the Democratic nomination
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   California Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa told reporters
in a luncheon meeting here, ``I believe Al Gore is going to be the
Democratic nominee and ... the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in his forecast for Gore, Villaraigosa said
Bradley's presidential bid ``is going to make you work hard. You're
going to have a race ... It's a good thing to have a primary
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley challenge will make Gore a better candidate in the
general election, Villaraigosa said, adding. ``When you go through
fire, it makes you tougher.'' He predicted that a Gore-Bradley race
would give the vice president ``an opportunity to show his vision,
to show he has a breadth of support ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa, 46, Assembly speaker since February 1998, is
expected to endorse Gore along with most of the Assembly's
47-member Democratic Caucus in a meeting here Wednesday with the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements will come at a critical time for Gore, who has
had trouble building enthusiasm among Democrats who say he is too
bland a candidate to beat the leading GOP contender, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bradley has been energized by Gore's poor
showing in polls pitting him against Bush. Since February many
polls have showed Gore 10 to 21 percentage points behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But a CNN/Gallup/USA Today poll Tuesday showed Gore widening the
gap with Bradley and narrowing it with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey Gore beat Bradley 66 percent to 23 percent among
respondents. The same poll on April 14 showed Gore with 54 percent
and Bradley with 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the poll showed Bush ahead of Gore 56 percent to 40
percent, a 16-point margin. On April 14, Bush led Gore by 21 points
_ 59 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With its massive 54 electoral votes, California is the prize of
the West. Political experts say no Democrat can hope to win the
White House without carrying the state.
</P>
<P>
   Villaraigosa dismissed the polls as insignificant this far in
advance of Election Day, citing President George Bush's high
standing in 1991 after the Persian Gulf War and his ultimate loss
to then Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, (Gore is) down in the polls right now, but I don't think
it's any indication of where he's going to end up,'' Villaraigosa
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly speaker acknowledged that Bush is a ``strong
nominee,'' especially because of his strength among Hispanic voters
_ a key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are ``excited about a George Bush because they think
he can cross over (and) penetrate the Latino vote,'' he said,
pointing out that it is critical not only in California and Texas,
but in other key states such as New York, Illinois, Florida and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Bush may prove vulnerable among Hispanics because
of his undefined views on divisive civil rights issues such as
Proposition 209, the 1996 ballot California ballot initiative that
banned affirmative action in state and local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's initially going to look attractive (to
Hispanics), but when we start getting beyond the surface, it's
going to be more difficult. (But) there's no question he's going to
be a formidable candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
