<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 5, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another bevy of severe thunderstorms will develop across the
region from the lower Ohio Valley to the central Gulf Coast states
on Wednesday as the weather pattern across the Middle West remains
rather volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Very humid air streaming inland from the Gulf of Mexico
initially will be prevented from rising high into the atmosphere by
a lid of warm air near 5,000 feet, allowing a powder-keg of energy
to build during the day. As a cold front and trailing jet stream
disturbance arrives Wednesday afternoon, tropical air will
explosively break through the lid, setting the stage for potent
thunderstorms to erupt across southern portions of Illinois,
Indiana and Kentucky southward to Mississippi, Alabama and the
western panhandle of Florida. Some of these storms will become
severe, spawning damaging winds, large hail and tornadoes. But, as
with most outbreaks of severe weather, the areas affected will tend
to be rather small and isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop over the upper Middle
West across the upper Mississippi Valley and western Great Lakes as
a surface low pressure draws moist air northward. Given the
sluggishness of the low, recurrent rains could exceed two inches in
parts of Minnesota, the Dakotas, Wisconsin, Iowa and northern
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds, patchy rain and drizzle will continue to affect
parts of the northern Middle Atlantic and New England Seaboards as
a floundering low pressure system remains trapped off the coast by
a blocking high pressure system over eastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Maxi Tornado
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary damage survey in the aftermath of the powerful
tornado that swept through Oklahoma on Tuesday indicated that the
twister ranked RF4S on the Fujita Scale, with winds estimated
between 207 and 260 mph. Such ``maxi'' tornadoes, which include the
most powerful F5 twisters, account for only 1 to 2 percent of the
nearly 1,000 tornadoes that occur each year in the United States.
Thus, maxi tornadoes are not common. Maxi tornadoes that strike
highly populated areas are even less common. Yet they account for
approximately two-thirds of all twister-related fatalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
