<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING FRESH GARLIC 
FLOURLESS CHOCOLATE CAKES 
EGG SAFETY 
SODA FOUNTAIN FLAVOR 
MONOSODIUM GLUTAMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the final graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do you choose fresh garlic?
</P>
<P>
   A. Look for a firm, plump bulb that has no obviously shriveled
or soft cloves and is not sprouting any pale yellow or green shoots
from the center. Those are signs of age and bitterness. The papery
skin covering the bulb should be dry and flaky. Avoid any heads
with dark or blackish spots, which could indicate interior mold.
Fat cloves are easier to peel and handle.
</P>
<P>
   Try not to buy garlic from a market that keeps it refrigerated
in the produce section. Moisture from the refrigerator can
encourage sprouting. If whole, unbroken heads of garlic are stored
in a cool, dry, dark place, they should keep about two months
without drying out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rise, and Fall, of Cakes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I cannot eat wheat and would like to make a flourless
chocolate cake, but I cannot get the soft, molten centers and caky
exteriors of the ones I get in restaurants. Mine are more like a
candy bar. My cakes are regular size; the restaurant cakes are
baked in individual portions. Is that the secret?
</P>
<P>
   A: Molten chocolate cakes can be baked in any size pan; the
secret lies in the recipe. For a spongy, airy exterior, a cake
needs to have structure to support its rise. Cakes and tortes that
don't rise will end up with a fudgey, candylike texture (which is
what many recipes aim for).
</P>
<P>
   The structure of flourless chocolate cakes comes from eggs
(either whole or just whites) that have been beaten into a
voluminous froth. The air incorporated into the eggs while beating
expands in the oven, just like a souffle. In fact, many of the
molten chocolate cake recipes popular these days are souffle
variations, enriched with butter and often stabilized with a touch
of ground nuts or cornstarch.
</P>
<P>
   Making Raw Eggs Safe
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a recipe for lemon icebox pie that calls for raw egg
yolks. Is there a way to raise the temperature of eggs enough to
make them safe without actually cooking them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Shirley Corriher gives directions in her book, ``Cookwise''
(William Morrow, 1997). She writes that the temperature at which
egg yolks are considered safe is 160 Fahrenheit, but holding them
at a somewhat lower temperature for a longer time is just as
effective. Keep them at 140 Fahrenheit (about the warmth of hot tap
water) for three and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests heating every two yolks in a small pan over very
low heat with a quarter cup of liquid from the recipe plus a half
teaspoon sugar. Stir constantly and scrape the bottom of the pan
with a spatula. At the first sign of thickening, remove the pan
from the heat and continue to stir as you immerse it in a large
bowl of cold water to stop the cooking. You can now use these yolks
instead of raw ones.
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Flavor Without Vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is the vanilla syrup that is used in soda fountains made?
I have added vanilla extract to sugar syrup, but it doesn't taste
the same.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's because vanilla-flavored soda fountain syrup doesn't
actually contain any vanilla extract. It is made from vanillin, an
artificial flavoring that tastes like vanilla, plus some other
artificial flavors that contribute to its characteristic taste. You
can buy vanilla-flavored syrups in most supermarkets. Fox's U-Bet
is one brand, 16 ounces for about $1.99.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to make something close, try using a mix of
imitation vanilla extract, corn syrup, sugar syrup and citric acid
or a touch of lemon juice. These are the main ingredients listed on
the label (other than the preservatives).
</P>
<P>
   The Use of MSG
</P>
<P>
   Q: When was MSG first used in food preparation?
</P>
<P>
   A: Monosodium glutamate, or MSG, was developed by Japanese
scientists in the 1920s. It is derived from glutamic acid, a
naturally occurring amino acid found in some types of seaweed.
Oddly, MSG is flavorless on its own but has the ability to enhance
the flavor of savory foods. On the downside, MSG can cause adverse
reactions in some people, such as headaches, dizziness, flushing
and burning. It is used in Japanese and Chinese cuisines and is
sometimes added to packaged spice mixes, soups and snack foods. If
MSG does make you ill, read all food labels carefully.
</P>
<P>
   _ MELISSA CLARK
</P>
<P>
   FLOURLESS CHOCOLATE SOUFFLE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted From Scott Bryan at Veritas
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (1 1/2 sticks) unsalted butter, plus extra for greasing
pan
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces bittersweet chocolate, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 extra-large eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar for garnish, optional
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream for serving, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Adjust oven rack to center position and heat oven to 375
degrees. Butter a 9-inch round springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small saucepan, melt chocolate and butter over low heat.
Transfer to a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   3. Using an electric mixer set on medium speed, beat egg whites
until very foamy. Continue beating and gradually add 1/4 cup sugar.
Beat on high speed until whites are glossy and form stiff peaks.
Transfer to a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   4. In the same mixer bowl (no need to wash it), combine egg
yolks, remaining 1/2 cup sugar and salt and beat on high speed
until mixture triples in volume and is light in color, about 5
minutes. Scrape egg yolk mixture and then whites over melted
chocolate mixture, then sift cornstarch on top. Gently and
carefully fold egg mixtures into chocolate mixture until batter is
smooth and uniform in color, but not deflated. Pour batter into
prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bake until cake has puffed, has a thin crust on top and
jiggles slightly at the center when shaken very gently, about 30
minutes. Run a paring knife around inside edges of the pan, then
let the cake rest 5 minutes before removing pan sides. Garnish with
confectioners' sugar and serve immediately with optional whipped
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food can be sent to Food Chain, the Dining
section, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036-3959, or by e-mail to: dining(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
