<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERGER-RACE-ART-2TAKE     05-04 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERGER-RACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAURICE BERGER: FACING DOWN HIS COLOR AS A PATH TO PRIVILEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Baldwin said that there was no hope for anyone
who considered himself white. By that measure, Maurice Berger
figures he has a chance at salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's skin is white, but increasingly he views race as a
social construct, a thing apart from all the more nuanced ways he
defines himself. He loves to cook, take long walks and spend time
with his companion of many years. When he looks back on his own
history, he can virtually smell the Sabbath candles and feel the
way his heart raced as he learned how to shape words into thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Berger is best known as the author of ``White Lies:
Race and the Myths of Whiteness'' (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux, 1999), a
book that is being widely read in circles pondering issues of race
and culture. The book's admirers say it stands out from the many
books about race because it is a detailed, intimate look by a white
man into his racial identity and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Berger writes about his mentally ill father, who admired blacks
from afar, his dark-skinned Sephardic Jewish mother, who loathed
them, and the mostly stunted dreams of the black friends from the
New York housing project where he grew up. He acknowledges how his
own racism came to the fore when he had to compete with a black
classmate in college and his repugnance over his father's
flirtation with a black woman.
</P>
<P>
   He also writes about his growing awareness of how whites are
personally limited by embracing racial myths in everything from
beauty to intelligence but continue to enforce those myths among
themselves to preserve a sense of superiority and the privileges of
whiteness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glasses we have on are the glasses of race,'' Berger said
recently, using his usual soft tone of voice. ``If we, as white
people, start taking stock of how we're introduced to race, to
black and white, we can see how whiteness is privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, an art historian by training, subverts what he sees as
the prevailing orthodoxy of whiteness that James Baldwin denounced
in the 1960s. Baldwin, best known for such essay collections as
``Notes of a Native Son'' and ``The Fire Next Time,'' as well as
his novels, saw people from all countries, religions and
ethnicities become simply ``white''' when they came to the United
States. In shedding the particulars of their histories, Baldwin
said, they lose some of their humanity, a tradeoff for inclusion in
a group that exists only to exercise privilege.
</P>
<P>
   It is a delicate and sad enterprise, this race business, Berger
said the other day in his Upper West Side Manhattan apartment. Race
is such a big, complex, painful topic that no one knows where to
start. Berger is suggesting that they start with their own
histories.
</P>
<P>
   He has, to mostly critical acclaim. Laurie Adlerstein said in
The New York Times Book Review that ``White Lies'' was ``often
startlingly original.'' David Roediger, a leading scholar in the
relatively new field of white studies, said that Berger's book
``brilliantly charts'' the process of racial awareness and
contributed to a meager body of work about the origins of
anti-racism among whites.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said he had received an avalanche of mail after the
book's publication that bore testament to how provocative and
intimate a subject race remains. People wrote him about their
experiences with other groups of people and about their own racial
prejudice, isolation or fear.
</P>
<P>
   `'I've gotten everything from hugs to hate mail in the last
three months,'' said Berger, a tall, thin man with piercing eyes
and a gentle manner. He is 42 and speaks in long, thoughtful
sentences. He wears a gold band on his wedding finger, a symbol of
his commitment to Marvin Heiferman, a historian of photography and
a writer on American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point that keeps coming up is how difficult it is to get
people to talk about these issues,'' said Berger, who has a
doctorate in art history but sometimes refers to himself as ``a
little project boy.'' He is a senior fellow at the Vera List Center
for Art and Politics at the New School for Social Research and has
written and edited a number of books and articles on the arts,
legal studies and race.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney Museum of American Art and the Jewish Museum in
Manhattan and the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington are among
the places where Berger has curated exhibitions, some race-related.
Current projects include part of ``The American Century''
exhibition at the Whitney and an Adrian Piper retrospective opening
at the University of Maryland in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``White Lies'' represents a curated collection of
racial tales. The book is a compilation of personal vignettes from
15 people and excerpts from literature about race _ everything from
Baldwin to ``The Bell Curve'' _ woven around Berger's recollections
of growing up poor and Orthodox Jewish in a predominantly black and
Hispanic housing project on Manhattan's Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the book are also on the Internet
(http://fsbassociates.com/fsg/whitelies.htm). Berger, who is also
talking to an independent producer about a documentary based on
``White Lies,'' said he was mostly meeting with small groups of
people to allow more intimate discussion than a traditional
promotional tour would allow.
</P>
<P>
   Berger does not believe that Americans are anywhere near ready
for a national conversation about race. He has found that most
whites believe that racial problems ended with the passage of civil
rights laws, while he himself sees a more subtle, more insidious
racism afoot, punctuated by incidents of racial violence or
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialogue about race gets played out in the courtroom, on
cable TV and in talk shows,'' said Berger. ``When you have a trial
like O.J. it's a catalyst for race talk or Louima or Diallo _ all
these tragedies. The media as a whole or the courtroom as a whole
is not a great place for Americans to talk about race. The best
space for discussion of race right now is the dinner table,
possibly the classroom or online, where there is the possibility of
anonymity, and mostly in our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It took Berger three years of sometimes painful memories to
write his book. He said he was able to write honestly about both
his parents because they are now dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``White Lies'' opens with the assassination of the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. Berger's father wept, the first time his
12-year-old son had seen him cry. He called the assassination a
nightmare. His mother said King was a troublemaker who deserved to
die. His mother's harangue made racism real for him in a way it had
never been.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of his mother, who believed that her dark coloring
had killed her career as a singer and an actress, adorns a wall in
his apartment. Ruth Secunda Berger was a woman who applied layers
of makeup to make her skin whiter and pomades to make her kinky
hair straighter. She was told again and again by casting agents
that her looks were too foreign, too exotic, and she was the victim
of open anti-Semitism. In his book, Berger says his mother was an
example of the irrationality of race and the mutability of racial
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walk around always with a mythic sense of who we are,''
said Berger, serving tea and madeleines in his airy living room
overlooking West End Avenue. ``There are myths about the purity of
whiteness, as seen in the conversation about Thomas Jefferson and
Sally Hemings. There is the myth of the superiority of white
intelligence, as reflected in the continuing IQ debate. There is
the myth of the danger and chaos associated with blackness, which
is demonstrated by the way people react when a black family moves
next door.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of looking at white culture and white identity started
in the academy about a decade ago and become known as whiteness
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia J. Williams, a professor of law at Columbia University
and the author of a number of books on race and culture, said that
Berger's book has ``gone beyond whiteness studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking at whiteness and saying, how is it related to my
immigration status, being Jewish, to the hair fetish?'' Ms.
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks through to a whole host of conversations. I think
the value on the one hand is that whiteness is unmarked. People who
are white don't think of themselves as having a race,'' Ms.
Williams said. ``Discussions of whiteness reveal racism for all the
compounded prejudices contained in it and makes it comprehensible
by aligning all the other prejudices. It allows other people to see
themselves as products of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said he had been asked why, as a white person, he cared
so much about race. It is a question he has asked and answered
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, my passion was a result of growing up with black
people and seeing the myths I had been fed were lies,'' Berger
said. ``I grew up very poor. I grew up in the projects, most of my
friends were black or Hispanic. A lot of these kids saw their lives
taken away from them. I knew because of my skin color I had power.
I could get out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these kids didn't get through high school. Those that
did didn't make it through college,'' he added. ``A lot of these
kids lost their parents young, partly because of poverty, partly
because of racism. These were parents who were working hard, who
didn't know if they were coming or going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an anti-racist is good for white people,'' he said. ``If
we can free ourselves from the mechanisms of bigotry maybe it will
free us in other ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
