<HEADER>
A4099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOGRAPHY-NYT &LR;      05-04 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: BIOGRAPHICAL SOUND BITES? WELL, THESE HAVE
TEETH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who was it who wrote a long letter, apologizing that he didn't
have time for a short one? I don't remember, and I can't look it
up. Too much to do; no time to do it. It is therefore something of
a relief to pick up the first four volumes in a new series of
books, biographies of 150 pages or so, well written by people who
know.
</P>
<P>
   The series is called Penguin Lives, and at first glance it might
be seen as a kind of biographical literature for the age of the
sound bite. In fact, in its way, the new books are biographical
literature for the age of celebrity, at least that small stream
running off the great river of celebrity that is literary
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The creator of the series (full disclosure: he is a former New
York Times editor, James Atlas, who is a friend of mine) had two
interdependent ideas. One is that there is a market for short
biographies when so many biographies are of the 600-, 700-, even
1,000-page variety. ( Atlas, somewhat paradoxically, has been
working for many years on a very long biography of Saul Bellow.)
</P>
<P>
   The other part of Atlas' concept was to have famous writers do
these biographies. And so, for example, the first two to appear
were ``Crazy Horse'' by Larry McMurtry (author of ``Lonesome
Dove,'' ``Terms of Endearment'' and many other popular novels) and
``Proust'' by Edmund White. White is less famous than McMurtry, but
he has written 11 books, including ``Genet: A Biography,'' which
won a couple of major literary prizes and is a celebrity in
literary criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Soon two more Penguin Lives will be published, ``Mozart'' by
Peter Gay and ``St. Augustine'' by Garry Wills. I have read these
two in galley form, and doing so makes clear that Penguin Lives are
far from a kind of biographical Cliff Notes, a Classic Comics of
the deservedly famous. Certainly, there are no major departures in
these books, no radical reinterpretations or troves of previously
unknown information. But Gay and Wills are serious writers who
treat their subjects with discernment, clarity and elegance. Most
of all, they both have a point of view, a theme, a vision that sets
them gently at odds with other accounts of the same lives that they
have studied.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguin series joins other sets of short biographical
presentations on what are usually long subjects. But short divides
into two rough categories, what might be called high short and low
short. In the former rank, for example, is Paul Strathern's
continuing series on philosophers (``Wittgenstein in 90 Minutes''
and a dozen or so others published so far by Ivan R. Dee in
Chicago). Switching media and moving down an intellectual level or
two, there is ``Biography,'' a series of cable television programs
running one hour apiece, about the amount of concentrated time one
would need to read, say, Wills' ``Augustine.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving further toward the mass market, is, say, People magazine,
which is, in its way, a series of short biographies, usually of
living people.
</P>
<P>
   Lives, in other words, are in, especially lives recounted
succinctly. Historians and philosophers may debate the role of the
individual in history and whether, as Tolstoy said, supposedly
seminal individuals are nothing more than vessels of larger forces.
The reading and television-viewing public, whether they are
consuming the Penguin Lives or People magazine, have voted on this
issue, and have decreed that genius is interesting, instructive,
inspiring; that far from being a kind of illusion, it matters. The
public in this sense agrees with Thomas Carlyle, who famously
declared: ``The history of the world is but the biography of great
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Short biographies do not necessarily indicate some lesser
yearning or interest, simply a demand that these needs be satisfied
more quickly. Atlas and his chief investor, the financier Kenneth
Lipper, are hoping that the public's desire for the essence of a
life will make a success of books whose chief feature is an
elegant, literary brevity. And on the intellectual scale, from high
short to low short, Penguin Lives has a claim to being at the top
of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for example, in his account of Mozart, Gay begins with the
pithy remark: ``The life of Mozart is the triumph of genius over
precociousness.'' Wills begins with an equally epigrammatic
statement: ``A word from his inmost being goes direct to our most
guarded self; `My heart's fellow will love in me what You (Lord)
tell is lovable, deplore in me what You tell is deplorable.'''
Nobody who reads those lines will assume that he is in for an
especially easy time of it. The message is that these books will
take a bit of effort, even if less time than other books, and,
moreover, that the effort will be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Gay's ``Mozart'' is an especially appealing brief work, one that
manages to probe deeply even if not at great length. He covers such
essential subjects as Mozart's excessively demanding father and the
implications of his presence on the son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolfgang Mozart was a good son, but was Leopold Mozart a good
father?'' he asks. He gives marvelous examples of Mozart's personal
and verbal crudeness, in such remarkable contrast with the music.
He disposes of myths: for example, that Mozart died penniless after
being poisoned by the rival composer Antonio Salieri and was buried
in a pauper's grave. And he deals knowledgeably with the
``astonishing caliber'' of the music itself, but he does so
unsentimentally, without mawkish hero-worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The widely accepted portrait of Mozart the lonely genius
listening to his inner voices alone is a romantic distortion of the
more mundane reality,'' Gay writes. ``Once he was moved to compose,
inspiration took over, but the inspiration for that inspiration was
likely a commission he had just received.''
</P>
<P>
   Wills' book is a more difficult slender volume, in part because
Augustine is a less accessible figure. Wills subjects Augustine's
writings to a close scrutiny to test the conventional wisdom about
his subject and in some instances to argue against it. He begins
with the idea that Augustine's best-known book, ``Confessions,''
does not refer mainly to his supposed youthful debauches but is
actually testimony on his entire theology, his deep examination of
himself as part of a lifelong search for God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beginning in 397, there was an implosion of his mind, down
into himself, back into his past, as the place where God could be
found,'' Wills writes. ``His own mystery was an echo of God's; and
God was hiding in the vaster areas he felt opening within.''
</P>
<P>
   This and many other passages like it in Wills' short book are
uncompromising in their rigor. Brevity, in other words, may be the
soul of Penguin Lives but downmarket simplification is not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1748EDT &QL; 
