<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-DANCERS-2TAK     05-04 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-DANCERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCING BOOMS ON BROADWAY: MORE JOBS, SAME OLD GRIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Aside from her spiky frosted hair, it was hard to
pick out Amy Brewer in the two dozen or so black-clad dancers at
the Broadway Dance Center strutting, twirling and kicking, doing
the same routine 8, 10, 12, 14 times to the 30-second finale of
Natalie Cole's ``Orange-Colored Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Allison Ellner-Teitelbaum, who owns the five-floor studio
that is ground zero for New York dance, saw something she liked
amid the symphony of black spandex and high-heeled Capezio
character shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooooh,'' she said approvingly as she watched the working
dancers and the wannabes in Tony Stevens' advanced professional
theater dancing class one recent afternoon. ``Amy wheedled her way
up to the front. Good for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the front increases the likelihood of being noticed
by the teacher, who may one day be casting a show, and it denotes a
bit of chutzpah, neither of which is likely to hurt in the
ultra-competitive world of theatrical dancing.
</P>
<P>
   After years of decline, as the gold standard on Broadway became
song and drama mega-shows like ``Phantom of the Opera'' or ``Les
Miserables'' and the great choreographer-directors of the past
departed, it is suddenly a fertile time for dancers on Broadway.
Dance thrives in ``Chicago'' and ``Fosse,'' which feature classic
Bob Fosse choreography by the theater's top dancers; in the
youthful sweat-athon ``Footloose,'' and in shows as diverse as
``Ragtime,'' ``Annie Get Your Gun'' and ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain logic for the resurgence of dancers. In an
age of body lust, the long, lean ``Chicago'' dancers on the ads
running the length of city buses have the best-toned abs and thighs
around. And in the cyclical rhythms of Broadway fashion, dance has
been out so long, it is probably time for it to be in.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see them with their turned-out duck feet, baggy
pants, pulled-back hair and backpacks showing up to teach or take
classes at the Broadway Dance Center on West 57th Street. You can
find them going in for the dancer's best friend, physical tuneups
at Performing Arts Physical Therapy or West Side Chiropractic. You
can spot them, at least the younger ones, after shows having a
glass of wine or a martini at Arriba Arriba, Barrymore's, Joe Allen
or the other theater-district hangouts.
</P>
<P>
   The life is too diffuse and tribal _ each show its own world _
to allow much in the way of shared experience aside from the aches
and pains and economic uncertainty. What they have in common is an
almost blindingly intense devotion to their craft and a realization
that few careers provide less of a secure foothold on status and
security than dancing for a living in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of dance going on now, but there are a lot more
good dancers too; they're well trained and they look great,'' said
Jane Lanier, a featured dancer in ``Fosse'' who has been dancing
professionally since 1983, when she was 21. ``So there's
opportunity, but unless you're totally committed, this is a crazy
choice. You would never want to try it unless it's something you
almost felt that you had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brewer, a 22-year-old from Seattle who arrived in New York
last July, represents life at the bottom of the dance food chain.
She lives with three friends _ a dancer, a singer-actress and a
theater technician _ in a $1,200-a-month three-bedroom apartment in
Astoria and works at a Starbucks coffee shop and as an usher at
``The Lion King.'' She came as part of an internship at the
Broadway Dance Center, where about 4,500 people take lessons each
week for $12.50 apiece. The internship allowed her to take 10
classes a week for six months, and she now takes about five, part
of a work-study program.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at age 4, Ms. Brewer grew up doing ballet, tap, jazz
dancing, baton twirling and the rest. She got hooked on Broadway
dancing after turning on the Rosie O'Donnell show and seeing the
cast of ``Chicago'' with Bebe Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my dream show,'' she said. ``Since I've been here I've
seen it about 15 times. Can I do that? Well, I know I've got to get
better. But I don't feel that I can't do that. I feel my time will
come. You have to feel that way if you want to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   If she succeeds, it will not be just because of the way she
dances.
</P>
<P>
   First, almost no one makes it as just a dancer these days.
Nearly everyone has to sing, act and dance, be what's dutifully
called a triple threat. Second, Ms. Brewer is already learning that
who you know on the dance floor can mean as much as how you dance
on it. This is not necessarily invoked cynically. It is assumed
that no one works, particularly in the top shows, unless their
dancing is first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also assumed that with a glut of talent,
choreographers are most likely to pick dancers they know. That
means the dancers will know what the choreographer wants and the
choreographer will know the work habits and personality of the
dancers. It is no accident that Stevens' next class _ the day
before he stages an audition _ is completely jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all theatrical dance careers lead to Broadway.
Between growing music video production in Los Angeles and show
tours, young dancers often chart career paths that owe little to
the world of ``A Chorus Line.'' One of the more vivid presences at
the Broadway Dance Center is Glenn Douglas Packard, a 27-year-old
with streaked hair, the son of a Michigan dairy farmer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Packard runs a talent agency and markets himself by cooking up
cover stories for Dance Spirit magazine. He has done tours or shows
in Norway, Hawaii and Japan, was part of a troupe that danced for
the King of Morocco and is part of a show being put together by
singer Jimmy Buffett. He is the dancer as entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like variety,'' he said. ``I'd be bored on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   For those with more traditional aspirations, the road to
Broadway begins with endless lessons in childhood and leads through
television commercials, theme parks, industrial shows and cruise
ships where the idea is both to dance and to oversee the
shuffleboard game.
</P>
<P>
   Some take a different path. Bernard Dotson, who dances in
``Ragtime,'' got a business degree and was working in a corporate
job in Los Angeles 13 years ago when he decided that what he really
wanted to do was dance. He started taking 12 dance classes a week,
got a job six months later in a show doing a three-month European
tour and has been working steadily ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A more typical story, if any dancer's life is typical, is that
of Serena Soffer, who dances in ``Footloose.'' She grew up in
Edison, N.J. Her father was a used-car salesman, and her mother had
been an acrobat and contortionist in a German circus. Ms. Soffer
began dancing at age 3, got her Actors' Equity card at 10 and
entered the dancers' purgatory of industrial shows, where teams of
dancers hop planes to Florida or Las Vegas to do 15-minute shows 9
or 10 times a day at conventions and trade shows for a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make thousands of dollars, but it's a nightmare,'' said
Ms. Soffer, who has a Medusa's head of blond hair and carries her
gear in a pink Rugrats bag. ``You get off the plane, and it's cold
and strenuous on your body, and you have to do these shows over and
over, selling a fabric or pushing a product. I've never done theme
parks, but they're about the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Her break came when she was hired by A.C. Ciulla for a cabaret
show, ``Hollywood to Broadway,'' which ran for almost two years at
the Tatou Supper Club on the East Side. When Ciulla was hired for
``Footloose,'' he brought her and two other dancers with him.
</P>
<P>
   Now she sleeps until 11 or so every day, spends her days
cooking, taking classes, working on other dance projects or going
to physical therapy, then shows up for work each evening to do the
show.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the food chain are the dancers in ``Chicago'' and
``Fosse,'' many of them the best-known and most skilled dancers of
their generation. Elizabeth Parkinson and Scott Wise, two of the
featured dancers in ``Fosse,'' share both a job and a life. They
plan to marry in June.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Broadway after a career with the Joffrey Ballet,
Feld Ballet and Donald Byrd. Broadway, she says, is like a parallel
universe to ballet, with its own rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``In ballet, you have to keep a higher level technically, so in
one way it's physically more demanding,'' said Ms. Parkinson, who
at 25 is the youngest dancer in ``Fosse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But dancing on Broadway demands more on a performance level.
You can't get away with just being technically amazing the way you
can in ballet. You really have to perform. The individual
performance can be more difficult in ballet, but you don't do it
eight times a week, week after week, the way we do. And the way you
get your job is so different. In Broadway your role is assigned
before you start the work process. In ballet you're a member of a
company, so you're always competing for roles. There's a lot more
angst in ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise, who at 40 has been dancing for 36 years, has won two Tonys
and was nominated for a third this week for featured actor in a
musical. He is one of Broadway's best-known male dancers, with
credits including ``Victor/Victoria,'' ``State Fair,'' ``Damn
Yankees,'' ``Guys and Dolls,'' ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' and ``A
Chorus Line.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, dancers have it better now than they did in the
past, he said. ``The shoes are better, the stages are better, they
have sprung floors that can really save your knees, back and
ankles,'' he said. ``Dancers have more protection, pregnancy
leaves, things you didn't have in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wise is not sure Broadway will ever take the same risks with
dance or see the same kind of commanding choreographer-directors of
the past like Fosse or Robbins or Michael Bennett. And he thinks
the tempestuous autocrats of the past demanded a consistently
higher level than choreographers now do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more corporate and much more expensive now,'' he
said. ``Dance is hard to sell at a producing table. You can read a
script or sing a song, but it's not easy to get people in costumes
dancing around. The way the machine is built right now, I'm not
sure that even if you had a Fosse or a Bennett, they'd be able to
get their work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Dancers, like most people, may be prone to nostalgia. But what
Wise seems to miss is not just an era but also a sensibility, the
passing of Broadway's ``gypsies,'' veteran dancers who flitted from
show to show. Now dancers tend to stay with a show for two or three
years, then sometimes do it on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you would do a couple of shows a year at
least,'' Wise said. ``It was taboo to stay on a show for more than
a year. It was as if you couldn't get another job. Now because
shows are so expensive and there are fewer of them, people do shows
for two, two and a half, three years. Producers don't like it if
you leave, and they make it contractually harder to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, as ever, a tough way to live. Dancers remain at the low
end of Broadway's pecking order in pay and in status. They are
always one injury away from being out of work. And in a culture
obsessed with youth, no one hears the clock tick louder than they
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of aches and pains, and you have to learn to
pace yourself,'' said Ms. Soffer, s 29. ``There's a dancer in my
show who is 17, she's absolutely brilliant, and I have to realize I
can't always keep up with the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Fosse'' and ``Chicago'' feature mature
dancers, most of them well on the other side of 30. Ms. Lanier, for
example, struts her stuff in ``Fosse'' while raising two young
children. And though the heyday of Fosse, Robbins or Bennett
musicals is gone, many see the current popularity of dance as an
encouraging sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balanchine is gone, but at some point another choreographer
like Balanchine will come along,'' said Ann Reinking, choreographer
of ``Chicago'' and co-director and co-choreographer of ``Fosse.''
``It's the same on Broadway. It might take 50 years, it might take
5. But in the meantime there's incredibly good work for us to dance
and explore and re-explore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
