<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERY FISHER PRIZE GOES TO WOMEN FOR FIRST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three American violinists, Sarah Chang, Pamela Frank
and Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg, have been named winners of the 1999
Avery Fisher Prize. This is the first time in the 25-year history
of the prestigious award, founded by Avery Fisher to support
outstanding performing musicians, that the prize has gone to women.
</P>
<P>
   The prize was last given to pianist Garrick Ohlsson in 1994, the
year of Fisher's death. This year, to commemorate the 25th
anniversary, the cash award has been doubled to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Avery Fisher Prize is separate from the Avery Fisher Career
Grant, which awards $10,000 to each of up to five emerging artists
annually. There have been 73 Fisher Career Grants since 1974, and
many of the recipients have been women.
</P>
<P>
   The more select Avery Fisher Prize is awarded only when an
executive awards committee agrees upon a musician who merits it.
The committee has 11 members, artists like pianist Emanuel Ax and
the cellist Yo-Yo Ma (both previous recipients), as well as
administrators like Lincoln Center president Nathan Leventhal and
Juilliard president Joseph Polisi.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Borda, executive director of the New York Philharmonic
and a member of the Avery Fisher Artist Program since 1991, said
recently that there had been much discussion about the absence of
female recipients during the selection of prize winners in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about it, I wouldn't mislead you,'' she said.
``There were times we tried to select a woman, or someone on the
committee would push for a particular woman artist. But it didn't
fly for whatever reasons with the full committee. And in making
selections, excellence always comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, she said, the board wanted to ``make a major
statement'' by honoring three female artists. ``We think the
results are terrific,'' she added, with violinists ``from different
generations and from different schools of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chang, 18, born in Philadelphia to Korean parents, has
best-selling recordings on the EMI label and has been a soloist
with orchestras around the world, including the London Symphony,
the Vienna Philharmonic and the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   New York-born Ms. Frank, 31, the daughter of pianists Claude
Frank and Lilian Kallir, balances her burgeoning solo career with a
deep commitment to chamber music.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg, 38, born in Rome, has won an ardent
following, as well some criticism, for her highly charged music
making and dramatic performances. All three musicians had received
Avery Fisher Career Grants.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ax, Ma and Ohlsson, past winners of the Avery Fisher
Prize include the pianists Murray Perahia, Richard Goode, Horacio
Gutierrez, Andre Watts and Yefim Bronfman; the cellist Lynn
Harrell; the violinist Elmar Oliveira, and the clarinetist Richard
Stoltzman.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes are to be presented Wednesday night at a gala
reception onstage at Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
