<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOLING-DIXIE-ART-NYT     05-04 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOLING-DIXIE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DIXIE GOT ITS COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Miss.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What technological advance made the South what it
is today? No, not the cotton gin, pick-up truck or deep-fat fryer.
</P>
<P>
   The irrefutable answer is air conditioning, the engineering
marvel that transformed Dixie from a struggling region of the
country into an economic and demographic power without hardly
breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Now the invention that put the buckle on the Sun Belt is being
celebrated in a first-ever museum exhibition that explores the
profound social, cultural and architectural changes wrought by the
conquest of climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other factors in the rise of the South, but air
conditioning certainly makes a difference,'' said Chrysanthe
Broikos, associate curator at the National Building Museum, where
the novel exhibition opened Saturday. ``You can't imagine Central
Florida as the home of Disney World or Universal Studios without
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter ``Stay Cool! Air Conditioning America,'' via an
oversized sheet-metal air conditioning duct. They journey through
three galleries that employ videos, photographs, old
advertisements, artifacts and interactive displays to trace the
development of engineered air and its impact on the modern world.
</P>
<P>
   In the initial room, a glimpse of ``Hot America'' in the days
before air conditioning makes one thirst for an icy lemonade as
pictures show sweltering citizens trying to keep cool by sleeping
on city fire escapes.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition gives ample evidence of the role of air
conditioning in the evolution of the modern South. A large
thermometer traces the demographic shift of people migrating from
the region during the first half of the century, peaking with a net
loss of 3 million people in the 1950s. The movement stabilized in
the 1960s and completely reversed itself in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Broikos said that decade's population count is sometimes
referred to as the ``air conditioning census'' since it was the
first to reflect the population trends hinged to advances in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air conditioning helped fuel the explosive postwar growth of
Sunbelt cities like Houston, Phoenix, Las Vegas and Miami,''
proclaims the exhibition, which also attributes the shift in
migration patterns to civil rights gains.
</P>
<P>
   While air conditioning has been important to the development of
the South, the region was also key to the development of air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the air-conditioning industry began in the North,
most of its early growth took place in the South,'' wrote Raymond
Arsenault, a University of South Florida history professor, in a
Journal of Southern History essay used as a basis for the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the father of air conditioning is considered to be John
Gorrie, an Apalachicola, Fla., physician who first began
experimenting with mechanical cooling in the 1830s in his search
for a way to help victims of subtropical diseases. He had visions
of artificially cooled cities even then.
</P>
<P>
   Other early pioneers included textile mill and tobacco industry
engineers determined to control the temperature and humidity
problems that affected their production. Arsenault credits Stuart
Cramer, a Charlotte, N.C., engineer, with coining the term air
conditioning in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   But in the South as elsewhere, it was movie theatres that
brought the general public its first real taste of air conditioning
in the Roaring '20s. Movie houses advertised their ``comfort
control'' as prominently as their films and no longer had to close
for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenault recounted how at the ``grand opening of St.
Petersburg's Florida theatre in 1926, the proud management had the
temperature down so low that ladies in evening dresses almost
froze.''
</P>
<P>
   The home air conditioning boom took off in the 1950s with the
development of affordable residential units, and the shape of
housing was changed forever. Gone were thick insulating walls and
wrap-around porches, giving way to plate glass and sliding doors.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the consequences of air conditioning are necessarily
positive. The exhibition points out that changing home design
confined people indoors, sacrificing the sense of community they
gained from visiting porch-to-porch.
</P>
<P>
   And on a global scale, the chlorofluorocarbons used in air
conditioning refrigerants have been blamed for damaging the earth's
ozone layer and are being banned worldwide, forcing the industry to
develop other, less harmful coolants and new hybrid methods of
naturally and artificially cooled air.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition also raises the prospect that the advent of air
conditioning precipitated the decline of Southern literature, as
the cool air sapped the emotion from the region's fiery authors.
Consider William Faulkner, who has been replaced by John Grisham as
the first man of letters of Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can one imagine Faulkner writing `Absalom, Absalom!' under the
spell of central air?'' asks writer Fred Hobson in a quotation
prominently displayed in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenault argued in his essay that air conditioning forever
altered the very way of life that made the South unique in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southerners, more than most other Americans, have tied
themselves to a local geography,'' he wrote. ``Their lives and
identities have been rooted in a particular piece of turf _ a
county, a town, a neighborhood, a homestead, a family graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet in recent years, thanks in part to air conditioning,
Southern particularism has been overwhelmed by an almost endless
string of look-alike chain stores, tract houses, glassed-in high
rises, and perhaps, most important, enclosed shopping malls. The
modern shopping mall is the cathedral of air-conditioned culture
and it symbolizes the placelessness of the New South.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000-square-foot exhibition was financed by $250,000 in
grants from the Air-Conditioning and Refrigeration Institute and
the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating &AMP; Air Conditioning
Engineers. It will be open through Jan. 2 at the museum, which is
situated in a spectacular building somewhat off the beaten track in
the Judiciary Square area of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
