<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC05-COX     05-04 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC HEAD TARGETS ONLINE BROKERAGE ADS
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Online brokerage ads that play on a get-rich-quick
theme are ``demeaning'' to investors, the chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission said Tuesday as he promised
closer scrutiny of their content.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't rule out the fact that some of these commercials are
tongue-in-cheek,'' SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt said at the National
Press Club. He cited a Discover Brokerage Direct ad in which a tow
truck driver tells of buying his own island nation with his stock
trading profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a market environment such as the one we're in, where
many investors are susceptible to quixotic euphoria, I'm worried
these commercials step over the line and border on
irresponsibility,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said he has asked the National Association of Securities
Dealers ``to hold a round-table on advertising to add to the work
they're already doing to improve fairness in advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The round-table discussion is likely to be held in mid-June,
said spokeswoman Nancy A. Condon of NASD Regulation, the regulatory
arm of the National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, NASD Regulation issued reminders that
advertising and promotional material should not ``set unrealistic
expectations'' about the speed of online trading or the opportunity
to make money in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discover Brokerage Direct supports Chairman Levitt's vision of
an informed investing public who are aware of the risk as well as
the reward of investing,'' the unit of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
said in a statement. ``We would welcome the opportunity to
participate in a NASD-led round-table on advertising for online
brokerages.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's Levitt also took a crack at day traders, who hold
stocks only for brief periods, and at the operations of online
brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't think day traders are speculating,'' said
Levitt, ``because traditional speculation requires some market
knowledge. They are instead gambling, which really doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   While he reiterated a warning that investors are responsible for
their own actions, Levitt also cautioned that online brokerages
still have ``obligations to customers.'' He cited the need to
ensure that online brokerages can handle an increasing number of
transactions and respond to e-mail and phone inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also said the SEC has started a ``broad-reaching''
examination to make sure brokerages provide customers with the best
prices available when they buy or sell stock.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he sent a letter Tuesday ``to all of the on-line
brokerage firms requesting they improve the quality of their
disclosure to investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt wants the brokerages to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Explain that transactions on the Internet may not be
instantaneous.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spell out clearly the trading limitations and risks in a
volatile market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop ways to help investors more easily spot mistakes when
they place orders to buy or sell stocks online.
</P>
<P>
   _ Adequately warn investors about the risks and costs of buying
stocks on margin, or using borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it clear that getting in on a hot initial public
offering, or getting as many shares as an investor would prefer, is
not always possible.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also said he would like online brokerages and Internet
providers hosting chat rooms to provide links to the SEC's investor
education site (http://www.sec.gov/invkhome.htm).
</P>
<P>
   He did not propose new regulations governing online trading, but
didn't rule out the possibility the SEC may someday need ``new
approaches to better meet the imperatives of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
