<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-LEGOLAND-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-KEY THRILLS AT LEGOLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 9) 
(jt) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something fascinating about other people's obsessions.
Take Legoland, the newly opened theme park in the golfing mecca of
Carlsbad, Calif., about 30 miles north of San Diego. The park is a
sea of primary colors that covers 128 acres and includes the usual
range of attractions and rides. But, at least judging by the
interests of my two children, Marina, 7, and Sammy, 5, it was the
odd, obsessive character of Miniland that most captured their
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Miniland section of the park is a model builder's dream come
true, where the makers of Lego _ the small plastic building blocks
that fill playrooms everywhere in the industrialized world _ have
faithfully recreated miniature cityscapes out of these brightly
hued bricks in a frighteningly precise level of detail.
</P>
<P>
   Washington includes, for instance, the Capitol, the White House
and all the favorite monuments and historic sites, at a height of
four feet or so. In addition, there are protesters with placards,
multirace families enjoying picnics in front of the Washington
Monument (but without the scaffolding that currently covers the
real one) and even people waving to the President in his limousine.
Midtown Manhattan has hot dog vendors and taxis. And there is even
Belvedere Fountain from Central Park. There is also a New England
harbor, downtown San Francisco and even New Orleans, with a jazz
funeral parade winding through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, look, the boat's moving,'' said my daughter, pointing to
the tourist barge gliding along the artificial Potomac. My son
raced around and counted three such boats and then marveled at a
tiny Lego windsurfer in a small San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   And then, a few minutes later, they wanted to know what else we
were going to do. That seems to sum up the delight and problem with
this park: fascination, but hardly enough to fill a day.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland, which opened on March 20, cost $130 million and took
several years to build. It is about 100 miles south of Los Angeles
just off the major north-south artery, Interstate 5, and has to
compete with a host of major theme parks, including Disneyland,
Knott's Berry Farm, Universal Studios, Six Flags and Sea World, not
to mention various zoos and the biggest theme park of all, the
Southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland is going through some understandable growing pains.
Lines are at times exceptionally slow, from getting into the
parking lot to getting onto the more popular rides, which include
the Sky Cycle, the Driving School and the Kid Power Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Mindstorms, a workshop where kids are taught how to build
motorized Lego robots and vehicles, requires reservations made the
day of a visit. But on a recent Sunday it was booked solid by
midmorning, and an attendant said that has been the norm on
weekends. The landscaping has not had much time to grow full and
tall, so there is a dearth of shade. On the positive side, at least
for parents, Legoland is not designed so that kids are constantly
shrieking for merchandise. There are shops with Lego paraphernalia,
but they are not as omnipresent as at, say, Disneyland, or as
intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   But Legoland seems to be based on a different premise from that
of many other theme parks, where the focus is frequently on
thrills. Here, the emphasis is on comforting, childlike pleasures,
aimed at a somewhat younger audience than the other parks. It is
based on the premise that if kids love Lego blocks, they will love
an amusement park built around them and, literally, out of them.
The question is not whether that captures children's attention, but
for how long. My kids grew restless and wondered how they would
fill their day after some excited moments. So did I.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Legoland is aimed in general at a younger audience
than, say, Universal Studios. The company says it is for children
from 2 to 12, but it seems skewed toward the younger end of the
range. It is also expensive. The entry fee is $32 a day for adults
and $25 for children 3 through 16, with another $6 for parking. The
fee covers all the rides, and there are four restaurants and many
snack stands spread throughout the park that sell food at prices
typical for theme parks, not cheap but not outrageous either, with
kids' meals available for between $3 and $5.
</P>
<P>
   The Lego group is based in Denmark, and this is its third theme
park; the others are in Billund, Denmark, and Windsor, England. All
the parks are celebrations of the famous Lego bricks. The standard
eight-knob bricks are about an inch and a quarter by a half inch,
and just over a half inch thick, and any six bricks can be combined
in 102,981,500 ways, in case you were wondering. Thirty million of
them were used to construct the attractions in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland is convenient to the freeway, but the line at the
entrance, though short, took nearly 20 minutes. Once we parked, and
then waited 15 minutes to buy passes, the kids scampered happily
through the multihued gate.
</P>
<P>
   The first attraction near the entrance is the Village Green.
There is a slow boat ride through Fairy Tale Brook, where there are
trolls and other characters made from _ what else? _ Lego bricks.
There is also a menagerie of large, nearly life-sized Lego animals:
elephants spouting water, lions and the like. And there are a
couple of outdoor theaters where humorous stage shows are
performed, such as a clown act done on a fire engine.
</P>
<P>
   Close at hand after that is the Ridge, a slightly raised area
with two of the more popular (read: crowded) rides. The Sky Cycle
is a cycle-of-sorts, for two or three, decorated in vivid colors,
that progresses along an elevated track under power from the
riders. The Kid Power Tower has seats, where a parent and child can
sit, buckled in, side by side. They tug on a rope to lift the seats
to the top of a tower, about 20 feet up, and then can drop very
slowly down again by letting go.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle boat cruises on a man-made lake run along the shores of
Miniland, where the short urban towers shimmer under the Southern
California sun.
</P>
<P>
   Fun Town, which is nearby, includes the Driving School, where
children are instructed on driving methods and then set loose in
mini-cars on a course of roads and stop lights. There's a Junior
Driving School for those under 6 and a Sky Patrol, with small
helicopters that pump up and down and turn about.
</P>
<P>
   We found Castle Hill, a sort of medieval castle themed area, to
be the most engaging part of the park. The Dragon, a small roller
coaster, offers the closest thing to a thrill ride at Legoland. The
wait is long and the ride brief, just a couple of minutes, but the
twists and turns had children shrieking delightedly.
</P>
<P>
   The Hideaways, also in Castle Hill, is a giant playground maze
and climbing gym, perfect for games of tag. At the least, it gives
children itchy from waiting in lines a chance to unwind and blow
off some pent-up energy _ although it is just a slightly larger
version of the playgrounds you can find in many public parks.
</P>
<P>
   The Imagination Zone offers a very different experience from the
rest of the park: it is indoors, a welcome relief on a warm day,
and it is a bit more challenging. In one section, kids can choose
which model they want to build, such as a vehicle or robot, then
check out a kit with lots of Lego bricks to build the item at
little desks. The bricks must be returned when the child is
finished.
</P>
<P>
   There is another area for smaller children where there are large
boxes of the larger Lego blocks known as Duplo. Kids can build at
work desks or on the floor, where many gathered because of the
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The Mindstorms attraction is the most sophisticated challenge in
the Imagination Zone. At 45-minute intervals, older children enter
and use the most advanced company product, Lego Technic bricks, to
build what are essentially robots. The park suggests that only
children 8 years old and up sign up. For those interested, it is
advisable to rush to the Mindstorms immediately after you enter the
park to book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
