<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-COMPETITION-     05-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-COMPETITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. SWEENEY INTRODUCES AIRLINE COMPETITION LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories) ,
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Sweeney watched the price of his weekly
airline ticket from Albany, N.Y., to Washington, D.C. rise by 25
percent in recent weeks so Tuesday he joined a growing number of
lawmakers urging Congress to increase airline competition in small-
and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who is vice-chair of the aviation subcommittee of the
House Transportation Committee, introduced legislation that would
encourage smaller carriers to serve places like Albany. The measure
includes $65 million to help smaller airports build additional
runways and gates that are necessary to attract new airlines.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the jump in his ticket price and the recent reduction
in the number of US Airways' flights from New York City's LaGuardia
Airport to Syracuse, N.Y., as evidence ``that some airlines are
moving in a direction opposite to consumer demand to provide better
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline competition and ``passenger bill of rights'' legislation
has become a hot issue in Congress as frequent-flying lawmakers,
like many of their constituents, have become increasingly
frustrated with rising airfares and delays.
</P>
<P>
   Recent government studies have shown that while airfares have
dropped at many large airports that are served by a number of
carriers, fares have risen in places like Albany that are served by
fewer airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, a Republican freshman from Albany, held hearings last
month on airline competition issues and said he and other lawmakers
tried to send the nation's major airlines a message that they had
better improve service or Congress would increase its regulation of
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense by many of us in Congress that the major
airlines are approaching this with an arrogant attitude,'' Sweeney
said. ``I can't say how angry I am at their response.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he now pays $670 for a round-trip ticket to
Washington, D.C., up from the $536 he paid six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who is working with local officials to bring Southwest
Airlines to Albany, said the airport needs to build two additional
gates to accommodate the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would allow the Department of Transportation (DOT)
to give smaller airlines additional landing and take-off rights at
four airports in New York, Chicago and Washington, D.C., on routes
to small- and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law the number of hourly landings and take-offs is
limited at Chicago's O'Hare, New York's Kennedy and LaGuardia
airports and Washington, D.C.'s Ronald Reagan National Airport. The
slot system, which refers to landings and takeoffs, was implemented
at the four airports in 1968 to reduce delays.
</P>
<P>
   A recent General Accounting Office report said the slot system
is dominated by large airlines and gives them virtual monopolies at
those airports and little incentive to cut fares.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's bill would also establish a $120 million annual loan
program through the DOT to help small carriers purchase jets that
would be used to help serve small and mid-sized airports.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also give DOT the authority to crack down on
so-called predatory pricing practices. This occurs when a new,
often small airline, enters a new market. Large carriers then drop
their prices on routes served by the new airline in order to drive
it out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Smallen, a DOT spokesperson, said the DOT already has this
authority but is in the process of writing new guidelines to more
clearly define predatory pricing practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ultimate goal is to establish a level playing field for
low-fare carriers,'' he said. The new guidelines, which have been
vigorously fought by large airlines, probably won't be final until
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said his legislation is designed to complement a broader
measure authored by Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House
Transportation Committee, that would impose fines on airlines which
keep passengers waiting inside airplanes that are on the ground for
more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's bill would require so-called hub airports, in which a
large carrier often controls a majority of gates, to submit a plan
to Congress detailing how they would open up the hub airport to
increased competition in order to receive additional federal funds.
Delta Airlines, for example, controls 80 percent of the market in
Atlanta while Northwest controls 79 percent of the gates in its hub
airports of Minneapolis and Detroit, according the House
Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation sponsored by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz. and Ron
Wyden, D-Ore., contains many of the same provisions as Shuster's
and Sweeney's measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
