<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `NOAH'; RE-ENACTMENTS; PBS PROGRAMMER LEAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   High Water For Ratings
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Noah's Ark'' was the biggest mini-series of the
television eseason in terms of ratings and reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The two-part movie, which starred Jon Voight as Noah, reached
about 50 million viewers Sunday night, the largest number for any
movie this season. Although the number of viewers fell Monday to
about 42 million, the film still dominated the night. The movie had
a larger audience than this year's other highly promoted NBC
mini-series, ``The '60s'' and ``The Temptations.''
</P>
<P>
   But NBC and many of its affiliated stations also reported
receiving hundreds of calls complaining that the film diverged too
much from the story of Noah presented in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The clamor was enough for NBC to issue a statement defending the
``artistic and historical license'' taken by the film but
apologizing to viewers if they found ``the treatment of the
material objectionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The mini-series expanded on the rather limited account in the
Bible by having Noah live in the town of Sodom, be a friend of Lot
and his wife (who do not appear in the Bible until after the story
of Noah), and even fight a naval engagement after the flood against
Lot, who has become an eye-patch-wearing pirate.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, NBC said the film ``remains faithful to the
essential spirit and values of faith and humanity in the story of
Noah, as told in the Book of Genesis in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   The mini-series did have a disclaimer at the start of each part:
``For dramatic effect, we have taken dramatic license with some of
the events of the mighty epic of Noah and the flood.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings, if not the reaction, surely will make CBS feel
better about a planned mini-series of its own. Next season CBS is
to present a four-hour movie called simply ``Jesus.'' CBS is
already promising a film that emphasizes the humanity of the lead
character, although it will also feature several miracles. Those
who have seen the first draft of the script describe it as a
portrait of the adult Jesus, who starts out as a carpenter before
moving on to his broader mission.
</P>
<P>
   The production of ``Jesus'' may be one of the most expensive in
recent television history, with a budget estimated at $30 million.
Locations in Morocco will be standing in for the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   While Gary Oldman has been signed to play Pontius Pilate, the
title role has not been cast.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Truth in Packaging
</P>
<P>
   The Fox network issued a rather sheepish statement Monday
promising that any staged re-enactments used in the popular
``reality specials,'' like ``World's Wildest Police Videos'' or
``When Animals Attack,'' would be clearly labeled as such in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   That is because producers of some of those shows' dramatic
``caught on tape'' segments were themselves caught on tape by
sharp-eyed investigate reporters at the syndicated news magazine
program ``Inside Edition.'' In a segment broadcast on Monday,
``Inside Edition'' showed how producers had staged re-creations of
the police capturing criminals and of an elephant attacking a
photographer in Kenya, and had passed off the re-creations as real.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident from ``World's Wildest Police Videos,'' viewers
saw a boat chase, purportedly captured by a police camera, with the
suspects beaching their boat and one suspect being tackled by
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Inside Edition'' reporter, Matt Meagher, then interviewed
someone he described as ``a respected local fireman,'' who told
him: ``They needed somebody to play a criminal and a bad guy, and
so we just volunteered.'' He added, ``They went ahead and gave us a
script and told us that this is what happened and to re-enact as
best we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Meagher interviewed the program's host, a former Oregon sheriff,
John Bunnell, who said that only a few incidents were staged, and
that he tried to use the words ``police training video'' in
describing them. He also said that his show was entertainment and
should not be held to the same standards as a news program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many viewers don't make a distinction between a reality show
and a news magazine show,'' said Marc Rosenweig, senior vice
president for programming and production, East Coast, for King
World, the syndicator of ``Inside Edition.'' ``One reason is that
we in news magazines started running these `caught on tape' clips a
decade ago _ authentic ones.''
</P>
<P>
   That experience led ``Inside Edition'' to catch the reality-show
producers in their deceptions. Rosenweig said a producer had
watched several of the reality shows and had become suspicious
because of the multiple camera angles used.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew it was impossible to have the four or five camera
angles they had if it was real,'' he said. ``A real chase would
usually have just one camera, mounted in a police car or somewhere
else, or maybe a surveillance camera in a workplace or store or
something. Knowing what we all know about production, this producer
said we ought to look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenweig added that Fox was not the only network victimized by
such techniques; he had seen cable programs with similar stunts, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The specials are produced for Fox by independent companies. But
in its statement Monday, Fox said that the producers ``must adhere
to'' its policy ``to clearly identify all re-creations,
re-enactments and training videos.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Public TV
</P>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service has lost its chief programming
executive, Kathy Quattrone, to a new venture of Discovery
Communications, a multimedia company called Discovery Health Media
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Quattrone, who worked at PBS for 20 years and headed its
programming division for almost four years, the move is a chance to
join a new kind of company ``at the ground floor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Health is developing a cable channel (to start Aug.
2), a health portal on the Internet (to start June 28), interactive
television, videos for home and professional use and a publishing
unit. She will supervise all these services as senior vice
president for programming and production, reporting to the
company's president, John Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health is both one of the most global and one of the most
personal subjects,'' Ms. Quattrone said Tuesday. ``There are a lot
of opportunities to get people information in a number of different
ways they can use.''
</P>
<P>
   But for PBS, the move adds anxiety to a beleaguered department,
and adds a hefty workload to John Wilson, Ms. Quattrone's top
deputy, who will take over for her on an interim basis. He is
already shouldering the job of chief of children's programming, one
of PBS's most important divisions. The director of that division,
Alice Cahn, left last summer to join the Children's Television
Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quattrone, who was praised within the public broadcasting
system for the way she got stations around the country to agree to
carry prime-time programs simultaneously, also had helped Ms. Cahn
add many lively programs to the PBS children's menu and had been
leading PBS's conversion to digital television.
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure, PBS chief executive Ervin Duggan pointed out
in a memo to stations, ``PBS programs earned an extraordinary
number of prestigious awards, dominating the Peabodys, the du
Ponts, the daytime Emmys and the news and documentary Emmys.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for a successor will begin shortly, said a PBS
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
