   T O R N A D O S T O R I E S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Stunned residents of Oklahoma and Kansas recover
the dead and injured from the devastating series of tornadoes that
raked through the two states Monday night, killing at least three
dozen people. By BILL HANNA. Story will move in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-DEVASTATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The tornado outbreak that tore through Oklahoma
Monday night generated winds up to 300 mph and wreaked devastating
damage, wiping foundations clear of their structures. A look at the
devastation from the twister outbreak. By BETSY BLANEY. Story will
move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-HOSPITALS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Emergency and medical personnel in Oklahoma were
faced Monday night with their worst disaster since the terrorist
bombing of the Oklahoma City federal building April 19, 1995. A
look at the emergency response, including the number of casualties
treated at major facilities. By YVETTE CRAIG. Story will move in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-SHELTERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Thousands of people were left homeless by Monday
night's outbreak of tornadoes and had to seek shelter in emergency
shelters set up in schools and other suriviving buildings by such
organizations as the Red Cross and the Federal Emergency Management
Agency. By JENNIFER AUTREY. Story will move in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-STORM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ What atmospheric conditions are required to brew such
a devastating storm. By ANITA BAKER. Story will move in ``a''
general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-CHICKASHA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKASHA, Okla. _ Chickasha and Bridge Creek, towns southwest
of Oklahoma City, were particularly hard hit by Monday night's
tornado outbreak. Many of those killed near here were in their
cars. By DEANNA BOYD. Story will move in ``a'' general news
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-BOMB VICTIMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The rubble _ and who might be under it _ triggers the
worst memories for Frank Koch, a veteran Oklahoma City policeman
and an up-close witness to terror. Just over four years ago, Koch
began the first of 17 consecutive days inside the twisted and torn
Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building, pulling out people. Some were
still alive, others dead and dismembered by a bomb made of diesel
fuel and fertilizer. On Tuesday, Koch said that he is prepared to
return to the rubble, this time left by massive tornadoes that
ripped through Oklahoma and Kansas on Monday. By JACK DOUGLAS JR.
and MIKE LEE. Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-JUSTICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The twice-monthly meetings of Parents of
Murdered Children's Tarrant County chapter are part of a quiet
revolution. Over the past 20 years, services and support groups
have drawn victims into the criminal justice process, making them
informed and influential participants in prosecutions, observers
say. Still, a growing network of scholars, lawyers and civil
libertarians say that the victims movement has gone too far by
promoting legislation that robs defendants of many constitutional
rights. By MICHAEL WEISSENSTEIN. Story has moved in ``a'' general
news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KILLING GAMES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ By his own reckoning, Lt. Col. David Grossman is ``the
flavor of the day.'' ``60 Minutes'' has recently come calling, with
NBC's ``Today'' show and ``Court TV'' not long behind. Print and
broadcast journalists otherwise fill up Grossman's day in 15-minute
interview chunks. Grossman's message explains his new notoriety,
one as timely as it is troubling. He is a former Green Beret, West
Point psychology professor and now a widely quoted expert on how
soldiers are taught to kill. Those same methods, he says, are also
being employed on our children through the debased images of
television and video games. For children, Grossman says, the media
amounts to boot camp. By TIM MADIGAN. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Questions about the lyrics for the song ``You Are My
Sunshine'' and the college in Ohio where John Glenn teaches. By
ROGERS CADENHEAD. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHAPMAN-TEXAS AT LARGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHART, Texas _ There will be a new altar here soon, a
brilliant new shrine to one of Texas' most revered cultural
treasures _ barbecue. Plans are under way for the ceremonial
placing of the pits at the new Kreuz Market. Kreuz (pronounced
krites) has long been considered one of the top barbecue cathedrals
in the state. Texas Monthly magazine has crowned Kreuz as being
among the best, and so have the thousands of diners from Austin,
San Marcos and San Antonio who gladly travel to this Czech-German
community on U.S. 183 about 20 miles east of San Marcos. By ART
CHAPMAN. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I need your help. I'm issuing an all-points bulletin
for a missing person. I've known her for years, and she's very
special to me. She's been to my home many, many times, but,
unfortunately, I don't have a picture of her. Actually, I can't
even give you a very good description because I've never seen her
face to face. By MONICA ANDERSON. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
