<HEADER>
A4122 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-STADIUM-PA     05-04 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STADIUM-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        SPECTER WANTS NFL AND MAJOR LEAGUE BASEBALL TO PAY FOR HALF
OF STADIUMS   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 4 -- The National Football League or Major
League Baseball would have to pay for half the construction costs
of any new stadium, under a bill introduced today in the Senate by
Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is necessary because baseball and football
have for too long had a public-be-damned attitude,'' said Specter,
R-PA. ``Major League sports is out of control on franchise moves
for football teams and the demands upon cities and states for
exorbitant construction costs is a form of legalized extortion in
major league sports.'' If the bill passes, it would have the
leagues pay 50 percent of construction or renovation costs of
stadiums, with the team owner and public each paying 25 percent.
The bill would require the NFL and Major League baseball to place
10 percent of its television revenues into a trust fund. That
money, would pay for half the cost of construction or renovation of
ballparks and stadiums if the local government agrees to pay one
dollar for every two trust fund dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the problem of the high costs of stadium
construction is especially acute in Pennsylvania, where there are
four projects underway with a more than $1 billion dollar price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Two stadiums are under construction in Western Pennsylvania for
the Pirates and Steelers, and two more are being sought in Eastern
Pennsylvania for the Eagles and Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of sports franchises to their owners has ballooned
in recent years,'' Specter said. ``These revenues are shared by the
club and their players. One would think some of that giant revenue
windfall might trickle down and be used to help finance new
ballparks and stadiums, which produce greatly enhanced revenues for
team owners, yet it seems the more network TV money a league makes,
the more its clubs demand from local taxpayers to fund the
construction of new playing facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also extend an anti-trust exemption to give the
authority to the NFL to deny a member club's request to move its
franchise to a different city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe a federal law of this type is necessary,''
said Joe Browne, a spokesman for the NFL. ``Its players have
contributed hundreds of millions of dollars for public-private
partnerships and stadium projects throughout the 1990s. We
anticipate contributing additional substantial revenues to future
stadiums.'' Major League Baseball did not return phone calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
