<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-0505-COX     05-04 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-0505-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS SUPPORT BILL TO PROTECT STATE TOBACCO
SETTLEMENTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bolstered by state and local officials, a
bipartisan group of senators Tuesday urged Congress to bar the
federal government from seizing any portion of the nearly $250
billion in tobacco settlements with states or dictating how the
money must be used.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations representing the nation's governors, mayors, state
legislatures, counties and cities joined Sens. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, and George Voinovich, R-Ohio, to
support adding the proposed legislation to an emergency
appropriations bill designed to aid domestic and international
victims of last fall's hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to see final action early this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Michael O. Leavitt, R-Utah, said a recent poll indicated
that citizens would rather see state governments -- instead of the
federal government -- decide how to spend tobacco settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Clarence Anthony of South Bay, Fla., president of the
National League of Cities, urged Congress to allow the tobacco
money to be spent by the government ``that is closest to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the Clinton administration's claim that the federal
government -- which contributes to state Medicaid payments -- is
entitled to about 60 percent of the state tobacco settlements. The
actual amount would vary from state to state. In Florida it would
be about 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's major tobacco companies have agreed to pay the
states nearly $250 billion over the next quarter century. Florida
and Texas settled separate suits -- Florida for $13 billion, Texas
for $15.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a former governor, said the federal government is not
entitled to the money because the settlements came in response to
state suits. Congressional efforts to dictate how the money should
be spent is based on an arrogant view that the federal government
is more responsible than state governments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the states are acting responsibly,'' Graham
said. ``We don't have to assume that the states require the federal
government to hold their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said that if Congress dictates how the tobacco money
should be spent, each state would have to get federal approval
before it could spend any settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Without assurances that states can spend the money as they
choose, she said programs aimed at children's health and smoking
cessation could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich, another former governor, said state and local
officials can do a better job of targeting where the money should
be spent than federal officials. ``So often people in Washington
think that they know more about local people than state and local
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
