<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, May 5. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-STORMS (Oklahoma City) _ Ledeall: Devastating tornadoes too
numerous to count roared across Oklahoma and Kansas. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-SCENE (Bridge Creek, Okla.) _ The scene of devastation in
Bridge Creek, a small town near Oklahoma City destroyed by the
storm. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Serbs and a few
Albanians are trickling back to Pristina, Kosovo's capital. The
sunny daytime streets, with a few pedestrians and shoppers, now
display a poor imitation of ordinary life, so long as one doesn't
focus too hard on the empty, looted Albanian districts, the bomb
damage and the nearly total lack of children in the town. By Steven
Erlanger. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   EVEREST (Undated) _ The discovery of a body high on the slopes
of Mount Everest reported to be George Mallory, who disappeared in
1924, raises anew speculation on whether he reached the summit,
beating Edmund Hillary, credited with Nepalese Sherpa Tenzing
Norgay with being the first to reach the top in 1953. By
Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Describing the graphic details of a
police brutality charge that rocked New York City, a federal
prosecutor holds that a Haitian immigrant was beaten and tortured
by police officers who turned a precinct station house bathroom
into a ``torture chamber.'' By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-DEFECT (Washington) _ The game ended around midnight on
Monday, and for the next few hours, the Cuban baseball team and
their band of noisy supporters continued celebrating a 12-6 victory
over the Baltimore Orioles in the hotel where the team and its
300-member delegation were staying. But when the group made a hasty
departure from the Baltimore-Washington International Airport for
Havana, at least seven members of the traveling party were missing.
American government officials say one coach defected. Cuban
government officials say the other six Cubans overslept. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Los Angeles) _ Compare the last episode of
``Seinfeld'' with the recent taping of the final episode of ``Home
Improvement,'' a prime-time hit on ABC for the past eight seasons.
After a tearful Tim Allen, the star, told a joke for a cast and
crew drenched in tears, they taped a slightly maudlin story,
scheduled to air on May 25, in which Allen's character reaffirms
his love for his wife and family, and his loyal sidekick finds the
love that had long eluded him, lending the closing a poignant moral
gravity. The episode is touching, and a historical relic, as the
traditional family sitcom goes the way of the western. By James
Sterngold. 1,587 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
