<HEADER>
A4134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-WEBSHOPPING-COX     05-04 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-WEBSHOPPING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN gets into web shopping
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ These are the two key factors behind that nifty black
``Shop(at)CNN'' icon in the right hand corner of every CNN.com
page. First, online shopping is hotter than hot. Second, analysts
say Web surfers don't mind seeing ads for BellSouth, Fidelity
Investments or Toyota mixed in with news and other information
sites.
</P>
<P>
   This is all the information you need to know to understand the
reason for the debut of the mini-shopping section, dubbed
``Shop(at)CNN'' which offers users the opportunity to engage in a
little electronic commerce while catching up on the news of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Shop(at)CNN retailers include Barnes and Noble, FlowerClub, the
TotalE online music store, the Internet Travel Network and Staples.
There are five categories now, but CNN says it plans to eventually
have 16.
</P>
<P>
   Users who click on the Shop icon, will see a smaller browser
window open up within the CNN window, so there won't be any
confusion about whether you are reading news or shopping. Should
you decide to browse, the window will expand to full size, but if
you close the window, the CNN site will still be right there
waiting for you.
</P>
<P>
   The caliber of retailers CNN has recruited may make Shop(at)CNN
a feature users like. In addition it's also an excellent ``sticky
product'' that will keep users dallying on the CNN site longer than
they might otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   On the sales side, CNN is hoping the site will draw more
advertisers to the site and promises to deliver an upscale audience
of news junkies who will spend money on books, CD's, office
supplies and videos.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bernstein, CNN senior vice president and general manager,
CNN Interactive, says research shows that CNN users are 141 percent
more likely than the average Web user to make an online purchase.
It's a clever an unobtrusive concept that should add value to users
and generate revenue for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
