A4138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NET-HEALTHCARE-ADAM-C     05-04 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-HEALTHCARE-ADAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the end, the dot's the difference for internet health company
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ And Dot Com it is.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM Internet Health today will change its name to Adam.com
Inc., solidifying its Internet identity as it announces another
deal aimed at propelling the company to the front of the pack in
Net healthcare information.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM, originally ADAM Software, this week landed a deal that
will put its content _ including more than 4,000 medical topics _
on Netscape Netcenter, a portal that leads Net users to a variety
of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is an extension of a previous agreement with Excite,
the search engine used on Netcenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is another step toward making Adam.com the leader
in consumer health information on the Internet,'' said Chairman and
Chief Executive Robert Cramer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Adam would have to outpace a local rival _ WebMD
Inc., which has announced a series of high-profile partnerships,
including a $220 million investment from DuPont. WebMD has
announced its intent for a public offering of stock, a move that
has already drawn much investor interest.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Adam has until recently been struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Founded a decade ago, Adam was for a long time a premier maker
of software and CD-ROMs with medical diagrams and information.
Although its reputation for quality remained solid, the company hit
some tough times several years ago, suffering losses and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has changed that, Cramer said. In addition to
putting Adam content on the Excite and Netcenter sites, the deals
will put links back to Adam on those sites, he said. ``Now we have
a distribution system that will allow us to reach tens of millions
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Netcenter and Excite deals Adam has an agreement
with the CNN Networks.
</P>
<P>
   But Adam receives a fee for providing its content, while others
pay for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is significantly different and significantly
better,'' Cramer said. ``The difference is that we own our content.
I think content ownership is key.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, which has a partnership with Adam, paid $52 million to be
featured on the Lycos network.
</P>
<P>
   Adam has apparently been noticed by investors. Company stock,
which languished in the doldrums for much of last year, has lately
come alive.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a 52-week low of $2.25 a share in November, Adam
increased in value by more than 400 percent by Monday when it
closed at $12.
</P>
<P>
   Adam on Tuesday sipped 75 cents a share to close at $11.25.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
