<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-BANK-COX     05-04 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BANK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lines may be shorter at neighborhood bank branches
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When was the last time you walked into your bank?
</P>
<P>
   If success stories like Net.B(at)nk and new Internet ventures by
traditional bankers like Synovus Financial are any indication, foot
traffic in traditional bank branches may continue to dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 17 of the 100 largest banks offered their customers
the ability to turn their PCs into ATMs, to look up their account
balances and transfer funds online. This year, 22 more banks
started offering those services, said Chris Musto, a research
analyst with Gomez Advisors, a Massachusetts firm that studies
financial services on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable that in the near future, a bank customer will
have his paycheck direct deposited, get and pay bills
electronically, make withdrawals from an ATM and transfer funds
between accounts by telephone. None of which require a visit to the
neighborhood bank.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have offered their customers the option of paying bills
through their PC software for years.
</P>
<P>
   But Alpharetta, Ga.-based Net.B(at)nk is one of a handful of
banks _ Atlanta's Security First Network Bank and Virginia-based
TeleBank among them _ that have taken ultimate advantage of the
Internet's efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   By operating mostly as an Internet-only bank, Net.B(at)nk,
Security First Network Bank and TeleBank are able to save the money
it costs to build and staff branches. Some of that savings is
passed on to customers in the form of higher interest rates on
accounts. Last week, Security First Network Bank announced a
introductory interest rate of 6 percent for a checking account,
almost four times the national average, according to Bank Rate
Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has noticed. Shares of Net.B(at)nk and TeleBank hit
52-week highs in April. Net.B(at)nk shares are up 529 percent for
1999. TeleBank's stock has increased 164 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, traditional banks are seeing the potential. Last month,
Sovereign Bancorp, North Fork Bancorp and Synovus Financial
announced they are filing for separately chartered, Internet-only
banks. Synovus plans to have an Internet-mostly bank that will be
able to offer lower rates than its traditional bank cousin by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet-only bank is a more efficient option,'' said
James D. Yancey, Synovus Financial president. ``You can't compete
from a price standpoint with an Internet-only bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Yancey said it costs about $1.5 million to open a traditional
branch in typical Synovus markets. He said setting up and running
Synovus' Internet-only bank will cost about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Musto, of Gomez Advisors, has been rating the online banking
services every three months for the last year.
</P>
<P>
   He said the traditional banks are starting to open separately
chartered Internet-mostly branches for defensive and offensive
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a green field strategy,'' he said. ``How do you
cope with a potential disruption from doing business and at the
same time plant the seeds of future growth? And for the Internet
bank, it gives them access to the power and the leverage of the
overall firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Musto said the so-called ``branchless'' banks are still small by
traditional bank standards. TeleBank has about 50,000 accounts,
Net.B(at)nk has about 30,000, Security First Network Bank has less
than 16,000. Wells Fargo, on the other hand, has 820,000 customers
doing their banking online. The San Francisco-based bank added
164,000 in the first three months of this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bruene, Online Banking Report editor, said banks also are
chartering Internet-mostly banks because the market is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Net.B(at)nk started as an online venture by Carolina First Bank
that paid off and set an example, Bruene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carolina First's gain on paper from Net.B(at)nk stock is in
the tens of million of dollars and that's before the stock went
whacko,'' he said. ``It was an incredible grand slam for them. If
you're a bank, you look at that and say, 'Wow. How can we do
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bruene said synovusbank.com should do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a wonderful medium for financial services.
It's such an ideal way for customers and a financial institution to
interact.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruene said he does not see the branch disappearing altogether.
People still like to know there are humans connected to all the
technology to which they trust their money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you see a lot less square feet devoted to banking,''
Bruene said. ``In California, they are starting to ration the
branch system. You see kiosks inside grocery stores as opposed to
12,000 square-feet on the corner. There's still a human. But all
you need is a kiosk. You don't need that huge monument. Unless the
people want to pay for them. It's up to us to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
