<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONKONG-MARKET-NYT &LR;      05-04 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONKONG-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET FRENZY HITS HONG KONG MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Investors here are usually entranced by tycoons
rather than technology. Put them together, though, and it can whip
up a high-tech frenzy to rival the Nasdaq as its frothiest.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Tricom Holdings Ltd., a telecommunications
provider that labored in obscurity until Tuesday, when Richard Li
announced a plan to take it over and turn it into a vehicle for his
Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Tricom's stock went on a wild ride, multiplying in value by as
much as 24 times before closing at $1.83 (Hong Kong), or 23 cents
(U.S.). That was a 1,246 percent increase from its previous closing
price. Although Tricom trades at penny-stock levels, about $240
million worth of the shares changed hands, making it the most
active issue on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a frenzy about anything that's Internet-related,
regardless of what the business is,'' said Joseph Locke, a
telecommunications analyst at ABN Amro. ``The Hong Kong market
doesn't seem to make a distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tricom's case, the business may matter less than its backer.
Li is the son of the legendary Hong Kong tycoon, Li Ka-shing. He is
trying to become a high-tech version of his father, with plans to
build a $2 billion technology park in Hong Kong and a satellite
service that will deliver Internet access across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Li's announcement that he would fold his technology ventures
into Tricom and rename it Pacific Century Cyberworks was enough to
create Hong Kong's equivalent of Netscape Communications _ a stock
that takes off like a rocket on little more than the vague promise
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a piece of good news for Hong Kong,'' said Alexander
Arena, who will be managing director of the new company. ``There's
obviously a pent-up demand for these kinds of stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tricom is not the only Hong Kong company to be caught in the
Internet frenzy. Earlier this year, two local telephone providers,
Hong Kong Telecom and Smartone Telecommunications Holdings Ltd.,
announced Internet deals with Microsoft and Yahoo, respectively.
Though the announcements were notably short of details, they turned
both companies into shooting stars.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the insatiable demand for technology stocks has
helped fuel the remarkable rally in the Hong Kong market, which has
risen more than 20 percent since March. On Tuesday, the Hang Seng
Index rose 223 points, closing at 13,559. During the morning
session, when Tricom was at its peak, the Hang Seng hit 13,690 _
its highest level since before the market crash in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Hong Kong would seem to be fertile ground for an
Internet business. More than 15 percent of people here have
personal computers and about 10 percent subscribe to an online
service.
</P>
<P>
   But other so-called broadband services have failed to take root.
Hong Kong Telecom, the territory's largest Internet service
provider, started an interactive television service in March 1998.
The service, called iTV, fell far short of its target of 250,000
subscribers by the end of its first year.
</P>
<P>
   In teaming up with Microsoft, Hong Kong Telecom said its goal
was to create entertainment, information and business services that
would be transmitted over its network to personal computers and
televisions. Microsoft's participation is not exclusive, however,
and there is no guarantee it will work with Hong Kong Telecom
beyond the 90-day development period.
</P>
<P>
   Because Li developed Star TV, Asia's first and largest
satellite-delivered cable television service, analysts here are
prepared to give the 32-year-old entrepreneur the benefit of the
doubt on this new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies in Hong Kong are way behind the curve in the
Internet,'' said Mac Overton, an independent portfolio manager.
``If you believe Richard Li has a game plan and is ahead of the
curve, this company could become the Amazon.com or Cisco of the
Asia region.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Li is guarded about what assets Pacific Century
Cyberworks will contain. Arena said, for example, that Li would
contribute the planned satellite Internet service only if he
obtained the approval of his joint venture partner, Intel Corp. The
same is true of Cyberport, a $2 billion technology park that Li is
building with the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberport has set off a rancorous controversy here, as rival
property developers have accused the government of donating prime
real estate to Li for a project that will include lucrative
residential buildings.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about cyberspace, some experts said that buying
shares of Tricom was a cheap way to participate in a real estate
deal. Investors in Hong Kong have rarely been able to pass up that
kind of opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
