<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRTUAL-ASSISTANT-COX     05-04 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-ASSISTANT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth adding virtual service
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The idea is in the name: virtual assistant.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the phone line is the disembodied voice of
woman, sounding somewhere over 30. She is friendly but not perky.
Polite but not intimate. Efficient but not Prussian, she reads you
your e-mail and voice mail, helps update your calendar.
</P>
<P>
   You suggest a response to this or that message. She assures you
it will be sent.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally she asks you to repeat a command, but generally the
conversation flows smoothly. Perhaps you are interrupted, so you
ask her to wait. She wordlessly waits until you are done, then is
instantly ready for your next summons.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, you may forget that your assistant is actually a
bundle of software code, connected to a sizable database residing
on a computer server in California.
</P>
<P>
   This virtual assistant is the latest version of Portico from
California-based General Magic. Until now, it has been available
only through resellers, but BellSouth on Tuesday became the first
phone company to piggyback the service on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Some BellSouth wireless customers can get it now as part of a
trial, while Portico _ which will probably be given a different
name for purposes of BellSouth marketing _ will be generally
available next month.
</P>
<P>
   Portico can be used from a land-line phone or via the Internet's
Web, but it is perhaps not an accident that its first offering is
to BellSouth's wireless customers only.
</P>
<P>
   Portico is meant to give BellSouth another lure in the effort to
retain the high-end customers of wireless service _ something that
the company has lacked. Mostly mobile professionals, many of those
big-spending customers have been drawn to AT&AMP;T, Sprint or even
Nextel. Companies that have national presence can offer calling
plans that treat calls the same whether they are made in Marietta,
Ga. or Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, whose wireless service is mainly in the Southeast and
has only recently started to fight back, announced one-rate plans
pitched at customers who travel _ and use a lot of wireless phone
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is that this is a tool for people who are
mobile,'' said BellSouth spokeswoman Kristie Madara. ``It is aimed
toward mobile professionals who mostly would be using it on a
wireless phone.''
</P>
<P>
   At $30 a month _ not much less than an average monthly cellular
bill _ it is clearly not aimed at a casual consumer. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a mass consumer product yet,'' Madara said. ``This is
the first step to see how customers react to things like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Meisel, president of TMA Associates and editor of Speech
Recognition Update, said he thinks BellSouth's offering will start
off a bit pricey. And Portico's Web capabilities lag behind the
best desktop personal information managers.
</P>
<P>
   But its voice-recognition power is substantial, and the
potential market for telephone assistance is huge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Internet sites known as portals, a phone assistant will
eventually be seen as a gateway to various kinds of information and
services, he said. For instance, Portico already can be programmed
to call a user with selected stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from similar phone services could surpass $1 billion
next year and then double the year after, Meisel said. ``I think I
may have been a little optimistic about how fast it will take off,
but I think that it will grow very rapidly once it is broadly
introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   A Portico user can choose among several different voices, from a
hard-driving male to the low-key woman that General Magic used this
week in a demonstration. The voices have been created with
profiles, general identities meant to be implicitly carried in the
sound of the voice and to appeal to the real human customers at the
other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange as it sounds, people bond with it,'' said Andre
Nakaso, director of business development for General Magic.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few good business reasons for that. First, a
customer who begins to think of the virtual assistant as a person
is less apt to dump the service. And switching to a competing
service should become harder than just switching phones. That is,
if the customer thinks of this less as a product than a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The $30-a-month rate for Portico will permit unlimited use. But
of course, if the customer enjoys talking to the virtual assistant,
that could very well translate to more time on the wireless phone _
which would likely mean higher revenue for BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between General Magic and BellSouth means Portico
will not be offered in any markets in which BellSouth has a
wireless business. And with the service, General Magic and
BellSouth are combining several key elements seen by analysts as
the next technology wave.
</P>
<P>
   First is the notion of voice-enabled computing, which has been
kicking around various labs for decades. Yet in recent years the
technology has taken tremendous strides, with the best-known
products coming from IBM, Philips and Dragon Software.
</P>
<P>
   A bevy of techno-gurus has also predicted the coming of
``pervasive computing,'' in which computers will be linked to
myriad functions in everyday life. Already, computers dominate
automotive technology.
</P>
<P>
   Combining voice-enable technology with the desire to put
computers in our homes and soon people will perform all sorts of
tasks from afar, from starting the oven to turning on an alarm
system.
</P>
<P>
   Portico stops short of that but has taken the first large step:
unified messaging. The idea is one of convenience, that most people
would like access to e-mail, voice mail and faxes all through one
source.
</P>
<P>
   General Magic is not the only company that has noticed the
potential in these markets. For instance, Atlanta-based Premier
Technologies uses software from Intellivoice to build a system for
unified messaging.
</P>
<P>
   But General Magic's Portico talks to you. Perhaps as
importantly, it listens to you and _ if all goes well _ it does
what you say.
</P>
<P>
   Portico is programmed to respond to ``grammar,'' to phrases,
expressions and sentences and not just single words. That means it
can respond to more than 2 million different phrases and is not
bothered by ``ummms, ahhs, wouldja or couldja,'' Nakaso said.
</P>
<P>
   But ask something incoherent or otherwise outside her job
skills, and that woman's voice at the other end of the line will
not answer. The virtual assistant is not supposed to respond to
non-business conversation or personal questions.
</P>
<P>
   So there is no point in asking her for even a virtual date.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
