<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-ART-NYT     05-04 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY 4 ARRIVES, BUT PALESTINIAN STATEHOOD DOES NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARAM, West Bank _ If Tuesday had turned out to be the ``sacred
date'' that Yasser Arafat had promised, Artistic Studio Co. here
would have been cranking out Palestinian flags, stickers and
T-shirts by the tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Samir Joubeh, an owner, would have had no time to sip hot coffee
laced with cardamom. The three workers who listlessly silkscreened
tank tops would have had the company of a dozen more laborers. And
the machines would have been buzzing with the business of
Palestinian statehood, not with Adidas knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no May 4,'' Joubeh said. ``There is no business.
And, most significantly, there is no Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Arafat took May 4 off the Palestinian calendar. For
months he had been promising to declare a state in the West Bank
and Gaza on this date, when final-status peace talks were supposed
to have been completed under the terms of the Oslo peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the final talks have barely begun and, bowing to
international pressure, Arafat and the Palestinian leadership have
recommitted themselves to the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian National Authority decreed that Tuesday would be
a normal workday, and it was. Arafat traveled abroad as usual.
There were a few small protest marches. In Hebron, Palestinians who
marched brandishing weapons clashed with Israeli police; 17 were
wounded, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Israeli government that made the day into a moment _
its moment: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu called a news
conference to take credit for Arafat's ``backing off'' a unilateral
declaration of a Palestinian state ``with Jerusalem as its
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he understood that our response would be very firm,''
said Netanyahu, flanked by Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and
Defense Minister Moshe Arens.
</P>
<P>
   In the Palestinian daily newspaper Al Quds, a political cartoon
Tuesday showed a calendar with an annotation May 4: ``Never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   On a small scale a battle over Jerusalem's fate, a particularly
thorny issue, took place late Tuesday afternoon in a small corner
of the city. There was a potential for volatile clashes, but
Israeli police officers formed a tight buffer between two
gatherings _ one Palestinian, one Jewish _ a few blocks apart.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the American Colony Hotel, several hundred
Palestinians gathered to defend Orient House, which was draped with
a giant Palestinian flag. Orient House is a Palestinian institution
that the Netanyahu government has threatened to close, saying it
operates illegally.
</P>
<P>
   And on the other side of the hotel, thousands of religious Jews
converged on the tomb of a holy man both to celebrate Lag b'Omer, a
minor holiday, and to mark their attempt to reclaim Sheik Jarrah, a
Palestinian neighborhood, for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the divide, there were fiery speeches in Arabic
asserting Palestinian claims to Jerusalem, accompanied by the
bagpipe music that is customary at formal Palestinian events.
Israeli police officers guarded the gates, chasing away the handful
of Israelis who cruised by in cars, shouting insults in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, in the heart of a Palestinian neighborhood,
crowds of Jews gathered in a rocky field beneath three huge Israeli
flags. The flags crowned the rooftops of houses that three Jewish
couples and six yeshiva students have recently settled as part of a
campaign to re-establish a Jewish presence there.
</P>
<P>
   A banner in Hebrew read, ``Jerusalem United Forever,'' and a
popular Hasidic musician, Mordechai Ben David, performed. His
albums include ``Jerusalem Is Not for Sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Palestinian nor the Israeli gathering was ostensibly
connected to the May 4 date. But it permeated both events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of turned into a party to celebrate the end of
Oslo,'' said Judy Balint, an organizer of the Jewish event. ``The
Oslo agreement is dust, if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian agreement negotiated in Oslo laid out an
interim period that hard-liners on both sides believe to be over,
canceling everything agreed to. But both sides have extended their
commitment to the accord.
</P>
<P>
   It is less than two weeks before the Israeli elections, and in
warrior campaign mode, Netanyahu and his key ministers kept
swinging Tuesday even though Tuesday's fight was over.
</P>
<P>
   They warned of retaliation _ annexation of West Bank land, a
cutoff of Oslo-mandated tax payments to the Palestinians _ should
Arafat contemplate a unilateral declaration of statehood in the
future. But Netanyahu also made it clear that even negotiated
Palestinian statehood, which polls show most Israelis would accept,
is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could bring in weapons, missiles, planes, tanks,
artillery,'' Netanyahu said. ``It could make military pacts with
other countries, like Iran and Iraq. It could build terror bases to
a greater extent, on our doorstep, at the edge of our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's opponents criticized his news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw was a propaganda show, which is designed to turn
what in my opinion is the greatest failure in the history of
Israeli foreign policy into an achievement,'' said Shlomo Ben Ami,
a high-ranking Labor Party official. ``We are at May 4, the
Palestinian state is an accomplished fact, and the last push to its
founding was given by Netanyahu himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Sarid, leader of the Meretz Party, asked: ``The
Palestinian state doesn't already exist? Then I don't know what a
state is. They have territory, an elected president and an elected
parliament. They have an anthem, a flag, a symbol and relations
with more than 100 countries. High-ranking visitors come and go.
They have an army that is called a police force.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in withdrawing his pledge to declare statehood, told
Palestinians that the state more or less already exists, with broad
support abroad if not that from the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they like it or not, our state is already
established,'' Arafat told reporters Monday night, on his return
from Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   At the small flag and sticker factory in this town just outside
Jerusalem, Joubeh seemed skeptical of the claim. He said
Palestinian business people are enduring an agonizing limbo, a
complaint echoed by many in Gaza, too, who say the economy is
paralyzed because the future of the peace talks is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Joubeh showed off one of his few new products, a sign of how
closely Israelis and Palestinians are linked even in this
conflicted moment: not Palestinian flags, but bumper stickers for
Yitzhak Mordechai, a candidate for prime minister of Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
