u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTEL-FIBEROPTIC-BOS     05-04 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-FIBEROPTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL UNIT DEVELOPS HIGH-CAPACITY FIBEROPTIC TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A subsidiary of Canada's Northern Telecom Ltd. says it has
developed a technology that will massively increase the capacity of
the world's telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel Networks Carrier Packet Solutions in Billerica, Mass.
plans to bring the product to market next year.
</P>
<P>
   The new data compression method will allow a single strand of
optical fiber to carry 160 high-speed data streams at the same
time. That would mean that a single strand, about the thickness of
a human hair, could transmit the contents of the Library of
Congress in just a few seconds, or support 28 million Internet
users at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Valovic, research manager for optical networking at
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass., said the Nortel
system would prevent what communications engineers call ``fiber
exhaust,'' a situation in which the optical fiber in a network is
crammed to capacity with data. ``The name of the game is capacity,
pure and simple,'' Valovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optic cables transmit data as pulses of laser light.
Booming Internet use is rapidly consuming the capacity of existing
fibers. So Nortel and other fiber optic technology companies have
been scurrying to find ways to squeeze more signal onto existing
fiber cables, rather than force telephone and Internet companies to
lay new cables.
</P>
<P>
   The favored approach, and the one used by Nortel, is called
``dense wavelength division multiplexing.'' This is a way of
squeezing many different streams of laser light, each with a
slightly different ``color'' or wavelength, onto one strand of
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Valovic said that a massive increase in data network capacity
won't translate quickly into lower telecommunications costs,
because it'll cost many millions of dollars to install the new
technology. ``It'll take a long time for the benefits to get to the
end user,'' he said, ``but we've got to make these systems cheaper,
easier to deploy, and then we'll see the costs come down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
