<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKOREA-GENERATION-GAP     05-04 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-GENERATION-GAP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAN PASTE VS. MINISKIRTS: GENERATION GAP GROWS IN KOREA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOK, South Korea _ A blast of steam caught Park Ki Soon in the
face as she peered into the caldron of beans and began stirring,
feeling ever more sorry for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young I did what my mother-in-law said,'' Mrs.
Park, 70, said morosely as she used a wooden paddle to churn the
beans. ``But now my daughter-in-law doesn't listen to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now I'm making this bean paste, and I'm feeling miserable
because I'm an old woman and she's using me. I don't know why she
doesn't make bean paste herself. I think she just wants to be
comfortable. She never likes hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The small group of women clustered around Mrs. Park, here in the
village of Hanok about 30 miles northwest of Seoul, nodded their
heads in agreement. Young Koreans, they concluded, are
incomprehensible and insufferable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to the cities, I look at young people, the way they
dress, the way they behave, and they aren't Korean,'' said Choi Sam
Soon, 55, who was also making bean paste. ``Young people always
carry credit cards, and they get money from machines! They always
spend money so recklessly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And young people abandon things that are still usable,'' Mrs.
Choi added, shaking her head at the idea. ``Some people throw out
old kettles, so I pick them up and take them home and use them.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that young people are not thrilled
about having their mothers or mothers-in-law rifling through other
people's garbage to rescue battered old kettles. And such
skirmishes are only one facet of a generation gap that many South
Koreans say is greater than almost anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Korea was one of the last places to open up to Western
influences; until a century ago it was an ancient kingdom that
operated on Confucian traditions and deeply regimented customs.
Those customs _ especially respect for the elderly _ permeated
Korean society until the last few decades.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, South Korea has been one of the
fastest-changing societies in the world. The economy grew at a
blistering pace, the country industrialized and urbanized, a middle
class emerged, and these days respect tends to go to those with
money and e-mail accounts, not to the old men and women who make
great bean paste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generation gaps exist everywhere, but the gap is wider here,
because Western culture is pouring in at an amazing speed,'' said
Annette E.Y. Ahn, 28, an interpreter in Seoul who grew up partly in
the United States and Europe. ``I also think it's wider here
because looking back in history, we were the last country to open
up to Western culture, and now the doors are open and it's pouring
in.''
</P>
<P>
   These gaps seem to cause misunderstandings and sadness, but
fewer open explosions than one might expect. Young and old alike
may stew inside at the foolishness of the other, but they also
describe how they go out of their way to accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant bother to live with the old folks,'' said
Chong Kum Sook, 38, who lives in the same house as her husband's
parents. ``It's very hard. It's not that they complain, but I feel
the burden on myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My in-laws are early risers, so I try to get up when they do.
And in the summer I can't wear skimpy clothes, because I have to
dress cautiously so as not to disturb them. I should be careful not
to make them unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Korean women were traditionally expected to dress very primly,
and indeed a young woman was arrested for indecency just four years
ago when she wore a T-shirt that exposed her navel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see girls exposing themselves in short dresses, I'm
shocked,'' said Koh Kap In, a 79-year-old matriarch who was sitting
outside her house. ``But I've never said a word to my
granddaughters. It's the times. All the young women are in those
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   Most elderly Koreans say that they are often shocked at the
laziness, immorality or extravagance of young people, but that
mostly they bite their tongues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I complain, would they listen?'' asked Kim Hae Song, 78, a
stooped woman who was outside weeding her garden. ``No. That would
only put them on bad terms with me. In my heart I feel upset at
what goes on, but I don't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kim and her husband, Kwon Sang Mook, 81, are most offended
at the disappearance of traditional etiquette, which young people
often breach without even realizing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see young people smoking in front of their elders,'' Kwon
said, shaking his head. ``Young people say they are so smart, but
what is the point of knowledge if you don't know how to behave?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   The elderly often seem particularly poignant because, mixed in
with the outrage at the way their grandchildren or daughters-in-law
behave, there is also often pride at their education and
worldliness.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her kitchen, Lee Hee Ja, 58, a housewife, served
coffee and a 40-minute denunciation of young people. She fretted
that her eldest daughter-in-law will not carry on the family
rituals, that her second daughter-in-law has not minded her advice
to dress modestly, that neither can cook properly and that none of
the young people are attentive enough to her own needs. But then
Mrs. Lee paused, smiled and sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm wrong,'' she said. ``Young people now are very
bright. So smart! So I don't know. Maybe in the end my
daughters-in-law will be better than I was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-NYT &LR;      05-04 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS TO WELCOME CLINTON AS SUPPORT FOR WAR WAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ President Clinton is to arrive in Germany on Wednesday
for a two-day visit intended to demonstrate allied unity and to
bolster the German government, which is under increasing pressure
over NATO's air campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said no diplomatic breakthrough was expected
during Clinton's stay and made clear that the bombing was expected
to continue at least into next week, despite the president's
allusion on Monday to the possibility of a pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, up to now, Slobodan Milosevic has scarcely moved,''
said one senior German official, referring to the Yugoslav
president. ``I do not see any imminent possibility of a halt to the
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer NATO's campaign goes on, the more frayed the
``red-green'' coalition of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder may become.
Already, Schroeder is facing some vociferous calls for an end to
the war from within his own Social Democratic Party and from the
once pacifist Greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing of Serbia cannot be justified from any possible
standpoint,'' Oskar Lafontaine, a prominent Social Democrat and
former finance minister in Schroeder's government, said last
weekend. ``It is wrong to label whole groups of people good or
evil. It is senseless to bomb bridges and then turn around and plan
how to rebuild them.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was Lafontaine's first since he quit the
government in March. It reflected growing uneasiness on the left of
the Social Democratic Party, although up to now such antiwar
feeling has been fairly muted.
</P>
<P>
   The growing criticism has involved allegations that the bombing
violates international law, outrage over civilian deaths and
uneasiness at the high cost of the war. Schroeder told his party on
Monday that the United States is paying 90 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, minority partners in the government, are to hold a
party congress next week that is certain to reflect its sharp
divisions over the war. If a motion for an immediate stop to the
bombing is passed, the coalition could be endangered. But Joschka
Fischer, the Green foreign minister, will strive to avert such a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not Great Britain,'' said one official close to
Schroeder. ``This war is not an easy sell to a people whose
pacifist feelings are still strong. That is one reason why the
picture of Clinton and Schroeder standing together is so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be particularly important because German uneasiness is
such that any suggestion of the use of ground troops could lead to
the fall of the government. And without ground forces, or even the
threat of their use, NATO's air campaign could be extremely long.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has found itself at the center of Balkan diplomacy over
the past week, striving to use its strong ties with Russia to coax
Russia toward support of the allied demands in Kosovo. These
demands include the withdrawal of Yugoslav troops, the return of
all refugees, and their protection by an international military
force.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said Russia appeared to have moved some way
toward realizing that it had greater interest in supporting the
West than in supporting Milosevic. Germany said Tuesday that it
would be host to a meeting of foreign ministers from the Group of
Seven major industrialized nations, plus Russia, in Bonn on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also be in Bonn that day. The meeting will be aimed
above all at demonstrating Russian backing for most of NATO's aims,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working above all to secure a single front,'' said
Michael Steiner, the chief diplomatic adviser to Schroeder, ``and
to make sure that Milosevic's World War III tactics make no
headway.''
</P>
<P>
   German officials with normally reliable intelligence say they
have detected some indications of cracks in Milosevic's support.
``Those who back Milosevic because they depend on him see that he
cannot protect them any longer,'' said one official. ``Internal
opposition is growing, and that could become clear next week.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say what might happen next week, or where the
focus of resistance might emerge.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether allied countries were working on a covert
plan for Milosevic's overthrow _ something they publicly deny _ and
whether the official was indulging in propaganda or wishful
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The core of Milosevic's backing has traditionally come from a
small group of ministers and political allies who have been granted
lucrative control of various import-export businesses, from the
well-paid architects of the government's propaganda, and from a
cosseted core of military police. The army has been more
ambivalent, at least until the NATO campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting Schroeder on Thursday, Clinton is to visit
American military bases in Germany that have played a role in the
Kosovo campaign, meet Kosovar Albanian refugees who have come to
Germany, and talk to the three American soldiers released from
Yugoslav captivity on Sunday. They are at an American military
hospital near Ramstein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
