<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS THREATEN ENTERTAINMENT INDUSTRY OVER VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top senators on Tuesday warned the makers of
violent films and video games to stop targeting children in their
advertising or the government would do it for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us wants to resort to regulation, but if the
entertainment industry does not do something to change their
methods, we will be forced to act,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., told the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the mass killing at a high school in
Littleton, Colo., several key senators accused the entertainment
industry of luring young viewers with violence and threatened to
investigate the industry's marketing strategies if it did not start
to police the targeting of advertising toward minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not hard to guess who they're trying to sell to when
violent films are advertised on MTV, and directors pick teen idols
to star in their films and video games are sold at `Toys R' Us'
stores,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
said he would propose having the Federal Trade Commission probe
whether entertainment companies are marketing violent films, music
and videos to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans were justifiably outraged when it was
discovered that tobacco companies marketed cigarettes to
children,'' Hatch said. ``I believe that we should be equally
concerned if we find that violent music and video games are being
marketed to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the state and federal governments, tobacco
companies have pulled mascots and advertising that appealed to
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch added that he was considering an ``enforcement mechanism''
for the current ratings systems to ensure that children cannot
watch movies or buy video games without parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the entertainment industry voluntarily rates each
movie and video game according to the amount of violence, sex and
offensive language in the product. The ratings are used by theaters
and video rental stores to theoretically prevent minors from
watching or buying inappropriate material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite a comprehensive rating system, there is little
evidence that such ratings are enforced or even taken seriously,''
said Hatch, who did not explain how the mechanism would work.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the National Institute on Media and the Family found
that a majority of children spend more time watching television,
listening to music and playing video games than they do with their
parents. The study also said that most children will see nearly
1,000 killings on television and in the movies by the age of 10.
</P>
<P>
   While calling on increased self-regulation of the entertainment
industry and greater enforcement of ratings systems, the senators
pointed out that they were not in favor of government censorship of
films, music or videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to tell artists what they can and can't
produce, only that they should not try to sell violent products to
our children,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was part of Washington's effort to delve into last
month's shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton. Two
teen-aged boys killed a teacher and 12 fellow students before
turning their guns on themselves. At least 21 other people were
wounded in the assault.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, President Clinton will hold a conference on violence
that will include leaders from government, the clergy, and the
entertainment and Internet industries.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's hearing, only one entertainment industry
representative testified before the senators. Jack Valenti,
president of the Motion Picture Association of America, defended
the film industry, saying most directors and producers use little
violence in their movies.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned how large an influence films had on
teen-agers, arguing that a person's moral character is developed
very early in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with my old priest who said, `Give me a child until he
is 7 years old and the world can have him after that,''' Valenti
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three ``pillars'' of children's lives _ home, school
and church _ must form an ``impenetrable shield'' around them to
protect them from immorality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that moral core, no legislation or executive order
will protect our children,'' Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Congress and the president to require elementary school
students to take an ethics class each year to learn the difference
between right and wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
