<HEADLINE>
UNKNOWN DISEASE KILLING GOLD MINERS IN CONGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia _ More than 60 people in northeastern Congo have
died of an unknown disease that has killed most its victims, nearly
all of them gold miners, within six days.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the disease, which has killed 63 people, appeared
to be some kind of hemorrhagic fever, the most deadly of which is
caused by the Ebola virus. In 1995, 244 people died in an outbreak
of Ebola in the city of Kikwit, in western Congo.
</P>
<P>
   A medical team Tuesday shipped out the first samples of infected
blood to a laboratory South Africa in an effort to identify the
disease. Dr. Marc Biot, a researcher with Doctors Without Borders,
the medical group that sent the team into the mining town of Durba,
said the symptoms of this disease appear to differ slightly from
Ebola. He said that even though a doctor who had treated the
patients died, many more medical workers had died in the Ebola
outbreak, as did more family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems not to be as contagious as the Kikwit version,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Biot stressed that it was too early to draw firm conclusions
about the virus until the blood samples were tested. He said the
tests could be completed by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There is no treatment for Ebola or many other hemorrhagic
fevers, so the concern about the deaths runs deep among doctors
around the world. Dr. Ray R. Arthur, a medical officer at the World
Health Organization in Geneva, said that in the last two years
there had been 50 confirmed cases of Ebola worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur said that while details were sketchy, doctors in the
field said the first cases might have appeared in November. Biot
said 58 of the people who had died were miners who worked illegally
in a closed gold mine near Durba, living together in what he called
``terrible,'' unsanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Two women and two children who lived with the miners also died,
Biot said. A regional medical officer who had treated patients also
died on April 23 in the town of Isoro, to the west. Most of the
victims died in clinics in Durba or in the nearby town of Watsa.
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms start with a headache, as well as joint and muscle
pain. On the second day, diarrhea and vomiting begin and soon blood
appears in both. Death usually occurs on the sixth day, Biot said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that patients also develop respiratory infections, which
is not the case with Ebola. Also they do not develop red, bloody
eyes, as happens with Ebola, he said. . Ray said it did not appear
that the disease was spreading rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragic as the number of deaths that have occurred are, we are
not looking at an explosive outbreak at this time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congo is in the midst of a civil war, and the area is controlled
by rebels seeking to overthrow President Laurent Kabila. But in an
unusual display of cooperation, government health officials have
been given permission to travel to the region to help stem any
spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
