<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAKASHIMA-FURNITURE-A     05-04 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAKASHIMA-FURNITURE-ANTIQUES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FURNITURE MAKER WHO PAID HOMAGE TO THE TREE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Wash.)  (af) 
 Elizabeth hayt is an art historian and critic  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 40 years ago, when Roland and Victoria Fiore went to a
local fair at St. Martin's Church in New Hope, Pa., they won a
small cherry wood stool by the designer George Nakashima, who lived
in the area. The couple became friendly with him and, by the
mid-1970s, Ms. Fiore, 77, a former opera singer, was spending
Saturdays at his studio.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 15 years, she helped out there as a receptionist,
receiving $100 every month, earnings that she diligently applied to
buying her employer's furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Like most collectors of Nakashima's furniture, Ms. Fiore did not
just buy a handful of pieces to use as design accents; she filled
her home with the designer's work. Installing Nakashima tables,
chairs, cabinets, bedroom sets and more, she created a total
environment out of his elegant wood furniture, notable for angular
bases topped with primitive slabs of wood displaying grain patterns
and naturally craggy edges.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the entire collection _ save for that very first
stool _ was sold for more than $170,000, roughly three times the
presale estimate, at David Rago Modern Auctions in Lambertville,
N.J., one of the primary auctioneers of Nakashima furniture.
</P>
<P>
   A walnut music stand made for Ms. Fiore's husband, a conductor,
went for $27,500. A pair of walnut stools with the original
cushions of vintage Japanese silk sold for $21,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, prices for Nakashima's work have more
than doubled. In June 1996, a king-size platform bed with a walnut
headboard sold at David Rago for $6,300; in November 1998, a
queen-size version with a maple burl headboard went for $22,000. In
March 1998, Sotheby's auctioned a walnut dining table and six
chairs, circa 1970. Estimated at $10,000 to $15,000, the lot went
for $43,200, the record price for the designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that he was recently discovered but that people are
appreciating him more,'' said Greg Kuharic, vice president of
20th-century decorative arts at Sotheby's, explaining the demand
for work by Nakashima, who died in 1990 at 85. ``New buyers have
entered the market. The furniture doesn't look dated; the
craftsmanship is quite good. The most popular pieces are the great
slabs of wood that are irregular, with free-form edges and bold
grain patterns, and have butterflies holding together the natural
splits in the wood.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the so-called defects in the wood _ the splits, burls and
knots _ that inspired Nakashima to develop his signature butterfly
joints. ``My father had a reputation for buying weird pieces of
wood,'' said Mira Nakashima-Yarnall, 57. ``A burl could be
conceived as an aberration but for him; that was the art, something
to be recognized and used. The form that nature gives was his
inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   To Nakashima, imperfections in the wood gave his pieces
individuality. Working with domestic woods like black walnut and
cherry and, later, more exotic varieties like English oak burl
rosewood, he oiled and polished the surfaces rather than lacquering
them.
</P>
<P>
   As a Japanese-American, Nakashima attributed his relationship to
trees to his Eastern heritage. He described woodworking as a
spiritual communion with nature. Born in Spokane, Wash., he grew up
surrounded by the great forests of the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, after studying architecture at the University of
Washington and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, he
traveled to Paris, encountering avant-garde art. To trace his own
roots, he then moved to Tokyo to work for Antonin Raymond, an
American architect; later he went to India to construct an ashram
for Sri Aurobindo, a spiritual leader whose teachings were deeply
influential.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the United States, he married Marion Okajima, and
the couple settled in Seattle in 1941, where Nakashima opened a
furniture business, although he had no formal training as a
craftsman. A year later, after Pearl Harbor, the couple and their
baby daughter, Mira, (a son was later born) were interned in a
relocation camp in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   There, Nakashima met a Japanese carpenter and learned ancient
Asian woodworking techniques. Released from the camp in 1944,
Nakashima and his family moved to New Hope, where he built a
workshop and eventually a museum. The compound is still run by his
daughter, who reissues his designs while producing her own.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did create designs for the furniture makers Knoll
Inc. and John Widdicomb, Nakashima distinguished himself from his
contemporaries with his hand-turned objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work is interesting because it is finely handcrafted at
the same time that everyone else is making industrialized, plastic
furniture in the 50s and 60s,'' said Christopher Mount, assistant
curator in the department of architecture and design at the Museum
of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   The myth surrounding Nakashima's work is that it was a highly
personalized, one-man operation. In fact, Nakashima employed nearly
a dozen workers to execute his designs. ``Customers would go to the
studio and pick a piece of wood, and the image was that George
would make the piece from beginning to end and deliver it to you,''
said Robert Aibel, owner of the Moderne Gallery in Philadelphia.
``After he died, the business nearly died with him because
customers thought he was working independently.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Moderne Gallery held a Nakashima exhibition,
reviving interest in his work and bringing attention to the fact
that the studio was still in operation under Ms. Nakashima-Yarnell.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Nakashima-Yrnall has created her own line of
furniture, Keisho, which means continuation in Japanese. And a new
generation of architects, like Micheal Gabbelini and David Ling,
has commissioned her to make furniture for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked under Dad for 20 years,'' she said. ``He was like a
great Zen master. As I was growing up, his Eastern philosophy
seemed like hogwash to me. But now, the whole idea that energy
comes from a tree, from the wood, makes sense to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
