<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons pondered Anderson trade
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons spoke with the New England
Patriots on NFL draft day about trading All-Pro running back Jamal
Anderson, coach Dan Reeves confirmed Tuesday. ``Things never got
serious, and it never came close to happening,'' said Reeves, who
described the conversation as typical draft-day negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons would have considered trading their top
offensive player if New England had agreed to the Falcons' asking
price of two first-round picks in this year's draft _ the Pats
owned the 20th and 28th overall choices _ and other considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked and surprised and, I guess, stunned by this,''
Anderson said. ``I don't know what's going on or what to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said, ``It's not unusual in any draft to talk about
specific players and what it might take to do something. In fact,
it's rare when it doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they indicated an interest in Jamal last year,'' Reeves
said, ``and their situation is worse now. Every team is looking for
the great back. Look what New Orleans gave up for Ricky Williams. I
think Jamal is a great player, and I hope he finishes his career
here in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   New England has been seeking a top-rate running back since
former Georgia star Robert Edwards, the Patriots' first-round
choice in 1998, suffered a career-threatening knee injury during a
flag-football exhibition. The Falcons initiated talks between the
organizations. The Patriots were concerned about the ability to
sign Anderson to a long-term contract, and because the trade talks
began on draft day, New England had no opportunity to talk with
Anderson's agent, Jim Sims.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also are concerned about re-signing Anderson, 26,
who led the NFC in rushing last season with 1,846 yards, the
ninth-highest total in league history. A five-year veteran,
Anderson is entering the final year of his contract, and
negotiations toward an extension have proceeded slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Without an extension, Anderson would be eligible for
unrestricted free agency next spring, although the Falcons could
retain his right by designating him a ``franchise'' or
``transition'' player.
</P>
<P>
   During negotiations, the Falcons have made an issue about
Anderson's preference for training on his own instead of
participating in the formal offseason conditioning program at
Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   Sims, who was scheduled to speak with general manager Harold
Richardson on Tuesday, said his goal is to reach agreement on an
extension that will make Anderson one of the three highest-paid
running backs in the NFL. He also said Anderson is concerned about
the number of Falcons starters whose contracts lapse after this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't moved to keep key players who have contracts
coming up after 1999,'' he said. ``One of our concerns is lack of
commitment as far as locking up key players.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Matt Winkeljohn contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
