A4171 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-04 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY VERSUS GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Bill Bradley jumped to within 20 points of
Vice President Al Gore in a Democratic trial heat three weeks ago,
the former New Jersey senator suddenly became a hot media property
and Gore the object of pitying remarks about declining political
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   We journalists like a competitive horse race, and some pundits
were happy, on the slightest pretext, to gin up a little momentum
for Bradley and plant the fear of losing in Gore. If there's no
contest, there's no story.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is fading as rapidly as he rose.
</P>
<P>
   His main appeal is that he's the unGore. If you want a party
alternative to the vice president, Bradley is the only game in
town. But the inescapable questions for Democrats in 2000 are: Why
should they want an alternative? If they do, why Bradley? Who is
Bradley anyway?
</P>
<P>
   It's still Gore's show. He's got the money, the organization,
the name identification and the behind-the-scenes White House
contacts and clout. The powerful political endorsements continue to
roll in.
</P>
<P>
   He's relatively scandal-free, despite a few moneybag monks and
his linkage to President Clinton. In the first three months of this
year, he raised $8.9 million compared with Bradley's $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley becomes a realistic contender only if Gore somehow
throws it away or if the political climate turns dramatically
against the Clinton administration. Gore cannot control the
people's mood, which depends on the result of the air strikes
against Yugoslavia, the state of the domestic economy and the
surprise scandal of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But so far he's doing okay with his own act. His verbal gaffes
remain silly rather than scary. Nobody thinks Gore is a dummy like
Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll, Gore now has
nearly a 3-to-1 lead over Bradley, 66 percent to 23 percent. This
huge gap is unlikely to last forever, but it does indicate that the
Bradley boomlet is a fragile flower indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is supposed to be in political trouble because of wobbly
poll numbers, an unexciting personality and a tendency toward
hyperbole that makes him vulnerable to ridicule. He trails Texas
Gov. George W. Bush in the new USA Today/CNN poll by a larger
margin, 40 percent to 56 percent, than he did in January when Bush
beat him by only one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Washington Post poll, 56 percent of those surveyed
described Gore as a bore. His image as a wooden post is firmly
planted in the public mind.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's colorless nature is actually among the least of his
worries in a primary match with Bradley. Gore is not tussling with
a rabble-rousing bomb-thrower here.
</P>
<P>
   Have you heard Bradley speak lately? Throughout his 18-year
Senate career Bradley was a prominent contender in the boredom
sweepstakes. Observers report that in recent appearances his
oratorical style still doesn't set audiences aflame. If it remains
a contest between a boring vice president and a boring Senate
has-been, count on the guy with the title to win.
</P>
<P>
   At this point the Bradley campaign is an educational exercise,
not a viable come-from-behind political phenomenon. In 1996 Bradley
declined to seek re-election, complaining that the political system
was ``broken.'' Others noted that he had nearly been beaten six
years before and was having trouble raising campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 55, his public service and his fame as a New York Knicks
basketball star are well behind him. Hardly anyone understands his
thinking on public policy or why he has belatedly decided he wants
to be president.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Bradley was considered possible presidential material
_ an ethical, cerebral mainstream Democrat who had stayed out of
trouble and could rally the party faithful. But twice he passed up
opportunities to run and gained a reputation as the Democratic Jack
Kemp, never quite bold enough to take the risk.
</P>
<P>
   His change of heart is a mystery. His political views, insomuch
as we know them, are not so different from Gore's as to drive him
to run as a matter of ideological principle. For example, he has
not taken the lead in the Kosovo debate _ on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's not a bad guy, and he wouldn't sell out his party or
his country or his wife. But neither would Gore, and Gore's got a
lot more going for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
