<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-POWS-HNS &LR;      05-04 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-POWS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FORMER POWs JUST CAN'T `BELIEVE' ALL OF THE SUPPORT IN U.S. 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
and DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ Families of the American POWs released by
Yugoslavia spent their first hours with the soldiers offering
plenty of hugs and stories about their loved ones and the rally of
support across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't believe it,'' said Deanna Stone, sister of
Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone. ``They don't believe that everything
would be centering around them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the three servicemen released Saturday received news from
home, doctors who have finished examining the former captives
offered a few more grim details of their month in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the broken bones and minor injuries reported
Monday, doctors reported that the three men suffered from
disorientation because they were forced to wear hoods, and had
abrasions on their wrists from handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez also was shackled, while Spc. Steven
Gonzales and Stone each had a chipped tooth.
</P>
<P>
   The men were seized March 31 after a skirmish with Serbian
forces on the Macedonia-Yugoslav border. Details of how the men
were injured were not released because of the ongoing investigation
into their capture.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen relatives of the three soldiers were flown to Germany
on Monday and spent several hours with them while the men received
medical and psychological examinations and military debriefings.
The soldiers arrived at the medical facility Sunday and are
undergoing a 72-hour repatriation process.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. David Vetter, a Landstuhl doctor, said the Serbs gave
Gonzales fluids intravenously during the first days of captivity.
While too much time has passed to trace if any drugs were
administered, Gonzales told Vetter he was ``shaky'' before he
received the fluids. Vetter said the Serbs may have been treating
him for shock.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, officials said only two soldiers lost weight, but
Tuesday the doctors said all had lost between 8 and 14 pounds. But
the three had been making up for the loss, eating heavily since
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Vetter said Gonzales was taking ``a bite out of everything that
passes in front of him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas, reportedly was most
concerned about his bills and worried creditors might try to
contact his parents. Gonzales asked the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who
negotiated their release, to tell the creditors he promised to pay
them when he got home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the evaluations and debriefings, part of the
soldiers' reintegration process includes spending time with their
families.
</P>
<P>
   The families of Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and of
Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles talked with reporters Tuesday at an
Army hospital at the Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, where the
U.S. servicemen were treated.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales' family declined to talk to the media. Parents Gilbert
and Rosie Gonzales and aunt Rosalinda Barrow apparently were
overwhelmed by all the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's mother, Vivian Ramirez, said she could not stop
hugging her son at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to let him go so he could breathe,'' she said. ``It was
good to see him. He looks really good. His spirits are up. He's
just wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The families bore gifts to ease the men's return: Stone received
a jersey bearing the logo of his favorite National Hockey League
team, the Detroit Red Wings, and a new coat. Ramirez's gift was a
little more perishable: He got a hamburger from his favorite
California fast-food restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably all hard, but we got it there,'' Vivian
Ramirez said. ``He said, `We'll put it in the microwave.'''
</P>
<P>
   The families said they did not dwell on the soldiers' captivity
and injuries, but instead talked about family and friends and all
the media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't discuss anything that really happened,''
Deanna Stone said. ``We were just glad to see them. That was it.
You can't even explain the feelings that you have, that you don't
even want to talk. You just want to see them and you want to give
them a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are dealing with what happened,'' Stone's sister Dawn
Reliford said. ``It was a very traumatic experience for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it by looking at him that it was painful. That was not
the issue. The issue was that we love him and that we were glad to
see him. We just want to be with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stone nor Ramirez, who had been part of the U.N. Bosnian
peacekeeping force, had seen their families since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows about the excitement that's been going on,'' Vivian
Ramirez said. ``He can't believe it. He's really surprised. Wait
until he gets home. He will not believe all that's going on until
he sees it for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton left Tuesday for Europe and will try to meet
with the former prisoners of war when he arrives in Germany on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The families agreed the hardest part of the ordeal was behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first time that his picture was shown (of Ramirez in
captivity), there's really nothing you could really think,'' said
Steven Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's mother also said that television broadcast of her son
haunts her still.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that will just stay in my mind,'' Vivian Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Ramirez said she hopes she can stay with her son until he
receives the 30 days leave granted the former prisoners of war by
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay here until they kick us out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
