<HEADLINE>
CUBAN COACH DEFECTS AS TEAM VISITS BALTIMORE, U.S. OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES, moving in `s' sports category) 
(rm) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The game ended around midnight on Monday, and for
the next few hours, the Cuban baseball team and their band of noisy
supporters continued celebrating a 12-6 victory over the Orioles in
the downtown Baltimore hotel where the team and its 300-member
delegation were staying.
</P>
<P>
   But by early Tuesday, when the group made a hasty departure from
the Baltimore-Washington International Airport for Havana, at least
seven members of the traveling party were missing. American
government officials said one coach defected. Cuban government
officials said the other six Cubans just overslept.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials denied that any members of their team or the
traveling party had sought political asylum in the United States,
which would be a political embarrassment for the Cuban president,
Fidel Castro, who greeted the team Tuesday upon its arrival at Jose
Marti Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But the Baltimore police said that a member of the Cuban
delegation walked into the city's central district police station
at 10 a.m. Tuesday, identified himself as Rigoberto Herrera and
requested asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., who was one of several politicians
who spoke outside the stadium at a boisterous anti-Castro rally
before the game, said the man was Rigoberto Herrera Betancourt, 54,
one of the team's pitching coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Weinhold Jr., a police department spokesman, said
after Herrera identified himself, officers immediately contacted
officials with the Immigration and Naturalization Service, who
``took custody'' of him about 90 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Weinhold nor Menendez said they knew how Herrera escaped
the watch of Cuban security forces and found the police station,
which is about a 10-minute walk from the hotel where the Cuban team
was staying. Menendez, an outspoken critic of the Cuban president,
said it was his understanding that about half of the members of the
Cuban delegation were involved with security.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ferro, the INS regional director in Baltimore, said he would
neither confirm nor deny that a Cuban traveling to Baltimore for
the baseball game had sought to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But two U.S. government officials confirmed that the agency was
processing one asylum seeker, and one of them described the man as
one of the Cuban team's coaches.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other six who missed the Havana-bound plane, a
Canadian charter jet that left before 6 a.m., officials at the
Cuban Interests Section here said that the men, all former Cuban
baseball players, did not awake in time to accompany the group to
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Garcia Hernandez, the second secretary of the interests
section, which is housed in the Swiss embassy, described the six as
``former prestigious baseball players'' who ``unfortunately
overslept and missed their airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much celebrating, Garcia was asked? He nodded his head
affirmatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens all the time, in all the countries we play,'' said
another Cuban official, who declined to give his name. ``I don't
know the reasons. I just know the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither official would provide the names of the late-sleepers,
but they said arrangements were being made to fly them home.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Defections are a constant source of concern for Cuban officials
when their star athletes venture outside the country for
competitions. Over the years, a steady stream of them have walked
away from their teams, many to seek the considerable rewards of
professional status in the United States even if their defection
actually occurs in a third country.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Cuban baseball players have been more likely to
defect outside the United States. If they defected here, they would
be required to go through the major league baseball draft, a
restrictive system that ties them to one team. Entering the United
States from a third country enables them to sign with any team as a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   While Cuban athletes enjoy widespread celebrity in their home
country and earn more than average citizens, their salaries and
living conditions are well below even average American standards.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cubas, a Miami-based player agent who has helped other Cuban
athletes defect, including Livan Hernandez of the Florida Marlins,
the World Series most valuable player in 1997, said he met with
several of the Cuban players while they were in Baltimore and
discussed the possibility of defecting.
</P>
<P>
   But time grew short after the game, he said, when Cuban
officials began notifying members of the traveling party sometime
after 3 a.m. that their departure time had been moved up. According
to the delegation's original schedule, the Cubans were to fly out
of Baltimore in mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Cubas and Menendez said that the early departure was spurred by
the disappearance of Herrera and the fear that others in the
traveling party might follow him, seeking asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get out as quickly as possible,'' Cubas said.
``Everyone was told to get their suitcases and they would be
leaving at 4:40. Players were willing to defect. Unfortunately
because of the rush, they had to cut it short, but this won't be
their last trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Menendez said he was not convinced that the others who missed
the plane had simply overslept. He said Cuba's security forces
would not have overlooked them, and the six had intended to defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing mixed stories,'' Menendez said. ``They might have
overslept. But those of us who know Cuban State Security know they
would not have been unable to wake them to get them out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
