<SLUG> BC-INDIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANDHI AND VAJPAYEE MATCHED UP AS INDIA SCHEDULES NATIONAL
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ In the contest to see who will be India's
next prime minister, Sonia Gandhi, the widowed inheritor of India's
founding political dynasty, will be matched against the veteran
Hindu nationalist leader Atal Behari Vajpayee. Tuesday the general
elections were scheduled for September and the first week of
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Election Commission rejected the request of the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party for elections next month, citing
what it called ``an unprecedented heat wave'' that has already
pushed temperatures in northern India as high as 118 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The party, which is led by Vajpayee, hoped quick elections would
let it capitalize on a wave of sympathy from voters. Some are upset
that Mrs. Gandhi and her Congress Party helped topple the
Hindu-nationalist-led coalition last month by a single vote in
Parliament, then was unable to form a government to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Election Commission said it needs more time to prepare
for what it called ``the largest organized operation in the
world.'' It is currently adding 15 million voters to rolls that
already list more than 600 million people, a task that will not be
complete until July. And the commission has to mobilize 4 million
people to work at 800,000 polling stations, as well as hundreds of
thousands of security guards.
</P>
<P>
   The balloting will take place in phases on dates in September
and October that the commission will announce ``in due time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Vajpayee's government, now serving as caretakers,
contend they must operate as an effective government for the next
five months to avoid paralysis. That stance has drawn sharp
criticism from Congress Party officials.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, for example, the government transferred several top
civil servants, including the home secretary, B.P. Singh, a step
that it called a routine shuffle but that Congress leaders
condemned as an attempt to consolidate its power in advance of the
election.
</P>
<P>
   The voting will avoid the worst of the heat, which can seriously
depress turnout, but the commission acknowledged that monsoon rains
and flooding in September are likely to be a serious problem some
areas.
</P>
<P>
   It noted that almost all Indian elections have been held between
November and May. But because the government fell on April 17 and
elections must be held within six months, the commission's only
choice was between oppressive, sometimes life-threatening heat and
torrential downpours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
