<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-05-CO     05-04 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    NEW WAVE OF KOSOVO REFUGEES TELL OF CHILLING BRUTALITY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ Chilling stories of killings,
brutality and destruction poured out of refugees who arrived here
non-stop Tuesday on foot, in tractors and in cars from disparate
parts of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The tales of cold-blooded shootings and gunpoint robberies, if
true, invoke a picture of a new level of barbarity in the Serbian
campaign to erase the ethnic Albanian population from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the drivers get out of the tractors and they
executed them. They took my son, and four meters away from his
father and mother they killed him. They killed my son,'' said Hodit
Aslemi, 59.
</P>
<P>
   Shootings also were reported by refugees arriving from other
parts of Kosovo, and refugees who were questioned said Serb police
or military demanded money from them while holding a knife to the
throat or gun at the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers from Zrze, who had harbored and fed hundreds of
displaced Kosovars in recent weeks, said Serb troops evicted the
entire town of about 3,000 people Tuesday and looted and trashed
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Groups came from four different geographic areas, including
about 2,000 people who had been camping in the mountains for the
last several weeks after being forced from their homes, said Ray
Wilkinson, spokesman for the United Nations refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were reports of widespread abductions and kidnappings of
men, and eyewitness reports of executions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,400 Kosovar Albanians crossed from Yugoslavia into
Albania in the stream of refugees that began around noon and
stopped at about 9 p.m. local time
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Wilkinson said the ``closure or movement
of the camps in Kukes'' is ``under active discussion'' by
international relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He said no decision had been made by Tuesday night, but stressed
the Albanian government has evidenced ``growing anxiety'' over the
presence of an estimated 100,000 refugees here, many of whom live
outside the camps.
</P>
<P>
   The closure of camps would mean fast, mandatory removal of at
least 35,000 refugees, a move the refugee agency has been trying to
avoid in favor of convincing the Kosovars to shift voluntarily to
areas in the Albanian interior that are safer from growing
cross-border conflict.
</P>
<P>
   They have refused to go. Most say they want to stay close to
their homes and to the border where they might yet find family
members left behind when they had to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson had no details on how the refugees might be forced to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee Aslemi said the shooting of his 27-year-old son happened
Sunday night, as his convoy of about 200 tractors was trying to
leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Another son had been wounded Sunday and was limping toward
medical care here as the sun dropped behind the mountains. Aslemi
said a third son had run away Sunday to escape the terror that
struck the caravan about 12 miles outside of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know how many men were shot when the Serb
forces demanded they get down from their tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Aslemi said the Serbs also separated his 83-year-old
father-in-law from the family and left him sitting alone, without
food or water in the middle of a field.
</P>
<P>
   It took the convoy from Sunday until Tuesday night to get here
to safety, said Aslemi, who sat with his sister atop the blankets
and other goods his family managed to haul away on their
tractor-drawn cart. His wife and other family members had been
taken to shelter, but the pair was settling in to guard the last of
their possessions all night in the cart that had blown a wheel and
could not be moved to the camps in Kukes 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we crossed the border we did not cry,'' he said, as he
and his sister sat atop the remnants of their lives and wept.
``Everything is over in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in weeks, refugees everywhere seemed
overwhelmed by anguish and despair of ever returning to normal life
in their homes. Till now, a buoyant spirit of hope has prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   At a holding tent on the Kukes square where hundreds of refugees
probably would spend the night, 56-year-old Nuhi Kolgeci expressed
feelings that NATO and America had betrayed the Kosovo people by
failing to stop the Serb military and police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tanks all over my village. Why don't they bomb
them?'' asked Kolgeci, who sat on the ground with his wife and a
retarded daughter, dirty and ragged from the two weeks they had
spent in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   He said a son and a brother both had been wounded Sunday night
when they tried to flee Serb army troops that surrounded their
makeshift mountain camp, where their only shelter had been plastic
sheeting. Both were left in the care of young men on the run from
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Kolgeci did not see the killing of a distant cousin who was said
to have been shot while being herded down the mountain later that
day, but three women said they witnessed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was putting his cap in a bag carried by his wife,'' said
Nexhamije Rraci, 35. ``They said to stop, but he left it in the
bag. Then they separated him from the others and shot him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rraci said she was directly behind the man, Ramadan Kolgeci,
when he was drawn from the column coming down the mountain and shot
in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all so close, I don't know how they didn't shoot
others,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As Nuhi Kolgeci told the rest of his story _ about the odyssey
of walking through two days and many towns, about his daughter who
was a student in Pristina and now has gone missing _ he became
inconsolable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would feel better to die myself,'' he said, sobbing. ``What
is the use of my life now?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
