<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISASTER-INDUSTRY-ART     05-04 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-INDUSTRY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPLYING DISASTER RELIEF GROUPS BECOMES A BOOMING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fax in Joe Addis' makeshift office near Skopje, Macedonia,
has been whirring since the Catholic Relief Services official set
up shop near a refugee camp in April. Businesses and brokers have
besieged him with sales pitches for tents, toothpaste, food,
vegetable oil, laundry soap, sanitary napkins and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Several auto dealers that have exclusive franchises with Toyota,
Ford or Nissan to sell to relief groups, have offered him
all-terrain vehicles. Generic drug wholesalers in Britain and the
Netherlands that specialize in supplying field clinics with
aspirin, antibiotics and antidepressants, have been in touch with
him. So has a company in South Carolina that sells plastic
sheeting, a New York City company that offers blankets and one in
Massachusetts that sells prefabricated warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   In any disaster _ war, hurricane, famine _ government agencies
and humanitarian organizations rush to bring aid. Standing behind
them is a growing ``disaster industry,'' a loose conglomeration of
companies and middlemen for which bad times can mean boom business.
</P>
<P>
   The companies include small manufacturers whose normal business
does not include disasters but which are eager to seize a sudden
opportunity. But for the bulk of the companies, which are largely
based in Europe and employ from 10 to 500 people, sales to relief
and development agencies are their main business. Some are
specialized procurement brokers that for a commission of 5 to 20
percent will search for items needed by relief groups like surplus
field kitchens, bulletproof vests and concertina wire.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, governments and international organizations spend
tens of billions of dollars on both long-term relief projects and
emergencies. And large buyers like the federal government will buy
directly from manufacturers, negotiating contracts and storing
emergency supplies at warehouses worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But in a crisis like the war in Kosovo, charities, both large
and small, pour hundreds of millions into a region. In these
chaotic situations, they often turn to companies and brokers that
are disaster specialists that can ship goods quickly, track down
hard-to-find items and even extend credit. In addition, some relief
organizations do not have their own procurement offices and rely on
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies employ former relief workers and say they can do
well by doing good. Others see a huge aid effort as an opportunity
to profiteer by selling goods at inflated prices to humanitarian
groups or to donate drugs close to their expiration date rather
than paying to destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of thousands of refugees in the Balkans in need of
blankets, some dealers are holding back the 5 to 10 percent
discount normally given for bulk purchases, one major procurement
agency said. Depending on quality and material, a blanket used in
relief operations costs from $1.50 to $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we would normally expect a bulk discount, the discount
is not coming through,'' said Tony Urwin, a buyer with Crown Agents
Ltd., a nonprofit procurement service that was part of the British
government until a few years ago. Urwin declined to identify the
dealers but said he was able to find a blanket manufacturer in the
United States willing to give him the discount.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Vliestra, the commercial director of the International
Procurement Agency, a Dutch company, said it was supplying groups
in Kosovo, including World Vision International, with items it had
bought from around the world. Blankets are coming from an Egyptian
producer, plastic sheeting used for ground coverings is coming from
a Dutch company, and inexpensive pots and pans from a Czech
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a madhouse at the moment,'' Vliestra said.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable estimates for the size of the industry that serves the
disaster and long-term relief market do not exist. With rare
exceptions, all the companies selling disaster supplies are private
and do not disclose their sales. But Kim Ginnerup, the director of
Mission Pharma, a Danish drug wholesaler for which relief groups
account for about half of sales, estimated that for drugs alone,
the relief market amounted to $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   He said that much of the modern industry sprang up in Europe
about 25 years ago among companies focused on supplying Africa,
where much relief work was then under way.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have roots in the nonprofit world. Greg
Spitzfaden, an official of Tri-Med of Britain, said that company
got its start when its three founders began arranging the shipment
of relief items bought with the proceeds from charity rock concerts
like Live Aid and Band Aid.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the company branched into procurement and now has offices
close to troubled regions, said Spitzfaden, who recently flew to
Macedonia to visit refugee camps and work with clients, including
Addis of Catholic Relief Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 13 offices in the places in the world that are at the
absolute bottom of everyone's tourist list,'' he said. Spitzfaden's
office is in one of the world's more idyllic spots, Peterborough,
N.H., and many of the European-based concerns have offices here so
they can work closely with relief groups based in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   While brokers like Tri-Med will seek out anything requested by a
relief group, other companies specialize. Toyota Gibraltar, in the
British colony, is Toyota Motor's exclusive dealer to agencies
working in relief and development worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   A competitor, Kjaer &AMP; Kjaer, a Danish company that holds the
Nissan Motor relief distributorship, has based a salesman in
Sarajevo to deal with charities and government agencies operating
in Albania and Macedonia and has posted his cellular telephone
number on its Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Kosovo is deteriorating every minute,'' the
company's site states. ``We may be able to assist your efforts in
the region.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Soeren Laursen, Kjaer's marketing manager, said it had sold
about 100 all-terrain and pickup vehicles in recent years to groups
working in the Balkans. He said the vehicles were stripped-down
models built to ``Africa specifications'' to endure rough
conditions. Some have been modified as ambulances or fitted with
armor and ballistic floor mats to protect occupants if they go over
a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have just started to get a toehold in the
business. Three years ago, for instance, Schein Pharmaceutical
Inc., a generic-drug producer based in Florham Park, N.J., hired
Allison Formal, a former official with International Services for
Medical Services for Health, a relief group, to help sell drugs to
humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Formal said Schein, in some cases, had given drugs at cost
to relief groups to build up relationships. But typically, the
company charges from 12 to 30 percent above a drug's production
cost, she added. Drugs sold to commercial wholesale buyers
typically cost at least twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies in the disaster market must sell products to
charities at a steep discount because they are competing against
United Nations agencies, which buy huge quantities directly from
manufacturers and pass the savings along.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, sales to humanitarian groups are about 1 percent of
Schein's annual sales, or about $5 million, Ms. Formal said.
</P>
<P>
   Donated medical supplies, which are desperately needed in crises
like Kosovo, can cause their own problems for aid groups. A 1997
article in the New England Journal of Medicine estimated that it
would cost the World Health Organization about $2,000 a ton to
destroy the hundreds of tons of expired drugs and unusable medical
supplies sent to Bosnia-Herzegovina during the conflict there.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a pharmaceutical company must destroy expired drugs in
a hazardous waste incinerator, an expensive form of disposal.
</P>
<P>
   A WHO guideline now calls for donated medical supplies to be no
less than a year away from expiration. But Max Ziv, a pharmacist
working at Genpharm Inc., a generic drug maker in Toronto, said in
a telephone interview that he had been giving charities drugs with
a shelf life of six months.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ziv and Genpharm president Bruce Simpson said they were
unaware of the WHO guideline but defended the practice, saying the
drugs were good. Genpharm is a subsidiary of Merck KGaA, a German
company that is not related to Merck &AMP; Co., the U.S. drug giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a moral issue,'' Ziv said. ``Would you rather see people
in the Third World dying because they need medicines?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, the Vietnamese government burned about 1,000
pounds of expired Genpharm antibiotics and drugs that Ziv had
collected and donated. He said the drugs were no older than six
months from expiration when they reached Vietnam in March.
Government officials destroyed the drugs last fall, according to
news reports.
</P>
<P>
   As the Kosovo crisis continues, some sellers of tents are
apparently seeking to unload products of little use to refugees.
Normally, such products are made by specialized factories, said
Urwin, the buyer with Crown Agents. In recent weeks, he said that
some tent producers that normally did not serve the relief market
tried to sell him expensive tents designed for campers. The
problem: the tents are too small for people to stand inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are fine if you are looking to spend a weekend in the
mountains or on the beach,'' Urwin said.
</P>
<P>
   And even products designed for refugees are not always right for
the situation. Addis, the Catholic Relief official, said some of
the tents delivered to Stankovic I, a sprawling refugee camp
outside Skopje, do not have floors because they were produced for
Africa, where it is hot and relatively dry. As a result, the
charity has bought plastic sheeting to serve as tent bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Addis said, his experience with companies in the
disaster business had been good. Not long after surveying the needs
of the 30,000 Kosovar Albanian refugees at the Stankovic camp, he
decided to bring in military-style field kitchens to cook hot meals
for thousands of them at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But when he looked into buying that number of new kitchens,
Addis said he quickly found that the cost was steep and that new
kitchens would take six to eight weeks to get to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   He alerted Spitzfaden of Tri-Med of the problem, and the
procurement company found a surplus dealer that had 22 used NATO
field kitchens. Catholic Relief Service bought the kitchens,
utensils included, for $9,000 each and shipped them immediately to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Tri-Med's markup was, Addis figures he got a deal. It
would have cost him $1 million, about five times what he paid, to
buy 22 new kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we got a good price,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
