<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ Serbs and a few Albanians are
trickling back to Pristina, Kosovo's capital. The sunny daytime
streets, with a few pedestrians and shoppers, now display a poor
imitation of ordinary life, so long as one does not focus too hard
on the empty, looted Albanian districts, the bomb damage and the
nearly total lack of children in the town. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ With no consensus on ground troops and
no sign of Slobodan Milosevic wavering, Allied leaders are
beginning to face the prospect of housing a half million refugees
through the bitter Balkan winter. Yet even with that forbidding
prospect, top military and civilian officials keep saying that the
bombing of Yugoslavia will eventually get Milosevic to concede
defeat. What they cannot say is when. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ White House officials said today
that they believed they had persuaded the Russian envoy to the
Balkans that a military force, rather than just a monitoring
mission, would be needed in Kosovo after the bombing campaign. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GORE (Washington) _ Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, the former
stolid Russian prime minister, and Al Gore, the stolid current
American vice president, are engaged in an intensive search for a
diplomatic exit to the bloodshed in the Balkans, an effort that
bring some risk to both men, but potentially large political
benefits. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO forces shoot down another
Yugoslav MiG-29; other military developments.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NUKE (United Nations) _ The International Atomic Energy
Agency decides to go back to Serbia to inspect some worrisome
nuclear material there after getting invitation from Yugoslavia. By
Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica) _ Of the 70,000 Kosovar Albanians
who have sought refuge in the Yugoslav province of Montenegro, many
are leaving for Albania because they do no feel safe. Refugee
agencies are hampered in what they can do because these people are
technically still in their own country. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   These, budgeted earlier, are now scratched:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS, its spot elements folded into other stories.
