<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADN-BUDGET &LR;      05-04 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 5, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-TOXINS (Santa Clarita, Calif.) _ Health department
officials will meet this week with parents of children at a Saugus
school where several children have taken ill and blood tests
indicate high levels of toxins in their blood and urine. By
Patricia Farrell Aidem. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-SCHOOL-HATE (Los Angeles) _ While hate crimes have dropped
across Los Angeles County in 1998, they increased at schools last
year by 15 percent to 46. Authorities say the number only scratches
the surface of the problem because too many schools don't report
incidents that might lead to hate crimes. By Michael Coit. (Will
move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-POPULATION (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles grew by more
population than any community in California in 1998, according to a
state report released Tuesday. Also, U-Haul's annual moving report
shows L.A.'s San Fernando Valley is the nation's ninth most popular
destination, placing it ahead of Las Vegas. By Robert Monroe. (Will
move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-SUIT (Los Angeles) _ No longer the mouse that roared,
Walt Disney Co.'s poor performance sets a bleak backdrop for
chairman Michael Eisner as he testifies in a high-stakes legal
battle with the company's former studio chief, Jeffrey Katzenberg.
By Peter Hartlaub. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   POWS-RABBI (Los Angeles) _ Triumphant from their mission with
the Rev. Jesse Jackson to free the American prisoners of war, Rabbi
Steven Jacobs and Nazir Uddin Khaja return to Los Angeles from
Yugoslavia. By Sharline Chiang. (Will move in the ``n'' California
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ROCKETDYNE-REACTION (Los Angeles) _ Residents, former workers
and members of an independent citizen's committee say it's a step
in the right direction but still have little confidence in Gov.
Gray Davis's decision to move the oversight of the Rocketdyne
investigation to a new state agency because of fears of collusion.
By Terri Hardy. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
