<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTE-CARLO-BALLET-2T     05-04 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTE-CARLO-BALLET-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MONTE CARLO DIRECTOR GAMBLES ON NOVELTY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about the choreographers Danial   Shapiro and Joanie Smith. 
By CHRISTOPHER REARDON  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its Mediterranean vistas and posh casinos, the little
principality of Monaco has reigned for generations as a playground
for the rich and famous. It's not all fun and games, though, for
Les Ballets de Monte Carlo, a local troupe that spent 48 weeks
rehearsing and performing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Jean-Christophe Maillot, an amiable young Frenchman with
big ambitions, this 14-year-old company is striving to reconcile
its loyalty to tradition with a passion for something new.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fitting that the company will take up this theme when
it opens a weeklong season at City Center in New York City on
Wednesday. The program spotlights Maillot's sleek new rendering of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' set to Prokofiev's familiar rhapsodic score.
Framed as a flashback and focusing on psychological tensions, the
three-act work brings a fresh eye to a story that is often
freighted with props and pantomime.
</P>
<P>
   It also renews Maillot's efforts to couple classical ballet with
contemporary dance, two clans that have sometimes quarreled as
ardently as the Montagues and the Capulets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim is to take the classical world _ its codes, its
esthetic, its dancers _ and find a new approach,'' he said during a
recent interview in New York. ``The alternative to classical dance
is not automatically modern dance. There are other propositions
which are more subtle and, for me, more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Princess Caroline asked him to direct Les Ballets de Monte
Carlo six years ago, Maillot has gained a reputation for
challenging the dance establishment. In 1996, for the troupe's only
previous New York engagement, he juxtaposed Balanchine's ``Four
Temperaments'' with his own dance to the same score by Paul
Hindemith. Although he seemed to be inviting unfavorable
comparisons, many critics commended his gutsy choice.
</P>
<P>
   With his new ``Romeo et Juliette,'' Maillot has once more thrust
himself into some lofty company. Leonid Lavrovsky, John Cranko,
Jerome Robbins and Kenneth MacMillan are among more than 80
choreographers who have taken inspiration from Shakespeare's
star-crossed lovers.
</P>
<P>
   (American Ballet Theater will perform the MacMillan version,
which also uses the Prokofiev score, at the Metropolitan Opera
House through Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   Maillot said he found much to admire in these productions, but
he questioned their emotional resonance with young audiences today.
His staging owes less to Cranko and MacMillan, he said, than to
Franco Zeffirelli's impassioned 1968 film and Baz Luhrmann's
turbo-charged 1996 remake.
</P>
<P>
   In a makeover that's not just cosmetic, Maillot replaced the
heavy period look with strapless gowns (by Jerome Kaplan),
otherworldly light (by Dominique Drillot) and a shifting psychic
landscape (by Ernest Pignon-Ernest).
</P>
<P>
   The central narrative role belongs to Friar Laurence, usually a
character of little depth. His culpability and distance, however,
led Maillot to depict him as a failed peacemaker who punctuates the
ballet with expressive bursts of moral anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one I want the audience to identify most strongly
with,'' the choreographer said. ``Not Romeo, and not Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece presumes that theatergoers know the basic story: two
lovers, their feuding families, a tragic miscommunication. So
instead of having to dramatize each plot twist, Maillot said, he
felt free to create a sequence of character studies.
</P>
<P>
   When Tybalt and Mercutio duel, for example, he skips the
swordplay in favor of a fiery pas de deux. And while MacMillan lets
the wounded Mercutio caper about for three minutes before dying, he
gives the musical passage to Romeo (Chris Roelandt), who is
transformed from a docile lover into a vengeful murderer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
