u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIMINATE-KOSOVO-IRAQ     05-04 0031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-KOSOVO-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IRAQ (Washington) will not move in tonight's New York
Times News Service file.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.Times News Service, May 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4207 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTE-CARLO-BALLET-2N     05-04 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTE-CARLO-BALLET-2NDTAKE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: vengeful murderer.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most significantly, the third act brings the Friar (Gaetan
Morlotti) into the bedroom and later the crypt for a pair of
lengthy, hypnotic duets with Juliet (Bernice Coppieters). Maillot
said the scheme served both to implicate the Friar and to advance
the narrative without relying on props.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no swords, no poison vial,'' he said. ``Their
dancing will tell us who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's tale of forbidden love has had a hold on Maillot,
who is now 38, for nearly half his life. In 1983, as a soloist with
the Hamburg Ballet, he wrenched his knee while rehearsing the part
of Romeo in John Neumeier's version of the ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, shortly before opening night, ended his career as a
dancer. Moving back to his hometown, Tours, in France's Loire
Valley, he signed on as director of a 12-member troupe and began
making dances.
</P>
<P>
   His hybrid esthetic (``evolution, not revolution'') endeared him
neither to classicism's ancien regime nor to iconoclastic peers
like Maguy Marin, Jean-Claude Gallotta and Daniel Larrieu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my role is to give the people in the audience partly
what they expect,'' he said, citing his new work's familiar story
and score. ``Now, once they are in their seats, my job is to not to
completely shock them but maybe to destabilize them a little bit,
to bring them to be curious, to begin wondering if there are other
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Maillot's first forays into choreography was an 80-minute
piece called ``Juliette et Romeo.'' (His first child, born that
same year, is also named Juliette.) He commissioned an electronic
score and, as with the other dances he made before going to Monte
Carlo, kept the dancers off point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just too young,'' he said. ``I didn't have the rights to
the score by Prokofiev, and I didn't have the quality of dancers
that I have today. But dramaturgically everything was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since going to Monte Carlo _ he lives with his family in nearby
Nice _ Maillot has replaced all but a few of the troupe's 50
dancers. One of the newcomers, Morlotti, followed him from Ballet
de Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring the troupe plans to leave the belle epoque studio
and stage where Diaghilev's legendary Ballets Russes was based from
1911 and 1929. ``It's very nice historically, but otherwise it's
terrible,'' Maillot said. ``There are three showers for 50 dancers.
People told me that Diaghilev used to do everything there. I said:
`Yes, he also used to not pay the dancers. You want us to do that
also?'''
</P>
<P>
   In its new home, the troupe will enjoy the use of three large
studios plus a weight room, sauna and whirlpool. It will perform at
the new 1,800-seat Grimaldi Forum, named for the family that has
ruled Monaco for seven centuries. The building costs, like the
troupe's $5.5 million annual budget, are being covered by the
principality.
</P>
<P>
   Maillot said the best choreography is transparent, leaving the
viewer with palpable emotions, not pretty images. ``I want the
audience to come away from the balcony scene and not remember one
step,'' he said. ``Romeo and Juliet should be so much in love that
when the curtain closes you feel like, `Wow! I would like to live
that.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
