<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINE-STATEHOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI TROOPS WOUND 17 IN HEBRON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU DIS, West Bank _ It was to be the dawn of an independent
Palestinian state, but Tuesday ended up just another day on the
edge of peace.
</P>
<P>
   After Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat postponed a unilateral
declaration of statehood on May 4 _ the day set out in accords with
Israel for the completion of a final peace deal _ clashes broke out
in the West Bank. Israeli troops shot and wounded at least 17
protesters in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu seized the opportunity
to boost his bitterly fought campaign for reelection by saying his
government's hard-line position forced Arafat to back down. And
Palestinian leaders reiterated their vow that Palestinian statehood
is inevitable in the future ``whether the Israeli government likes
it or not,'' as Palestinian Authority general secretary, Ahmed
Abdel-Rahman, put it.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from the politics, and a small group of young people
who threw rocks at Israeli soldiers, the Palestinian people _ from
struggling businessmen to fed-up mothers _ showed surprising
indifference as the date, which Arafat had called ``sacred,''
slipped by. They seemed to understand the international pressure
that led Arafat to delay, and largely agreed with his decision.
What they said they care about is the practical side of peace _
developing an economy and improving public works.
</P>
<P>
   They expressed impatience with the Palestinian Authority for
failing to deliver basic services they need, for violating civil
rights of Palestinians, and for rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Nabil Safadi, 34, who owns a small Gaza
factory that makes bamboo furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me a real Palestinian state will be when we, as business
people, have the right to import and export our goods,'' said
Safadi.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that his imports of bamboo are often delayed in
Israeli ports, and that when Israel closes the borders, which it
would certainly do if Arafat unilaterally declared statehood,
deliveries don't come through at all. That means his 25 employees
do not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the real frustration. The peace process has never
produced the economic benefits it promised, and a piece of paper
that says we are a state will do nothing to change that,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority may issue Palestinian passports, have
its own postage stamps, and even have its own airport in Gaza. But
many see those as the trappings of a state, and far from the true
benefits of independence.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gaza, at the Shatti UN Refugee Camp, where 55,000 live in
cinder-block hovels with corrugated tin roofs, the frustration is
growing. Half of Gaza's 1.2 million people still live in the
squalor of camps where sewerage is inadequate and water shortages
are a daily occurence in the dry season.
</P>
<P>
   Rabiha Salem, 47, and her daughter, Wafa, 20, took shelter from
a blazing sun in the camp in a thin line of shade along a
garbage-strewn alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``More important than the words of a declaration of statehood
are the things we need to live our lives,'' said Rabiha, whose
husband and two sons, both in their early 20s, are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent years and years fighting for nothing. What we need is
housing, and schools, and factories. We need a future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A construction site in Abu Dis, straddling Jerusalem, is an apt
metaphor for the promise, and failure, of a Palestinian state. When
work began three years ago, the site was intended to be the future
seat of government in East Jerusalem, which Palestinians see as the
capital of a future state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Palestinian officials are evasive when asked about the
purpose of the building. But Abu Usama, 50, the supervisor of the
construction, Tuesday showed a reporter a large terraced conference
center that he said is ``designed for 180 seats for the Palestinian
parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he proudly walked to the half-built, seven-story
``government office building'' next door and showed a large room
which he said would be ``the office of the prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost of the Palestinian Authority-funded project
is $10 million, he said, and it is one year behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   No windows have been installed, but a hole in a seventh story
wall looked out on a commanding view of Jerusalem's Kidron Valley
and the magnificent golden Dome of the Rock in Jerusalem's Old
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud when I see this view,'' said Abu Usama. ``It
tells me that we are building a state, and that its capital will be
in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Daoud Hanafsi, an unemployed construction worker who lives in
Abu Dis, saw the building as a different kind of symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Arafat's state,'' he said, pointing to the
construction site, ``unfinished, over-budget, and full of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanafsi said his village of Abu Dis, which remains under Israeli
security but Palestinian civil control, suffers from deep poverty.
There is no hospital, schools are crumbling, and unemployment soars
over 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a state means dealing with those problems,'' he said.
``Not waving a piece of paper before the world that declares
statehood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
