<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-AMEREXP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY TO OFFER AMERICAN EXPRESS CARDS TO SOME CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a powerful marketing alliance that unites two
financial services giants and signals growing convergence between
investment service companies, Fidelity Investments said Tuesday it
would offer American Express credit cards to its brokerage
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, which brings together the nation's largest mutual
fund firm and the world's leading credit card issuer, allows
Fidelity to offer an American Express gold card sporting the
Fidelity Investments name to brokerage clients beginning in June.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity will provide a single, consolidated monthly statement
that includes card charges and waive the card's $75 annual fee. To
qualify, clients must have brokerage account balances of at least
$30,000. American Express Co. will debit purchases directly from
the customer's account.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's ``brokerage'' account, technically known as an Ultra
Service Account, or USA, is a bit of a misnomer. It is essentially
an asset management account with check writing, direct deposit,
stock trading, investment research, and mutual fund features, all
reported on one monthly statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is best known as a fund giant. But the alliance between
Fidelity and American Express is designed to help both
household-name companies offer ``one-stop shopping'' for financial
services, from credit cards and mutual funds to checking and
on-line stock trading. Alfred F. Kelly, president of American
Express's consumer card group, said the Fidelity alliance was ``a
major step in our efforts to build relationships with leading
financial services companies around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the partnership reflected a growing trend among
financial services and Internet-related companies to team up to try
to gain a greater share of the customer's wallet. Fidelity expects
to announce a major alliance with an Internet provider in coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the alliance trend, Fidelity's marketing head,
Stephen A. Cone, said Tuesday that Fidelity had already forged a
unique arrangement with 3Com Corp., the maker of Palm Pilot
personal organizers. The Series 7 Palm Pilot, to debut nationally
in July, comes preloaded with software allowing access to Fidelity
brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The device will function like Fidelity's two-way pagers, which
let customers trade stocks and funds instantly. The Fidelity name
and logo will be displayed prominently on the screen of the new
Palm Pilots, which will be manufactured in the millions, Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 75 percent of Fidelity's 2.5 million brokerage
clients have American Express cards, giving the credit card issuer,
whose market share has slipped in recent years, a prime pool of
customers. Fidelity will also provide at no fee an unlimited number
of supplementary cards to brokerage clients. Around 60 percent of
Fidelity's brokerage accounts are jointly held, which could
translate into a bigger customer base.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Fidelity is hoping that the convenience of a
single monthly statement will encourage customers to consolidate
their mutual fund, banking, and credit card accounts into one
Fidelity product. About 90 percent of Fidelity's total revenues
comes from 10 percent of the firm's clients. The private firm,
which manages $806.1 billion in assets and has the nation's
second-largest discount brokerage, wants to leverage more business
out of its top customers and stronger revenue at a time of falling
fund sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Express alliance is a critical step in Fidelity's
plan to attract and retain top clients,'' said Eric M. Kobren,
publisher of the independent Fidelity Insight newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity will offer a platinum American Express card beginning
in July and reduce the $300 annual fee to $225.
</P>
<P>
   While the two companies spoke in glowing terms of the venture,
under which they will share revenues and expenses, they declined to
provide profit projections.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity currently offers a direct-debit Visa card. Fidelity
customers will have to choose between the American Express and Visa
cards. Cone, a former American Express executive, said Fidelity
planned to promote its American Express relationship in a current
campaign devoted to its on-line brokerage but would not put much
marketing muscle behind its Visa arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is considering offering its Advisor fund family, sold
through third-party channels, to American Express's financial
advisory arm, which has a captive sales force. American Express has
smaller credit card ventures with Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. and
CIBC Oppenheimer &AMP; Co. but does not promote them heavily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
