r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-BOMBVICTIMS-T     05-04 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-BOMBVICTIMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO DEVASTATION EVOKES MEMORY OF ANOTHER DAY OF TERROR IN
OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
and MIKE LEE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rubble _ and who might be under it _ triggers the worst
memories for Frank Koch, a veteran Oklahoma City policeman and an
up-close witness to terror.
</P>
<P>
   Just over four years ago, Koch began the first of 17 consecutive
days inside the twisted and torn Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building,
pulling out people. Some were still alive, others dead and
dismembered by a bomb made of diesel fuel and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said Tuesday that he is prepared to return to the rubble,
this time left by massive tornadoes that ripped through Oklahoma
and Kansas on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Like four years ago, Koch said, the Oklahoma City area ``looks
like a war zone. And knowing there might still be victims in the
rubble makes it just like with the Murrah building ... We're going
to have to go through each home and look piece by piece for any
survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Koch, Jannie Coverdale said she has never forgotten what
happened on April 19, 1995, when 168 people died in the bombing.
But this week's tragedy, she said, brings back even more vividly
the memory of those late-evening storms and tornado warnings in
1995 that delayed discovery of her grandsons, Aaron, 5, and Elijah,
2, inside the Murrah building.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys were among the 19 children killed by the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think God is trying to tell Oklahoma City something,''
Coverdale said. ``I think he's trying to say we need to change the
way we're living. We need to become closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there is an overwhelming sense of sadness and loss
drifting through Oklahoma. But the anger, so prevalent in the
aftermath of the OKC bomb, has not resurfaced, say Koch and
Coverdale.
</P>
<P>
   The fury of a tornado, an act of God, they say, cannot compare
to the hatred and meanness exhibited by Timothy McVeigh and Terry
Nichols, the convicted architects of the Murrah bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing was mass murder,'' Coverdale said, while ``the
tornadoes were not something that human beings did.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Koch: ``We can't blame this on God; It's just one of those
things that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Treanor said she was blaming no one when she huddled
with her family in the basement of her Oklahoma home Monday night.
Instead, as tornadoes danced around her, Treanor said she thought
of her 4mATQ0Z ATQ0Z +++ &QC; Umcpv3M&AMP;x
</P>
