<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOROCCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SHUNNING NETANYAHU GOVERNMENT, HASSAN RECEIVES ISRAELI
DELEGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARRAKESH, Morocco _ After three years of shunning the Israeli
government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, King Hassan II of
Morocco has returned to the role of potential Middle East
intermediary by receiving a delegation of 50 Israeli legislators,
religious leaders and businessmen at the royal palace in Marrakesh.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old king was a key intermediary in negotiations
between Israel and its Palestinian and Arab adversaries over nearly
25 years from the early 1970s. But he froze his contacts with
Israel after the Netanyahu government took power and adopted a
hard-line approach toward carrying out the 1993 accords between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the king's new initiative prompted criticism from
some in Israel, who suggested that Hassan was trying to influence
the Israeli election on May 17. Most members of the Israeli
delegation received by the king belong to Israel's large and
politically influential community of Moroccan Jews, many of whom
have supported Netanyahu's right-wing Likud Party in the past.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli polls pointing to a close battle between Netanyahu
and Ehud Barak, the leader of the opposition Labor Party, a small
shift in voting patterns among the 500,000 Jews of Moroccan origin
could influence the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception in the Marrakesh palace on Monday night, Hassan
appeared sensitive to the charge that he was interfering in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never interfered in Israel's internal affairs, and I
have no wish to interfere in your election now,'' he said. ``All
that I would ask is that you vote for an idea, the idea of peace.
Israel and the Arab nations need peace, and you must do whatever
you can to help achieve that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, a trade minister in the Netanyahu Cabinet and a
leader of Israel's Russian immigrants, said the king had allayed
concerns that he might be seeking to sway the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the private meeting, he told us four times, I'm not trying
to tell you how to vote,'' Sharansky said. ``So I think even those
who saw this as an attempt to interfere have realized that the king
has much longer-term goals, in terms of reviving the peace process
and offering himself as a possible intermediary.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
