<HEADLINE>
TRAMPING FOR RAMPS, A SURE SIGN OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: W.Va., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENSSELAERVILLE, N.Y. _ Bill Bensen, the chef of the Palmer
House Cafe here, was tramping through the woods two weeks ago,
searching for signs of green ramp tips breaking the frosty ground
cover, insisting that spring had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He was still layered in polar fleece and a parka, his breath
forming wisps in the chilly air. Even so, he was mentally composing
dishes for his annual Rampage, the almost-all-ramp menu served each
spring in his 20-seat cafe in this upstate hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``See! Over there! The green!'' he yelled, jumping up and down,
either in excitement or for warmth. ``When it gets a little warmer
in that dell, this whole place will smell like onions!''
</P>
<P>
   Let the meek extol the virtues of mild-mannered cultivated
leeks. Real cooks forage for ramps. The leafy, bulbous, aromatic
plants, the wild cousins of leeks, sprout in rich forest soil from
Canada to Georgia, and as far west as Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ramps have more heat and bite than leeks or scallions and, when
cooked, a soft nutty taste rarely found in either garlic or onions.
</P>
<P>
   Ramps tend to cluster near groves of sugar maples. Foragers like
Bensen know better than to try to pick a ramp. Their root systems
are so deep and entwined that only a shovel can scoop six inches
beneath the earth and loosen a clump of ramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know three things for sure,'' he said as he knelt to clear
frost and old leaves and pine needles from one of his favorite ramp
patches. ``First, ramps on the perimeter of the patch are usually
bigger. Secondly, they can look like lily of the valley, which are
poisonous, so if the plant doesn't smell like onion, don't eat it.
And the third thing I know is that for every ramp I dig, two more
come the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lexicographers say the word ``ramp'' was Middle English for
wild garlic, others say for wild leeks. But people around here say
the similarity to ``tramp'' explains the name. The tramping and
digging, cleaning and cooking required to turn muddy,
garlic-smelling bulbs and their leafy greens into a toothsome
delicacy play no small role in ramp mystique.
</P>
<P>
   Bensen walks about a mile into a rocky forest in the Helderberg
Mountains and digs for about an hour to get a bushel of dirt-caked
ramps (32 quarts), which need to be trimmed of their roots and
outer sheaths, then soaked in cold water and rinsed repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about two hours to clean and cook a bushel of ramps,
and the hunter-gatherer is left with only two to four cups of
cooked greens. About 55 ramps make a pound; when cooked, they will
serve three people as a side dish or an ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   But the triumph of emerging from the dark woods, a ramp-filled
bushel basket balanced on the end of a shovel, makes all the effort
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Ramp-rich places tend to be isolated little hamlets like
Rensselaerville, and many of them celebrate the aromatic delicacy
with festivals in springtime like Bensen's Rampage. The Ramp Romp
in Helvetia, W.Va., is probably the best-known revel, serving up
ramp chili, ramp home fries, ramp omelets, ramp pie, batter-fried
ramps, scalloped ramps and potatoes, ramp slaw, and corn-bread
sandwiches with pulled pork and raw ramps.
</P>
<P>
   Similar dishes can be found in Elks' lodges and church basements
throughout Appalachia and New England, and parts of the Midwest and
the South, from late March to mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs in cities tend to take a more sophisticated tack with
ramps, which are heaped high in bunches in the Union Square
Greenmarket in Manhattan at this time of year. Union Square Cafe
features a gratin of ramps, potatoes and Gruyere cheese; Home
offers ramp and mint pesto; Verbena serves blini with grilled
ramps, and Gotham Bar and Grill serves farfalle with ramps, cremini
mushrooms, pea shoots, Parmesan and white truffle oil.
</P>
<P>
   Ramps are often braised in wine or grilled, but that robs them
of their full nutty flavor. It blooms only when they are covered
with olive oil, braised until tender and allowed to rest in a
covered dish. Rural cooks use pork or goose fat instead.
</P>
<P>
   After they are braised, ramps can be served in a vinaigrette,
laid onto pizza or added to pasta or risotto. The oil or fat they
have flavored can then add a blast of spring-in-the-woods to shad
or shad roe, chicken, game or shellfish _ although you won't
usually see much shellfish in places where you see lots of ramps.
</P>
<P>
   Bensen's Rampage last weekend was the sort of event that
celebrates one of the things that tiny hill towns hold in common.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 guests, who ate family style _ johnnycakes with wilted
ramps and creme fraiche; scalloped ramps and potatoes topped with
shad roe; a spring ragout of ramps with spinach, fiddlehead ferns
and morels, topped with chicken from the Palmer House Cafe smoker _
were in complete accord: ramps are worth the work.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RAMPS BRAISED IN OLIVE OIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes, plus 10 minutes resting time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups olive oil, plus more if necessary
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ramps (approximately 6 bunches), cleaned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place olive oil in a large, shallow pan with a tight-fitting
lid over high heat. When oil is warm, roll a bunch of ramps in
paper towels to remove excess moisture, and unwrap. Reduce heat to
medium and add ramps to pan. Toss to coat each leaf with oil.
Working quickly, dry second bunch and add to oil, tossing until
ramps wilt. Continue with remaining ramps, adding more oil if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   2. When all ramps are wilted, season to taste and reduce heat to
low, then stir and cover pot. Cook 5 to 10 minutes, depending on
the size of the ramps, stirring frequently to avoid burning. When
ramps are very, very tender, remove pan from heat and let sit,
covered, for 10 minutes. Season again if desired, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings as a side dish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPRING GREEN RISOTTO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Savoy Restaurant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ramps, cleaned
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken or vegetable broth or water, warmed
</P>
<P>
   { pound spring greens (spinach, dandelion or watercress),
roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Parmesan or Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut off ramp bulbs. Thinly slice greens and chop bulbs
coarsely. Reserve about 2 tablespoons bulb.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a heavy pot over medium-high heat and warm olive oil.
Add chopped ramp bulbs and greens. Toss quickly to soften, about 2
minutes. Add rice and stir for several minutes. Add wine, stir and
cook for 2 to 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Begin adding the warmed broth, a cup or so at a time,
stirring and cooking for 5 to 15 minutes between additions. When
rice has lost its rock-hard center, add spring greens. Stir and add
the reserved ramp bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   4. When greens have wilted, add butter and half the cheese.
Taste. Each grain of rice should have a firm center, and the
mixture should be soupy. If necessary, add more water or broth and
cook a few minutes, stirring occasionally. Add thyme, season with
salt and pepper and serve, garnished with remaining grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN WITH LEMON AND RAMPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Palmer House Cafe, Rensselaerville, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 70 minutes, plus up to 24 hours resting time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken, about 3 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   10 ramps
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2{ teaspoons coarsely ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Dry chicken with paper towels. Cut off and discard wing tips.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut two wedges into each end of the lemon in a cross shape,
deep enough to expose the tiniest bit of the fruit. Wrap ramps
around lemon, using the grooves of the cross-cut to secure them.
Tie on with kitchen twine.
</P>
<P>
   3. Rub lemon with about { teaspoon shortening and season it well
with salt. Stuff lemon in the cavity of the chicken. Truss chicken
and rub with remaining vegetable shortening. Season liberally with
salt, then press pepper all over skin. Refrigerate overnight or for
up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove chicken from the refrigerator and preheat oven to 450
degrees. Roast chicken 10 minutes, reduce heat to 350 degrees and
roast 40 to 45 minutes, until juices run clear when pricked with a
knife. Let rest for 10 minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
