<HEADLINE>
MORALES SUBPOENAED IN TOBACCO FEE CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorney General John Cornyn has subpoenaed his
predecessor, Dan Morales, to possibly testify in a federal court
hearing Thursday about the role that a Morales friend played in
Texas' lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Morales is fighting the subpoena, which was issued last week but
wasn't announced until Tuesday. He wasn't available for comment.
But his attorney, Sam Millsap of San Antonio, called Cornyn's
effort to force Morales' attendance ``unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Folsom ruled earlier that witnesses
won't be necessary for the hearing in Texarkana, Millsap said. He
filed a motion to quash the subpoena, but Folsom hadn't ruled on
the motion late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is related to Houston lawyer Marc Murr's claim for
about $260 million in legal fees from the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has said that Murr, a longtime friend, was crucial to
the state's success in negotiating a $17.3 billion settlement from
tobacco companies last year. But other lawyers have complained that
Murr did little work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has said that both he and the FBI are investigating
Murr's role in the lawsuit. Millsap says the controversy stems from
``politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody from the FBI, the Justice Department or the U.S.
attorney's office has contacted Dan or me, and they know I
represent Dan,'' Millsap said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn spokesman Ted Delisi said the attorney general subpoenaed
Morales last week after Murr's lawyer, Roy Minton of Austin, told
the judge that Murr would be available to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the judge has ruled witnesses wouldn't be necessary,
Cornyn still wants Morales available for possible questioning if
Murr shows up at the hearing, as is expected, Delisi said.
</P>
<P>
   A state arbitration panel appointed by Morales and Murr awarded
Murr $260 million for work on the tobacco case last fall. But
cigarette makers are bound under the Texas agreement to pay Murr
only $1 million, which was awarded by national arbitrators.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom has ordered Murr to ``show cause'' why the $260 million
arbitration award should not be dismissed because, he said, the way
the state panel was appointed violated his order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
