<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST-JOHN-CATHEDRAL-ART     05-04 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST-JOHN-CATHEDRAL-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONUMENTS OF STONE, TESTAMENTS TO AN ISLAND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Maine, N.Y.)   (af)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Today the residents of Vinalhaven Island, Maine,
nestled in Penobscot Bay some 15 miles off Rockland, boast of their
lobstering industry and an aversion to tourists. But nearly a
century ago, the tiny island, roughly nine miles long and five
miles wide, had another source of pride: its cliffs and knolls
provided the granite for some of the nation's most imposing
structures, among them the Brooklyn Bridge, the United States
Custom House and the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the island's quarries, and specifically the
erection of eight monumental columns in the cathedral's sanctuary,
are the subject of an exhibition lining the cathedral's photography
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eight Columns of Worship: A Tribute to Human Ingenuity and
Faith'' tells the story behind the buildings that stand as a
testament to the majesty and endurance of Vinalhaven granite. And
though the photographs and artifacts are on view only through next
Sunday, the structures themselves will live on as a kind of
three-dimensional exhibit _ one that is being documented anew by
Chester Higgins Jr., a photographer for The New York Times and an
occasional visitor to the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``My love for stone comes from my love for ancient Egyptian
architecture,'' Higgins said. ``While visiting the island I heard
that they had these quarries, and through my research I discovered
that so much of the stuff that came from the island landed in New
York. I was fascinated.''
</P>
<P>
   He set out to photograph the stone monuments whose impact on
society transcended time but whose architectural style fell out of
favor after only a few decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of steel and reinforced concrete replaced the massive
granite buildings,'' said Roy Heisler of the Vinalhaven Historical
Society, where the exhibition originated. ``The importance is the
legacy of the stones, and the great buildings that were produced
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Settled by fishermen in the late 18th century, Vinalhaven
reached its population peak (2,855) in 1880, when the quarries
employed some 1,500 men from New England, Canada and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   What made Vinalhaven granite unique was not only its superb
quality and color _ a warm pinkish-gray _ but the ease with which
it could be transported off the island. By the 1850s, the Bodwell &AMP;
Webster quarry (later the Bodwell Granite Co.) had received a
number of federal contracts for reinforcements at forts along the
Atlantic and gulf coasts.
</P>
<P>
   But the demand for granite escalated enormously after the Civil
War, when a trend toward European grandeur in American architecture
sent the government scurrying for an economical but beautiful stone
to use in custom houses, post offices, dams, bridges and banks as
far west as St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The stones used in the Pennsylvania Railroad Station in
Philadelphia, the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Executive
Office Building and part of the Washington Monument were culled
from the Vinalhaven quarries.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the architect George Heins had set out in
search of the stone for the cathedral's eight columns. He
ultimately chose Bodwell's Wharff Quarry. With its 100-foot-tall
ridge of nearly flawless virgin granite, the quarry could easily
accommodate the columns' dimensions: 54 feet long and 6 feet in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
   The first block of granite, extracted in August 1899, was some
64 feet long and 8{ feet wide and weighed about 300 tons. After
being cut from the bed, each block was hewn with hand tools to
within 3 inches of a column's finished dimension. In order to turn
and polish the columns, the quarry commissioned the world's largest
lathe, a behemoth weighing 135 tons that became an overnight media
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   But disaster struck. As it neared completion, the first column
suddenly snapped in the lathe. The second and third columns soon
followed suit. By August 1901, the architects had determined that a
single block of such proportions could not withstand the pressure
of the turning on the lathe. They decided to build the columns in
two pieces: a 90-ton, 36-foot-long lower monolith and a 40-ton,
18-foot-long upper portion that could be reattached so as not to be
noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, 1903, the first two columns and their bases were
loaded for the trip to New York aboard a specially designed barge.
After being pulled through the Atlantic, into Long Island Sound and
up the Hudson River, the barge arrived at the West 134th Street
pier eight days later.
</P>
<P>
   The moving and erecting of the columns is widely considered
among the world's most remarkable engineering feats. When the tide
was right, the columns were rolled off the barge using its huge
derrick, a timber hitch and an inclined plane.
</P>
<P>
   A truck with wooden wheels, pulled ahead by a powerful winch
some 300 feet at a time, then carried the column pieces through the
streets of New York to 112th Street and Amsterdam Avenue, a journey
of about two miles. It took 19 days.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a derrick made of two 96-foot lengths of Oregon pine
and powered by three steam engines was constructed to swing the
columns into place atop the bases. By Nov. 25, 1904, all eight
columns were in position, waiting for the walls to be built around
them.
</P>
<P>
   The onset of modern construction techniques put an end to major
quarrying in 1918, but paving blocks continued to be exported until
1939. Aside from a smattering of rusty pieces of machinery, the
only existing evidence of Vinalhaven's legacy is a single column.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flawed column, remaining right on the shore,'' Heisler
said. ``It's overgrown, but its meaning is fairly evident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
