<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-LOWE-BOS &LR;      05-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LOWE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MAY BE LOOKING TO LOWE FOR RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day will come, Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan is sure,
when Derek Lowe will be a closer in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Gordon entering his third week on the disabled list
with a sore pitching elbow, that day can't come soon enough for the
Red Sox, who opened the season with five straight wins but are now
a game under .500 (12-13) for the first time as they return home to
face the Texas Rangers Wednesday at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a devastating sinker that this past winter made Lowe the
object of desire for many clubs talking trade with Sox general
manager Dan Duquette, Lowe hasn't seized the role with the ease
that some expected.
</P>
<P>
   Given his age (25) and level of experience (last season was his
first full year in the big leagues), those expectations may have
been misguided. Manager Jimy Williams is preaching patience despite
Lowe's recent travails, which include a yield of five runs last
Friday in Oakland and the inability to close out a game with a
five-run lead Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needs one good outing, that's all,'' Williams said.
``The stuff is there. There's nothing wrong with him. Probably have
him the next time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is not alone in a relief corps that outside of lefthander
Rheal Cormier has struggled mightily in Gordon's absence. Jim
Corsi, who has blown four saves, calls it a plague. ``It almost
doesn't matter who's out there,'' Corsi said in the aftermath of
Monday's 12-11 loss to the A's, in which the Sox blew a 7-0 lead
that was still 11-6 in the eighth. ``Something bad has been
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't made the bullpen's job any easier that the starters
have been coming up short. On the recently completed 2-5 trip, only
Pedro Martinez and Pat Rapp were able to pitch at least six
innings. Tim Wakefield has pitched a total of 15 innings in his
last four starts. Mark Portugal has lasted five and four innings in
his last two outings. Bret Saberhagen missed a start last Friday
with a sore shoulder; instead of summoning another pitcher from
Pawtucket, the Sox decided they could muddle through the weekend
with what they had.
</P>
<P>
   That idea blew up on Williams. Kip Gross was lit up early as
Saberhagen's stand-in, and Wakefield and Portugal were both KO'd
quickly, placing the bullpen in the position of having to toil 22
innings in the four games in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Overexposed and overtaxed, the Sox relievers gave up 20 earned
runs in the four games (counting Gross's three-inning, five-run
start). In that span, they allowed 20 hits while walking an
astounding 19 batters, hitting six others, and uncorking three wild
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let this snowball,'' Lowe said Monday. ``We have to
figure out individually what we're doing wrong and correct it.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying, of course, that Lowe's confidence has
taken some hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a struggle to get an out right now,'' he said. ``Before,
when I was making good pitches, outs came easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, when you're struggling, everyone starts doubting
themselves, because obviously you're doing something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who didn't give up a home run in 53 relief appearances
last season, already has surrendered three this year. And the
five-run yield Friday, in which A's rookie Olmedo Saenz took him
deep for a three-run home run, was the worst inning of his
big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanically, I'm all messed up,'' said Lowe, who in watching
video of his outing found that he was turning his back too far,
then springing wide open. ``Normally when I'm going good, I miss
down, but when I'm continually missing up, that tells everyone
something is mechanically wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to overanalyze it. Let it be. You want to go out
there and pitch again as soon as you can and feel aggressive. You
can't be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the process for a young reliever-in-training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a long way to go,'' he said. ``Up to this point,
my stats have been pretty good, but I've been pitching behind (in
the count to) hitters and given up three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get back where I was in spring training. In spring
training, I knew every time I went out there I would get people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the practice games ended five weeks ago. For the Sox to
right themselves, they have to be able to rely on Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I need is one good outing and I'll be right back to where
I want to be,'' Lowe said, echoing his manager. ``It doesn't take
much. But my job is to minimize the damage, and I haven't been
doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
