<HEADLINE>
IOC PURGE ALMOST OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Except for an ongoing investigation of Australian member Phil
Coles, the International Olympic Committee's internal purge appears
to be over.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's executive committee decided Tuesday to take no further
action against board member Kim Un Yong of South Korea but will
keep Coles's case open amid fresh allegations that Salt Lake City
bidders acquired sensitive information about Sydney's bid for the
2000 Summer Games plus Coles's notes about how his colleagues might
vote in the balloting for the 2002 Winter Games site.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC's new outside ethics panel will look into more
than two dozen leftover cases involving members and bid cities from
other years, those alleged improprieties appear to be relatively
trivial. Most of them involve entertainment for relatives or extra
guests during visits to bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, which has expelled six members and pressured four
others to step down, had already issued severe warnings to both Kim
and Coles for their roles in the Salt Lake payoff scandal, the
worst in modern Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   Though he said there was no new evidence to justify expelling
Kim, vice president Richard Pound of Canada said the Coles inquiry
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is now the issue is the nature of his relationship with
Salt Lake and the information that he may or may not have been
passing on,'' said Pound. ``There's enough there that we should
keep it open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
