<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA EXECUTES VIETNAM VET FOR 1980 MURDER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Manuel Pina Babbitt, a Vietnam Veteran who was
awarded a Purple Heart while on death row, was executed early
Tuesday morning at San Quentin prison for the 1980 murder of a
78-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Gov. Gray Davis, also a Vietnam veteran, denied
Babbitt's bid for clemency, despite pleas for mercy from thousands
of veterans who believed that Babbitt's experiences during two
tours of duty in the war, particularly during the 77-day siege at
Khe Sanh, were at least partly responsible for his crime.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, who turned 50 just hours before he was killed, became
the seventh person put to death by the state since it resumed
executions in 1992, and the second since Davis took office in
January.
</P>
<P>
   He asked that the $50 allotted for the last meal, which he
turned down, be donated to a homeless Vietnam Veteran. Prison
officials refused the request. A last-minute appeal to the Supreme
Court for a stay delayed the execution by 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt was convicted of breaking into the Sacramento apartment
of Leah Schendel in 1980 and beating her severely, causing a fatal
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested when his older brother, Bill, called police
after finding a cigarette lighter with the initials ``L.S.'' among
Babbitt's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Babbitt, whose paranoid schizophrenia was diagnosed after
the war, when he became homeless, had said he did not remember
attacking Ms. Schendel, nor an attack the following night on
another woman who was slightly injured before a friend intervened.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers argued in appeals that he had severe post-traumatic
stress syndrome and was having a flashback to the Vietnam War when
he attacked Ms. Schendel.
</P>
<P>
   During Babbitt's 1982 trial, his lawyer, James Schenk, mentioned
post-traumatic stress syndrome but it was not the centerpiece of
his defense. In an affidavit filed with Babbitt's appeal, Schenk
said he had failed ``completely,'' most notably by failing to note
Babbitt's mental illness and his amnesia during combat.
</P>
<P>
   His appeals lawyers argued that Babbitt's flashback the night of
Ms. Schendel's death was triggered by seeing headlights in the fog
shortly before he broke into her apartment. Babbitt had said the
lights, which reminded him of aircraft lights that were always met
by enemy fire moments later, were the last thing he remembered that
night.
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt's appeals were exhausted without his receiving a
single evidentiary hearing. While on death row, Babbitt received
the Purple Heart for wounds suffered during Khe Sanh.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who watched Babbitt die were his brother Bill, and
seven members of Mrs. Schendel's family. Afterwards, the Schendel
family, which had mounted a relentless campaign over 18 years to
have Babbitt executed, expressed sympathy for his family in a
statement and said: ``It is the necessary conclusion to a horrible
crime that should never have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's last words, said San Quentin's acting warden, Jeanne
Woodfard, who walked him to his death, were: ``I forgive all of
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
