<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMBEL OFFICIALLY WELCCOMED TO ``CBS THIS MORNING'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the fanfare CBS could muster, including appearances by
New York mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and developer Donald J. Trump,
the network Tuesday heralded the return of Bryant Gumbel to morning
television as the new coanchor of ``CBS This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy live television, and morning is the best place to do
that,'' Gumbel said during a news conference in New York that was
transmitted nationally via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel, a three-time Emmy winner who coanchored NBC's ``Today''
show from 1982 to 1997, added that he is ``very excited and
optimistic'' about the chance ``to build a program from the ground
up with an old and trusted friend,'' a reference to former
``Today'' executive producer Steve Friedman, who was put in charge
of the CBS program.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Gumbel said he did not miss morning television in
the two years since he left ``Today,'' and acknowledged that it
took a while for him to come to grips with ``the idea of getting up
at 4:30 every day and doing two hours of a live broadcast . . .
It's a grind.'' With three years remaining on his $5 million-a-year
contract, Gumbel declined to specify how long he would remain with
the morning program, saying he would approach it ``a day at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about returning to mornings after a failed bid to become a
prime-time star with his canceled newsmagazine ``Public Eye With
Bryant Gumbel,'' he said: ``I don't view coming back to do
something that I enjoy as a step down.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel will begin his stint on Nov. 1 in a new,
5,000-square-foot studio on the ground floor of the Trump-managed
General Motors Building. His coanchor is expected to be named by
the end of this summer. CBS News president Andrew Heyward Tuesday
declined to say what will become of Mark McEwen and Jane Robelot,
the current coanchors of ``This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward made clear, however, that the network will urge local
affiliates and CBS-owned stations _ such as WBZ-Ch. 4 _ to carry
the 7-to-8 a.m. hour of the Gumbel-hosted program, rather than
preempt it for local news as many currently do.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 4 general manager Ed Goldman said Tuesday he is ``very
receptive'' to surrendering the 7-to-8 a.m. hour, now devoted to
the last hour of the station's ``News Four New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said he wants to give the network ``full competitive
leverage'' in Boston as it embarks on ``one of the great things CBS
has done: getting Bryant Gumbel on its morning show.'' In addition,
Goldman predicted a ``halo effect'' of extra viewers for Channel
4's early-morning newscasts akin to that provided to NBC affiliates
by the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's new duties will put him in competition with his old
``Today'' colleagues. He said Tuesday that he called Matt Lauer,
who replaced him as ``Today'' coanchor, executive producer Jeff
Zucker, and weather forecaster Al Roker (no mention was made of a
call to Katie Couric).
</P>
<P>
   ``They all sincerely _ at least it sounded sincere _ wished me
luck,'' said Gumbel. ``We're not looking to run them off the road.
. . . We're looking to compete on an even keel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' may already be on its guard. Heyward quoted Couric as
directing this jab at him during a recent dinner: ``Getting a
street studio, getting Bryant Gumbel to do a morning show: What an
original idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel's morning competition includes Couric and Lauer at
``Today'' and Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson at ABC's ``Good
Morning America.'' The amount of star power deployed in the morning
underscores the growth and profitability of a time period that used
to be relegated, in Gumbel's words, to ``a rehash of the evening
news. Now, people view what happens in the morning as much more
cutting edge than the evening newscasts.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the heavy hitters at Tuesday's news conference
underscored CBS's high hopes for Gumbel. His presence is sorely
needed at a network whose morning show has been stalled in third
place since 1975. CBS Television president Leslie Moonves called
Gumbel and Friedman ``the cornerstone of a plan to make CBS fully
competitive in the morning,'' which he noted is one of the few time
periods where viewership is growing. Heyward, though he declined to
say how much CBS spent on the new studio, said the network has made
``the most significant investment by far that CBS has ever made in
this time period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
