<HEADLINE>
PURGE IN KOSOVO SLOWED, NOT STOPPED, NATO GENERAL REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of President Clinton's arrival at NATO
headquarters in Belgium, the alliance's top general reported
Tuesday that NATO's 42-day aerial assault against Serb forces has
failed to halt the brutal purge of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress growing increasingly restless over the US role in
the NATO mission, German General Klaus Naumann, the head of NATO's
military arm, said the allied siege has slowed but ``cannot stop''
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign of ``ethnic
cleansing'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic's mass deportation campaign appears
achievable,'' Naumann said at a news conference at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment came as a prominent Republican senator questioned
Clinton's courage and political will in handling the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is prepared to lose a war
rather than do the hard work, the politically risky work, of
fighting it as the leader of the greatest nation on earth should
fight when our interests and our values are imperiled,'' Senator
John McCain of Arizona said in the harshest attack yet on the
Senate floor against Clinton's handling of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, the Senate voted 78-22 to shelve McCain's
resolution calling on Clinton to use ``all necessary force'' to
defeat Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Senator John F. Kerry are among a group of Vietnam
veterans in the Senate who have argued that the United States
should enter a military conflict only if the political leaders
intend to use every necessary means to win. ``I wanted this
resolution considered in now-forlorn hope that the president would
take courage from it, find the resolve to do his duty,'' said
McCain, a presidential candidate and former Navy pilot who spent
more than seven years in a North Vietnam prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, before departing the White House for his 48-hour trip
to Europe, warned against viewing the Kosovo crisis with
``indifference or impatience.'' His call for patience was seen as a
response to McCain and others, including Kerry, who have rebuked
him for failing to prepare for a possible ground war against
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The president, citing his meeting on Monday with Russian envoy
Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, said he is prepared to ``seize every
diplomatic possibility'' to end the conflict, but only on the
condition that Milosevic accepts NATO's key demands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton left open the prospect of an agreement that could
save face for Milosevic and his Serb forces. ``This is not a defeat
for Serbia we are seeking,'' he said. ``What we are seeking is the
simple right of Kosovar Albanians to live in peace on their own
land without fear of cleansing because of their religious or ethnic
background.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments as the sixth week of NATO
bombing neared an end:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ethnic Albanians continued to flee marauding Serb forces in
Kosovo by the thousands, pouring through border stations with new
reports of murder and extortion by Milosevic's troops. An estimated
6,000 refugees crossed into Albania, while more than 11,600 reached
critically overcrowded camps in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the refugees told similar stories of Serb soldiers
demanding money from fleeing ethnic Albanians and shooting those
who did not comply. In one episode, Serb troops murdered about 100
civilians and dumped them in a mass grave, according to the Kosovo
Liberation Army's news agency. The reports could not be
independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   To date, nearly 680,000 Kosovar Albanians have been driven from
Kosovo, while an estimated 750,000 remain homeless within the
Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   _ The exodus continued despite another 24 days of NATO
bombardment, as allied warplanes hit targets throughout Kosovo and
Serbia. Amid the assault, a US Air Force F-16 shot down a Yugoslav
MiG-29 fighter jet in a dogfight, the first downing of Yugoslav
aircraft since two MiG-29s went down on the second day of the NATO
operation. The Russian-made MiG-29s are Yugoslavia's best fighter
jets.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also said its planes Tuesday bombed a MiG-29 parked at an
airfield, leaving Milosevic with only four of his original 15
MiG-29s. The others also were destroyed on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon, responding to reports by the Serbian news media,
said one of the three Army soldiers who were released from a
Yugoslav prison on Sunday left his captors a note thanking them for
treating him with ``dignity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sergeant Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.,
signed the note and added in quotations, ``Slobodan,'' the Pentagon
acknowledged. In addition to being the Yugoslav president's first
name, ``slobodan'' means ``free'' in Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   The state-controlled Serbian news media translated the note as
saying: ``I have much liking for Serbian people after this and I
will continue to pray to God for (peace sign) and an end to this
war. Thank you mostly for the cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon declined to release a copy of the note. But the
Army released a statement that said, ``The note in no way reflects
a lack of support for his mission or NATO policy. This note in no
way lessens the US Army Europe's and 1st Infantry Division's
respect and admiration for Staff Sgt. Stone's personal conduct
during his trying ordeal.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The day after Clinton indicated he might support a pause in
the NATO bombing to seek a diplomatic resolution, Bob Dole, his
Republican rival in the 1996 presidential race, urged him not to
end the conflict short of a NATO victory. Dole had helped the
ethnic Albanians develop a peace plan that six countries endorsed
before Milosevic ultimately rejected it, triggering the NATO
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reaffirmed his commitment to achieving NATO's demands
for peace before he left for Europe, where he also will visit US
pilots in Germany and some of the Kosovar Albanians who were
relocated to Germany after fleeing their homeland. The president
also plans to meet the three freed US POWs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin said a major sticking point in resolving
the military conflict is the type of peacekeeping force that will
patrol Kosovo. ``Whether it would be paramilitary, military or
civil forces, of course, is subject to negotiations,'' Chernomyrdin
said after he met at the United Nations with Secretary General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Engaged in nearly non-stop shuttle diplomacy, Chernomyrdin met
earlier Tuesday in Washington with Vice President Al Gore and other
senior administration officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
