<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE PANEL MAY VOTE ON COMPROMISE PARENTAL NOTIFICATION
BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A key sponsor in the Texas House of a bill that
would require parents to be notified when their teens seek
abortions said Tuesday a compromise bill appears heading for a vote
of an influential legislative committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dianne Delisi, R-Temple, expressed hope for a compromise
parental notification bill drafted by Rep. Steve Wolens, D-Dallas,
chairman of the House State Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who formed a committee this spring to
explore a 2000 presidential bid, has promised social conservatives
in his party he would push for passage of a parental involvement
measure this year.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago a similar measure sat in Wolens' committee so long
that anti-abortion activists accused the lawmaker of intentionally
undermining its chances. It died on the House floor on a
technicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairman Wolens has written a good bill,'' Delisi said of the
substitute legislation expected to face a committee vote Wednesday
or Thursday. She described a ``team approach'' to the new bill,
forged between Wolens and Republican lawmakers. Others said
anti-abortion activists played a large role as well, and abortion
rights supporters said they were kept informed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's language that has a lot of support,'' Delisi said, noting
some still have reservations. ``There may be a nip here or a tuck
there that needs to be done to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens' bill, like one that passed the Senate in March, says at
least one parent must be told when daughters 17 and under seek
abortions. None of the measures under serious consideration this
session would require parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   Compromises in the works include waiving a two-day waiting
period for pregnant teens who arrive for abortions along with a
parent who agrees to the procedure, Delisi confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   In return, anti-abortion activists made certain that only a
judge can act in the parent's behalf if a young woman is deemed
mature and fears physical and emotional reprisals at home.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Wolens bill would explicitly give girls the
right to choose a counselor, psychologist, psychiatrist, member of
the clergy and others to advocate in their behalf before a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters say the change might ease the trauma
of young women in crisis, but a leading player on the anti-abortion
side dismissed it as trivial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it's a token,'' said Bill Price, president of Texans
United for Life. ``The judge could have allowed that anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolens was unavailable for comment Tuesday afternoon, his office
said, because he had flown to Dallas to celebrate his young
daughter's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, negotiations as the bill underwent changes took
several tense turns, those familiar with the process said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we are not interfering,'' said Kae McLaughlin,
director of Texas Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
``Our friends know what's at stake here and are simply not willing
to negotiate young women's lives without giving them some
flexibility. They are working for any softening.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said his group still has problems with three sticking
points in the Wolens substitute. He questioned whether the bill's
definition of abortion is a ``landmine to make the bill
unconstitutional'' and said his side didn't like conceding on the
waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   Price also questioned whether criminal sanctions for doctors
violating the law could stick under Wolens' version.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said her side really wished it could have prevented
young pregnant women having to face judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor action is going to be really compelling on this,''
she said of what her opponents say might be a ``bloody'' battle.
``What we need is a deal that's solid enough that everyone agrees
on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
