<HEADLINE>
FARMING COMMUNITY OF BRIDGE CREEK AMONG HARDEST HIT BY TORNADO
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Subs for budgeted story TORNADO-CHICKASHA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ A 6-year-old boy walked aimlessly along a
road in the Southern Hills subdivision amid twisted mobile homes,
crumpled cars and appliances scattered randomly amid the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   When a massive tornado struck the community Monday evening, he
and his mother were running to what they believed would be the
safety of a nearby creek, the boy told officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he saw the wind pick her up and take her off,'' said
Bob Paul, a deputy with the Grady County sheriff's office. ``When
they found him he was wandering the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Added deputy Dick McCoy: ``He was looking for his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers and the National Guard continued to
look Tuesday afternoon for the boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   While the National Guard scoured the south side of Bridge Creek,
the 30-member volunteer firefighter department headed the search
teams in northern Bridge Creek. By afternoon, the search had
revealed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the Bridge Creek community, specifically the
Southern Hills addition, was among the hardest hit in Monday's
deadly tornadoes that ravaged Oklahoma and Kansas. Officials said
11 people were killed in the farming community of 6,000 about 30
miles southwest of Oklahoma City, most of them in Southern Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Lindsey was among the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   As the mile-wide tornado headed toward her mobile home, she had
four screaming children at her side and a pickup in her back
driveway that wouldn't run. Lindsey, who was celebrating her 31st
birthday on Monday, grabbed bedding and sofa cushions and ushered
the family into the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, the walls were gone and only a kitchen
island and a few pieces of furniture remained of her home. Lindsey
and her four children, age 11 months to 9 years, crouched in the
rubble unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we lived through it,'' an almost cheerful Lindsey said
Tuesday as she and her husband James picked through the debris that
had once been their home. ``What better birthday than that? Happy
Birthday to me. Best present I ever got.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her neighbors weren't so fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Grady County sheriff's officials tailing the huge tornado
arrived in Southern Hills to find bodies mingled with twisted
debris scattered across the hilly landscape. Among the dead were an
elderly woman and a 2-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Palmore, a volunteer firefighter, said his first discovery
was a family huddled together, the grandmother dying and a
3-week-old baby missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a body about 300 feet away in the trees,'' Palmore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar wrenching scenes would be repeated throughout the night,
he said, but the memories he clung to were of finding people alive.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to take ambulances into the rural area, rescuers used
pickup trucks to load the injured, and later the dead. The Bridge
Creek school's gymnasium was transformed into a triage area; the
school cafeteria was a temporary morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that were alive, they were just covered with mud.
You just had to look and then suddenly you'd see a pink tongue or
white eyes,'' Palmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of the Lord in my heart,'' he added. ``The Lord
was around here (Monday) night. I think he saved my family and a
bunch of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady County sheriff's deputy Al Hooper said he believed
meteorologists' warnings to residents about the tornado spared many
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have that certain amount of people that say, `Oh,
it's not going to get me. It's not going to hit,''' Hooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it did.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
