<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-SPRAWL-NYT &LR;      05-04 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PUSHES MASS TRANSIT IN AUTOMOBILE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also AUTO-SALES) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Pursuing the suburban voters who may prove crucial in
next year's presidential elections, as well as traditional
Democratic constituents in cities, Vice President Al Gore called in
a speech here Tuesday for reviving urban centers and reducing
traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the heart of the nation's auto industry, Gore called
not only for better schools and the redevelopment of abandoned
industrial sites, but also for shifting spending from highway
construction to mass transit systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to build subways instead of highways, you ought to
be able to make that choice,'' he told nearly 3,000 local
politicians and community advocates from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments provoked scowls and whispers among the handful
of auto executives in the audience, not one of whom was willing
afterward to criticize the Clinton administration. With nearly 5
million people, Detroit is the nation's largest metropolitan area
without a subway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the executives' skepticism, Gore replied, ``That's
not universally the case; they know that mass transit has a
legitimate and larger role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Spending on mass transit has barely kept pace with inflation in
the Clinton administration, rising to $5.39 billion this fiscal
year from $4.58 billion in the 1994 fiscal year, the first for
which the administration set the budget. By comparison, federal
highway appropriations have soared to $27.37 billion now from
$18.99 billion in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater blamed Republicans for
the disparity, saying that the administration had sought higher
mass transit spending only to see Congress devote more money to
highway construction instead.
</P>
<P>
   But even though many Republicans have been hostile to mass
transit programs, which tend to benefit big, heavily Democratic
cities, the federal budget is the result of a series of compromises
between Congress and the administration, and both sides share
responsibility for the final spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, Slater and a bevy of other senior federal
officials spoke on Monday and Tuesday at an administration
conference here on ways to improve the quality of life in
communities and protect the environment while still encouraging
economic growth. The Town Hall Meeting for a Sustainable America
was transmitted through satellite video links to 60,000 local
advocates and officials at more than 100 sites around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to critics who have suggested that issues like
traffic congestion and suburban sprawl are not big enough to
justify so much attention from a vice president and presidential
candidate, Gore said, ``I think it's good that people tune in to
the fact that this is a huge issue for Americans who live in the
suburbs, and at long last they're shedding this misconception that
it's somehow a small issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore met with top auto executives Tuesday afternoon as part of
an effort to persuade them to work with the government on ways to
improve the fuel efficiency of sport utility vehicles. The big,
off-road vehicles account for a fifth of all family vehicle sales.
They are allowed a much lower federal fuel-economy standard than
cars, a legacy of the days when sport utilities and other
pickup-truck-based vehicles were used mainly by small businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
