<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4267 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ESPN-LAWSUIT-HNS &LR;      05-04 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ESPN-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Major League Baseball said Tuesday it will terminate its
regular-season cablecast agreement with ESPN at the end of the 1999
season, and ESPN responded by filing a lawsuit against baseball in
a New York City federal court.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday's developments stem from a dispute that began when ESPN
signed an eight-year, $4.4 billion agreement in January 1998 to
broadcast NFL games on Sunday nights, creating a conflict with its
Sunday night baseball broadcasts. ESPN proposed moving its Sunday
night baseball games in September to ESPN2, but baseball objected
and the games eventually were returned to the control of local
teams.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, MLB president Paul Beeston accused ESPN of
``willful violation'' of its contract, which runs through 2002, and
added, ``We now must move forward and explore other options.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, baseball must deal with ESPN's lawsuit, which seeks
unspecified monetary damages, an injunction to keep the agreement
in force and a judgment granting it permission to move the three
September games _ including the Astros' Sept. 26 game at Milwaukee
_ to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Glover, ESPN's executive vice president for programming,
said Beeston notified ESPN on April 21 that baseball would
terminate its contract at the end of the season. ESPN, Glover said,
``was left with absolutely no choice but to go to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover said baseball proposed that ESPN settle the dispute by
signing a new, extended deal that, according to some estimates,
would have increased ESPN's rights payments to baseball by $350
million. After ESPN refused, baseball said it would revoke the
deal, and ESPN responded with Tuesday's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes no sense to us, and that is why we are really
disappointed and upset,'' Glover said. ``We have made numerous
proposals that were in the best interests of baseball to settle
this, and baseball's response has consistently been
disproportionate to the issue at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were left with no choice. We have to go to court and say to
the court, `Hey, we would like you to tell baseball that they have
to live up to the agreement they made with us.'''
</P>
<P>
   MLB spokesman Richard Levin would not comment specifically on
Glover's comments about baseball's request for more money but said,
``We would be very happy to live with the contract as it stands,
providing they (ESPN) didn't break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover said ESPN is allowed under its contract with baseball to
pre-empt up to 10 games a year. Baseball's approval is required, he
said, but it cannot be withheld for ``events of significant viewer
interest.'' For example, the network has sought and received
permission to pre-empt its June 2 baseball broadcast if the Stanley
Cup playoffs are in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have requested and been granted the right to pre-empt for
NASCAR, U.S. Open golf, Senior U.S. Open golf, the College World
Series, World Cup soccer and the NHL playoffs,'' Glover said. ``To
suggest that the NFL is of lesser interest is preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when baseball on ESPN went head-to-head with the NFL on
TNT, baseball's Sunday night average Nielsen was 1.7 to TNT's 9.1
for the NFL. ESPN's first three NFL games last September had an
average 7.3 Nielsen rating, said Glover, adding, ``The NFL
represents the gold standard of viewer interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin disagreed with Glover's description of the ``significant
viewer interest'' clause, adding: ``The clause doesn't say anything
about ratings. We feel our pennant-race games on Sunday nights are
events of significant viewer interest. It doesn't pertain to
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using their logic, if they signed a deal with the WWF (World
Wrestling Federation), does that mean they could bump baseball?''
</P>
<P>
   Glover said ESPN made repeated efforts to reach a settlement
with baseball, even though the network said it had the right to
move the September games from ESPN, which has 76.2 million
subscribers, to ESPN2, which has 64.5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The first offer, which was turned down by baseball last year,
was to allow over-the-air carriers in the participating teams'
markets to carry the games in addition to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Glover said ESPN then suggested the Sunday games, which are
traditionally the lowest-rated of the year, be returned to the
control of the local clubs. In return, he said, ESPN would trade
the Sunday games for ``meaningful'' Tuesday or Friday night
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   That was rejected, as were two other proposed compromises, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they've come back with is a proposal to charge
us a huge amount of money to renew and extend the deal we had, or
to cut back the deal we had and charge us a lot more money,''
Glover said.
</P>
<P>
   But Beeston said baseball's efforts to settle the dispute ``were
rejected out of hand'' by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's efforts to terminate the ESPN deal led to speculation
owners might be angling to cut a new deal with a different carrier,
such as Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to comment on the prospect of programming
that may or may not be available in the future,'' a Fox Sports Net
spokesman said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
