<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-WARNING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDAY NIGHT'S STORM HIT IN WORST PLACE AT WORST TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAN JARVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The devastating storm that struck Oklahoma City Monday night hit
in the worst place at the worst time: a heavily populated area
during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   But trained weather spotters and forecasters using sophisticated
storm-prediction equipment may have kept the death toll down by
giving tornado-leery residents enough time flee, experts said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the damage in Oklahoma City it looks like the
warning system did work well for the death toll to be so low, when
you see the amount of catastrophic damage there was,'' said Dave
Imy of the Storm Prediction Center in Norman, Okla., which issues
severe weather alerts to more than 100 National Weather Service
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment used in Oklahoma, called a warning decision
support system, played a large part in getting accurate information
out, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses artificial intelligence and Doppler radar
image-processing to automatically provide information about where
the tornado was, plus or minus two miles, said Mike Eilts,
assistant director of the National Severe Storms Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows where it was 10 minute ago, 15 minutes ago and where
it will be in the next 15 minutes,'' Eilts said. ``It shows where
it has been and where it's going to go in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   With a tornado watch issued by the weather service at 4:40 p.m.
for central and southwest Oklahoma, people were being alerted well
in advance of the storm moving into Oklahoma City, Imy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sirens were sounded, it was all over the media, you could see
off in the distance that the tornado was coming,'' he said. ``There
was plenty of advance watch and warning that resulted in the
possibility of a significant savings of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a 20-hour period, the weather service issued 174 warnings
covering dozens of Oklahoma counties. Oklahoma City television
stations went live as soon as the twisters formed and, using
helicopters, ground spotters and radar, followed the storm across
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma Weather Center, a confederation of federal, state
and University of Oklahoma organizations, is recognized for its
collective expertise in severe weather research. It is in Oklahoma
because the area is known as Tornado Alley.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma also has the Mesonet, a system of weather monitors in
every county that provides detailed real-time readings, said Gary
Sickler, a Texas A&AMP;M meteorology professor who wants Texas to have
the same system with sites in every county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mesonet is wonderful,'' he said. ``But with a tornado like the
one in Oklahoma there is no place to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the most sophisticated technology the local national
weather offices depend on trained storm spotters to relay and
report severe weather and forecasters who can analyze information,
Imy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is important but it comes down to a forecaster
being able to diagnose the atmosphere and the knowledge to
determine when a storm is becoming severe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the best warning system in the world was in operation,
the storm's timing could not have been worse, experts said. The
tornado hit a populated area during the end of rush hour and stayed
30 minutes to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings gave residents 20 to 25 minutes of lead time, but
there were still fatalities because the tornado was extreme and it
went over a highly populated area, Eilts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen 30 to 40 tornadoes over my lifetime and this was
definitely the strongest,'' he said. ``This was a very intense
tornado that tracked over the worst possible place.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an area where people grow up practicing tornado drills
and are well prepared for such emergencies. Even though they
responded to the warnings, the storm was so powerful that there was
no good place to hide, Imy said. It appears this was an F4 (on the
Fujita Scale) or stronger, with winds above 200 mph, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people were in a safe place,'' he said. ``If it
had been a weaker tornado their houses would not have been
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though forecasters were tracking the storm from early in
the day, it was difficult to predict that the tornado would become
so strong and head over a heavily populated area, said
meteorologist Daphne Zaras of the National Severe Storm Laboratory
in Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was a good probability for tornadoes but nobody
expects an event this extreme,'' Zaras said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
