<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-WEATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS PUZZLED AS TO WHY SO MANY TWISTERS HIT OKLAHOMA, KANSAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Tornado-deaths, Tornado-scene, Tornado-witnesses
and Tornado-Kansas) 
 
By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The devastation inflicted by the tornadoes that slammed Oklahoma
and Kansas was the product of textbook weather conditions and
unlucky geography, say meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   But the experts say it is still a mystery as to what caused so
many tornadoes and why a few of them were of such width and
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Monday's conditions made everyone confident
tornadoes were coming,'' said Joshua Wurman, a University of
Oklahoma professor of meteorology and storm researcher. ``But there
was also no great reason to think it would be as bad as things
turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wurman emphasized that was partly because many of Monday's
tornadoes hit heavily populated areas. Saying it was fortunate the
death toll wasn't even higher, Wurman noted similarly powerful
tornadoes form fairly often but don't inflict so much damage
because they travel in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   At least 43 people were reported dead in Monday's twisters.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said they only have preliminary data about
Monday's tornado activity, but say it appears to be either an F-4
or F-5 on the Fujita scale. The activity also appears to have
covered 100 times more ground than most strong tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions that made Oklahoma and Kansas so ripe for
Monday's tornadoes are the exact ones that have made the area known
as Tornado Alley. Starting in the Texas Panhandle and extending
into Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, Missouri and a few other states,
that section of the country is more conducive to tornadoes than
anywhere in the world, according to local meteorologists. It is
busiest from May to June during the warmest part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions involve strong, moist, southeasterly winds
blowing in at a low altitude from the Gulf of Mexico and cool, dry,
westerly winds coming in from the Rocky Mountains at an altitude of
10,000 to 20,000 feet. Such were the conditions Monday in Oklahoma
and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   When the southeasterly and westerly winds meet, the moist air
below and the dry air above create an instability that kick-starts
the storm. Meanwhile, the moisture provides the energy that drives
vertical winds inside the tornado; and the westerly wind gives it
its rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The high winds in a tornado are due to an extreme low pressure
that forms at the center of the spinning column of air. Air
converging toward the low pressure speeds up faster and faster as
it gets closer to the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analogy is the ice skater bringing in his or her arms to
make them faster,'' says Arthur Few, a Rice University professor of
space physics and environmental science. ``He or she starts with a
large, slow rotation and brings it in to become faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the conditions caused the National Weather Service to
issue high-risk forecasts Monday afternoon, Wurman said he
nevertheless didn't think the tornado activity would be so bad
because ``ideal conditions rarely stay ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wurman also noted that a thick deck of cirrus clouds blocking
the sun Monday suggested it might not warm upper winds enough for
such strong tornado activity.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous meteorologists said they look forward to analyzing data
from the tornadoes. Ernst Kiesling, a Texas Tech professor of civil
engineering in Lubbock, said the reported one-mile width of one
tornado is in ``the upper limit of what we're accustomed to
seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wurman said he is still particularly puzzled as to why there
were so many tornadoes. &UR;  &LR; He said his team counted at least two
dozen when they were in the field Monday; other reports put the
total at three dozen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
