<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIAL GROUP OF REFUGEES TO ARRIVE IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first of up to 20,000 refugees from Kosovo to be received in
the United States are scheduled to arrive at 5 p.m. Wednesday at
Fort Dix, N.J. The White House press office said Hilary Rodham
Clinton will welcome them to the country.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 to 400 people, all from camps in Macedonia, will be in
the group. A second group of the same size is due Friday. Two more
groups are scheduled to arrive next week. All the refugees are
expected to remain at Fort Dix, a 31,000-acre military station 17
miles southeast of Trenton, for two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While there, they will be interviewed by immigration officials
and receive physical checkups. Also during that period, they will
be assigned housing, and arrangements for their transportation to
housing sites will be made.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kharfen of the US Department of Health and Human
Services, which along with the State Department is running the
refugee program as Operation Open Door, said priority is being
given to families with senior citizens or young children _ who are
particularly vulnerable to deteriorating health conditions in the
Macedonian camps _ and only those who volunteer are being
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   He said a full array of of health services, counseling, and
clothing would be made available at Fort Dix.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees will be housed in military barracks, but efforts
will be made to keep families together, said a military
spokeswoman. Dayrooms have been prepared with toys, rockers, dolls,
and games for children.
</P>
<P>
   The fort can accommodate 3,000 refugees at a time. In addition
to those coming to Fort Dix, there will be periodic flights of
persons who have been pre-screened in the Balkans and have sponsors
in the United States to receive them. The first of these is
scheduled to arrive Saturday night at New York's JFK airport, and
will go directly from the airport to their hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Regional offices of the United States Catholic Conference are
still organizing housing sites for the refugees who will be
processed at Dix, and numbers to be sheltered in various regions of
the contry have not yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Doolin, director of Catholic Charities of Greater Boston,
said very few of the ethnic Albanians being evacuated from the
Balkans are requesting reunification with relatives in the United
States. Only New York surpasses Boston and Worcester in numbers of
residents of Albanian extraction.
</P>
<P>
   Doolin said emphasis is being put on finding appropriate
group-living situations. He said a donor has offered a large bus on
which representatives of Governor Paul Cellucci and Mayor Thomas M.
Menino will travel to New Jersey when the first group is sent to
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge will be helping Muslims, because we don't have
the same (highly developed) network with them'' as with other
communities, Doolin said. ``We are still trying to reach out to the
Muslim community.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that, while media reports have concentrated on
farmers and other rural people who have fled Kosovo, the refugees
include large numbers of lawyers, accountants, and other urban
professionals. Because many of the urban centers of Kosovo have now
been laid waste, a high percentage of these people may remain
outside the disputed Serbian province for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Kharfen said government officials still expect that ``most of
these families will want to return when it is safe, but as legal
residents of the United States, they will be able to stay if they
choose to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday, about 24,500 refugees had been evacuated to
countries outside the Balkans. By far the greatest number to
Germany, which has taken in 9,974. Turkey was second with 3,685.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 countries have offered to shelter refugees
temporarily: 20,000 each in Turkey and the United States, 10,000
each in Germany, Finland and Italy. Virtually every European nation
has offered to take a few thousand, and, in all, temporary shelter
has been pledged for up to 111,445 Kosovars, according to the US
Agency for International Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
