<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: BIRDS HUMILIATED BY CUBANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CUBA-DEFECT, moved in `w' category) 
(bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ At some early-morning hour Tuesday, Brady Anderson
was putting toothpaste on his clubhouse toothbrush and said, ``It
didn't look that good, did it?'' No, he was told. ``I thought that,
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That succinctly, the Baltimore center fielder offered his candid
assessment of the debacle that had just occurred, a humiliating
12-6 loss to the Cubans that epitomized the Orioles' play one month
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   When they came back to Camden Yards to play the Chicago White
Sox on Tuesday night, Ray Miller was still their manager and Frank
Wren the general manager, but their life expectancy in their jobs
was about as secure as a window washer working on the 82nd floor
without a scaffold.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson didn't think team owner Peter Angelos would let the
loss to Cuba influence his thinking, saying Angelos knew his
fervent desire to play the games carried with it no guarantee of
victory. But how long can he tolerate that kind of play from a team
he is paying $78.5 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help anything,'' B.J. Surhoff, the team's veteran
left fielder, said of the display Monday night. ``I don't think it
helps the situation at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I don't care if you spend $200 million if you
don't make good evaluations. Just because you pay a guy a lot of
money doesn't mean you made a great evaluation. You still have to
pick good players and good players have to play well. Right now we
have not played well as a team. I single out nobody but I exclude
nobody either, including myself. Our team has played poorly. We
have not played baseball well enough to win on a consistent level
in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it's only a month, this is the second successive season
that the Orioles are playing poorly, and last year they had the
major leagues' largest payroll. With the team they put together
this season, the Orioles resemble the Yankees of the 1980s, who
were built on money and poor personnel judgments.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested to Surhoff that the Orioles appeared to be an
ill- conceived team, constructed in a scattershot manner in a
desperate attempt to fill holes created by free- agent defections.
``I don't know if that's a fair assessment,'' he said, ``because I
don't know what went into the process of picking the players they
picked.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant player was Albert Belle, at $13 million a
year no less. Belle started the season hitting well, but in the 15
games before Tuesday night he had 8 hits in 46 at-bats (.174) and
had driven in only 4 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to put the burden on him,'' Surhoff said, ``but
when he gets hot, hopefully the rest of us go with him. He's a guy
who can carry a team through tough periods. In the meantime the
rest of us have to find a way to pick him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Belle played lethargically against the Cubans, as if he didn't
want to be there. Actually, none of the players did because they
preferred the day off that Monday otherwise would have been. But
Belle reacted worse than most, not running hard on a grounder on
which he could have been safe because the throw pulled the first
baseman off the base and striking out twice (swinging at none of
the 11 pitches he saw) for a total of four strikeouts in eight
at-bats against Cuba's pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos couldn't be blamed for thinking he deserved more for his
money and that of the 47,940 fans who attended the game. But the
Orioles knew the character of the player when they signed him. All
they wanted was his 50 home runs and 150 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   They still might get them, but they also might not help a team
that was nine and a half games behind the Yankees in the first
month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to play better,'' Surhoff said. ``Guys
in this room are capable of playing better. If you look around the
room, everybody's got a track record and most of the guys have very
good track records. You definitely would not anticipate them
playing as poorly as we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles played so poorly against the Cubans that until a
three-hit, three-run flurry in the ninth inning against Norge Vera,
who had held them hitless for seven innings of relief, the Cubans
had outhit them 18 to 3. Seven of the hits were for extra-bases,
not bad for a team that supposedly had no power.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban players clearly relished their dominance over the
Orioles. In the second inning, shortstop Danel Castro slid into
third with the first of his two triples and four hits, instantly
popped up and exhorted the Cuban delegation behind the third- base
dugout to cheer, not that they needed an invitation. In the ninth,
designated hitter Andy Morales slugged a three-run home run and did
a dance of ecstasy as he flew around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The most demonstrative member of the Cuban contingent, though,
was second-base umpire Cesar Valdez, who tackled, body-slammed and
pummeled a protester fan who ran onto the field carrying a small
sign that said, ``Freedom _ strike out against Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff jumped into the fray and pulled Valdez away from the
protester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was just going to hold him for the security
people,'' Surhoff said. ``Next thing you know he was throwing
haymakers. He wanted to go back and hit the guy some more. I tried
not to let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpire explained later that he felt the fan's action was a
lack of respect and believed he handled the situation the way it
should have been handled. Omar Linares, the great Cuban third
baseman, also called it a lack of respect and said, ``The ones who
should worry about this are the organizers, our hosts.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now the Orioles have much more to worry about than the
behavior of some anti-Castro fan.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
