<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-IRAQ-NYT &LR;      05-04 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
  
 U.S. QUIETLY iNTENSIFIES ATTACKS ON IRAQ, DESTROYING RADAR SITES  
(Eds.: This story, eliminated earlier, is now restored) 
(bl) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even with Pentagon attention riveted on Yugoslavia,
the United States has quietly stepped up what amounts to a
low-level conflict with Iraq, with almost daily skirmishes that
have resulted in destroying Iraqi radar sites and reports of the
deaths of dozens of Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon accused Iraqi President Saddam Hussein this week of
placing air-defense missiles and radar sites in civilian
neighborhoods. By endangering civilians, the tactic could be seen
as an attempt to hinder U.S. attacks on those sites. The move would
also make it easier for the Iraqis to hide their weapons and have a
clear shot at U.S. warplanes that are patrolling northern and
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration official said they feared that Saddam
might be planning a major confrontation with the United States in
the belief that the U.S. military is stretched thin and distracted
as a result of the Balkan conflict. Reports in the Middle East last
week quoted the Iraqi leader as predicting a ``crucial'' showdown
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strains on U.S. forces, U.S. officials said, the
United States can wage war against both Yugoslavia and Iraq, and
the number of U.S. planes on patrols over Iraq is nearly at full
strength. On Monday, U.S. jet fighters launched missiles against an
air-defense site in a civilian area of northern Iraq, after the
pilots had reported that they had come under fire by surface-to-air
missiles. Iraq said two civilians were killed and 12 were wounded
in the raids near Mosul, 220 miles north of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Other accounts of civilian deaths in Iraq have also circulated.
The Iraqi armed forces reported that a family of seven was killed
Friday 25 miles north of Mosul in a separate attack on nearby
defense sites.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of the casualties could not be independently
confirmed, and Clinton administration officials said any civilian
deaths or injuries were Saddam's responsibility, not the United
States'.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his tactics,'' said Defense Department spokesman
Kenneth Bacon, ``may now be to place his air-defense systems in
civilian neighborhoods, thinking that he can challenge us with
impunity, because he's done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that in Monday's attack, U.S. pilots fired two
missiles against air-defense sites in northern Iraq but called off
additional attacks after having determined that at least one radar
installation was in a civilian neighborhood. The missiles were
fired ``in self-defense,'' Bacon said, adding, ``I don't think we
know at this stage what it hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of confrontations began in December, when the
United States and Britain unleashed an intensive four-day aerial
bombardment in response to Iraq's repeated refusal to cooperate
with United Nations weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since, Iraq has fired scores of missiles at U.S.
and British planes and sent up planes to confront them, apparently
hoping to lure allied pilots within range of missile batteries.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening weeks of the air campaign against Yugoslavia,
Iraqi air-defense forces were unusually quiet. But in late April,
the Iraqis resumed their almost daily provocations of Western
pilots in the no-flight zones, which were imposed in response to
the persecution of minority groups in northern and southern Iraq
after the Persian Gulf war in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pattern appears to be that he challenges for a while,''
Bacon said. ``We whack him day after day in response to his
challenges, and then he pulls back and goes down for a period and
does nothing. And then he comes back up and presents a new series
of challenges, sometimes with slightly different tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   After the intense raids in December, Clinton gave U.S. pilots
wider authority to retaliate when threatened, allowing them to
strike at any defense system, not just those that actually aimed at
U.S. aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   A result has been the destruction of a large number of
antiaircraft batteries and surface-to-air missile sites throughout
the country. By one intelligence estimate, Iraq has lost nearly 20
percent of its air-defense weapons since December.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis have remained defiant. Last week, Vice President
Yassin Ramadan was quoted as saying that he expected the United
States to launch a surprise attack on Iraq and that Washington
would ``pay a dear price if it does so, because Iraq is fully alert
to confront such aggression.'' Later reports in Arab newspapers
said Saddam had sent a letter to his army commanders to notify them
that ``the showdown with the United States is not far away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
