<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WANG-GETRONICS-BOS &LR;      05-04 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANG-GETRONICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETRONICS TO BUY WANG GLOBAL IN $2 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wang Global, the Massachusetts technology pioneer that has
symbolized the boom and bust of the state's high-tech economy,
agreed to be purchased by a large European firm for about $2
billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Getronics NV of the Netherlands, an information services
company, will acquire Wang, a one-time titan in minicomputers that
reinvented itself as a computer services firm after a plunge into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wang is a major provider of network data services in
North America, Europe and Asia, with expected 1999 revenues of $3.5
billion. Getronics is in the same line of work, but concentrated in
northern Europe. The company sees Wang as a quick way to become a
worldwide power in the business of managing other companies'
computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't for sale,'' said Wang chief executive officer Joe
Tucci, who rebuilt the Billerica, Mass. company after it emerged
from bankruptcy in 1993. ``We weren't shopping ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But a number of firms had expressed interest in a deal, said
Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when other high-tech stocks have been soaring, Wang's
share price has hovered around $20 _ well below the $29.25 offer
from Getronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trading at 20, 21, 22, for the past year,'' said
Tucci. ``And somebody came in and gave us, cash, a 39 percent
premium over where we've been trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang shares Tuesday rose 3 1/8, ending at 28 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci said Wang has no choice but to get bigger. It competes in
a $236 billion-a-year computer services market worldwide against
the largest computer firms _ IBM Corp., Compaq Computer Corp.,
Hewlett-Packard Co. and Electronic Data Services Corp., to name a
few. ``You've got to be big,'' said Tucci. ``Size counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci had grown Wang from 6,000 workers in 1993 to 20,000 today,
and spent $390 million last year to buy the European computer
services business of Italy's Olivetti SpA, but he knew this
wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, IBM alone derives about $32 billion in 1998 from
computer services, according to Andrew Efstathiou, senior analyst
at Boston's Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   The deal marks the end of nearly a half century of independence
for the company once known as Wang Laboratories Inc. The company
was founded in 1951 by Chinese immigrant An Wang, who came to the
United States to earn a Ph.D at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Born as a maker of cutting-edge computer gear, the company's
word-processing machines and minicomputers made it a giant during
the 1980s, with employment peaking at 30,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, along with Digital Equipment Corp. and Data General
Corp., came to symbolize the ``Massachusetts Miracle,'' an era of
robust economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But founder Wang's refusal to embrace microcomputers like the
IBM Personal Computer led the firm to disaster and
near-destruction. The company filed for bankruptcy in 1992, marking
a downturn in fortunes that swept up some of Massachusetts other
leading minicomputer makers. An Wang died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   When it emerged from bankruptcy in 1993, Wang was committed to
an entirely new business as a provider of computer services. Last
year's Olivetti deal instantly made Wang a major player in Europe,
generating over half its revenues there. Even so, Richard Brewer,
network services analyst for International Data Corp. in
Framingham, Mass., said that many potential European customers have
avoided Wang, dismissing it as ``a company only known for going
bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been losing money over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Wang reported a net loss of $57.7 million on revenue of
$789 million for the quarter ending March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci said the new Getronics-Wang company will have instant
market credibility, largely because of its size _ a market
capitalization of about $5 billion. Tucci said that this will make
it much easier for the new company to raise capital in the world's
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci himself will stay on during an open-ended transition
period in the office of the chairman. He expects no job losses
under Wang's new owners. But he does suspect that the famous Wang
name will soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that officially yet,'' said Tucci, ``but I'm a
realist. They pay $2 billion, they get to call it what they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
