<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SUGAR LIPS RIPS NRA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ I was hiding from Lamar.
</P>
<P>
   An aide for the perpetual presidential candidate was imploring
journalists to come up to his Holiday Inn suite and submit to
``exclusive'' interviews with Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   I crouched behind a door, but the aide found me and begged me to
hear the candidate's revised thoughts on education reform.
</P>
<P>
   I ran away.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Germond, the roly-poly veteran political columnist for The
Baltimore Sun, has a rule that he will not travel more than half an
hour to cover a candidate who is not in the top three. I have a
rule that I won't get in an elevator for a candidate who, after six
years of campaigning full time, is stuck at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only question I had for Alexander, at this first New
Hampshire pageant of GOP losers, was why he had dropped the
exclamation point from his bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   And the only question I had for John Kasich was why he had
appropriated the exclamation point (``Get involved!'') for his
banners.
</P>
<P>
   Can't the Republican Party afford two exclamation points?!
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio congressman is already too bouncy sans punctuation. He
makes Dan Quayle seem mature. On the day Bob Dole resigned from the
Senate, I actually saw Kasich weeping into his Tweetie Bird tie.
</P>
<P>
   The press pack tried to fill the void created by the absence of
W. _ who is still relying on Austin Power _ by mulling the trivial.
We analyzed Steve Forbes' beauty makeover (acid peels  &UR; and &LR;  hair
straightening?). We marveled at the sparrow-like Gary Bauer
comparing himself to the eagle-like Ronald Reagan. We admired the
Howard Beale style of the mad and angry Alan Keyes, who ends his
screeds by stalking off the stage. We pondered the enduring
question about Dan Quayle:  &UR; Why? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, we didn't care about the boys. We wanted the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole got off to her usual Little Miss Perfect start.
When all the candidates lined up for a group photo, she pounced on
her mark with a head-of-her-Harvard-law-school-class smile, leaving
the boys to fumble in her coiffed wake.
</P>
<P>
   We plotted how to trap Liddy into an ad lib. I considered faking
a nosebleed, to see if the former head of the Red Cross really knew
first aid.
</P>
<P>
   We trailed her to a stilted visit with Pembroke High School
students. ``Thank  &UR; ye-e-e-w-w-w, &LR; '' she said. ``Thanks for all your
good input.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, clad in a violet suit, black high heels and big gold
earrings, knew what we were after. She decided to outfox us by
proving she could get loosey-goosey. She added an ``impromptu''
stop at Dairy Queen, where she let fly and ordered a cup of vanilla
ice cream with hot fudge sauce and ``a little whipped cream and
lots of nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   She sat in a booth and stared down at the sundae, teetering at
the precipice of improvisation, perhaps recalling Jackie O's
dictum: Never chew in camera range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all are just waiting for this,'' she smilingly accused the
photographers. ``They can't wait. Here you go. Are  &UR; ye-e-e-e-w &LR; 
ready?''
</P>
<P>
   As she took dainty bites, a reporter asked her position on Dairy
Queen vs. Tastee Freeze. ``Anything sweet,'' replied the woman
whose sweet-talking Washington ways earned her the nickname ``Sugar
Lips.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own controlled way, Mrs. Dole made a bold move at the GOP
dinner in the ``Live Free or Die'' state. She called for stiffer
regulation of guns, observing, ``I don't think you need an AK-47 to
defend your family.'' Incredibly, one man booed her when she urged
gun safety locks to protect children.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Littleton, when other Republicans have taken
cheap shots at Hollywood, Mrs. Dole was the only one in this
mediocre mob who had the courage to stand up to the NRA, saying
special interests should not dictate policy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can be sure when Mrs. Dole's pollster, Linda
DiVall, publicly praised her guts, that the candidate's stand was
also smart politics. She is pitching her ``Let's make history''
candidacy to middle-of-the-road soccer moms who are turned off by
Charlton Heston's assertion that ``we cannot let tragedy lay waste
to the most rare and hard-won human right in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's position may have been calculated, but it was also
correct. And this bite wasn't dainty.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
