<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TRAUMA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TWISTERS HIT, INJURIES RUN TO EXTREMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Tornado-deaths, Tornado-scene, Tornado-witnesses,
Tornado-Kansas and Tornado-weather.) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is very little in between when it comes to tornado
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Most victims of a twister are either killed outright or left
with minor cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Tornado casualties are different from what emergency medical
experts normally see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is, when you get there, you expect to be able
to help people,'' said John Sneed, director of Williamson County
Emergency Medical Service which responded when a tornado killed 27
in Jarrell, Texas, on May 27, 1997. ``We only had 11 patients. We
dealt with them quickly. Then you get into the search, rescue and
recovery mode ... and you keep finding fatalities.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wichita, Kan., it was a similar story of contrasts at Via
Christi St. Francis Hospital, where 100 victims from nearby
Hayesville were taken for treatment after Monday night's storm.
</P>
<P>
   Trauma director Dr. Steve Smith said he saw cuts and abrasions
on people who had ``bounced around'' inside a trailer, and he
treated people with broken arms, legs and pelvises.
</P>
<P>
   Some people had limbs that had been crushed under debris. One
woman had a ``penetrating chest wound'' caused by a flying object.
An infant who was sucked out of a mobile home died of massive head
injuries shortly after admission.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the rest had the same kind of injuries people might have
from a skateboarding accident,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado's seemingly fickle pattern of death and destruction
can be attributed to the immense power packed into a relatively
small area, said Jon Zeitler, senior forecaster for the National
Weather Service in League City, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The intense force created by high winds blowing in a tight
spiral destroys everything in its path. But that path is short and
narrow compared to that of a hurricane, Zeitler said.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane's strongest winds may blow several hours; most
tornadoes touch ground only for a few minutes. A hurricane can be
200 to 500 miles wide; a tornado may be only 75 yards to a mile
wide.
</P>
<P>
   That's why one house may be destroyed while another across the
street is left standing, Zeitler said. Similarly, one family may be
wiped out and another left intact.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Coscia, a trauma services director in Austin, Texas,
spent 25 years as a surgeon in Springfield, Mo. _ located in the
so-called Tornado Alley that includes the Texas Panhandle,
Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, Missouri and a few others states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that come in make it. The majority will go home, by
far,'' he said. ``The gamut of injuries is from one extreme to
another.''
</P>
<P>
   He said flying objects cause the most damage. Shattered glass
lacerates, other objects cause wounds similar to gunshot wounds or
stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Craig Key, associate medical director of Houston Fire
Department EMS, compares the impact on humans to being close to a
large explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a lot of force,'' he said. ``Our bodies
are relatively frail. When they come in contact with those forces,
there's really no contest.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
