<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-840&AMP;A     05-04 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE BOMBING WILL WORK, ALLIES STILL PLAN FOR WINTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ With no consensus on ground troops for
Kosovo and no sign that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
is wavering, allied leaders are beginning to face the prospect of
housing half a million refugees through the bitter Balkan winter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with that forbidding prospect, NATO's top military and
civilian officials continue to assert that the bombing of
Yugoslavia will eventually force Milosevic to concede defeat and
accept a settlement in Kosovo. What they cannot say is when.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making progress,'' Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany,
NATO's senior military officer, said on Tuesday. ``We are nibbling
away night by night and day by day at some of his military
capabilities. Why should we change?''
</P>
<P>
   But the allies are beginning to have doubts that Milosevic will
be brought to heel in time to get the masses of Kosovar refugees
home before subfreezing temperatures return to the Balkans in
October.
</P>
<P>
   With 136,000 Albanians now in camps in Macedonia and 400,000
huddled in tents in Albania, one allied foreign minister, Knut
Vollebaek of Norway, told editors of The New York Times on Tuesday,
``Realistically, we have to be prepared for keeping the refugees in
for at least the start of the winter.'' Vollebaek is also chairman
in office of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, which would have a role in implementing a settlement in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official also said on Tuesday that Sadaka
Ogata, the United Nations high commissioner for refugees, had been
advised to start thinking about making the camps habitable in
winter.
</P>
<P>
   This is contingency planning now, the American said, but it
could become necessary if the bombing fails to convince Milosevic
to give up. The allies have been unable so far to bring themselves
to accept any other strategy to achieve victory, which is probably
the only way refugees outside the country and the 650,000 people
displaced inside Kosovo will ever be able to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that military experience so far has suggested that
an air campaign so far in history never won a war, that's true,''
Naumann said on Tuesday at a news conference marking his retirement
after three years as chairman of NATO's military committee, which
advises the alliance's civilian authorities here. ``But we see a
real chance that we can make it, and for that reason I think there
is no necessity at this point in time to change strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance of 19 nations could not decide to invade Kosovo
without a consensus of all of them, he said, ``and that is
something which you can't get on this critical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a consensus existed, one official said, it would take
until September for the allies to plan and assemble a ground force
to fight its way in, and refugees could not follow for many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some other officials say that it may not take so long, that it
may be possible to get ground troops into Kosovo by August, which
might make it possible to get the refugees back before winter if
the planning and deployment began at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   But so far NATO has given itself no choice but to continue
intensifying the bombing in hopes that it will eventually convince
Milosevic to withdraw the 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers and police
officers from Kosovo and accept an international peacekeeping force
to protect the returning refugees and allow reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing strategy, Naumann said, is based more on political
than military logic and, after months of ultimatums and
negotiations, the allies have lost an advantages that every
military strategist sees as essential: surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Military logic, as most officers understand it, would have
dictated a strategy that led to a clear military end: an imposed
settlement after an invasion and occupation of Kosovo, for example,
or conquest of Yugoslavia and unconditional surrender by Milosevic
from a bunker in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies have never really considered total war against
Yugoslavia, leaving only the hope that continued bombing and
diplomacy will convince Milosevic to accept a settlement rather
than take his country down with him.
</P>
<P>
   The intensified bombing will make life so miserable for
Milosevic and his regime, Naumann said on Tuesday, that eventually
the authorities in Belgrade will see the light. But how long would
that take?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see how they will feel after a few more weeks and
months or what have you of continuously pounding them into
pieces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in comments in Washington after the NATO summit meeting last
month, Naumann acknowledged, ``We may have one flaw in our
thinking, and this flaw may be that we believe that no responsible
man who is at the helm of a country like Yugoslavia can wish to run
the risk that his entire country will be bombed into rubble before
he gives up and complies with the demands of the international
community,''
</P>
<P>
   But he added then that it had been a ``fair assumption'' to
assume that Milosevic would not try to beat unbeatable odds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Naumann, Gen. Wesley Clark, the allied commander in charge
of the bombing, knows Milosevic well from many previous encounters,
the last of them at the beginning of this year when the two
generals went to Belgrade to warn the Yugoslav leader what lay in
store for him unless he agreed to peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think back to my experience with President Milosevic in late
January, and all the subsequent events,'' Clark recalled here last
week. ``I suppose that he may have thought that NATO really
wouldn't launch the air strikes, but he was wrong. He may have
believed they wouldn't last after they were started. Wrong. He may
have thought that some countries would be afraid of his bluster and
intimidation, they would withdraw the use of their bases or buckle
under his intimidation. He was wrong. He thought that other
countries might rush to his aid. Wrong again.''
</P>
<P>
   Running through a litany of the Yugoslav leader's
miscalculations, Clark sounded almost as if he were trying to
convince himself that NATO's political assumptions would finally
turn out to be correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning, Milosevic is losing, and he knows it,'' he
said. ``He should face up to this, and he should face up to it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Naumann echoed that view on Tuesday. ``I believe that the air
campaign is properly working, but you should also take into account
that we have conditions which we have to follow which are degrading
to some extent the impact of the air campaign,'' he added, ``most
notably the condition that we have to avoid collateral damage.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies avoid ``civilian damage'' _ civilian casualties or
damage to civilian property _ because they fear that public opinion
would turn against the war if such damage were extensive.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen thousand bombs and missiles have been dropped so far,
Naumann said, and the fact that by NATO's count only six have gone
astray _ even though some killed scores of civilians _ is a marvel
of modern warfare, he added. Still, ``I regard every single
civilian killed as being one too much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Milosevic's forces are still killing Albanian
civilians in Kosovo. ``Our military intervention can and has slowed
down the instruments President Milosevic uses for ethnic
cleansing,'' the general said. ``We cannot stop such a thing
entirely from the air. But we certainly can succeed in degrading
his capability to conduct operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there can be no doubt that we have got to succeed,
since anything short of that would mean risks for the stability of
Europe.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
