<HEADER>
A4290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-720&AMP;ADD     05-04 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF BLAME, NO CONSENSUS AT SENATE HEARING ON SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., openly rued the
estrangement of too many parents from their children's lives. Sen.
Richard Bryan, D-Nev., decried the dearth of adequate counseling in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, lamented the absence of prayer in
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the only time we tolerate prayer in school these
days,'' Hatch said, ``is when people come to on-school memorials in
the wake of tragedies.''
</P>
<P>
   The three senators were all speaking at a Senate hearing Tuesday
into the entertainment industry's marketing of violent fantasies to
children.
</P>
<P>
   But their remarks, which strayed well beyond those parameters,
underscored the multitude of directions in which lawmakers are
looking for solutions to the deadly school shootings in Littleton,
Colo., and their lack of consensus about what Congress can and
should do.
</P>
<P>
   In the two weeks since the 15 deaths at Columbine High School,
Republicans have focused largely on broad cultural realities that
promote, or fail to stem, violence among children. Democrats, too,
have emphasized that an array of factors give rise to such
behavior, but many Democrats have also called for more stringent
gun control measures, which many Republicans oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said Tuesday
that Democrats would try to bring to the floor several modest gun
control proposals when the Senate begins consideration of broad
juvenile justice legislation early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi has indicated a
willingness to allow debate on such measures. But Lott, who has
spoken at conventions of the National Rifle Association, made clear
Tuesday that he is unlikely to support anything beyond minor
tinkering in gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think additional gun control measures are probably not
needed,'' Lott said. Referring to the shootings in Littleton, he
added, ``The press and others may want this to turn into gun
control. That's not what this is about. That may be a small part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing approaching unanimity in either party about gun
control. Just as a number of moderate Republicans have indicated
support for more regulations, a number of Democrats have played
down the importance of gun control, partly reflecting a belief that
their advocacy of the issue was one reason they lost control of the
House in the 1994 elections. The National Rifle Association threw
its efforts into singling out certain Democrats for defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But several Democrats have sought to train the spotlight of
Littleton on gun control. Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., held an
unofficial hearing of Democrats on the House Government Reform
Committee this week to draw attention to a specific military sniper
rifle, able to shoot targets four miles away, that is easier to
obtain than a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., said that two days after the
shooting, she placed a telephone call to House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., urging him to support a bill she has introduced
that would, among other regulations, require firearms manufacturers
to make weapons more child-resistant and make it harder for young
adults to purchase weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. McCarthy said on Monday that she had not heard back from
Hastert. Speaking of Republican leaders, she said, ``They still
don't want to touch this issue with a 10-foot pole.''
</P>
<P>
   John P. Feehery, a spokesman for Hastert, said that the speaker
was still reviewing her proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats at Tuesday's Senate hearing
acknowledged that they have limited Constitutional authority to
regulate artistic expression, no matter how violent, in movies,
music and video games.
</P>
<P>
   They may have limited political appetites, too; just as money
from the National Rifle Association lines the pockets of
Republicans, money from the entertainment industry lines the
pockets of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's political action committee donated $1.35 million to
Republican congressional candidates in the 1998 election cycle and
$283,000 to Democratic congressional candidates, according to the
Center for Responsive Politics, a non-partisan research group. PACs
and individuals affiliated with the movie and music industries,
meanwhile, poured $4.4 million into Democratic campaigns and
contributed $2.8 million to Republican candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many Republicans, along with some Democrats, have exhibited a
legislative hesitancy in the aftermath of Littleton and a
preference, instead, for talk.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and Lott announced the creation of what they called a
nonpartisan National Conference on Youth and Culture that would
bring students, teachers, religious leaders and others together for
periodic discussions around the country.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, said Monday that his committee would hold hearings next
week to talk about the causes of juvenile violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would caution everyone, however, that disenchantment among
America's youth defies simple and politically expedient
explanations, nor should we expect a rapid consensus on new
legislation,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, lawmakers have promoted a panoply of measures from
better school counseling to the installation in schools of
sophisticated security gadgetry.
</P>
<P>
   As senators at Tuesday's hearing listened to Charles J. Chaput,
the Roman Catholic archbishop of Denver, talk about the power of
art to shape the soul and questioned Jack Valenti, president of the
Motion Picture Association of America, about Hollywood's bloodier
products, they frequently called for the industry to regulate
itself, essentially trying to shame it into restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., said that seven industry executives
had declined to come to the hearing to defend the language and
imagery in their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are words they wouldn't use at their country clubs,''
Brownback said, ``but they'll sell them to our children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
