<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS PREPARING FOR DRAMA CLASS WHEN TORNADO HITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ High school senior Crystal Cantrell and about 50
other theater students were in a lecture hall at Westmoore High
School on Monday afternoon, preparing to perform scenes from many
of the plays the class had done in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 younger students, teachers and parents from Moore West
Junior High School, about two miles away, were in the school's
auditorium for an awards presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The radio was on as the theater students donned their costumes.
They listened as a vicious storm cell took aim at Oklahoma City.
Then, as the tornadoes closed in, they abandoned their
preparations, got on the floor between the seats and waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were crying `cause you could hear it coming. It was so
bad. It was so scary,'' Cantrell said. ``It sounded like
explosions, you could hear the roof coming off and falling in.''
</P>
<P>
   A police officer assigned to the school alerted the visiting
middle schoolers that the storm was about to hit, said Carri Smith,
a Westmoore student.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the one who got everybody out'' of the auditorium, Smith
said. ``She's pretty much our little hero.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday students recounted their close call as they waited
with their families to be allowed back into their devastated
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The school is adjacent to the area that officials said sustained
the worst damage from Monday's killer tornadoes _ southwest of
119th Street and Western Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm passed, they could see part of the school roof
torn off. Lockers were strewn through hallways, ceiling tiles and
insulation were all over the school, students said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, cars in the parking lot were tossed about like toys,
some piled on top of others, Westmoore students said.
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell's mother, Deborah, had been at the school to watch her
daughter perform and had carried the family's Siamese cat, Mesha,
with her. She knew what kind of storm was brewing, she said
Tuesday. Many in the area chose to ride out the storm in their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have no idea what's about to happen,'' she
remembered thinking as she went to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell went outside the school after the storm passed. She and
friends, and her mother went atop a small hill and looked at a
subdivision across Western Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it looks like is a bombing over there,'' said
Deborah, Cantrell's mother who declined to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
