A4295 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      05-04 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MOTHERS WHO THINK: TALES OF REAL-LIFE PARENTHOOD &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Camille Peri and Kate Moses (Villard, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy, the editors point out, to find written accounts
of motherhood ``that haven't had their sharp, thought-provoking
edges sanded off.'' These women have put together a book that is an
antidote to what they call ``the saccharine, oversimplified
literature of motherhood.'' It's a collection of 37 essays from
prominent and new writers, including stories from the ``Mothers Who
Think'' feature of the online magazine ``Salon'' that inspired the
project. Their subjects include anything connected to motherhood,
which means there are no limits. Among the contributors are Cathy
Wilkinson, an Arizona mom who describes how she saved her sons from
an intrusive bull by smacking it with her blender; Susan Straight,
who tells of being suddenly single and in possession of an
87-year-old farmhouse plus ``three kids, a job, a big yard, seven
rabbits and two hands''; Elizabeth Rapoport, whose essay, ``How
Many Working Fathers Does It Take to Screw in a Lightbulb?,'' is
really a quiz _ a Superparent Achievement Test that ``reflects and
quantifies the real psychic energy and time-suck of child
rearing''; Anne Lamott, who discusses anger (she told her son that
when his pets, due to his neglect, began starving to death she
would no longer intercede to keep them alive but would, instead,
have them immediately put to sleep); and Alex Witchell, who
contemplates the perplexities of being a stepmother. This book is a
lot like motherhood itself _ full of joy, trauma, insanity, hard
work, exhaustion and more than a few good laughs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TELLING &QL; 
 &UR; Patricia Weaver Francisco (HarperCollins, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Here is a lesson for those of us who have been lucky. One summer
night in 1981, Francisco awoke to find a stranger in her bedroom.
Her husband was away for a week, her sister had just left.
Francisco lived in a shady old Minneapolis neighborhood where she
felt smugly, naively safe, but still she did not take chances. She
was careful. She locked her doors and windows. And suddenly, there
was a stranger in her room. Rape, she says, is not a word we like
to use _ we fall back on terms like assault or sexual violence
because they are easier for us to say. But Francisco says it, over
and over, with a persuasive eloquence that sets her book apart from
others of its kind. She does not want pity, or even sympathy. She
wants intellect. She wants us to know and think about what happened
to her, and to realize that it happened to us, too _ that the
victim of a rape should not be left alone with a problem she did
not create. She wants us to think about how women are portrayed on
television and in advertising, and she wants us to know what it is
like to have to, as a counselor put it, ``build an extra room onto
your house for the fear.'' She also wants to tell us that she was
able to regain her sanity because of other people, not in spite of
them _ that there were friends, male and female, who did and said
the right things, and that even though she had endured one of the
most isolating of crimes, she knew that she was not alone. This is
a fierce and ultimately moving book. It isn't an easy choice to
make, but anyone who reads it will be better for it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MORGAN: AMERICAN FINANCIER &QL; 
 &UR; Jean Strouse (Random House, $34.95)
</P>
<P>
   Edward Steichen, who took J. Pierpont Morgan's photograph when
the financier was an old man, said that meeting his gaze was like
looking into the lights of an oncoming express train. A woman who
knew Morgan well told Strouse that when he entered a room ``you
felt something electric. He wasn't a terribly large man but he had
a simply tremendous effect _ he was the king. He was it.'' When
Morgan died in 1913 at age 75, his estate was valued at $80 million
and he was the most powerful banker in the world, organizer of
giant railroad systems and corporate trusts, and the man who had
helped transform an agrarian society into one based on modern
industry. He had many critics (one senator called him ``a beefy,
red-faced, thick-necked financial bully, drunk with wealth and
power''), but he was deaf to the claims of his adversaries. Oddly
enough, this most powerful man struggled with depression and
feelings of worthlessness. He had no conversational skills, and
even his appearance created trauma for him (Morgan suffered from a
skin disease that turned his nose into a swollen purple bulb).
Working from material unavailable to previous biographers, Strouse
has written a lively, if long (700 pages) biography of the man who
was cast as the high priest of capitalism, and whose actions nearly
a century ago raise questions that are at the center of the
financial news today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; STANDING IN A RIVER WAVING A STICK &QL; 
 &UR; John Gierach (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23)
</P>
<P>
   We had never read a book by Gierach before, but we admired his
titles (others are ``Sex, Death and Fly-fishing'' and ``Another
Lousy Day in Paradis''e), so we ventured into new territory in the
hopes that we'd discover something wonderful _ a Tim Cahill of the
fly-fishing set, maybe, or a stick-waving cross between Steve
Martin and Norman Maclean. At first, Gierach's voice sounded folksy
and amiable, his stories seemed to mosey off the page, his pace
mirrored what we'd always imagined the pace of fishing to be _ that
is to say no pace at all. We went along with it until we realized
that we weren't listening anymore, that we were looking at the page
but thinking of dinner, that the only thing worse than watching a
man fish is hearing him tell you about it. We say this with regret.
We know that Gierach has lots of fans, and they have sticks of
their own. &QL; 
 &QL; 
You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net, via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
