<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STORM'S WAKE, LITTLE LEFT OF A LITTLE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OKLA-STORMS, OKLA-AID) 
(rm) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ There was never a whole lot to Bridge
Creek. The church. The school. The Pinetree grocery. Ollison's
convenience store. And perhaps 8,000 residents, a mixed community
of farmers who have lived here for decades and Oklahoma City
commuters who have flocked here more recently in search of space
and solitude.
</P>
<P>
   But now, there is a whole lot less to Bridge Creek. The
merciless series of tornadoes that flattened this area some 30
miles southwest of Oklahoma City on Monday left little but massive
piles of wreckage and the mangled memories that neighbors plucked
from the debris.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people _ eight women, two men and one infant _ died here
in Monday's storm, the largest group among the 38 killed throughout
Oklahoma. Scores more were injured and five are still missing,
according to Grady County Sheriff Stan Florence. The Oklahoma State
Patrol estimates that 235 houses in this unincorporated area were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeannette L. Ralston emerged from the sturdy storm cellar
that her husband built of landscaping timbers 20 years ago, she
came up with one word to describe the devastation caused by the
twisters that had just churned through. ``Hiroshima,'' she said.
``It just looked like the pictures of Hiroshima. When we came up,
everything was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The landscape here is utterly torched. The storms left a
6-mile-long skid mark on the earth, a blighted wasteland that is
nearly a mile wide in some places. Houses and mobile homes are so
thoroughly demolished that residents are not sure where their
rubble ends and their neighbors' begins. Trees are denuded, as if
whittled by God's hand, and many are wrapped with ribbons of sheet
metal. Barbed wire is strewn everywhere, and property is fenced by
fallen electric cables.
</P>
<P>
   Because this area was largely rural, the ground was littered
Tuesday with the corpses of horses and cows and pigs, their legs
pointing stiffly skyward. On Tuesday afternoon, as National Guard
helicopters surveyed the damage from above, relief workers riding
backhoes began plowing graves for the livestock. ``My son saw a
full-grown cow that had been impaled on a broken power pole,''
Raltson said, ``just like a shish kebab.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence, the sheriff, said the loss of life may have been
particularly severe here because the area had a high concentration
of mobile homes and had no warning sirens, leaving people to rely
on television and radio reports for information about the
approaching calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston said that she and her husband discovered two bodies, one
male and one female, at a nearby house shortly after the storm
passed. Although she knows her neighbors, she did not know these
people, or at least did not recognize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to identify them but I couldn't,'' she said. ``The
bodies were so mangled. They must have come from someplace else.
They were completely nude and the way they were injured I think the
wind had stripped them. The woman had a huge hole in her right side
and the man was just laying there as if he didn't know what had
happened, just in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said his tired troops had been buoyed by one bit of
good news. A missing woman who had been separated from her
six-year-old son was found Tuesday afternoon under layers of debris
near her house. Though she had been missing for nearly 24 hours,
she was in good condition, the sheriff said. ``That gives us some
hope and spurs us on to look a little harder,'' he said, although
he added that the entire area had now been searched.
</P>
<P>
   Many Bridge Creek residents did hear about the storm in time to
escape on Monday afternoon, with many speeding to Oklahoma City as
the swirling charcoal clouds chased them from behind. Some trickled
back in the darkness, armed with flashlights and sneaking around
police roadblocks, only to find concrete foundations where houses
once stood. Others returned Tuesday and began the unimaginable
process of surveying their losses, checking on neighbors, mourning
the dead and searching for faith.
</P>
<P>
   Linda J. Wood spent the afternoon tearily scanning her property
for keepsakes like a beachcomber searching for sharks' teeth. She
unfolded her hand to show the day's bounty. ``Here's my mother's
i.d. bracelet, her wedding ring, my diamond heart necklace,'' she
said. ``The chain's gone but the main thing is here. We just found
it lying on the ground. It was on a shelf in my bathroom and as you
can see the bathroom is gone.'' As she spoke, her daughter, Angela,
exclaimed: ``Oh my gosh, it's Grandma's coin,'' she said, plucking
an 1884 silver dollar from the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Wood could not figure out what had become of the six-foot-long
freezer chest where she stored meat and other perishables. ``Who
knows where it is,'' she said. ``Do you see it? Oh, that might be
the lid over there in that tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the dirt road, Dennis L. Fellin, a 39-year-old computer
technician who was planning to build a house on the plot where his
trailer once stood, let out a whoop when a friend found a baby
picture of his 7-year-old son in a heap of trash. ``All right,'' he
said. ``There's baby Joseph.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellin had already made another important discovery. A neighbor
had found his 6-year-old dalmatian, Cira, hiding in a car and had
just returned the dog. ``She's a little sheepish,'' he said,
glancing toward the seemingly confused dog, ``but she's fine.'' His
father's old pickup truck, a gift from his mother after his
father's recent death, was a different matter. The wind had lifted
it out of his driveway and deposited it in a field 150 yards away.
It looked as if it had been firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   As is so often the case with tornadoes, the ones here seemed
remarkably discriminating in what they left in place and what they
tossed aside. Heather J. Dawkins, a 27-year-old mother of three,
T-ball coach and church youth director, could not understand how
the storm had left a file folder seemingly untouched atop a cabinet
in her now nonexistent bedroom. ``It was still sitting there,'' she
said, ``in the bedroom with the wall gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Like virtually all of the victims interviewed here Tuesday,
Dawkins said the killer storm had done nothing to vanquish her deep
Christian faith. ``That's why I can look at this and still have a
smile on my face,'' she said. ``Because I know who's in control of
things even when a whole town gets blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom R. Duckett, the 45-year-old ponytailed preacher at
Ridgecrest Baptist Church, made similar observations as he stood
within his destroyed church, where collapsed girders groaned in a
strong, dusty wind. While the school complex and the community's
stores survived, its house of worship did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why all things happen,'' he said, backed by a
crumbled brick wall. ``I just know the Lord walks through them with
us. I don't think the Lord ever said in Scripture that there
wouldn't be hardship. This is just life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
