<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCIAL-REFORM-BOS &LR;      05-04 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIAL-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BEGINS FINANCIAL SERVICES REFORM DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The US Senate, making another attempt to pass a
bill that has failed about a dozen times in the past two decades,
Tuesday began considering a measure to wipe out Depression-era laws
that prevent banks, brokerages and insurance firms to enter each
other's markets.
</P>
<P>
   Because industry squabbling and political considerations have
killed the bill many times, few people are predicting outright that
it will become law this year. ``But you have industry consensus and
bipartisan agreement that the time is long overdue for this,'' said
Dan Zielinski of the American Insurance Association. ``So the stars
seem to be aligning here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the laws that regulate financial securities firms date
to the Depression, when lawmakers feared that risky business
activities should be segregated from the banking system so that
they do not harm the broader economy.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, industry leaders and regulators have said
the US financial system includes enough safeguards so that American
firms can safely form the kind of ``financial supermarkets'' that
are now common in Europe and Japan, where banking services,
insurance, mutual funds, and stocks are sold under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Given the wide array of business interests affected by the bill,
the number of disputes this year is small.
</P>
<P>
   One set comes from consumer advocates. The Senate bill ``gives
everything to industry and nothing to consumers,'' said Mary
Griffin of Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Senate should require banks, for example, to offer
services at a reduced cost to low-income people. In addition, she
said, it should require the financial conglomerates of the future
to disclose what kind of customer information is being shared among
the bank, brokerage, and insurance units, and to allow consumers to
block the sharing of that information.
</P>
<P>
   Without that protection, she said, an insurer might be able deny
insurance coverage to a person merely because he or she bounced a
lot of checks. A mortgage company might deny a loan to someone
based on his or her health insurance records, she suggested.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton Tuesday unveiled a package of measures that
aim to protect consumers against the increasing trend toward
information-sharing among banks, insurance companies, and
securities firms. Griffin said consumer advocates would seek to
attach the package to the Senate's financial services bill.
</P>
<P>
   An even more prominent debate involves how the new law would
affect the existing Community Reinvestment Act, or CRA. The
22-year-old CRA requires banks that collect deposits in low-income
and minority communities to make sure that some of that money goes
to work in those neighborhoods in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CRA is one of the crowning achievements of the Civil
Rights Movement,'' said Wade Henderson, executive director of the
Leadership Conference on Civil Rights. ``With the CRA, our
neighborhoods have a chance of developing, and without it they are
victimized and discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Phil Gramm, the Texas Republican who leads the
Senate banking committee, says the bill gives community groups too
much power to demand cash payments and commitments to loan programs
for low-income people. On the Senate floor Tuesday, Gramm appeared
to criticize the Boston-based Neighborhood Assistance Corp. of
America for its confrontational tactics in securing loan
commitments from banks. He did not specifically name the group.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's version of the bill would give community groups only a
limited right to use the CRA to block mergers between banks that
have been given a ``satisfactory'' rating by regulators for CRA
compliance. Opponents say this would make the CRA far less
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Another major debate concerns the financial structure of banks
that want to enter the insurance and securities businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and some other
regulators want these banks to create a holding companies that
become the parent of separate banking, insurance, and brokerage
units. They say this will protect taxpayers, who insure bank
deposits through the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., and who might
have to cover bank losses due to insurance or brokerage activities.
</P>
<P>
   Other regulators say that banks should be able to run insurance
and brokerage businesses as operating subsidiaries of the banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
