u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      05-04 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR SHIFT IS SUGGESTED AS TREASURY PRICES DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices dropped sharply Tuesday, pushing
long-term interest rates to their highest level in nine months.
</P>
<P>
   There was no significant economic news to prompt the selling,
said traders and analysts, who instead cited a shift in view among
bond investors.
</P>
<P>
   The selling has pushed the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond up
almost a quarter of a percentage point in just three trading days.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading in the Treasury market Tuesday, the price of the
30-year bond dropped 25/32 to 93 15/32; the yield, which moves in
the opposite direction, jumped to 5.71 percent, from 5.65 percent
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, investors are losing the conviction that the U.S.
economy will slow this year, with inflation remaining in check;
instead, a growing number worry that a rebound in the rest of the
world will keep growth strong here and _ combined with a rise in
the prices of oil and other commodities _ will nudge inflation
higher.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in prices should not be large _ from 1998's 1.6 percent
increase in the Consumer Price Index to an expected rise this year
of 2 percent or more. But investors appear to fear that this
acceleration may still be enough to prompt the Federal Reserve to
raise interest rates to slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are becoming increasingly aware that the global
economy is improving and that the prospect for low inflation is
less, while the prospect for higher inflation has increased,'' said
Richard Berner, the chief U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   This outlook on inflation and growth, he added, means that the
Fed is likely to raise interest rates by the first quarter of next
year, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates, and the fear of inflation that would
cause them, are a threat to the stock market, which retreated
Tuesday after the Dow Jones industrial average topped 11,000 points
for the first time Monday. Tuesday, the Dow dropped 128.58 points,
or 1.2 percent, to 10,886.11.
</P>
<P>
   But so far this year, equity investors have ignored the rise in
rates, which has seen 30-year bond yield shoot up from a low of
5.05 percent in January. But at the current level, according to the
valuation model used by Byron Wien, the U.S. investment strategist
at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the stock market is overvalued by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign of concern about an impending rise in the federal
funds rate, the central bank's interest rate target, the yield on
the fed funds futures contract for December has jumped to 5 percent
since Thursday. The fed funds target is now 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Connor, the head government trader at J.P. Morgan
Securities, said a Morgan survey showed that money managers, who
had been betting on an economic slowdown here and a bond rally,
were changing their views.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, he said, 89 percent of the money managers
surveyed were at or ahead of their performance benchmarks in terms
of their bet on bonds _ meaning many were expecting a rally. But
now the survey shows the percentage has dropped to 75 percent.
Reducing bond exposure in this direction means selling.
</P>
<P>
   Connor also said there was a lot of selling because investors
were switching from Treasury securities to corporate and other
bonds, which offer higher yields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wake-up call for a bond manager,'' said N. Graham
Allen, managing director of global fixed income for Wells Capital
Management. He still believes that this is just a wide swing in a
trading range that will see bond prices rally and yields fall
again. But he admitted that the bond market ``is a little shaky at
the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Slifer, the chief U.S. economist at Lehman Brothers also
argues that investors are overreacting. He said that the 1.4
percent rise in the inflation measure for the gross domestic
product is overstated. It was the report of that rise Friday, along
with the news that the economy grew at 4.5 percent during the first
quarter, a rate much stronger than expected, that set off the
latest round of bond selling.
</P>
<P>
   He also says that while some commodity prices have risen
recently from their lows for the year, they have not had the kind
of surge that amounts to an inflationary threat.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledges that right now this analysis does not matter
in the bond market. ``While I may kiss this off,'' he said, ``there
is nothing that says that interest rates can't go up in the near
term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
