<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-NYT &LR;      05-04 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPARTMENT CLEARS U.N. NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department's inspector general said
Tuesday that she had cleared Richard Holbrooke, President Clinton's
nominee as chief U.S. diplomat to the United Nations, after an
investigation of speaking fees that he accepted while working as an
unpaid White House envoy to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to close the investigation removed one more
roadblock from Senate confirmation of Holbrooke, whose nomination
to the U.N. post has been stalled for months.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional officials said Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, would not allow
the nomination to advance further until the Senate had received a
variety of internal documents from the Justice Department about an
earlier ethics investigation of Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Inspector General Jacquelyn Williams-Bridgers
said Tuesday that her office ``initiated an investigation based on
information that Ambassador Holbrooke inappropriately received
compensation for speaking and writing on activities that were part
of his official duties.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, the statement said, ``did not find evidence
of a clear violation of the standards of conduct and the Office of
Inspector General closed the investigation'' last Friday. She
offered no details on her reasons for dropping the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's lawyer, Richard Beattie, said that the outcome was a
``complete exoneration'' of the veteran diplomat, and that
Holbrooke's nomination should now be able to advance in the Senate.
``There was no evidence of any wrongdoing,'' Beattie said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was the second by the inspector general. The
first ethics investigation, conducted with the Justice Department,
delayed Holbrooke's nomination by eight months and ended with
Holbrooke's agreement in February to pay $5,000 to settle civil
charges that he had violated federal lobbying laws. He denied
wrongdoing at the time of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The second inquiry, which threatened additional delays in Senate
hearings for Holbrooke, was prompted by an opinion article in The
Washington Post in March that questioned whether it was proper for
Holbrooke to receive lecture fees for speaking about the current
situation in the Balkans while serving as a special presidential
envoy to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said investigators focused on a speech that Holbrooke
gave last November at Stanford University, for which he was paid
$16,000.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, Holbrooke had been named an unpaid envoy to the
Balkans, focusing on the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said the investigation showed that the speech had
centered not on recent developments in Kosovo, but on broader
foreign policy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech was about foreign policy and the need to have a
foreign policy,'' Beattie said. ``He threw in a couple of anecdotal
things at the end, and he used Kosovo as an example. But the speech
wasn't about Kosovo at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms has not yet scheduled a confirmation hearing for
Holbrooke, whose formal nomination was submitted by the White House
to the Senate in February.
</P>
<P>
   And while the senator's staff had no comment Tuesday on
Holbrooke's nomination, congressional officials said that Helms
would not organize the hearing until the Foreign Relations
Committee had received a variety of Justice Department documents
about the original ethics investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One other roadblock to the nomination was recently removed after
the Clinton administration and Helms reached agreement on
legislation to pay back dues to the United Nations in exchange for
reforms within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, a former ambassador to Germany who was the architect
of the Dayton peace agreement in 1995 that ended the war in Bosnia,
has found himself a case study for the ethical mine fields faced by
former officials who agree to return to work for the government
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier investigation, prompted by an anonymous letter to
the State Department, focused in part on accusations that Holbrooke
had illegally lobbied his former government colleagues at the U.S.
Embassy in South Korea shortly after resigning from the State
Department in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to the $5,000 settlement with the Justice
Department, Holbrooke denied wrongdoing and insisted that he had
agreed to the settlement only to avoid further delays in his
nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0505-C     05-04 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0505-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PURSUING DIPLOMACY, CARRYING BIG STICK OF WAR
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-POWS-0505; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0505;
KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0505.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ President Clinton was scheduled to meet here
Wednesday with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana to update him
on diplomatic efforts to end the alliance's air war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who left Washington late Tuesday for the
overnight trans-Atlantic flight, also planned to meet with the NATO
commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, and with the three American
soldiers released from Yugoslav captivity over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the White House on Tuesday, Clinton vowed ``to seize
every diplomatic possibility,'' for ending the conflict on NATO's
terms. At the heart of those terms is the demand that ethnic
Albanian refugees be allowed to return ``safe and secure'' to their
homes in the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what our effort in Kosovo is all about,'' said
Clinton. `` Whatever can be negotiated, it is not that.''
</P>
<P>
   After six weeks and nearly 4,000 attack sorties, U.S. and allied
attacks are increasing ``in intensity and impact,'' Clinton said,
following NATO's single most successful day yet in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During the 24-hour period that ended early Tuesday, NATO bombs
struck 80 targets, ranging from individual tanks and artillery
pieces in the field to fixed ammunitions dumps and command and
control centers, by far the most targets hit since the punishing
air campaign began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO pilot flying an F-16 shot down a Yugoslav MiG 29 fighter
Tuesday, the first such shoot down since the early days of the
campaign, as it streaked to within two miles of the Bosnian border.
</P>
<P>
   Clear skies and around-the-clock strikes have helped allied
pilots with increasingly aggressive search and destroy missions
against Serb forces dispersed across the Kosovo, a province of
Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign intensifies, the Pentagon acknowledged for the
first time Tuesday that B-52 Superfortress heavy bombers have begun
pounding Yugoslav forces in the field with mass drops of 500-pound
bombs. Dumped 54 at a time, the bombs cut a lethal swath the length
of three football fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just keeps rolling and keeps rolling,'' Air Force Gen.
Charles Wald said of the air campaign targeting the forces of Serb
leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia. ``I doubt very
seriously if he has any idea how bad he's being hit right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As the strikes have intensified, so has the risk to U.S. pilots
and to civilians on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said, though, that he had calculated the number of bombs
dropped and the number that have killed or injured civilians thus
far, and found that 99.93 percent of NATO bombs had not caused
civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said there would be some collateral damage; we've had some
of that,'' said Wald. ``But I think over a 41- or 42-day period,
with that many bombs, that's pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wald, `` I think if you look at Milosevic's record, I'd say
99.9 percent of his targets
</P>
<P>
   are collateral damage, so kind of take it for what it's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the escalating war, however, Clinton spoke of the prospects
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   In departure remarks on the South Lawn of the White House,
Clinton said he told Russia's special envoy to the Balkans, Victor
Chernomyrdin, that he was devoted to seeking a diplomatic solution
to the Yugoslav conflict, even as he pursues an increasingly
aggressive air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reaffirmed our support for his efforts and our willingness
to seize every diplomatic possibility for Serbian authorities to
meet the requirements that NATO has articulated,'' Clinton said of
his meeting Monday with Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of ongoing talks between Clinton and Chernomyrdin
is the issue of how to constitute a peacekeeping force that would
deploy inside Kosovo once the conflict concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ``there is no middle ground,'' however, on the
question of security for the estimated 1.8 million ethnic Albanians
who have fled their homes in the face of military repression inside
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clarifying a comment he made Monday concerning the composition
of such a force, Clinton said the force must have ``NATO at its
core.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is traveling here with Defense Secretary William Cohen,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Joint Chiefs of Staff
Chairman Gen. Hugh Shelton, and National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to travel to Germany's Ramstein Air Base
on Wednesday to visit with the American soldiers released over the
weekend and to speak with U.S. pilots at a base at Spangdahlem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0505-C     05-04 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0505-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PURSUING DIPLOMACY, CARRYING BIG STICK OF WAR
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-POWS-0505; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0505;
KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0505.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
