<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 EUROPEAN STOCK EXCHANGES FORM ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Edging closer to the vision of a unified
European stock market, eight stock exchanges agreed Tuesday to
develop a common trading system for stocks in Europe's biggest
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The eight exchanges are those of Frankfurt; London; Paris;
Amsterdam, Netherlands; Brussels, Belgium; Madrid, Spain; Zurich,
Switzerland, and Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is a step toward eliminating the inefficiency of
Europe's stock exchanges, which play a much smaller role in the
overall economy than their counterparts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the allure of creating one big market and taking
advantage of Europe's single currency, the euro, the exchanges are
still divided by rivalries and are feuding over the kind of system
to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tuesday's agreement was an attempt to soothe the anger
of France and several other countries, which were shocked last July
when the London and Frankfurt stock exchanges _ the largest and
second-largest in Europe by market capitalization _ announced their
plan for a joint-trading system and merely ``invited'' others to
join.
</P>
<P>
   The move was particularly galling to executives at the Paris
Bourse, the third-biggest exchange in Europe, who did not learn
about the Frankfurt-London deal until it was publicly announced. It
was also troubling that Frankfurt was teaming up with an exchange
outside the 11 nations that use the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the smaller exchanges have vacillated between the
anxiety of being left out and the fear of being swallowed up.
Tuesday's agreement was the most concrete step toward
reconciliation, but those involved offered no clues about the
exchange's structure, trading hours, common rules, preferred stock
index benchmark or timetable, all key issues that must be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief signing ceremony in Madrid, which was chosen as a
neutral site, the eight exchanges ``underlined their commitment''
to bring their rules into agreement and eventually develop a single
electronic-trading system for stocks of Europe's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a complex project, but it is possible and
necessary,'' said Antonio Zoido, chairman of the Madrid exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is essentially an endorsement of common goals, and
it is limited to trading in a fairly small universe of Europe's
biggest companies. It does not include Europe's fast-growing ``new
markets,'' the new exchanges, affiliated with the older ones, that
were created primarily for newer technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the French, Swiss and Italian stock exchanges said
they were continuing with plans for a ``virtual market'' that would
probably compete with the Frankfurt-London alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
