<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLD-BATTLE-SPI &LR;      05-04 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLD-BATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD BATTLE LOOMS OVER BUCKHORN MOUNTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deep within a mountain in Washington state near the
Canadian border are microscopic veins of gold worth tens of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Battle Mountain Gold Co., a publicly traded Houston-based
company, is so convinced of the value of that gold that it claims
to have spent $80 million over the past seven years winning more
than 50 state and local permits and a variety of legal skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
   But a month ago, Battle Mountain ran into a sudden and
unexpected obstacle: the Clinton administration announced that,
under a little-known provision of an 1872 mining law, the Crown
Jewel mining project could not proceed as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Now a largely local dispute over the future of Buckhorn Mountain
and its gold has turned into a congressional battle with national
implications.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are jobs in a depressed part of a booming state, the
health of the environment, and the future of mining in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., is so irate over the Clinton
administration's handling of the proposed mine that he is working
to get Congress to overturn the action.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has twice berated administration officials over the
issue. He has suggested that an overseer of the Forest Service
should resign, and upbraided Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt at a
public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton declined to be interviewed on the subject, but his
spokeswoman, Cynthia Bergman, said, ``We aren't going to give up
and roll over on this one. The people of eastern Washington and
Battle Mountain have been treated unfairly by this administration,
and we intend to seek solutions to rectify this manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Doc Hastings, R-Wash., who represents the region, also is
eager to get the mine project moving.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, environmentalists and Indian tribes are raising an
alarm because they are fearful that Gorton will find a way to
revive the mine project while circumventing both public debate and
the presidential veto pen. The environmentalists say they have been
told by congressional staffers that Gorton and his allies will
attempt to attach a mine-friendly provision to an unamendable
budget unlikely to be vetoed by Clinton because it will include
money for the military operation in Yugoslavia or for hurricane aid
to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few days or weeks mining industry supporters will
likely attempt to attach in conference yet another
anti-environmental mining rider to the hurricane disaster relief
Emergency Supplemental Appropriations bill,'' warns a letter going
to all members of Congress Wednesday from the Mineral Policy
Center, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please do not permit a last-second, stealth rider shielded
from public scrutiny to grant special favors to the mining industry
in one week when American citizens have been waiting for legitimate
mining law reform for over 125 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Crown Jewel mine was rejected by both the Interior
Department and the Agriculture Department _ who together own much
of Buckhorn Mountain _ based on a provision of the 1872 mining law
largely ignored by the more mine-friendly Reagan and Bush
administrations. The provision, as interpreted by the Clinton
administration, limits the amount of surrounding land that the
company can use to dispose of its waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration claims Battle Mountain can still mine
Buckhorn Mountain using different methods, but the company and its
allies say the alternatives are impractical. The mining industry is
warning that if the administration's decision to block the Crown
Jewel project remains, it could stop virtually all future mining in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most outrageous decisions that has come out
of the Department of Interior in the last 20 or 30 years,'' said
Laura Skaer, the executive director of the Northwest Mining
Association, an industry group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has very little to do with the Crown Jewel project and
everything to do with Secretary Babbitt and his rogue solicitor
trying to leverage mining law reform. They are putting a gun to the
mining industry's head and saying `Agree to our form of mining law
reform and we'll call off the dogs.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the industry's critics say the brouhaha spurred by Crown
Jewel may be just what is needed to force mining companies to the
bargaining table for negotiations to change the nation's
127-year-old mining law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mining law gives away the nation's mineral wealth with no
royalties to the United States and very limited environmental
controls,'' said Stephen Suagee, reservation attorney for the
Confederated Tribes of the Colville Reservation, which oppose the
mine. ``Now, rather than have a public debate on the merits of the
mining law as it stands and ways in which it ought to be changed,
they want an exemption from the one part of the law that they've
discovered is no longer to their liking.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior officials say they will resist any effort to overturn
their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're opposed, of course, to Congress passing laws and then
attempting to exempt particular industries from those laws,'' said
Michael Gauldin, director of communications at the Interior
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The mine proposed at Buckhorn Mountain, expected to generate at
least 1.6 million ounces of gold, is supported by a variety of
local officials because of its potential to create jobs in a part
of the state left behind during the state's economic boom. In
Okanogan County, a rural county with 38,000 residents, the
unemployment rate was 11.6 percent in March, more than double the
state average of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okanogan County desperately needs something,'' said Wilbur
``Web'' Hallauer, an Oroville orchardist, onetime Democratic state
senator and former director of the state Department of Ecology.
``The timber harvest is way down. Apples took a hit last year. The
cattle business isn't very good. Anything we do with our natural
resource base is on the blink.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Department of Ecology, which has given a
green light to the Crown Jewel project, the mine would employ 144
people during its operation, which would be 24 hours a day for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and the Colvilles oppose the mine because
of concerns about damage to the landscape. Battle Mountain is
proposing an open pit mine, a method of mining in which the company
would blow a large hole in the side of the mountain and then remove
large chunks of rock.
</P>
<P>
   The rocks containing gold veins would then be soaked in vats
containing cyanide, which is used to extract the gold.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmentalists worry more about sulfurous rocks that
would be exposed to the elements by the operation, and fear the
sulfer would contaminate water in area. The Indian tribes worry
that the water would harm mule deer, which form a major part of the
Indians' food supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine another use of the public land that so
transforms it from a rural pristine area to an industrial zone,''
said Roger Flynn, an attorney with the Western Mining Action
Project, which is fighting Crown Jewel. ``The waste rock will sit
there until the next Ice Age.''
</P>
<P>
   The mine's boosters say they don't believe the operation would
contaminate the environment, and that the company has done more
than enough to satisfy environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``No mining company has undergone the scrutiny this project has
endured, and met so many requirements,'' said Oroville Mayor Jimmie
Dale Walker. ``How can you take a company that has spent $80
million and tell them, `Oops, we're sorry?' What does this do to
relations between the business community and our federal
government?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
