<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO'S CIGARS ARE A HOT MAGAZINE ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The June issue of Cigar Aficionado magazine is back on
newsstands at Miami International Airport after authorities
rescinded a ban issued last week. The magazine was taken off the
shelves because its cover featured pictures of &UR; Fidel Castro &LR;  and
 &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  with the headline, ``Is It Time to End the Embargo?''
</P>
<P>
   It also contained a travel guide to Cuba that was deemed
flattering to Castro. ``We don't want to be part of enhancing
Castro's government,'' said airport spokesman  &UR; Hernando Vergara &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The ban was lifted after the American Civil Liberties Union
threatened to sue, and Miami Mayor  &UR; Alex Penelas &LR;  ordered the
magazine placed on sale again, saying its removal ``goes against
some of the very principles which make this nation the free society
it is.'' Penelas also took pains to say the magazine's story was
``a total misrepresentation of the state of affairs in Cuba, which
recently was condemned in Geneva by the U.N. Commission on Human
Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gordon Mott &LR; , managing editor of the publication, told the
Miami Herald that he wasn't too concerned about the mayor's
opinion. ``It's a free country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOOKING FINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ivana's Style magazine has come up with a tally of the money
spent by a woman to keep herself beautiful, including $560 a year
for 14 $40 tubes of anti-cellulite cream. One recommended
money-saver: a fake tan to cover the lumps.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reporting on the stylishness of white jeans for summer, New
York magazine notes: `` &UR; Gilles Bensimon &LR; , Elle's creative director,
claims to have nearly 20 white Levi's 501s in his denim collection,
explaining that he puts on a fresh pair at midday to ensure optimum
whiteness.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Joan Collins, &LR;  whose ``My Friends' Secrets'' has just been
published in England, told the Telegraph of London that at 66, she
believes in ``exercise in an unobsessive way.'' According to the
book, exercise that is too vigorous results in ``loose chins,
sagging breasts and flabby bottoms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Fortune magazine says October's annual conference of the
Employee Assistance Professionals Association will offer a workshop
on cybersex addiction.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your left ear is bigger than your right or your right
nostril is bigger than your left, you may be at a disadvantage when
it comes to running. A study reported in the International Journal
of Sports Medicine, cited in Muscle and Fitness magazine, found
that people with symmetrical features posted faster running times
on average than those with uneven features. The magazine speculates
that the difference may be caused by ``hormonal fluctuations in the
womb, which might affect the development of athletic potential.''
</P>
<P>
   _ How do you moisten the pears without moistening the customers?
 &UR; Ron Kalinin &LR; , manager of the produce department at the Safeway on
Taraval, says that store's warning device for fruit misting has
become an attraction for neighborhood kids. Ten seconds before the
sprays go on, a tape recording of thunder is played, and lights
flash to simulate lightning _ the latter being temporarily
impaired, he admits, because there are boxes of croutons in front
of the light source.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RECYCLED BRIDAL ATTENDANT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Five top tips from  &UR; Rebecca Whitlinger &LR; 's ``Always a Bridesmaid,
89 Ways to Recycle That Bridesmaid Dress'' (Andrews McMeel; $8.95):
</P>
<P>
   _ Use it as a cover to protect plants from frost.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give it to a little girl to wear for dress-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Throw it into a divorce party bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear it for casual day at work, just to express individuality.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Wear it while pleading temporary insanity for a parking
violation.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. More clothing news: Police in Germany have just received
government permission to wear blue jeans on patrol. A six-month
study determined they were more comfortable than standard uniforms,
and less intimidating to the public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees, in spite of the fact it is a horrible thing that
some 3,000 of them have lost their lives, still when you look at
the refugees, I was shocked to find out, as perhaps you were, that
they are very well off, considering they are refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Senator  &LR; James Inhofe, R-Okla., just back from a trip to the
Balkans, as quoted in Roll Call. ``In spite of'' those deaths,
Inhofe said the children ``are all wearing Nikes and were very well
dressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
