<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-HELP-TEX     05-04 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-HELP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF SPECIALISTS WORKING TO PROVIDE BASIC NEEDS TO TORNADO
VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRYON OKADA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ The initial pleas from Oklahoma are for the most
basic human needs _ water, electricity, light, medicine, money.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster specialists, utility crews, insurance agents, rescue
workers and an array of volunteers from North Texas are converging
on Oklahoma City to provide assistance to tornado victims and to
help ease the devastated region into what officials say will be a
months-long road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   From the underground Region VI headquarters of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency in Denton, disaster specialists worked
through the night and day Tuesday devising an emergency services
strategy for the Oklahoma City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state told us they had a great need for power lines, water
and essential needs,'' said Carrie Moorehead, FEMA external affairs
specialist. ``We don't know a lot at this point because we're in
the initial stages and the state is struggling because it was so
widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   Waves of FEMA officials and disaster reservists began driving to
Oklahoma City about 4 a.m. Tuesday, ``pre-staging'' in anticipation
of President Clinton's declaration of a federal emergency, which he
signed just before noon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That cleared federal officials to begin operations and freed up
federal money to pay for temporary housing for victims, as well as
home repairs not covered by insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   The cluster of tornadoes that ripped through the Oklahoma City
area downed phone lines, ruptured natural gas lines and scattered
utility poles.
</P>
<P>
   TU Electric/Lone Star Gas spokesman Ray Granato said 35
Metroplex workers _ including some from Arlington, Fort Worth and
the Hurst-Euless-Bedford areas _ have been sent to assist repair
efforts. An additional 35 contract employees also were released
from local duties to help the effort, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma Gas and Electric called this morning for assistance
and the crews were trying get on the road by 1 p.m.,'' Granato
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, they are prepared to stay a week. But that
could change depending on what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Because power was out across the region, up to 12 Southwestern
Bell offices in Oklahoma were running on generator power Tuesday,
said Bell spokeswoman Michelle Smith.
</P>
<P>
   To help displaced residents communicate with family and friends,
Bell is offering free call forwarding and voice messaging services,
Smith said. Free local calls can be made from existing
coin-operated phones and portable phone banks at emergency
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency relief volunteers from local religious organizations
remain on call Wednesday, ready to spring into action should
Oklahoma churches sound a call for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said, `We are ready as soon as you invite us to
come,''' said Rachael Sandifer, director of missions for the
Central Texas Conference of the United Methodist Church in Fort
Worth. ``We are ready with a first responder team.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, eight volunteers from the Tarrant Baptist Association
Disaster Relief Team were waiting word Tuesday afternoon from the
Baptist regional organization in Oklahoma, said Bobby Cox, director
of church and community ministry for the Tarrant County
association.
</P>
<P>
   To help search for survivors and victims, more than 10 seasoned
rescue specialists, including search dogs from the Metroplex, were
dispatched to Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 47 search and rescue specialists of the Texas Task
Force One Search and Rescue Team are on standby, an official said.
The team, which includes firefighters, paramedics and structural
engineers from across the state, is in Dallas this week for
training.
</P>
<P>
   Seven members of the Mark 9 Search and Rescue Team of Dallas and
seven search dogs were sent early Tuesday to Oklahoma City. Two
members of the First Response Search and Rescue Team of Keller
accompanied the Dallas crew, said Don Stephens executive director
of the Tarrant County group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our jobs would be to hunt for victims trapped in rubble,''
Stephens said. ``One dog can do the work of 50 searchers in
situations like this.''
</P>
<P>
   A team of four tactical/paramedics from the Denton County
Sheriff's Office also left Tuesday to help in the search for
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Arlington-area law enforcement agencies said they
are ready to help with relief efforts but are waiting to see what's
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield Police Chief Steve Noonkester said he sent a teletype
Monday night to officials in Chickasha, Okla., offering to send two
police officers and two police cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these types of situations it's a real drain on manpower,''
Mansfield Police Chief Steve Noonkester said. ``No one is allowed
in or out of the area for the next few days. It's a painstaking
process going through the debris.''
</P>
<P>
   About 50 members of Allstate Insurance's national catastrophe
team were sent to the area to assist adjusters already based there,
said Justin Schmitt, a spokesman with Allstate's regional
headquarters in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   The team is equipped with what Allstate calls ``mobile rescue
units'' _ essentially oversized recreational vehicles that serve as
claims offices on wheels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They drive right into devastated neighborhoods and help
customers process claims on the spot,'' Schmitt said. ``Right now,
we're writing a lot of ALEs _ additional living expense checks _
which we issue immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
