<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4323 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-     05-04 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ONCE-SWEET BOTTLING PLAN TURNS SOUR FOR COKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   M. Douglas Ivester, the mastermind of Coca-Cola's worldwide
bottling network, stood by like a proud uncle through most of the
1990s as the company racked up impressive gains in sales and
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company and this system have never been better equipped
or better aligned than they are today,'' Ivester, the chairman and
chief executive of Coca-Cola Co., said nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, though, Ivester's grand plan appears to be faltering.
Weak economies around the world have savaged many of the individual
bottling companies' profits. So the bottlers, from Sao Paulo to
Sydney, are turning to Coke to help them out, a move that is likely
to cost Coke hundreds of millions of dollars this year. The shift
is stunning, for the bottlers were supposed to be Coke's engine of
growth, not the parts needing copious amounts of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign governments are putting up some roadblocks, too. Ivester
has announced plans to buy several foreign brands, including
Orangina, the French citrus drink, with an eye to helping generate
the heavy volume needed to make his bottling network cost
effective. But those plans are being attacked by officials abroad
as threats to competition.
</P>
<P>
   As Coca-Cola's chief accountant, Ivester led the 1996 spinoff of
Coca-Cola Enterprises, which was Coke's first ``anchor bottler''
and has become its largest. He then urged smaller bottlers around
the globe to combine; by January of this year, he had built a chain
of 11 anchor bottlers, the most recent in Japan, with the argument
that a unified bottling system was the most efficient. Coca-Cola
has large investments in all 11 of those bottlers and in scores of
smaller ones as well.
</P>
<P>
   Coke earns money from the system on two fronts. It sells
concentrate to the bottlers, which mix it up, package it and sell
drinks like Diet Coke, Sprite and Fanta. Coke also receives
dividends on its bottling investments _ a 42 percent stake, for
example, in Coca-Cola Enterprises. At the same time, Coke bears
none of the enormous costs of bottling.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement works well in good times and can camouflage a
couple of trouble spots around the world. But when Coke's sales are
flat or declining in several markets, as they are now from Germany
and Japan to Brazil and South Africa, the system starts to sag.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Coke has both paid more to its bottlers to
help sell its drinks and collected less from its investment in
them. Dividend income from the bottlers fell to just $32 million in
1998, a 79 percent decrease from $155 million the previous year.
Meanwhile, spending on marketing and infrastructure payments to
bottlers soared to a record $1.84 billion, about 39 percent more
than in 1997. Some payments were made to ward off price increases
that bottlers wanted, but that also would have cut into sales
volume, and thus reduced demand for Coca-Cola concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman defended the pattern, saying it was spending
for the long term. ``We make these investments because the mission
of the Coca-Cola system is to build shareowner value over time,''
said the spokesman, Rob Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of last year's payments, $1.2 billion, went to
Coca-Cola Enterprises. But at least one analyst says similar
payments will have to be made to overseas bottlers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it in baseball terms, while CCE is in perhaps the
seventh inning, with the rest of the world Coke just threw out the
first pitch,'' said Michael Branca, an analyst for Lehman Brothers
who is concerned about what he sees as a split between growth in
sales volume and in per-share earnings at the company. Coke will
probably eke out volume growth of 5 percent or so this year, he
said, but at an extraordinary cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with volume growth of 5 or 6 percent in the second half,
we expect second-half profits to be flat with the second half of
1997, when volume and the stock price were considerably lower,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which rose to nearly $89 a share in July, bottomed in
September at $53.625 and closed Tuesday at $68.6875, a day after
Warren Buffett, the investor who holds a large stake in the
company, reiterated his confidence in the stock.
</P>
<P>
   While Branca is focusing on payments to other bottlers, other
analysts foresee no decrease in the amount paid to Coca-Cola
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Coke ever, in its wildest dreams, thought it
would have to make these kinds of payments to CCE,'' said Albert
Meyer, an analyst for David W. Tice &AMP; Associates, a Dallas research
firm. Meyer, who has been critical of the relationship between Coke
and Coca-Cola Enterprises, says many bottlers are ``maxed out after
years of feeding the parent's bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer has written a report saying that since 1995 actual cash
operating profits at Coca-Cola Enterprises have declined from 8.9
percent of revenue to 5.7 percent. Payments from Coca-Cola to the
bottler have made up the difference, he said, allowing profit
growth to track revenue growth at 14.8 percent for each of the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, a year when they couldn't make any money from their
customers, Coke provided the funds,'' he said, adding that he
expects Coke to pay at least $1.3 billion this year to Coca-Cola
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Coke has already declared plans to spend close to $1 billion in
Brazil in the next three years. One anchor bottler doing business
there, the publicly traded Pan American Beverages, or Panamco,
reported Monday a loss of 31 cents a share for the first quarter,
its first loss. Coke's volume in Brazil declined by 13 percent in
the first quarter, 24 percent in Venezuela and 26 percent in
Colombia, other areas where Panamco is the major bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Under a program disclosed in April, Coke calls for price cuts of
15 percent to 20 percent in an effort to spur consumer sales. The
goal is to seize market share from less expensive local brands.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Panamco has little choice but to cut prices. ``Coke does not
permit its bottlers to promote a proprietary brand or a discount
brand,'' said Laura D. Meizler, an analyst for Salomon Smith
Barney. ``So at the beginning of the month, when a worker gets
paid, he will buy a Coke. But at the end of the month, he can't
afford it, so those sales go to some other beverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Panamco's debt load is also becoming unwieldy, ballooning to
$1.2 billion from less than $600 million 18 months ago. Nearly all
its debt is denominated in United States dollars, Ms. Meizler said,
so if the Brazilian currency was to fall further the debt would
swell yet again. A significant chunk of its debt stems from a 1996
purchase of a bottling company in Venezuela that had been a bottler
for Pepsico for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another troubled anchor bottler is Coca-Cola Amatil, in Sydney,
Australia. The company is experiencing a sales slump in many Asian
countries, and its former chief executive, Norbert Cole, is suing
Coca-Cola over the decision to split the bottler into two parts
last year. The spinoff, Coca-Cola Beverages, includes much of
Amatil's former business in Europe and was more than 50 percent
owned by Coca-Cola at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Branca noted that the global bottling network is profitable only
if it handles the high volume it was intended to accommodate.
Mindful of that, Ivester has pursued other global-growth
strategies, including the $1.85 billion purchase of overseas
distribution rights to Cadbury Schweppes brands announced in
December.
</P>
<P>
   But that deal and an $880 million plan to buy the Orangina brand
from Pernod Ricard have been stalled by the governments of France,
Mexico, Australia and the competition commission of the European
Union. In hopes of winning French approval, Coke amended its
Orangina proposal Tuesday to allow French companies to continue
distributing the drink for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ivester has seemed surprised by the widespread opposition
to Coke having such a large share of certain soft-drink markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed with the Mexican competition authorities'
decision not to approve the proposed acquisition of Cadbury
Schweppes brands by the Coca-Cola Co. in Mexico,'' the company said
last week, adding that it planned to continue the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   With Cadbury Schweppes, Coke faces an uphill battle. All five
commission members there voted against the plan, and the
commission's head, Fernando Sanchez Ugarte, said Coke would have to
radically change its plan in Mexico to win approval. ``It's not
likely that they will make such a change,'' he said on Friday.
Germany is expected to rule on the proposed merger this Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's accounting of its payments to bottlers has also raised a
few eyebrows. James Chanos, who runs Kynikos Associates and is
betting that the price of Coca-Cola Enterprises stock will fall,
says the payment from Coca-Cola that the bottler treated as income
last year should be treated as a straight expense by Coca-Cola.
``From Coke's perspective, they can have their cake and eat it
too,'' he said, adding that such payments mask declining growth in
cash flow at the bottler.
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman said that the payments were treated as
prepaid expenses and other assets on the balance sheet, but
deducted ultimately from the equity-income line to reflect the
expense in that year.
</P>
<P>
   While that is permitted under accounting rules, it may not give
the most accurate picture of Coke's financial health, said Robert
E. Verrecchia, the Ernst &AMP; Young professor of accounting at the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, he said, such accounting ``makes their operating
income look higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
