<HEADER>
A4326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-NYT     05-04 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRO'S LATEST PROBLEM: AIDING ALBANIANS WHO ARE NOT
REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ULCINJ, Montenegro _ They were kicked out of their homes and
herded across the border, like so many other refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the 70,000 ethnic Albanians who came to Montenegro are
distinct from the others because they are not considered refugees.
They are citizens of the federal republic of Yugoslavia and they
have moved from one part of the republic, Serbia, to another part,
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Because these people were displaced within their own country,
they _ and the Montenegrin government _ are in a rather complex and
delicate position. Because they are not, technically, refugees,
relief agencies, particularly the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, are limited in how they can help.
</P>
<P>
   That means that even though many of the ethnic Albanians who
arrive here want to continue on into Albania, the United Nations
cannot provide the transportation, because that could be seen as
encouraging them to flee their own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``To recommend, advocate or support their becoming refugees is
difficult,'' said Robert Breen, head of the U.N. office in
Montenegro. ``We're not in the business of creating refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations does not just turn a blind eye to the
thousands who have come and continue to come to Montenegro.
Officially, they are considered ``internally displaced persons,'' a
bureaucratic phrasing that allows the United Nations to provide a
range of aid, in coordination with other relief agencies. Thus,
with the help of the government, more than 30,000 of these
displaced people have been transported to the main border crossing
with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Others have chosen to stay, perhaps to wait for other family
members or because they are afraid to wander too far from Kosovo.
They have been put up in tent camps, or in factories, mosques, or,
in one unusual case, a beach camp here in the resort of Ulcinj
where the beach is free and street signs are in Albanian as well as
Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other ethnic Albanians forced to leave their homes in
Kosovo, these people were not compelled to give their passports and
identification cards to Serbian forces. Their cars still bear their
Kosovo license plates.
</P>
<P>
   While their numbers are far smaller than the 350,000 who flooded
neighboring Albania, the Kosovars who crossed into Montenegro
represent over 10 percent of the tiny republic's population. They
are placing a heavy burden on the already shaky Montenegrin
government.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, there were an estimated 30,000 refugees
from the wars in Croatia and Bosnia still here in Montenegro before
the NATO strikes began March 24 and the new crowd of exiles started
to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Montenegro estimates that it costs more than
$8 million a month to care for the displaced Kosovars who have
settled here. That is an enormous expense for a government already
suffering from heavy unemployment and widespread business failures
caused by the war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our best to accommodate them, but it's
difficult,'' said Dragisa Burzen, the deputy prime minister of
Montenegro, who has been handling refugee issues.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Montenegro's connection to Serbia in the Yugoslav
republic, and wartime embargoes, it has been difficult for relief
agencies to bring in food and supplies, especially fuel. Breen said
he had spent more than a week trying to arrange a delivery of
diesel fuel to supply the vehicles of relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The people from Kosovo who have come to Montenegro arrived just
as tired and hungry as those who staggered into Albania or
Macedonia over the last five weeks. And the terror of being forced
out of their homes by army troops and special forces was just as
real as for all the others.
</P>
<P>
   But those who were forced by the army to come here are in an
exile unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   Although Montenegro does not consider itself to be at war, the
Second Yugoslav Army is based here and the consequences that
presents for the exiles can be deadly. About two weeks ago, the
Yugoslav Army moved into into an area along the border where
thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees were camped.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven ethnic Albanians, including a child and a woman,
were killed in what the army said later was an offensive against
the Kosovo Liberation Army, a group of ethnic Albanian rebels
fighting for the independence of Kosovo. The army's explanation
satisfied few people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes it's just a crime,'' said Burzen, who has demanded
a full public inquiry into the killings.
</P>
<P>
   After such an incident, displaced Kosovars could not help but
feel they had not found safe refuge in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the safest place to be,'' said Afija Arifaj, an
ethnic Albanian from the Kosovo town of Istok, near Pec, in western
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arifaj and her family were forced from their home but they
feel lucky to have resettled in what for them is a familiar place.
For the last few years, she and her family had spent two weeks of
their annual vacation at a small trailer camp in Ulcinj, which
before the war had been a popular destination for vacationers from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mrs. Arifaj was forced to flee Kosovo two weeks ago, she
has been living in a beige canvas tent set up by a French relief
agency inside the same trailer park she visited last year on
vacation. The ground they sleep on is hard and damp, and days
stretch on interminably with little to do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they know they are lucky, compared with other Kosovo
Albanians. ``We feel comfortable here because we know it,'' Mrs.
Arifaj said, sitting at a folding table with some friends. ``But I
never thought I'd be back here to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others among the 1,400 people who are now being sheltered
at the Neptun Camp also have memories of pleasant summer vacations
spent camping here. But now there are intrusions, including the
memories of the harsh treatment they received at the hands of the
Yugoslav Army as they were forced out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go into town I see the Yugoslav Army and I feel
harassed,'' said Ime Redzep, who escaped from the village of Istok
as the troops started burning the houses. ``They don't do anything
to me here, but just seeing them in their uniforms reminds me of
what those people did to us in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   Others said they do not feel safe because the Montenegrin
government itself is so shaky right now. The Yugoslav Army here has
made menacing moves toward seizing power from the civilian
government, and members of the parliamentary opposition who support
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic are trying to whip up
anti-government sentiment that some analysts fear could lead to a
civil war or a coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now I've felt safe but I don't know about the future,''
said Rizo Gashi, 40, who came from Pec three weeks ago with his
86-year-old mother. He worries the war might spread here, or the
army might try the same kind of ``ethnic cleansing'' as in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't know,'' he said, ``what's going to happen to
Montenegro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
