<HEADER>
A4331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTHMA-HOMELESS-KIDS-     05-04 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-HOMELESS-KIDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTHMA FOUND IN 38 PERCENT OF CHILDREN IN NYC SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A study has found that at least 38 percent of
homeless children in the city's shelters have asthma, more than six
times the national rate and more than double the rate found by an
earlier study of some of the city's poorest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, only 9 percent of the asthmatic homeless children were
on proper medication, according to Dr. Diane McLean, the author of
the study and director of the childhood asthma initiative of the
Children's Health Fund. The results have been presented at
professional meetings over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of inadequate treatment, almost half the
children already found to have asthma had made at least one trip to
a hospital emergency room in the previous year because of the
disorder, an irritation of the lungs that, if improperly treated,
can cause chronic breathing impairment and even death.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Suzanne Hurd, director of the division of lung diseases at
the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, said that even though
poor children in big cities are disproportionately affected by
asthma, she found the ``terribly high rates'' the study documented
among homeless children surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's of great concern,'' Dr. Hurd said, calling the study's
indications of undertreatment particularly important. ``If these
children had good medical care and someone showing them how to use
their medication, they should do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on checks from July through September last
year of all 393 children who entered two New York City family
shelters, one in Queens and one in the Bronx. Because families all
over the city are randomly assigned to the shelters as space
becomes available, the researchers consider these children
representative of the 8,685 children in 4,900 families who are in
the city's shelter system in any given month.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that remain unclear to researchers, the prevalence
of asthma is rising worldwide. But the problem is most acute in
cities, where studies have found it to be aggravated by poverty _
exposure to factors like cockroach feces, dust mites, mold,
dampness, rat and mouse urine and crowded living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The last national survey, in 1996, reported that 6.3 percent of
children in the United States have asthma. A survey conducted that
year in association with a seven-city study by researchers at the
Albert Einstein College of Medicine put the highest childhood
asthma rate in poor sections of the Bronx at just under 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The highest asthma rate reported by any previous study in New
York City was the 21 to 23 percent found last year in three
elementary schools in the Hunts Point section of the Bronx in a
survey by the New York City Health Department, which is conducting
its own childhood asthma initiative, a program of citywide asthma
education and prevention. But asthma had already been diagnosed in
30 percent of the homeless children involved in Dr. McLean's study,
and 8 percent of the rest showed persistent, moderate to severe
symptoms of the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astounding,'' Dr. McLean said. ``Asthma really is an
indicator of what's happening to the health of homeless children
and their living conditions in the broadest sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayvon Brown, now 3, seems typical of the children seen in the
study. His mother, April Brown, 33, said the boy's asthma kept
flaring up last year as his family spent almost five months
shuttling between the Emergency Assistance Unit in the Bronx, the
central office where homeless families apply for emergency shelter,
and a 10-day temporary shelter in Jamaica, Queens, where the
family's eligibility was still under review. Ms. Brown said she
repeatedly took Clayvon to emergency rooms, in part because it was
too far to travel to the medical clinic where she had taken him and
his two brothers, 8 and 10, when she lived in her mother's
apartment in Far Rockaway, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   While many families are found eligible for shelter the first
time they apply, city data show that half those eventually approved
have had to apply an average of five times, under rules intended to
insure that only families truly in need of emergency shelter are
allowed into the system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Redlener, president of the Children's Hospital at
Montefiore Medical Center, said, ``We knew that the prevalence of
asthma had increased dramatically,'' he said, referring to national
studies that show a two-thirds increase in cases since 1980. ``But
even we who work with homeless children were taken aback by the
extent to which this vulnerable population was affected by this
debilitating, chronic disease.''
</P>
</TEXT>
