<SLUG> BC-GM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal between GM, AM General could bring jobs to midwest
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ AM General Corp., a maker of military vehicles,
is close to signing a deal with the General Motors Corp. to buy the
automaker's 6.5-liter diesel engine business in Moraine.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to GM told said the deal would create about 150
jobs once AM General takes control of the business, but the
agreement would not include the diesel engine plant. AM General,
headquartered in South Bend, Ind., will be forced to find an
existing site or build a plant for the diesel operation somewhere
in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 6.5-liter diesel business is on the sale block and we have
been negotiating with a company for some time,'' said Dan Greene,
spokesman for GM's Powertrain Division. ``We have been asked by the
company not to identify them publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig MacNab, spokesman for AM General, said the company would
not confirm or deny the deal with GM.
</P>
<P>
   AM General and GM have been doing business together in Moraine
for more than a decade. All of the military vehicles manufactured
by AM General, which include the commercial HUMVEE, military jeeps
and trucks, are equipped with GM's Moraine-based 6.5-liter diesel
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The Moraine diesel plant employs about 500 workers. But the
plant is expected to be shut down in about a year after GM and
Isuzu start building 6.6-liter diesel engines at a new $310 million
plant, also located in Moraine. About 300 workers are going to be
shifted to the new diesel plant and the other 200 were expected to
be phased out through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said GM approached AM General about taking over the
6.5-liter business because the automaker still needs the older
engine for some of its vans and pick-ups trucks. Once the deal is
approved, AM general is expected to use some of the current work
force from the diesel plant and possibly hire some additional
workers.
</P>
<P>
   AM General apparently doesn't want to buy the building as part
of the deal because of its large size and cost.
</P>
<P>
   The hourly work force at the diesel plant is represented by the
International Union of Electronic Workers, which represents about
13,000 autoworkers in the Dayton area. Sources close to the deal
said one reason AM General would keep the diesel operation in
Dayton is because the IUE is a ``cooperative'' work force that has
been willing to accept tiered-contracts that pay new workers about
$8 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   AM General operates an assembly plant in Mishawaka, Ind.,
located east of South Bend, that employs about 700 hourly workers
who are represented by the United Auto Workers Local 5. The sources
said AM General didn't want the deal to become public because its
UAW work force would be angered by the IUE's involvement in the new
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for both unions were unavailable for comment on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   AM General's roots trace back nearly a century when the company,
under a different name, made wagons and bicycles. But its identity
changed in 1972 when American Motors purchased it and the company
started making military vehicles. It landed the HUMVEE contract in
1983 and now sells the ultra-rugged vehicles for anywhere between
$60,000 and $100,000. The company has sold about 6,000 HUMVEE's
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   AM General has 1,200 total employees at its Mishawaka plant, its
headquarters and at an engineering plant in Michigan. The company
generated about $392 million in net sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
