<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKING-LAW DEBATE IS REVIVED IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Md.)  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate began debate Tuesday on a broad measure
to rewrite the nation's banking laws despite deep partisan
disagreements over both regulatory authority and existing
requirements that banks lend to members of minority groups and
others with little access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which Congress has spent the better part of 20
years struggling unsuccessfully to write, would be the first
comprehensive overhaul of the laws governing financial services
since the Depression. It would largely eliminate the barriers
between banks, insurance companies and securities brokers and allow
them to make more inroads into one another's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsed in principle by many powerful interests on Wall Street,
the legislation has nonetheless become bogged down in a regulatory
dispute between Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Alan Greenspan,
the chairman of the Federal Reserve, over who would oversee the
financial giants that would arise as a result of the new law. It
cleared the Senate banking committee two months ago on a party-line
vote of 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in the past, President Clinton again threatened to
veto the measure, which was brought to the floor by Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, chairman of the banking committee. At an afternoon
briefing to announce his endorsement of initiatives to protect the
financial and medical records of consumers, Clinton said the
legislation would undermine the Community Reinvestment Act, which
encourages banks to lend to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will oppose any effort to weaken or undermine the continued
relevance of the Community Reinvestment Act,'' the president said,
adding that while the law has been on the books for two decades,
``over 90 percent of the lending under it has occurred in the last
six years in our administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud of that,'' he said. ``It has not done anything
to hurt bank profits, and we ought to stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation tilts toward giving more authority to the
Federal Reserve, in contrast to legislation moving through the
House that provides for a sharing of authority between the Fed and
the Treasury. By exempting 4,000 smaller banks and savings
associations from the Community Reinvestment Act and proposing to
make it harder for community groups to challenge minority lending
practices, Gramm has provoked strong opposition from many Democrats
and from civil rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The groups held a rally Tuesday denouncing the legislation as an
enormous step backward.
</P>
<P>
   Still, lobbyists from the banking, securities and insurance
industries expressed some optimism that an agreement might
ultimately be reached to rewrite the old laws, principally the
Glass-Steagall Act of 1933.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the legislation, which affects three of the
nation's wealthiest industries, has become a vehicle for House and
Senate members to raise campaign money. As such, few are willing to
publicly write off the chances of final passage of a measure.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the legislation Tuesday, Gramm called it the ``most
important banking bill in 60 years.'' He dismissed criticism of the
legislation's provisions regarding the Community Reinvestment Act,
saying that he was simply trying to put a level of
``accountability'' into the law by making it harder for community
groups to challenge the lending records of banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If CRA exams have any integrity,'' Gramm said, ``a bank that
receives three satisfactory exams in a row should have a
presumption of innocence when someone challenges the bank's right
to open a new branch or merge with another bank. That's why this
legislation simply asks challengers to provide proof that a bank
isn't in compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who has in the past suggested he was amenable to watering
down the provisions of his legislation on the Community
Reinvestment Act, suggested Tuesday that he was not inclined to
make such changes. ``It is better to have no bill than to have a
bad bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., the ranking Democrat on the banking
committee, introduced a substitute bill Tuesday afternoon based
largely on a measure that had sailed through the committee last
year and was supported by most Democrats and Republicans. It was
forged by former Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York, who
headed the committee before his defeat last fall by Charles
Schumer. That legislation does not contain any provisions on the
Community Reinvestment Act and died last year largely after it was
opposed by Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we have a sharp contrast with last year's
bipartisan vote,'' Sarbanes said.
</P>
<P>
   The House is awaiting Senate action before deciding whether to
proceed with its own measure. That legislation, in contrast to the
Senate bill, has been supported by both senior Republicans and
Democrats on the House banking committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
