<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANNIE-REVIVAL-THEATER     05-04 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNIE-REVIVAL-THEATER-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREVER BEL IS THE CANTO, DATED OR NOT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9)
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note subslug for MUSICALS-MELODIES) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story creaks, the characters are stereotypes from another
time, the theatrical style doesn't work on modern audiences, but
oh, that music. It is as fresh as on the day it was born.
</P>
<P>
   Surely we're talking about ``La Sonnambula'' or one of its bel
canto opera pals, but what about ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' a musical
pulled forcibly from the past and now running strong at the Marquis
Theater on Broadway? Vincenzo Bellini and Irving Berlin have more
things in common than you think: not least, an infallible gift for
melody.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Bellini and Berlin were writing their immortal
tunes, they were also embedding them in a contemporary theater that
has proved anything but deathless. Take away the music, and ``La
Sonnambula'' (1831) is hopelessly silly. ``Annie Get Your Gun'' is
only 53 years old, but it is a revivalist's minefield.
</P>
<P>
   Much has happened since the 1946 original and its rebirth on
Broadway 20 years later. Stage techniques are slicker and attention
spans shorter. Political correctness has made its debut, with
antennas raised high in hopes of catching the racist or misogynist
red-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun'' occupied a more innocent and carefree
time, when the American Indian could be made fun of and a woman's
place was in the home. In 19th-century Italian opera, cursory
disguises baffled hero and villain alike, plot coherence was of low
priority, and melodrama inflated normal behavior to twice its
customary size.
</P>
<P>
   Bellini today has an advantage over Berlin. ``Annie Get Your
Gun'' must update or die; audiences will stand for nothing less,
and their money keeps it on stage. Most opera doesn't even try. The
medium has long since made the necessary pact with its audience:
you put up with bad theater, and we give you beautiful music. I
know of no other art where suspenders of disbelief work so hard.
</P>
<P>
   What were the poor revivers of ``Annie Get Your Gun'' supposed
to do? The American Indian jokes had to go, but the reverse spins
that replace them are so self-conscious and apologetic that their
sincerity is dubious. Feminist editors snipe around the edges of
Annie's capitulation to the man of her dreams, but without a woman
who will do anything for love, including the sublimation of her own
gifts, there is no show.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Annie'' puts new things around old ones and trusts in
Bernadette Peters, an Annie of uncommon appeal. It has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   All the threats that face new productions of old operas are
repeated here. How do you make the primitive plot and subplots of
boy-meets-loses-wins-girl acceptable? This production makes them a
show within a show. What we are seeing is secondhand, a historical
artifact: theater not as it is now but as Buffalo Bill Cody's Wild
West Show knew it a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   How do you keep things moving when Ms. Peters isn't singing?
Current audiences pay a lot of money for sex and velocity, so
rump-wiggling choristers, tight costumes and a frenetic
choreographic pace are inserted. What results is two shows playing
simultaneously and against each other.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 show is meant to carry the 1946 original into the
present, but it only widens the gap between the present and the
past. Glitz and speed surround a simpler and less hurried work.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Berlin's music is coming to the rescue. ``The
Girl That I Marry'' and ``They Say That Falling in Love Is
Wonderful'' make us forget the confusions of style, just as ``Ah!
non giunge'' momentarily dispels the silliness of ``La
Sonnambula.''
</P>
<P>
   When faced with outdated theater, bad opera directors descend
into ridicule. How many times have we struggled through a ``Magic
Flute'' forced to emulate the animated cartoon. Particularly
repugnant a few summers ago was Rossini's ``Comte Ory'' at the
Glimmerglass Opera in Cooperstown, N.Y.: a travesty of a travesty.
Younger Americans are usually responsible, directors whose
sensibilities are received from a childhood of Saturday-morning
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun'' has traces of self-parody, but then it
has so many other tendencies as well. It sidesteps the total
update: the wholesale translation of people, places and things to a
contemporary setting. Think of Peter Sellars staging ``The Rake's
Progress'' in a California prison, ``Don Giovanni'' in the ghetto
or ``The Marriage of Figaro'' in the Trump Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Sellars methodology can be striking, but finding
20th-century equivalents for an opera's every 18th-century word and
deed creates a far-fetchedness exceeding that of the originals.
``Annie Get Your Gun'' modernizes the harmonizations and
orchestrations of Berlin's music, something Sellars would never do.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Annie Get Your Gun'' falters because it has examined all
the ways of bringing a simpler show into a more complex world and
tried them all. Singly, it could have gone the early-music route by
precisely reconstructing the postwar musical.
</P>
<P>
   People try. ``As Thousands Cheer'' (also Irving Berlin) at the
tiny Greenwich Theater, not long ago, was a work of archeology if
not the embalmer's art, with every topical gag from 1933 in place.
The show attracted nostalgia-lovers, but the Marquis is a bigger,
more expensive place to fill.
</P>
<P>
   The best artistic solution may be to reduce staging or take it
away altogether. Les Arts Florissants from France and Yves Abel's
Opera Francais at Alice Tully Hall do it nicely, and the Opera
Orchestra of New York is performing ``La Sonnambula'' in concert on
Tuesday evening at Carnegie Hall. The listener's imagination
invents its own theater, much as enthusiastic audiences are doing
at the City Center's ``Encores'' series.
</P>
<P>
   But musicals in concert are hit-and-run: a few performances and
then gone. A Broadway ``Annie'' must be seen and heard, and it has
to last. Irving Berlin never stood a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2112EDT &QL; 
