<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4342 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GILBERTO-GIL-MUSIC-2T     05-04 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILBERTO-GIL-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIGINS OF A BRAZILIAN ORIGINAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gilberto Gil, like Caetano Veloso, Gal Costa and Carlinhos
Brown, comes from the Brazilian state of Bahia. If the
Brazilian-music fetishism of the moment centers too heavily on that
northern region (and especially on the late-60s Tropicalia
movement), it doesn't change the fact that ``Ensaio Geral,'' a
12-CD set of early work by Gil, from 1967 to 1977, is an
extraordinary document _ a tracking of a distinctly Bahian but also
fairly universal pop artist's growth and achievement. Taken as a
whole, the set is one of the best arguments there is for the notion
of world music.
</P>
<P>
   Gil himself has bristled at the idea of ``world music,''
comparing it to the old-fashioned model of colonialist
exploitation, the ``attitude of the adventurer, the guy who comes
in search of novelty ... and enters the jungle saying, `Where are
all the rare specimens?,''' as he put it in a 1992 interview.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the big recent hits of the world-music genre _ albums
like Cesaria Evora's ``Cabo Verde'' or ``Buena Vista Social Club''
_ Gil's music isn't quaint or nostalgic. A North American can't put
this music on and enter an idealized land of the Other; on the
contrary, he'll feel shocked at how much feels familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ensaio Geral'' (it means ``General Rehearsal'') is as good a
place as any to fall in love with Brazilian pop _ to hear samba,
marcha frevo, bossa nova, the slow Afro-Brazilian processional
rhythm called maracatu and the accordion-driven forro. But it's
also a place to hear these Brazilian sounds fused with psychedelia,
blues, free jazz and a kind of ecstatic folk-rock.
</P>
<P>
   The set captures a kinetic performer, often pouring out his
music in a jam session of one. His voice scats, shoots up into
falsettos and punctuates songs with cries, and his acoustic-guitar
style advances from standard bossa nova self-accompaniment to a
quick-reflex improvisatory style.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, some of his Anglophone counterparts of the same
period _ John Lennon's early solo records or those by the Who, Led
Zeppelin, Traffic or Bob Dylan _ display the self-conscious
composure of a model in a formal portrait.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Ensaio Geral'' (Universal Brazil; no catalog number), the
listener can take the measure of Gil as a performer, songwriter,
musician and, significantly, band leader: even the previously
released albums come with unreleased tracks, contributing to the
sense that you're fully understanding Gil during each of the four
periods represented here.
</P>
<P>
   The box opens with ``Louvacao,'' his 1967 debut album, recorded
before the dawn of the Tropicalia era. At the time, Gil was a
second-wave bossa nova singer whose lyrics were coded with
intimations of social redemption to come, when the country's
military regime might end.
</P>
<P>
   He was a romantic, in the popular mode of singers like Elis
Regina; the album's complex orchestrations and production, by Dori
Caymmi, are calibrated to prolong a mood of relaxed melancholy. But
the romanticism feels mediated by the fashion of bossa nova; you
don't quite know who Gil is.
</P>
<P>
   That posture toward him changes radically one year later, when
we enter the next period and find Gil in the thick of the
self-questioning, bricolage-happy Tropicalia movement, whose aim
was to shake up Brazilian popular music by conflating electric
guitars and folk forms of the outback.
</P>
<P>
   His self-titled album from 1968 bears the thumbprints of the
producer Rogerio Duprat and is backed by the rock band Os Mutantes.
Without carrying explicit messages about Brazilian politics, the
metaphors in the songs are suddenly stronger; he sings about
hunger, death, bombs.
</P>
<P>
   But luckily for non-Portuguese speakers, so many of the delights
here are musical. The album creates shocking superimpositions with
a purpose: blaring horn sections, suggesting television
advertisements, sitting on top of indigenous folk rhythms. It's a
brilliantly colorful, polyglot album, the closest pop music ever
came to the restless esthetic prowling of a Godard film.
</P>
<P>
   The messages don't have to be articulated in political rhetoric;
the signals are there in the music like raisins in a cake: it's a
record about a sad populace stuck between the archaic and the
modern. Satisfactorily remastered at last, it's one of the best
rock albums ever made, though Gil is so much more than a rock
musician that one might not consider characterizing it as such.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are moments when you're aware that English-speaking pop
rubbed off on Gil. Traces of the Beatles' ``Sergeant Pepper's
Lonely Hearts Club Band'' can be found in the tape-edited
interactions between orchestral music and rock on the 1968 album;
the lead guitar is pure Eric Clapton in ``Nega (Photograph
Blues),'' from Gil's self-titled 1971 English-speaking album (his
three-year political exile in London was his third period).
</P>
<P>
   But after his return to Brazil in 1972, which initiates the
fourth period, the rock influence ends, or becomes a good deal less
direct. The album ``Expresso 2222,'' from 1972, has all of the
delicious denouement-of-an-era moodiness that characterizes the
canon of early-70s rock music _ that of Sly and the Family Stone,
the Grateful Dead, the German art-rock group Can.
</P>
<P>
   But the album is also deeply Brazilian: it includes a track by a
folkloric flute group from the Northeastern interior of the country
and a remake of the 1959 Brazilian hit by Jackson do Pandeiro,
``Chiclete com Banana.'' In the proper context of this collection,
one can see that the music of the Tropicalia period has been a bit
overrated; it wasn't until the 1970s that the movement's main
creators came into their own.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Gil special is that as a Brazilian of mixed ancestry
and mixed cultural influence, he felt multiple citizenships and
used it. As a black pop artist in the 70s, he absorbed the music of
Stevie Wonder and Bob Marley; in his London sojourn, he became a
band leader, comfortable with the informality and adventurousness
of rock, and as a Bahian he had a natural understanding of
Afro-Brazilian culture.
</P>
<P>
   The result of this mixture, when you get to the full-band tracks
on the double-disk 1972 live album ``O Viramundo,'' is densely
rhythmic, well-organized music with strong melodies and a lot of
improvisation: like the Grateful Dead and the Allman Brothers in
their own ways, this is rock that comes close to achieving the
state of jazz.
</P>
<P>
   There is much of significance among the set's four disks of
unreleased material. They include two CDs worth of sessions that
were to go into a lost album, ``Cidade do Salvador,'' from 1974,
featuring the first-rate band Gil had assembled upon his return to
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   By this time Gil was a full-fledged experimental poet, playing
with sound-alike words to make their meanings blend and transform,
and the sound of the records indicate that he was listening to
Miles Davis' wildest studio experiments as well as to his
compatriot Milton Nascimento. ``O Viramundo,'' two disks of mostly
solo live acoustic performances that demonstrate Gil's facility at
meshing voice and guitar improvisation, is also unreleased, as is a
hippie-folk soundtrack to the 1970 film ``Copacabana Mon Amour''; a
fourth disk collects rarities from 1975 and 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The box set, which has been sold at around $250 when sighted in
this country (if record stores don't carry it, try
www.dustygroove.com) comprises only Gil's recordings for the
Philips label; it ends at 1977, when his interest in the black
diaspora was crystallizing. Many more significant albums were yet
to be recorded. But till now there has been no possibility in
America for a reasonable understanding of his work. ``Ensaio
Geral'' is a start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
