A4347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-SUED-COX     05-04 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-SUED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit claims governor's office held pollution-plan records
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An environmental group sued Gov. George W. Bush
on Tuesday, charging that his office violated the state's
open-records law by withholding documents concerning its role in
shaping a policy on industrial air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in state district court by the Sustainable
Energy and Economic Development Coalition, an Austin organization
that opposes the governor's plan to encourage but not require about
800 older industrial plants to reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Bush received a disappointing but expected
warning from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency on another
matter concerning air pollution. The agency, citing an inadequate
state plan to meet air-quality standards in the Dallas-Fort Worth
area, said in a letter to Bush that it would restrict the expansion
of business and industry and limit highway funding if the plan is
not improved.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for the governor, offered a cool
response to the suit: ``The governor's office has fully complied
with the law. And this is a frivolous lawsuit. And these publicity
stunts are becoming tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEED Coalition criticized Bush last week for accepting
presidential campaign contributions from supporters of voluntary
emissions reductions. In addition, several activists have been
arrested on the sidewalk and steps outside the Governor's Mansion
in recent weeks while protesting Bush's voluntary plan.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Bush from EPA Regional Administrator Gregg Cooke
marked the first time that the federal government has threatened
sanctions against Texas under the Clean Air Act. But Edwards said
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission is already
improving the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TNRCC has assured us they are working with local officials
and the EPA to develop a comprehensive plan to meet clean-air
standards,'' she said, adding that the revised plan would be filed
by March 2000, in time to avoid sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The suit accuses the governor's office of providing ``very
limited information'' concerning the policy on so-called
grandfathered plants. That is the term for plants that were
exempted from complying with newer anti-pollution rules when the
state enacted clean-air legislation in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Altman, director of the SEED Coalition, said he suspects
that the governor's office has many more records because John
Howard, natural resources and environmental director for the
office, participated in several meetings with state conservation
commission and industry officials. Altman said records obtained
from the state commission point to Howard's role. No environmental
or health groups were asked to participate in the meetings, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong is that a major public policy of critical
importance to the economy and health of Texas was developed in a
series of meetings between the governor's office and industry,''
Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the office has not withheld any documents. She said
it's routine for Howard and other officials in the office to attend
meetings involving state agencies and representatives of regulated
companies. The meetings on grandfathered emissions were ``very
preliminary'' fact-finding sessions, and environmentalists had
plenty of input during subsequent public meetings, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
