<SLUG> BC-BEBE-MILLER-DANCE-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMING AT THE AUDIENCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Valerie Gladstone is writing a book on the black tradition in
American dance, to be published next spring in conjunction with a
PBS series, ``Free to Dance.''  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It didn't look like a rehearsal. On the periphery of
a spacious studio on lower Broadway, a couple of dancers stood
close together as if in conversation. Several others mingled
casually in the center.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer Bebe Miller, wearing baggy black pants and a
simple black shirt, took a position in front of the wall-length
mirror. A compact woman with dreadlocks, she faced front, then
side, then back, and front again, allowing herself to be
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Over a tape recording came her mellow voice. ``Who is looking
for gay men in the group?'' The questions are aimed at her
audiences. ``Who is counting the white people?'' ``How important is
it that these dancers work for a black choreographer?''
</P>
<P>
   The dancers remained lost in their own worlds until a gentle rap
by the Fugees started up. They then fell into loose, silky
movements. ``This section represents a party,'' Ms. Miller reminded
them. ``Don't be so serious.''
</P>
<P>
   But this 60-minute piece, ``Going to the Wall,'' which had its
premiere at Dartmouth College last year, is very serious. It will
be seen for the first time in New York on Tuesday at the Joyce
Theater, when the company begins a weeklong engagement, its first
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the program is her new solo for herself, performed to
the live music of the three-piece Harriet Tubman Group.
</P>
<P>
   As the rehearsal progressed, the troupe's eight members picked
up the action. Frances Craig leaped into a group of men only to
find herself attacked. She screamed yet jumped back into their
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sarah Gamblin grooved with Anthony Phillips,
indifferent to the violence close at hand. Was their detachment a
metaphor for the human condition? The funky sounds rounded out into
something smoother.
</P>
<P>
   As is her custom, Ms. Miller chose several different elements
for accompaniment. With a text based on her own meditations on
life, she combined a commissioned score by the jazz clarinetist Don
Byron, song-poems by Sadiq and music by the Fugees and another
popular rap group, Nonchalant.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Talvin Wilks acted as Ms. Miller's dramatist.
``These are dialogues in the flesh,'' her taped voice continued
during a pause in the music. ``They give hints of how we make our
way in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Ms. Miller has explored the human condition in
dance for more than 25 years. A native New Yorker, she first took
classes as a child at the Henry Street Settlement, where the
choreographer Murray Louis introduced her to the abstract
vocabulary of his partner, Alwin Nikolais.
</P>
<P>
   Everything went smoothly until she tried ballet at 13. Feeling
out of place, she quit dance. At Ohio State University, where she
received her MA in 1975, a master class given by Merce Cunningham
lured her back. In 1985, she formed her own company. The fiery,
abstract piece ``The Hendrix Project'' (1991), to music by Jimi
Hendrix, and the poignant narrative ``Tiny Sisters'' (1994), about
two silent sisters and their secret language, indicate her range
and her depth.
</P>
<P>
   ```Going to the Wall,' deals with the question of identity and
race,'' said Ms. Miller. ``After several workshops on these issues
on tour, I learned that no matter how much you might want to, you
can't step into someone else's shoes. I had to figure out how to
arrange dancers in space to get that point across. I had to craft
that isolation and chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Her choreography relies heavily on improvisation and
collaboration. Both attracted Ms. Craig to the company six years
ago. ``Bebe ventures into new territory, using techniques more
common in theater,'' she said. ``It makes her movement very
charged, very intense. No matter where we perform this piece,
people say that by the end we are revealed, and so are they to
themselves. That's what she's after.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
