<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDUFFIE-MUSIC-$ADV09     05-04 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDUFFIE-MUSIC-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNHURRIED JOURNEY TO THE TOP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of musicians these days are already starting international
careers before they have completed the early stages of professional
development, so that they find themselves putting their clothes on
in public.
</P>
<P>
   Into such a world suddenly comes Robert McDuffie, a violinist
fully and impeccably dressed, ready to make his New York
Philharmonic debut on Thursday evening at Avery Fisher Hall after
nearly two decades of giving concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Experience tells. McDuffie, at 40, is a musician with his own
voice: not just the engaging, cozy drawl that has been with him
since his early days in Macon, Ga., but the fine sound he makes
with his instrument.
</P>
<P>
   In that sound you seem to meet the man: his charm, his courtesy,
his openness and enthusiasm with regard to people and to life. It
is a singing sound, sweet or airy but always vividly present, and
always with beautiful intonation.
</P>
<P>
   It is, he says, impossible for string players always to play in
tune. The important thing is to seem to: to make the imprecision
work. ``One thing I learned from Dorothy DeLay at the Juilliard
School,'' he explained, ``is the difference between expressive
intonation and out-of-tune playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the things that please him most now _ a mark of his
modesty _ is when he gets congratulated on his intonation by a
fellow musician among the players in an orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Miss DeLay looks back with affection on the lessons she gave
him. ``I liked him enormously,'' she said. ``He was obviously very
gifted, and he had a tremendous sense of humor.'' She has also
followed his career, hearing him two or three times a year in New
York, where he now lives, or at the Aspen Music Festival in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   She is not surprised by the success he is having now or by its
slow arrival. ``An awful lot depends on how managements decide to
handle a young person,'' she said, ``whether to push them forward
at once, or allow them to do a lot of concerts at a level of more
comfort, which gives them a chance to develop. Robert, I find, is
developing all the time. Every time I hear him, he's better. He's
grown. The interpretation has more depth, more ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does McDuffie himself seem bothered by having had a long
apprenticeship. ``I was having a wonderful time, traveling,
learning great music,'' he said. ``I kind of knew it was going to
happen some day.''
</P>
<P>
   Time out of the limelight gave him an opportunity to explore the
repertory, and to establish preferences and loves that are
reflected in the recordings he has recently been making for Telarc.
He is superb in the lyrical concertos of Mendelssohn and Bruch. He
plays Viennese schmaltz with huge appeal. And he makes a strong
case for American music of widely different kinds, across the
spectrum from the craggy to the blithe.
</P>
<P>
   He will be at the blithe end with the Philharmonic this week,
for the work is Lou Harrison's Suite for Violin, Piano and Small
Orchestra, of 1951, with Christopher Taylor as pianist and Franz
Welser-Most conducting. But his recital repertory includes Elliott
Carter's ``Riconoscenza,'' and he has recorded the concertos of
Samuel Barber, John Adams and Philip Glass.
</P>
<P>
   His first recording was of Leonard Bernstein's ``Serenade'' and
William Schuman's Concerto: a lonely release from more than 10
years ago, when both composers were alive to be consulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy meeting the composer and having an exchange of
ideas,'' McDuffie said. ``There's more freedom than when you're
performing ultra-familiar music. You can bring more to the piece.
And I think that playing these modern works has made me play
Mendelssohn better.''
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie's next recording project is a disk of music by Miklos
Rozsa, including the Concerto and the Theme and Variations for
Violin, Cello and Orchestra, with Lynn Harrell as cellist, and Yoel
Levi conducting the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra. This music takes
him back to his childhood; the teacher whom his mother, herself an
active musician, found for him in Macon was a Hungarian, Henrik
Schwarzenberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I came back from my first music camp, at the
age of 12 or 13, and Schwarzenberger wanted to see what they'd
written about me,'' McDuffie said. `` `Plays like a Gypsy,' he read
out. `I don't know whether that's good or bad.''' (The answer is,
good _ if the Gypsy forwardness comes with McDuffie's style of
tonal perfection.)
</P>
<P>
   A year or two later, Itzhak Perlman visited Macon, and though
the young McDuffie had to be dragged away from a basketball game to
the recital, when he got back home, he instantly started
practicing. Another couple of years after that, at 16, he was ready
to attend the Juilliard precollege division. And there, hearing a
student play the Sibelius Concerto, he recognized what he wanted
his life to be.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has it. Or at least, he is embarked on it, for he shows
no sign of self-satisfaction, and the best may be yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   He tries to speak honestly, without false modesty, of the
experience he had performing and recording Adams' Concerto in
Houston with Christoph Eschenbach, a conductor with whom he loves
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a kid in a candy store,'' McDuffie said, ``adoring
his job and willing to learn from anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Then quietly comes the memory of what he began to sense in
himself: ``Playing the Adams, I felt for the first time that I was
flirting with greatness. I felt that I could, in a benign and
musical way, manipulate everyone around me: the orchestra and the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Given McDuffie's character, that moment will act as a spur. And
given his musicianship, there will be many more of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
