<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEVITT OF SEC CRITICIZES ADS FOR ONLINE INVESTING
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, criticized brokerage industry advertisements focusing
on the get-rich aspect of on-line investing, contending they were
doing more harm than good for both Wall Street and the public.
Levitt also admonished individual investors to better educate
themselves about on-line trading. But he called on brokerage firms
to strengthen their disclosure of the risks of trading stocks over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURY BOND PRICES DROP SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices dropped sharply, pushing long-term interest rates to
their highest level in nine months. The yield of the benchmark
30-year Treasury jumped to 5.71 percent. Investors are losing the
conviction that the United States economy will slow this year, with
inflation remaining in check; instead, a growing number worry that
a rebound in the rest of the world will keep growth strong here and
nudge inflation higher.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS FALL; DOW DOWN 129 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks tumbled, sending the Dow Jones industrial average down
128.58 points, or 1.17 percent, to 10,886.11. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 50.46 points, or 2 percent, to 2,485.12. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index declined 22.63 points, or 1.7 percent, to
1,332.00.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Goldman Sachs Group, Wall Street's last big private
partnership, soared on their first day of trading, rising $17.375,
or 32 percent, to $70.375.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER GASOLINE PRICES FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the key summer driving season, gasoline prices are
up sharply from historically low levels, a result of cuts by major
oil producing countries. Now, citing tight American supplies of
gasoline, experts foresee still higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   CBS PUTS PRESSURE ON MORNING TV
</P>
<P>
   CBS's decision to bring Bryant Gumbel back to morning television
raises the ante in the competition among network morning programs,
an area gaining more attention from network executives because it
offers far more potential for increased profits than prime time or
any other hour of the day. With Gumbel, a new program and new
studio, to be built in one of the most visible sites in Manhattan,
CBS is making a commitment to compete head to head with NBC's
``Today'' show, by far the dominant show in the morning with Katie
Couric and Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCE FORMED WITH SHEEP CLONER
</P>
<P>
   Geron, a leader in what has been called regenerative medicine,
said it was forming a $20 million alliance with the Roslin
Institute of Scotland, which cloned Dolly the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO SALES ROSE 3.9 PERCENT IN APRIL
</P>
<P>
   Auto sales climbed 3.9 percent in April despite
lower-than-expected results at GM.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE DEBATES BANKING LEGISLATION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate began debating a broad measure to rewrite the
nation's banking laws despite deep partisan disagreements over both
regulatory authority and existing requirements that banks lend to
members of minority groups and others with little access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   EISNER TESTIFIES IN KATZENBERG SUIT
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Walt Disney, Michael Eisner, testifying for the
first time in the lawsuit by his former studio chief, Jeffrey
Katzenberg, disputed Katzenberg's contention that Disney owes him
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A KEY EASTMAN KODAK OFFICIAL DIES
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak's chief financial officer, Harry Kavetas, who was
an architect of the company's revival, died.
</P>
</TEXT>
