A4359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-EXPANSION-COX     05-04 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EXPANSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nashville expected to land Dell campus
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. is expected to announce on
Thursday that Nashville, Tenn., will be the home of a major
regional campus for sales, service and computer assembly and its
first U.S. expansion outside the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement in Tennessee's State Capitol will end weeks of
intense competition and speculation in the Nashville area over
which of several sites in two or three counties will get the boost
in sales and property taxes and bragging rights for thousands of
jobs. Dell disclosed April 1 that it had chosen the Nashville area
for the expansion but had not settled on a specific site.
</P>
<P>
   Dell spokesman Peter Scacco declined Tuesday to confirm that
Nashville and Davidson County had beaten out Rutherford and other
nearby counties. But a news conference advisory sent to area news
media said Nashville Mayor Phil Bredesen will join Gov. Don
Sundquist and Dell officials for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Vice Chairman Kevin Rollins is expected to make the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our fervent prayer,'' said Mark Drury, Bredesen's press
secretary, when asked whether Nashville landed Dell and an
estimated 3,000 jobs within five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conceivable, if Dell maintains the growth rate it has
experienced, that we could be looking at 10,000 jobs in several
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell employs nearly 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's imminent arrival in central Tennessee touched off intense
local speculation about the site and incentives that the competing
cities and counties were offering the Round Rock-based company. Two
weeks ago, historical preservationists urged Dell not to build on
private land in Rutherford County, where a Civil War battle was
fought in December 1862.
</P>
<P>
   Dell did not confirm that the site was a serious contender. But
until then, many in the Nashville area assumed Rutherford County
was leading the charge for Dell's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, Bredesen said he and Dell reached an
informal agreement to locate the expansion in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Bredesen also said that in addition to property-tax breaks and
free land, Nashville hoped to give Dell some of the sales taxes the
company collected on Tennessee PC sales, which is similar to a deal
that Round Rock lured Dell with in 1993. But a state official tried
to quash that speculation, noting that sharing sales tax with
private companies is illegal in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Scacco said Tuesday that public discussion in Tennessee about
incentives has been ``highly speculative'' and ``not necessarily
what Dell has been requesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
