<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-HOSPITALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL EMERGENCY WORKERS DEAL WITH THE CARNAGE FROM DEVASTATING
STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ The first three tornado victims to arrive
at Midwest Regional Medical Center Monday afternoon were siblings,
all younger than 5. They were all in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Owen, a physician's assistant, jumped into action. One
child had an open skull fracture. Another was bleeding from a head
injury. The third had a piece of plywood lodged in his back, less
than an inch from his spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I heard this voice say, `Bret, save my babies,''' Owen
recalled, choking back tears. ``I looked up and it was a man from
my church. I've worked on his children several times before. ...
They weren't recognizable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Owen, like other hospital employees across the greater
Oklahoma City area, had to push aside personal feelings and keep
working.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens more were arriving for medical help.
</P>
<P>
   Some would be their neighbors. Some were friends. A nurse,
working around the clock, had a 4-month-old niece killed in the
tornado's path and another relative injured and admitted to the
hospital. The nurse didn't learn the news until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Many had no clue how their own families fared in the deadly
storm. As many as 14 Midwest Regional workers were left homeless _
their homes gobbled up in the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You totally wipe all of those thoughts from your mind and you
worry about the here and now,'' said Rosemarie Shepherd, head
emergency room nurse. ``We see the horror first-hand. ... You've
just got to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   As the storm passed Monday, 110 victims made it Midwest
Regional. Many found their own way because paramedics were unable
to reach them. Others managed to wave down help from passing
emergency officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 30 minutes we were almost overwhelmed,'' said Dr. Dan
Donnell, medical director of the emergency department. ``Then it
became a matter of deciding which patient needed to go to the
emergency room first.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Hefton, a hospital spokeswoman, said that as of 4 p.m.
Tuesday, the hospital treated 114 tornado victims. Twenty-one were
admitted. Four remained in critical condition and three were listed
as serious.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state, 541 victims were treated at hospitals by
midafternoon Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Donnell said one person he was working on died on the operating
table. Another man died before he could get to surgery, his leg
severed and a piece of wood wedged deep into his head.
</P>
<P>
   He said the toughest part of his job is assessing each case and
deciding ``who's salvageable and who isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people looked like someone had a sandblaster
held in front of them,'' Donnell said. ``Almost everyone I saw had
foreign bodies embedded. Some of them had their clothes blown off
them and their underwear shredded.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the hospital got so crowded that ambulances were
diverted.
</P>
<P>
   Donnell said Monday's catastrophe was worse than the Oklahoma
City bombing four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for 20 years and to me this is worst than
the bombing,'' Donnell said. ``It affects more people I know and
entire communities. The recovering is going to take much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
