<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-SHELTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY HOMELESS MEN FIND SHELTER AT CHURCH, VERY LITTLE AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER AUTREY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ Shelter workers had mattresses spread on the
lobby floor and in the fellowship hall at First Southern Baptist
Church, but frayed nerves kept the two men from sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Left homeless by Monday's storm, the men declined food and
coffee, too. Almost anything beyond conversation seemed frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ruhman and Dan Tillotson lived around the corner from each
other in a subdivision in southeast Oklahoma City called Frolich
Meadows. They didn't know each other beyond an occasional
``Howdy.''
</P>
<P>
   A tornado buried each man in his home in a blitz of shattering
glass, ricocheting bricks and collapsing shingles. At the shelter,
they felt the need to stick close to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Like many left without shelter, Ruhman and Tillotson took refuge
at the church. They speculated on what they would find when they
returned to Frolich Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going back to try to dig out, try to find my money,'' said
Ruhman, 71, a professional bowler who has maintained his athletic
physique even though he now limits himself to seniors competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen my dune buggy, and I know my dachshund was all
right because I saw him when it first happened _ but when I went
back, he was gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tillotson nodded in agreement in the reddish-glow of oil lamps
and candles used by the shelter, which hadn't enough generators for
electric light. Flashlights popped off and on as nurses recorded
blood pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Digging out valuables was too strenuous a goal for Tillotson.
Just finding his medicine would be enough. Although he said he
feels strong for 74, the 30 staples in his knee from the
replacement surgery he had three weeks ago have slowed him. He was
also tired. His next-door neighbors, the LeClaires, had dug him out
from his collapsed roof Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Their hopes Tuesday of getting to the houses quickly dimmed
early in the day when a torrential downpour opened from a sky so
black it seemed more like 10 in the evening than 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everything that wasn't ruined will be soaked,'' Ruhman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sun began to peer out mercifully about noon, and Ruhman and
Tillotson bummed a ride, grateful to get away from the bustling
shelter for a while. National Guardsmen turned them away at seven
checkpoints before they found a sympathetic one who allowed them
into the cordoned area the police had set up for the most damaged
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The devastation in the midday sun looked worse than they
expected. Ruhman arrived to see his neighbor across the street,
Jake Self, removed in a body bag. Ruhman had tried to dig Self out
Monday night, but was unable to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   Some houses on Tillotson's street still had partial walls
intact. On Ruhman's street, it looked as if nothing but a scrap
yard had ever been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? I was just ready to apply for a home
improvement loan on that house,'' Tillotson said. He mentioned the
loan several times as if it were the timing of the tragedy that was
annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Tillotson recruited neighbors to help get his medicine and his
briefcase and decided to return to the shelter. There was nothing
left to claim.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhman, on the other hand, declared he would work long into the
night. He wanted to clear up the mess and to be there when _ if _
his dog came home. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
