<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT &LR;      05-04 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CALLED CLOSER TO GAINING RUSSIAN SUPPORT ON KOSOVO PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-GORE) 
(bl) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials said Tuesday that
they believe they have persuaded the Russian envoy to the Balkans
that a military force, rather than just a monitoring mission, would
be needed in Kosovo after the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The White House outlined some details of the talks that the
envoy, Victor Chernomyrdin, held Monday with President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore. Chernomyrdin continued his diplomatic
efforts Tuesday at the United Nations, where he met with
Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   While the officials stressed that Chernomyrdin had not formally
accepted the idea of a military force in Kosovo, they said he
seemed to understand that an armed contingent was necessary to
allow the return of more than 600,000 Kosovo Albanian refugees. The
Russians have always agreed with the United States that the
refugees should return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   During the more than five hours of talks, Chernomyrdin was also
told that an international force, with NATO at its core, would be
the most forceful way to prevent a potential civil conflict between
the returning armed refugees and remnants of Yugoslav forces, the
officials said. NATO leaders have worried that without military
protection, clashes between Albanian rebels and the Yugoslav
military could erupt into a civil war that would imperil the masses
of returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   By the conclusion of the talks, which ended around the dining
room table at Gore's residence Tuesday morning, Chernomyrdin was
discussing the possibility of a military force. One official who
was briefed on the discussions said this was taken as a
``significant'' step.
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, after meeting with Annan in New York,
Chernomyrdin spoke more positively than he has in the past about an
international security force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it would be paramilitary, military or civil forces _
of course it's subject to negotiations,'' he said. ``There must be
political will, both in Belgrade and NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the discussions at such a high level _ 90
minutes with Clinton, followed by lengthier discussions with Gore _
signaled a commitment by the White House to push aggressively for a
way to get the United States out of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, the Senate dodged a vote on NATO's battle in
the Balkans by voting 78-22 on Tuesday to kill a measure pushing
Clinton to escalate the war. The resolution's sponsor, Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., is running for president and all but called
Clinton a coward from the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is prepared to lose a war
rather than to do the hard work, the politically risky work, of
fighting it as the leader of the greatest nation on earth should
fight when our interests and values are imperiled,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly ruled out the use of ground troops, and
in recent weeks has wooed the Russians to be the primary
intermediary for a diplomatic solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As the president left late Tuesday afternoon for a visit to NATO
headquarters in Brussels and then U.S. troops in Germany, he
emphasized the importance of diplomacy and Chernomyrdin's efforts
in ending the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reaffirmed our support for his efforts and our willingness
to seize every diplomatic possibility for Serbian authorities to
meet the requirements that NATO has articulated,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president added that an international security force with
NATO would give an incentive to the Albanian guerrillas in the
Kosovo Liberation Army to disarm and would also help protect Serbs,
who make up a minority of the Kosovo population. Both these points
have special appeal to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials who were briefed on Chernomyrdin's
comments in the meetings with Gore, said that the Russian envoy
insisted that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had become more
flexible on the question of withdrawal of his forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO now estimates that the Yugoslav forces number about 40,000
in Kosovo, and the Yugoslav leader is talking about reducing his
forces there to 1998 levels, the officials said Chernomyrdin told
them. But that reduction _ interpreted by the administration to
mean maintaining a Yugoslav force of 20,000 troops _ would be
totally unacceptable to NATO, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo was a main element
of a sequence of events that the White House told Chernomyrdin must
occur for the conflict to end, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration still wants Milosevic to begin the drawdown
of his forces in Kosovo and make a commitment to a complete
withdrawal before NATO would suspend its bombing campaign, the
officials said. But bombing would resume, the officials warned
Chernomyrdin, if the commitment to withdraw the Yugoslav forces was
not kept, an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the forces had withdrawn, an international security force _
still described as one with NATO troops at the core _ would
``quickly'' enter Kosovo. ``This has to happen before the refugees
come in,'' the official said the Russian was told.
</P>
<P>
   This sequence _ Serbian forces out and international force in _
was essential in order to prevent a ``worst case'' scenario of
armed Albanian refugees and their guerrilla supporters returning to
Kosovo while Serbian forces were still there.
</P>
<P>
   They would certainly fight each other, meaning that a light
peacekeeping force, the type suggested by Milosevic, would be
caught in the middle, Chernomyrdin was told, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
