<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAYER-DAY-PROFILE-CO     05-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYER-DAY-PROFILE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prayer celebration volunteer hitting high notes
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At 10 p.m., Evelyn Davison of Leander _ a
mother, grandmother and prayer parent _ took to the lectern on the
West Mall at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, God created heaven and Earth,'' she began,
kicking off the Bible reading marathon that began Sunday as part of
the National Day of Prayer celebration.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 readers, working in shifts, are participating in
the event at UT. They expect to finish by 7 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second year the Bible-reading marathon has ushered in
the National Day of Prayer, recognized by federal law on the first
Thursday in May.
</P>
<P>
   For 13 years, Davison has volunteered to be the Central Texas
coordinator for the annual prayer day. It's no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be 300 events in the Austin area,'' she
said. ``It's to call people of faith to prayer that they might pray
in a matter that's comfortable for them for our nation and our
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Davison prays for one leader every day: Gov. George W. Bush. The
first year Bush was in office, she adopted him as part of a prayer
day program that matches regular folks with politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As his prayer parent, her job is to keep an eye on the potential
presidential candidate, making sure he stays in line with biblical
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to pray for him faithfully and when he is in
error, according to the will of God ... to tell him,'' Davison
said. ``I just write and talk to one of his aides.''
</P>
<P>
   She usually pens words of encouragement; only once has she
criticized the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen his picture when he runs in the Capitol
10,000? Those shorts he wears are awful,'' Davison said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bush said: ``I believe in the power of prayer and
I appreciate those, including Evelyn Davison, who celebrate the
importance of prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, after the prayer breakfast that this Thursday morning
will be in Austin's City Coliseum, Davison and local religious
leaders meet with the governor. She usually brings him an
inspirational book and a National Day of Prayer shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Davison said she never dreamed, initially, that the man she was
praying for might run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he had those aspirations,'' she said. ``I just
pray he will do what he says he will do and what is best for his
family and what's best for the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Davison is a familiar face in Christian circles. She is the
publisher and primary owner of the Good News Journal, a monthly
tabloid newspaper that offers inspiration and encouragement to
families. Each Saturday at noon, she hosts the show ``Love Walk''
on gospel station KFIT 1060 AM.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be around Evelyn long without understanding the
profound impact that she has on the Austin community through her
personal prayer life,'' said Greg Davidson, Bush's deputy
legislative director. ``She lives her life as she proclaims it,
daily in prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said it was prayer that brought the two of them
together. He was wondering why there wasn't a prayer day event at
the Capitol, and she was praying that someone would step forward to
coordinate one.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson called the prayer day information number. ``Little did
I know that my call was an answer to her prayer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of her qualities, Davidson said, is how how much she can
accomplish in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is definitely focused and has a great ability to get a lot
of things done simultaneously,'' said Amy Budwit, who coordinated
the Bible reading marathon. ``I just respect the fact she has so
much energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Budwit, a process engineer at Samsung, launched the Bible
reading concept last year. Bible reading marathons have sprung up
across the nation ever since President George Bush's 1990
proclamation that named this the decade of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Davison, who spent late hours reading the Bible at UT, said it
is important for students to hear God's word, even at unusual
hours. ``Probably the biggest crowds we have are at 2 o'clock in
the morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sue Lia Perkes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
