<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NUKE-NYT &LR;      05-04 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL MONITORING OF YUGOSLAVIA'S ENRICHED URANIUM TO
RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ International nuclear inspectors have decided
to return to Yugoslavia to inspect the nuclear reactor at Vinca and
to insure that all its highly enriched uranium is still in place,
inspectors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   David Kyd, a spokesman for the Vienna-based International Atomic
Energy Agency, said the agency had decided to return despite the
danger after receiving a letter from the government in Belgrade on
April 26 urging a resumption of inspections ``as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they expect an inspection to take place in
the middle of May. The officials and nuclear experts previously
expressed concern that Yugoslavia, if pushed to the wall, might
seize the fissionable material to embark on a nuclear weapons
program, sell it to a rogue state or terrorist group or use it as a
bargaining chip.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter, Yugoslavia said an inspection would be useful in
allaying such concerns and convincing skeptics ``that the nuclear
materials are in the same condition, in the same place, and in
unchanged quantities.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes as Russia has privately expressed concern
about the risk to the region if the Vinca Institute of Nuclear
Science, less than 30 miles from Belgrade, were bombed by NATO,
whether intentionally or by mistake. Russia raised the issue in a
letter last week from Russian Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeny Adamov
to U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, said Clinton
administration officials. An official said that Richardson was
still drafting a response. A senior administration official said
that the United States welcomed the agency's decision to return to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   David Albright, president of the Institute for Science and
International Security, an arms control research group in
Washington, said that whatever the inspection's outcome, ``the IAEA
has established an important precedent: verifying the peaceful use
of nuclear material is important enough to the international
community to justify the risk that such a mission entails.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency has not conducted its usual monthly inspections since
late January. Kyd said that the agency was planning to send two
inspectors into Yugoslavia as soon as safe passage could be
assured.
</P>
<P>
   IAEA officials previously said there was no evidence that
Yugoslavia was preparing to abandon its longstanding renunciation
of nuclear weapons. Nor were there signs, they said, that elements
within the military were diverting the uranium at Vinca or taking
other steps that would suggest an intention to use the material to
develop a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said there was enough material at Vinca to make two
nuclear weapons of an implosion-type design, which Iraq is said to
be pursuing, or one bomb of a ``gun type'' design, which South
Africa had made. The large nuclear reactor at Vinca has been closed
since 1984, he said. A smaller research reactor was operating at
least until 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Most officials and nuclear experts have been more concerned
about Vinca's inadequate protection and its relatively poor history
of handling radioactive material. Albright said that although the
IAEA had improved security at the facility several years ago and
Russia had helped Vinca improve its handling of the nuclear waste
produced by its nuclear reactors, there were still safety concerns
about the 5,000 spent fuel rods that are stored in some 30 aluminum
casks in a pool of water.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials have said that Vinca is not on
the list of NATO targets, there is growing concern about potential
damage to the people of the surrounding area and the environment if
it were hit by accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
