<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREE-SEASONS-FILM-2T     05-04 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREE-SEASONS-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARING LOTUS BLOSSOMS AND HOPE, NOT GUNS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (af) 
 Laura Winters' most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the director Wes Anderson  
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 2, Tony Bui escaped Vietnam with his family after the
1975 fall of Saigon. Growing up in Sunnyvale, Calif., as one of the
few Vietnamese in his community, he was intent on assimilation.
``My brother and sister and I didn't spend much time trying to
learn our culture,'' Bui said. ``Vietnam, to me, was a past-tense
word.''
</P>
<P>
   His father had been an officer in the South Vietnamese Air
Force; his mother came from a family of Vietnamese artists. On his
first trip back to his birthplace, Bui (pronounced like buoy), then
19, stayed with his uncle, one of the country's best-known film
actors. He hated the heat and the lack of amenities, but when he
came home he sank into a depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't understand this deep longing,'' he said during a
recent trip to New York, at the Algonquin Hotel. ``Everything I
thought about took me back to Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   On school breaks from his studies at Loyola Marymount University
in Los Angeles, Bui made several trips to Vietnam. What he saw
there was radically different from the images he had seen in
American films, which showed a country of ``people running around
in the jungle, guns in their hands,'' as he described it.
</P>
<P>
   Bui's visits led to his first short film, ``Yellow Lotus,'' and
then to ``Three Seasons,'' which opened in New York on April 30 and
nationwide on Friday. It is the first American feature film to
attempt a portrait of contemporary postwar Vietnam, poised on the
brink of modernity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons,'' which landed a major American star, Harvey
Keitel (who has been known to be partial to small, independent
films), is an interweaving of three stories and operates on several
narrative levels: past and present, personal and national,
realistic and poetic.
</P>
<P>
   The characters (``people who are all trying to find something,''
Bui says) are caught in the clash between old and new within Ho Chi
Minh City. One story is about a young lotus-blossom picker and the
ailing, reclusive poet she works for. Another is about a cyclo
(rickshaw) driver's love for a young prostitute. The third is about
an encounter between a street urchin and an American ex-marine who
is searching for the daughter he left behind. That is the closest
the film comes to a war-related story line.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his desire to debunk cliches about Vietnam, Bui, who
is 26 and wears his long black hair in a ponytail, is serious and
soft-spoken. ``The Vietnam that I saw is a country where more than
half of the population wasn't born yet when the war ended,'' he
says. ``I saw people filled with hopes and ambitions and
frustrations. But their entire attitude is about moving forward and
reaching out. I wanted to show this humanity, this side which no
one knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the film won three awards at the Sundance Film
Festival, including the grand jury prize for best dramatic feature.
Even critics who have found it sentimental have praised its visual
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Bui's choice of a lyrical tone is intentional, however, as is
his adoption of a poetic, rather than a political, approach. His
film carves out its own territory alongside other film treatments
of Vietnam: American views of the war, films of the
French-Vietnamese artist Tran Anh Hung, and the melodramatic
tradition of film within Vietnam itself.
</P>
<P>
   At the time that Bui shot ``Yellow Lotus,'' only a few French
productions (``The Lover,'' ``Indochine'') had filmed in Vietnam.
The crop of American films about the war had all been shot
elsewhere. But by 1995, with the establishment of diplomatic
relations with Vietnam, filming there became possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bui's entree to shoot in Vietnam came about through an
accidental meeting between his mother, Susie Truong Bui, and the
head of the Giai Phong Film Studio, one of Vietnam's two largest
state-run film companies. He also had a trump card in that his
uncle the actor Don Duong agreed to star in both ``Yellow Lotus''
and ``Three Seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bui attended the Sundance Filmmakers and Screenwriters Lab
in 1996, he had four goals for the feature he was planning. ``One,
to shoot entirely in Vietnam,'' he said. ``Two, to use Vietnamese
actors. Three, to have real Vietnamese dialogue. Four, to have the
film not be about the war or politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The characters in ``Three Seasons'' are all based on people and
situations that Bui had seen during his trips to Ho Chi Minh City
(still called Saigon locally and in the film).
</P>
<P>
   The characters' stories captivated Jason Kliot and Joana
Vicente, of the New York production company Open City Films, who
met Bui at the Sundance Independent Producers Conference and who
signed on as his producers. They eventually persuaded October Films
to finance the project and Keitel to play the former marine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read Tony's script I was aware _ not unlike when I read
`Reservoir Dogs' _ of a voice I hadn't heard before,`` Keitel said
in a telephone interview from Italy, where he is shooting a new
film. ``It's a poetic and touching voice. Once upon a time, our
politicians visited Vietnam and there was a war. But this young man
is talking about the internal war that we all wage with ourselves:
trying to find a life, a love, to take care of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shooting in Vietnam, with its lack of basic supplies, was a
challenge, especially on a budget of only $2 million or so. Perhaps
the most delicate situation, however, was the relationship between
the filmmakers and the censors.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese practice requires that a censor be on the set
throughout the shoot, and if he objects to something political or
sexual or even symbolic, the issue has to be discussed until both
sides reach a resolution or compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Communist government allowed a film to be made
that touched on sensitive issues like prostitution and destitute
street children. It no doubt helps that ``Three Seasons'' is
resolutely nonpolitical in nature and celebrates the spirit of the
Vietnamese people rather than taking a critical stance.
</P>
<P>
   When Bui showed the film to a group of government officials and
artists after completion, the response was positive, he said, and
he is hopeful that the film will be approved for showing in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Vietnamese films are made each year, mostly
because of a lack of financing. But there is a Vietnamese film
industry, and it has some noted directors, like Dang Nhat Minh,
whose films (including ``When the 10th Month Comes'' and
``Nostalgia for Countryland'') have been presented in the United
States by the UCLA Film and Television Archive.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Gilmore, co-director of the Sundance Film Festival,
believes that critics who call ``Three Seasons'' sentimental are
judging the film too much through Western eyes. ```Three Seasons''
is a kind of filmmaking which comes out of a poetic expressiveness
true to Vietnam,'' he said. ``There's a quality in Thai and
Vietnamese dramatic productions that we would view as excessively
sentimental but that they would view as traditional. It's a certain
kind of melodramatic convention that Tony made a very specific
choice to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Bui acknowledged this connection: ``I was trying to make
something that would be universal, but at the same time to voice
certain sensibilities that were Vietnamese.''
</P>
<P>
   Among these sensibilities are a love of flowers and poetry. The
Vietnamese love of metaphor is apparent in the words of Dang
himself, who saw Bui's film at the Berlin Film Festival in February
and who wrote from Vietnam, through an interpreter, to praise Bui's
ability to capture what Dang called ``the inner world of the
Vietnamese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For those filmmakers who are living and working in Vietnam,
this type of search doesn't exist, because Vietnam is the
environment of their daily life,'' Dang wrote. ``Tony looked for
the first spring that feeds the beginning of the river, but we are
soaking in this river.''
</P>
<P>
   Bui is not, however, the only Vietnamese living abroad who is
making films in Vietnam today. Tran Anh Hung, the director of ``The
Scent of Green Papaya,'' who grew up in France, made his second
film, ``Cyclo'' (1996), in Vietnam and plans to do another there.
</P>
<P>
   Though he admires the older filmmaker's work, Bui said, he does
not consider Tran an influence. ``I was making `Yellow Lotus' even
before I had seen `Scent of Green Papaya,''' he said. ``And `Three
Seasons' is not a dialogue with `Cyclo': it's very much a personal
journey for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That journey is now leading Bui homeward, where ``Three
Seasons'' recently opened the San Francisco International
Asian-American Film Festival. But it is equally important to him,
he says, to reach out to audiences who are not Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   His next plan is to produce the feature that his brother,
Timothy, is going to direct this summer, about American camps
formed in 1975 for Vietnamese refugees waiting to receive formal
sponsorship to enter the country. He is also writing a script that
has nothing to do with Vietnam, the story of a man on a spiritual
journey that takes him from New York to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   All of Bui's projects seem to embrace the complexity inherent in
questions of identity, something he has learned about firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to dissect which part of me is Vietnamese, and
which American,'' he said. ``I've gained a lot by having experience
of both. It may be a constant struggle to understand where I fit
into it all, but it's a struggle I enjoy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
