<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIZABETH-FRANZ-THEAT     05-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-FRANZ-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I HAVE A LOT OF WILLY LOMANS IN MY LIFE'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some people say there has never been a ``Death of a
Salesman'' with a Linda Loman like that of Elizabeth Franz. The
play's author is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the actress' portrayal in the 50th-anniversary
production now on Broadway, Arthur Miller said, ``She has
discovered in the role the basic underlying powerful
protectiveness, which comes out as fury, and that in the past, in
every performance I know of, was simply washed out.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something else: a sexual bond between Ms. Franz's Linda
and the Willy Loman of Brian Dennehy that, Miller said, ``I always
assumed was there, but here it is far more emphasized _
correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Loman is usually played as a beaten-down figure, a
dishrag. She is a prop for her husband's despair over losing his
job, and his worries about his sons, Biff (played in the current
version by Kevin Anderson), a failed athlete and occasional thief,
and Happy (Ted Koch), a banally self-confident loser.
</P>
<P>
   But in the production at the Eugene O'Neill Theater, which was
first staged last year at the Goodman Theater in Chicago, Ms.
Franz's Linda is no passive victim. She is an actor in her
husband's fate, engaged in a primal war with the gods as she
struggles to pull him from the abyss into which he is ineluctably
falling.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Ms. Franz received a Tony nomination as best
featured actress for her portrayal of Linda. The production
garnered a total of six, with Dennehy, Anderson and Robert Falls,
the director, among them. Miller will receive a special Tony for
lifetime achievement in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Franz's analysis of Willy and Linda's relationship may
surprise traditionalists. ``They are very sexually bound
together,'' the actress said in a recent interview. ``For Linda,
Willy is everything. She could do without her sons.''
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of sexual relationship, she added: ``You can say
anything because you know in the end you're going be in that bed,
curled up and having the most wonderful conversations. When she's
curled up in his arms and she's singing to him _ you can't tell me
that isn't a very sexual moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress was speaking in an Upper West Side apartment she has
rented during the play's run. She shares it with her 100-pound
companion, Max, ``the tallest German shepherd seen.'' Usually, she
lives in an old farmhouse in northwest Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write a novel about the characters I play,'' Ms. Franz
confided. ``Linda,'' she said, ``was very close to her parents. She
fell head over heels in love with Willy. Her parents were very
strongly against this marriage, but she defied them and never saw
them again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are secrets,'' Ms. Franz added, with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She insists that her performance derives from Miller's text and
quotes Happy, who wants to marry: ```Somebody with character, with
resistance! Like mom.''' And then mentions Willy's line, ```You're
my foundation and my support, Linda.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her blond hair stylishly cropped, Ms. Franz, who is 57, seems at
least 10 years younger than the onstage Linda, with her 1940s
pageboy. The actress' soft-spoken manner hardly suggests her other
well-known role, that of the demented nun in Christopher Durang's
satire ``Sister Mary Ignatius Explains It All for You'' in the
early 1980s, which won her an Obie award.
</P>
<P>
   She told Durang that she wanted to play Sister Mary because she
understood her. ``They thought, `Maybe we should audition her, if
she's so sick she understands Sister Mary,''' Ms. Franz said.
</P>
<P>
   A killer look came into her eyes. ``Why don't you drop that
polite-boy manner, buster,'' she said, summoning the lines from
memory. ``You do that thing that makes Jesus puke, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   For her portrayal of Linda in ``Death of a Salesman,'' Ms. Franz
said, she used memories of her father, Joe Frankovitch, who worked
at a tire factory in Akron, Ohio, for 36 years. Her father, who was
Serbo-Croatian, had diabetes and missed two and a half months of
work because of bad medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The day he returned, ``they fired him right away,'' Ms. Franz
said, with no pension. ``He got a gold watch, which he had to pawn
to pay the mortgage.'' He died the day the mortgage was paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resonance of my father came to me,'' Ms. Franz said. ``You
look at Brian, a mammoth of a man, disintegrating in front of your
eyes. You realize there's no way you can help him.'' The disparity
in their sizes seems to underscore the futility of this small,
slender Linda saving the large, baffled Willy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are also echoes of Ms. Franz's father in Willy's tortured
relationship with his sons. Ms. Franz recalls her father fighting
with one of her brothers, and his remorse after the boy left home.
``I have a lot of Willy Lomans in my life,'' Ms. Franz said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Harriet, who was half American Indian and half
Irish, suffered from mental problems, Ms. Franz said. As a child,
she found her behavior sometimes frightening. ``My grandmother
would hide me in her closet,'' the actress said. Other times, her
mother disappeared. ``I remember holding onto my father and saying,
`She'll come back.'''
</P>
<P>
   When she was 5, she saw Loretta Young in ``The Bishop's Wife''
and decided to be an actress. Acting would enable her to express
the emotions she had to restrain when she tried to comfort her
father or take care of her mother.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Ms. Franz worked as a secretary, saving until
she could enroll at the American Academy of Dramatic Arts in New
York. There, she said, a teacher told her she was a good actress
but might not get work until she was in her 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Franz said she received some of her best training in summer
stock, ``the only place I could get to do ingenues.'' Later came
regional theater. She has had a career as a supporting actress,
often playing characters older than herself. She portrayed the same
character of the mother in Neil Simon's ``Brighton Beach Memoirs''
and his ``Broadway Bound.''
</P>
<P>
   But her career, she said, has been stymied because Broadway
producers often import British productions and then British actors
to play the leads.
</P>
<P>
   For 17 years, Ms. Franz shared her life with Edward Binns, a
character actor. They married in 1983; Binns died in 1990. There is
a new man in her life now, a screenwriter in California, ``with
(italics)two(end italics) dogs,'' Ms. Franz said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Falls, who is also the artistic chief of the Goodman Theater,
said he chose Ms. Franz to play Linda because ``I love the strength
she possesses.'' He also liked the way her strength would appear
``to be fragility in contrast to Brian Dennehy's size.''
</P>
<P>
   When he invited Ms. Franz to lunch, Falls discovered that her
view of Linda matched his. ``She is far more a wife than a
mother,'' Falls said. ``She is devoted to Willy in a fierce way.
She exists to protect him.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a contemporary performance. ``It would have been
inconceivable,'' Falls said, ``that an American woman could have
played the role that way _ she would have been deemed unladylike _
because there had to be a kind of `niceness' in 1948-49,'' when the
play was first produced.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Franz has portrayed Linda once before _ in 1996 opposite Hal
Holbrook in a performance Falls did not see. But Holbrook was a
more broken, defeated Willy than Brian Dennehy, Ms. Franz said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until she began rehearsals with Dennehy last year
that she really ``found'' Linda. Because of Dennehy's more
aggressive Willy, she was forced to assume a more aggressive
personality to match his, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me know how to love him as a woman,'' Ms. Franz added.
``And he is so similar to my father in build, in his outrage over
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Franz's conception that is being used for the last
moments of ``Death of a Salesman.'' Linda flings herself onto
Willy's grave, as if to lie close to him one last time. ``Willy,
dear,'' Linda says, ``I can't cry. Why did you do it? I search and
search and I search, and I can't understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
