u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES05-CO     05-04 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko calm about slump
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The home runs haven't exactly been pouring in for
Braves first baseman Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   He's had only one this year in his first 46 at-bats and four in
his last 179 at-bats, going back to last July. But Klesko, who's
missed nine games with a hamstring pull, isn't going to get worked
up about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go out and hit five in a week,'' Klesko said. ``As long
as I'm hitting the ball hard, line drives, the power numbers are
going to come...Maybe when I was younger, I'd start worrying,
swinging at the fences, but that's the worst thing you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko got his only home run of 1999 in the second game of the
season, a two-run job off the Phillies Chad Ogea. Seven games later
he pulled his hamstring in Philadelphia and didn't return to the
lineup until last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else was kind of piling up numbers, RBI, hits,''
hitting coach Don Baylor said. ``He felt he had to come back and
catch up in one day...Last night he got back to where he was when
he left.''
</P>
<P>
   Since returning, Klesko endured a 1-for-15 stretch before going
2 for 3 on Monday night. His average was .407 when he first hurt
himself in Philadelphia on April 14. Three weeks later it's .326.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was swinging at everything,'' Klesko said of his 1-for-15
spell. ``I don't think I swung at three or four strikes the whole
time. I should have known better than that. I just want to try and
find a rhythm and relax and get back in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter plays hero
</P>
<P>
   From being released by the St. Louis Cardinals last August to
beating them with a run-scoring single on Monday night for the
Braves isn't as big a jump as some might think. For Brian Hunter,
it may just be a matter of how he's been perceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had to change anything - I believed in my
ability - it's a matter of someone else believing in me,'' Hunter
said. ``I don't think (Cardinals manager) Tony (La Russa) had ever
seen me play with his being in the American League, I came up in
the National League. He didn't know what I could do. Being with
Bobby, Bobby drafted me when I was 19, brought me up when I was 23.
He knows how I play. I can't fault (LaRussa).''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter has been involved in some key Brave rallies this season.
He started the seven-run 12th that helped beat the Dodgers 11-4
with a single. He's now 2 for 4 as a pinch hitter and hitting .333
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say you don't want to do too much because you do,''
Hunter said. ``I'm really out there trying to do something. The
difference in me being in St. Louis is I put too much pressure on
myself trying to impress Tony. Here if I don't get a hit, I know
I'll get another chance somewhere down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy on McGwire
</P>
<P>
   For the rookie who struck out slugger Mark McGwire with three
pitches on Monday night, Kevin McGlinchy has this to say for
himself:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good feeling to get out of the inning,'' McGlinchy
said. ``It was a big inning, score tied 1-1 in a good
pressure-filled situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He threw McGwire fastball, slider, fastball, the last of which
caught McGwire looking at an outside strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went after him like any other hitter,'' McGlinchy said. ``I
didn't want to give in to him. He'd never seen me, I'd never seen
him. That helps a lot....The next time I think he'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker mends
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker has had some soreness in both his elbow and shoulder
this spring, but for the first time in quite a while Rocker went
without getting any treatment in the Braves clubhouse on Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night I felt as good as I've felt all year,'' said
Rocker, who picked up his third save of the year on Monday in his
third consecutive night of work. ``I'm used to getting biceps
tendinitis every year. It's probably something I've got to go
through to get in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves bearing hardware
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-game ceremony on Tuesday night, Braves were honored
with the presentation of quite a few 1998 awards. Tom Glavine was
presented with his second Cy Young award, which he was originally
presented at a banquet in New York, and his fourth Silver Slugger
for being the top hitting pitcher in the National League. Greg
Maddux was presented his ninth Gold Glove, while Andruw Jones and
Bret Boone each picked up their first Gold Gloves. Glavine was also
awarded as the Brave of the year by the Atlanta chapter of the
Baseball Writers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
