<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMANS ASSESS THE DAMAGE FROM MONSTER TWISTER, VOW TO REBUILD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA, REBECA RODRIGUEZ and JENNIFER AUTRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Their cities pulverized, yet miraculously spared
greater human loss, Oklahomans raked through splintered ruins on
Tuesday, vowing to rise from the destruction of a behemont twister
that ravished its namesake Tornado Alley.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's swirling 260-mph winds killed at least 38 people in
Oklahoma City and outlying cities, injured hundreds, destroyed
2,000 buildings and left thousands without homes or electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The largest twister formed about 45 miles southwest of Oklahoma
City late Monday afternoon and cut a path at least a half-mile
wide, staying on the ground for up to four hours, according to some
estimates, as TV stations tracked and televised its vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one did not go up and down,'' Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating
said after surveying the damage. ``This was a half-mile-wide
tornado the length of an aircraft carrier that just sat down and
stayed on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on NBC's ``Today'' show, he said, ``We have
whole communities that simply aren't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the devastation, Keating promised that Oklahomans ``will
rebuild this state. We'll be back stronger than we ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor mobilized the National Guard to help in the rescues
and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The entire state was declared a disaster area and President
Clinton approved federal assistance, saying he also planned to
visit Oklahoma on Saturday for a tour of the devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the damage in Oklahoma City, it looks like
the warning system did work well for the death toll to be so low,
when you see the amount of catastrophic damage there was,'' said
Dave Imy of the Storm Prediction Center in Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hansen, an assistant fire chief in Oklahoma City, likened
the scene to that of the Oklahoma bombing on April 19, 1995: ``It
looks like the Murrah Building, but instead of nine stories tall,
it's spread out over a large area.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Charles Allen, Oklahoma City police spokesman, also
recalled the bombing and how the city responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like the national champions when it comes to dealing
with disasters,'' Allen said. ``We bury our dead. We take care of
our wounded. We rebuild. We move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Oklahoma communities fell victim to the twister's vicious
force. The most deadly was Bridge Creek, about 30 miles southwest
of Oklahoma City, where 11 people were killed. Other fatalities
were in Oklahoma City and nearby Midwest City, Moore, Del City and
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Spawned by the same storm system that raked Oklahoma, another
tornado cut a path 12 miles long and three miles wide in Kansas,
killing five people and injuring 100 in southern Wichita and
suburban Haysville.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the Oklahoma toll, the tornado outbreak was the
nation's deadliest since 42 people were killed in Florida last
year. It was also the deadliest such tragedy to hit Oklahoma since
April 9, 1947, when a twister killed 113 people in Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   While on its destructive tear in Oklahoma, the tornadoes crossed
four freeways and brushed Tinker Air Force Base, wiping out or
damaging half of the homes in Moore, a city of 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   One Oklahoma state trooper likened the destruction in a Moore
neighborhood to a war zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen pictures of the damage in Kosovo _ well just go
down there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Oklahoma City area, cars were tossed about and
crushed, natural gas lines were ruptured and utility poles were
shredded into kindling.
</P>
<P>
   Along Interstates 35 and 240, the storm littered the freeway
shoulders with debris and personal items from as far away as
Chickasha, where the tornadoes began their rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, taking advantage of ample warning provided by a
radar system that allowed televisions to track its path street by
street, fled in advance of the mammoth funnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many lives were saved by the early warning,'' said
Oklahoma City Mayor Kirk Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   The early warning alerted an off-duty police officer to lead to
shelter about 300 students meeting at West Moore High School, most
likely saving them from serious injury or death, said Capt. Charles
Allen, Oklahoma City police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most tornadoes that hop-scotch around, this one didn't.
It was so big it seemed to rumble, wiping out everything in its
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `There's no way something that big moves
on this earth,''' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't miss it,'' said Randy Lacy, a Moore resident who
watched it pass within a mile of his home. ``Every time you looked,
the storm looked like it was coming right at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fred Carr, director of the University of Oklahoma School of
Meterology, called the tornado's one-mile width ``extreme'' and
``just a few percent will do that in a given year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most tornadoes, he said, measure only 500 to 600 feet wide, skip
across landscape and don't pack the wallop necessary to rate an F5
classification on the Fujita Scale _ the highest storm severity
designation, meaning winds in excess of 260 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, ambulances and U-hauls crawled through the
ruins of what once was a cozy, diverse subdivision in southeast
Oklahoma City called Frolich Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and daughters hugged and cried as they looked upon acres
of haunting, twisted trees and 8-foot-high mounds of oozing pink
fiberglass insulation, broken bricks and splintered wood, all that
was left of what had been $80,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some homeowners, such as Carol Warner, 62, and her husband,
survived the tornado by clinging to pillows on the floor of their
hall bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ears were popping and I could feel the gusts like they were
going to suck me into the air,'' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Warners lived to talk about their terror, others did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a back-hoe lifted a van off the collapsed
bathroom of a neighbor's house, where rescuers worked more than
four hours to retrieve the body of Jack Self, 86, a retired
minister known in the community simply as ``Brother Jake.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the family of Aaron LeClaire, 47, a computer specialist
for the Federal Aviation Administration, stopped looking for their
three-wheeler to watch a neighbor search for his wife under a mound
of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a thick line of tall trees that separated their
properties was now two feet high, and the neighbor's grief played
out as he frantically cried, ``Linda! Linda! Linda!''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, rescue workers found his wife dead.
</P>
<P>
   Along the southern edge of Oklahoma City, drivers jammed
two-lane county roads in a futile attempt to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't going nowhere,'' said Carl Haynes. ``I don't know
what's left of my home, but this can't be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating urged Oklahoma residents to follow the neighborly
example set during the Oklahoma City bombing four years ago,
warning businesses not to gouge customers and take advantage of
their plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your neighbor is homeless, take him in,'' Keating said.
``If your neighbor is without clothing or food, make sure they get
what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
