<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-TORNAODES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD TORNADOES BRING DEATH, DESTRUCTION TO OKLAHOMA, KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ Tami Low has lived here all her life, well
aware the town's name might as well be ``Tornado City.'' She grew
so used to the yearly weather warnings that last spring, she and
her husband took a drive out to the suburbs to try to catch a
glimpse when one blew through.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Low had to go no farther than her porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't need to,'' Low, 33, said Tuesday night, tearing up
as she picked through piles of glass in her demolished living room,
beneath a crumbling ceiling on the verge of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Out back, behind a forest of flattened elm trees, what was once
a neighborhood of single-story ranch homes lay in flat rubble, a
virtual highway carved by one of the worst tornadoes ever to hit
this suburb of Oklahoma City, or, indeed, the region.
</P>
<P>
   Low, her husband and their four children survived the brutal
storm Monday night, huddled together in a six-foot by six-foot
bathroom, pillows clamped over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighboring home, however, a four-year-old boy was killed.
And even in a part of the country so accustomed to tornado season,
it was the randomness _ and the lethality _ of the storm that
seemed most overwhelming in the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Officials confirmed 38 deaths in Oklahoma and five in Kansas,
making this the deadliest wave of tornadoes since 42 people were
killed in February 1998 in Kissimmee, Fla. It was also the worst
weather-related tragedy in Oklahoma since a tornado killed 113
people in Woodward in April 9, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds were injured, including more than 500 in Oklahoma City
and more than 100 in Wichita, Kan. At least 1,500 businesses and
homes were destroyed or heavily damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers swept through the wreckage twice Tuesday to look for
survivors, then brought in bulldozers to make a third search in the
afternoon. At least one woman was found alive in a trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared a major disaster for 11 counties in
Oklahoma and one county in Kansas. The president also ordered
federal aid, including disaster housing, grants, and low-cost loans
to cover uninsured property. Jamie Lee Witt, director of the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, is traveling to Oklahoma City
to oversee federal relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our top priority is to make sure people are safe,
that everyone is accounted for, and that initial cleanup can
begin,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the president is considering a trip
to the tornado zone on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimated the group of tornadoes traveled as much as
80 miles after forming 45 miles southwest of Oklahoma City on
Monday afternoon. Over the next 20 hours, as many as four dozen
tornadoes developed, moving diagonally toward the northeastern
corner of the state. The deadliest of the twisters measured nearly
a mile wide as it swept through Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   The same weather system spawned the Kansas tornado, which struck
about 8:30 p.m. Monday and cut a swath 12 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tornadoes moved swiftly across the flat countryside,
sometimes striking just minutes after a tornado warning had been
issued, officials said the number of deaths and injuries was held
down because the public responded to warnings and took cover
underground.
</P>
<P>
   A huge storm system was first detected at about 4 p.m. CDT
Monday by the National Weather Service in Norman, Okla., as a mass
of cold air from the north collided with warm, moist air from the
south. At 4:47, the weather service issued its first tornado
warning of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The main storm formed near Chikasha, about 45 miles southwest of
Oklahoma City. A funnel was spotted at about 5:30, and moving
toward the northesast, hit the municipal airport about 15 minutes
later. But the twister remained several miles and northwest of the
heavily populated areas of Chikasha.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of bypassed us,'' said Chickasha police Captain Lynn
Williams. ``We got extremely lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6:51, the National Weather Service issued a severe
thunderstorm warning for the Oklahoma City area. Soon, the advisory
was upgraded to a tornado warning _ just minutes before the twister
hit the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, the deaths occurred in Wichita and suburban
Haysville, where some mobile homes from the Lake Shore Trailer Park
were hurled into a nearby lake. At least 150 homes, 27 businesses,
and three churches were damaged in Haysville.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy,'' said Eric Peterson, a recent transplant from
Seattle who end up with a tree in his bedroom. ``I have been in
typhoons in the South Pacific and in hurricans, but this tops it.''
</P>
<P>
   While residents were trying to recover from the devastation,
insurance claims adjusters were on the scene Tuesday, evaluating
the cost of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   While estimates won't be available for several days, some
believed the losses will be the steepest ever caused by a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We studied 37 mid-sized to large catastophes last year,'' said
John Eager, director of claims services for the National
Association of Independent Insurers. ``I don't remember any that
were as devastating as this one seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   The costliest tornado on record struck Xenia, Ohio, in April
1974, causing $400 million in damage, according to the Property
Claim Services unit of New York-based Insurance Services Office
Inc. Adjusted for inflation, that's about $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
