u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ESPN-MLB-BOS &LR;      05-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ESPN-MLB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN SUES TO PRESERVE MLB CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN filed suit in federal court Tuesday seeking to prevent
Major League Baseball from terminating its $40 million-per-year
contract with the cable sports giant.
</P>
<P>
   The suit revolves around ESPN's right to put three baseball
games on its sister network, ESPN2, in order to air higher-rated
professional football games in September.
</P>
<P>
   Though the contract doesn't specifically mention NFL games, ESPN
officials said it gives them the right to bump up to 10 baseball
games for ``events of significant viewer interest.'' Further, ESPN
said, baseball tried to ``extort'' about $350 million from ESPN to
renegotiate the contract.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, events for which baseball games have been bumped
included the College World Series, auto racing, pro golf, NHL
playoff games, and World Cup soccer. Major League Baseball has the
right to approve such preemptions, and as far as anyone can recall,
it approved every one until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball does have a point: ESPN has 76.2 million
subscribers, ESPN2 64.5 million. But it's a small point. The real
issue is whether baseball can get more money from television
networks. ESPN recently renewed its deal with the NHL for a total
of $600 million, about $120 million per year. It is also paying
about $600 million over the next eight years to air 18 NFL games
per season on Sunday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by last year's historic home run chase of Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa, Major League Baseball balked at games being
bumped to ESPN2 this year. The sides sparred until April 21, when
ESPN received a letter from baseball's chief operating officer,
Paul Beeston, informing the network that the contract would be
terminated at the end of this regular season instead of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN thought they had an opportunity to make a lot more on the
NFL and decided not to pay attention to us,'' Rich Levin, a
spokesman for MLB, told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The sports business is filled with short memories. Just four
years ago, baseball was devastated by a player strike and the
failure of its join television arrangement with ABC and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN came to the rescue in 1997 by agreeing to air hours and
hours of games, and Sosa and McGwire infused popularity back into
the sport last season. All of that good will was erased Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no sense to us,'' said Dick Glover, ESPN's executive
vice president of programming.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN president George Bodenheimer went further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about nine hours of programming in the course
of the almost 500 hours of dedicated MLB coverage we provide each
year,'' Bodenheimer said. ``It's outrageous for baseball to attempt
to terminate its agreement with ESPN.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially considering the efforts made by ESPN to make up for
bumping games.
</P>
<P>
   Glover said ESPN was willing to allow the three games assigned
to ESPN2 to also be aired in local markets on over-the-air
stations. That would give baseball even greater distribution than
ESPN could provide.
</P>
<P>
   When that offer was rejected, ESPN countered with another. It
offered to give the games back to the teams and allow them to place
them anywhere they could. In addition, the Sunday night games could
be traded for ``more meaningful'' games to be picked up by ESPN on
Tuesdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN even offered to forgive Major League Baseball for one game
per season that couldn't be delivered because of of rain or other
unforeseeable events. ESPN also was willing to expand its
``Baseball Tonight'' show to two hours to highlight the pennant
race.
</P>
<P>
   All ESPN received back from Major League Baseball was a demand
for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wanted to renegotiate its $40 million-a-year deal to
$135 million a year. In its suit, ESPN said that ``baseball has
attempted to extort hundreds of millions of dollars of economic
concessions'' as the price of letting ESPN move the games.
</P>
<P>
   The average rating for a baseball game on ESPN is about 1, while
football does much better. Last year, for instance, September
baseball games averaged a 1.7 rating. The three football games that
month averaged a 7.3.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, baseball on ESPN has averaged a paltry 1.3
rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
