<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u b &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-STORM-TEX     05-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-STORM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RESIDENTS TRY TO FLEE STORM CELL, TORNADO TRACKERS PURSUE IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANITA BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine times on Monday, Joshua Wurman and his storm-chasing team
of scientists from the University of Oklahoma saw clouds drop out
of the sky and spin.
</P>
<P>
   The first two tornadoes they spotted Monday afternoon helped
their research, but the third one that dropped near the tiny town
of Cement, Okla., took them on the ride of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours, they chased a half-mile-wide tornado with
winds clocked in excess of 200 mph as it swept through Chickasha,
Newcastle, Moore, Del City and then Midwest City, killing dozens
and destroying thousands of homes before vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   Their adrenaline surged as their van sped toward the
debris-filled spiral, stopped to set up Doppler radar long enough
to record data about the twister, then rushed back into the van to
continue the chase.
</P>
<P>
   While others fled from the path of the dozens of tornadoes in
Oklahoma and Kansas, Wurman _ nationally renowned tornado chaser _
and his team pursued the deadly twister.
</P>
<P>
   Fear seldom crossed their minds, Wurman said, even though they
were once within a few hundred feet from what scientists gauged as
at least an F4 tornado, the second-strongest level on the Fujita
Scale.
</P>
<P>
   But a pinprick of reality invaded their scientific sphere in
Moore, on the southwestern edge of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove through Moore probably a minute after the tornado,
through the damage path,'' Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   The twister cut a three-mile-long, five-to-six-block wide swath
through the town, destroying hundreds of homes, smashing
automobiles and uprooting trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to see,'' Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   Louis J. Wicker, an associate professor of meteorology at Texas
A&AMP;M University, said, ``In terms of a single tornado, it will be
among the top 10 in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Wurman added that the data scientists collected Monday might
lead to a better assessment of how massive tornadoes work and
enable scientists to give residents more warning before such
devastation hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much we can do to prevent the homes from being
destroyed,'' Wurman said. ``We hope we can get them to shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reports said the half-mile-wide tornado was on the ground
for an unprecedented four hours, but Wurman estimated the time as
closer to an hour or two. He didn't keep track of the duration, but
will have a precise time line when researchers sift through the
tons of computer data his team collected for the 12-hour period
they trailed tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   But even one or two hours is rare, Wurman and other scientists
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty uncommon for an hour and happens only a couple of
times a year,'' Wicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday started as a favorable day for tornadoes, but not a
perfect one, Wurman said. Because of high cloud cover, which can
inhibit tornado development, some storm chasers didn't go out to
hunt for tornadoes, he said. Wurman and a few other tornado
watchers decided to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists don't completely understand the complexities of
tornadoes, but they know that when hot and cold air collide, the
hot air rushes rapidly upward, pulling even more air up from the
earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing stops the circulation, the air masses can begin to
twist and turn the huge cloud mass.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, several supercell storms developed over Oklahoma and
Kansas dropping maybe 50 or more tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes of such duration and intensity as those described
Monday afternoon through early Tuesday morning occur only when the
atmosphere is very unstable and updraft winds reach at least 150
mph with nothing to shut it off, Wicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Wurman said they had the half-mile-wide twister in their sight
for most of the 40 miles it traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it was continuous, although we can't say 100
percent for certain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using Doppler radar, Wurman and his team spotted an even bigger
tornado at least a mile wide about 11 p.m. between Crescent and
Mulhall, north of Oklahoma City, he said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Oklahoma researchers should have some details
about the twisters within a few days, Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   Had the storm hit at 2 a.m. when more people were home asleep,
many more would have died, Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   The misfortune Monday ``was not that it was just a large
tornado, but that it lasted a long time and passed through a
populated area,'' he said. ``I am amazed with the description that
more were not killed.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
