<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `Living Wage' _ Effects On Firms
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  How would San Francisco Supervisor Tom Ammiano's $11
``living wage'' proposal affect the thousands of small businesses
based in the city?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The living wage proposal is making a lot of
businesses livid, but it by no means affects everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The current proposal, which still is subject to change and a lot
of economic analysis before a vote, would raise the minimum wage
from $5.75 to $11 an hour for businesses that provide more than
$25,000 of annual services to the city and county of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses that provide goods, like office supplies, to the city
would be immune. But businesses that lease land from the city, like
shops and restaurants at Fisherman's Wharf, Pier 39 and other port
property as well as Moscone Center and the airport, would be
subject to paying the higher minimum wage just like service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the near-doubling of the hourly wage, affected
businesses would be required to provide health benefits; 12 days of
paid vacation, sick or personal leave each year; and 10 days of
unpaid leave.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the financial impact range from $15 million to $100
million. There are no clear numbers, but Jim Mathias, public
affairs manager for the San Francisco Chamber of Commerce, said the
impact is likely to be 10 to 20 times greater than mandated city
contract wage increases had on Oakland and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   That's because so many more workers are affected in San
Francisco. For example, there are about 6,500 health services
workers who make home visits to the city's elderly, sick and
disabled who get paid about $7 an hour. There also are many
thousands of workers who work for businesses that pay rent to the
city that will be disadvantaged severely if the living wage bill
passes without any amendments, Mathias said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, restaurant waiters who make $5.75 an hour in wages
but a multiple of that in tips would get their base wage raised to
$11 an hour. Some members of the Golden Gate Restaurant Association
that operate on city land estimate that they would have to raise
their prices 30 percent to remain profitable. However, that would
be extremely difficult to do in the highly competitive food
business.
</P>
<P>
   One casualty could be Fog City Diner, which operates on port
land and competes with Il Fornaio on the other side of Battery
Street, which would be immune from the living wage ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for business opponents, some city officials, including
the mayor, are proposing careful economic analysis before the
living wage ordinance goes to a vote. There also are questions
about who is going to pay all the bills because the city is facing
a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Mathias believes that the issue could drag into the summer or
beyond. The earliest the higher wage could be imposed is a year
from September _ the beginning of the 2001 fiscal year. Some
suppliers to the city wouldn't have to pay the higher rates until
their contracts with the city came up for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a Used Business
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to run my own business, but I think I am better
at managing than creating something from scratch. What are the best
strategies for buying an existing business?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: A lot of people are better at building or buffing up a
venture that already exists than dreaming one up. Often, there also
is a lot less risk adopting a business that's a known quantity.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book ``101 Answers to the Most Frequently Asked
Questions From Entrepreneurs'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $16.95),
Courtney Price provides a useful checklist for buying a business:
</P>
<P>
   _Hire the owner of a similar business outside your competitive
area to help you evaluate purchase opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   _Seek outside help from accountants, lawyers and bankers in
assessing opportunities to purchase a business.
</P>
<P>
   _Ask for audited financial statements and tax returns for the
past three to five years. Also, compare operating ratios with
comparable statistics from Robert Morris studies, and thoroughly
review assets and liabilities including uncollected bills and
pending law suits.
</P>
<P>
   _Run a background check with the Better Business Bureau, Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet or other sources. Also, assess the current staff and
review their personnel files.
</P>
<P>
   _Evaluate the local economic and political conditions.
</P>
<P>
   _Meet with current customers and former customers to gauge their
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   _Present yourself as a fully qualified business person.
</P>
<P>
   _Negotiate with the seller to carry back debt and give you good
terms so that the business generates enough cash to pay for itself
in five years.
</P>
<P>
   _Ask the seller to continue working in the business for three to
six months to help you make the transition and provide training.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
