<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Geron Buys Cloning Ability
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Geron Corp., a Menlo Park biotech company, said yesterday that it
has purchased the Scottish firm that owns the technology used to
clone Dolly the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Geron said control of the Dolly technology could eventually lead
to radical new types of medical treatments, such as growing healthy
cells to graft onto _ and repair _ sick livers or hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly made headlines in 1997 after she became the first cloned
mammal. She was created by a scientist at the Roslin Institute, a
Scottish research outfit, which formed a company, Roslin Bio-Med,
to commercialize the cloning technique.
</P>
<P>
   Geron said it would acquire Roslin Bio-Med for 2.1 million
shares of Geron stock. Wall Street reacted coolly, driving Geron
stock &UR;  &LR; down 13 cents to $12.25, making the deal worth about $26
million at yesterday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all very interesting and I'm glad it makes people talk
about biotech,'' said Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical
Technology Stock Letter in Berkeley. ``But I don't see how it makes
anybody any money for years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology Industry
Organization, the Washington, D.C., trade group, put the news in a
more dramatic light.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't usually comment on mergers,'' Feldbaum said. ``But
this is one combination we'll look back on as launching an entirely
new field called regenerative medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Okarma, Geron's vice president for research and
development, said even in the most optimistic circumstances, it
would take three to five years for some of the Dolly technology to
be commercialized.
</P>
<P>
   According to Okarma, Geron hopes to combine cloning with the
advances that earned Geron huge headlines last year _ its patents
on the immortality enzyme and its licensing of human stem cell
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Okarma said Geron's hopes begin with stem cells, a type of cell
harvested from developing embryos. Stem cells, which emerge in the
earliest days after fertilization, are the factories that divide
and differentiate, eventually producing all the cells, from nerves
to blood to muscle, that make us live and breathe, Okarma said.
</P>
<P>
   When the discovery of stem cells was announced in November,
Geron held out the prospect that these cellular factories could one
day be used to create tissues that could be used as transplant
material. But in order to grow large numbers of specialized cells,
Okarma said Geron will need to use its second technology, the
immortalizing enzyme known as telomerase.
</P>
<P>
   In nature, cells have a definite life span. The telomerase
enzyme allows cells to stay alive and keep dividing indefinitely.
Geron got a second blast of publicity in December when scientists
working with the firm published data showing that this immortality
enzyme allowed tissue cultures to grow almost endlessly in the
laboratory _ without turning into dangerous cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   Even before yesterday's announcement, Geron said that by adding
telomerase to cultures of differentiated stem cells, it hoped to
one day grow large batches of skin, lung, heart and other cells.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Okarma explained, the acquisition of the cloning
technology should allow Geron to do something new with its cellular
factories, that is turn them into customized assembly lines. It
would do this by taking the nucleus out of a cell from a patient's
body, and injecting it into the cell factory so that the tissues
produced are biologically identical to the tissues in the patient's
body.
</P>
<P>
   If this can be done, he said, it would solve the biggest problem
in organ transplant medicine: Patients often reject their new
hearts or livers, perceiving them as infectious agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could maintain a large vat of reprogrammed cells to create
your heart muscle cells or my heart cells,'' Okarma said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would not be to grow replacement hearts or livers, he
said. Rather, the aim would be to grow healthy cells, cloned to be
identical to the cells in the patient's body. These cultured cells
could be grafted onto the damaged organ, he said, in the same way
someone might iron on a patch to mend pants.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Pedersen, a professor of reproductive sciences at the
University of California at San Francisco, sounded the same theme
in an article in April's Scientific American. Pedersen, a member of
Geron's scientific advisory board, was out of the country yesterday
and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But his article says scientists already have all the tools they
need to one day perform the types of cell grafts Okarma talked
about. ``This scenario is for now hypothetical, but it is not
farfetched,'' Pedersen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The cell graft technique is just one of the possible advances
Okarma said could grow out of the Dolly deal. In the meantime,
Geron hopes to earn money in more mundane ways, such as creating
tissue cultures that drug companies can use as test beds for
prospective remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Robbins-Roth, a biotech industry analyst in San Mateo,
said Geron has proven adept at garnering attention for its novel
and provocative approaches to biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to keep in mind is that can take a decade or more
for some of these promising ideas to turn into products that are
clinically or commercially viable,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
