<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIAONE-960&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      05-04 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T, CLOSE TO GETTING MEDIAONE, SEEN FORGING MICROSOFT LINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT and SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. is close to forming a wide-ranging partnership with
Microsoft Corp. as part of an intricate web of deals that has put
AT&AMP;T on the verge of winning the battle against Comcast Corp. for
MediaOne Group Inc., the big cable television company, executives
close to the negotiations said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, whose initial $53 billion bid for MediaOne was topped
by an AT&AMP;T offer of $58 billion, has agreed to accept a two-part
consolation settlement in which it will end up with as many as 2
million of AT&AMP;T's existing cable subscribers, mostly on the East
Coast, for up to $9 billion, the executives said. It will also
assume management control over an additional 2 million AT&AMP;T cable
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The companies could announce the deals as soon as Wednesday, the
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after selling up to 2 million subscribers to Comcast, AT&AMP;T,
the nation's biggest telephone company, would emerge from the fray
as the nation's biggest cable television company. Before agreeing
to acquire Tele-Communications Inc. for about $32 billion last
summer, AT&AMP;T had no presence in cable television. But C. Michael
Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman of 18 months, is pursuing a vision of
delivering integrated packages of telephone, television and
high-speed Internet access to millions of households using cable
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, its ambitions for MediaOne apparently dashed, will
still end up the No. 3 cable television company. The residential
customers it is set to buy from AT&AMP;T will serve to solidify
Comcast's dominance between Philadelphia and Washington, executives
close to the talks said. They added that AT&AMP;T and Comcast would
form a venture to offer telephone service over Comcast's cables.
</P>
<P>
   But the most intriguing and potentially important element of the
numerous deals is the partnership that AT&AMP;T is negotiating with
Microsoft, the No. 1 maker of personal computer software. Together,
AT&AMP;T and Microsoft have a market value of more than half a trillion
dollars and, if linked, would form the world's leading force in
technology and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Any AT&AMP;T-Microsoft partnership would be sure to rouse concern
among politicians and regulators. Though the two companies are not
now competitors, both AT&AMP;T and Microsoft are behemoths with long
traditions of dominating their industries. The prospect of an
alliance is sure to seem mind-boggling to at least some powerful
people in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, declined to comment Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal being negotiated Tuesday night,
Microsoft would invest about $5 billion in AT&AMP;T to acquire 2 to 3
percent of the communications giant, executives close to the talks
said. Microsoft would pay more than the closing price of AT&AMP;T
shares Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange, the executives said.
They added that the size of the premium to be paid was one of the
central sticking points in the negotiations Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T does not need the money, an investment from Microsoft
would buoy AT&AMP;T's shares, which may fall as the company continues
its headlong deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   As for Microsoft, it would get what it has long been seeking: a
commitment from AT&AMP;T to use Microsoft's Windows operating system in
the advanced set-top boxes that AT&AMP;T will deploy to offer bundles
of digital services.
</P>
<P>
   With $22 billion in cash and no debt _ and already owning 11
percent of Comcast _ Microsoft finds itself in a kingmaker role in
the deal, choosing sides or threatening to bid for MediaOne on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   An investment in AT&AMP;T would be partly defensive for Microsoft.
The company has scrambled for advantage for Windows CE _ the
version of its operating system for small devices _ in the young,
fast-changing market for software used in television set-top boxes.
And Microsoft also wants to try to insure access to high-speed
networks for its other software and Internet commerce businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's move would also be offensive in that it could
help the company as the Internet business moves toward the
so-called broadband model in which households are continuously
connected to high-speed data lines.
</P>
<P>
   Though Comcast has agreed to drop out of the bidding for
MediaOne, it will walk away with a rich prize, analysts said
Tuesday. At a price of up to $9 billion in cash and stock for as
many as 2 million cable subscribers, Comcast is paying roughly
$4,500 a subscriber, about the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, based in Philadelphia, will swap another 700,000
subscribers to give it more clustered subscribers in crucial
markets. Though only half of the exact locations for cable swaps
and purchases had been determined late Tuesday night, a person
involved in the discussions said Comcast was increasing cable
subscribers in some of its main markets, including Philadelphia,
Nashville, Tenn., and parts of Michigan, and giving up some in
Chicago, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the subscribers, Comcast will use the $1.5 billion
fee that MediaOne will pay for backing out of the original deal
with Comcast. Comcast is also swapping back to AT&AMP;T $1.5 billion in
AT&AMP;T stock and another $1 billion in the stock of At-Home, a
provider of Internet services over cable modems. Had Comcast sold
that stock on the open market, it would have paid heavy capital
gains taxes. Selling it back to AT&AMP;T is a tax-free transaction,
people close to the company noted Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   To pay the balance of the purchase price, Comcast will issue
additional shares of its own nonvoting stock at a price based on
how the stock trades over the next 50 days. A person close to the
talks said that Comcast expected to add 75 million new shares to
its existing base of 450 million shares.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Comcast clearly wanted MediaOne but was unable to form a bidding
alliance with America Online, which was not in a position to issue
more stock to pay its share because its stock price has been
volatile. Microsoft, another potential ally, decided to cut a deal
with AT&AMP;T, and Comcast did not have the financial muscle to buy the
company on its own.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts who follow Comcast were pleased by the new
deal. For one thing, Comcast will be using its deal-breakup fee of
$1.5 billion, which one analyst called found money. It is also
using a large slug of Comcast stock, which is trading near record
prices. It closed Tuesday at $64.125. And for analysts who believe
that size is less important than clustered systems that enable
cable companies to sell local advertising and have better
management control, Comcast is moving close to that model.
</P>
<P>
   Continued consolidations have reassured investors that cable
companies will be well run and will benefit from economies of
scale.
</P>
<P>
   In a related transaction, AT&AMP;T is buying the half of Lenfest
Communications that it does not already own from that company's
chairman, Jerry Lenfest. The price for the midsize cable company is
$2 billion, or 43 million shares of AT&AMP;T stock.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Roberts, Comcast's president and a member of the family
that controls the company, will manage those cable systems, which
are heavily weighted in New Jersey and Philadelphia, where Comcast
already has cable systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
