<SLUG> BC-MOVEON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Anti-Impeach Site Moves On to Gun Control
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The Berkeley software entrepreneurs who spearheaded an Internet
petition opposing the impeachment of President Clinton have
launched a new cyber campaign supporting gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In response to this month's massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., Joan Blades and Wes Boyd started an online gun
control drive on their Web site,  &LR; www.moveon.org,  &LR; last Thursday
night. By yesterday, they had gathered more than 42,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Blades and Boyd are the husband-and-wife founders of Berkeley
Systems, a screen saver and computer game company. In September,
they started MoveOn.org as a one-issue grassroots political site.
The site eventually gathered about 500,000 signatures to pressure
members of Congress to censure but not impeach Clinton for the
Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   MoveOn.org also received about $13 million in pledges for money
to be used in election campaigns next year against House and Senate
members who voted for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Gun Safety First'' campaign promotes the ``common
sense regulation of firearms,'' such as child safety standards for
gun manufacturers and laws forcing gun-show operators to enact
more-stringent background checks on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another issue where a vast majority of citizens want
reasonable gun control but what's happening inside the Beltway is
not reflecting that desire,'' Blades said. ``This is an opportunity
for people who are concerned to become an effective voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than 1 million online signatures gathered by
MoveOn.org and other political Web sites, Clinton was impeached by
the House, though the Senate did not force the president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control is just as contentious an issue for Congress. In the
Columbine High aftermath, Clinton proposed a package of new gun
control laws, some of which have been voted down in Congress
several times in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocacy groups also are using the Internet to lobby
Congress. For example, the Gun Owners of America's site,
 &LR; www.gunowners.org, &LR;  offers already-written e-mail messages
opposing proposed gun control laws and the messages can be sent
automatically to key members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Blades believes that MoveOn.org can be successful because it
pushes a ``moderate'' gun control law that should appease pro-gun
advocates. ``We want to be able to support basic legislation that
keeps guns out of the hands of irresponsible people,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
