<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Mutual Fund Betting That Japan's Economy Is on the Rebound
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The sun also rises, but when?
</P>
<P>
   If you're visionary investor Bill Hambrecht and Asian fund
manager G. Paul Matthews, the answer is: any day now.
</P>
<P>
   While nobody seems to know for sure whether Japan's ruinous
economy has finally bottomed out, Hambrecht and Matthews are
betting that investors can't afford to avoid Japan for much longer.
So, Matthews' international fund complex, in which Hambrecht owns
about a 30 percent stake, is launching a mutual fund targeted at
the world's second largest economy: the Matthews Japan Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is still that question (of whether earnest
economic recovery has begun) in Japan, but when we find the answer
it will be too late to invest,'' says Matthews, who is chief
investment officer of the San Francisco fund complex bearing his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, a former GT Global fund manager, founded his fund
group in 1991. It consists of Matthews Pacific Tiger Fund, Matthews
Asian Convertible Securities Fund, Matthews Korea Fund and Matthews
Dragon Century Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Japan's turn. And for those investors with strong
stomachs who like to buy low (and hopefully sell high), now may be
the time to sink some money into the island nation's stock market
through the diversification of his latest mutual fund, Matthews
says.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, there are considerable risks. ``Volatility is a
constant,'' Matthews reminds.
</P>
<P>
   And even if you aren't prepared to plunk down hard-earned cash
on beaten-down Japanese stocks, should you give a rip about the
country's economic health?
</P>
<P>
   Probably. For one thing, so goes Japan _ so goes Asia. Aside
from China, it is really the only Asian economy of any monumental
consequence. And if you've been celebrating the recent blue-chip
rally, the catalyst behind the rebirth of many cyclical stocks has
been a spate of positive rumblings from key foreign markets, such
as Brazil, Russia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, President Clinton's summit on Monday with Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi spotlighted the impact of Japan's
better-late-than-never economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economic health is critical because American companies
need to sell their oil, chemicals and bulldozers to somebody. And
when Japan's brutal recession caused its industrial base to falter,
many U.S. companies saw their revenues get whacked.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while it is bound to chart a choppy course, a Japanese
recovery of any sort is still welcome news to the U.S. economy and
American investors. What's more, if once-moribund foreign economies
rebound solidly, then it's more likely that investor rotation into
a broader array of stocks may continue. All of which is considered
to be healthy for U.S. financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics will argue that many Japanese companies have yet to
swallow the bitter _ yet essential _ medicine of economic reform
and restructuring, fostering doubts as to whether the worst is
truly over.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Headley, a Matthews portfolio manager, counters by
saying that Japan has managed to initiate more reform than many
people expected it to do, such as wiping bad debt off the books of
banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's correct to say that the government has
nationalized its banking system. It had to bail out the banking
industry, and taxpayers hated doing that,`` Headley says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Japan's economy improves slowly, ``there are some
tremendous opportunities,'' Headley says. ``The economy has been a
wreck, (but) there are a lot of good companies there that make
great products.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, trust the stock pickers not to simply invest in
Japan Inc., but to find a select group of winners amid the rubble,
says co-manager James Bogin, who has lived off and on in Japan
since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of extended visits recently, Bogin is focusing on
a handful of investment sectors: chain retailing,
telecommunications, manufacturing and financial services. The
following are some companies he is eyeing:
</P>
<P>
   _Hikari Tsushin is a company that sells cellular phone handsets
and contracts for international and domestic long-distance
telephone service. It recently established an internet service
provider, and its profits are growing 30 to 40 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   _Chofu Seisakusho is a manufacturer of water boilers which sells
near the value of its cash on its balance sheet. It is profitable
despite the lousy economy. ``You get the underlying business for
free,'' Bogin says.
</P>
<P>
   _Ralse is a supermarket chain, which has been growing earnings
during the recession. It has figured out how to offer the freshest
produce at low prices, which is a relatively new concept for
Japanese retailing.
</P>
<P>
   _Banks and nonbank lenders. ``The bad news is already built into
many of these stocks,'' Bogin says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Matthews and Hambrecht would be delighted if the
Japan fund could duplicate the success of their Korea Fund. When
Street Smarts first reported that Hambrecht was taking a stake in
the fund complex on September 30, the Korea fund was bottoming out
at about $2 a share.
</P>
<P>
   During the past six months, the Korea Fund has nearly tripled to
$5.94 a share. Of course, Japan's economy is much bigger than that
of South Korea, which means its opportunity for upside may be that
much larger as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
