<SLUG> BC-OKLA-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DECLARES PARTS OF OKLAHOMA AND KANSAS DISASTER AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OKLA-STORMS, OKLA-SCENE) 
(sw) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday declared parts of
Oklahoma and Kansas disaster areas because of the damage caused by
tornadoes on Monday, and the Federal Emergency Management Agency
sent assistance that included communications equipment and a team
of morticians and medical workers trained in identifying bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whole communities have been leveled,'' Clinton said. ``Homes
and possessions have been turned into splinters and rubble.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's declaration makes residents of the stricken
areas eligible for benefits like low-interest loans to rebuild
their homes, and orders many federal agencies to help in the
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Walker, deputy director of the emergency agency, said a
truck loaded with sophisticated communications equipment had been
sent to Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a communications problem because all the phone lines
are down,'' Walker said, and the truck has satellite phones and
ultrahigh frequency radios that will allow rescuers to reach one
another.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is coordinating the work of 27 federal organizations
and the American Red Cross. One of the organizations, the Public
Health Service, sent a mortuary team from Rockville, Md., to help
deal with the death toll.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross said that it put its emergency shelter
program into effect as soon as the tornadoes hit and that 10
shelters were now set up in Oklahoma, and three in Kansas. Darren
Irby, a spokesman for the Red Cross, said the organization had
advance agreements with schools, churches and other organizations
to use their buildings as emergency shelters to house and feed
disaster victims.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in cases of major loss of life like this one, the
Red Cross sends in teams of mental health workers and condolence
counselors, ``not only to those involved with loss but to emergency
workers and the community at large,'' Irby said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is concerned, he said, that among rescue workers
and residents alike, the tornado disaster may bring on emotional
recollections of the Oklahoma City bombing of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Five Red Cross emergency response trucks have been activated in
Oklahoma City and seven in Wichita, Kan., Irby said, each capable
of serving up to 5,000 meals a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      05-04 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT RAISES CONCERNS ABOUT BIAS IN CRASH INQUIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's system for organizing crash
investigations is too dependent on work from groups with direct
interests in the results, including manufacturers, operators and
regulators, a draft report by the RAND Corp. says.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary report, which RAND has been asked to present at
a House budget hearing on Thursday, also found that lengthy
investigations like those involving USAir 427, which lasted for
more than four years, and TWA 800, now two and a half years old,
are becoming the norm, as fewer airplanes crash from simple causes
like navigation error or parts failure. The USAir flight crashed
near Pittsburgh in September 1994, killing 132 people, and the TWA
flight went down off Long Island in July 1996, killing 230.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are rising in each investigation, the report said,
with higher and higher payments in civil suits brought by
survivors, or settlements in suits among airlines, manufacturers
and component producers. Market share and public confidence are
also at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dispassionate fact-finding becomes problematic,'' said notes
by RAND for a briefing to executives on the National Transportation
Safety Board last month.
</P>
<P>
   The board had requested the study last year out of concern over
public criticism of accident investigations, especially air
crashes. Beyond concerns over the length of time investigations
take, families of the dead, and especially their lawyers, are
seeking a greater role in the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Those investigations follow what the board calls its ``party
system,'' under which it invites those with specific expertise to
help it investigate, but not analyze or draw conclusions. For
example, in the case of USAir 427, it had help from the airline,
the pilots' union, Boeing, the company that manufactured a suspect
hydraulic valve and the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia C. Lebow, a RAND analyst who is leading the study, said
in a telephone interview that ``the party process is essential in
many respects because the safety board is never going to be an
enormous agency, and it will never have the staff and the technical
capability to design an aircraft or operate an airline.''
</P>
<P>
   But of the parties, she said, ``you have to recognize that in
this day and age, those guys are coming in with multiple agendas,''
including limiting their legal liability and maintaining public
reputation and market share.
</P>
<P>
   The study recommends that the agency add more experts to its
staff, but also practice ``knowledge management,'' focusing on
where to find outside expertise, from NASA, the Defense Department,
national laboratories or academic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, top safety board officials say _ and the study
confirms _ that the agency lacks the resources to keep training its
investigators, as the complexity of airplanes, air traffic control
systems and related equipment advances year by year. In a survey,
40 percent of the investigators told RAND that they get no training
at all, the report said, and average training expenditure per
aviation employee was $2,000 a year, at a time when learning to fly
new models of airplanes could cost $15,000 to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the safety board's staff of about 400
people, of whom about half are investigators, has been ``operating
under continuing excessive workload.''
</P>
<P>
   Aviation investigators told RAND researchers that they work an
average of 51.5 hours a week, not counting periods of intense work
immediately after crashes, when they are in the field from sunup
until sundown, and meet every evening to compare notes.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials say that no matter what the investigators' pay
grade, their overtime is at the time-and-a-half rate of junior
employees, which is sometimes less than their straight-time pay.
Board officials say investigators for other agencies, sometimes
working shoulder-to-shoulder with NTSB investigators, receive
traditional time-and-a-half overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The study said many of the employees were eligible for
retirement, suggesting a looming personnel crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's budget request for the NTSB for the fiscal
year beginning Oct. 1 is $57 million, which is about equal to
spending in the current fiscal year, including extra funds voted by
Congress for TWA 800 and other special investigations. But the
safety board wants $73 million for overtime and training in fiscal
year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hire smart people, and then we work them hard, and we don't
train them,'' said Peter Goelz, the agency's managing director, in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Goelz said more money would allow the board to once more
complete major crash investigations in 12 to 18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
