<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GUMBEL, CBS AIMS TO COMPETE IN THE MORNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ CBS' decision to bring Bryant Gumbel back to morning
television, announced officially on Tuesday, raises the ante in the
competition among network morning programs, an area gaining more
attention from network executives because it offers far more
potential for increased profits than prime time or any other hours
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The network said it was creating an entirely new show to replace
``CBS This Morning'' and investing the most money it had ever spent
on morning television to try to become competitive at an hour when
CBS has never even been a serious ratings contender. It has
consistently finished third among the three network morning shows.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS News, said the morning was
a part of the day when audiences were growing. ``And there are very
few of those for network television,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel added: ``The skyrocketing production costs and diminished
numbers make prime time a very difficult area to grow profits.
Whereas the morning has been a pretty consistent block in terms of
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gumbel, a new program _ likely to have a new title _ and a
new studio, to be constructed in one of the most visible locations
in Manhattan, the corner of Fifth Avenue and 59th Street,
overlooking the entrance to Central Park, CBS is making a
commitment to compete head to head with General Electric's NBC.
That network's ``Today'' show, by far the dominant show in the
morning, has two entrenched stars in Katie Couric and Matt Lauer
and the prototype of the Manhattan tourist location, its set in
Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had already revamped its morning show ``Good Morning,
America'' in an effort to be more competitive with NBC by bringing
in two of its highest- profile correspondents, Diane Sawyer and
Charles Gibson, and beginning construction on its own
view-on-Manhattan set, on Broadway overlooking Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., made the move in
January, when ``Good Morning America'' had fallen to its lowest
ratings ever, occasionally even falling into third place behind
CBS. Since the addition of Ms. Sawyer and Gibson, the program has
reversed itself and is currently up more than 20 per cent from that
low point.
</P>
<P>
   ABC announced Ms. Sawyer and Gibson as temporary anchors until a
permanent team was found. But lately the network has emphasized
that this team will be in place for much longer than initially
expected, which was as short as three months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, CBS saw the interim status of the anchors at ``Good
Morning America'' as, in Heyward's words, ``a window of
opportunity.'' He said, ``As long as there is not a permanent plan
in place there, we have a chance to make some gains.''
</P>
<P>
   No one at CBS had more formidable morning credentials than
Gumbel, who was the centerpiece of the ``Today'' show for 15 years.
He left the show to join CBS and host a prime-time magazine show,
but that failed last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at going back to the morning as any kind of
comedown,'' Gumbel said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it like somebody who was a Broadway star and then went
and did a movie. And the movie wasn't a big box office smash and so
they decide to go back to Broadway. Does that make them a bomb? I
don't think so. I just think there are some people who are better
suited to Broadway. I love doing live television. I love doing
morning television.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS had struggled so much in morning television that three years
ago it scaled its program back, allowing its affiliated stations to
provide most of the material for the first hour of the program.
Now, Heyward said, the stations will be asked to commit to the
revamped show under Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   It is due to start in November, when the studio will be
complete. CBS still must add a female co-anchor to the program, a
decision Heyward said would be made ``in collaboration with
Bryant.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward did not disclose how much CBS is investing in the new
program but he said published figures, which have been in the range
of $20 million, were of a ``dimension that is essentially
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gumbel's deal, both he and Heyward declined to discuss if
it had been altered from the original $5 million a year contract he
signed when he joined the network. However, one executive familiar
with the terms of Gumbel's agreement said that the financial terms
had not changed because of this shift in assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The new studio will be on the ground floor of the General Motors
building, the same building that houses the FAO Schwarz toy store.
General Motors had used the space for a car showroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
