<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 U.S. WEIGHS REPATRIATING 2 POWs TO YUGOSLAVIA  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is considering freeing two
Yugoslav prisoners of war as a reciprocal gesture after the release
of three U.S. prisoners over the weekend, NATO and U.S. officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two low-ranking soldiers have been held at a U.S. military
base in Germany since being captured separately last month by
ethnic Albanian rebels who are fighting the Yugoslav army in
Kosovo. The rebels turned the captives over to Albania, which gave
them to the U.S. force in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who left Tuesday on a trip to NATO
headquarters in Brussels and to Germany, asked Defense Secretary
William Cohen to review the prisoners' status, said David Leavy, a
spokesman for the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said the president had not decided whether to release
them, although a NATO official said their release was expected in a
day or two, possibly during Clinton's visit to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Although the war against Yugoslavia is a NATO operation, the
United States has legal custody of the prisoners and can make a
decision unilaterally, Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ordered the three U.S.
soldiers released after meeting the Rev. Jesse Jackson. The three _
Staff Sgts. Andrew Ramirez and Christopher Stone, and Specialist
Steven Gonzales _ were part of a peacekeeping mission in Macedonia
unrelated to the NATO air war. They were captured while on patrol
near the border with Yugoslavia in circumstances that remain
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials had initially played down the idea of a
reciprocal release, fearing that it would seem like bargaining with
Milosevic. One official noted that the Yugoslav prisoners were
involved in the campaign against Kosovo Albanians and that the
Americans were not combatants.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has been eager to contrast the difference in
treatment of the prisoners. As required by the Geneva Conventions,
the International Committee of the Red Cross visited the first
Yugoslav prisoner, who was initially identified as a lieutenant but
is a private, within days of his capture in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is expected to visit the other captive Wednesday.
That prisoner, identified only as an enlisted soldier, was captured
late last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
