<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- BERGER-RACE, 5-04 -- Maurice
Berger is best known as the author of ``White Lies: Race and the
Myths of Whiteness,'' a book that is being widely read in circles
pondering issues of race and culture. The book's admirers say it
stands out from the many books about race because it is a detailed,
intimate look by a white man into his racial identity and
attitudes. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- May 4, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS-2, 5-04 --
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., packs up his papers after testimony
before the Senate Committe on Commerce, Science and Transportation
on Tuesday. Testimony before the committee on Tuesday, two weeks
after the shootings at Columbine High School, focused on the
marketing of violence particularly in movies and video games,
samples of which are in the foreground. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 4, 1999 -- COOLING-DIXIE, 5-04 -- A 1954
marketing brochure for Lennox air conditioners, left, and for ``The
New Silhouette Room Air Conditioner,'' an which was part of the
company's advertising campaign in 1955. Air conditioning is widely
credited for being the invention that put the buckle on the Sun
Belt and is being celebrated in a first-ever museum exhibition that
explores the profound social, cultural and architectural changes
wrought by the recent conquest of mankind's immediate climate. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 4, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 5-04 -- Sen.
Orin Hatch, R-Utah, holds up a copy of the computer game ``Quake,''
as Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., looks on during testimony before
the Senate Committe on Commerce, Science and Transportation on
Tuesday. Hatch told the committee that the game was an example of
how products using violence, intended for adults, commonly end up
in the hands of children. Testimony before the committee on
Tuesday, coming two weeks after the shootings at Columbine High
School, focused on the marketing of violence particularly in movies
and video games. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 4, 1999 -- HOME-FRENCH-FRIES, 5-04 -- Few
foods cross as many boundaries as the french fry. With bistro food
becoming the everyday equivalent of pizza and countless Belgian
restaurants serving frites opening up, the french fry seems to be
everywhere. Wherever it appears, though, it is nothing more than a
slice of potato deep-fried and seasoned with salt. (Igor
Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- RESTAURANTS-CELL-PHONES-2,
5-04 -- Many customers in New York City bars and restaurants have
complained about cell phone use prompting restaurant owners to post
signs banning them. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- RESTAURANTS-CELL-PHONES-1,
5-04 -- Kevin Duncan uses his cell phone while having lunch in a
restaurant in Greenwich Village. Many customers in New York City
restaurants have complained about cell phone use in dining rooms
and restaurant owners are begining to ban them. (Norman Y. Lono/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
