<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-SCENE-HNS &LR;      05-04 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOCK AFTER BLOCK, THERE'S LITTLE LEFT IN THIS NEIGHBORHOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Tornado-deaths, Tornado-trauma, Tornado-witnesses,
Tornado-Kansas and Tornado-weather.) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ The trees, those that are left standing,
have been stripped raw, their splintered limbs left to claw the
sky. Instead of leaves and branches, they carry scraps of
corkscrewed steel, a child's crib, the occasional car.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Tuesday, the people who lived in a collection
of modest homes known as the Crosby edition were trickling back
into their flattened neighborhood to begin digging out anything
salvageable. For block after block here, there wasn't much left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody all right?'' yelled one woman to the neighbors she
hadn't seen since the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' came the answer. ``We were in the cellar.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these homeless storm survivors exhibited an almost eerie
cheeriness as they pulled out chairs, photos and scraps of
clothing, and loaded their lives into the trunks of cars. But in
their least guarded moments, these victims stand on piles of debris
that used to be home can't seem to manage much more than a blank
stare.
</P>
<P>
   The storm plowed through nearby Del City, skipped across
Interstate 40, and then blasted a swatch about a quarter-mile wide
and two miles long through Midwest City. At least three people died
in this little community, and about 320 homes were either leveled
or so damaged as to be unlivable.
</P>
<P>
   At least 44 people, 38 in Oklahoma, died Monday as twisters
ripped through the region.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the worst devastation, there's a U.S. flag
waving from a makeshift stand in Lena Klepackie's soggy front yard.
A few yards behind it, a little stack of timber and a couple of
sheetrock walls are still standing to mark the hallway where nine
members of Klepackie's family huddled against the killer storm.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a bad week already.
</P>
<P>
   Klepackie's son had died after a heart attack, and her family
was sitting a vigil next to his casket at a nearby funeral home
when the weather warnings were issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back from the viewing to find a safe place for the
kids,'' Klepackie said. They were shoehorned into the small hallway
for nearly a half hour before the tornado roared overhead, and
Klepackie hollered for her family to ``tuck and duck.''
</P>
<P>
   Klepackie theorizes her recently deceased son arranged a little
divine intervention for her family. They found his picture lying on
the floor of the hallway once the storm blew threw.
</P>
<P>
   Klepackie's daughter, Taunya Griffith wasn't sure how to explain
that flag waving stubbornly in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she said. ``I guess to keep us together, you
know, helping each other out. That's what America's about.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks over, Wayne Canfield was rooting through his
elderly parents belongings, looking for family photos and the
things that can't be replaced. The three-bedroom house that Harley
and Minnie Canfield had lived in was gone, though a large chunk of
its flooring had landed on a neighbor's house across the street.
</P>
<P>
   That's where neighbors found the Canfields, buried under debris
but alive and still clinging to that patch of briefly airborne
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Canfield laughed about how stubborn his parents were, and
how they'd resisted moving into a smaller home or apartment. He
pointed to a crumpled mountain of tin cans spilling across their
property, and explained, ``They were getting ready for the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The area is thick with law enforcement officers, positioned on
nearly every corner to guard against looters. Those hardest hit in
Midwest City were having to show proof of identity before being
issued an orange pass that would allow them access past police
lines back into their homes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall, those left homeless would be ordered back out.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard is patrolling the blasted commercial strip
that hugs 15th Street along the southern edge of this community as
utility trucks begin the slow job of restoring power. Long lines of
military vehicles were still snaking into Midwest City as nightfall
approached.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Baldwin was walking up and down the street in front of
her flattened house, her jaw jutting out against the unfairness of
it all. She lost her husband about 18 months ago, and now the house
he'd filled with hand-made furniture was gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   She rode out the storm in her hallway also, with pillows
clutched over her head. Her 15-year-old son, Bradley, had been
visiting friends up the street when the storm hit, but came rushing
back to look for his mother in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him say, `Momma, Momma, are you all right? I can't
lose you after losing Daddy,''' Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son asked me (later) how I survived,'' said Baldwin,
nodding to what was left of her house. ``I said, `Don't ask.``
</P>
<P>
   Standing out in the street, shaking her head in frustration, she
said she didn't know what she was going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a beautiful neighborhood,'' she sighed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
