   (NYT28) ATLANTA -- May 4, 1999 -- MARKETPLACE-COKE, 5-04 -- M.
Douglas Ivester, chairman and chief executive officer of Coca Cola,
at the corporation's world headquarters in October, 1998. Ivester,
the mastermind of Coca-Cola's worldwide bottling network, stood by
like a proud uncle through most of the 1990's as the company racked
up impressive gains in sales and profits. Today, though, Ivester's
grand plan is faltering. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- ASTHMA-HOMELESS-KIDS, 5-04 --
Maritza Colon craddles her 10-month old son Matthew undergoing
asthma treatment at a hospital on Tuesday. A study has found that
at least 38 percent of homeless children in the city's shelters
have asthma, more than six times the national rate and more than
double the rate found by an earlier study of some of the city's
poorest neighborhoods. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) FORT-DIX, N.J. -- May 4, 1999 -- NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
5-04 -- Agents with the Immigration and Naturalization Service go
over proceedures for admitting refugees from Kosovo on Tuesday. The
first of 400 refugees, presently in camps in Macedonia, will begin
to arrive on Wednesday. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- May 4, 1999 --
SUB-WAR-CRIMINALS-I-1, 5-04 -- Carl Dorelien, a former Haitian army
colonel, now lives along with his family in this Florida resort
community on a visa granted him by the same government that
launched a full-scale invasion and spent $2.2 billion to remove him
and his fellow officers from power. Dorelien's case is not an
isolated one. A Globe investigation has discovered a broad range of
people who have gained refuge in the United States over the last
several years despite evidence of their involvement in serious
human rights abuses. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- BROADWAY-DANCERS-2, 5-04 --
Amy Brewer, center, in a Manhattan dance class. Ms. Brewer, a
22-year-old from Seattle who arrived in New York last July,
represents life at the bottom of the dance food chain. ``I feel my
time will come,'' she says. ``You have to feel that way if you want
to do this.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- BROADWAY-DANCERS-1, 5-04 --
Scott Wise and Elizabeth Parkinson, stretching, are two of the
featured dancers in ``Fosse.'' ``In ballet, you have to keep a
higher level technically, so in one way it's physically more
demanding,'' says Ms. Parkinson, who at 25 is the youngest dancer
in the show. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NAPA VALLEY, Calif. -- May 4, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 5-04 --
Phylloxera, the dreaded parasite that had devastated the vines of
Europe and California a century before, sparked an epidemic in the
Napa Valley in the early '90s. But by 1996, tighter plantings and
new kinds of trellises yielded more flavorful grapes at this Robert
Mondavi vineyard. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HANOK, South Korea -- May 4, 1999 --
KOREA-GENERATION-GAP, 5-04 -- ``When I was young I did what my
mother-in-law said,'' said Park Ki Soon, 70, as she used a wooden
paddle to churn a couldron of beans. ``But now my daughter-in-law
doesn't listen to me.'' Korea was one of the last places to open up
to Western influences, for until a century ago it was an ancient
kingdom that operated on Confucian traditions and deeply regimented
customs. Those customs, especially respect for the elderly,
permeated Korean society until the last few decades. (Nicholas
Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- May 4, 1999 -- LOUIMA-TRIAL, 5-04 --
Attorney Marvin Kornberg, right, escorts New York City Police
Officer Justin Volpe from the U.S. District courthouse in Brooklyn
on Tuesday. Volpe is one of five New York City police officers on
trial after being indicted on federal civil rights charges in the
case of Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant allegedly beaten and
sodomized in a police station. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) JERUSALEM -- May 4, 1999 -- MIDEAST-PEACE-2, 5-04 --
Palestinians watch a ceremony for Arab dignitaries in front of
Orient House, the unofficial Palestinian headquarters in the Arab
section of east Jerusalem on Tuesday. Under diplomatic pressure, an
announcement of statehood planned for this date, was cancelled by
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) STANKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 4, 1999 --
DISASTER-INDUSTRY, 5-04 -- Gregory Spitzfaden, an American
businessman with the British company Tri-Med, which sells supplies
to humanitarian aid groups, sits atop his company's products at a
refugee camp last month. Spitzfaden, whose office is in
Peterborough, N. H., said that company got its start when its three
founders began arranging the shipment of relief items bought with
the proceeds from charity rock concerts like ``Live Aid'' and
``Band Aid.'' (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) JERUSALEM -- May 4, 1999 -- MIDEAST-PEACE, 5-04 -- An
Orthodox Jew places an Israeli flag on a site near Orient House,
the unofficial Palestinian political headquarters, on Tuesday.
Moledet, a right-wing party, organized a mass gathering at the site
on the date Palestinians said they were planning to announce
statehood. Under diplomatic pressure, the announcement was
cancelled. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LITTLETON, Colo. -- May 4, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING,
5-04 --Volunteers and parks department employees work to remove
memorials left near Columbine High School on Tuesday. Parks
department officials said they are trying to consolidate the
ever-expanding memorial and remove materials from muddy, slippery
hills that put visitors at risk. Many of the items left in memory
of the 13 students killed at the high school will be stored by the
Colorado Historical Society. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PRISTINA, Kosovo -- May 4, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PRISTINA-1,
5-04 -- A woman visits the central cemetery on Tuesday near where
an errant bomb, dropped during the opening days of NATO's bombing
campaign, destroyed several tombs. Serbs and a few Albanians are
trickling back to Pristina, Kosovo's capital. The sunny daytime
streets, with a few pedestrians and shoppers, now display a poor
imitation of ordinary life. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- May 4, 1999 -- GERTNER-BOS, 5-04 -- Juge Nancy
Gertner in her Federal courtroom. Gertner will decide soon whether
she has the authority to reopen the case of a man serving a life
sentence for the 1988 slaying of 12-year-old Darlene Tiffany Moore
during one of Boston's most notorious gang gunfights. If she does,
the move would run counter to the federal trend against reopening
criminal cases tried in state court. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BURLINGTON, Vt. -- May 4, 1999 -- WAR-CRIMINALS-II, 5-04
-- Zijad Music is hardly a typical refugee of the war in the former
Yugoslavia. Although he entered the United States by portraying
himself as a victim of ethnic cleansing, Music appears to have been
a participant in one of the most brutal episodes of the war: the
deadly purge of some 60,000 non-Serbian civilians from Prijedor and
its surrounding villages in northwestern Bosnia. (Wendy
Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MIDWEST CITY, Okla. -- May 4, 1999 -- OKLA-STORMS-5,
5-04 -- Toby Henry, 11, steps through what remains of his home on
Tuesday. The death toll stood at 36 on Tuesday after fierce
tornadoes destroyed entire neighborhoods in Oklahoma and Kansas.
One monstrous twister chewed across miles of Tornado Alley for four
hours. (Michael Wyke/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOORE, Okla. -- May 4, 1999 -- OKLA-STORMS-4, 5-04 -- A
pedestrian walks past destroyed buildings on Tuesday. The death
toll stood at 36 on Tuesday after fierce tornadoes destroyed entire
neighborhoods in Oklahoma and Kansas. One monstrous twister chewed
across miles of Tornado Alley for four hours. (Michael Wyke/New
York Times Photo)
