<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF GOLDMAN RISE 33 PERCENT ON FIRST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Goldman Sachs Group Inc. soared on their
first day of trading, making Wall Street's longest holdout its
latest darling.
</P>
<P>
   Trading under the symbol GS on the New York Stock Exchange, the
shares rose $17.375, or 33 percent, from their $53 offering price,
closing at $70.375. Though the stock was well off a high of $77 a
share, investors who bought at the offering price have a paper
windfall considerably larger than the 10 percent to 15 percent
increase many investors hope to receive when a large company like
Goldman first issues shares.
</P>
<P>
   The offering ended Goldman's status as Wall Street's last big
private partnership. It joined the ranks of publicly traded
securities firms more than a decade after the last of its big
competitors issued shares. Goldman ended the day ranked third in
terms of market value, behind Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and
Charles Schwab, and a notch ahead of Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Paulson, Goldman's co-chairman and chief executive, led a
team of Goldman executives on to the floor of the New York Stock
Exchange to ceremonially supervise the first day of trading, and
rang the exchange's opening bell. Some 14,000 employees around the
world then watched on closed-circuit television as the firm's
initial-offering team counted down to the first trade of a Goldman
share, which changed hands at $76 about an hour after the market
opened.
</P>
<P>
   The rise was not as drastic in percentage terms as some initial
offerings by Internet companies. But at $3.7 billion, Goldman's
share sale was the second-largest domestic issue of all time after
Conoco's $4.4 billion initial offering last year. Many new Internet
companies raise a small fraction of that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The rise added greatly to the already considerable paper wealth
of Goldman's top executives. Paulson, for example, saw his stake
rise $95 million, to almost $315 million, for the day. Jon S.
Corzine, the co-chairman who lost his executive role in a struggle
with Paulson earlier this year, will leave Goldman later this month
with a $335 million paper nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, employees below the level of partner, down to the
level of janitor and receptionist, were allocated 116 million
shares. If those shares could be sold today _ they are not tradable
for up to five years _ they would be worth $8.12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, of course, earned it pinstripes underwriting stock
issues, and it was not about to fumble its own. Like every company
that goes public, Goldman had an underwriting syndicate. Unlike
most other companies, Goldman micro-managed its own offering: even
the top underwriters were relieved of the burden of finding buyers
for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just handed us a check _ easiest money we ever made,''
the executive of one firm listed as a top underwriter said of its
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The opening was exceptionally smooth. Although about 22 million
shares changed hands during the day, the price was contained within
a relatively narrow range after the opening. One reason was that
Goldman found investors that it expects to hold the shares long
term instead of dumping them when the price spikes temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders hold most of the stock. Goldman sold only 15 percent of
its shares on Tuesday. Most outside investors are prized Goldman
clients, including mutual and pension funds and wealthy private
clients.
</P>
<P>
   The performance was strong despite a slump in financial stocks
generally. Merrill fell $5.5625, to $81.6875, while Morgan Stanley
was off $6.75 at $98.125.
</P>
<P>
   Some market analysts said the resilience of Goldman's offering
on a turbulent trading day suggested that the firm easily could
have raised the price of the shares before trading, earning more
money for the company instead of its investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just shaking my head that this stock could add so many
billions on opening in a sloppy market,'' said Ted Aronson of
Aronson &AMP; Partners, a Philadelphia-based fund manager. ``They left
a lot of money on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman now faces the task of managing itself as a public
company after 130 years as a private one. That means further
opening its cloistered culture to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
