r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STARWARS-TOYS-SF     05-04 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STARWARS-TOYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INVASION HAS BEGUN: `STAR WARS' TOY ONSLAUGHT STRIKES
STORES  EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STACK  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toys from the forthcoming movie ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The
Phantom Menace'' arrived in stores Monday and became a force on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of ``Episode 1'' merchandise _ including dinnerware,
underwear and kids' bikes _ marked the first time any release of
licensed products from a movie had gone nationwide on a specific
target date. Stores across the country opened at midnight Monday
morning in compliance with contracts with ``Phantom Menace''
director George Lucas' Lucasfilm.
</P>
<P>
   The latest plastic good-versus-evil action figures, as well as a
menagerie of creature characters, droids, and space and land
vehicles, provided the first mass glimpse at how Lucas'
much-anticipated film, which opens May 19, will look.
</P>
<P>
   From the get-go, a spiky supervillain named Darth Maul ($10-$40
in various versions) _ essentially the new Darth Vader _ was a hit
with toy buyers. He's a ferocious, punky warrior with horns, a
reddish mottled face and yellow eyes, who wields a double-edged
lightsaber (also new) against Jedi heroes Qui-Gon Jinn and Obi-Wan
Kenobi. Their mission in the new film, a ``prequel'' to the first
trilogy, is to protect the beautiful, peace-loving Queen Amidala.
</P>
<P>
   Another instant hit were the toy battle droids, which stand 6
feet 3 in the film. These mechanical figures with equine heads are
shown advancing in a mass platoon in the ``Phantom Menace''
trailers playing at theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the hot new ``Star Wars'' toys:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VEHICLES
</P>
<P>
   The slick yellow and silver Naboo Royal N-1 Starfighter is a
signature ``Episode 1'' flying machine, piloted by 9-year-old
Anakin Skywalker (the future Darth Vader) with help from R2-D2.
It's best realized in a $29.99 ``electronic'' form from Hasbro that
hums and lights up. Galoob also has a scaled-down version for
$10.99. In addition, Lego, new to Star Wars licensing, issued a
174-piece kit ($19.99) for kids who want to build their own
Starfighters.
</P>
<P>
   Young Anakin proves his Jedi potential in a thrill-ride Pod Race
in the trade-center city of Mos Espa on the planet of Tatooine in
the new film. His Podracer (Hasbro, $29.99), with a sledlike
driving station attached to jets, takes lightning-fast reflexes to
operate in the film and is bound to be a favorite toy. An Anakin
figure is included. Lego's interlocking version sells for $14.99.
</P>
<P>
   The best of several versions of the Naboo Royal Starship, Queen
Amidala's sleek silver personal-transport vessel, is a $25 model by
Estes that either rests on a desktop stand or can be turned into a
flying rocket (rocket kit sold separately) with a flight altitude
of 300 feet (parental guidance recommended).
</P>
<P>
   Trade Federation transport ships are also on store shelves.
Probably the most popular will be the Multi-Troop Transport (MTT),
a cumbersome, utilitarian vehicle. Galoob's version sells for
$10.99.
</P>
<P>
   The reddish-pink Jedi Transport named Radiant VII is an unarmed
diplomatic vessel _ and a cool-looking toy. Other new vehicles are
the menacing Sith Infiltrator (Lego's version is $29.99) and a dark
Gungan sub that transports friendly creature Jar Jar Binks and
heroes Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan to the Naboo city of Theed. There are
also Trade Federation Droid Fighters that can go from flight mode
to walking mode, and Trade Federation Armored Attack tanks piloted
by battle droids.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHARACTERS
</P>
<P>
   In the forthcoming movie, Obi-Wan Kenobi (portrayed in the new
movie by Ewan McGregor) is a Jedi knight apprentice. His mentor in
using the Force and in lightsaber techniques is Jedi master Qui-Gon
Jinn (Liam Neeson). They discover a promising young Jedi in a
Tatooine slave named Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd). On the small,
peaceful planet of Naboo, all undertake a mission to protect young
Queen Amidala (Natalie Portman) from evil. Mace Windu (Samuel L.
Jackson) is a senior Jedi Master and member of the Jedi Council, as
is the much-respected Yoda _ but Yoda is younger in ``Episode 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Action figures (most from Hasbro) representing almost all the
characters are the biggest sellers already and easily the most
accessible, since they cost $10 or less.
</P>
<P>
   A new gadget called a COMMtech Reader ensures their popularity _
the $21.99 device enables the action figures to talk to one
another. Each Hasbro figure comes with a ``dialogue chip'' that has
four lines of dialogue implanted in it. Insert the chip into the
figure, power up the reader (batteries sold separately) and a
control panel allows the figure to speak phrases.
</P>
<P>
   C-3PO is represented among action figures as an unfinished
bundle of wires, since ``Episode 1'' precedes the familiar ``Star
Wars'' stories. He was originally just a protocol droid, according
to the toy's packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Bad guys represented by action figures include Darth Sidious, a
lord of darkness who orders evil Darth Maul to ``wipe them out, all
of them'' on Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   Bad creatures include Neimoidians and their viceroy, Nute
Gunray, who help to carry out a Sith Lord's destructive orders. A
Sando Aqua Monster, Opee Sea Killer and Colo Claw Fish are also
ferocious.
</P>
<P>
   Gungans, a race of amphibians living on planet Naboo, speak a
strange fractured dialect (picked up by the COMMtech Reader). A
crowd-pleasing creature is a googly-eyed critter named Jar Jar who
helps out the Jedi heroes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WEAPONS
</P>
<P>
   The big items here are lightsabers, and easily the most
interesting new one is Darth Maul's double-edged model (Hasbro,
$29.99), which emits an ``energy hum,'' lights up on contact and is
expandable to five feet, tip to tip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
