<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY CHAIRMAN TESTIFIES IN FORMER AIDE'S FRAUD SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The chairman of Walt Disney Co., Michael Eisner,
testifying Tuesday for the first time in the lawsuit by his former
studio chief, Jeffrey Katzenberg, disputed Katzenberg's contention
that Disney owes him hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also came under intense questioning from Katzenberg's
lawyer about harsh personal remarks he had made about Katzenberg as
well as a comment to his biographer that he hated his former studio
chief.
</P>
<P>
   After acknowledging that he had said this, Eisner added: ``I did
not hate Katzenberg. I do not hate Katzenberg.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came in Katzenberg's fraud and breach-of-contract
suit against Walt Disney. Katzenberg has insisted that Disney owes
him at least $250 million. The former studio chief, who worked with
Eisner for more than a decade, contends he is owed a bonus on all
future profits of Disney movies made while he was at the studio.
Disney had agreed to a settlement, but nothing close to $250
million.
</P>
<P>
   With Katzenberg staring intently at his former boss, Eisner said
that Katzenberg had agreed to forfeit a substantial bonus if he
left the company before his contract expired. Eisner said that
Katzenberg, in one of their conversations, seemed unconcerned about
the huge bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of those conversations he had that flip attitude,''
Eisner said. The Disney chairman said that Katzenberg told him,
``I'm not going to exercise that so don't worry. I have to have it
for my comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Eisner said he told Katzenberg that he was
going to lose $100 million in compensation if he left the company
early. Eisner said, ``He acknowledged he was leaving $100 million
on the table and on one occasion he said, `It's no big deal. I'll
get that back in no amount of time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his relationship with Katzenberg _ which is now
severed _ Eisner said that he did not have ``major
misunderstandings or major angst,'' but there may have been one or
two contentious conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going to the dentist,'' Eisner said. ``You forget
the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing grew somewhat lively in midafternoon when
Katzenberg's attorney, Bert Fields, embarrassed Eisner by referring
to unpublished notes from his autobiography, ``Work in Progress,''
published last year. The notes were taken by Eisner's ghostwriter,
Tony Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Fields asked Eisner if he recalled saying that Katzenberg was
``the pom-pom'' spurring Disney's success, and on another occasion
saying of the studio executive, ``I think I hate the little
midget.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner told Fields that the comments were completely private,
and occurred in the course of hundreds of hours of interviews and
never appeared in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pursue this line of questioning,'' Eisner told Fields,
``it will put in the public record things which I do not think
deserve to be in the public record.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner avoided gazing at Katzenberg, who sat with his wife,
Marilyn, only several feet away. Instead, Eisner focused his
attention on Katzenberg's lawyer, Fields, who represents numerous
film and television stars.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg left Disney studios in anger in 1994 when Eisner
failed to promote him to the No. 2 job, following the death of
Frank Wells, Disney's president, in a helicopter crash. Two years
later, after unsuccessfully seeking an incentive bonus that he said
was owed to him, Katzenberg sued Disney for at least $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg said that the bonus entitled him to 2 percent of the
profits from the films and television shows _ as well as the
merchandising from those films _that were put into production
during the 10 years he ran Disney studios. In November 1997, Disney
and Katzenberg announced a settlement, essentially saying that the
former studio chief was due some bonus money. But the two sides
have failed to reach any agreement on the exact sum. Last week
Michael Ovitz, the former Disney president, had suggested a
compromise of about $100 million, but Eisner refused.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Eisner acknowledged that he told his biographer, in
unpublished notes, that he would not give Katzenberg any money.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner acknowledged that when Disney agreed in 1984 that
Katzenberg would get a bonus, it was relatively meaningless. ``The
residual value of the films were very minor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this changed after 1988 when Disney began releasing its
lucrative animated films like ``Little Mermaid,'' ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' ``Aladdin'' and ``The Lion King.'' These films, as well as
a number of children's movies made while Katzenberg ran the studio,
reaped huge sums in merchandising and other spinoffs as well as
video sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
