</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-YUGOSLAVIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN PLANS RELIEF MISSION FOR YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced Tuesday
that he intended to send a mission to Yugoslavia to assess relief
needs, but faced immediate skepticism from the United States and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs,
Sergio Vieira de Mello, wrote Tuesday to the Yugoslav
representative here to request permission for the team to enter the
country. U.N. relief agencies have not been in Kosovo since shortly
after the NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Such a mission, Annan told reporters, would enable the United
Nations to ``prepare the ground for the refugees to go back to
Kosovo'' after there is an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But American and Russian officials complained that they had not
had a chance to study the proposal and blocked Security Council
endorsement for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining about a lack of coordination between Washington and
Annan's office, American officials said they had learned about the
statement minutes before Annan briefed the council. They said they
were uncertain whether the safety of such a team could be assured
in view of the bombing, which they said would not be interrupted to
ease the team's work.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official said Washington would have to study
the proposal to ensure, among other factors, that sending a team
would not suggest that NATO was willing to suspend the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Annan spoke to reporters after having briefed the 15-member
Security Council on his talks in Germany and Russia and, Tuesday,
with the special Russian envoy on the Balkans, Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the talks in Berlin and Moscow, Annan said, he felt
that there was general agreement on the basic issues, that is the
``withdrawal of Yugoslav forces,'' both militia and police, from
Kosovo and the need for the refugees to be able to return ``in a
secure environment assured by a presence of international force.''
</P>
<P>
   Still at issue, he added, is ``how do we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there seems to be a consensus on the need for an
international force in Kosovo, there is no agreement, Annan said,
on ``the composition, nature and strength of the force'' and on the
extent of the Serbian withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said if Yugoslavia agreed to accept the mission,
a team that represented at least 10 agencies could leave as early
as Saturday. They plan to survey all the provinces of Yugoslavia,
starting in Kosovo, in 10 days, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and American officials expressed uneasiness about the
mission. The Russian representative to the United Nations, Sergey
Lavrov, said the objections of two council members to the proposed
wording of the announcement kept the council president from
including any endorsement of the proposal in his summary of the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lavrov did not clarify his specific objections,
American officials strongly criticized the lack of coordination
between Annan's office and the United States on the Kosovo crisis
and on other actions.
</P>
<P>
   American officials were widely known to be displeased, for
instance, with a statement that Annan made on Wednesday in Berlin
that deplored the loss of life as a result of the Kosovo conflict.
After meeting Cornelio Sommaruga, president of the International
Committee of the Red Cross, Annan said that although ``we've all
been consumed with the tragedy of the Kosovo Albanians,'' the
``negative impact'' of the crisis was ``spreading through the
subregion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
