<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      05-04 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVES FOR EUROPE AS NATO FORCES POUND YUGOSLAV POSITIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
and GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As bombers pounded Yugoslavia and Republicans
rhetorically pummeled the White House, President Clinton departed
Tuesday for Europe to meet with NATO officials, the freed U.S.
soldiers and Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   For a second day, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin met with
Vice President Al Gore as Moscow's former prime minister sought a
diplomatic solution to the NATO air campaign against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's Serbian forces. Still, there was no
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot see what we have seen with our own eyes and take
refuge in the false comfort of indifference of impatience. We have
to take a stance. We have done that. We have to see our effort
through. We will do that,'' Clinton told reporters as he left the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke hours after NATO forces intensified their campaign
against ground troops in Kosovo and after the Senate, under intense
White House lobbying, shelved a war resolution that would have
given Clinton broad power to initiate a ground invasion of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is prepared to lose a war
rather than do the hard work, the politically risky work, of
fighting it as the leader of the greatest nation on earth should
fight when our interests and our values are imperiled,'' the
resolution's sponsor, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., asserted in a
speech that also was bitterly critical of Republican and Democratic
senators who voted to table his resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the president reaffirmed his commitment to continue
the bombing until Milosevic withdraws his forces from Kosovo,
allows the Kosovar refugees to return home under the protection of
international security force, and accepts self-government for
Kosovo's predominantly ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin met for 45 minutes with Gore, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and national security adviser Sandy Berger at
the vice president's residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, NATO countries and Russia are moving closer
to a common set of objectives and a common understanding of the
rationale for those objectives, and hopefully, at some point, a
common plan for implementing those objectives,'' said State
Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said at his meeting Monday with Chernomyrdin that he
``reaffirmed our support for (Chernomyrdin's) efforts and our
willingness to seize every diplomatic possibility for Serbian
authorities to meet the requirements that NATO has articulated.''
Clinton broached the possibility of a pause in the bombing if
Milosevic showed signs of accepting NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   The president will meet Wednesday in Brussels, Belgium, with
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana and NATP Supreme Commander
Gen. Wesley Clark to discuss the progress in the North American
Treaty Organization's air campaign. Clinton said he will meet with
the pilots based in Spangleheim Air Base, Germany, and visit
humanitarian relief operations at Ramstein Air Base, Germany. He
also will meet with the three Americans captured by Yugoslav troops
and released this weekend to the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our men and women in uniform are doing their jobs with
uncommon courage and skill. They have the support of the American
people. They should hear unqualified support from their leaders in
Washington,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the president will meet with German Chancellor
Gerhardt Schroeder and hear first-hand stories from Kosovar
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will assure them of our determination and resolve to see
them returned with security and self-government,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will meet the first planeload
of an expected 20,000 Kosovar Albanians being flown to New Jersey
for a temporary safe haven. The United States and European nations
are taking in some of the 600,000 ethnic Albanians forced out of
Kosovo by Yugoslav troops.
</P>
<P>
   On the military front, clearing weather allowed NATO to fly 600
sorties against 80 targets Tuesday as the European alliance
sharpened and stepped up its attacks against Serb military targets
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon reported that a U.S. F-16 fighter downed a Yugoslav
MiG-29 in a dogfight while NATO bombers destroyed another MiG-29
and a Super Galeb attack plane on the ground. The Yugoslav Air
Force has only four Russian-made MiG-29s left of the original 15
jets it had before the bombing began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces also are taking a toll on Milosevic's armor and
soldiers, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say probably 25 percent of his tanks, armored
personnel carriers and trucks were destroyed in Kosovo,'' said U.S.
Air Force Gen. Charles Wald, estimating 16 tanks and personnel
carriers were destroyed in overnight raids Tuesday. He said
American B-52s also dropped 54 500-pound bombs on Serb ground
troops during the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the talk of increasing success from U.S. military
leaders, a divided Congress continued to question whether an air
campaign alone can stop Milosevic's plan to purge Kosovo of its
ethnic Albanian population, which accounts for more than 90 percent
of the Yugoslav province's citizens.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for example, said the United States and its NATO allies
``are not winning this conflict'' because Clinton refuses thus far
to commit NATO ground troops to battle against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that the president is losing this war,'' McCain, a
candidate for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination, said in
a CNN interview, ``because Milosevic is continuing his ethnic
cleansing and ... we are unable to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain sought to force the president's hand on ground troops
with his resolution calling for use of ``all necessary force and
other means'' to bring the war to a quick end.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate shelved the measure by a vote of 78-22, with only
13 Democrats and nine Republicans supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and members of his Cabinet have joined with the
opponents of the war and lobbied hard for the resolution's
defeat,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, McCain called it ``indefensible'' for Clinton
repeatedly to rule out the use of ground troops, and said the
president's reluctance had only emboldened Milosevic to escalate
his bloody campaign against Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a fact of this war that is undeniable. And shame on
the president for creating it,'' McCain told his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh comments drew a sharp response from House Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., who said it was ``unfair and
inaccurate'' to attack the president ``in this way.'' He expressed
outrage at the treatment McCain and other Republicans were giving
Clinton, noting that no other American president he was aware of
had ever had to endure such criticism from lawmakers that Clinton
has while U.S. forces are engaged in hostilities abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has not asked for this authority, nor have his
military advisers,'' Daschle told his colleagues. ``The air
campaign is working. This is not a matter of lack of courage, this
is not a matter of lack of resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continues to draw support from public opinion polls
showing that 58 percent of Americans prefer the president's tactic
for now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
