<SLUG> BC-FHS-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS ANTICIPATION BOOSTS FHS STOCK 9.9 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in first graf refers to Wednesday.) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in managed care specialist Foundation
Health Systems Inc. rose nearly 10 percent Tuesday on anticipation
of improved quarterly earnings due out today.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation stock gained $1.375, or 9.9 percent, to close at
$15.25, on volume of 1.27 million shares or roughly three times its
30-day average trading volume. Tuesday's close was the stock's
highest this year.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation is expected this morning to announce earnings of
approximately $28 million, or 23 cents per share, compared with 22
cents per share in the like period one year ago. Though
year-on-year not much of a gain, the earnings are a clear
improvement over Foundation's recent quarterly performance. The
company lost $104 million in the last quarter of 1998, for an
annual loss of $164 million.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that stemmed from the poor performance of the company's
Medicare contracts in the northeast United States. In several
counties, Foundation subsidiaries spent more providing care to
elderly members than they were paid by the government. Analysts say
they are looking for news of a turnaround in that sector in the
company's conference call today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a turnaround in the Northeast, a lot of the other
issues become secondary or tertiary,'' said analyst Robert Hoehn at
ING Baring Furman Selzs in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Among those secondary concerns is Foundation's high debt load.
The company owes creditors more than $1 billion stemming from its
rapid growth through the purchase of competitors over the last
decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
