<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GROUP PARALYZED BY LEADERSHIP DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The diplomatic struggle over who should be the next
head of the World Trade Organization continued unabated Tuesday
while most work at the global trade forum seemed to grind to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   After putting off deliberations for a day, the chairman of the
search team jolted delegates at a meeting Tuesday by declaring that
the candidacy of Suphachai Panichpakdi of Thailand was over and
that the group should consider only his rival, Michael Moore of New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Ali Mchumo, Tanzania's trade delegate, set
forth vigorous protests from Suphachai's supporters, led by Asian
countries, as the meeting stretched late into the evening with no
final decision. Delegates will meet again, after taking ``time for
reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Suphachai declared that he was
``confident of the outcome'' but criticized the selection process
as taking too long. ``I won't say that I feel cheated, but a number
of countries seem to feel the whole process was not consistent,''
he said. In Thailand, where Suphachai is a deputy prime minister,
there has been an outcry against the United States, which was seen
as the chief obstacle to his winning the international post.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of reviewing four initial candidates, the field
was winnowed to the two recent candidates. Mchumo, who heads the
trade organization's decision-making General Council, announced on
Friday that Moore had edged out Suphachai, by a vote of 62-59,
among the members and should be nominated as the new
director-general.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings over the weekend, some vitriolic, among envoys of the
134-nation trade forum failed to come up with a choice or even
agree on a method of proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Mchumo urged the delegates to wrap up the selection or, he said,
``we shall see the intensification of the already unhealthy
divisiveness, recrimination, mistrust and erosion of friendships
which has already taken its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when he declared that the process was over for
Suphachai, representatives of two dozen countries took to the floor
to disagree and to argue that the race was too close to count him
out. Kenya's envoy proposed that Mchumo sound out delegates on
Suphachai's acceptability as the new WTO chief, and Mchumo
eventually agreed to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the option of a vote to decide between the two
candidates, although many countries oppose this as contrary to the
four-year-old organization's way of doing business by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   If the deadlock continues, diplomats increasingly were
entertaining the possibility of jettisoning both candidates and
starting over.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the meeting got under way, Renato Ruggiero, the
outgoing director-general, whose selection four years ago had been
marked by bitterness, officially left his post and drove off,
foreclosing the option that he might stay on to tide the trade
group over until it resolved its leadership crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
