<HEADLINE>
AMWEST GROUP TO QUIT WRITING CALIFORNIA HOMEOWNERS POLICIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ Amwest Insurance Group reported a 15 percent
increase in earnings for the first quarter and announced that it
was pulling out of the California homeowners insurance and Arizona
automobile markets.
</P>
<P>
   The holding company for Amwest Surety Insurance, Condor
Insurance and Far West Insurance credited an improvement in risk
factors for better business. But the company has decided not to
write homeowners policies in California and private passenger
insurance in Arizona because they weren't paying off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results just weren't that good,'' said Steven Kay, chief
financial officer of Amwest, based in Calabasas, northwest of Los
Angeles. ``These two were ancillary markets we got sidetracked
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Amwest wasn't writing a lot of homeowners insurance in
California in the first place, which left the company vulnerable to
a handful of big claims, Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Arizona, ``It's tough to make money there,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Amwest is concentrating on commercial trucking
insurance. The company began improving its ``loss ratio'' in
property and casualty insurance _ it managed its risks better by
targeting agents who will charge appropriate rates.
</P>
<P>
   Amwest also employs a staff that checks whether the trucks of
its clients are well-maintained, in an effort to control insurance
losses.
</P>
<P>
   A better loss ratio in property and casualty insurance led to
improved earnings at Amwest.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a net income of $2.37 million (or 55 cents
a diluted share) for the first quarter ended March 31 compared with
a net income of $2.06 million (48 cents) in the like period a year
ago. Gross premiums written rose 9.5 percent to $32.13 million from
$29.34 million in the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
