<HEADLINE>
MERCURY GAINS HELP ALL AROUND IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A bigger, tougher and better-shooting Mercury, likely
with two new starters, emerged Tuesday from the third WNBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard Edna Campbell (10th pick overall) and small
forward Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil (22nd) potentially are capable of
beating out two-year starters Bridget Pettis and Umeki Webb, Coach
and General Manager Cheryl Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But the 5-foot-9 Pettis, for all her inconsistencies, will not
surrender easily to the 5-8 Campbell, creating a major competition
in training camp, which opens May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping her job will be much harder for Webb, 5-10, who is three
inches shorter than Davis-Wrightsil and not nearly the scorer or
physical presence of the 1992 Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Webb and backup guard/forward Andrea Kuklova are likely to
battle with the other two draft picks, forwards Lisa Harrison (34th
pick overall) and Amanda Wilson (46th), for the final two spots on
an 11-woman roster.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, one of four players from the Colorado Xplosion of the
defunct American Basketball League taken among the first 15 picks,
was a 40.8 percent career three-point shooter in the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   Pettis shot 30.6 from three-point range in 1997 and 28.5 in '98.
Her scoring averages (12.6 and 11.3) are lower than Campbell's
(14.2 in 1996-97, 13.9 in 1997-98, 17.3 in 1998-99).
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Campbell, 30, ``can pull up for a three, she can
create her own scoring opportunities, she can break off the
dribble, pull up at mid-range and finish, she can get to the rack
and get to the free-throw line. And defensively, she can get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, Campbell said, ``seems like a very enthusiastic
team. Obviously they've been successful in the past, and hopefully
that will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new situation. I'm very excited for someone
who has gone through a league folding.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Wrightsil, 31, was a sophomore at Texas in 1985-86 when
the Longhorns became the first undefeated NCAA champion. Their
conquest in the title game: two-time national champion Southern
California and Miller in her final collegiate game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first game of our season, she'll be benched for messing up
my national championship game,'' Miller joked.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Davis-Wrightsil probably will be starting from game
one, June 12 against Sacramento, as the league runner-up Mercury
strives to get bigger on the perimeter and meaner to a degree _
just shy of the level reached on Dec. 15, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Davis-Wrightsil, then playing for the ABL's New
England Blizzard first leveled Seattle's Cindy Brown with a punch
that drew a $1,500 fine and two-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is going into her second season with the WNBA Detroit
Shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two knocks I heard about Clarissa were her attitude and
her age,'' Miller said. ``Age isn't the same as with the men, it
really isn't. That doesn't mean anything to me. I want players who
are competitive and have some experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attitude is somebody cracking the heck out of somebody. Do I
want a player like that? No question. People mistake attitude with
somebody being a competitor. I've had nothing but good dealings
with Clarissa.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis-Wrightsil, who enjoyed watching Mercury games on TV, said
Miller ``knows what I bring to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot Harrison joins from two-time defending ABL champion
Columbus. She played less than half a season for the Quest after
being traded from the Portland Power.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, on Tennessee's 1991 national championship team, and
the 6-foot Wilson, a pro rookie out of Louisiana Tech, have Kodak
All-America credentials and offer versatility and youth to a team
with four players 30 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Vice President Seth Sulka said that in a draft without
ABL players, Wilson, who must transition to the perimeter, would
have been a top-10 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Of Harrison, Miller said: ``You won't see her do anything
spectacular, but at the end of the game she has 10 points, four to
five rebounds, three assists and a couple of steals. She knows the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and Wilson will get especially good looks in camp
because centers Maria Stepanova and Marlies Askamp are not
reporting until after the European Championships, which run May
28-June 6.
</P>
<P>
   That probably will force the 6-3 Gillom, who has slimmed down,
to continue at center, with 6-1 Toni Foster at power forward and
the newcomers working at both forward positions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
