<HEADLINE>
KICKERS PREPARING FOR BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Kicker  &UR; Joe Nedney wants to burn memories of this
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to light a match to miniature footballs he has been
kicking while recovering from a torn anterior cruciate of his left
(kicking) knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a sacrificial ceremony,'' Nedney said.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney is kicking regulation footballs at this week's voluntary
camp but is not kicking off at full speed or attempting field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chris Jacke, his competition for the kicking job, is handling
the field-goal chores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do field goals right now,'' Nedney said. ``But it's
too early to push anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Both kickers know the job won't be won in May. It will be won in
August at training camp and in four preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a legitimate battle,'' special teams coach  &UR; Al Everett
said. ``It's going to be exciting. The bottom line is they know
they're not kicking against each other. They're kicking for a job,
and they know if they do well enough, one will get (the Cardinals')
job and the other will land a job elsewhere in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he thought Nedney was about 75 to 80 percent
recovered from the injury. ``There's no soreness or swelling,'' he
said. ``He's kicking with pretty good pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke, who replaced an injured Nedney the final four games of
the regular season, said he thinks each kicker will get a fair
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``All indications are that they are going to take the best
guy,'' Jacke said. ``The teams who make things political are
fighting for the first draft pick (overall). This is fighting to
get in a position to go to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We each had three games in which we won with (field goals). So
from that standpoint, I think we're dead even.'' &QL; 
Miller watch &QL; 
Another team has entered the picture in the free-agent
linebacker &UR; Jamir Miller sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Browns are interested in Miller, an unrestricted
free agent whose only contract offer has come from his old team,
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans, Tennessee, New England and Chicago also showed
interest earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials have said they haven't closed the door to
inviting Miller back. &QL; 
Quick learners &QL; 
Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin thinks the switch of  &UR; Pat Tillman to strong
safety and  &UR; J.J. McCleskey to free safety has been an easy
transition for each.
</P>
<P>
   ``With J.J.'s quickness and speed, he can have more range at
free safety,' ' Tobin said. ``Pat has more size and bulk that helps
him in the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman played free safety and McCleskey was used at cornerback
and strong safety last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin switched the two at the start of last weekend's minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman said he likes strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little more active there and there is a lot more run
support,'' he said. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Defensive end  &UR; Simeon Rice will miss this week's camp because of
personal business in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver  &UR; Kevin Drake scored his first touchdown in the
Europe League, a 12-yard grab in Scotland's overtime loss to
Frankfurt last weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
