<HEADLINE>
SUNS WAIVE SIMS, SIGN LIVINGSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - While point guard  &UR; Jason Kidd has compiled more
playing time than any other player in the NBA, the Suns have had a
seasonlong problem finding somebody to take care of those remaining
six minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Suns signed yet another backup point
guard, &UR; Randy
 &UR; Livingston, and waived their previous experiment,  &UR; Alvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, a 6-foot-5, 209-pound guard from Louisiana State, is
the fourth player the Suns will use as a backup to Kidd this
season, joining undrafted free agent  &UR; Gerald Brown, who is on the
injured list,
 &UR; Jimmy Oliver and Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver was signed to a 10-day contract and released before he
completed it. Sims was signed for the balance of the season April
28 but was waived after appearing in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston at least has NBA experience. He played in 64 games
and two playoff contests as a rookie with the Houston Rockets in
1996-97 and spent 12 games with the Atlanta Hawks last season.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was a highly regarded prospect in high school but
suffered two serious knee injuries while at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was intrigued by him when he came out of college,'' Suns
Coach
 &UR; Danny Ainge said. ``I saw him at (an evaluation) camp, and he was
the best player out there while dragging one leg around. I hadn't
heard anything about him in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember wondering who this guy was who was playing great
and doing it on one leg. He had some knee injuries, but the Rockets
loved him. He isn't a spot-up shooter like they wanted with &UR; Hakeem
 &UR; (Olajuwon) and  &UR; Charles (Barkley), but he knows how to play. And
he's a born one (point guard).''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston played this season for CBA champion Sioux Falls,
averaging 13.7 points, 6.5 assists and 4.2 rebounds a game. He
averaged 19.2 points, 7.8 assists and 4.2 rebounds in the CBA
playoffs. &QL; 
Working for tips &QL; 
Centers  &UR; Joe Kleine and &UR; Luc Longley, along with assistant
coaches &UR; Frank Johnson and  &UR; Tom Chambers and former Suns star
 &UR; Connie Hawkins will join the Mercury's &UR; Umeki Webb as celebrity
waiters Thursday night at Majerle's Sports Grill. The group will
work the tables from 5 to 7 p.m. to raise money for Suns Nite
Hoops, a program that assists young adults with vocational and
educational development through a basketball league. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
