<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-TWOLVES-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING TIME BIG QUESTION IN SUNS' FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Danny Ainge would never say it, but he's damned if he
does and he's damned if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   OK, for Ainge, he's danged if he does and danged if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Suns finish the lockout-abbreviated, 50-game
regular season tonight against the Minnesota Timberwolves at
America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   If Ainge plays his regulars and goes all out to win the game, he
risks having a player hurt.
</P>
<P>
   For which Ainge will be second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   If he rests players such as Jason Kidd, Tom Gugliotta, Clifford
Robinson and George McCloud, the Suns risk taking a two-game losing
streak into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For which Ainge will be second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, it's a no-win situation,'' Ainge agreed.
``The fans want to see a player like Jason play, and we want to win
the game. At the same time, what if we lose of one of our key
players because of an injury? For what? For seventh instead of
eighth (seed) in the playoffs?''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the Suns are playing for nothing tonight other than
perhaps pride and momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could play any of three teams in the first round _
Utah, Portland or San Antonio. And it might not matter whether they
win or lose tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Portland swept the Suns this season, but Phoenix had a chance to
win two games down the stretch. The Suns won two from San Antonio
and lost another on a buzzer-beating shot by Sean Elliott. They
split with the Jazz, winning the last two, including one in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter who we play,'' Robinson said. ``We're
capable of beating any of the three in a series _ if we're playing
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Suns swear they don't have any preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if we're six, seven or eight,'' Ainge said.
``It's no bargain playing one, two or three. I think the most
important thing is to be healthy. The second-most important thing
is to be confident.''
</P>
<P>
   So doesn't a victory provide that confidence and momentum?
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum changes,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   There's evidence of that. Last season, the Suns won 11 of their
last 12, including their season finale at Houston. They lost their
first-round playoff series to San Antonio in four games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97, the Suns won 13 of their last 16 but lost two of
their last three, including the season finale to a bad Vancouver
club. The Suns bounced back to win Game 1 of their first-round
series against Seattle and led the series, 2-1, before falling in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1995-96, the Suns lost guard Michael Finley to a sprained
ankle in a season-ending loss to Houston and were beaten, 3-1, in
the first round by San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd almost rather we go into the playoffs angry,'' Ainge said.
``We respond better after a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge hasn't been able to convince his players, particularly
Kidd. The Phoenix playmaker suffered a sprained wrist in a game at
Utah, and the team attempted to keep news of the injury quiet.
Ainge figures that even hand-checking an opponent could make the
wrist a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Jason if he wanted to take the night off up in
Sacramento,'' Ainge said. ``He wasn't having any part of it. He
said, `No. I'm playing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want a night off. I'm not afraid of injuries if a
player is already healthy. But if somebody is hurt, you don't want
them to aggravate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd agreed that having everybody healthy is important. But he
isn't ready to concede a game, even it it means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to win the last game,'' he said. ``The biggest
thing is to make sure everybody is healthy. We don't want any freak
accidents. I don't know how much it's going to mean because we're
going to come up against a good team in the playoffs if we face
Utah, San Antonio or Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, I think our team is playing extremely
well right now. I think we trust each other. And we want to carry
that into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go in on a high note, not a low note,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to play well and not worry about who we play. We
really have no preference. When you get caught up in who you'd
rather play, sometimes that comes back to bite you.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
