<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUND AFTER WNBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston selecting a post player instead of a point guard in the
first round?
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Goodson dropping to the third round?
</P>
<P>
   Carol Blazejowksi and Richie Adubato: Geniuses or bunglers?
</P>
<P>
   Those were among the questions being asked after the WNBA draft
Tuesday, a week later than originally scheduled due to glitches in
putting the league's first collective bargaining agreement on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   The extra week did nothing to deter two of the teams picking
among the top three from substantially improving. Whether the
three-win Washington Mystics, with the only collegian of the first
round in No. 1 overall pick Chamique Holdsclaw, did as well remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA President Val Ackerman called the draft, which included
every former American Basketball League star except 34-year-old
Teresa Edwards, who opted not to sign, the ``deepest in modern-day
sports. I'm just not aware of any other draft that has had this
level of talent available.''
</P>
<P>
   In draft order, here's a look at what the Mercury's rivals did: &QL; 
Washington
</P>
<P>
   Even the all-everything Holdsclaw will need pro seasoning,
although she should evolve enough to be Rookie of the Year.
Third-rounder Andrea Nagy gets the point duty, working with former
ABL MVP Nikki McCray and Holdsclaw on the perimeter, while quality
second-rounder Shalonda Enis stays inside instead of going to the
perimeter as she would have with the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   But Enis, Murriel Page and Alessandra Santos de Oliveira are not
enough inside. The Mystics might want to trade with Utah for Wendy
Palmer. &QL; 
Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   An argument can be made that Natalie Williams would have been
the better choice with the No. 2 overall pick than Yolanda
Griffith, but why quibble. Either is a monster improvement in the
post.
</P>
<P>
   A perimeter of point Ticha Penicheiro, a healthy Ruthie
Bolton-Holifield, second-rounder Kedra Holland-Corn and third-round
wing Kate Starbird will be a challenge to defend, though Starbird
can be a defensive liability. Fourth-rounder Amy Herrig joins
another 6-foot-4 post, Tangela Smith, Griffith and Latasha Byears
underneath. &QL; 
Utah
</P>
<P>
   In landing hometown favorite Williams, who estimates she has 200
relatives in the area, the Starzz make a healthy leap in talent and
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Frank Layden already is talking about a lineup of
second-rounder Debbie Black at point, 6-5 Elena Baranova at
shooting guard, 7-2 Margo Dydek at small forward, 6-2 Palmer at
power forward and 6-2 Williams at center.
</P>
<P>
   But why play Dydek away from the basket when the third-rounder,
6-foot Goodson, averaged 17.5 points and 7.9 rebounds in her ABL
career? They could trade Palmer for depth at guard, use Olympia
Scott-Richardson low with Dydek and Williams, Baranova on the wing
and Goodson at shooting guard. &QL; 
Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Going big for 6-1 DeLisha Milton, rather than point guard Dawn
Staley, in the first round and 6-5 Clarisse Machanguana in the
second is a gamble dependent on point Penny Toler's attitude and
rookie third-rounder Ukari Figgs being a quick study.
</P>
<P>
   Machanguana conceivably could play either post position with
Milton and 6-5 Lisa Leslie. The perimeter includes Allison Feaster,
who missed most of 1998 due to injury, Tamecka Dixon, Toler, Figgs
and athletic Mwadi Mabika.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcement for Leslie has to help a team embarassed by two
years outside the playoffs. &QL; 
Detroit
</P>
<P>
   The Shock are a perimeter heavy team with the additions of
first-rounder Jennifer Azzi and Dominique Canty, the collegiate
All-America from Alabama who slipped to the third round by not
appearing at the pre-draft camp. They join Kori Hlede and
Australians Sandy Brondello and Carla Porter in a mix that will
take some figuring out.
</P>
<P>
   Second-rounder Val Whiting and fourth-round comer Astou Ndiaye
join Cindy Brown and inconsistent 6-8 Raja Mujanovic inside. &QL; 
New York
</P>
<P>
   Although Alicia Thompson (1.6 ppg, 1.3 rpg) was a 1998
first-round bust, the Liberty went collegiate in the second and
third rounds with posts Michele VanGorp of Duke and Tamika Whitmore
of Memphis. Then they took a future pick in the fourth with Carolyn
Jones-Young, who averaged 21.5 points for the ABL New England
Blizzard but is out this season due to injury.
</P>
<P>
   First-rounder Crystal Robinson probably will push Vickie Johnson
to the bench at small forward, but the front line of aging Kym
Hampton and Rebecca Lobo has to have help. The learning curve needs
to be quick for VanGorp and/or Whitmore for General Manager
Blazejowski and her new coach Adubato to warrant the luxury of
taking Jones-Young. &QL; 
Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Former Quest Coach Brian Agler exceeds his expectations with
four of his former Quest players. But just because Sonja Tate and
Angie Potthoff were available late, does that justify overlooking
collegians Angie Braziel and Amanda Wilson or Elaine Powell, snared
by Orlando with its extra expansion pick?
</P>
<P>
   The Lynx has no one taller than second-rounder Trish Fallon, a
6-3 forward from Australia. Agler's system that worked so well in
the ABL will be put to a major test. &QL; 
Orlando
</P>
<P>
   Hometowner Tari Phillips went too high at No. 8 overall, but Taj
McWilliams was a get at No.T32 and Powell was a steal at No. 50.
Second-rounder Sheri Sam is friends with Nykesha Sales, an
allocated player, and the Miracle's other allocation, Shannon
Johnson, has some national-team time with Sales.
</P>
<P>
   Give Coach-General Manager Carolyn Peck credit for going with
ABL experience and not reaching for her former Purdue guards,
Stephanie White-McCarty and Figgs. &QL; 
Charlotte
</P>
<P>
   Marynell Meadors wasn't as disciplined as Peck, unaccountably
taking White-McCarty in the second round after coming up with
Staley in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Third-rounder Charlotte Smith raises the in-state college
connection to five, even though the Sting averaged just 8,561 with
the previous four. &QL; 
Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   Chasity Melvin went to Spain after the ABL folded and hopefully
learned enough to justify being the 11th pick overall. If Janice
Braxton retires and Isabelle Fijalkowski isn't paid enough to
warrant returning from France, the weight falls unfairly on the
second-year pro. The Rockers will be hard-pressed to defend their
Eastern Conference crown. &QL; 
Houston
</P>
<P>
   The Comets could cruise to a third league title with the
additions of 6-3 Zassoulskaia and 6-7 Kara Wolters to a team that
also gets 6-4 Polina Tzekova, its 1998 No. 1 pick who missed last
season due to her mother's illness.
</P>
<P>
   If second-rounder Sonja Henning, fourth-rounder Jennifer
Rizzotti and Janeth Arcain can replace cancer-stricken Kim Perrot
at point by committee, the race might be for second place. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
