<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S NOT SEVENTH HEAVEN
</HEADLINE>
   (With HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS) 
(nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the decisive seventh game of a
Stanley Cup playoff series, it always boils down to the
goaltenders. It always has. It always will.
</P>
<P>
   If the ace of a baseball team's pitching staff could start every
game in the league playoffs or the World Series, it would be
comparable to a hockey goaltender's burden. But that doesn't happen
in baseball. And there's no one player on a basketball or a
football team who is perpetually on trial as much as a hockey
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   All the other players on a hockey team skate to the bench for a
breather every so often as the forward lines and defensemen change,
but a goaltender is a sentry who is never off duty.
</P>
<P>
   In a showdown that would be seventh heaven for one goaltender
and hell for the other, Martin Brodeur of the Devils confronted Tom
Barrasso of the Penguins Tuesday night in the finale of the
opening-round playoff series at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hell for Brodeur, who gave up four goals in
Pittsburgh's 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Neither goaltender had to worry about the specter of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   After last Sunday's sixth game went into overtime in Pittsburgh,
Barrasso skated off the ice as a winner after Jaromir Jagr drilled
the winning goal past Brodeur at 8 minutes 59 seconds for a 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, in contrast, could be excused for starting to be
spooked by the thought of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's loss was the sixth straight time that Brodeur and the
Devils had been victimized by an overtime goal in the playoffs; his
career record is 3-10, not what is expected from a goaltender of
his All-Star stature.
</P>
<P>
   Of the active goaltenders, Colorado's Patrick Roy has the best
playoff overtime record, 32-9.
</P>
<P>
   Over his six Devils seasons, Brodeur's career 2.19 goals-against
average is the best in the National Hockey League's modern era. Ken
Dryden had a 2.24 average for Montreal during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils won the Stanley Cup in 1995, Brodeur was
brilliant: a 1.67 goals-against average with a 16-4 record and
three shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Until the current playoffs, he had a 1.84 goals-against average
in the playoffs and a 31-23 record.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent season, Brodeur led the league with 39
victories, but his goals-against average was 2.29 with four
shutouts, up from 1.88 with 10 shutouts a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first six games of this playoff series with the
Penguins, Brodeur's goals-against average was a shaky 2.62 and his
save percentage was an even shakier .873.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's loss, Brodeur's teammates talked about how he had
thwarted the Penguins in the final minutes of regulation (until
Jagr's goal with less than 3 minutes remaining) and again during
the early minutes of overtime until Jagr's winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   But were his teammates simply trying to bolster Brodeur's
confidence for Tuesday night's showdown? Especially those who knew
of his 0-6 streak in overtime games?
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's previous seventh game, an overtime loss to the Rangers
at Madison Square Garden in the 1994 Eastern Conference finals, had
been especially haunting.
</P>
<P>
   After the Devils had created a 1-1 tie on Valery Zelepukin's
goal with only 7.7 seconds remaining in regulation, Brodeur and
Rangers goaltender Mike Richter dueled into the second overtime
before the Rangers won, 2-1, on Stephane Matteau's goal after 4:24.
</P>
<P>
   In that year's opening-round series, Brodeur lost a 1-0 sixth
game in Buffalo in the fourth overtime period as Sabres goaltender
Dominik Hasek made 70 saves, but two nights later, in Brodeur's
only other previous seventh game, he stopped the Sabres, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils won the Stanley Cup in 1995, Brodeur was the
goaltender in two of the Devils' overtime victories, against Boston
and Pittsburgh, but his 0-6 streak started with Eric Lindros'
overtime goal for Philadelphia in the third game of the Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 playoffs, Brodeur lost in overtime twice _ to
Montreal and to the Rangers (on Adams Graves' goal that ended the
Eastern Conference semifinals).
</P>
<P>
   In last year's playoffs, Brodeur lost in overtime twice as the
eighth-seeded Ottawa Senators stunned the top-seeded Devils in six
games in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday night, for the first time since 1994, Martin Brodeur
found himself in a seventh-game showdown that has always boiled
down to the goaltenders. And he lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
