<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 44 DEAD AS TORNADOES RIP THROUGH OKLAHOMA, KANSAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Eds.: Also see: Tornado-trauma, Tornado-witnesses, Tornado-scene
and Tornado-weather.) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
and DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The heart of Oklahoma lay in tatters Tuesday
after as many as 36 tornadoes roared from the inky maw of a
torrential thunderstorm, killing at least 38 people and injuring
more than 669.
</P>
<P>
   Six others died and another 60 were injured in neighboring
Kansas when the same storm tore through the Wichita area.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the storm, which hit the Oklahoma City area
late Monday afternoon, was the deadliest since since the 1947
tornado in Woodward, which killed 116. One person was killed in
North Texas on Tuesday as the storm cell continued to drift
eastward.
</P>
<P>
   The devastation near Oklahoma City and Haysville, Kan., was so
complete Tuesday that residents conjured images of bomb-wasted
Belgrade and the rubble of Oklahoma City's blasted Alfred P. Murrah
federal building to describe what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe as many as 1,700 structures in Oklahoma were
heavily damaged or destroyed and that more than 6,000 people had
been left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Frank Keating placed damage in his state in the hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   James Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management
Administration, said, ``This is some of the worst, most massive
destruction I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who Tuesday declared 11 counties eligible for
federal disaster assistance, noted Oklahoma City residents have
``suffered too much devastation in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   He alluded to the 1995 bombing of the Murrah building, the worst
terrorist attack in U.S. history, in which 168 people died.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our fellow Americans have had everything taken from
them in those two states,'' he said. ``I know that they will be in
your prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he plans to visit the stricken area Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As Oklahoma struggled to cope with Monday's storm damage,
meteorologists warned Tuesday that the storms, still packing lethal
power, would move into eastern Oklahoma, Texas, Louisiana, Missouri
and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, The Associated Press reported, a tornado
tore through the downtown district of the Northeast Texas town of
DeKalb, damaging buildings and injuring at least 11 people, three
of them critically.
</P>
<P>
   A second tornado touched down Tuesday afternoon in rural Titus
County near Mount Pleasant, killing one person. No details were
available Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado also was sited Tuesday near the Cass County community
of Atlanta. It did not touch ground, a sheriff's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma City, a 12-square-mile area was cordoned off as
rescuers equipped with cameras and search dogs probed the
mountainous rubble for signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had not seen what I have seen over the last five or so
hours,'' said Oklahoma U.S. Rep. J. C. Watts, ``I would not have
been able to believe it, nor would I have been able to comprehend
it ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The area looks like they have taken these homes apart board by
board. It's not a pretty sight. I will be surprised if the death
toll stops at 40.''
</P>
<P>
   In Haysville, Kan., the Rev Bob Osenga said the twister carved a
quarter-mile wide, five-mile long path through the community of
14,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like bombs were just dropped in a row,'' he said
``You and I could have taken Caterpillar bulldozers and couldn't
have done a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   An oral surgeon, whose office is in the Oklahoma City suburb of
Moore, said he saw a man stumbling down the street after the storm
with a piece of wood protruding from his back. ``There was one
woman with a leg injury,'' he said. ``We put her on an ironing
board and took her to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City hospitals nearest to the main strike zone were
swamped with victims, but doctors and spokespersons said they were
able to cope with the large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Irby of the American Red Cross told The Associated Press
that 10 emergency shelters have been established in Oklahoma; three
in Kansas. The Red Cross also has dispatched 12 emergency response
vehicles to the scene, each capable of dispensing 5,000 meals
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief M. T. Berry said officers reported seeing
relatively few people in the shelters because neighbors and people
around Oklahoma City were taking them in.
</P>
<P>
   The tornadoes _ some of which likely packed winds in excess of
260 mph _ grew out of a massive storm system that moved into
Central Oklahoma about 4 p.m. CST Monday. Meteorologists noted that
some of the tornadoes remained on the ground for 30 to 45 minutes.
One cut a milewide, 60-mile path through rural Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hot and humid, very oppressive,'' recalled
University of Oklahoma meteorology graduate student Marc Weinberg.
``It was perfect weather for storms to form.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg, equipped with a video camera and accompanied by a
friend, began following the storm system at Cyril, about an hour's
drive southwest of Oklahoma City. At Chicasha, he encountered the
first of nine tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching within a mile of the twister, Weinberg was astounded
by the ear-shattering roar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were explosions all over the place,'' he said. ``Power
lines falling all over the road. The destruction was amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People call this an act of God,'' said Wayne Canefield, whose
elderly parents' home was destroyed in the suburban community of
Midwest City. ``This is not an act of God. The other side did
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, houses were reduced to splinters. Automobiles were
tossed about like toys, stacked in crazy heaps on the roadways.
Trees, left standing, were stripped of their bark.
</P>
<P>
   One of the storm's miracles occurred at the West Moore High
School, where about 300 students, parents and teachers were
attending a meeting when the twisters hit. Although the school
gymnasium's roof was peeled back like a sardine can lid, no one
attending the meeting was injured.
</P>
<P>
   When they stepped into the school's debris-littered parking lot,
they found the bodies of two horses. The nearest field, locals
noted, is miles from the school.
</P>
<P>
   In Bridge Creek, a subdivision about 20 miles southwest of
Oklahoma City, National Guardsmen found a woman in the wreckage of
a church. She had spent nearly a full day in the debris, which had
fallen in such a way as to protect her from injury.
</P>
<P>
   The once-placid neighborhoods of suburban Oklahoma City offered
snapshots of despair.
</P>
<P>
   In front of one ruined house, a tattered U.S. flag was buffeted
by a 40 mph wind.
</P>
<P>
   In many neighborhoods there were no street signs left, but
families found the site of their former homes nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Families searched for mementos, photos, even things as basic as
a change of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City resident Jo Shepherd, who was in Washington, D.C.,
when the storm hit, said 16 of her family members and neighbors
emerged from her home's basement to find that a Rottweiler _
apparently blown into the home through a window _ had taken refuge
in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was paying attention,'' Shepherd's traveling companion,
Susan McMakin, said of the dog. Authorities, she noted, often
advise residents to seek shelter from storms in bathrooms. ``You've
got to laugh.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
