<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON IS DAY-TO-DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT -- Tim Salmon has made the play dozens of times, and not
once has he hurt himself doing it. But this is the Angels we're
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon tried to make a sliding catch on a sinking liner hit to
right field by the White Sox's Paul Konerko Monday afternoon. But
instead of sliding, his left knee stuck in the turf and caused him
to land awkwardly on his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Salmon and the Angels, X-rays were negative and he
has only a sprain. He is listed as day-to-day, and Tuesday he said
it felt better even though he was not in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could slide like that a hundred times and never hurt
myself,'' Salmon said. ``It was one of those situations where I
tried to make a play when maybe I shouldn't have. ... But if you
get hurt from playing aggressively, you've got to live with that.
It wasn't a stupid play. I was trying to pick up a pitcher who's
struggling a little bit. I would have done it for anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury, Salmon said, is common: ``We've all done it. You
fall off your skateboard and tweak your wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were skateboarding, Salmon could have returned Tuesday.
But swinging the bat with a bad wrist is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your bottom hand,'' Salmon said, ``and that's everything.
At least for me it is. ... My wrists are everything as far as my
swing. It's different than hobbling around the bases like I did
last year. At least I could swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon added he doesn't want to come back too soon because ``I
don't want to get into bad habits, which could result from favoring
the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels already losing players like Mo Vaughn, Gary
DiSarcina and Jim Edmonds to injuries, Salmon worried that the
wrist was broken when it happened. But he stayed in the game for
another at-bat anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't swing when I was on-deck,'' Salmon said.
``But I had adrenaline going. And part of it is denial. The first
thing that went through my mind was `You've got to be kidding me.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Tim Belcher's ERA of 9.96 is the worst on the Angels
staff, starters and relievers included. But if not for the fifth
inning of his starts, Belcher's ERA would be a respectable 4.68.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher has allowed three runs or more in the fifth inning in
four of his six starts. And that includes one start in which he
didn't even reach the fifth inning. His ERA in the fifth inning is
54.00.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins, pitching coach Dick Pole and bullpen
coach Joe Coleman looked at video tape of Belcher Tuesday -- both
from games this year and last year -- in an effort to find the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get him going, he's big for us,'' Collins said.
``His ball's got life. His velocity in the fifth inning is the
same, but it's right down the middle of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he didn't think Belcher's fifth-inning woes have
become a mental problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to bother a guy like Tim Belcher,''
Collins said. ``He's been through too many wars. He's having a
tough time. I've managed a lot of 'em -- some guys aren't very good
at the start, then in June they're pitching great.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa was not available for Tuesday's
game because of food poisoning. ``He brought some noodles onto the
plane, Collins said. ``He added some hot water and immediately
started to barf. Collins jokingly called it a ``gastronomical
abnormality.'' ... With Salmon out of the lineup Tuesday, Tim Unroe
started in right field. Unroe went into the game hitting .500 (7
for 14) with one homer. Todd Greene, who will start at catcher
today, might get a start in right field if Salmon doesn't return in
the next few days. ... Last Friday, Troy Percival gave up five runs
in the ninth inning in the Angels' 8-5 loss to the White Sox. And
it happened after Hasegawa threw a 1-2-3 eighth inning. ``I had
breakfast in Seal Beach on Saturday morning, and the girl who
waited on me told me I should have left Shige in, Collins said.
``That's real easy Saturday morning. I told her `Where were you
last night? I could have used you then.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Tigers play the second game of their three-game
series today at 4:05. Steve Sparks (0-3, 5.22 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Detroit's Jeff Weaver (3-1, 2.45).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
