<SLUG> BC-NY-DOMESTIC-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. GOVERNOR MOVES TO TOUGHEN LAWS AGAINST DOMESTIC VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki pressed ahead Tuesday with his
effort to stiffen New York's laws against domestic violence,
proposing lifetime orders of protection, tougher bail requirements
for accused batterers and increased penalties for several offenses.
</P>
<P>
   He said his legislation would strengthen protections for victims
by insuring that judges, prosecutors and the police have more tools
to fight domestic violence, which elected officials of both major
parties have increasingly championed.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki pushed through laws in his first term that made defying
an order of protection a felony and that require Family Court
judges to consider domestic violence in child custody cases. He
also was one of the most outspoken critics of Brooklyn Criminal
Court Judge Lorin Duckman, who was later removed from the bench
after being accused of showing bias against prosecutors and
disparaging blacks and women. Duckman drew criticism in 1996 after
he lowered the bail of a man jailed on domestic abuse charges, who
was then released and who subsequently killed a former girlfriend
and himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are sweeping and comprehensive reforms that will build
on the successes we've had,'' the governor said of the proposal at
a news conference today. ``You can never do enough. We want to see
that this crime is driven out of New York State, that there is in
fact not just the talk of zero tolerance, but is in fact the action
of zero tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate, which is controlled by Pataki's Republican
allies, is all but certain to approve the legislation quickly. With
domestic violence measures popular among politicians, the
Democratic majority in the state Assembly is not likely to reject
it. But the Democrats could delay passage in a bid to obtain the
governor's support on other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, judges can generally issue orders of
protection for up to a year, after which the orders must be
renewed. In his bill presented Tuesday, Pataki called on the
Legislature to allow judges to make the orders permanent. Only one
state, Washington, allows such lifetime orders of protection,
although judges in three other states _ New Jersey, Oklahoma and
Utah _ can issue orders of indeterminate length, aides to Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also proposed altering the way that judges consider
bail in domestic violence cases. The bill would require that judges
consider a defendant's history of domestic violence, whether an
order of protection had been previously issued against the accused
and whether there was evidence that an order had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   The change in the law would tend to increase the chances that a
defendant would not be released on bail, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that under the bill, people who engage in domestic
violence in front of children would be charged with endangering the
welfare of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the proposals in the legislation stemmed from
recommendations by a commission that Pataki established, which was
led by Westchester County District Attorney Jeanine Pirro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990504.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-04 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-WITNESSES-HNS     05-04 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-WITNESSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADO SURVIVOR: `I'VE NEVER SEEN ANYTHING LIKE THIS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Tornado-trauma, Tornado-deaths, Tornado-scene and
Tornado-weather.) 
 
By PATTI MUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ First came the softball-sized hail and the
horrible roaring wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really sounded like Armageddon,'' said Zach Whitaker, who
survived one of the monster tornadoes that tore through Oklahoma
and Kansas on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath came a worse sound _ the voices of
terrified neighbors searching for family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hear, `Oh God, Oh God, please don't be dead''' said
Whitaker, who rode out the storm in a bathroom closet of his house
with his 1 1/2-year-old son, his wife and his in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   He was glad to be alive Tuesday, but forever shaken by a
life-changing act of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here all my life, and I've been through three
tornadoes, and I've never seen anything like this,'' Whitaker said.
``It came in, as they say, `like a thief in the night.'''
</P>
<P>
   For 36-year-old Chong Wren, the lights went out, and through
several minutes of darkness and stark terror, she thought her life
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `I'm going to die.' I said, `God help me, God help
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   As she huddled in a bathtub in her second-floor apartment near
Moore, a suburb of Oklahoma City, the apartment disintegrated
around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is gone,'' she said. ``The wall is gone. The
refrigerator blew out, the oven blew out. I saw a lot of people
lying down and bleeding.``
</P>
<P>
   The stairway vanished into rubble, and she had to be rescued
before beginning a frantic search for her 6-year-old son, Alan, who
was visiting a friend.
</P>
<P>
   They were reunited at a nearby shelter, and she rejoiced at
their survival, but wept as she contemplated the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I can start all over again,'' said Wren, a
department store employee. ``I'm a single mom, working hard for
many years. I try the best I can, but I don't have insurance and my
car is gone, too.``
</P>
<P>
   Alan Wren was in a car with his best friend, Billy Webb Payne,
7, and Payne's mother, Margie Payne, 28. They sought shelter under
an interstate bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just so scared,'' said Margie Payne. ``I saw it cross
the interstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, Wren, Whitaker and dozens of other
victims waited desperately at a blocked intersection, unable to
reach whatever was left of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities kept them away because of downed, live electrical
wires and hissing gas lines.
</P>
<P>
   The residents' frustration peaked and replaced the fear of the
previous night as the evening curfew approached.
</P>
<P>
   One man who would not give his name complained bitterly that
some police officers and firefighters who lived in the area were
allowed in to salvage their possessions. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Just because I don't have a badge, I can't get in,'' he
fumed.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, a 21-year-old carpenter, said the family's 10-year-old
dog, Millie, refused to leave the flattened house after the tornado
and needs medication to live.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood was littered with splintered 2-by-4s, cars and
trucks thrown randomly about, and houses simply leveled, residents
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we could see it was flat,'' Whitaker said. ``My
father-in-law helped one lady with a split two-by-four stuck in her
foot. It was pretty terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kiefner, 46, an attorney whose home was demolished,
compared the scene to a ``a garbage dump _ piles of debris as far
as you can see.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not expect the magnitude of the devastation. I was
unprepared for that,`` said Kiefner, who was able to salvage a few
family photographs but nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Terri, 42, a social worker, went to a
relative's house before the storm hit, and called family in Houston
soon after to say they were safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already homesick, but we're fine, and we're going to be
OK,'' said Terri Kiefner.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Oklahomans have been supportive and will help them return
to normal, they said. ``I think they know what to do and how to
pull together really quick,'' said Terri Kiefner. ``Pretty
resilient bunch of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was accounted for by Tuesday night, and neighbors
feared that some may have been trapped in rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors spread through the crowd at the blocked intersection. One
neighbor reportedly lost a leg in the storm. Another hadn't been
heard from.
</P>
<P>
   And there in the crowd, holding a sign high above her head,
Oklahoma City resident Charlene Jay and her 10-year-old son
searched for two people they don't even know.
</P>
<P>
   A man working with Jay's husband on a job site in Texas lived in
the neighborhood, and was desperate for word of his wife and
10-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Jay, 37, a homemaker, carried a sign asking for information
about the pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've called five shelters and left my name everywhere,'' Jay
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
