<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-DIAMONDBACKS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Larkin like old self, leads Reds to win
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It must be May because Barry Larkin is bustin' out
all over.
</P>
<P>
   After another of his yearly stumbles through April, living in
below .200 poverty, the 35-year-old captain of The Good Ship
Cincinnati Reds, which took on a lot of water in April, is his old
self again.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin broke a tie game Tuesday night with a two-run home run to
lift the Reds to a 6-4 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks in
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin also was in the middle of two-run rallies in the second
and fourth and scored three times. On Monday, during a 4-3 victory,
Larkin had two hits and drove in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 600th of manager Jack McKeon's managerial
career in this, his 50th year of professional baseball, and added a
few gray hairs under his hat, thanks to wobbly starting pitcher
again by Jason Bere.
</P>
<P>
   Bere had the most deceiving 2-0 record imaginable when he took
the mound, having pitched beyond 5 1/3 innings only once in five
starts. His 6.00 earned run average said it all.
</P>
<P>
   His spot in the rotation was precarious and he did nothing to
change it.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds gave him a 2-0 lead in the second on catcher Brian
Johnson's two-run double, but Arizona ripped into Bere for four
runs in the third, including a three-run home run by Matt Williams,
his 11th.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tied it in the fourth on Pokey Reese's two-out,
two-strike, two-run single and McKeon permitted Bere to bat.
</P>
<P>
   After Bere struck out, he walked to the mound in the fifth and
promptly walked Luis Gonzalez on four pitches and surrendered a
double to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gonzalez was caught off third base on the Wiliams
double, an awful piece of base-running, McKeon had seen enough and
hooked Bere.
</P>
<P>
   In four-plus innings, Bere had given up four runs, eight hits
and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds had gone 13 straight innings without back-to-back hits,
and only once in their previous 34 innings, when the second inning
began against Arizona left-hander Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   That ended after Greg Vaughn reached first on shortstop Andy
Fox's error. Aaron Boone singled and Johnson followed with his
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds put back-to-back hits together again in the two-run
fourth when Vaughn and Larkin opened with singles. It looked
fruitless when Daal struck out Boone and Johnson, but Reese slapped
his two-run single to make it 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
