<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami clinches top seed in East, 93-79
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With smothering playoff-caliber defense, the Miami
Heat beat the Atlanta Hawks 93-79 Tuesday night to clinch the No. 1
seed in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, who also won a third consecutive Atlantic Division
title, are assured of the home-court advantage through the Eastern
Conference finals. The Hawks were eliminated from contention for
the Central Division title and were swept in the three-game season
series.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Mashburn scored 18 points and P.J. Brown 16 to lead
Miami's offense, but it was the defense that made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks shot just 27 percent in the final three quarters, and
the Heat forced six turnovers in the pivotal third period while
taking the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith scored 21 points for Atlanta but missed 11 of 18
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were surprisingly sharp from the outset, a marked
contrast to recent performances even while they were winning eight
of their previous nine.
</P>
<P>
   Their passes were crisp and they ran their plays precisely. With
Smith and Mookie Blaylock both sharp, the result was a terrific 8
1/2 minutes in which they grabbed a 21-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Smith made his first four shots and was 6-for-11 in the opening
half while Blaylock hit 5-for-7, including both 3-pointers he
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the opening basket of the game, Miami could not get
the lead until a 6-0 surge with Clarence Weatherspoon sinking a
baseline jumper to make it 39-37.
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast to their previous appearance here, the Hawks
dug in. They held a narrow lead into Miami's final possession of
the half, when Terry Porter sank an open 3-pointer to tie it
45-all.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's offense came from three players, Mashburn, Brown and
Weatherspoon combining for 33 of their points.
</P>
<P>
   Had they been as good at the line as they were in other
departments, the Hawks would have led. Alonzo Mourning and
Weatherspoon both worked into foul trouble, giving the Hawks 15
free throws in the half, but they missed six.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum swing came for Miami in the third quarter with the
score tied at 49. It started with Brown at his favorite spot,
sinking a right baseline jumper. Then it was Hardaway from nearly
the same spot, then for a 3-pointer. When Dikembe Mutombo
goaltended Brown's hook, the Heat was on an 8-1 run and leading by
six.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
