A4577 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS05-CO     05-04 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cards tattoo Maddux
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the seconds it took a Mark McGwire home run to
sail 429 feet on Tuesday night, 39,161 fans at Turner Field caught
a glimpse of the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Braves fans and their pitchers had managed to steer
pretty clear of McGwire and his Chase, but this time they had
nowhere to run.
</P>
<P>
   Captured in a sea of flashbulbs, McGwire unleashed a little of
what fans all over the nation saw last year _ a ball rocketing
through the night _ for a grand slam in the second inning, a
six-run lead and a hold on the game the Cardinals would not lose.
</P>
<P>
   They slammed shut a six-game Braves win streak with a 9-1
victory of their own. The Braves, 10-5 at Turner Field, will wrap
up a nine-game homestand today against the Cardinals at 1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The only drama that followed the home run was two bench-clearing
meetings on the infield in response to Greg Maddux plunking Ray
Lankford after the McGwire grand slam and Kent Mercker's
retaliatory pitch aimed at Andruw Jones to start the bottom half of
the second inning. Mercker, whose pitch went behind Jones, was
ejected.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who had hit his two of his record-setting 70 home runs
off Dennis Martinez and Kevin Millwood last year at Busch Stadium,
got his first career home run in Turner Field, first ever off
Maddux, sixth of the season and 12th grand slam of his career,
which leads all active hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, McGwire had been 1-for-5 in the series and 11-for-51
(.216) in his career against the Braves with three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   One inning made it a night of frustration for Maddux, who had
flirted with this kind of disaster in an April 24 start in Florida
but didn't have to watch it play out, thanks to eight Braves runs
in an 8-7 win. This time he left trailing 8-0 after Joseph McEwing
got his third hit in three at-bats with a two-run bases-loaded
single in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Maddux (4-1) was finished with his shortest outing of
the year (4 1/3 innings). He had surrendered a season-high 12 hits
and eight earned runs, matching his career high for earned runs
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
