u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-AR     05-04 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING ARMY BARRACKS INTO TEMPORARY HOMES FOR REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ As relief workers in Macedonia took the final
steps toward sending some 400 Kosovar Albanian refugees to the
United States on Tuesday, parishioners at the Church of the Good
Shepherd in Willingboro, N.J., put together ``shoe box ministries''
_ boxes stuffed with shampoo, toothbrushes and other essentials
that people uprooted from their homes would most likely miss.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Fort Dix, a nearby Army base that was established during
World War I, the mess hall was being outfitted as a medical
station, while a team of budget analysts turned off their computers
to parcel out linens and towels in the newly cleaned dormitories.
Soldiers trained to fire heavy weapons were instead assembling
bassinets and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing whatever it takes to make the kids happy,'' said
Pvt. Joshua Bennett, 18, as he put together an indoor basketball
game.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, the first 400 of about 20,000 Kosovar
Albanian refugees that the United States has agreed to shelter are
expected to arrive on a charter plane at nearby McGuire Air Force
Base, where they will be greeted by Hillary Rodham Clinton and Gov.
Christie Whitman. A second planeload of 400 or so refugees is
expected to arrive Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers will be mostly women and children whose families
have been decimated by the Serbian campaign to redraw the ethnic
map of Kosovo through violence.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the families arriving here will not have
relatives in the United States, and will encounter an array of
government and nonprofit agencies, including the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, Health and Human Services and the private
Immigration and Refugee Services of America.
</P>
<P>
   They will remain at the base for three to six weeks, and
eventually be resettled in communities throughout the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, an additional 300 Albanian refugees will fly into
Kennedy International Airport. But these have relatives in the
United States who have agreed to take them in and who are expected
to welcome them at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Those coming here to Fort Dix will be sheltered in barracks
previously used for reservists during their annual training.
Contractors have been reconfiguring the rooms to house families of
varying sizes. Bilingual signs have gone up, and buildings that had
been quiet were bustling Tuesday with final preparations.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, as the Defense Department began closing
bases around the country, the community here fought to keep McGuire
Air Force Base open. It succeeded, but operations were scaled back.
In 1995, the Army stopped using Fort Dix for basic training, and
laid off many civilian employees.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Anna Hinkle, 62, was one of them. She worked in the mess
hall until 1995. Tuesday, she wore bright yellow plastic gloves as
she cleaned the corridors for the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might start working there again, because I know all sides of
the mess hall operation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hinkle came to the United States herself as a refugee in
1946, after World War II. She had been expelled from the
Sudetenland, a region of Czechoslovakia that Germany had invaded in
Hitler's first expansionist drive.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the refugees from Kosovo now, she said, ``brings
memories.'' Her own family left its home practically penniless, and
came to the United States along with 3,000 or so other refugees,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a child, and didn't understand,'' she said. ``Now, I do,
and I help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
