<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS WHO ADVERTISE ARE LIABLE UNDER CONSUMER LAWS, COURT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doctors and other medical providers who advertise their services
can be held liable under New York's consumer fraud and false
advertising laws just like car dealers, clothing stores or any
other kind of business, the state's highest court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the state Court of Appeals essentially
upheld longstanding practices by state and city officials, who have
pursued cases of false medical advertising and fraud under consumer
laws. But the ruling is likely to encourage more individual civil
cases under the laws, because the consumer cases tend to be easier
for patients to win than cases alleging medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also reflected a fact apparent to anyone who opens
the Yellow Pages or rides a subway: Doctors and managed-care
companies, in heated competition, advertise much more _ and more
boldly _ than they did even a few years ago. And so, as with other
businesses, the chances of deceptive ads have increased.
</P>
<P>
   In the case before the Court of Appeals, a New York state
couple, Jayne and Kenneth Karlin, sued a company that provides
services to doctors who perform fertility treatments. The Karlins
said in court papers filed in 1994 that they had been assured by
the company's brochures that women who completed four in vitro
fertilization procedures generally had a 50 percent chance of
becoming pregnant. But the couple underwent seven such procedures
over two and a half years at a hospital in Port Chester, N.Y., and
the woman did not become pregnant. They claimed that the company
overstated its success rates, and that the company's advertising
did not disclose potential risks from fertilization procedures like
high miscarriage rates, neonatal deaths and birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   Before the couple filed their suit, the company, based in
Purchase, N.Y., and then known as IVF America, was accused of
deceptive advertising by the Federal Trade Commission in 1990. The
company agreed to stop misrepresenting success rates from
fertilization procedures. And three years later, the company was
charged with similar violations of New York City's consumer
protection laws and settled that case.
</P>
<P>
   But in the summer of 1997, the appellate division of state
Supreme Court refused to allow the Karlins to pursue their case
under false advertising and consumer fraud laws because it said
that opening doctors up to such cases would represent a ``drastic
change in basic tort law.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's decision, Chief Judge Judith Kaye ruled that the
lower court was mistaken and that there was no reason to exempt
medical providers from the laws that cover other businesses. She
wrote that ``when they choose to reach out to the consuming public
at large in order to promote business _ like clothing retailers,
automobile dealers and wedding singers _ they subject themselves to
the standards of an honest marketplace'' protected by the consumer
fraud laws.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Court of Appeals added that Kaye's language
was also meant to be a warning to lawyers and other professionals
who have recently begun to advertise in ways more often associated
with used car lots or electronics store close-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Burman, the Karlins' lawyer, said Tuesday that the
couple did not wish to comment publicly about the decision, which
returns their case to Supreme Court in Westchester County for a
trial. But Burnham said the couple, who also did not want to
disclose their professions or where they live, were elated.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ledy-Gurren, the lawyer for the company, now known as
IntegraMed America, said she remained ``very confident that a trial
on the merits will be in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the success rates were honestly and thoroughly
communicated to the Karlins,'' she said. She added that she fears
the ``effect of this decision will be less dissemination of
information for medical consumers. I suspect that the flow of
information _ particularly on the Internet _ will be curtailed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the New York attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, whose office
has pursued consumer fraud cases against health care providers,
said that would be better than a surfeit of false information.
``Just as we are trying to insure that people can obtain the care
they need, particularly from managed care companies,'' he said,
``we have to make sure that representations about the quality of
the care they can obtain are verifiable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
