<HEADLINE>
SEC COMMISSIONER STRONGLY CRITICAL OF METHODS OF ONLINE BROKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Maybe some tow-truck drivers do own islands that
they bought with profits from trading stocks online.
</P>
<P>
   But Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, said Tuesday that he thought brokerage industry
advertisements focusing on the get-rich aspect of online investing
were doing more harm than good for both Wall Street and the public.
</P>
<P>
   In a stinging rebuke to the companies that have aggressively
promoted such ``grandiose and unrealistic expectations,'' Levitt
said that even ads intending to offer a tongue-in-cheek look at the
potential rewards of online investing trivialized what to most
Americans is an important, and often confusing, responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also admonished individual investors to better educate
themselves about online trading and whether it was appropriate for
them. But to a greater extent than before, he focused the spotlight
on whether brokerage firms were being honest in portraying the
potential risks and rewards of online trading.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt, who made his remarks in a speech at the National Press
Club, also called on brokerage firms to strengthen their disclosure
of the risks of trading stocks over the Internet. And he disclosed
that the commission, which plans to double the number of agents
policing the Internet for investment fraud, is preparing a new
round of enforcement actions against firms that have misused the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC and the National Association of Securities Dealers,
which governs securities firms, are about two-thirds of the way
through a sweep of online brokerage and day-trading firms to assess
their compliance with regulations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the results of those examinations give Levitt cause to
worry. ``Based on our initial findings, I sent a letter this
morning to all of the online brokerage firms asking them to improve
the quality of their disclosure to investors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Levitt said, he does not think new regulations are
necessary to oversee online investment. ``Yet there may come a time
when the SEC sees a need for new approaches to better meet the
imperatives of the Internet,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also made clear that he was bothered by commercials that
imply that teen-agers who trade online can afford their own
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't accept the notion that tongue-in-cheek is all there is
to it,'' Levitt said. Without mentioning the firm, Levitt cited a
well-known ad for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's Discover online
brokerage unit, which portrays a tow truck driver who bought an
island with his trading profits as one that ``trivializes a process
that is so crucial and so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt acknowledged that the SEC does not directly regulate
brokerage advertising, which is instead the purview of the
regulatory unit of the NASD. ``But nobody is going to stop me from
giving my own feelings to you about advertising that may be cute
but is ultimately demeaning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt announced that he had asked that the NASD conduct a
round-table discussion with brokerage firms and advertising
professionals to help improve fairness in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Schapiro, president of the NASD regulatory unit, said she,
too, was concerned about the tenor of recent online brokerage ads.
``They have failed to be truly balanced in disclosing the risks as
well as the benefits'' of online trading, she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One willing participant in the organization's round-table
discussion, tentatively scheduled for mid-June, is Discover
Brokerage Direct, the Morgan Stanley Dean Witter unit that ran the
ads that drew Levitt's ire. Wesley McDade, a spokesman for the
brokerage unit, said the firm ``would welcome the opportunity to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also announced the formation of an advisory group to help
the commission examine issues specific to online trading. And to
better enforce the rules in a rapidly changing industry, the SEC
would double, to 250 lawyers, the number of people the commission
has working to uncover investment fraud on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has already asked for an $11 million increase in
its budget for the 2000 fiscal year to expand its efforts to combat
Internet fraud, he said. Tuesday, the White House said it would ask
Congress to approve an additional $5.5 million for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is also working with the FBI on a project called
``Operation Investnet,'' to address fraud on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the brokerage firms themselves who might have the
greatest effect on investors but who are not doing what they should
to educate their customers, Levitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While most online brokerage firms address the different types of
orders for trades that investors can enter into the system, ``fewer
firms discuss how market volatility and the use of margin can
affect online investors, and almost none talk about the risks or
what to do in the event of system capacity and outage problems,''
Levitt said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
