<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FOCUSED ON DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last week it was Robert Horry, pounding Portland
with a season-high 22 points. Sunday it was Rick Fox, squashing
Seattle with big plays down the stretch. Monday, it was Glen Rice
(22 points) and Kobe Bryant (10 assists) dispatching Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have won three straight, their rhythm has returned,
and Shaquille O'Neal seemingly has found help just in time for the
playoffs. But the reason for the outstanding offense and breakout
performances lies on the other end of the court, with a renewed
dedication to defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with our defense, as evidenced by the last few
games,'' Lakers point guard Derek Fisher said. ``The defense turns
into offense. We're never going to be great at executing or being a
half-court offensive team, but if we get stops and turnovers and
rebounds, that gives us more opportunities to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's giving extra effort to be better on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   In their lengthy team meeting last week after the embarrassing
losses to Houston and San Antonio, the Lakers covered every subject
imaginable _ from contracts to opponents to relationships and
paychecks. And they spent a good portion of the day discussing
defense _ or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, they held Portland to 40 percent shooting. They
held Seattle to 37.5 percent Sunday. And Dallas managed just 15
points in the decisive third quarter Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They're communicating. They're rotating. They're watching each
other's back. Bryant, Fisher, O'Neal, even Rice.
</P>
<P>
   No, make that !ital!especially Rice, the sharp-shooting small
forward whose porous defense received more attention than his
errant jumper during the losing days of March and April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen's defense has been phenomenal,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis
said. ``It's been a major pleasant surprise for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rice: ``If we're going to be a championship team, we have
to focus on defense first. We've tried to do that the past week.''
</P>
<P>
   Home or road? The Lakers are taking a detached approach to the
home-court advantage competition with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Houston wallowing in self-pity if they don't get
it, and I don't see us doing that, either,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers are thrilled to conclude the regular season
against Portland, which has won two of three meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good we close out the season against a formidable
opponent like Portland,'' Fisher said. ``It's an opportunity once
again to gauge where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy day: The Lakers gathered for an 11 a.m. video session
Tuesday. After 30 minutes, Rambis was so impressed he gave the
veterans the rest of the day off. Meanwhile, he played
three-on-three with the younger guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten to the point where guys are seeing the video and
acknowledging their mistakes. They're saying, `I should have passed
one more time.' They're even jokingly getting on someone when
something goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their willingness to accept constructive criticism is a real
good sign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
