A4608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     05-04 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPEAKER HASTERT, AWOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 5:
</P>
<P>
   After Newt Gingrich, Republicans no doubt wanted a speaker who
was not a revolutionary. But the question is whether House Speaker
Dennis Hastert is prepared to lead at all. Lately he has yielded
his authority to Tom DeLay, the highly partisan Republican whip,
who undercut Hastert last week by working to defeat a resolution
backing military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the speaker has a chance to assert himself. Moderate
Republicans are to meet with him to ask for an early vote on the
campaign finance reform legislation sponsored by Reps. Christopher
Shays of Connecticut and Martin Meehan of Massachusetts. Hastert
should break with DeLay, who is trying to kill the bill, and
listen. He needs to act like the speaker he promised to be.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the Shays-Meehan ban on ``soft money'' last
year, 252 to 179. Its support is even greater this year, with 54
Republicans on record in favor. That is why opponents prefer to
postpone consideration of the bill until late in the year, when
there may not be enough time to overcome a GOP filibuster in the
Senate. So far, Hastert has sided with those trying to run out the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, Zach Wamp of Tennessee and 27
other Republicans who asked for the meeting with Hastert must make
it clear that if he refuses to budge, they will join with the 190
Democrats who have signed a petition bringing the bill to the
floor. An additional 28 signatures would do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert pleads that the House has a busy calendar. This is
nonsense. The House has found time to amend the Death on the High
Seas Act and issue a Leif Ericson Millennium Coin. Hastert also
managed last week to squeeze in a Republican fund-raising dinner
that brought in $14 million, including a large slug of the
unrestricted corporate donations that would be banned by the
Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker has been getting poor reviews lately, especially
after the Kosovo vote fiasco. He voted to support the air attacks
and reportedly assured the White House that there would be enough
Republican votes for a resolution to pass. Then he sat by while
DeLay exhorted fellow Republicans to vote no, labeling the Kosovo
tragedy as ``Clinton's war.'' Last year Hastert won the speakership
with the active lobbying of DeLay, who now seems to be calling the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is also behind the drive to double the administration's
request for emergency military appropriations. But his most visible
effort has been to oppose the Shays-Meehan legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The danger now is in the faint-heartedness of Shays and other
Republican supporters of the bill. They say they do not want to
embarrass Hastert with a petition bringing campaign reform to the
floor. But no Republican member could embarrass the speaker more
than DeLay did last week. Republican moderates, who can determine
the bill's success in the House, have a higher obligation than
making nice to their speaker. They need to tell him so today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
