<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS, PLAYING BAD BASEBALL, LOSE A STINKER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Something is missing. Maybe it's Joe Torre, or
perhaps depth on their bench, or the calming presence of veteran
Tim Raines. Maybe it's simply unfair to measure the 1999 Yankees
against the incredible standard of concentration they established
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But they are playing bad baseball these days, even when they win
and especially when they lose, as they did in a 8-5 stinker against
the Minnesota Twins Tuesday night, despite two home runs from
Bernie Williams. Last year, the Yankees lost only four of 21 games
against Minnesota and Kansas City, bottom-dwellers in the American
League. The Yankees have lost three games in the last five days to
the Twins and Royals, and they are 6-9 in road games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lincoln, a 24-year-old right-hander who was in Class AA
last year, pitched exceptionally well against the Yankees in
collecting his first major league victory Tuesday night. Lincoln
didn't reach a three-ball count until the sixth inning, after
facing 20 batters, and for this he deserves much credit. But the
Yankees fell behind early, playing as if they had spent the last
three months ice fishing for walleye on Minnesota's Lake Mille
Lacs, moving and reacting numbly, committing errors and bumbling
constantly.
</P>
<P>
   The work of advance scouts is revealed in the first game between
two teams in any season, because strategy is implemented at the
first opportunity. The Twins tried to do a number of things against
the Yankees Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They challenged the defense of left fielder Ricky Ledee, whose
stock continues to plummet. When Doug Mientkiewicz singled to left
field with two out in the first inning, Matt Lawton raced around
third, and Ledee's throw sailed 30 feet up the first base line; had
Ron Coomer, the runner turning at second, been more aggressive, he
could have taken third base easily.
</P>
<P>
   Coomer then tried to score when Terry Steinbach singled to left
and was thrown out when Jorge Posada made a nice catch and tag. The
scoring attempts by Lawton and Coomer seemed like just a matter of
third base coach Ron Gardenhire forcing the issue with two outs.
But in the inning that followed, Cristian Guzman tagged up at first
base on a fly ball to Ledee, taking second with a slide. Ledee
tends to catch fly balls flat-footed and is in a horrible position
to throw when he receives the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the seventh Gardenhire sent Coomer again from second
on a base hit to Ledee, and Coomer scored easily with no one out.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins, like other teams, buried Posada with breaking balls
when he was batting. Lincoln threw five pitches to Posada in his
first at-bat, all breaking balls, all about the same speed (74 to
77 mph), until Posada struck out swinging. In Posada's second
at-bat, three innings later, Lincoln threw a fastball for a
first-pitch strike, then four straight curveballs, the count moving
to two balls and two strikes. With Posada looking for a breaking
ball, Lincoln zipped a fastball over the outside corner. Posada
stared helplessly: Strike three. He has only five hits in 40
at-bats as a left-handed hitter, for a .125 average.
</P>
<P>
   But there were moments when the Twins needed no catalogues of
intelligence to beat the Yankees, because the Yankees were handling
that themselves, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   They lead the American League East, they have 16 victories in 25
games, and at that pace they would win 103 games. But the Yankees
are playing poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not played the kind of baseball these guys are capable
of,'' Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, said before batting
practice Tuesday. ``That'll come, and it'll happen tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Todd Walker slapped a double to the left field corner in
the first inning and took third on a ground ball. Mendoza threw a
sinking fastball for strike two _ and it slammed through the mitt
of Posada, between his legs and to the backstop. Walker lurched off
third and scored, with Posada grimacing disgustedly as he jogged to
retrieve the ball. Already this year Posada has six passed balls,
after he had seven for the entire 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota led, 2-0, after the first, and added another run in
the second, its rally beginning when Chuck Knoblauch threw errantly
to first base, his fifth error of the season. Four of his five
errors have come on throws, and he is tied for the most errors
among second basemen in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, too, committed a costly error, throwing the ball
away on a ground ball starting the bottom of the sixth inning.
Torri Hunter ended up at second base as the Yankees scurried to
retrieve Jeter's bouncing underthrow, and the play was charitably
scored a hit and an error. Two outs into the inning, Coomer tripled
and Mientkiewicz singled. The Twins had control, 5-1, and it was
one of those rare moments when the Yankees looked demoralized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
