<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON ROAD TO CUP, DEVILS TAKE FIRST EXIT
</HEADLINE>
   (With HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils, who captured the Stanley Cup
four years ago, are establishing an embarrassing legacy of thriving
in the regular season and not surviving in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the Devils made an abrupt exit in
the first round of the playoffs after finishing atop the Eastern
Conference standing in the regular season. This time they suffered
a stunning 4-2 loss Tuesday night to Pittsburgh and Jaromir Jagr in
Game 7 of this playoff series at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by three games to two against the Penguins, seeded
eighth in the conference, the top-seeded Devils caved in against a
team that did not have Jagr, its best player, for four games in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, whose game-tying and game-winning goals in game 6 rescued
Pittsburgh, had two assists Tuesday night for the Penguins, who had
only 13 shots on goal, just three in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better team sometimes doesn't win a seven-game series,''
said Bobby Holik, who finished as the leading scorer in the series
for the Devils with seven points, all from assists.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyle Odelein, who made few mistakes on defense for the
Devils, gave Pittsburgh credit. ``They played with desperation and
they have a great player,'' Odelein said, referring to Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons ago, the Devils made it through the first round,
only to lose to the Rangers in round two. Last season, the Devils'
first-round loss was to the Ottawa Senators, who also were seeded
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   This season, New Jersey, Ottawa and Carolina _ the top three
seeds in the Eastern Conference _ were eliminated in the first
round. Boston will meet Buffalo in the second round and Pittsburgh
will play Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins never trailed Tuesday night after getting the first
goal of the game in the second period from German Titov. After the
Devils' Jason Arnott tied the score at 1-1, Pittsburgh struck
suddenly with less than three minutes left in the period ended with
goals by Aleksei Kovalev and Jan Hrdina.
</P>
<P>
   Hrdina's goal with 17 seconds left in the period silenced the
crowd, the first home sellout of the series for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr had quieted the crowd long before that, in the ninth minute
of the game, when he went round the Devils' defense on the left.
But he lost control of the puck as he cut into the middle, and the
crowd roared seconds later when Jagr was crushed against the boards
by Ken Daneyko, the defenseman who has played in all 107 of New
Jersey's playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   More silence filled the arena three minutes into the second
period when Titov opened the scoring with his first goal in the
series, beating Martin Brodeur up close to the goaltender's left.
The play developed when Jagr outmuscled Scott Stevens for a loose
puck, allowing Straka to pick it up and feed Titov.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils brought life to the crowd 6:22 into the period, when
Arnott scored his second goal of the series from almost directly in
front after a pass by Patrik Elias, who went around the net from
right to left. Arnott found himself on his back, mobbed by his
teammates immediately after the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Down by two goals, Dave Andreychuk revived the Devils with a
goal 7:24 into the third period to make the score 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Pittsburgh's Martin Straka capped a gutsy series comeback by
scoring with five and a half minutes to play to put the game beyond
New Jersey, which beat Pittsburgh four times in five games in the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing to go out of the playoffs so early as
the No. 1 seed,'' said Petr Sykora, who had three goals in the
series for the Devils, but failed to take a shot in Tuesday night's
game. ``I'm personally disappointed because the three goals I got
were not enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
