<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERO BEACH SET TO MAKE ITS PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Florida officials believe the state will grant them
$7.5 million in funding, so they've started mapping out their
proposal to keep the Dodgers in Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   Until this point, officials from Vero Beach and Indian River
County have focused their attention on raising $20 million in funds
to purchase Dodgertown and keep the Dodgers in the Florida
shoreline community.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dodgertown managing director Craig Callan said he met
with officials from Vero Beach, Fla., and Indian River County late
last week. They will meet again next week to continue formulating
their proposal, the next step in negotiating to keep the Dodgers,
who've trained for 51 straight springs at Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started going over broad-stroke concepts with the city and
the county,'' Callan said. ``We're giving ideas to the city and
county. We were waiting for the funding from the state. Without the
funding from the state, Vero Beach could not happen. Once we get
the extra dollars... it ups the ante.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are also thinking about moving their spring site to
the Fort McDowell Indian Reservation near Scottsdale, Ariz. The
Fort McDowell Indian Community is trying to build a $30 million
complex for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million Vero Beach is seeking would be used to purchase
Dodgertown and renovate it; the Florida communities would use $10.5
in bonds and $2 million from a tourism tax. The final hurdle is
Florida Gov. Jeb Bush signing the $7.5 bill, which would be split
over two years.
</P>
<P>
   Callan, an employee of the Dodgers who lives in Vero Beach,
doesn't think that will be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Callan, Dodgers senior vice president Tommy Lasorda, Dodgers
secretary and general counsel Sam Fernandez, Vero Beach city
manager Rex Taylor and Indian River County administrator Jim
Chandler visited the state capital in Tallahassee last week after
the bill moved through the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have the money and are confident we're going to get
the $7.5 million,'' Callan said. ``Our comfort level was high
because it passed so easy through the Senate and the House.
(Governor Bush) has been very supportive. We left (the meeting) and
were all feeling good about the state dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want Dodgertown renovated. They want a new
weight-training facility, new clubhouses and the renovation and
expansion of 6,500-seat Holman Stadium to 10,000 or 12,000 seats.
They also want the city and county to purchase the neighboring
9-hole golf course for future expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vero Beach is in an enviable position to come up with the
money and build a facility, or renovate a facility, the Dodgers
would be happy with,'' Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's hitting: An alteration in Todd Hundley's batting
stance, from the left side, is the reason behind the recent surge
in his batting average, which rose from .148 to .217.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't move my front foot at all and it keeps my head
still,'' Hundley said. ``In Philly, just during batting practice,
the wind was gusting like a son of a gun. I hit one in the upper
deck and said, `You gotta be kidding me.' If you don't figure it
out from there, you're an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last four games, Hundley is 7 for 16 (.438) with two
homers, two doubles and seven RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: With second baseman Eric Young out with a strained
right calf, shortstop Mark Grudzielanek batted leadoff. In 1996
with Montreal, Grudzielanek hit .306 and was an All-Star. He went 0
for 4 on Tuesday.... Right-hander Antonio Osuna pitched 12/3
innings of scoreless relief in his first appearance since being
activated from the disabled list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
