<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE GARDEN MISSES OUT ON A GEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Life is more often competitive than it is convenient.
So while Natalie Williams is going home to Utah, Chamique Holdsclaw
is bound for what was the worst team in the surviving women's pro
basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw was picked first in the Women's National Basketball
Association draft on Tuesday by the Washington Mystics, the only
college player taken in the first round. The selections were
announced and Holdsclaw was introduced at the Sheraton Hotel at 53d
Street and Seventh Avenue, a subway ride from the Astoria Houses in
Queens, where she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw had too big a name and too little leverage to get her
first choice, which was home sweet home. She stayed a year too long
in college, at Tennessee, trying unsuccessfully to win a fourth
national title. The rival American Basketball League folded before
she could say, ``Give me Liberty, or the Columbus Quest.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tribute to Holdsclaw's presence and popularity that she
was picked before so many talented and experience pros, such as
Williams, who went third to the Utah Starrz.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the WNBA did the credible thing, by not rigging
its draft, by hook, crook, lottery or trade. You always got the
feeling, reading between the quotes, that Madison Square Garden's
team wanted to believe that something would be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Washington's pick to make, not ours, and we owed that
to our teams and fans,'' Val Ackerman, the WNBA president, said.
</P>
<P>
   It was her boldest statement yet that David Stern's women's
annex has a mandate, beyond marketing, to do right by the sport.
Anyway, 14 years ago, there were suspicions that it was arranged
for the New York Knicks to land Patrick Ewing, who has spent much
of his career front and center in a storm of contention about
everything the Knicks are not.
</P>
<P>
   June Holdsclaw came to the draft, and proclaimed her
granddaughter better off three hours away by Amtrak from New York's
inherent expectations, distractions and pressure. If the woman who
raised her from the time she was 11 believes this, fine. Chamique,
total talent and team player, wasn't about to publicly contradict
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just praying I wouldn't go to Utah,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No offense intended, or taken, by Williams, who is from
Taylorsville, Utah, about 15 miles outside Salt Lake City. As a
29-year-old refugee of the more competitive ABL, and its last most
valuable player, not only is Williams more likely to have a greater
immediate impact, she will play in front of the more than 100
members of her extended family, plus Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand he has a season ticket,'' said the 6-foot-2-inch
Williams, a fan of Stockton-to-Malone since high school.
</P>
<P>
   When her agent called Monday night to say that Utah was likely
to take her, she held off calling her mother, Robyn Gray, in Salt
Lake City. She wanted to be sure, as certain as Holdsclaw became
these last few days that she was not going to play in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw could have called that shot, and extracted a few extra
dollars (she is likely to earn about $250,000 a year under a
personal services contract) had she left school last year. She
could have pocketed an extra year's earnings, been back at
Tennessee by last fall, on track for the political science degree
she will get May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith once told a reluctant Michael Jordan to leave school
early for his own good. Sometimes the coach has to be the educator
in less conventional ways. Pat Summitt, at least publicly, never
campaigned for the obvious, for the fact that Chamique could have
had it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   The degree came first for June Holdsclaw, a stickler for
education who said she is looking forward to graduation more than
any game her granddaughter will play. Two of her adult children
completed college, and a third, Chamique's mother, Benita,
currently attends the College of Staten Island. She hopes Chamique
will pursue her master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   The loser here is the Garden, once again victimized, you might
say on a day the Miami Heat was visiting, by the single-minded
agenda of another coaching Pat from down south. As for Chamique,
she left New York four years ago and became the biggest basketball
name in the state of Tennessee. She and her jump shot will do fine
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   First things first. Graduation in Knoxville. Then the wedding of
Kellie Jolly, the Tennessee point guard, Holdsclaw's four-year
teammate and the fourth-round draft choice yesterday of the
Cleveland Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bridesmaid,'' said Holdsclaw, darling of the draft,
whose long-rumored marriage to the Liberty could not be arranged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
