<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS MAKE MILTON THEIR NO. 1 PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Sparks are feeling pretty good
about themselves after snagging what they feel is the best draft
class of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks chose 6-foot-1 forward DeLisha Milton as their No. 1
draft pick and were surprised to see 6-5 center Clarisse
Machanguana still available for their second selection in the
four-round WNBA draft Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ukari Figgs, who led Purdue to its first NCAA championship
last month, was their third choice, and they picked 6-3 forward
La'Keisha Frett in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say, we were very surprised that Machanguana was there
in the second round,'' Sparks general manager Rhonda Windham said.
``I'm very happy with the players we selected. We needed to get
bigger and I think we definitely secured our front line with the
players we selected.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton, Machaungua and Frett were among 35 players drafted from
the defunct American Basketball League. Figgs was one of only 12
college players drafted. The other three were from overseas. The
expansion teams, the Orlando Magic and Minnesota Lynx, had five
picks to bring the number of players drafted to 50.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Mystics nabbed three-time NCAA Player of the Year
Chamique Holdsclaw, the forward-guard from Tennessee, with their
No. 1 overall draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Former Long Beach StingRays forward Yolanda Griffith was the
second pick who went to the Sacramento Monarchs where she will be
reunited with former StingRays coach Maura McHugh, now an assistant
coach with the Monarchs. Natalie Williams, who played 21/2 seasons
with Portland Power and almost played with the StingRays before the
team folded last August, was the third overall pick by the Utah
Starzz.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the Sparks feel they have a big and talented lineup to
compete in the league's third season.
</P>
<P>
   Milton averaged 9.3 points and 5.3 rebounds with the Portland
Power. She played with Sparks center-forward Lisa Leslie on the
U.S. national team last year and is seeking a spot on the team for
the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Milton said what she brings to the Sparks ``is my ability to run
the floor, play outstanding defense, rebound, and put the ball in
the basket if I need to''
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, ``I will compliment Lisa Leslie in games.
She's an outstanding player and I feel that with the attributes
that I have I can only make her stand out that much more and make
life a little bit easier for her in the paint.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what head coach Orlando Woolridge had envisioned
in choosing Milton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frees (Lisa) up as a perimeter player as well as a post
player,'' Woolridge said. ``Now we can go with big lineups. It
gives us more versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with Machaungua on the roster. The native from
Mozambique and graduate of Old Dominion averaged 10.2 points and
4.8 rebounds with the San Jose Lasers.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said Figgs, who averaged 11.6 points and 4.2 assist for
the Boilermakers last season, was the best available point guard in
the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figgs can play in big games and she has proven that she can
overcome adversities,'' Windham said. ``She's a very good, young
talent and she's what we wanted in a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Frett averaged 9.0 points and 4.3 rebounds with the Philadelphia
Rage.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA NOTES: Training camp opens May 14. The 14-player roster
must be trimmed to the maximum 11 by June 9. The Sparks open their
season at home against Sacramento. They will play the Detroit Shock
in a preseason game June 10 at the Arrowhead Pond. ... Other former
StingRay players to be drafted were forward Clarissa-Davis
Wrightsil (Phoenix) in the second round and guard Andrea Nagy
(Washington) in the third round.
</P>
</TEXT>
