<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAN TO EASE PAIN OF DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author Sanford Braver recommends two ways to make divorce easier
on families.
</P>
<P>
   The first is making joint legal custody a presumption under the
law rather than a point to be negotiated. Judges would retain the
option of awarding sole custody in appropriate circumstances, such
as cases of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``With sole legal custody, one parent becomes a visitor. Joint
legal custody is a way of telling both parents, the child and
society that this child still has two parents,'' Braver said.
</P>
<P>
   Joint custody allows both parents to share important decisions
about the child, such as medical care and education. It is not the
same as residential custody, which specifies where the child lives
most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that joint custody is good for families in the
following respects: It makes for better adjusted children and it
makes for better child-support payments. We spend $4 billion a year
in this country on child-support enforcement. This solution is free
and it works,'' Braver said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Braver said divorce court should be demilitarized.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter has diabetes. When she was diagnosed, they sent
out a public-health nurse to explain the disease to her and tell
her what her life was going to be like. Why don't we send somebody
out to talk to people who file for divorce? Why not have a
social-service person make the initial contact instead of making
the first stop a lawyer's office?'' Braver said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Armstrong, presiding judge of Family Court in Maricopa
County Superior Court, said the courts already are taking steps to
do that.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation services are available to divorcing couples, as is an
early intervention program that promotes early settlement,
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature passed a law three years ago requiring divorcing
parents to attend education classes about the effects of divorce on
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really aimed at reducing parental conflict,'' Armstrong
said. ``We know now that persistent conflict is the foremost
indicator of divorce outcomes. If there is conflict, that puts
children at higher risk for delinquency, self-destructive behavior,
depression and reduced academic performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Braver credits the education classes with the upswing in
joint-custody orders. Only one-third of the Maricopa County divorce
cases resulted in joint-custody agreements when he conducted his
study. Now, two-thirds of divorcing parents opt for joint custody.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong favors joint custody, echoing Braver's opinion that it
makes for better relationships and compliance with child-support
orders. But the judge opposes Braver's proposal to make joint
custody a legal presumption, because he thinks each case should be
evaluated independently.
</P>
<P>
   A bill that would have instituted legal presumption stalled in
the House Human Services Committee this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Anderson, R-Mesa and committee chairman, said most
members didn't think it was necessary to change the law because the
majority of cases were resolved by joint custody anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of those ideas that takes a couple of years
for people to get comfortable with,'' Anderson said. ``The state of
Washington has this kind of legislation in place. It is
ground-breaking. Arizona would become the second state if we passed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Braver both serve on the Legislature's Domestic
Relations Reform Committee, which will explore some of the ideas in
Braver's study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his conclusions are very accurate. He has done one of
the most comprehensive studies in the country. We need to realize
that children are best off with both parents in their lives,''
Anderson said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-04-99 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
